<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D558 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D558>
      <H2 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 100.25pt 0pt 101.3pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 17pt">PREFACE </SPAN><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR><BR><BR></SPAN></H2>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.7pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">This book is written in the =
conviction=20
      that our </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">own=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">existence=20
      </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">once =
</SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">presented the greatest of all =
mysteries,=20
      but that it is a mystery no longer because it is solved. Darwin =
and=20
      Wallace solved it, though we shall continue to add footnotes to =
their=20
      solution for a while yet. I wrote the book because I was surprised =
that so=20
      many people seemed not only unaware of the elegant and beautiful =
solution=20
      to this deepest </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold">of=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">problems but,=20
      incredibly, in many cases actually unaware that there was a =
problem in the=20
      first place! </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.45pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The problem is that of complex =
design.=20
      The computer on which I am writing these words has an information =
storage=20
      capacity of about 64 kilobytes (one byte is used to hold each =
character of=20
      text). The computer was consciously designed and deliberately=20
      manufactured. The brain with which you are understanding my words =
is an=20
      array of some ten million kiloneurones. Many of these billions of =
nerve=20
      cells have each more than a thousand 'electric wires' connecting =
them to=20
      other neurones. Moreover, at the molecular genetic level, every =
single one=20
      of more than a trillion cells in the body contains about a =
thousand times=20
      as much precisely-coded digital information as my entire computer. =
The=20
      complexity of living organisms is matched by the elegant =
efficiency of=20
      their apparent design. If anyone doesn't agree that this amount of =
complex=20
      design cries out for an explanation, I give up. No, on second =
thoughts I=20
      don't give up, because one of my aims in the book is to convey =
something=20
      of the sheer wonder of biological complexity to those whose eyes =
have not=20
      been opened to it. But having built up the mystery, my other main =
aim is=20
      to remove it again by explaining the solution. <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.1pt 0pt =
255.35pt"><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">xiii </SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.1pt 0pt 255.35pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall></DIV><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<DIV class=3DSection2>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D630 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D377 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D630>
      <P class=3DStyle9 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.25pt"><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">XIV </SPAN></B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Preface </SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.2pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Explaining is a difficult art. =
You can=20
      explain something so that your reader understands the words; and =
you can=20
      explain something so that the reader feels it in the marrow of his =
bones.=20
      To do the latter, it sometimes isn't enough to lay the evidence =
before the=20
      reader in a dispassionate way. You have to become an advocate and =
use the=20
      tricks of the advocate's trade. This book is not a dispassionate=20
      scientific treatise. Other books on Darwinism are, and many of =
them are=20
      excellent and informative and should be read in conjunction with =
this one.=20
      Far from being dispassionate, it has to be confessed that in parts =
this=20
      book is written with a passion which, in a professional scientific =

      journal, might excite comment. Certainly it seeks to inform, but =
it also=20
      seeks to persuade and even - one can specify </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">aims </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">without presumption - to =
inspire. I want=20
      to inspire the reader with a vision of our own existence as, on =
the face=20
      of it, a spine-chilling mystery, and simultaneously to convey the =
full=20
      excitement of the fact that it is a mystery with an elegant =
solution which=20
      is within our grasp. More, I want to persuade the reader, not just =
that=20
      the Darwinian world-view </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">happens to </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">be true, but that it is the =
only known=20
      theory that </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">could,=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">in principle, =
solve the=20
      mystery of our existence. This makes it a doubly satisfying =
theory. A good=20
      case can be made that Darwinism is true, not just on this planet =
but all=20
      over the universe wherever life may be found. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">In one respect I plead to =
distance myself=20
      from professional advocates. A lawyer or a politician is paid to =
exercise=20
      his passion and his persuasion on behalf of a client or a cause in =
which=20
      he may not privately believe. I have never done this and I never =
shall. I=20
      may not always be right, but I care passionately about what is =
true and I=20
      never say anything that I do not believe to be right. I remember =
being=20
      shocked when visiting a university debating society to debate with =

      creationists. At dinner after the debate, I was placed next to a =
young=20
      woman who had made a relatively powerful speech in favour of =
creationism.=20
      She clearly couldn't </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">be=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">a creationist, =
so I=20
      asked her to tell me honestly why she had done it. She freely =
admitted=20
      that she was simply practising her debating skills, and found it =
more=20
      challenging to advocate a position in which she did not believe.=20
      Apparently it is common practice in university debating societies =
for=20
      speakers simply to be </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">told on </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">which side they are to speak. =
Their own=20
      beliefs don't come into it. I had come a long way to perform the=20
      disagreeable task of public speaking, because I believed in the =
truth of=20
      the motion that I had been asked to propose. When I discovered =
that=20
      members of the society were using the motion as a vehicle for =
playing=20
      arguing games, I resolved to decline future invitations from =
debating=20
      societies that encourage insincere advocacy on issues where =
scientific=20
      truth is at stake. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D380 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle11 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 3.1pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica-Oblique">Preface =
</SPAN></I><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica-Bold">xv </SPAN></B><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.35pt 0pt 2.65pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">For reasons that are not =
entirely clear=20
      to me, Darwinism seems more in need of advocacy than similarly =
established=20
      truths in other branches of science. Many of us have no grasp of =
quantum=20
      theory, or Einstein's theories of special and general relativity, =
but this=20
      does not in itself lead us to </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">oppose </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">these theories! Darwinism, =
unlike=20
      'Einsteinism', seems to be regarded as fair game for critics with =
any=20
      degree of ignorance. I suppose one trouble with Darwinism is that, =
as=20
      Jacques Monod perceptively remarked, everybody </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">thinks </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">he understands it. It is, =
indeed, a=20
      remarkably simple theory; childishly so, one would have thought, =
in=20
      comparison with almost all of physics and mathematics. In essence, =
it=20
      amounts simply to the idea that non-random reproduction, where =
there is=20
      hereditary variation, has consequences that are far-reaching if =
there is=20
      time for them to be cumulative. But we have good grounds for =
believing=20
      that this simplicity is deceptive. Never forget that, simple as =
the theory=20
      may seem, nobody thought of it until Darwin and Wallace in the mid =

      nineteenth century, nearly 200 years after Newton's =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Principia, </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">and more than 2,000 years after =

      Eratosthenes measured the Earth. How could such a simple idea go =
so long=20
      undiscovered by thinkers of the calibre of Newton, Galileo, =
Descartes,=20
      Leibnitz, Hume and Aristotle? Why did it have to wait for two =
Victorian=20
      naturalists? What was </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">wrong </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">with philosophers and =
mathematicians that=20
      they overlooked it? And how can such a powerful idea go still =
largely=20
      unabsorbed into popular consciousness? </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.3pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">It is almost as if the human =
brain were=20
      specifically designed to misunderstand Darwinism, and to find it =
hard to=20
      believe. Take, for instance, the issue of 'chance', often =
dramatized as=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">blind =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">chance. The great majority of =
people that=20
      attack Darwinism leap with almost unseemly eagerness to the =
mistaken idea=20
      that there is nothing other than random chance in it. Since living =

      complexity embodies the very antithesis of chance, if you think =
that=20
      Darwinism is tantamount to chance you'll obviously find it easy to =
refute=20
      Darwinism! One of my tasks will be to destroy this eagerly =
believed myth=20
      that Darwinism is a theory of 'chance'. Another way in which we =
seem=20
      predisposed to disbelieve Darwinism is that our brains are built =
to deal=20
      with events on radically different </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">timescales </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">from those that characterize=20
      <BR>evolutionary change. We are equipped to appreciate processes =
that take=20
      seconds, minutes, years or, at most, decades to complete. =
Darwinism is a=20
      theory of cumulative processes so slow that they take between =
thousands=20
      and millions of decades to complete. All our intuitive judgements =
of what=20
      is probable turn out to be wrong by many orders of magnitude. Our=20
      <BR>&shy;well-tuned apparatus of scepticism and subjective=20
      probability-theory misfires by huge margins, because it is tuned - =

      ironically, by evolution </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.3pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle13 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.95pt"><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica-Bold">XVI </SPAN></B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica-Oblique">Preface =
</SPAN><BR><BR></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.4pt 0pt 0.95pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.8pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">itself - to work within a =
lifetime of a=20
      few decades. It requires effort of the imagination to escape from =
the=20
      prison of familiar timescale, an effort that I shall try to =
assist.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.5pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">A third respect in which our =
brains seem=20
      predisposed to resist Darwinism stems from our great success as =
creative=20
      designers. Our world is dominated by feats of engineering and =
works of=20
      art. We are entirely accustomed to the idea that complex elegance =
is an=20
      indicator of premeditated, Grafted design. This is probably the =
most=20
      powerful reason for the belief, held by the vast majority of =
people that=20
      have ever lived, in some kind of supernatural deity. It took a =
very large=20
      leap of the imagination for Darwin and Wallace to see that, =
contrary to=20
      all intuition, there is another way and, once you have understood =
it, a=20
      far more plausible way, for complex 'design' to arise out of =
primeval=20
      simplicity. A leap of the imagination so large that, to this day, =
many=20
      people seem still unwilling to make it. It is the main purpose of =
this=20
      book to help the reader to make this leap. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.95pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Authors naturally hope that =
their books=20
      will have lasting rather than ephemeral impact. But any advocate, =
in=20
      addition to putting the timeless part of his case, must also =
respond to=20
      contemporary advocates of opposing, or apparently opposing, points =
of=20
      view. There is a risk that some of these arguments, however hotly =
they may=20
      rage today, will seem terribly dated in decades to come. The =
paradox has=20
      often been noted that the first edition of </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Origin of Species =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">makes a better case than the =
sixth. This=20
      is because Darwin felt obliged, in his later editions, to respond =
to=20
      contemporary criticisms of the first edition, criticisms which now =
seem so=20
      dated that the replies to them merely get in the way, and in =
places even=20
      mislead. Nevertheless, the temptation to ignore fashionable =
contemporary=20
      criticisms that one suspects of being nine days' wonders is a =
temptation=20
      that should not be indulged, for reasons of courtesy not just to =
the=20
      critics but to their otherwise confused readers. Though I have my =
own=20
      private ideas on which chapters of my book will eventually prove =
ephemeral=20
      for this reason, the reader - and time - must judge. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.15pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">I am distressed to find that =
some women=20
      friends (fortunately not many) treat the use of the impersonal =
masculine=20
      pronoun as if it showed intention to exclude them. If there were =
any=20
      excluding to be done (happily there isn't) I think I would sooner =
exclude=20
      men, but when I once tentatively tried referring to my abstract =
reader as=20
      'she', a feminist denounced me for patronizing condescension: I =
ought to=20
      say 'he-or-she', and 'his-or-her'. That is easy to do if you don't =
care=20
      about language, but then if you don't care about language you =
don't=20
      deserve readers of either sex. Here, I have returned to the normal =

      conventions </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.15pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D586 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D381 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D586>
      <P class=3DStyle14 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.15pt 0pt =
3.35pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Preface </SPAN></I><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">xvii </SPAN></B><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle15 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 3.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.65pt">of=20
      English pronouns. I may refer to the 'reader' as 'he', but I no =
more think=20
      of my readers as specifically male than a French speaker thinks of =
a table=20
      as female. As a matter of fact I believe I do, more often than =
not, think=20
      of my readers as female, but that is my personal affair and I'd =
hate to=20
      think that such considerations impinged on how I use my native =
language.=20
      </P>
      <P class=3DStyle15=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.7pt 0pt 2.15pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt">Personal,=20
      too, are some of my reasons for gratitude. Those to whom I cannot =
do=20
      justice will understand. My publishers saw no reason to keep from =
me the=20
      identities of their referees (not 'reviewers' - true reviewers, =
<I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">pace </SPAN></I>many Americans =
under 40,=20
      criticize books only <I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">after=20
      </SPAN></I>they are published, when it is too late for the author =
to do=20
      anything about it), and I have benefited greatly from the =
suggestions of=20
      John Krebs (again), <I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">John=20
      </SPAN></I>Durant, Graham Cairns-Smith, leffrey Levinton, Michael =
Ruse,=20
      Anthony Hallam and David Pye. Richard Gregory kindly criticized =
Chapter=20
      12, and the final version has benefited from its complete =
excision. Mark=20
      Ridley and Alan Grafen, now no longer even officially my students, =
are,=20
      together with Bill Hamilton, the leading lights of the group of =
colleagues=20
      with whom I discuss evolution and from whose ideas I benefit =
almost daily.=20
      They, Pamela Wells, Peter Atkins and John Dawkins have helpfully=20
      criticized various chapters for me. Sarah Bunney made numerous=20
      improvements, and John Cribbin corrected a major error. Alan =
Grafen and=20
      Will Atkinson advised on computing problems, and the Apple =
Macintosh=20
      Syndicate of the Zoology Department kindly allowed their laser =
printer to=20
      draw biomorphs. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle15=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.6pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt">Once=20
      again I have benefited from the relentless dynamism with which =
Michael=20
      Rodgers, now of Longman, carries all before him. He, and Mary =
Cunnane of=20
      Norton, skilfully applied the accelerator (to my morale) and the =
brake (to=20
      my sense of humour) when each was needed. Part of the book was =
written=20
      during a sabbatical leave kindly granted by the Department of =
Zoology and=20
      New College. Finally - a debt I should have acknowledged in both =
my=20
      previous books - the Oxford tutorial system and my many tutorial =
pupils in=20
      zoology over the years have helped me to practise what few skills =
I may=20
      have in the difficult art of explaining. <SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle15 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.55pt 0pt =
201.35pt">Richard Dawkins=20
      Oxford, 1986 </P>
      <P class=3DStyle15 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.55pt 0pt 201.35pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
