<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D530 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D376 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D530>
      <P class=3DStyle16 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 105.5pt 0pt 1.5in">CHAPTER =
1 <SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <H2 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 40.9pt 0pt 43.45pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 16.5pt">EXPLAINING THE VERY IMPROBABLE =
</SPAN><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR><BR><BR></SPAN></H2>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">We animals are the most =
complicated=20
      things in the known universe. The universe that we know, of =
course, is a=20
      tiny fragment of the actual universe. There may be yet more =
complicated=20
      objects than us on other planets, and some of them may already =
know about=20
      us. But this doesn't alter the point that I want to make. =
Complicated=20
      things, everywhere, deserve a very special kind of explanation. We =
want to=20
      know how they came into existence and why they are so complicated. =
The=20
      explanation, as I shall argue, is likely to be broadly the same =
for=20
      complicated things everywhere in the universe; the same for us, =
for=20
      chimpanzees, worms, oak trees and monsters from outer space. On =
the other=20
      hand, it will not be the same for what I shall call 'simple' =
things, such=20
      as rocks, clouds, rivers, galaxies and quarks. These are the stuff =
of=20
      physics. Chimps and dogs and bats and cockroaches and people and =
worms and=20
      dandelions and bacteria and galactic aliens are the stuff of =
biology.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.2pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The difference is one of =
complexity of=20
      design. Biology is the study of complicated things that give the=20
      appearance of having been designed for a purpose. Physics is the =
study of=20
      simple things that do not tempt us to invoke design. At first =
sight,=20
      man-made artefacts like computers and cars will seem to provide=20
      exceptions. They are complicated and obviously designed for a =
purpose, yet=20
      they are not alive, and they are made of metal and plastic rather =
than of=20
      flesh and blood. In this book they will be firmly treated as =
biological=20
      objects. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
1.2pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The reader's reaction to this =
may be to=20
      ask, 'Yes, but are they </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">really </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">biological objects?' Words are =
our=20
      servants, not our masters. For different purposes we find it =
convenient to=20
      use words in different </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">senses. </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Most cookery books class =
lobsters as=20
      fish. Zoologists </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold">can=20
      </SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
1.2pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall></DIV><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<DIV class=3DSection4>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D625 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D625>
      <P class=3DStyle10 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.5pt 0pt =
174.25pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica-Oblique">The Blind Watchmaker=20
      </SPAN></I><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: =
9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
1.4pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">become quite apoplectic about =
this,=20
      pointing out that lobsters could with greater justice call humans =
fish,=20
      since fish are far closer kin to humans than they are to lobsters. =
And,=20
      talking of justice and lobsters, I understand that a court of law =
recently=20
      had to decide whether lobsters were insects or 'animals' (it bore =
upon=20
      whether people should be allowed to boil them alive). Zoologically =

      speaking, lobsters are certainly not insects. They are animals, =
but then=20
      so are insects and so are we. There is little point in getting =
worked up=20
      about the way different people use words (although in my =
nonprofessional=20
      life I am quite prepared to get worked up about people who boil =
lobsters=20
      alive). Cooks and lawyers need to use words in their own special =
ways, and=20
      so do I in this book. Never mind whether cars and computers are =
'really'=20
      biological objects. The point is that if anything of that degree =
of=20
      complexity were found on a planet, we should have no hesitation in =

      concluding that life existed, or had once existed, on that planet. =

      Machines are the direct products of living objects; they derive =
their=20
      complexity and design from living objects, and they are diagnostic =
of the=20
      existence of life on a planet. The same goes for fossils, =
skeletons and=20
      dead bodies. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.95pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">I said that physics is the =
study of=20
      simple things, and this, too, may seem strange at first. Physics =
appears=20
      to be a complicated subject, because the ideas of physics are =
difficult=20
      for us to understand. Our brains were designed to understand =
hunting and=20
      gathering, mating and child-rearing: a world of medium-sized =
objects=20
      moving in three dimensions at moderate speeds. We are ill-equipped =
to=20
      comprehend the very small and the very large; things whose =
duration is=20
      measured in picoseconds or gigayears; particles that don't have =
position;=20
      forces and fields that we cannot see or touch, which we know of =
only=20
      because they affect things that we can see or touch. We think that =
physics=20
      is complicated because it is hard for us to understand, and =
because=20
      physics books are full of difficult mathematics. But the objects =
that=20
      physicists study are still basically simple objects. They are =
clouds of=20
      gas or tiny particles, or lumps of uniform matter like crystals, =
with=20
      almost endlessly repeated atomic patterns. They do not, at least =
by=20
      biological standards, have intricate working parts. Even large =
physical=20
      objects like stars consist of a rather limited array of parts, =
more or=20
      less haphazardly arranged. The behaviour of physical, =
nonbiological=20
      objects is so simple that it is feasible to use existing =
mathematical=20
      language to describe it, which is why physics books are full of=20
      mathematics. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.25pt 0pt 1.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Physics </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">books </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">may be complicated, but physics =
books,=20
      like cars and computers, are the product of biological objects - =
human=20
      brains. The objects and phenomena that a physics book describes =
are=20
      simpler than </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.25pt 0pt 1.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D382 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 141pt 0pt 5.3pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Explaining the very improbable =

      </SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.15pt 0pt 4.55pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">a single cell in the body of =
its author.=20
      And the author consists of trillions of those cells, many of them=20
      different from each other, <BR>organized with intricate =
architecture and=20
      precision-engineering into a <BR>working machine capable of =
writing a book=20
      (my trillions are American, like all my units: one American =
trillion is a=20
      million millions; an American billion is a thousand millions). Our =
brains=20
      are no better equipped to handle extremes of complexity than =
extremes of=20
      size and the other difficult extremes of physics. Nobody has yet =
invented=20
      the mathematics for describing the total structure and behaviour =
of such=20
      an object as a physicist, or even of one of his cells. What we can =
do is=20
      understand some of the general principles of how living things =
work, and=20
      why they exist at all. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.4pt 0pt 2.65pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">This was where we came in. We =
wanted=20
      </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">to =
</SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">know why we, </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">and all </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">other complicated things, =
exist. And we=20
      can now answer that question in general terms, even without being =
able to=20
      comprehend the details of the complexity itself. To take an =
analogy, most=20
      of us don't understand in detail how an airliner works. Probably =
its=20
      builders don't <BR>comprehend it fully either: engine specialists =
don't in=20
      detail understand wings, and wing specialists understand engines =
only=20
      vaguely. Wing specialists don't even understand wings with full=20
      mathematical precision: they can predict how a wing will behave in =

      turbulent conditions, only by examining a model in a wind tunnel =
or a=20
      computer simulation - the sort of thing a biologist might do to =
understand=20
      an animal. But <BR>however incompletely we understand how an =
airliner=20
      works, we all <BR>understand by what general process it came into=20
      existence. It was designed by humans on drawing boards. Then other =
humans=20
      made the bits from the drawings, then lots more humans (with the =
aid of=20
      other machines designed by humans) screwed, rivetted, welded or =
glued the=20
      bits together, each in its right place. The process by which an =
airliner=20
      came into existence is not fundamentally mysterious to us, because =
humans=20
      built it. The systematic putting together of parts to a purposeful =
design=20
      is something we know and understand, for we have experienced it at =
first=20
      hand, even if only with our childhood Meccano or Erector set. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.7pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">What about our own bodies? Each =
one of us=20
      is a machine, like an airliner only much more complicated. Were we =

      designed on a drawing board too, and were our parts assembled by a =
skilled=20
      engineer? The answer is no. It is a surprising answer, and we have =
known=20
      and <BR>understood it for only a century or so. When Charles =
Darwin first=20
      explained the matter, many people either wouldn't or couldn't =
grasp it. I=20
      myself flatly refused to believe Darwin's theory when I first =
heard about=20
      it as a child. Almost everybody throughout history, up to the =
second half=20
      </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">of =
</SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the nineteenth century, has =
firmly=20
      believed in the opposite - the </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.7pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle18 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.3pt 0pt =
174.5pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker=20
      </SPAN><BR><BR></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.85pt 0pt 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.95pt">Conscious=20
      Designer theory. Many people still do, perhaps because the true, =
Darwinian=20
      explanation of our own existence is still, remarkably, not a =
routine part=20
      of the curriculum of a general education. It is certainly very =
widely=20
      misunderstood. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.85pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt">The=20
      watchmaker of my title is borrowed from a famous treatise by the=20
      eighteenth-century theologian William Paley. His <I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Natural Theology - or =
Evidences of the=20
      Existence and Attributes of the Deity Collected from the =
Appearances of=20
      Nature, </SPAN></I>published in 1802, is the best-known exposition =
of the=20
      'Argument from Design', always the most influential of the =
arguments for=20
      the existence of a God. It is a book that I greatly admire, for in =
his own=20
      time its author succeeded in doing what I am struggling to do now. =
He had=20
      a point to make, he passionately believed in it, and he spared no =
effort=20
      to ram it home clearly. He had a proper reverence for the =
complexity of=20
      the living world, and he saw that it demands a very special kind =
of=20
      explanation. The only thing he got wrong - admittedly quite a big =
thing! -=20
      was the explanation itself. He gave the traditional religious =
answer to=20
      the riddle, but he articulated it more clearly and convincingly =
than=20
      anybody had before. The true explanation is utterly different, and =
it had=20
      to wait for one of the most revolutionary thinkers of all time, =
Charles=20
      Darwin. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 47.65pt 0pt 11.3pt">Paley =
begins=20
      <I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Natural Theology=20
      </SPAN></I>with a famous passage: <BR><BR></P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 16.35pt 0pt 11.3pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10pt">In =
crossing a=20
      heath, suppose I pitched my foot against a stone, and were asked =
how the=20
      stone came to be there; I might possibly answer, that, for =
anything I knew=20
      to the contrary, it had lain there for ever: nor would it perhaps =
be very=20
      easy to show the absurdity of this answer. But suppose I had found =
a=20
      <I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">watch </SPAN></I>upon =
the=20
      ground, and it should be inquired how the watch happened to be in =
that=20
      place; I should hardly think of the answer which I had before =
given, that=20
      for anything 1 knew, the watch might have always been there. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.2pt 0pt 1.9pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt">Paley =
here=20
      appreciates the difference between natural physical objects like =
stones,=20
      and designed and manufactured objects like watches. He goes on to =
expound=20
      the precision with which the cogs and spring's of a watch are =
fashioned,=20
      and the intricacy with which they are put together. If we found an =
object=20
      such as a watch upon a heath, even if we didn't know how it had =
come into=20
      existence, its own precision and intricacy of design would force =
us to=20
      conclude </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.1pt 0pt 12.5pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 9.95pt">that =
the watch=20
      must have had a maker: that there must have existed, at some time, =
and at=20
      some place or other, an artificer or artificers, who formed it for =
the=20
      purpose which we find it actually to answer, who comprehended its=20
      construction, and designed its use. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.1pt 0pt 12.5pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 9.95pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D625 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D381 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D625>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 141.05pt 0pt =
4.8pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Explaining the very improbable =

      </SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 4.1pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.45pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Nobody could reasonably dissent =
from this=20
      conclusion, Paley insists, yet that is just what the atheist, in =
effect,=20
      does when he contemplates the works of nature, for: =
<BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 8.9pt 0pt 13.45pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 9.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">every indication of =
contrivance, every=20
      manifestation of design, which existed in the watch, exists in the =
works=20
      of nature; with the difference, on the side of nature, of being =
greater or=20
      more, and that in a degree which exceeds all computation. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.25pt 0pt 3.35pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Paley drives his point home =
with=20
      beautiful and reverent descriptions of the dissected machinery of =
life,=20
      beginning with the human eye, a favourite example which Darwin was =
later=20
      to use and which will reappear throughout this book. Paley =
compares the=20
      eye with a designed instrument such as a telescope, and concludes =
that=20
      'there is precisely the same proof that the eye was made for =
vision, as=20
      there is that the telescope was made for assisting it'. The eye =
must have=20
      had a designer, just as the telescope had. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.95pt 0pt 2.65pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Paley's argument is made with =
passionate=20
      sincerity and is informed by the best biological scholarship of =
his day,=20
      but it is wrong, gloriously and utterly wrong. The analogy between =

      telescope and eye, between watch and living organism, is false. =
All=20
      appearances to the contrary, the only watchmaker in nature is the =
blind=20
      forces of physics, albeit deployed in a very special way. A true=20
      watchmaker has foresight: he designs his cogs and springs, and =
plans their=20
      interconnections, with a future purpose in his mind's eye. Natural =

      selection, the blind, unconscious, automatic process which Darwin=20
      discovered, and which we now know is the explanation for the =
existence and=20
      apparently <BR>purposeful form of all life, has no purpose in =
mind. It has=20
      no mind and no mind's eye. It does not plan for the future. It has =
no=20
      vision, no foresight, no sight at all. If it can be said to play =
the role=20
      of watchmaker in <BR>.nature, it is the </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">blind </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">watchmaker. I shall explain all =
this, and=20
      much else besides. But one thing I shall not do is belittle the =
wonder of=20
      the living 'watches' that so inspired Paley. On the contrary, I =
shall try=20
      to illustrate my feeling that here Paley could have gone even =
further.=20
      When it comes to feeling awe over living 'watches' I yield to =
nobody. I=20
      feel more in common with the Reverend William Paley than I do with =
the=20
      distinguished modern philosopher, a well-known atheist, with whom =
I once=20
      discussed the matter at dinner. I said that I could not imagine =
being an=20
      atheist at any time before 1859, when Darwin's </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Origin of Species =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">was published. 'What about =
Hume?',=20
      replied the philosopher. 'How did Hume explain the organized =
complexity of=20
      the living world?', I asked. 'He didn't', said </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">the </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">philosopher. 'Why does it need =
any=20
      special explanation?' </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.95pt 0pt 2.65pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D11 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D59 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D11>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D11 =

      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image005.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D59></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.35pt 0pt =
174.5pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
2.15pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Paley knew that it needed a =
special=20
      explanation; Darwin knew it, and I suspect that in his heart of =
hearts my=20
      philosopher companion knew it too. In any case it will be my =
business to=20
      show it here. As for David Hume himself, it is sometimes said that =
that=20
      great Scottish philosopher disposed of the Argument from Design d =
century=20
      before Darwin. But what Hume did was criticize the logic of using =
apparent=20
      design in nature as </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">positive </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">evidence for the existence of a =
God. He=20
      did not offer any </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">alternative </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">explanation for apparent =
design, but left=20
      the question open. An atheist before Darwin could have said, =
following=20
      Hume: 'I have no explanation for complex biological design. All I =
know is=20
      that Cod isn't a good explanation, so we must wait and hope that =
somebody=20
      comes up with a better one.' I can't help feeling that such a =
position,=20
      though logically sound, would have left one feeling pretty =
unsatisfied,=20
      and that although atheism might have been </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">logically </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">tenable before Darwin, Darwin =
made it=20
      possible to be an intellectually fulfilled atheist. I like to =
think that=20
      Hume would agree, but some of his writings suggest that he =
underestimated=20
      the complexity and beauty of biological design. The boy naturalist =
Charles=20
      Darwin could have shown him a thing or two about that, but Hume =
had been=20
      dead 40 years when Darwin enrolled in Hume's university of =
Edinburgh.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.2pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">I have talked glibly of =
complexity, and=20
      of apparent design, as though it were obvious what these words =
mean. In a=20
      sense it is obvious - most people have an intuitive idea of what=20
      complexity means. But these notions, complexity and design, are so =
pivotal=20
      to this book that I must try to capture a little more precisely, =
in words,=20
      our feeling that there is something special about complex, and =
apparently=20
      designed things. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.95pt 0pt 1.45pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">So, what is a complex thing? =
How should=20
      we recognize it? In what sense is it true to say that a watch or =
an=20
      airliner or an earwig or a person is complex, but the moon is =
simple? The=20
      first point that might occur to us, as a necessary attribute of a =
complex=20
      thing, is that it has a heterogeneous structure. A pink milk =
pudding or=20
      blancmange is simple in the sense that, if we slice it in two, the =
two=20
      portions will have the same internal constitution: a blancmange is =

      homogeneous. A car is heterogeneous: unlike a blancmange, almost =
any=20
      portion of the car is different from other portions. Two times =
half a car=20
      does not make a car. This will often amount to saying that a =
complex=20
      object, as opposed to a simple one, has many parts, these parts =
being of=20
      more than one kind. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.3pt 0pt 2.15pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Such heterogeneity, or =
'many-partedness',=20
      may be a necessary condition, but it is not sufficient. Plenty of =
objects=20
      are many-parted and heterogeneous in internal structure, without =
being=20
      complex in the sense in which I want to use the term. Mont Blanc, =
for=20
      instance, consists of many different kinds of rock, all jumbled =
together=20
      in such a </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.3pt 0pt 2.15pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D625 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D380 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D625>
      <P class=3DStyle9 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 140.75pt 0pt =
4.3pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Explaining the very improbable =

      </SPAN></I><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: =
9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.05in; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.55pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">way that, if you sliced the =
mountain=20
      anywhere, the two portions would differ from each other in their =
internal=20
      constitution. Mont Blanc has a heterogeneity of structure not =
possessed by=20
      a blancmange, but it is still not complex in the sense in which a=20
      biologist uses the term. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.65pt 0pt 3.1pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Let us try another tack in our =
quest for=20
      a definition of complexity, and make use of the mathematical idea =
of=20
      probability. Suppose we try out the following definition: a =
complex thing=20
      is something whose constituent parts are arranged in a way that is =

      unlikely to have arisen by chance alone. To borrow an analogy from =
an=20
      eminent astronomer, if you take the parts of an airliner and =
jumble them=20
      up at random, the likelihood that you would happen to assemble a =
working=20
      Boeing is vanishingly small. There are billions of possible ways =
of=20
      putting together the bits of an airliner, and only one, or very =
few, of=20
      them would actually be an airliner. There are even more ways of =
putting=20
      together the scrambled parts of a human. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.95pt 0pt 2.15pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">This approach to a definition =
of=20
      complexity is promising, but something more is still needed. There =
are=20
      billions of ways of throwing together the bits of Mont Blanc, it =
might be=20
      said, and only one of them is Mont Blanc. So what is it that makes =
the=20
      airliner and the human complicated, if Mont Blanc is simple? Any =
old=20
      jumbled collection of parts is unique and, </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">with hindsight, =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">is as improbable as any other. =
The=20
      scrap-heap at an aircraft breaker's yard is unique. No two =
scrap-heaps are=20
      the same. If you start throwing fragments of aeroplanes into =
heaps, the=20
      odds of your happening to hit upon exactly the same arrangement of =
junk=20
      twice are just about as low as the odds of your throwing together =
a=20
      working airliner. So, why don't we say that a rubbish dump, or =
Mont Blanc,=20
      or the moon, is just as complex as an aeroplane or a dog, because =
in all=20
      these cases the arrangement of atoms is 'improbable'? </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.95pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The combination lock on my =
bicycle has=20
      4,096 different positions. Every one of these is equally =
'improbable' in=20
      the sense that, if you spin the wheels at random, every one of the =
4,096=20
      positions is equally unlikely to turn up. I can spin the wheels at =
random,=20
      look at whatever number is displayed and exclaim with hindsight: =
'How=20
      amazing. The odds against that number appearing are 4,096:1. A =
minor=20
      miracle!' That is equivalent to regarding the particular =
arrangement of=20
      rocks in a mountain, or of bits of metal in a scrap-heap, as =
'complex'.=20
      But one of those 4,096 wheel positions really is interestingly =
unique: the=20
      combination 1207 is the only one that opens the lock. The =
uniqueness of=20
      1207 has nothing to do with hindsight: it is specified in advance =
by the=20
      manufacturer. If you spun the wheels at random and happened to hit =
1207=20
      first time, you would be able to steal the bike, and it would seem =
a minor=20
      miracle. If you struck lucky </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">on </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">one of those multi-dialled =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.95pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D381 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.25pt 0pt =
174pt"><B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: 'Times-Bold Italic'">The Blind =
</SPAN></I></B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Watchmaker </SPAN></I><I><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"LINE-HEIGHT: 11.6pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.05in"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">combination locks on bank =
safes, it would=20
      seem a very major miracle, for the odds against it are many =
millions to=20
      one, and you would be able to steal a fortune. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.3pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Now, hitting upon the lucky =
number that=20
      opens the bank's safe is the equivalent, in our analogy, of =
hurling scrap=20
      metal around at random and happening to assemble a Boeing 747. Of =
all the=20
      millions of unique and, with hindsight equally improbable, =
positions of=20
      the combination lock, only one opens the lock. Similarly, of all =
the=20
      millions of unique and, with hindsight equally improbable, =
arrangements of=20
      a heap of junk, only one (or very few) will fly. The uniqueness of =
the=20
      arrangement that flies, or that opens the safe, is nothing to do =
with=20
      hindsight. It is specified in advance. The lock-manufacturer fixed =
the=20
      combination, and he has told the bank manager. The ability to fly =
is a=20
      property of an airliner that we specify in advance. If we see a =
plane in=20
      the air we can be sure that it was not assembled by randomly =
throwing=20
      scrap metal together, because we know that the odds against a =
random=20
      conglomeration's being able to fly are too great. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.6pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Now, if you consider all =
possible ways in=20
      which the rocks of Mont Blanc could have been thrown together, it =
is true=20
      that only one of them would make Mont Blanc as we know it. But =
Mont Blanc=20
      as we know it is defined with hindsight. Any one of a very large =
number of=20
      ways of throwing rocks together would be labelled a mountain, and =
might=20
      have been named Mont Blanc. There is nothing special about the =
particular=20
      Mont Blanc that we know, nothing specified in advance, nothing =
equivalent=20
      to the plane taking off, or equivalent to the safe door swinging =
open and=20
      the money tumbling out. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.7pt 0pt 2.15pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">What is the equivalent of the =
safe door=20
      swinging open, or the plane flying, in the case of a living body? =
Well,=20
      sometimes it is almost literally the same. Swallows fly. As we =
have seen,=20
      it isn't easy to throw together a flying machine. If you took all =
the=20
      cells of a swallow and put them together at random, the chance =
that the=20
      resulting object would fly is not, for everyday purposes, =
different from=20
      zero. Not all living things fly, but they do other things that are =
just as=20
      improbable, and just as specifiable in advance. Whales don't fly, =
but they=20
      do swim, and swim about as efficiently as swallows fly. The chance =
that a=20
      random conglomeration of whale cells would swim, let alone swim as =
fast=20
      and efficiently as a whale actually does swim, is negligible. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.5pt 0pt 0.05in; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">At this point, some hawk-eyed =
philosopher=20
      (hawks have very acute eyes =97 you couldn't make a hawk's eye by =
throwing=20
      lenses and lightsensitive cells together at random) will start =
mumbling=20
      something about a circular argument. Swallows fly but they don't =
swim; and=20
      whales swim but they don't fly. It is with hindsight that we =
decide=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.5pt 0pt 0.05in; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D9 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D66 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D9>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D9=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image006.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D66></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D625 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D625>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 140.6pt 0pt 3.1pt"><I><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Explaining the very improbable =

      </SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05pt 0pt 2.65pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">whether to judge the success of =
our=20
      random conglomeration as a swimmer or as a flyer. Suppose we agree =
to=20
      judge its success as an Xer, and leave open exactly what X is =
until we=20
      have tried throwing cells together. The random lump of cells might =
turn=20
      out to be an efficient burrower like a mole or an efficient =
climber like a=20
      monkey. It might be very good at wind-surfing, or at clutching =
oily rags,=20
      or at walking in ever decreasing circles until it vanished. The =
list could=20
      go on and on. Or could it? </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.85pt 0pt 1.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">If the list really =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">could </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">go on and on, my hypothetical =
philosopher=20
      might have a point. If, no matter how randomly you threw matter =
around,=20
      the resulting conglomeration could often be said, with hindsight, =
to be=20
      good for </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">something,=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">then it would =
be true to=20
      say that I cheated over the swallow and the whale. But biologists =
can be=20
      much more specific than that about what would constitute being =
'good for=20
      something'. The minimum requirement for us to recognize an object =
as an=20
      animal or plant is that it should succeed in making a living=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">of some sort=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">(more =
precisely that it,=20
      or at least some members of its kind, should live long enough to=20
      reproduce). It is true that there are quite a number of ways of =
making a=20
      living - flying, swimming, swinging through the trees, and so on. =
But,=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">however many =
ways there=20
      may be of being alive, it is certain that there are vastly more =
ways of=20
      being dead, </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">or =
rather=20
      not alive. You may throw cells together at random, over and over =
again for=20
      a billion years, and not once will you get a conglomeration that =
flies or=20
      swims or burrows or runs, or does </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">anything, </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">even badly, that could remotely =
be=20
      construed as working to keep itself alive. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.2pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">This has been quite a long, =
drawn-out=20
      argument, and it is time to remind ourselves of how we got into it =
in the=20
      first place. We were looking for a precise way to express what we =
mean=20
      when we refer to something as complicated. We were trying to put a =
finger=20
      on what it is that humans and moles and earthworms and airliners =
and=20
      watches have in common with each other, but not with blancmange, =
or Mont=20
      Blanc, or the moon. The answer we have arrived at is that =
complicated=20
      things have some quality, specifiable in advance, that is highly =
unlikely=20
      to have been acquired by random chance alone. In the case of =
living=20
      things, the quality that is specified in advance is, in some =
sense,=20
      'proficiency'; either proficiency in a particular ability such as =
flying,=20
      as an aero-engineer might admire it; or proficiency in something =
more=20
      general, such as the ability to stave off death, or the ability to =

      propagate genes in reproduction. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-RIGHT: 2.35pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Staving off death is a thing =
that you=20
      have to work at. Left to itself - and that is what it is when it =
dies -=20
      the body tends to revert to a state of </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-RIGHT: 2.35pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D11 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D28 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D11>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D11 =

      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image007.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D28></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D377 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.4pt 0pt 0.5pt"><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">10 </SPAN></B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">equilibrium with its =
environment. If you=20
      measure some quantity such as the temperature, the acidity, the =
water=20
      content or the electrical potential in a living body, you will =
typically=20
      find that it is markedly different from the corresponding measure =
in the=20
      surroundings. Our bodies, for instance, are usually hotter than =
our=20
      surroundings, and in cold climates they have to work hard to =
maintain the=20
      differential. When we die the work stops, the temperature =
differential=20
      starts to disappear, and we end up the same temperature as our=20
      surroundings. Not all animals work so hard to avoid coming into=20
      equilibrium with their surrounding temperature, but all animals do =

      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">some =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">comparable work. For instance, =
in a dry=20
      country, animals and plants work to maintain the fluid content of =
their=20
      cells, work against a natural tendency for water to flow from them =
into=20
      the dry outside world. If they fail they die. More generally, if =
living=20
      things didn't work actively to prevent it, they would eventually =
merge=20
      into their surroundings, and cease to exist as autonomous beings. =
That is=20
      what happens when they die. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.7pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">With the exception of =
artificial=20
      machines, which we have already agreed to count as honorary living =
things,=20
      nonliving things don't work in this sense. They accept the forces =
that=20
      tend to bring them into equilibrium with their surroundings. Mont =
Blanc,=20
      to be sure, has existed for a long time, and probably will exist =
for a=20
      while yet, but it does not work to stay in existence. When rock =
comes to=20
      rest under the influence of gravity it just stays there. No work =
has to be=20
      done to keep it there. Mont Blanc exists, and it will go on =
existing until=20
      it wears away or an earthquake knocks it over. It doesn't take =
steps to=20
      repair wear and tear, or to right itself when it is knocked over, =
the way=20
      a living body does. It just obeys the ordinary laws of physics.=20
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.7pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Is this to deny that living =
things obey=20
      the laws of physics? Certainly not. There is no reason to think =
that the=20
      laws of physics are violated in living matter. There is nothing=20
      supernatural, no 'life force' to rival the fundamental forces of =
physics.=20
      It is just that if you try to use the laws of physics, in a naive =
way, to=20
      understand the behaviour of a </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">whole </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">living body, you will find that =
you don't=20
      get very far. The body is a complex thing with many constituent =
parts, and=20
      to understand its behaviour you must apply the laws of physics to =
its=20
      parts, not to the whole. The behaviour of the body as a whole will =
then=20
      emerge as a consequence of interactions of the parts. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.45pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.35pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Take the laws of motion, for =
instance. If=20
      you throw a dead bird into the air it will describe a graceful =
parabola,=20
      exactly as physics books say it should, then come to rest on the =
ground=20
      and stay there. It behaves as a solid body of a particular mass =
and wind=20
      resistance ought to behave. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.45pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.35pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D383 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle5 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 6.5pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Explaining the very improbable =

      </SPAN></I><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">11 =
</SPAN></B><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.15pt 0pt 5.5pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">But if you throw a live bird in =
the air=20
      it will not describe a parabola and come to rest on the ground. It =
will=20
      fly away, and may not touch land this side of the county boundary. =
The=20
      reason is that it has muscles which work to resist gravity and =
other=20
      physical forces bearing upon the whole body. The laws of physics =
are being=20
      obeyed within every cell of the muscles. The result is that the =
muscles=20
      move the wings in such a way that the bird stays aloft. The bird =
is not=20
      violating the law of gravity. It is constantly being pulled =
downwards by=20
      gravity, but its wings are performing active work - obeying laws =
of=20
      physics within its muscles - to keep it aloft in spite of the =
force of=20
      gravity. We shall think that it defies a physical law if we are =
naive=20
      enough to treat it simply as a structureless lump of matter with a =
certain=20
      mass and wind <BR>resistance. It is only when we remember that it =
has many=20
      internal parts, all obeying laws of physics at their own level, =
that we=20
      understand the behaviour of the whole body. This is not, of =
course, a=20
      peculiarity of living things. It applies to all man-made machines, =
and=20
      potentially applies to any complex, many-parted object. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.8pt 0pt 2.65pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">This brings me to the final =
topic that I=20
      want to discuss in this rather philosophical chapter, the problem =
of what=20
      we mean by explanation. We have seen what we are going to mean by =
a=20
      complex thing. But what kind of explanation will satisfy us if we =
wonder=20
      how a complicated machine, or living body, works? The answer is =
the one=20
      that we arrived at in the previous paragraph. If we wish to =
understand how=20
      a machine or living body works, we look to its component parts and =
ask how=20
      they interact with each other. If there is a complex thing that we =
do not=20
      yet understand, we can come to understand it in terms of simpler =
parts=20
      that we do already understand. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4pt 0pt 1.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">If I ask an engineer how a =
steam engine=20
      works, I have a pretty fair idea of the general kind of answer =
that would=20
      satisfy me. Like Julian Huxley I should definitely not be =
impressed if the=20
      engineer said it was propelled by </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">'force locomotif. =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">And if he started boring on =
about the=20
      whole being greater than the sum of its parts, I would interrupt =
him:=20
      'Never mind about that, tell me how it </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">works.' </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">What I would want to hear is =
something=20
      about how the parts of an engine interact with each other to =
produce the=20
      behaviour of the whole engine. I would initially be prepared to =
accept an=20
      explanation in terms of quite large <BR>subcomponents, whose own =
internal=20
      structure and behaviour might be quite complicated and, as yet,=20
      unexplained. The units of an initially satisfying explanation =
could have=20
      names like fire-box, boiler, cylinder, piston, steam governor. The =

      engineer would assert, without explanation initially, what each of =
these=20
      </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">units =
</SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">does. I would accept this =
</SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">for </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the moment, without asking how=20
      </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">each =
</SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">unit does its own particular =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4pt 0pt 1.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D11 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D29 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D11>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D11 =

      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image008.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D29></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.2pt 0pt 0.95pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">12 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.8pt 0pt 0.25pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">thing. </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Given </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">that the units each do their =
particular=20
      thing, I can then understand how they interact to make the whole =
engine=20
      move. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.65pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Of course, I am then at liberty =
to ask=20
      how each part works. Having previously accepted the =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">fact </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">that the steam governor =
regulates the=20
      flow of steam, and having used this fact in my understanding of =
the=20
      <BR>behaviour of the whole engine, I now turn my curiosity on the =
steam=20
      governor itself. I now want to understand how it achieves its own=20
      behaviour, in terms of its own internal parts. There is a =
hierarchy of=20
      subcomponents within components. We explain the behaviour of a =
component=20
      at any given level, in terms of interactions between subcomponents =
whose=20
      own internal organization, for the moment, is taken for granted. =
We peel=20
      our way down the hierarchy, until we reach units so simple that, =
for=20
      everyday purposes, we no longer feel the need to ask questions =
about them.=20
      Rightly or wrongly for instance, most of us are happy about the =
properties=20
      of rigid rods of iron, and we are prepared to use them as units of =

      explanation of more complex machines that contain them. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.65pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Physicists, of course, do not =
take iron=20
      rods for granted. They ask why they are rigid, and they continue =
the=20
      hierarchical peeling for several more layers yet, down to =
fundamental=20
      particles and quarks. But life is too short for most of us to =
follow them.=20
      For any given level of complex organization, satisfying =
explanations may=20
      normally be attained if we peel the hierarchy down one or two =
layers from=20
      our starting layer, but not more. The behaviour of a motor car is=20
      explained in terms of cylinders, carburettors and sparking plugs. =
It is=20
      true that each one of these components rests atop a pyramid of=20
      explanations at lower levels. But if you asked me how a motor car =
worked=20
      you would think me somewhat pompous if I answered in terms of =
Newton's=20
      laws and the laws of thermodynamics, and downright obscurantist if =
I=20
      answered in terms of fundamental particles. It is doubtless true =
that at=20
      bottom the behaviour of a motor car is to be explained in terms of =

      interactions between fundamental particles. But it is much more =
useful to=20
      explain it in terms of interactions between pistons, cylinders and =

      sparking plugs. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.85pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The behaviour of a computer can =
be=20
      explained in terms of interactions between semiconductor =
electronic gates,=20
      and the behaviour of these, in turn, is explained by physicists at =
yet=20
      lower levels. But, for most purposes, you would in practice be =
wasting=20
      your time if you tried to understand the behaviour of the whole =
computer=20
      at either of those levels. There are too many electronic gates and =
too=20
      many <BR>interconnections between them. A satisfying explanation =
has to be=20
      in terms of a manageably small number of interactions. This is =
why, if we=20
      want to </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.85pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D385 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 6.95pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Explaining the very improbable =

      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">13 =
<BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.4pt 0pt 6pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.55pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">understand the workings of =
computers, we=20
      prefer a preliminary explanation in terms of about half a dozen =
major=20
      subcomponents - memory, processing mill, backing store, control =
unit,=20
      input-output handler, etc. Having grasped the interactions between =
the=20
      half-dozen major components, we then may wish to ask questions =
about the=20
      internal organization- of these major components. Only specialist=20
      engineers are likely to go down to the level of AND gates and NOR =
gates,=20
      and only physicists will go down further, to the level of how =
electrons=20
      behave in a semiconducting medium. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.4pt 0pt 4.55pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">For those that like '-ism' =
sorts of=20
      names, the aptest name for my approach to understanding how things =
work is=20
      probably 'hierarchical reductionism'. If you read trendy =
intellectual=20
      magazines, you may have noticed that 'reductionism' is one of =
those=20
      things, like sin, that is only mentioned by people who are against =
it. To=20
      call oneself a reductionist will sound, in some circles, a bit =
like=20
      admitting to eating babies. But, just as nobody actually eats =
babies, so=20
      nobody is really a reductionist in any sense worth being against. =
The=20
      nonexistent reductionist - the sort that everybody is against, but =
who=20
      exists only in their imaginations - tries to explain complicated =
things=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">directly=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">in terms of =
the=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">smallest=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">parts, even, =
in some=20
      extreme versions of the myth, as the </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">sum </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">of the parts! The hierarchical=20
      reductionist, on the other hand, explains a complex entity at any=20
      particular level in the hierarchy of organization, in terms of =
entities=20
      only one level down the hierarchy; entities which, themselves, are =
likely=20
      to be complex enough to need further reducing to their own =
component=20
      parts; and so on. It goes without saying - though the mythical,=20
      baby-eating reductionist is reputed to deny this - that the kinds =
of=20
      explanations which are suitable at high levels in the hierarchy =
are quite=20
      different from the kinds of explanations which are suitable at =
lower=20
      levels. This was the point of explaining cars in terms of =
carburettors=20
      rather than quarks. But the hierarchical reductionist believes =
that=20
      carburettors are explained in terms of smaller units . . ., which =
are=20
      explained in terms of smaller units . . . , which are ultimately =
explained=20
      in terms of the smallest of fundamental particles. Reductionism, =
in this=20
      sense, is just another name for an honest desire to understand how =
things=20
      work. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 6.7pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">We began this section by asking =
what kind=20
      of explanation for complicated things would satisfy us. We have =
just=20
      considered the question from the point of view of mechanism: how =
does it=20
      work? We concluded that the behaviour of a complicated thing =
should be=20
      explained in terms of interactions between its component parts, =
considered=20
      as successive layers of an orderly hierarchy. But another kind of =
question=20
      is how the complicated thing came into existence in the first =
place. This=20
      is the </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 6.7pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D630 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D630>
      <P class=3DStyle18 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.55pt 0pt 0.7pt">14 =
<I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker=20
      </SPAN><BR><BR></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle19 style=3D"LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
2pt">question=20
      that this whole book is particularly concerned with, so I won't =
say much=20
      more about it here. I shall just mention that the same general =
principle=20
      applies as for understanding mechanism. A complicated thing is one =
whose=20
      existence we do not feel inclined to take for granted, because it =
is too=20
      'improbable'. It could not have come into existence in a single =
act of=20
      chance. We shall explain its coming into existence as a =
consequence of=20
      gradual, cumulative, step-by-step transformations from simpler =
things,=20
      from primordial objects sufficiently simple to have come into =
being by=20
      chance. Just as 'big-step reductionism' cannot work as an =
explanation of=20
      mechanism, and must be replaced by a series of small step-by-step =
peelings=20
      down through the hierarchy, so we can't explain a complex thing as =

      <I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">originating =
</SPAN></I>in a=20
      single step. We must again resort to a series of small steps, this =
time=20
      arranged sequentially in time. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.75pt 0pt 0.7pt">In his =
beautifully=20
      written book, <I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The =
Creation,=20
      </SPAN></I>the Oxford physical chemist Peter Atkins begins: </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 11.65pt 0pt 10.3pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 9.9pt">I =
shall take=20
      your mind on a journey. It is a journey of comprehension, taking =
us to the=20
      edge of space, time, and understanding. On it I shall argue that =
there is=20
      nothing that cannot be understood, that there is nothing that =
cannot be=20
      explained, and that everything is extraordinarily simple ... A =
great deal=20
      of the universe does not need any explanation. Elephants, <B><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">for </SPAN></B>instance. Once =
molecules=20
      have learnt to compete and to create other molecules in their own =
image,=20
      elephants, and things resembling elephants, will in due course be =
found=20
      roaming through the countryside. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 1.2pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt">Atkins =
assumes=20
      the evolution of complex things - the subject matter of this book =
- to be=20
      inevitable once the appropriate physical conditions have been set =
up. He=20
      asks what the minimum necessary physical conditions are, what is =
the=20
      minimum amount of design work that a very lazy Creator would have =
to do,=20
      in order to see to it that the universe and, later, elephants and =
other=20
      complex things, would one day come into existence. The answer, =
from his=20
      point of view as a physical scientist, is that the Creator could =
be=20
      infinitely lazy. The fundamental original units that we need to =
postulate,=20
      in order to understand the coming into existence of everything, =
either=20
      consist of literally nothing (according to some physicists), or =
(according=20
      to other physicists) they are units of the utmost simplicity, far =
too=20
      simple <B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">to =
</SPAN></B>need=20
      anything so grand as deliberate Creation. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.4pt 0pt 1.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt">Atkins=20
      says that elephants and complex things do not need any =
explanation. But=20
      that is because he is a physical scientist, who takes for granted =
the=20
      biologists' theory of evolution. He doesn't really mean that =
elephants=20
      don't need an explanation; rather that he is satisfied that =
biologists can=20
      explain elephants, provided they are allowed to take </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.4pt 0pt 1.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D625 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D382 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D625>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 5.05pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Explaining =
</SPAN></I><B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: 'Times-Bold Italic'">the very improbable=20
      </SPAN></I></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">15=20
      <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.55pt 0pt 4.55pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">certain facts of physics for =
granted. His=20
      task as a physical scientist, therefore, is to justify our taking =
those=20
      facts for granted. This he succeeds in doing. My position is=20
      complementary. I am a biologist. I take the facts of physics, the =
facts of=20
      the world of simplicity, for granted. If physicists still don't =
agree over=20
      whether those simple facts are yet understood, that is not my =
problem. My=20
      task is to explain elephants, and the world of complex things, in =
terms of=20
      the simple things that physicists either understand, or are =
working on.=20
      The <BR>physicist's problem is the problem of ultimate origins and =

      ultimate natural laws. The biologist's problem is the problem of=20
      complexity. The biologist tries to explain the workings, and the =
coming=20
      into existence, of complex things, in terms of simpler things. He =
can=20
      regard his task as done when he has arrived at entities =
</SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">so </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">simple that they can safely be =
handed=20
      over to physicists. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle6=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.4pt 0pt 2.65pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">I am aware that my =
characterization of a=20
      complex object - statistically improbable in a direction that is =
specified=20
      not with hindsight - may seem idiosyncratic. So, too, may seem my=20
      characterization of physics as the study of simplicity. If you =
prefer some=20
      other way of defining complexity, I don't care and I would be =
happy to go=20
      along with your definition for the sake of discussion. But what I =
do care=20
      about is that, whatever we choose to </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">call </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the quality of being=20
      statisticallyimprobable- =
in-a-direction-specified-without-hindsight,itisan=20
      <BR>important quality that needs a special effort of explanation. =
It is=20
      the quality that characterizes biological objects as opposed to =
the=20
      objects of <BR>physics. The kind of explanation we come up with =
must not=20
      contradict the laws of physics. Indeed it will make use of the =
laws of=20
      physics, and nothing more than the laws of physics. But it will =
deploy the=20
      laws of physics in a special way that is not ordinarily discussed =
in=20
      physics textbooks. That special way is Darwin's way. I shall =
introduce its=20
      fundamental essence in Chapter 3 under the title of =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">cumulative </SPAN></I><I><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR></SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">selection. </SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 5.6pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Meanwhile I want to follow =
Paley in=20
      emphasizing the magnitude of the problem that our explanation =
faces, the=20
      sheer hugeness of <BR>biological complexity and the beauty and =
elegance of=20
      biological design. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 5.1pt 0pt 0.7pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Chapter 2 is an extended =
discussion of a=20
      particular example, 'radar' in bats, discovered long after Paley's =
time.=20
      And here, in this chapter, I have placed an illustration (Figure =
1) =97 how=20
      Paley would have loved the electron microscope! - of an eye =
together with=20
      two successive ' <BR>zoomings in' on detailed portions. At the top =
of the=20
      figure is a section through an eye itself. This level of =
magnification=20
      shows the eye as an optical instrument. The resemblance to a =
camera is=20
      obvious. The iris diaphragm is responsible for constantly varying =
the=20
      aperture, the / stop. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 5.1pt 0pt 0.7pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall></DIV><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<DIV class=3DSection5>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D51 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D131 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D51>
      <P class=3DStyle9><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The =
Blind=20
      Watchmaker </SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle22 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 9.65pt 0pt =
32.15pt">Transparent jelly=20
      </P>
      <P class=3DStyle22 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 9.65pt 0pt 32.15pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D546 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D354 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D546>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 8.5pt; COLOR: =
black"><IMG=20
      height=3D546=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
