;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image009.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D355></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 8.5pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D625 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D625>
      <P class=3DStyle24 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.9pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Explaining the very improbable =

      </SPAN></I>17 <SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.5pt 0pt 1.2pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The lens, which is really only =
part of a=20
      compound lens system, is responsible for the variable part of the=20
      focusing. Focus is changed by squeezing the lens with muscles (or =
in=20
      chameleons by moving the lens forwards or backwards, as in a =
man-made=20
      camera). The image falls on the retina at the back, where it =
excites=20
      photocells. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.05pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The middle part of Figure 1 =
shows a small=20
      section of the retina enlarged. Light comes from the left. The=20
      light-sensitive cells (' photocells') are not the first thing the =
light=20
      hits, but they are buried inside and facing away from the light. =
This odd=20
      feature is mentioned again later. The first thing the light hits =
is, in=20
      fact, the layer of ganglion cells which constitute the 'electronic =

      interface' between the photocells and the brain. Actually the =
ganglion=20
      cells are responsible for preprocessing the information in =
sophisticated=20
      ways before relaying it to the brain, and in some ways the word=20
      'interface' doesn't do justice to this. 'Satellite computer' might =
be a=20
      fairer name. Wires from the ganglion cells run along the surface =
of the=20
      retina to the 'blind spot', where they dive through the retina to =
form the=20
      main trunk cable to the brain, the optic nerve. There are about =
three=20
      million ganglion cells in the ' electronic interface', gathering =
data from=20
      about 125 million photocells. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.25pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">At the bottom of the figure is =
one=20
      enlarged photocell, a rod. As you look at the fine architecture of =
this=20
      cell, keep in mind the fact that all that complexity is repeated =
125=20
      million times in each retina. And comparable complexity is =
repeated=20
      trillions of times elsewhere in the body as a whole. The figure of =
125=20
      million photocells is about 5,000 times the number of separately=20
      resolvable points in a good-quality magazine photograph. The =
folded=20
      membranes on the right of the illustrated photocell are the actual =

      light-gathering structures. Their layered form increases the =
photocell's=20
      efficiency in capturing photons, the fundamental particles of =
which light=20
      is made. If a photon is not caught by the first membrane, it may =
be caught=20
      by the second, and so on. As a result of this, some eyes are =
capable of=20
      detecting a single photon. The fastest and most sensitive film =
emulsions=20
      available to photographers need about 25 times as many photons in =
order to=20
      detect a point of light. The lozenge-shaped objects in the middle =
section=20
      of the cell are mostly mitochondria. Mitochondria are found not =
just in=20
      photocells, but in most other cells. Each one can be thought of as =
a=20
      chemical factory which, in the course of delivering its primary =
product of=20
      usable energy, processes more than 700 different chemical =
substances, in=20
      long, interweaving assembly-lines strung out along the surface of =
its=20
      intricately folded internal membranes. The round globule at the =
left of=20
      Figure 1 is the nucleus. Again, this is characteristic of all =
animal and=20
      plant cells. Each nucleus, as we shall see in Chapter 5, contains =
a=20
      digitally coded </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.25pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D127 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D377 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D127>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">18 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05pt 0pt 0.5pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">database larger, in information =
content,=20
      than all 30 volumes of the </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Encyclopaedia Britannica=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">put together. =
And this=20
      figure is for </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">each=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">cell, not all =
the cells=20
      of a body put together. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle6=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.4pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The rod at the base of the =
picture is one=20
      single cell. The total number of cells in the body (of a human) is =
about=20
      10 trillion. When you </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold">eat=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">a steak, you =
are=20
      shredding the equivalent of more than 100 billion copies of the=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Encyclopaedia=20
      Britannica. </SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle6=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.4pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D9 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D43 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D9>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic"><IMG height=3D9=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image010.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D43></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
