style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<DIV class=3DSection6>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D510 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D361 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D510>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"><IMG=20
      height=3D510=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image012.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D361></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D560 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D375 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D560>
      <P class=3DStyle16 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 105.2pt 0pt =
107.05pt">CHAPTER 2 <SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <H2 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 70.1pt 0pt 77.3pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 17pt">GOOD DESIGN </SPAN><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR><BR><BR></SPAN></H2>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Natural selection is the blind=20
      watchmaker, blind because it does not see ahead, does not plan=20
      consequences, has no purpose in view. Yet the living results of =
natural=20
      selection overwhelmingly impress us with the appearance of design =
as if by=20
      a master watchmaker, impress us with the illusion of design and =
planning.=20
      The purpose of this book is to resolve this paradox to the =
satisfaction of=20
      the reader, and the purpose of this chapter is further to impress =
the=20
      reader with the power of the illusion of design. We shall look at =
a=20
      particular example and shall conclude that, when it comes to =
complexity=20
      and beauty of design, Paley hardly even began to state the case.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.45pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.35pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">We may say that a living body =
or organ is=20
      well designed if it has attributes that an intelligent and =
knowledgeable=20
      engineer might have built into it in order to achieve some =
sensible=20
      purpose, such as flying, swimming, seeing, eating, reproducing, or =
more=20
      generally promoting the survival and replication of the organism's =
genes.=20
      It is not necessary to suppose that the design of a body or organ =
is the=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">best =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">that </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">an </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">engineer could conceive of. =
Often the=20
      best that one engineer can do is, in any case, exceeded by the =
best that=20
      another engineer can do, especially another who lives later in the =
history=20
      of technology. But any engineer can recognize an object that has =
been=20
      designed, even poorly designed, for a purpose, and he can usually =
work out=20
      what that purpose is just by looking at the structure of the =
object. In=20
      Chapter 1 we bothered ourselves mostly with philosophical aspects. =
In this=20
      chapter, I shall develop a particular factual example that I =
believe would=20
      impress any engineer, namely sonar ('radar') in bats. In =
explaining each=20
      point, I shall begin by posing a problem that the living machine =
faces;=20
      then I shall consider possible solutions to the problem that a =
sensible=20
      <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.6pt 0pt =
258.75pt"><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">21 </SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.6pt 0pt 258.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D624 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D376 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D624>
      <P class=3DStyle10 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.15pt 0pt 0.95pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica">22 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica-Oblique">The Bli"d Watchmaker=20
      </SPAN></I><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: =
9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">engineer might consider; I =
shall finally=20
      come to the solution that nature has actually adopted. This one =
example=20
      is, of course, just for illustration. If an engineer is impressed =
by bats,=20
      he will be impressed by countless other examples of living design. =

      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.25pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Bats have a problem: how to =
find their=20
      way around in the dark. They hunt at night, and cannot use light =
to help=20
      them find prey and avoid obstacles. You might say that if this is =
a=20
      problem it is a problem of their own making, a problem that they =
could=20
      avoid simply by changing their habits and hunting by day. But the =
daytime=20
      economy is already heavily exploited by other creatures such as =
birds.=20
      Given that there is a living to be made at night, and given that=20
      alternative daytime trades are thoroughly occupied, natural =
selection has=20
      favoured bats that make a go of the night-hunting trade. It is =
probable,=20
      by the way, that the nocturnal trades go way back in the ancestry =
of all=20
      us mammals. In the time when the dinosaurs dominated the daytime =
economy,=20
      our mammalian ancestors probably only managed to survive at all =
because=20
      they found ways of scraping a living at night. Only after the =
mysterious=20
      mass extinction of the dinosaurs about 65 million years ago were =
our=20
      ancestors able to emerge into the daylight in any substantial =
numbers.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.75pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Returning to bats, they have an =

      engineering problem: how to find their way and find their prey in =
the=20
      absence of light. Bats are not the only creatures to face this =
difficulty=20
      today. Obviously the night-flying insects that they prey on must =
find=20
      their way about somehow. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.95pt 0pt 0.5pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Deepsea fish and whales have =
little or no=20
      light by day or by night, because the sun's rays cannot penetrate =
far=20
      below the surface. Fish and dolphins that live in extremely muddy =
water=20
      cannot see because, although there is light, it is obstructed and=20
      scattered by the dirt in the water. Plenty of other modern animals =
make=20
      their living in conditions where seeing is difficult or =
impossible.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.7pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Given the question of how to =
manoeuvre in=20
      the dark, what solutions might an engineer consider? The first one =
that=20
      might occur to him is to manufacture light, to use a lantern or a=20
      searchlight. Fireflies and some fish (usually with the help of =
bacteria)=20
      have the power to manufacture their own light, but the process =
seems to=20
      consume a large amount of energy. Fireflies use their light for =
attracting=20
      mates. This doesn't require prohibitively much energy: a male's =
tiny=20
      pinprick can be seen by a female from some distance on a dark =
night, since=20
      her eyes are exposed directly to the light source itself. Using =
light to=20
      find one's own way around requires vastly more energy, since the =
eyes have=20
      to detect the tiny fraction of the light that bounces off each =
part of the=20
      scene. The light source must therefore be immensely brighter if it =
is to=20
      be used as a headlight to illuminate the path, than if it is to be =
used as=20
      a signal to </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.7pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D624 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D380 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D624>
      <P class=3DStyle10 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 4.1pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica-Oblique">Good design 13 =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.4pt 0pt 3.35pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">others. Anyway, whether or not =
the reason=20
      is the energy expense, it seems to be the case that, with the =
possible=20
      exception of some weird deep-sea fish, no animal apart from man =
uses=20
      manufactured light to find its way about. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.5pt 0pt 2.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">What else might the engineer =
think of?=20
      Well, blind humans sometimes seem to have an uncanny sense of =
obstacles in=20
      their path. It has been given the name 'facial vision', because =
blind=20
      people have reported that it feels a bit like the sense of touch, =
on the=20
      face. One report tells of a totally blind boy who could ride his =
tricycle=20
      at a good speed round the block near his home, using 'facial =
vision'.=20
      Experiments showed that, in fact, 'facial vision' is nothing to do =
with=20
      touch or the front of the face, although the sensation may be=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">referred=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">to the front =
of the=20
      face, like the referred pain in a phantom (severed) limb. The =
sensation of=20
      'facial vision', it turns out, really goes in through the ears. =
The blind=20
      people, without even being aware of the fact, are actually using=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">echoes, =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">of their own footsteps and =
other sounds,=20
      to sense the presence of obstacles. Before this was discovered, =
engineers=20
      had already built instruments to exploit the principle, for =
example to=20
      measure the depth of the sea under a ship. After this technique =
had been=20
      invented, it was only a matter of time before weapons designers =
adapted it=20
      for the detection of submarines. Both sides in the Second World =
War relied=20
      heavily on these devices, under such code names as Asdic (British) =
and=20
      Sonar (American), as well as the similar technology of Radar =
(American) or=20
      RDF (British), which uses radio echoes rather than sound echoes.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.8pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The Sonar and Radar pioneers =
didn't know=20
      it then, but all the world now knows that bats, or rather natural=20
      selection working on bats, had perfected the system tens of =
millions of=20
      years earlier, and their 'radar' achieves feats of detection and=20
      navigation that would strike an engineer dumb with admiration. It =
is=20
      technically incorrect to talk about bat 'radar', since they do not =
use=20
      radio waves. It is sonar. But the underlying mathematical theories =
of=20
      radar and sonar are very similar, and much of our scientific =
understanding=20
      of the details of what bats are doing has come from applying radar =
theory=20
      to them. The American zoologist Donald Griffin, who was largely=20
      responsible for the discovery of sonar in bats, coined the term=20
      'echolocation' to cover both sonar and radar, whether used by =
animals or=20
      by human instruments. In practice, the word seems to be used =
mostly to=20
      refer to animal sonar. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
3.5pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">It is misleading to speak of =
bats as=20
      though they were all the same. It is as though we were to speak of =
dogs,=20
      lions, weasels, bears, hyenas, pandas and otters all in one =
breath, just=20
      because they are all carnivores. Different groups of bats use =
sonar in=20
      radically different ways, and they </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
3.5pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D629 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D376 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D629>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.65pt 0pt 0.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">24 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.25pt 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">seem to have 'invented' =
</SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">it </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">separately and independently, =
just as the=20
      British, Germans and Americans all independently developed radar. =
Not all=20
      bats use echolocation. The Old World tropical fruit bats have good =
vision,=20
      and most of them use only their eyes for finding their way around. =
One or=20
      two species of fruit bats, however, for instance </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Rousettus, </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">are capable of finding their =
way around=20
      in total darkness where eyes, however good, must be powerless. =
They are=20
      using sonar, but it is a cruder kind of sonar than is used by the =
smaller=20
      bats with which we, in temperate regions, are familiar. =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Rousettus </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">clicks its tongue loudly and =
rhythmically=20
      as it flies, and navigates by measuring the time interval between =
each=20
      click and its echo. A good proportion of </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Rousettus's </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">clicks are clearly audible to =
us (which=20
      by definition makes them sound rather than ultrasound: ultrasound =
is just=20
      the same'as sound except that it is too high for humans to hear).=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.4pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">In theory, the higher the pitch =
of a=20
      sound, the better it is for accurate sonar. This is because =
low-pitched=20
      sounds have long wavelengths which cannot resolve the difference =
between=20
      closely spaced objects. All other things being equal therefore, a =
missile=20
      that used echoes for its guidance system would ideally produce =
very=20
      high-pitched sounds. Most bats do, indeed, use extremely =
high-pitched=20
      sounds, far too high for humans to hear - ultrasound. Unlike=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Rousettus,=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">which can see =
very well=20
      and which uses unmodified relatively low-pitched sounds to do a =
modest=20
      amount of echolocation to supplement its good vision, the smaller =
bats=20
      appear to be technically highly advanced echo-machines. They have =
tiny=20
      eyes which, in most cases, probably can't see much. They live in a =
world=20
      of echoes, and probably their brains can use echoes to do =
something akin=20
      to 'seeing' images, although it is next to <BR>impossible for us =
to=20
      'visualize' what those images might be like. The noises that they =
produce=20
      are not just slightly too high for humans to hear, like a kind of =
super=20
      dog whistle. In many cases they are vastly higher than the highest =
note=20
      anybody has heard or can imagine. It is fortunate that we can't =
hear them,=20
      incidentally, for they are immensely powerful and would be =
deafeningly=20
      loud if we could hear them, and impossible to sleep through. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.7pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">These bats are like miniature =
spy planes,=20
      bristling with sophisticated instrumentation. Their brains are =
delicately=20
      tuned packages of miniaturized electronic wizardry, programmed =
with the=20
      elaborate software necessary to decode a world of echoes in real =
time.=20
      Their faces are often distorted into gargoyle shapes that appear =
hideous=20
      to us until we see them for what they are, exquisitely fashioned=20
      instruments for beaming ultrasound in desired directions. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.75pt 0pt 10.3pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Although we can't hear the =
ultrasound=20
      pulses of these bats directly, </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.75pt 0pt 10.3pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D10 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D52 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D10>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D10 =

      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image013.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D52></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D7 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D41 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D7>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D7=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image014.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D41></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D629 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D381 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D629>
      <P class=3DStyle23 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.1pt 0pt 4.1pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Good design </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica">25 </SPAN><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 3.1pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">we can get some idea of what is =
going on=20
      by means of a translating machine or 'bat-detector'. This receives =
the=20
      pulses through a special ultrasonic microphone, and turns each =
pulse into=20
      an audible click or tone which we can hear through headphones. If =
we take=20
      such a ' batdetector' out to a clearing where a bat is feeding, we =
shall=20
      hear </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">when=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">each bat pulse =
is=20
      emitted, although we cannot hear what the pulses really 'sound' =
like. If=20
      our bat is </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">Myotis,=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">one of the =
common little=20
      brown bats, we shall hear a chuntering of clicks at a rate of =
about 10 per=20
      second as the bat cruises about on a routine mission. This is =
about the=20
      rate of a standard teleprinter, or a Bren machine gun. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.05pt 0pt 2.15pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Presumably the bat's image of =
the world=20
      in which it is cruising is being updated 10 times per second. Our =
own=20
      visual image appears to be continuously updated as long as our =
eyes are=20
      open. We can see what it might be like to have an intermittently =
updated=20
      world image, by using a stroboscope at night. This is sometimes =
done at=20
      discotheques, and it produces some dramatic effects. A dancing =
person=20
      appears as a succession of frozen statuesque attitudes. Obviously, =
the=20
      faster we set the strobe, the more the image corresponds to normal =

      'continuous' vision. Stroboscopic vision 'sampling' at the bat's =
cruising=20
      rate of about 10 samples per second would be nearly as good as =
normal=20
      'continuous' vision for some ordinary purposes, though not for =
catching a=20
      ball or an insect. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.4pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">This is just the sampling rate =
of a bat=20
      on a routine cruising flight. When a little brown bat detects an =
insect=20
      and starts to move in on an interception course, its click rate =
goes up.=20
      Faster than a machine gun, it can reach peak rates of 200 pulses =
per=20
      second as the bat finally closes in on the moving target. To mimic =
this,=20
      we should have to speed up our stroboscope so that its flashes =
came twice=20
      as fast as the cycles of mains electricity, which are not noticed =
in a=20
      fluorescent strip light. Obviously we have no trouble in =
performing all=20
      our normal visual functions, even playing squash or ping-pong, in =
a visual=20
      world 'pulsed' at such a high frequency. If we may imagine bat =
brains as=20
      building up an image of the world analogous to our visual images, =
the=20
      pulse rate alone seems to suggest that the bat's echo image might =
be at=20
      least as detailed and 'continuous' as our visual image. Of course, =
there=20
      may be other reasons why it is not so detailed as our visual =
image.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.1pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">If bats are capable of boosting =
their=20
      sampling rates to 200 pulses per second, why don't they keep this =
up all=20
      the time? Since they evidently have a rate control 'knob' on their =

      'stroboscope', why don't they turn it permanently to maximum, =
thereby=20
      keeping their perception of the world at its most acute, all the =
time, to=20
      meet any emergency? One reason is that these high rates are =
suitable only=20
      for near targets. If a pulse </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.1pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.25pt 0pt 1.9pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">26 </SPAN><B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: 'Times-Bold Italic'">The =
</SPAN></I></B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.7pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">follows too hard on the heels =
of its=20
      predecessor it gets mixed up with the echo of its predecessor =
returning=20
      from a distant target. Even if this weren't so, there would =
probably be=20
      good economic reasons for not keeping up the maximum pulse rate =
all the=20
      time. It must be costly producing loud ultrasonic pulses, costly =
in=20
      energy, costly in wear and tear on voice and ears, perhaps costly =
in=20
      computer time. A brain that is processing 200 distinct echoes per =
second=20
      might not find surplus capacity for thinking about anything else. =
Even the=20
      ticking-over rate of about 10 pulses per second is probably quite =
costly,=20
      but much less so than the maximum rate of 200 per second. An =
individual=20
      bat that boosted its tickover rate would pay an additional price =
in=20
      energy, etc., which would not be justified by the increased sonar =
acuity.=20
      When the only moving object in the immediate vicinity is the bat =
itself,=20
      the apparent world is sufficiently similar in successive tenths of =
seconds=20
      that it need not be sampled more frequently than this. When the =
salient=20
      vicinity includes another moving object, particularly a flying =
insect=20
      twisting and turning and diving in a desperate attempt to shake =
off its=20
      pursuer, the extra benefit to the bat of increasing its sample =
rate more=20
      than justifies the increased cost. Of course, the considerations =
of cost=20
      and benefit in this paragraph are all surmise, but something like =
this=20
      almost certainly must be going on. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.2pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The engineer who sets about =
designing an=20
      efficient sonar or radar device soon comes up against a problem =
resulting=20
      from the need to make the pulses extremely loud. They have to be =
loud=20
      because when a sound is broadcast its wavefront advances as an=20
      ever-expanding sphere. The intensity of the sound is distributed =
and, in a=20
      sense, 'diluted' over the whole surface of the sphere. The surface =
area of=20
      any sphere is proportional to the radius squared. The intensity of =
the=20
      sound at any particular point on the sphere therefore decreases, =
not in=20
      proportion to the distance (the radius) but in proportion to the =
square of=20
      the distance from the sound source, as the wavefront advances and =
the=20
      sphere swells. This means that the sound gets quieter pretty fast, =
as it=20
      travels away from its source, in this case the bat. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.95pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">When this diluted sound hits an =
object,=20
      say a fly, it bounces off the fly. This reflected sound now, in =
its turn,=20
      radiates away from the fly in an expanding spherical wavefront. =
For the=20
      same reason as in the case of the original sound, it decays as the =
square=20
      of the distance from the fly. By the time the echo reaches the bat =
again,=20
      the decay in its intensity is proportional, not to the distance of =
the fly=20
      from the bat, not even to the square of that distance, but to =
something=20
      more like the square of the square - the fourth power, of the =
distance.=20
      This means that it is very very quiet indeed. The problem can be =
partially=20
      overcome if the bat </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.95pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 2.15pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Good design </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">27 <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.4pt 0pt 1.7pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">beams the sound by means of the =

      equivalent of a megaphone, but only if it already knows the =
direction of=20
      the target. In any case, if the bat is to receive any reasonable =
echo at=20
      all from a distant target, the outgoing squeak as it leaves the =
bat must=20
      be very loud indeed, and the instrument that detects the echo, the =
ear,=20
      must be highly sensitive </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">to </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">very quiet sounds - the echoes. =
Bat=20
      cries, as we have seen, are indeed often very loud, and their ears =
are=20
      very sensitive. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Now here is the problem that =
would strike=20
      the engineer trying to design a bat-like machine. If the =
microphone, or=20
      ear, is as sensitive as all that, it is in grave danger of being =
seriously=20
      damaged by its own enormously loud outgoing pulse of sound. It is =
no good=20
      trying to combat the problem by making the sounds quieter, for =
then the=20
      echoes would be too quiet to hear. And it is no good trying to =
combat=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">that =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">by making the microphone =
('ear') more=20
      sensitive, since this would only make it more vulnerable to being =
damaged=20
      by the, albeit now slightly quieter, outgoing sounds! It is a =
dilemma=20
      inherent in the dramatic difference in intensity between outgoing =
sound=20
      and returning echo, a difference that is inexorably imposed by the =
laws of=20
      physics. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.65pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">What other solution might occur =
to the=20
      engineer? When </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold">an=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">analogous =
problem struck=20
      the designers of radar in the Second World War, they hit upon a =
solution=20
      which they called 'send/receive' radar. The radar signals were =
sent out in=20
      necessarily very powerful pulses, which might have damaged the =
highly=20
      sensitive aerials (American 'antennas') waiting for the faint =
returning=20
      echoes. The 'send/receive' circuit temporarily disconnected the =
receiving=20
      aerial just before the outgoing pulse was about to be emitted, =
then=20
      switched the aerial on again in time to receive the echo. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.9pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Bats developed 'send/receive' =
switching=20
      technology long long ago, probably millions of years before our =
ancestors=20
      came down from the trees. It works as follows. In bat ears, as in =
ours,=20
      sound is transmitted from the eardrum to the microphonic, =
sound-sensitive=20
      cells by means of a bridge of three tiny bones known (in Latin) as =
the=20
      hammer, the anvil and the stirrup, because of their shape. The =
mounting=20
      and hinging of these three bones, by the way, is exactly as a =
hi-fi=20
      engineer might have designed it to serve a necessary =
'impedance-matching'=20
      function, but that is another story. What matters here is that =
some bats=20
      have well-developed muscles attached to the stirrup and to the =
hammer.=20
      When these muscles are contracted the bones don't transmit sound =
so=20
      efficiently - it is as though you muted a microphone by jamming =
your thumb=20
      against the vibrating diaphragm. The bat is able to use these =
muscles to=20
      switch its ears off temporarily. The muscles contract immediately =
before=20
      the bat emits each outgoing pulse, </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.9pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D377 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle9 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.45pt 0pt 1.45pt">28 =
<I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">thereby switching the ears off =
so that=20
      they are not damaged by the loud pulse. Then they relax so that =
the ear=20
      returns to maximal sensitivity just in time for the returning =
echo. This=20
      send/receive switching system works only if split-second accuracy =
in=20
      timing is maintained. The bat called </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Tadarida </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">is capable of alternately =
contracting and=20
      relaxing its switching muscles 50 times per second, keeping in =
perfect=20
      synchrony with the machine gun-like pulses of ultrasound. It is a=20
      formidable feat of timing, comparable to a clever trick that was =
used in=20
      some fighter planes during the First World War. Their machine guns =
fired=20
      'through' the propeller, the timing being carefully synchronized =
with the=20
      rotation of the propeller so that the bullets always passed =
between the=20
      blades and never shot them off. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.85pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The next problem that might =
occur to our=20
      engineer is the following. If the sonar device is measuring the =
distance=20
      of targets by measuring the duration of silence between the =
emission of a=20
      sound and its returning echo - the method which </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Rousettus, </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">indeed, seems to be using - the =
sounds=20
      would seem to have to be very brief, staccato pulses. A long =
drawn-out=20
      sound would still be going on when the echo returned, and, even if =

      partially muffled by send/receive muscles, would get in the way of =

      detecting the echo. Ideally, it would seem, bat pulses should be =
very=20
      brief indeed. But the briefer a sound is, the more difficult it is =
to make=20
      it energetic enough to produce a decent echo. We seem to have =
another=20
      unfortunate trade-off imposed by the laws of physics. Two =
solutions might=20
      occur to ingenious engineers, indeed did occur to them when they=20
      encountered the same problem, again in the analogous case of =
radar. Which=20
      of the two solutions is preferable depends on whether it is more =
important=20
      to measure range (how far away an object is from the instrument) =
or=20
      velocity (how fast the object is moving relative to the =
instrument). The=20
      first solution is that known to radar engineers as 'chirp radar'.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.15pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">We can think of radar signals =
as a series=20
      of pulses, but each pulse has a so-called carrier frequency. This =
is=20
      analogous to the 'pitch' of a pulse of sound or ultrasound. Bat =
cries, as=20
      we have seen, have a pulserepetition rate in the tens or hundreds =
per=20
      second. Each one of those pulses has a carrier frequency of tens =
of=20
      thousands to hundreds of thousands of cycles per second. Each =
pulse, in=20
      other words, is a highpitched shriek. Similarly, each pulse of =
radar is a=20
      'shriek' of radio waves, with a high carrier frequency. The =
special=20
      feature of chirp radar is that it does not have a fixed carrier =
frequency=20
      during each shriek. Rather, the carrier frequency swoops =
</SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">up </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">or down about an octave. If you =
think of=20
      it as its sound equivalent, each radar emission can be thought of =
as a=20
      swooping wolf-whistle. The advantage of chirp radar, as =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.15pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D9 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D44 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D9>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D9=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image015.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D44></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D380 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle11 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 3.35pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Good design =
</SPAN></I><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica-Bold">29 </SPAN></B><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.4pt 0pt 2.9pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">opposed to the fixed pitch =
pulse, is the=20
      following. It doesn't matter if the original chirp is still going =
on when=20
      the echo returns. They won't be confused with each other. This is =
because=20
      the echo being detected at any given moment will be a reflection =
of an=20
      earlier part of the chirp, and will therefore have a different =
pitch.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.8pt 0pt 2.15pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Human radar designers have made =
good use=20
      of this ingenious technique. Is there any evidence that bats have=20
      'discovered' it too, just as they did the send/receive system? =
Well, as a=20
      matter of fact, numerous species of bats do produce cries that =
sweep down,=20
      usually through about an octave, during each cry. These =
wolf-whistle cries=20
      are known as frequency modulated (FM). They appear to be just what =
would=20
      be required to exploit the 'chirp radar' technique. However, the =
evidence=20
      so far suggests that bats are using the technique, not to =
distinguish an=20
      echo from the original sound that produced it, but for the more =
subtle=20
      task of distinguishing echoes from other echoes. A bat lives in a =
world of=20
      echoes from near objects, distant objects and objects at all =
intermediate=20
      distances. It has to sort these echoes out from each other. If it =
gives=20
      downward-swooping, wolf-whistle chirps, the sorting is neatly done =
by=20
      pitch. When an echo from a distant object finally arrives back at =
the bat,=20
      it will be an 'older' echo than an echo that is simultaneously =
arriving=20
      back from a near object. It will therefore be of higher pitch. =
When the=20
      bat is faced with clashing echoes from several objects, it can =
apply the=20
      rule of thumb: higher pitch means farther away. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.5pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The second clever idea that =
might occur=20
      to the engineer, especially one interested in measuring the speed =
of a=20
      moving target, is to exploit what physicists call the Doppler =
Shift. This=20
      may be called the 'ambulance effect' because its most familiar=20
      manifestation is the sudden drop in pitch of an ambulance's siren =
as it=20
      speeds past the listener. The Doppler Shift occurs whenever a =
source of=20
      sound (or light or any other kind of wave) and a receiver of that =
sound=20
      move relative to one another. It is easiest to think of the sound =
source=20
      as motionless and the listener as moving. Assume that the siren on =
a=20
      factory roof is wailing continuously, all on one note. The sound =
is=20
      broadcast outwards as a series of waves. The waves can't be seen, =
because=20
      they are waves of air pressure. If they could be seen they would =
resemble=20
      the concentric circles spreading outwards when we throw pebbles =
into the=20
      middle of a still pond. Imagine that a series of pebbles is being =
dropped=20
      in quick succession into the middle of a pond, so that waves are=20
      continuously radiating out from the middle. If we moor a tiny toy =
boat at=20
      some fixed point in the pond, the boat will bob up and down =
rhythmically=20
      as the waves pass under it. The frequency with which the boat bobs =
is=20
      analogous to the pitch of a sound. Now suppose that the =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.5pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D376 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.4pt 0pt 0.95pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">30 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.2pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">boat, instead of being moored, =
is=20
      steaming across the pond, in the general direction of the centre =
from=20
      which the wave circles are originating. It will still bob up and =
down as=20
      it hits the successive wavefronts. But now the frequency with =
which it=20
      hits waves will be higher, since it is travelling towards the =
source of=20
      the waves. It will bob up and down at a higher rate. On the other =
hand,=20
      when it has passed the source of the waves and is travelling away =
the=20
      other side, the frequency with which it bobs up and down will =
obviously go=20
      down. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.5pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">For the same reason, if we ride =
fast on a=20
      (preferably quiet) motorbike past a wailing factory siren, when we =
are=20
      approaching the factory the pitch will be raised: our ears are, in =
effect,=20
      gobbling up the waves at a faster rate than they would if we just =
sat=20
      still. By the same kind of argument, when our motorbike has passed =
the=20
      factory and is moving away from it, the pitch will be lowered. If =
we stop=20
      moving we shall hear the pitch of the siren as it actually is,=20
      intermediate between the two Doppler-shifted pitches. It follows =
that if=20
      we know the exact pitch of the siren, it is theoretically possible =
to work=20
      out how fast we are moving towards or away from it simply by =
listening to=20
      the apparent pitch and comparing it with the known 'true' pitch.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.95pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The same principle works when =
the sound=20
      source is moving and the hstener is still. That is why it works =
for=20
      ambulances. It is rather implausibly said that Christian Doppler =
himself=20
      demonstrated his effect by hiring a brass band to play on an open =
railway=20
      truck as it rushed past his amazed audience. It is relative motion =
that=20
      matters, and as far as the Doppler Effect is concerned it doesn't =
matter=20
      whether we consider the sound source to be moving past the ear, or =
the ear=20
      moving past the sound source. If two trains pass in opposite =
directions,=20
      each travelling at 125 m.p.h., a passenger in one train will hear =
the=20
      whistle of the other train swoop down through a particularly =
dramatic=20
      Doppler Shift, since the relative velocity is 250 m.p.h. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
1.3pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The Doppler Effect is used in =
police=20
      radar speed-traps for motorists. A static instrument beams radar =
signals=20
      down a road. The radar waves bounce back off the cars that =
approach, and=20
      are registered by the receiving apparatus. The faster a car is =
moving, the=20
      higher is the Doppler shift in frequency. By comparing the =
outgoing=20
      frequency with the frequency of the returning echo the police, or =
rather=20
      their automatic instrument, can calculate the speed of each car. =
If the=20
      police can exploit the technique for measuring the speed of road =
hogs,=20
      dare we hope to find that bats use it for measuring the speed of =
insect=20
      prey? </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.15pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The answer is yes. The small =
bats known=20
      as horseshoe bats have long been known to emit long, fixed-pitch =
hoots=20
      rather than staccato clicks or descending wolf-whistles. When I =
say long,=20
      I mean long by bat </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.15pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D381 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.2pt 0pt 4.3pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Good design </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">31 <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 4.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">standards. The 'hoots' are =
still less=20
      than a tenth of a second long. And there is often a 'wolf-whistle' =
tacked=20
      onto the end of each hoot, as we shall see. Imagine, first, a =
horseshoe=20
      bat giving out a continuous hum of ultrasound as it flies fast =
towards a=20
      still object, like a tree. The wavefronts will hit the tree at an=20
      accelerated rate because of the movement of the bat towards the =
tree. If a=20
      microphone were concealed in the tree, it would 'hear' the sound=20
      Doppler-shifted upwards in pitch because of the movement of the =
bat. There=20
      isn't a microphone in the tree, but the echo reflected back from =
the tree=20
      will be Doppler-shifted upwards in pitch in this way. Now, as the =
echo=20
      wavefronts stream back from the tree towards the approaching bat, =
the bat=20
      is still moving fast towards them. Therefore there is a further =
Doppler=20
      shift upwards in the bat's perception of the pitch of the echo. =
The=20
      movement of the bat leads to a kind of double Doppler shift, whose =

      magnitude is a precise indication of the velocity of the bat =
relative to=20
      the tree. By comparing the pitch of its cry with the pitch of the=20
      returning echo, therefore, the bat (or rather its on-board =
computer in the=20
      brain) could, in theory, calculate how fast it was moving towards =
the=20
      tree. This wouldn't tell the bat how far away the tree was, but it =
might=20
      still be very useful information, nevertheless. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.15pt 0pt 1.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">If the object reflecting the =
echoes were=20
      not a static tree but a moving insect, the Doppler consequences =
would be=20
      more complicated, but the bat could still calculate the velocity =
of=20
      relative motion between itself and its target, obviously just the =
kind of=20
      information a sophisticated guided missile like a hunting bat =
needs.=20
      Actually some bats play a trick that is more interesting than =
simply=20
      emitting hoots of constant pitch and measuring the pitch of the =
returning=20
      echoes. They carefully adjust the pitch of the outgoing hoots, in =
such a=20
      way as to keep the pitch of the echo constant after it has been=20
      Doppler-shifted. As they speed towards a moving insect, the pitch =
of their=20
      cries is constantly changing, continuously hunting for just the =
pitch=20
      needed to keep the returning echoes at a fixed pitch. This =
ingenious trick=20
      keeps the echo at the pitch to which their ears are maximally =
sensitive -=20
      important since the echoes are so faint. They can then obtain the=20
      necessary information for their Doppler calculations, by =
monitoring the=20
      pitch at which they are obliged to hoot in order to achieve the=20
      fixed-pitch echo. I don't know whether man-made devices, either =
sonar or=20
      radar, use this subtle trick. But on the principle that most =
clever ideas=20
      in this field seem to have been developed first by bats, I don't =
mind=20
      betting that the answer is yes. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5 style=3D"MARGIN-RIGHT: 3.65pt"><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">It is only to be expected that =
these two=20
      rather different techniques, the Doppler shift technique and the =
'chirp=20
      radar' technique, would be </SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5 style=3D"MARGIN-RIGHT: 3.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.4pt 0pt 1.45pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">32 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.7pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">useful for different special =
purposes.=20
      Some groups of bats specialize </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">in </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">one of them, some in the other. =
Some=20
      groups seem to try to get the best of both worlds, tacking an FM=20
      'wolf-whistle' onto the end (or sometimes the beginning) of a =
long,=20
      constant-frequency 'hoot'. Another curious trick of horseshoe bats =

      concerns movements of their outer ear flaps. Unlike other bats, =
horseshoe=20
      bats move their outer ear flaps in fast alternating forward and =
backward=20
      sweeps. It is conceivable that this additional rapid movement of =
the=20
      listening surface relative to the target causes useful modulations =
in the=20
      Doppler shift, modulations that supply additional information. =
When the=20
      ear is flapping towards the target, the apparent velocity of =
movement=20
      towards the target goes up. When it is flapping away from the =
target, the=20
      reverse happens. The bat's brain 'knows' the direction of flapping =

      </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">of =
</SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">each ear, and </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">in </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">principle could make the =
necessary=20
      calculations </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">to=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">exploit the =
information.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.05pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Possibly the most difficult =
problem of=20
      all that bats face is the danger of inadvertent 'jamming' by the =
cries of=20
      other bats. Human experimenters have found it surprisingly =
difficult to=20
      put bats off their stride by playing loud artificial ultrasound at =
them.=20
      With hindsight one might have predicted this. Bats must have come =
to terms=20
      with the jamming-avoidance problem long ago. Many species of bats =
roost in=20
      enormous aggregations, in caves that must be a deafening babel of=20
      ultrasound and echoes, yet the bats can still fly rapidly about =
the cave,=20
      avoiding the walls and each other in total darkness. How does a =
bat keep=20
      track of its own echoes, and avoid being misled by the echoes of =
others?=20
      The first solution that might occur to an engineer is some sort of =

      frequency coding: each bat might have its own private frequency, =
just like=20
      separate radio stations. To some extent this may happen, but it is =
by no=20
      means the whole story. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.4pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">How bats avoid being jammed by =
other bats=20
      is not well understood, but an interesting clue comes from =
experiments on=20
      trying to put bats off. It turns out that you can actively deceive =
some=20
      bats if you play back to them their </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">own </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">cries with an artificial =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">delay. </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Give them, in other words, =
false echoes=20
      of their own cries. It is even possible, by carefully controlling =
the=20
      electronic apparatus delaying the false echo, to make the bats =
attempt to=20
      land on a 'phantom' ledge. I suppose it is the bat equivalent of =
looking=20
      at the world through a lens. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.7pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">It seems that bats may be using =
something=20
      that we could call a 'strangeness filter'. Each successive echo =
from a=20
      bat's own cries produces a picture of the world that makes sense =
in terms=20
      of the previous picture of the world built up with earlier echoes. =
If the=20
      bat's brain hears an echo from another bat's cry, and attempts to=20
      incorporate it into the </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.7pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle5 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.2pt 0pt =
2.65pt"><B><I>Good=20
      </I></B><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">design=20
      </SPAN></I><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">33 =
</SPAN></B><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.9pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">picture of the world that it =
has=20
      previously built up, it will make </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">no </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">sense. It will appear as though =
objects=20
      in the world have suddenly jumped in various random directions. =
Objects in=20
      the real world do not behave in'such a crazy way, so the brain can =
safely=20
      filter out the apparent echo as background noise. If a human =
experimenter=20
      feeds the bat artificially delayed or accelerated 'echoes' of its =
own=20
      cries, the false echoes </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">will </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">make sense in terms of the =
world picture=20
      that the bat has previously built up. The false echoes are =
accepted by the=20
      strangeness filter because they are plausible in the context of =
the=20
      previous echoes. They cause objects to seem to shift in position =
by only a=20
      small amount, which is what objects plausibly can be expected to =
do in the=20
      real world. The. bat's brain relies upon the assumption that the =
world=20
      portrayed by any one echo pulse will be either the same as the =
world=20
      portrayed by previous pulses, or only slightly different: the =
insect being=20
      tracked may have moved a little, for instance. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.2pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">There is a well-known paper by =
the=20
      philosopher Thomas Nagel called 'What is it like to be a bat?'. =
The paper=20
      is not so much about bats as about the philosophical problem of =
imagining=20
      what it is 'like' to be anything that we are not. The reason a bat =
is a=20
      particularly telling example for a philosopher, however, is that =
the=20
      experiences of an echolocating bat are assumed to be peculiarly =
alien and=20
      different from our own. If you want to share a bat's experience, =
it is=20
      almost certainly grossly misleading to go into a cave, shout or =
bang two=20
      spoons together, consciously time the delay before you hear the =
echo, and=20
      calculate from this how far the wall must be. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.7pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">That is no more what it is like =
to be a=20
      bat than the following is a good picture of what it is like to see =
colour:=20
      use an instrument to measure the wavelength of the light that is =
entering=20
      your eye: if it is long, you are seeing red, if it is short you =
are seeing=20
      violet or blue. It happens to be a physical fact that the light =
that we=20
      call red has a longer wavelength than the light that we call blue. =

      Different wavelengths switch on the red-sensitive and the =
blue-sensitive=20
      photocells in our retinas. But there is no trace of the concept of =

      wavelength in our subjective sensation of the colours. Nothing =
about 'what=20
      it is like' to see blue or red tells us which light has the longer =

      wavelength. If it matters (it usually doesn't), we just have to =
remember=20
      it, or (what I always do) look it up in a book. Similarly, a bat =
perceives=20
      the position of an insect using what we call echoes. But the bat =
surely no=20
      more thinks in terms of delays of echoes when it perceives an =
insect, than=20
      we think in terms of wavelengths when we perceive blue or red. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-RIGHT: 2.15pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Indeed, if I were forced to try =
the=20
      impossible, to imagine what it is like to be a bat, I would guess =
that=20
      echolocating, for them, might be </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-RIGHT: 2.15pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D377 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.2pt 0pt 0.7pt"><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">34 </SPAN></B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.95pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">rather like seeing for us. We =
are such=20
      thoroughly visual animals that we hardly realize what a =
complicated=20
      business seeing is. Objects are 'out there'; and we think that we =
'see'=20
      them out there. But I suspect that really our percept is an =
elaborate=20
      computer model in the brain, constructed on the basis of =
information=20
      coming from out there, but transformed in the head into a form in =
which=20
      that information can be </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">used. </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Wavelength differences in the =
light out=20
      there become coded as 'colour' differences in the computer model =
in the=20
      head. Shape and other attributes are encoded in the same kind of =
way,=20
      encoded into a form that is convenient to handle. The sensation of =
seeing=20
      is, for us, very different from the sensation of hearing, but this =
cannot=20
      be'directly due to the physical differences between light and =
sound. Both=20
      light and sound are, after all, translated by the respective sense =
organs=20
      into the same kind of nerve impulses. It is impossible to tell, =
from the=20
      physical attributes of a nerve impulse, whether it is conveying=20
      information about light, about sound or about smell. The reason =
the=20
      sensation of seeing is so different from the sensation of hearing =
and the=20
      sensation of smelling is that the brain finds it convenient to use =

      different kinds of internal model of the visual world, the world =
of sound=20
      and the world of smell. It is because we </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">internally use =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">our visual information and our =
sound=20
      information in different ways and for different purposes that the=20
      sensations of seeing and hearing are so different. It is not =
directly=20
      because of the physical differences between light and sound. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">But a bat uses its =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">sound </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">information for very much the =
same kind=20
      of purpose as we use our </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">visual </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">information. It uses sound to =
perceive,=20
      and continuously update its perception of, the position of objects =
in=20
      three-dimensional space, just as we use light. The type of =
internal=20
      computer model that it needs, therefore, is one suitable for the =
internal=20
      representation of the changing positions of objects in =
threedimensional=20
      space. My point is that the form that an animal's subjective =
experience=20
      takes will be a property of the internal computer model. That =
model will=20
      be designed, in evolution, for its suitability for useful internal =

      representation, irrespective of the physical stimuli that come to =
it from=20
      outside. Bats and we </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">need </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the same kind of internal model =
for=20
      representing the position of objects in three-dimensional space. =
The fact=20
      that bats construct their internal model with the aid of echoes, =
while we=20
      construct ours with the aid of light, is irrelevant. That outside=20
      information is, in any case, translated into the same kind =
</SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">of </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">nerve impulses on its way to =
the brain.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.65pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">My conjecture, therefore, is =
that bats=20
      'see' in much </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold">the=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">same way =
</SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">as </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">we do, even though the physical =
medium by=20
      which </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">the =
</SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">world 'out there' is translated =
into=20
      nerve impulses is so different - ultrasound </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.65pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
