<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D624 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D624>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.5pt 0pt 1.9pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Good design </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">35 <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.35pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">rather than light. Bats may =
even use the=20
      sensations that we call colour for their own purposes, to =
represent=20
      differences in the world out there that have nothing to do with =
the=20
      physics of wavelength, but which play a functional role, for the =
bat,=20
      similar to the role that colours play to us. Perhaps male bats =
have body=20
      surfaces that are subtly textured so that the echoes that bounce =
off them=20
      are perceived by females as gorgeously coloured, the sound =
equivalent of=20
      the nuptial plumage of a bird of paradise. I don't mean this just =
as some=20
      vague metaphor. It is possible that the subjective sensation =
experienced=20
      by a female bat when she perceives a male really is, say, bright =
red: the=20
      same sensation as I experience when I see a flamingo. Or, at =
least, the=20
      bat's sensation of her mate may be no more different from my =
visual=20
      sensation of a flamingo, than my visual sensation of a flamingo is =

      different from a flamingo's visual sensation of a flamingo. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.2pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Donald Griffin tells a story of =
what=20
      happened when he and his colleague Robert Galambos first reported =
to an=20
      astonished conference of zoologists in 1940 their new discovery of =
the=20
      facts of bat echolocation. One distinguished scientist was so =
indignantly=20
      incredulous that <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 7.25pt 0pt 10.3pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 9.9pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">he seized Galambos by the =
shoulders and=20
      shook him while complaining that we could not possibly mean such =
an=20
      outrageous suggestion. Radar and sonar were still highly =
classified=20
      developments in military technology, and the notion that bats =
might do=20
      anything even remotely analogous to the latest triumphs of =
electronic=20
      engineering struck most people as not only implausible but =
emotionally=20
      repugnant. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.9pt 0pt 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">It is easy to sympathize with =
the=20
      distinguished sceptic. There is something very human in his =
reluctance to=20
      believe. And that, really, says it: human is precisely what it is. =
It is=20
      precisely because our own human senses are not capable of doing =
what bats=20
      do that we find it hard to believe. Because we can only understand =
it at a=20
      level of artificial instrumentation, and mathematical calculations =
on=20
      paper, we find it hard to imagine a little animal doing it in its =
head.=20
      Yet the mathematical calculations that would be necessary to =
explain the=20
      principles of vision are just as complex and difficult, and nobody =
has=20
      ever had any difficulty in believing that little animals can see. =
The=20
      reason for this double standard in our scepticism is, quite =
simply, that=20
      we can see and we can't echolocate. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.2pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">I can imagine some other world =
in which a=20
      conference of learned, and totally blind, bat-like creatures is=20
      flabbergasted to be told </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">of </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">animals called humans that are =
actually=20
      capable of using the newly discovered inaudible rays called =
'light', still=20
      the subject of top-secret </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.2pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D380 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.2pt 0pt 2.9pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">36 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 2.65pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">military development, for =
finding their=20
      way about. These otherwise humble humans are almost totally deaf =
(well,=20
      they can hear after a fashion and even utter a few ponderously =
slow, deep=20
      drawling growls, but they only use these sounds for rudimentary =
purposes=20
      like communicating with each other; they don't seem capable of =
using them=20
      to detect even the most massive objects). They have, instead, =
highly=20
      specialized organs called 'eyes' for exploiting 'light' rays. The =
sun is=20
      the main source of light rays, and humans, remarkably, manage to =
exploit=20
      the complex echoes that bounce off objects when light rays from =
the sun=20
      hit them. They have an ingenious device called a 'lens', whose =
shape=20
      appears to be mathematically calculated so that it bends these =
silent rays=20
      in such a way that there is an exact one-to-one mapping between =
objects in=20
      the world and an 'image' on a sheet of cells called the 'retina'. =
These=20
      retinal cells are capable, in some mysterious way, of rendering =
the light=20
      'audible' (one might say), and they relay their information to the =
brain.=20
      Our mathematicians have shown that it is theoretically possible, =
by doing=20
      the right highly complex calculations, to navigate safely through =
the=20
      world using these light rays, just as effectively as one can in =
the=20
      ordinary way using ultrasound - in some respects even =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">more </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">effectively! But who would have =
thought=20
      that a humble human could do these calculations? </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.45pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Echo-sounding by bats is just =
one of the=20
      thousands of examples that I could have chosen to make the point =
about=20
      good design. Animals give the appearance of having been designed =
by a=20
      theoretically sophisticated and practically ingenious physicist or =

      engineer, but there is no suggestion that the bats themselves know =
or=20
      understand the theory in the same sense as a physicist understands =
it. The=20
      bat should be thought of as analogous to the police radar trapping =

      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">instrument,=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">not to the =
person who=20
      designed that instrument. The designer of the police radar =
speed-meter=20
      understood the theory of the Doppler Effect, and expressed this=20
      understanding in mathematical equations, explicitly written out on =
paper.=20
      The designer's understanding is embodied in the design of the =
instrument,=20
      but the instrument itself does not understand how it works. The =
instrument=20
      contains electronic components, which are wired up so that they=20
      automatically compare two radar frequencies and convert the result =
into=20
      convenient units - miles per hour. The computation involved is=20
      complicated, but well within the powers of a small box of modem =
electronic=20
      components wired up in the proper way. Of course, a sophisticated=20
      conscious brain did the wiring up (or at least designed the wiring =

      diagram), but no conscious brain is involved in the =
moment-to-moment=20
      working of the box. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.9pt 0pt 10.1pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Our experience of electronic =
technology=20
      prepares us to accept the </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.9pt 0pt 10.1pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D380 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 2.65pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Good design 37 =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.45pt 0pt 1.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">idea that unconscious machinery =
can=20
      behave as if it understands complex mathematical ideas. This idea =
is=20
      directly transferable to the workings of living machinery. A bat =
is a=20
      machine, whose internal electronics are so wired up that its wing =
muscles=20
      cause it to home in on insects, as an unconscious guided missile =
homes in=20
      on an aeroplane. So far our intuition, derived from technology, is =

      correct. But our experience of technology also prepares us to see =
the mind=20
      of a conscious and purposeful designer in the genesis of =
sophisticated=20
      machinery. It is this second intuition that is wrong in the case =
of living=20
      machinery. In the case of living machinery, the 'designer' is =
unconscious=20
      natural selection, the blind watchmaker. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.95pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">I hope that the reader is as =
awestruck as=20
      I am, and as William Paley would have been, by these bat stories. =
My aim=20
      has been in one respect identical to Paley's aim. I do not want =
the reader=20
      to underestimate the prodigious works of nature and the problems =
we face=20
      in explaining them. Echolocation in bats, although unknown in =
Paley's=20
      time, would have served his purpose just as well as any of his =
examples.=20
      Paley rammed home his argument by multiplying up his examples. He =
went=20
      right through the body, from head to toe, showing how every part, =
every=20
      last detail, was like the interior of a beautifully fashioned =
watch. In=20
      many ways I should like to do the same, for there are wonderful =
stories to=20
      be told, and I love storytelling. But there is really no need to =
multiply=20
      examples. One or two will do. The hypothesis that can explain bat=20
      navigation is a good candidate for explaining anything in the =
world of=20
      life, and if Paley's explanation for any one of his examples was =
wrong we=20
      can't make it right by multiplying up examples. His hypothesis was =
that=20
      living watches were literally designed and built by a master =
watchmaker.=20
      Our modern hypothesis is that the job was done in gradual =
evolutionary=20
      stages by natural selection. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
2.25pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Nowadays theologians aren't =
quite so=20
      straightforward as Paley. They don't point to complex living =
mechanisms=20
      and say that they are self-evidently designed by a creator, just =
like a=20
      watch. But there is a tendency to point to them and say 'It is =
impossible=20
      to believe' that such complexity, or such perfection, could have =
evolved=20
      by natural selection. Whenever I read such a remark, I always feel =
like=20
      writing 'Speak for yourself in the margin. There are numerous =
examples (I=20
      counted 35 in one chapter) in a recent book called </SPAN><I><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Probability of God =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">by the Bishop of Birmingham, =
Hugh=20
      Montefiore. I shall use this book for all my examples in the rest =
of this=20
      chapter, because it is a sincere and honest attempt, by a =
reputable and=20
      educated writer, to bring natural theology up to date. When I say =
honest,=20
      I mean honest. Unlike some of his theological colleagues, Bishop=20
      Montefiore is not </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
2.25pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D625 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D377 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D625>
      <P class=3DStyle18 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.15pt 0pt 0.7pt">38 =
<I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker=20
      </SPAN><BR><BR></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.65pt">afraid=20
      to state that the question of whether God exists is a definite =
question of=20
      fact. He has no truck with shifty evasions such as ' Christianity =
is a way=20
      of life. The question of God's <I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">existence </SPAN></I>is =
eliminated: it=20
      is a mirage created by the illusions of realism'. Parts of his =
book are=20
      about physics and cosmology, and I am not competent to comment on =
those=20
      except to note that he seems to have used genuine physicists as =
his=20
      authorities. Would that he had done the same in the biological =
parts.=20
      Unfortunately, he preferred here to consult the works of Arthur =
Koestler,=20
      Fred Hoyle, Gordon Rattray-Taylor and Karl Popper! The Bishop =
believes in=20
      evolution, but cannot believe that natural selection is an =
adequate=20
      explanation for the course that evolution has taken (partly =
because, like=20
      many others, he sadly misunderstands natural selection to be =
'random' and=20
      'meaningless'). </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.5pt 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.75pt">He=20
      makes heavy use of what may be called the Argument <B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">from </SPAN></B>Personal =
Incredulity. In=20
      the course of one chapter we find the following phrases, in this =
order:=20
      </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 7.8pt 0pt 10.3pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 9.85pt">.=20
      . . there seems no explanation on Darwinian grounds . . . It is no =
easier=20
      to explain . . . It is hard to understand . . . It is not easy to=20
      understand ... It is equally difficult to explain . . . I do not =
find it=20
      easy to comprehend ... I do not find it easy to see . . . I find =
it hard=20
      to understand . . . it does not seem feasible to explain ... I =
cannot see=20
      how . . . neo-Darwinism seems inadequate to explain many of the=20
      complexities of animal behaviour <B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">. . . it </SPAN></B>is not easy =
to=20
      comprehend how such behaviour could have evolved <B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">solely </SPAN></B>through =
natural=20
      selection . . . It is impossible . . . How could an organ <B><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">so </SPAN></B>complex evolve? . =
. . It is=20
      not easy to see . . . It is difficult to see . . . </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.95pt">The=20
      Argument from Personal Incredulity is an extremely <B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">weak </SPAN></B>argument, as =
Darwin=20
      himself noted. In some cases it is based <B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">upon </SPAN></B>simple =
ignorance. For=20
      instance, one of the facts that the Bishop <B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">finds it </SPAN></B>difficult to =

      understand is the white colour of polar bears. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 8.2pt 0pt 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 9.95pt">As for =

      camouflage, this is not always easily explicable on neo-Darwinian=20
      premises. If polar bears are dominant in the Arctic, then there =
<B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">would seem </SPAN></B>to have =
been no need=20
      for them to evolve a white-coloured form <B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">of </SPAN></B>camouflage. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19 style=3D"MARGIN-RIGHT: 168.2pt">This should be =
translated:=20
      </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.45pt 0pt 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 9.85pt">I =
personally,=20
      off the top of my head sitting in my study, never having visited =
the=20
      Arctic, never having seen a polar bear in the wild, and having =
been=20
      educated in classical literature and theology, have not so far =
managed to=20
      think of a reason why polar bears might benefit from being white. =
</P>
      <P class=3DStyle21 style=3D"MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.9pt"><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">In </SPAN></B>this particular =
case, the=20
      assumption being made is that only <B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">animals that </SPAN></B>are =
preyed upon=20
      need camouflage. What is overlooked is <B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">that </SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle21 style=3D"MARGIN-RIGHT: 0.9pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D625 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D381 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D625>
      <P class=3DStyle20 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 3.1pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Good design =
</SPAN></I><B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: 'Times-Bold Italic'">39 =
</SPAN><BR><BR></I></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.25pt 0pt 2.4pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">predators also benefit from =
being=20
      concealed from their prey. Polar bears stalk seals resting on the =
ice. If=20
      the seal sees the bear coming from farenough away, it can escape. =
I=20
      suspect that, if he imagines a dark grizzly bear trying to stalk =
seals=20
      over the snow, the Bishop will immediately see the answer to his =
problem.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.05pt 0pt 1.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The polar bear argument turned =
out to be=20
      almost too easy to demolish but, in an important sense, this is =
not the=20
      point. Even if the foremost authority in the world can't explain =
some=20
      remarkabk biological phenomenon, this doesn't mean that it is=20
      inexplicable. Plenty of mysteries have lasted for centuries and =
finally=20
      yielded to explanation. For what it is worth, most modern =
biologists=20
      wouldn't find it difficult to explain every one of the Bishop's 35 =

      examples in terms of the theory of natural selection, although not =
all of=20
      them are quite as easy as the polar bears. But we aren't testing =
human=20
      ingenuity. Even if we found one example that we </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">couldn't </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">explain, we should hesitate to =
draw any=20
      grandiose conclusions from the fact of our own inability. Darwin =
himself=20
      was very clear on this point. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.05pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">There are more serious versions =
of the=20
      argument from personal incredulity, versions which do not rest =
simply upon=20
      ignorance or lack of ingenuity. One form of the argument makes =
direct use=20
      of the extreme sense of wonder which we all feel when confronted =
with=20
      highly complicated machinery, like the detailed perfection of the=20
      echolocation equipment of bats. The implication is that it is =
somehow=20
      self-evident that anything so wonderful as this could not possibly =
have=20
      evolved by natural selection. The Bishop quotes, with approval, =
<BR>G.=20
      Bennett on spider webs: <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.6pt 0pt 10.3pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 9.85pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">It is impossible for one who =
has watched=20
      the work for many hours to have any doubt that neither the present =
spiders=20
      of this species nor their ancestors were ever the architects of =
the web or=20
      that it could conceivably have been produced step by step through =
random=20
      variation; it would be as absurd to suppose that the intricate and =
exact=20
      proportions of the Parthenon were produced by piling together bits =
of=20
      marble. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-RIGHT: 2.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">It is not impossible at all. =
That is=20
      exactly what I firmly believe, and I have some experience of =
spiders and=20
      their webs. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.9pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The Bishop goes on to the human =
eye,=20
      asking rhetorically, and with the implication that there is no =
answer,=20
      'How could an organ so complex evolve?' This is not an argument, =
it is=20
      simply an affirmation of incredulity. The underlying basis for the =

      intuitive incredulity that we all are tempted to feel about what =
Darwin=20
      called organs of extreme perfection and complication is, I think, =
twofold.=20
      First we have no intuitive grasp of the immensities of time =
available for=20
      evolutionary </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.9pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.25pt 0pt 1.45pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">40 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.45pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">change. Most sceptics about =
natural=20
      selection are prepared to accept that it can bring about minor =
changes=20
      like the dark coloration that has evolved in various species of =
moth since=20
      the industrial revolution. But, having accepted this, they then =
point out=20
      how small a change this is. As the Bishop underlines, the dark =
moth is not=20
      a </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">new species. =

      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">I agree that =
this is a=20
      small change, no match for the evolution of the eye, or =
</SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">of </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">echolocation. But equally, the =
moths only=20
      took a hundred years </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold">to=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">make their =
change. One=20
      hundred years seems like a long time to us, because it is longer =
than our=20
      lifetime. But to a geologist it is about a thousand times shorter =
than he=20
      can ordinarily measure! </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.8pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Eyes don't fossilize, so we =
don't know=20
      how long our type of eye took to evolve its present complexity and =

      perfection from nothing, but the time available is several hundred =
million=20
      years. Think, by way of comparison, of the change that man has =
wrought in=20
      a much shorter time by genetic selection of dogs. In a few =
hundreds, or at=20
      most thousands, of years we have gone from wolf to Pekinese, =
Bulldog,=20
      Chihuahua and Saint Bernard. Ah, but they are still =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">dogs </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">aren't they? They haven't =
turned into a=20
      different </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">' k =
i n d '=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">of animal? =
Yes, if it=20
      comforts you to play with words like that, you can call them all =
dogs. But=20
      just think about the time involved. Let's represent the total time =
it took=20
      to evolve all these breeds of dog from a wolf, by one ordinary =
walking=20
      pace. Then, on the same scale, how far would you have to walk, in =
order to=20
      get back to Lucy and her kind, the earliest human fossils that=20
      unequivocally walked upright? The answer is about 2 miles. And how =
far=20
      would you have to walk, in order to get back to the start of =
evolution on=20
      Earth? The answer is that you would have to slog it out all the =
way from=20
      London to Baghdad. Think of the total quantity of change involved =
in going=20
      from wolf to Chihuahua, and then multiply it up by the number of =
walking=20
      paces between London and Baghdad. This will give some intuitive =
idea of=20
      the amount of change that we can expect in real natural evolution. =

      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
1.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The second basis for our =
natural=20
      incredulity about the evolution of very complex organs like human =
eyes and=20
      bat ears is an intuitive application of probability theory. Bishop =

      Montefiore quotes C. E. Raven on cuckoos. These lay their eggs in =
the=20
      nests of other birds, which then act as unwitting foster parents. =
Like so=20
      many biological adaptations, that of the cuckoo is not single but=20
      multiple. Several different facts about cuckoos fit them to their=20
      parasitic way of life. For instance, the mother has the habit of =
laying in=20
      other birds' nests, and the baby has the habit of throwing the =
host's own=20
      chicks out of the nest. Both habits help the cuckoo succeed in its =

      parasitic life. Raven goes on: </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
1.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D8 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D23 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D8>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D8=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image017.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D23></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D357 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D357>
      <P class=3DStyle21 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.45pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Good design =
</SPAN></I><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">41 </SPAN><BR><BR></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 11.4pt 0pt 11.05pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 9.8pt">It =
will be seen=20
      that each one of this sequence of conditions is essential for the =
success=20
      of the whole. Yet each by itself is useless. The whole <I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">opus perfectum </SPAN></I>must =
have been=20
      achieved simultaneously. The odds against the random occurrence of =
such a=20
      series of coincidences are, as we have already stated, =
astronomical. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.75pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt">Arguments=20
      such as this are in principle more respectable than the argument =
based on=20
      sheer, naked incredulity. Measuring the statistical improbability =
of a=20
      suggestion is the right way to go about assessing its =
believability.=20
      Indeed, it is a method that we shall use in this book several =
times. But=20
      you have to do it right! There are two things wrong with the =
argument put=20
      by Raven. First, there is the familiar, and I have to say rather=20
      irritating, confusion of natural selection with 'randomness'. =
Mutation is=20
      random; natural selection is the very opposite of random. Second, =
it just=20
      isn't <I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">true =
</SPAN></I>that=20
      'each by itself is useless'. It isn't true that the whole perfect =
work=20
      must have been achieved simultaneously. It isn't true that each =
part is=20
      essential for the success of the whole. A simple, rudimentary, =
half-cocked=20
      <I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">eye/eat/=20
      </SPAN></I>echolocation system/cuckoo parasitism system, etc., is =
better=20
      than none at all. Without an eye you are totally blind. With half =
an eye=20
      you may at least be able to detect the general direction of a =
predator's=20
      movement, even if you can't focus a clear image. And this may make =
all the=20
      difference between life and death. These matters will be taken up =
again in=20
      more detail in the next two chapters. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.75pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D10 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D40 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D10>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D10 =

      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
