<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D454 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D335 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D454>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"><IMG=20
      height=3D454=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image019.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D335></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D562 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D562>
      <P class=3DStyle16 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 104.35pt 0pt =
109.7pt">CHAPTER 3 <SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <H2 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 66.45pt 0pt 68.15pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 16.5pt">ACCUMULATING </SPAN></H2>
      <H2 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 68.55pt 0pt 73.45pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 16.5pt">SMALL CHANGE </SPAN><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR><BR><BR></SPAN></H2>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">We have seen that living things =
are too=20
      improbable and too beautifully 'designed' to have come into =
existence by=20
      chance. How, then, did they come into existence? The answer, =
Darwin's=20
      answer, is by gradual, stepby- step transformations from simple=20
      beginnings, from primordial entities sufficiently simple to have =
come into=20
      existence by chance. Each <BR>successive change in the gradual=20
      evolutionary process was simple enough, <BR></SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">relative to its predecessor, =
to=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">have arisen by =
chance.=20
      But the whole sequence of cumulative steps constitutes anything =
but a=20
      chance process, when you consider the complexity of the final =
end-product=20
      relative to the original starting point. The cumulative process is =

      directed by nonrandom survival. The purpose of this chapter is to=20
      demonstrate the power of this </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">cumulative selection =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">as a fundamentally nonrandom =
process.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.5pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">If you walk up and down a =
pebbly beach,=20
      you will notice that the pebbles are not arranged at random. The =
smaller=20
      pebbles typically tend to be found in segregated zones running =
along the=20
      length of the beach, the larger ones in different zones or =
stripes. The=20
      pebbles have been sorted, arranged, selected. A tribe living near =
the=20
      shore might wonder at this evidence of sorting or arrangement in =
the=20
      world, and might develop a myth to account for it, perhaps =
attributing it=20
      to a Great Spirit in the sky with a tidy mind and a sense of =
order. We=20
      might give a superior smile at such a superstitious notion, and =
explain=20
      that the arranging was really done by the blind forces of physics, =
in this=20
      case the action of waves. The waves have no purposes and no =
intentions, no=20
      tidy mind, no mind at all. They just energetically throw the =
pebbles=20
      around, and big pebbles and small pebbles respond differently to =
this=20
      treatment so they end up at different levels of the beach. A small =
amount=20
      of order has come out of disorder, and no mind planned it. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle11 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.15pt 0pt =
260.15pt"><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica-Bold">43 </SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle11 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.15pt 0pt 260.15pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Helvetica-Bold"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 8pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica-Bold"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D629 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D629>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.1pt 0pt 3.1pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">44 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.1pt 0pt 2.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The waves and the pebbles =
together=20
      constitute a simple example of a system that automatically =
generates=20
      non-randomness. The world is full of such systems. The simplest =
example I=20
      can think of is a hole. Only objects smaller than the hole can =
pass=20
      through it. This means that if you start with a random collection =
of=20
      objects above the hole, and some force shakes and jostles them =
about at=20
      random, after a while the objects above and below the hole will =
come to be=20
      nonrandomly sorted. The space below the hole will tend to contain =
objects=20
      smaller than the hole, and the space above will tend to contain =
objects=20
      larger than the hole. Mankind has, of course, long exploited this =
simple=20
      principle for generating non-randomness, in the useful device =
known as the=20
      sieve. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.95pt 0pt 1.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The Solar System is a stable =
arrangement=20
      of planets, comets and debris orbiting the sun, and it is =
presumably one=20
      of many such orbiting systems in the universe. The nearer a =
satellite is=20
      to its sun, the faster it has to travel if it is to counter the =
sun's=20
      gravity and remain in stable orbit. For any given orbit, there is =
only one=20
      speed at which a satellite can travel and remain in that orbit. If =
it were=20
      travelling at any other velocity, it would either move out into =
deep=20
      space, or crash into the Sun, or move into another orbit. And if =
we look=20
      at the planets of our solar system, lo and behold, every single =
one of=20
      them is travelling at exactly the right velocity to keep it in its =
stable=20
      orbit around the Sun. A blessed miracle of provident design? No, =
just=20
      another natural 'sieve'. Obviously all the planets that we see =
orbiting=20
      the sun must be travelling at exactly the right speed to keep them =
in=20
      their orbits, or we wouldn't see them there because they wouldn't =
be=20
      there! But equally obviously this is not evidence for conscious =
design. It=20
      is just another kind of sieve. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.05pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Sieving of this order of =
simplicity is=20
      not, on its own, enough to account for the massive amounts of =
nonrandom=20
      order that we see in living things. Nowhere near enough. Remember =
the=20
      analogy of the combination lock. The kind of non-randomness that =
can be=20
      generated by simple sieving is roughly equivalent to opening a =
combination=20
      lock with only one dial: it is easy to open it by sheer luck. The =
kind of=20
      nonrandomness that we see in living systems, on the other hand, is =

      equivalent to a gigantic combination lock with an almost =
uncountable=20
      number of dials. To generate a biological molecule like =
haemoglobin, the=20
      red pigment in blood, by simple sieving would be equivalent to =
taking all=20
      the amino-acid building blocks of haemoglobin, jumbling them up at =
random,=20
      and hoping that the haemoglobin molecule would reconstitute itself =
by=20
      sheer luck. The amount of luck that would be required for this =
feat is=20
      unthinkable, and has been used as a telling mind-boggier by Isaac =
Asimov=20
      and others. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.05pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.3pt 0pt 1.2pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Accumulating small change=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">45 =
<BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">A haemoglobin molecule consists =
of four=20
      chains of amino acids twisted together. Let us think about just =
one of=20
      these four chains. It consists of 146 amino acids. There are 20 =
different=20
      kinds of amino acids commonly found in living things. The number =
of=20
      possible ways of arranging 20 kinds of thing in chains 146 links =
long is=20
      an inconceivably large number, which Asimov calls the 'haemoglobin =

      number'. It is easy to calculate, but impossible to visualize the =
answer.=20
      The first link in the 146-long chain could be any one of the 20 =
possible=20
      amino acids. The second link could also be any one of the 20, so =
the=20
      number of possible 2-link chains is 20 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">x 10, </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">or 400. The number of possible =
3-link=20
      chains is 20 x 20 x 20, or 8,000. The number of possible 146-link =
chains=20
      is 20 times itself 146 times. This is a staggeringly large number. =
A=20
      million is a 1 with 6 noughts after it. A billion 11,000 million) =
is a 1=20
      with 9 noughts after it. The number we seek, the 'haemoglobin =
number', is=20
      (near enough) a 1 with 190 noughts after it! This is the chance =
against=20
      happening to hit upon haemoglobin by luck. And a haemoglobin =
molecule has=20
      only a minute fraction of the complexity of a living body. Simple =
sieving,=20
      on its own, is obviously nowhere near capable of generating the =
amount of=20
      order in a living thing. Sieving is an essential ingredient in the =

      generation of living order, but it is very far from being the =
whole story.=20
      Something else is needed. To explain the point, I shall need to =
make a=20
      distinction between 'single-step' selection and 'cumulative' =
selection.=20
      The simple sieves we have been considering so far in this chapter =
are all=20
      examples of single-step selection. Living organization is the =
product of=20
      cumulative selection. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.8pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The essential difference =
between=20
      single-step selection and cumulative selection is this. In =
single-step=20
      selection the entities selected or sorted, pebbles or whatever =
they are,=20
      are sorted once and for all. In cumulative selection, on the other =
hand,=20
      they 'reproduce'; or in some other way the results of one sieving =
process=20
      are fed into a subsequent sieving, which is fed into . . ., and so =
on. The=20
      entities are subjected to selection or sorting over many =
'generations' in=20
      succession. The end-product of one generation of selection is the =
starting=20
      point for the next generation of selection, and so on for many=20
      generations. It is natural to borrow such words as 'reproduce' and =

      'generation', which have associations with living things, because =
living=20
      things are the main examples we know of things that participate in =

      cumulative selection. They may in practice be the only things that =
do. But=20
      for the moment I don't want to beg that question by saying so =
outright.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.85pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Sometimes clouds, through the =
random=20
      kneading and carving of the winds, come to look like familiar =
objects.=20
      There is a much published photograph, taken by the pilot of a =
small=20
      aeroplane, of what looks a bit </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.85pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D380 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 3.35pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">46 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05pt 0pt 3.1pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">like the face of Jesus, staring =
out of=20
      the sky. We have all seen clouds that reminded us of something - a =
sea=20
      horse, say, or a smiling face. These resemblances come about by=20
      single-step selection, that is to say by a Single coincidence. =
They are,=20
      consequently, not very impressive. The resemblance of the signs of =
the=20
      zodiac to the animals after which they are named, Scorpio, Leo, =
and so on,=20
      is as unimpressive as the predictions of astrologers. We don't =
feel=20
      overwhelmed by the resemblance, as we are by biological =
adaptations - the=20
      products of cumulative selection. We describe as weird, uncanny or =

      spectacular, the resemblance of, say, a leaf insect to a leaf or a =
praying=20
      mantis to a cluster of pink flowers. The resemblance of a cloud=20
      toaweaselisonly mildly diverting, barely worth calling to the =
attention of=20
      our companion. Moreover, we are quite likely to change our mind =
about=20
      exactly what the cloud most resembles. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 26.6pt 0pt =
12.25pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Hamlet. </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Do you see yonder cloud that's =
almost in=20
      shape of a camel? </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Polonius. </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">By the mass, and 'tis like a =
camel,=20
      indeed. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 127.4pt 0pt 12pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 9.85pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Hamlet. </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Methinks it is like a weasel.=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Polonius.=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">It is backed =
like a=20
      weasel. </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">Hamlet.=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Or like a =
whale?=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 161.5pt 0pt =
11.5pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Polonius. </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Very like a whale. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">I don't know who it was first =
pointed out=20
      that, given enough time, a monkey bashing away at random on a =
typewriter=20
      could produce all the works of Shakespeare. The operative phrase =
is, of=20
      course, given enough time. Let us limit the task facing our monkey =

      somewhat. Suppose that he has to produce, not the complete works =
of=20
      Shakespeare but just the short sentence 'Methinks it is like a =
weasel',=20
      and we shall make it relatively easy by giving him a typewriter =
with a=20
      restricted keyboard, one with just the 26 (capital) letters, and a =
space=20
      bar. How long will he take to write this one little sentence? =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.95pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The sentence has 28 characters =
in it, so=20
      let us assume that the monkey has a series of discrete 'tries', =
each=20
      consisting of 28 bashes at the keyboard. If he types the phrase =
correctly,=20
      that is the end of the experiment. If not, we allow him another =
'try' of=20
      28 characters. I don't know any monkeys, but fortunately my =
11-month old=20
      daughter is an experienced randomizing device, and she proved only =
too=20
      eager to step into the role of monkey typist. Here is what she =
typed=20
      </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">on =
</SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the computer: </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 108.35pt 0pt 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">UMMK JK CDZZ F ZD DSDSKSM S SS =
FMCV PU I=20
      DDRGLKDXRRDO RDTE QDWFDVIOY UDSKZWDCCVYT H CHVY NMGNBAYTDFCCVD D =
RCDFYYYRM=20
      N DFSKD LD K WDWK HKAUIZMZI UXDKIDISFUMDKUDXI </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 108.35pt 0pt 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
