<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D625 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D625>
      <P class=3DStyle23 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05pt 0pt =
1.45pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica-Oblique">Accumulating small change =

      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica">47 </SPAN><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.5pt 0pt 0.95pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">She has other important calls =
on her=20
      time, so I was obliged to program the computer to simulate a =
randomly=20
      typing baby or monkey: </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 86.05pt 0pt 0.15in; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">WDLDMNLT DTJBKWIRZREZLMQCO P Y=20
      YVMQKZPGJXWVHGLAWFVCHQYOPY MWR SWTNUXMLCDLEUBXTQHNZVIQF FU=20
      OVAODVYKDGXDEKYVMOGGS VT HZQZDSFZIHIVPHZPETPWVOVPMZGF=20
      GEWRGZRPBCTPGQMCKHFDBGW ZCCF </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.1pt 0pt 0.5pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">And so on and on. It isn't =
difficult to=20
      calculate how long we should reasonably'expect to wait for the =
random=20
      computer (or baby or <BR>monkey) to type METHINKS IT IS LIKE A =
WEASEL.=20
      Think about the total number of </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">possible </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">phrases of the right length =
that the=20
      monkey or baby or random computer </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">could </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">type. It is the same kind of =
calculation=20
      as we did for haemoglobin, and it produces a similarly large =
result. There=20
      are 27 possible letters (counting 'space' as one letter) in the =
first=20
      position. The chance of the monkey happening to get the first =
letter-M=20
      -right is therefore 1 in 27. The chance of it getting the first =
two=20
      letters =97 ME - right is the chance of it getting the second =
letter - E -=20
      right (1 in <BR>27) </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">given that </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">it has also got the first =
letter - M -=20
      right, therefore 1/27 x 1/27, which equals 1/729. The chance of it =
getting=20
      the first word - METHINKS - right is 1/27 for each of the 8 =
letters,=20
      therefore (1/27) X (1/27) x (1/27) x (1/27). .., etc. 8 times, or =
(1/27)=20
      to the power 8. The chance of it getting the entire phrase of 28=20
      characters right is (1/27) to the power 28, i.e. (1/27) multiplied =
by=20
      itself 28 times. These are very small odds, about 1 in 10,000 =
million=20
      million million million million million. To put it mildly, the =
phrase we=20
      seek would be a long time coming, to say nothing of the complete =
works of=20
      Shakespeare. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.75pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.8pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">So much for single-step =
selection of=20
      random variation. What about cumulative selection; how much more =
effective=20
      should this be? Very very much more effective, perhaps more so =
than we at=20
      first realize, although it is almost obvious when we reflect =
further. We=20
      again use our computer monkey, but with a crucial difference in =
its=20
      program. It again begins by choosing a random sequence of 28 =
letters, just=20
      as before: </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.35in 0pt 11.05pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">WDLMNLT DTJBKWIRZREZLMQCO P =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.55pt 0pt 0.95pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">It now 'breeds from' this =
random phrase.=20
      It duplicates it repeatedly, but with a certain chance of random =
error -=20
      'mutation' - in the copying. The computer examines the mutant =
nonsense=20
      phrases, the 'progeny' of the original phrase, and chooses the one =
which,=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">however =
slightly,=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">most resembles =
the=20
      target phrase, METHINKS IT IS LIKE A </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.55pt 0pt 0.95pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
