  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle5 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.05pt 0pt 0.25pt"><I><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Accumulating small change=20
      </SPAN></I><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">49 =
</SPAN></B><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.05pt 0pt 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the program was written in =
BASIC, a sort=20
      of computer baby-talk. When I rewrote it in Pascal, it took 11 =
seconds.)=20
      Computers are a bit faster at this kind of thing than monkeys, but =
the=20
      difference really isn't significant. What matters is the =
difference=20
      between the time taken by </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">cumulative </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">selection, and the time which =
the same=20
      computer, <BR>working flat out at the same rate, would take to =
reach the=20
      target phrase if it were forced to use the other procedure of=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">single-step =
selection:=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">about a =
million million=20
      million million million years. This is more than a million million =
million=20
      times as long as the universe has so far existed. Actually it =
would be=20
      fairer just to say that, in comparison with the time it would take =
either=20
      a monkey or a randomly programmed computer to type our target =
phrase, the=20
      total age of the universe so far is a negligibly small quantity, =
so small=20
      as to be well within the margin of error for this sort of=20
      back-of-an-envelope calculation. Whereas the time taken for a =
computer=20
      working randomly but with the constraint of </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">cumulative selection to =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">perform the same task is of the =
same=20
      order as humans ordinarily can understand, between 11 seconds and =
the time=20
      it takes to have lunch. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.25pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">There is a big difference, =
then, between=20
      cumulative selection (in which each improvement, however slight, =
is used=20
      as a basis for future building), and single-step selection (in =
which each=20
      new 'try' is a fresh one). If evolutionary progress had had to =
rely on=20
      single-step selection, it would never have got anywhere. If, =
however,=20
      there was any way in which the necessary conditions for =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">cumulative </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">selection could have been set =
up by the=20
      blind forces of nature, strange and wonderful might have been the=20
      consequences. As a matter of fact that is exactly what happened on =
this=20
      planet, and we ourselves are among the most recent, if not the =
strangest=20
      and most wonderful, of those consequences. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.7pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">It is amazing that you can =
still read=20
      calculations like my haemoglobin calculation, used as though they=20
      constituted arguments </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">against </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Darwin's theory. The people who =
do this,=20
      often expert in their own field, astronomy or whatever it may be, =
seem=20
      sincerely to believe that Darwinism explains living organization =
in terms=20
      of chance - 'single- step selection' - alone. This belief, that =
Darwinian=20
      evolution is 'random', is not merely false. It is the exact =
opposite of=20
      the truth. Chance is a minor ingredient in the Darwinian recipe, =
but the=20
      most important ingredient is cumulative selection which is=20
      quintessentially nonrandom. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.25pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Clouds are not capable of =
entering into=20
      cumulative selection. There is no mechanism whereby clouds of =
particular=20
      shapes can spawn daughter clouds resembling themselves. If there =
were such=20
      a mechanism, if a cloud resembling a weasel or a camel could give =
rise to=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.25pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D381 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.5pt 0pt 3.85pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">50 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.05in; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">a lineage of othel clouds of =
roughly the=20
      same shape, cumulative selection would have the opportunity to get =
going.=20
      Of course, clouds do break up and form 'daughter' clouds =
sometimes, but=20
      this isn't enough for cumulative selection. It is also necessary =
that the=20
      'progeny' of any given cloud should resemble its 'parent' =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">more </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">than it resembles any old =
'parent' in the=20
      'population'. This vitally important point is apparently =
misunderstood by=20
      some of the philosophers who have, in recent years, taken an =
interest in=20
      the theory of natural selection. It is further <BR>necessary that =
the=20
      chances of a given cloud's surviving and spawning copies should =
depend=20
      upon its shape. Maybe in some distant galaxy these conditions did =
arise,=20
      and the result, if enough millions of years have gone by, is an =
ethereal,=20
      wispy form of life. This might make a good science fiction story - =

      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The White =
Cloud, it=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">could be =
called - but=20
      for our purposes a computer model like the monkey/Shakespeare =
model is=20
      easier to grasp. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.1pt 0pt 1.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Although the monkey/Shakespeare =
model is=20
      useful for explaining the distinction between single-step =
selection and=20
      cumulative selection, it is misleading in important ways. One of =
these is=20
      that, in each generation of selective 'breeding', the mutant =
'progeny'=20
      phrases were judged according to the criterion of resemblance to a =

      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">distant ideal=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">target, the =
phrase=20
      METHINKS IT IS LIKE A WEASEL. Life isn't like that. Evolution has =
no=20
      long-term goal. There is no long-distance target, no final =
perfection to=20
      serve as a criterion for selection, although human vanity =
cherishes the=20
      absurd notion that our species is the final goal of evolution. In =
real=20
      life, the criterion for selection is always short-term, either =
simple=20
      survival or, more generally, reproductive success. If, after the =
aeons,=20
      what looks like progress towards some distant goal seems, with =
hindsight,=20
      to have been achieved, this is always an incidental consequence of =
many=20
      generations of short-term selection. The 'watchmaker' that is =
cumulative=20
      natural selection is blind to the future and has no long-term =
goal.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.65pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">We can change our computer =
model to take=20
      account of this point. We can also make it more realistic in other =

      respects. Letters and words are peculiarly human manifestations, =
so let's=20
      make the computer draw pictures instead. Maybe we shall even see=20
      animal-like shapes evolving in the computer, by cumulative =
selection of=20
      mutant forms. We shan't prejudge the issue by building-in specific =
animal=20
      pictures to start with. We want them to emerge solely as a result =
of=20
      cumulative selection </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold">of=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">random =
mutations.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
4.4pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">In real life, the form of each =
individual=20
      animal is produced by embryonic development. Evolution occurs =
because, in=20
      successive generations, there are slight differences in embryonic=20
      development. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
4.4pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D377 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle24 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.7pt 0pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Accumulating small change =
</SPAN></I>51=20
      <SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle24=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.7pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt">These=20
      differences come about because of changes (mutations - this is the =
small=20
      random element in the process that I spoke of) in the genes =
controlling=20
      development. In our computer model, therefore, we must have =
something=20
      equivalent to embryonic development, and something equivalent to =
genes=20
      that can mutate. There are many ways in which we could meet these=20
      specifications in a computer model. I chose one and wrote a =
program that=20
      embodied it. I shall now describe this computer model, because I =
think it=20
      is revealing. If you don't know anything about computers, just =
remember=20
      that they are machines that do exactly what you tell them but =
often=20
      surprise you in the result. A list of instructions for a computer =
is=20
      called a program (this is standard American spelling, and it is =
also=20
      recommended by the Oxford Dictionary: the alternative, =
'programme',=20
      commonly used in Britain, appears to be a Frenchified =
affectation). </P>
      <P class=3DStyle24=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.5pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.35pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt">Embryonic=20
      development is far too elaborate a process to simulate =
realistically on a=20
      small computer. We must represent it by some simplified analogue. =
We must=20
      find a simple picture-drawing rule that the computer can easily =
obey, and=20
      which can then be made to vary under the influence of 'genes'. =
What=20
      drawing rule shall we choose? Textbooks of computer science often=20
      illustrate the power of what they call 'recursive' programming =
with a=20
      simple <I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">tree-growing=20
      </SPAN></I>procedure. The computer starts by drawing a single =
vertical=20
      line. Then the line branches into two. Then each of the branches =
splits=20
      into two subbranches. Then each of the sub-branches splits into=20
      sub-sub-branches, and so on. It is 'recursive' because the same =
rule (in=20
      this case a branching rule) is applied locally all over the =
growing tree.=20
      No matter how big the tree may grow, the same branching rule goes =
on being=20
      applied at the tips of all its twigs. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle24=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.5pt 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt">The=20
      'depth' of recursion, means the number of sub-sub-. .. branches =
that are=20
      allowed to grow, before the process is brought to a halt. Figure 2 =
shows=20
      what happens when you tell the computer to obey exactly the same =
drawing=20
      rule, but going on to various depths of recursion. At high levels =
of=20
      recursion the pattern becomes quite elaborate, but you can easily =
see in=20
      Figure 2 that it is still produced by the same very simple =
branching rule.=20
      This is, of course, just what happens in a real tree. The =
branching=20
      pattern of an oak tree or an apple free looks complex, but it =
really=20
      isn't. The basic branching rule is very simple. It is because it =
is=20
      applied recursively at the growing tips all over the tree - =
branches make=20
      sub-branches, then each sub-branch makes sub-sub-branches, and so =
on -=20
      that the whole tree ends up large and bushy. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle24 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.2pt">Recursive =
branching is also a=20
      good metaphor for the embryonic development of plants and animals=20
      generally. I don't mean that animal </P>
      <P class=3DStyle24 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.2pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D17 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D375 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D17>
      <P class=3DStyle9><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica">52 =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle9><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D448 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D153 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D448>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic"><IMG=20
      height=3D448=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image026.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D153></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D131 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D377 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D131>
      <P class=3DStyle18 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 240.8pt 0pt =
0.95pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Figure 2 =
</SPAN><BR><BR></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle19 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.5pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt">embryos=20
      look like branching trees. They don't. But all embryos grow by =
cell=20
      division. Cells always split into two daughter cells. And genes =
always=20
      exert their final effects on bodies by means of <I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">local </SPAN></I>influences on =
cells,=20
      and on the two-way branching patterns of cell division. An =
animal's genes=20
      are never a grand design, a blueprint for the whole body. The =
genes, as we=20
      shall see, are more like a recipe than like a blueprint; and a =
recipe,=20
      moreover, that is obeyed not by the developing embryo as </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.5pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.65pt 0pt 0.25pt"><I><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Accumulating small change=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">53 =
<BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
1.35pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">a whole, but by each cell or =
each local=20
      cluster of dividing cells. I'm not denying that the embryo, and =
later the=20
      adult, </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">has=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">a large-scale =
form. But=20
      this large-scale form </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">emerges </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">because of lots of little local =
cellular=20
      effects all over the developing body, and these local effects =
consist=20
      primarily of two-way branchings, in the form of two-way cell =
splittings.=20
      It is by influencing these local events that genes ultimately =
exert=20
      influences on the adult body. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
1.45pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The simple branching rule for =
drawing=20
      trees, then, looks like a promising analogue for embryonic =
development.=20
      Accordingly, we wrap it up in a little computer procedure, label =
it=20
      DEVELOPMENT, and prepare to embed it in a larger program labelled=20
      EVOLUTION. As a first step towards writing this larger program, we =
now=20
      turn our attention to genes. How shall we represent 'genes' in our =

      computer model? Genes in real life do two things. They influence=20
      development, and they get passed on to future generations. In real =
animals=20
      and plants there are tens of thousands of genes, but we shall =
modestly=20
      limit our computer model to nine. Each of the nine genes is simply =

      represented by a number in the computer, which will be called its=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">value. =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The value of a particular gene =
might be,=20
      say 4, or -7. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">How shall we make these genes =
influence=20
      development? There are lots of things they could do. The basic =
idea is=20
      that they should exert some minor quantitative influence on the =
drawing=20
      rule that is DEVELOPMENT. For instance, one gene might influence =
the angle=20
      of branching, another might influence the length of some =
particular=20
      branch. Another obvious thing for a gene to do is to influence the =
depth=20
      of the recursion, the number of successive branchings. I made Gene =
9 have=20
      this effect. You can regard Figure 2, therefore, as a picture of =
seven=20
      related organisms, identical to each other except with respect to =
Gene=20
      <BR>9. I shan't spell out in detail what each one of the other =
eight genes=20
      does. You can get a general idea of the </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">kinds </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">of things they do by studying =
Figure 3.=20
      In the middle of the picture is the basic tree, one of the ones =
from=20
      Figure 2. Encircling this central tree are eight others. All are =
the same=20
      as the central tree, except that one gene, a different gene in =
each of the=20
      eight, has been changed - 'mutated'. For instance, the picture to =
the=20
      right of the central tree shows what happens when Gene 5 mutates =
by having=20
      +1 added to its value. If there'd been room, I'd have liked to =
print a=20
      ring of 18 mutants around the central tree. The reason for wanting =
18 is=20
      that there are nine genes, and each one can mutate in an 'upward'=20
      direction (1 is added to its value) or in a ' downward' direction =
(1 is=20
      subtracted from its value). So a ring of 18 trees would be enough =
to=20
      represent all </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">possible=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">single-step =
mutants that=20
      you can derive from the one central tree. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D16 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D375 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D16>
      <P class=3DStyle6><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">54 =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle6><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D310 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D310>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic"><IMG =
height=3D310=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image027.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D378></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D258 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D377 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D258>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 239.95pt 0pt =
0.95pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Figure 3 </SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Each of these trees has its =
own, unique=20
      'genetic formula', the numerical values of its nine genes. I =
haven't=20
      written the genetic formulae down, because they wouldn't mean =
anything to=20
      you, in themselves. That is true of real genes too. Genes only =
start to=20
      mean <BR>something when they are translated, via protein =
synthesis, into=20
      <BR>growingrules for a developing embryo. And in the computer =
model too,=20
      the numerical values of the nine genes only mean something when =
they are=20
      translated into growing rules for the branching tree pattern. But =
you can=20
      get an idea of what each gene does by </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">comparing </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the bodies of two organisms =
known to=20
      differ with respect to a certain gene. Compare, for instance, the =
basic=20
      tree in the middle of the picture with the two trees on either =
side, and=20
      you'll get some idea of what Gene 5 does. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.45pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">This, too, is exactly what =
real-life=20
      geneticists do. Geneticists normally don't know how genes exert =
their=20
      effects on embryos. Nor do they know the complete genetic formula =
of any=20
      animal. But by </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.45pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 2.4pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Accumulating small change=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">55 =
<BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.15pt 0pt 2.15pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">comparing the bodies of two =
adult animals=20
      that are known to </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">differ=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">according to a =
single=20
      gene, they can see what effects that single gene has. It is more=20
      complicated than that, because the effects of genes interact with =
each=20
      other in ways that are more complicated than simple addition. =
Exactly the=20
      same is true of the computer trees. Very much so, as later =
pictures will=20
      show. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.2pt 0pt 1.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">You will notice that all the =
shapes are=20
      symmetrical about a left/right axis. This is a constraint that I =
imposed=20
      on the DEVELOPMENT procedure. I did it partly for aesthetic =
reasons;=20
      partly to economize on the number of genes necessary (if genes =
didn't=20
      exert mirror-image effects on the two sides of the tree, we'd need =

      separate genes for the left and the right sides); and partly =
because I was=20
      hoping to evolve animal-like shapes, and most animal bodies are =
pretty=20
      symmetrical. For the same reason, from now on I shall stop calling =
these=20
      creatures 'trees', and shall call them 'bodies' or 'biomorphs'. =
Biomorph=20
      is the name coined by Desmond Morris for the vaguely animal-like =
shapes in=20
      his surrealist paintings. These paintings have a special place in =
my=20
      affections, because one of them was reproduced on the cover of my =
first=20
      book. Desmond Morris claims that his biomorphs 'evolve' in his =
mind, and=20
      that their evolution can be traced through successive paintings.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.35pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Back to the computer biomorphs, =
and the=20
      ring of 18 possible mutants, of which a representative eight are =
drawn in=20
      Figure 3. Since each member of the ring is only one mutational =
step away=20
      from the central biomorph, it is easy for us to see them as=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">children=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">of the central =
parent.=20
      We have our analogue of REPRODUCTION, which, like DEVELOPMENT, we =
can wrap=20
      up in another small computer program, ready to embed in our big =
program=20
      called EVOLUTION. Note two things about REPRODUCTION. First, there =
is no=20
      sex; reproduction is asexual. I think of the biomorphs as female,=20
      therefore, because asexual animals like greenfly are nearly always =

      basically female in form. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.15pt 0pt 0.5pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Second, my mutations are all =
constrained=20
      to occur one at a time. A child differs from its parent at only =
one of the=20
      nine genes; moreover, all mutation occurs by +1 or =97 1 being =
added to the=20
      value of the corresponding parental gene. These are just arbitrary =

      conventions: they could have been different and still remained=20
      biologically realistic. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.15pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The same is not true of the =
following=20
      feature of the model, which embodies a fundamental principle of =
biology.=20
      The shape of each child is not derived directly from the shape of =
the=20
      parent. Each child gets its shape from the values of its own nine =
genes=20
      (influencing angles, distances, and so on). And each child gets =
its nine=20
      genes from its parent's nine genes. This is just what happens in =
real=20
      life. Bodies don't get passed down the generations; genes do. =
Genes=20
      influence embryonic </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.15pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D377 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.2pt 0pt 1.45pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">56 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">development of </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">the </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">body in which they are sitting. =
Then=20
      those same genes either get passed on to the next generation or =
they=20
      don't. The nature of the genes is unaffected by their =
participation in=20
      bodily development, but their likelihood of being passed on may be =

      affected by the success of the body that they helped to create. =
This is=20
      why, in the computer model, it is important that the two =
procedures called=20
      DEVELOPMENTandREPRODUCTIONarewrittenastwowatertight compartments. =
They are=20
      watertight except that REPRODUCTION passes gene values across to=20
      DEVELOPMENT, where they influence the growing rules. DEVELOPMENT =
most=20
      emphatically does not pass gene values back to REPRODUCTION - that =
would=20
      be tantamount to 'Lamarckism' (see Chapter 11). </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.65pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">We have assembled our two =
program=20
      modules, then, labelled DEVELOPMENT and REPRODUCTION. REPRODUCTION =
passes=20
      genes down the generations, with the possibility of mutation. =
DEVELOPMENT=20
      takes the genes provided by REPRODUCTION in any given generation, =
and=20
      translates those genes into drawing action, and hence into a =
picture of a=20
      body on the computer screen. The time has come to bring the two =
modules=20
      together in the big program called EVOLUTION. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.65pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">EVOLUTION basically consists of =
endless=20
      repetition of REPRODUCTION. In every generation, REPRODUCTION =
takes the=20
      genes that are supplied to it by the previous generation, and =
hands them=20
      on to the next generation but with minor random errors - =
mutations. A=20
      mutation simply consists in +1 or =97 1 being added to the value =
of a=20
      randomly chosen gene. This means that, as the generations go by, =
the total=20
      amount of genetic difference from the original ancestor can become =
very=20
      large, cumulatively, one small step at a time. But although the =
mutations=20
      are random, the cumulative change over the generations is not =
random. The=20
      progeny in any one generation are different from their parent in =
random=20
      directions. But which of those progeny is selected to go forward =
into the=20
      next generation is not random. This is where Darwinian selection =
comes in.=20
      The criterion for selection is not the genes themselves, but the =
bodies=20
      whose shape the genes influence through DEVELOPMENT. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.2pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">In addition to being =
REPRODUCED, the=20
      genes in each generation are also handed to DEVELOPMENT, which =
grows the=20
      appropriate body on the screen, following its own strictly =
laid-down=20
      rules. In every generation, a whole 'litter' of 'children' (i.e.=20
      individuals of the next generation) is displayed. All these =
children are=20
      mutant children of the same parent, differing from their parent =
with=20
      respect to one gene each. This very high mutation rate is a =
distinctly=20
      unbiological feature of the </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.2pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 3.1pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Accumulating small change=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">57 =
<BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.35pt 0pt 2.65pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">computer model. In real life, =
the=20
      probability that a gene will mutate is often less than one in a =
million.=20
      The reason for building a high mutation rate into the model is =
that the=20
      whole performance on the computer screen is for the benefit of =
human eyes,=20
      and humans haven't the patience to wait a million generations for =
a=20
      mutation! </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.85pt 0pt 2.15pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The human eye has an active =
role to play=20
      in the story. It is the selecting agent. It surveys the litter of =
progeny=20
      and chooses one for breeding. The chosen one then becomes the =
parent of=20
      the next generation, and a litter of </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">its </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">mutant children are displayed=20
      simultaneously on the screen. The human eye is here doing exactly =
what it=20
      does in the breeding of pedigree dogs or prize roses. Our model, =
in other=20
      words, is strictly a model of artificial selection, not natural =
selection.=20
      The criterion for 'success' is not the direct criterion of =
survival, as it=20
      is in true natural selection. In true natural selection, if a body =
has=20
      what it takes to survive, its genes automatically survive because =
they are=20
      inside it. So the genes that survive tend to be, automatically, =
those=20
      genes that confer on bodies the qualities that assist them to =
survive. In=20
      the computer model, on the other hand, the selection criterion is =
not=20
      survival, but the ability to appeal to human whim. Not necessarily =
idle,=20
      casual whim, for we can resolve to select consistently for some =
quality=20
      such as 'resemblance to a weeping willow'. In my experience, =
however, the=20
      human selector is more often capricious and opportunistic. This, =
too, is=20
      not unlike certain kinds of natural selection. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.05pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The human tells the computer =
which one of=20
      the current litter of progeny to breed from. The genes of the =
chosen one=20
      are passed across to REPRODUCTION, and a new generation begins. =
This=20
      process, like real-life evolution, goes on indefinitely. Each =
generation=20
      of biomorphs is only a single mutational step away from its =
predecessor=20
      and its successor. But after 100 generations of EVOLUTION, the =
biomorphs=20
      can be anything up to 100 mutational steps away from their =
original=20
      ancestor. And in 100 mutational steps, much can happen. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
2.5pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">I never dreamed </SPAN><I><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">how </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">much, when I first started to =
play with=20
      my newly written EVOLUTION program. The main thing that surprised =
me was=20
      that the biomorphs can pretty quickly cease to look like trees. =
The basic=20
      two-way branching structure is always there, but it is easily =
smothered as=20
      lines cross and recross one another, making solid masses of colour =
(only=20
      black and white in the printed pictures). Figure 4 shows one =
particular=20
      evolutionary history consisting of no more than 29 generations. =
The=20
      ancestor is a tiny creature, a single dot. Although the ancestor's =
body is=20
      a dot, like a bacterium in the primeval slime, hidden inside'it is =
the=20
      potential for branching in exactly the pattern of the </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
2.5pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D11 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D36 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D11>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D11 =

      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image028.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D36></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
