clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle5 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 2.15pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Accumulating small change=20
      </SPAN></I><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">59 =
</SPAN></B><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.45pt 0pt 1.7pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">central tree of Figure 3: it is =
just that=20
      its Gene 9 tells it to branch zero times! All the creatures =
pictured on=20
      the page are descended from the dot but, in order to avoid =
cluttering the=20
      page, I haven't printed all the descendants that I actually saw. =
I've=20
      printed only the successful child of each generation (i.e. the =
parent of=20
      the next generation) and one or two of its unsuccessful sisters. =
So, the=20
      picture basically shows just the one main line of evolution, =
guided by my=20
      aesthetic selection. All the stages in the main line are shown.=20
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.45pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 8.15pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Let's briefly go through the =
first few=20
      generations of the main line of evolution in Figure 4. The dot =
becomes a Y=20
      in generation 2. In the next two generations, the Y becomes =
larger. Then=20
      the branches become slightly curved, like a well-made catapult. In =

      generation 7, the curve is accentuated, so that the two branches =
almost=20
      meet. The curved branches get bigger, and each acquires a couple =
of small=20
      appendages in generation 8. In generation 9 these appendages are =
lost=20
      again, and the stem of the catapult becomes longer. Generation 10 =
looks=20
      like a section through a flower; the curved side-branches resemble =
petals=20
      cupping a central appendage or 'stigma'. In generation 11, the =
same=20
      'flower' shape has become bigger and slightly more complicated.=20
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.65pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">I won't pursue the narrative. =
The picture=20
      speaks for itself, on through the 29 generations. Notice how each=20
      generation is just a little different from its parent and from its =

      sisters. Since each is a little different from its parent, it is =
only to=20
      be expected that each will be slightly </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">more </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">different from its grandparents =
(and its=20
      grandchildren), and even more different still from its great =
grandparents=20
      (and great grandchildren). This is what </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">cumulative </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">evolution is all about, =
although, because=20
      of our high mutation rate, we have speeded it up here to =
unrealistic=20
      rates. Because of this. Figure 4 looks more like a pedigree of=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">species =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">than a pedigree of individuals, =
but the=20
      principle is the same. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.2pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">When I wrote the program, I =
never thought=20
      that it would evolve anything more than a variety of tree-like =
shapes. I=20
      had hoped for weeping willows, cedars of Lebanon, Lombardy =
poplars,=20
      seaweeds, perhaps deer antlers. Nothing in my biologist's =
intuition,=20
      nothing in my 20 years' experience of programming computers, and =
nothing=20
      in my wildest dreams, prepared me for what actually emerged on the =
screen.=20
      I can't remember exactly when in the sequence it first began to =
dawn on me=20
      that an evolved resemblance to something like an insect was =
possible. With=20
      a wild surmise, I began to breed, generation after generation, =
from=20
      whichever child looked most like an insect. My incredulity grew in =

      parallel with the evolving resemblance. You see the eventual =
results at=20
      the bottom of Figure 4. Admittedly they have </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.2pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D382 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.15pt 0pt =
174.7pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4pt 0pt 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">eight legs like a spider, =
instead of six=20
      like an insect, but even so! I still cannot conceal from you my =
feeling of=20
      exultation as I first watched these exquisite creatures emerging =
before my=20
      eyes. I distinctly heard the triumphal opening chords of =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Also spiach Zaiathustia =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">(the '2001 theme') in my mind. =
I couldn't=20
      eat, and that night 'my' insects' swarmed behind my eyelids as I =
tried to=20
      sleep. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
3.9pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">There are computer games on the =
market in=20
      which the player has the illusion that he is wandering about in an =

      underground labyrinth, which has a definite if complex geography =
and in=20
      which he encounters dragons, minotaurs or other mythic =
adversaries. In=20
      these games the monsters are rather few in number. They are all =
designed=20
      by a human programmer, and so is the geography of the labyrinth. =
In the=20
      evolution game, whether the computer version or the real thing, =
the player=20
      (or observer) obtains the same feeling of wandering metaphorically =
through=20
      a labyrinth of branching passages, but the number of possible =
pathways is=20
      all but infinite, and the monsters that one encounters are =
undesigned and=20
      unpredictable. On my wanderings through the backwaters of Biomorph =
Land, I=20
      have encountered fairy shrimps, Aztec temples, Gothic church =
windows,=20
      aboriginal drawings of kangaroos, and, on one memorable but =
unrecapturable=20
      occasion, a passable caricature of the Wykeham Professor of Logic. =
Figure=20
      5 is another little collection from my trophy room, all of which =
developed=20
      in the same kind of way. I want to emphasize that these shapes are =
not=20
      artists' impressions. They have not been touched-up or doctored in =
any way=20
      whatever. They are exactly as the computer drew them when they =
evolved=20
      inside it. The role of the human eye was limited to =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">selecting, </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">among randomly mutated progeny =
over many=20
      generations of cumulative evolution. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.05pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">We now have a much more =
realistic model=20
      of evolution than the monkeys typing Shakespeare gave us. But the =
biomorph=20
      model is still deficient. It shows us the power of cumulative =
selection to=20
      generate </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">an=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">almost endless =
variety=20
      of quasi-biological form, but it uses artificial selection, not =
natural=20
      selection. The human eye does the selecting. Could we dispense =
with the=20
      human eye, and make the computer itself do the selecting, on the =
basis of=20
      some biologically realistic criterion? This is more difficult than =
it may=20
      seem. It is worth spending a little time explaining why. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.05pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">It is trivially easy to select =
for a=20
      particular genetic formula, so long as you can read the genes of =
all the=20
      animals. But natural selection doesn't choose genes directly, it =
chooses=20
      the </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">effects=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">that genes =
have on=20
      bodies, technically called phenotypic effects. The human eye is =
good at=20
      choosing phenotypic effects, as is shown by the numerous breeds of =

      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.05pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D10 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D46 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D10>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D10 =

      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
