<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D18 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D376 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D18>
      <P class=3DStyle14><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">Accumulating=20
      small change </SPAN></I><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold">61=20
      </SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle14><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D340 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D375 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D340>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold"><IMG=20
      height=3D340=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image031.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D375></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D244 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D244>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">dogs, cattle and pigeons, and =
also, if I=20
      may say so, </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">as=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">is shown by =
Figure=20
      <BR>5. To make the computer choose phenotypic effects directly, we =
should=20
      have to write a very sophisticated pattern-recognition program.=20
      Pattern-recognizing programs exist. They are used to read print =
and even=20
      handwriting. But they are difficult, 'state of the art' programs, =
needing=20
      very large and fast computers. Even if such a patternrecognition =
program=20
      were not beyond my programming capabilities, and beyond the =
capacity of my=20
      little 64-kilobyte computer, I wouldn't bother with it. This is a =
task=20
      that is better done by the human eye, together with - and this is =
more to=20
      the point - the 10-giganeurone computer inside the skull. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.4pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">It wouldn't be too difficult to =
make the=20
      computer select for vague general features like, say, =
tall-thinness,=20
      short-fatness, perhaps curvaceousness, spikiness, even rococo=20
      ornamentation. One method would be to program the computer to =
remember the=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">kinds =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">of qualities that humans have =
favoured in=20
      the past, and to exert continued selection of the same general =
kind in the=20
      future. But this isn't getting </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.4pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D376 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0.25pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">62 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.65pt 0pt 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">us any closer to simulating=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">natural =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">selection. The important point =
is that=20
      nature doesn't need computing power in order to select, except in =
special=20
      cases like peahens choosing peacocks. In nature, the usual =
selecting agent=20
      is direct, stark and simple. It is the grim reaper. Of course, the =

      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">reasons =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">for survival are anything but =
simple -=20
      that is why natural selection can build up animals and plants of =
such=20
      formidable complexity. But there is something very crude and =
simple about=20
      death itself. And nonrandom death is all it takes to select =
phenotypes,=20
      and hence the genes that they contain, in nature. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.95pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">To simulate natural selection =
in an=20
      interesting way in the computer, we should forget about rococo=20
      ornamentation and all other visually defined qualities. We should=20
      concentrate, instead, upon simulating nonrandom death. Biomorphs =
should=20
      interact, in the computer, with a simulation of a hostile =
environment.=20
      Something about their shape should determine whether or not they =
survive=20
      in that environment. Ideally, the hostile environment should =
include other=20
      evolving biomorphs: 'predators', 'prey', 'parasites', =
'competitors'. The=20
      particular shape of a prey biomorph should determine its =
vulnerability to=20
      being caught, for example, by particular shapes of predator =
biomorphs.=20
      Such criteria of vulnerability should not be built in by the =
programmer.=20
      They should </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">emerge,=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">in the same =
kind of way=20
      as the shapes themselves emerge. Evolution in the computer would =
then=20
      really take off, for the conditions would be met for a =
self-reinforcing=20
      'arms race' (see Chapter <BR>7), and I dare not speculate where it =
would=20
      all end. Unfortunately, I think it may be beyond my powers as a =
programmer=20
      to set up such a counterfeit world. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.6pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">If anybody is clever enough to =
do it, it=20
      would be the programmers who develop those noisy and vulgar arcade =
games -=20
      Space Invaders' derivatives. In these programs a counterfeit world =
is=20
      simulated. It has a geography, often in three dimensions, and it =
has a=20
      fast-moving time dimension. Entities zoom around in simulated=20
      three-dimensional space, colliding with each other, shooting each =
other=20
      down, swallowing each other amid revolting noises. So good can the =

      simulation be that the player handling the joystick receives a =
powerful=20
      illusion that he himself is part of the counterfeit world. I =
imagine that=20
      the summit of this kind of programming is achieved in the chambers =
used to=20
      train aeroplane and spacecraft pilots. But even these programs are =

      small-fry compared to the program that would have to be written to =

      simulate an emerging arms race between predators and prey, =
embedded in a=20
      complete, counterfeit ecosystem. It certainly could be done, =
<BR>however.=20
      If there is a professional programmer out there who feels like=20
      collaborating on the challenge, I should like to hear from him or =
her.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.6pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D381 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle26 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 4.55pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Accumulating small change=20
      </SPAN></I><B><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: 'Helvetica-Bold =
Oblique'">63=20
      </SPAN></I></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle15=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 4.1pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.65pt">Meanwhile,=20
      there is something else that is much easier, and which I intend =
trying=20
      when summer comes. I shall put the computer in a shady place in =
the=20
      garden. The screen can display in colour. I already have a version =
of the=20
      program which uses a few more 'genes' to control colour, in the =
same kind=20
      of way as the other nine genes control shape. I shall begin with =
any=20
      more-or-less compact and brightly coloured biomorph. The computer =
will=20
      simultaneously display a range of mutant progeny of the biomorph,=20
      differing from it in shape and/or colour pattern. I believe that =
bees,=20
      butterflies and other insects will visit the screen, and 'choose' =
by=20
      bumping into a particular spot on the screen. When a certain =
number of=20
      choices have been logged, the computer will wipe the screen clean, =
'breed'=20
      from the preferred biomorph, and display the next generation of =
mutant=20
      progeny. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle15=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.95pt 0pt 2.15pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt">I=20
      have high hopes that, over a large number of generations, the wild =
insects=20
      will actually cause the evolution, in the computer, of flowers. If =
they=20
      do, the computer flowers will have evolved under exactly the same=20
      selection pressure as caused real flowers to evolve in the wild. I =
am=20
      encouraged in my hope by the fact that insects frequently visit =
bright=20
      blobs of colour on women's dresses (and also by more systematic=20
      experiments that have been published). An alternative possibility, =
which I=20
      would find even more exciting, is that the wild insects might =
cause the=20
      evolution of insect-like shapes. The precedent for this - and =
hence the=20
      reason for hope - is that bees in the past caused the evolution of =

      bee-orchids. Male bees, over many generations of cumulative orchid =

      evolution, have built up the bee-like shape through trying to =
copulate=20
      with flowers, and hence carrying pollen. Imagine the 'bee-flower' =
of=20
      Figure 5 in colour. Wouldn't you fancy it if you were a bee? </P>
      <P class=3DStyle15=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.75pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt">My=20
      main reason for pessimism is that insect vision works in a very =
different=20
      way from ours. Video-screens are designed for human eyes not bee =
eyes.=20
      This could easily mean that, although both we and bees see =
bee-orchids, in=20
      our very different ways, as bee-like, bees might not see =
video-screen=20
      images at all. Bees might see nothing but 625 scanning lines! =
Still, it is=20
      worth a try. By the time this book is published, I shall know the =
answer.=20
      </P>
      <P class=3DStyle15=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.5pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt">There=20
      is a popular cliche, usually uttered in the tones Stephen Potter =
would=20
      have called 'plonking', which says that you cannot get out of =
computers=20
      any more than you put in. Other versions are that computers only =
do=20
      exactly what you tell them to, and that therefore computers are =
never=20
      creative. The cliche is true only in a crashingly trivial sense, =
the same=20
      sense in which Shakespeare never wrote anything except what his =
first=20
      schoolteacher taught him to write =97 words. I </P>
      <P class=3DStyle15=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.5pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D377 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.3pt 0pt 0.25pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">64 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.5pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">programmed EVOLUTION into the =
computer,=20
      but I did not plan 'my' insects, nor the scorpion, nor the =
spitfire, nor=20
      the lunar lander. I had not the slightest inkling that they would =
emerge,=20
      which is why 'emerge' is the right word. True, my eyes did the =
selecting=20
      that guided their evolution, but at every stage I was limited to a =
small=20
      clutch of progeny offered up by random mutation, and my selection=20
      'strategy', such as it was, was opportunistic, capricious and =
short-term.=20
      I was not aiming for any distant target, and nor does natural =
selection.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.1pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">I can dramatize this by =
discussing the=20
      one time when I </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">did=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">try to aim for =
a distant=20
      target. First I must make a confession. You will have guessed it =
anyway.=20
      The evolutionary history of Figure 4 is a reconstruction. It was =
not the=20
      first time I had seen 'my' insects. When they originally emerged =
to the=20
      sound of trumpets, I had no means of recording their genes. There =
they=20
      were, sitting on the computer screen, and I couldn't get at them, =
couldn't=20
      decipher their genes. I delayed switching the computer off while I =
racked=20
      my brain trying to think of some way of saving them, but there was =
none.=20
      The genes were too deeply buried, just as they are in real life. I =
could=20
      print out pictures of the insects' bodies, but I had lost their =
genes. I=20
      immediately modified the program so that in future it would keep=20
      accessible records </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold">of=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">genetic =
formulae, but it=20
      was too late. I had lost my insects. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">I set about trying to 'find' =
them again.=20
      They had evolved once, so </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">it </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">seemed that it must be possible =
to evolve=20
      them again. Like the lost chord, they haunted me. I wandered =
through=20
      Biomorph Land, moving through an endless landscape of strange =
creatures=20
      and things, but I couldn't find my insects. I knew that they must =
be=20
      lurking there somewhere. I knew the genes from which the original=20
      evolution had started. I had a picture of my insects' bodies. I =
even had a=20
      picture of the evolutionary sequence of bodies leading up to my =
insects by=20
      slow degrees from a dot ancestor. But I didn't know their genetic =
formula.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.45pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">You might think that it would =
have been=20
      easy enough to reconstruct the evolutionary pathway, but it =
wasn't. The=20
      reason, which I shall come back to, is the astronomical number of=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">possible=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">biomorphs that =
a=20
      sufficiently long evolutionary pathway can offer, even when there =
are only=20
      nine genes varying. Several times on my pilgrimage through =
Biomorph Land I=20
      seemed to come close to a precursor of my insects, but, then, in =
spite of=20
      my best efforts as a selecting agent, evolution went off on what =
proved to=20
      be a false trail. Eventually, during my evolutionary wanderings =
through=20
      Biomorph Land - the sense of triumph was scarcely less than on the =
first=20
      occasion -1 finally cornered them again. I didn't know (still =
don't) if=20
      these insects were exactly the same as my original, 'lost chords =
of=20
      Zarathustra' insects, or whether </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.45pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D382 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle11 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05pt 0pt 4.3pt"><I><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Accumulating small change=20
      </SPAN></I><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica-Bold">65=20
      </SPAN></B><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: =
9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 4.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.45pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">they were superficially =
'convergent' (see=20
      next chapter), but it was good enough. This time there was no =
mistake: I=20
      wrote down the genetic formula, and now I can 'evolve' insects =
whenever I=20
      want. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.1pt 0pt 0.05in; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Yes I am piling on the drama a =
bit, but=20
      there is a serious point being made. The point of the story is =
that even=20
      though it was I that programmed the computer, telling it in great =
detail=20
      what to do, nevertheless I didn't plan the animals that evolved, =
and I was=20
      totally surprised by them when I first saw their precursors. So =
powerless=20
      was I to control the evolution that, even when I very much wanted =
to=20
      retrace a particular evolutionary pathway it proved all but =
impossible to=20
      do so. I don't believe I would ever have found my insects again if =
I=20
      hadn't had a printed picture of the </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">complete set </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">of their evolutionary =
precursors, and=20
      even then it was difficult and tedious. Does the powerlessness of =
the=20
      programmer to control or predict the course of evolution in the =
computer=20
      seem paradoxical? Does it mean that something mysterious, even =
mystical=20
      was going on inside the computer? Of course not. Nor is there =
anything=20
      mystical going on in the evolution of real animals and plants. We =
can use=20
      the computer model to resolve the paradox, and learn something =
about real=20
      evolution in the process. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.4pt 0pt 1.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">To anticipate, the basis of the =

      resolution of the paradox will turn out to be as follows. There is =
a=20
      definite set of biomorphs, each permanently sitting in its own =
unique=20
      place in a mathematical space. It is permanently sitting there in =
the=20
      sense that, if only you knew its genetic formula, you could =
instantly find=20
      it; moreover, its neighbours in this special kind of space are the =

      biomorphs that differ from it by only one gene. Now that I know =
the=20
      genetic formula of my insects, I can reproduce them at will, and I =
can=20
      tell the computer to 'evolve' towards them from any arbitrary =
starting=20
      point. When you first evolve a new creature by artificial =
selection in the=20
      computer model, it feels like a creative process. So it is, =
indeed. But=20
      what you are really doing is </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">finding </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the creature, for it is, in a=20
      mathematical sense, already sitting in its own place in the =
genetic space=20
      of Biomorph Land. The reason it is a truly creative process is =
that=20
      finding any particular creature is <BR>extremely difficult, simply =
and=20
      purely because Biomorph Land is very very large, and the total =
number of=20
      creatures sitting there is all but infinite. It isn't feasible =
just to=20
      search aimlessly and at random. You have to adopt some more =
efficient -=20
      creative - searching procedure. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
3.85pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Some people fondly believe that =

      chess-playing computers work by internally trying out all possible =

      combinations of chess moves. They find this belief comforting when =
a=20
      computer beats them, but their belief is utterly false. There are =
far too=20
      many possible chess moves: the search-space is billions of times =
too large=20
      to allow blind stumbling to </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
3.85pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D376 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.95pt"><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">66 </SPAN></B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.1pt 0pt 0.7pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">succeed. The art of writing a =
good chess=20
      program is thinking of efficient short cuts through the =
search-space.=20
      Cumulative selection, whether artificial selection as in the =
computer=20
      model or natural selection out there in the real world, is an =
efficient=20
      searching procedure, and its consequences look very like creative=20
      intelligence. That, after all, is what William Paley's Argument =
from=20
      Design was all about. Technically, all that we are doing, when we =
play the=20
      computer biomorph game, is </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">finding </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">animals that, in a mathematical =
sense,=20
      are waiting to be found. What it feels like is a process of =
artistic=20
      creation. Searching a small space, with only a few entities in it, =
doesn't=20
      ordinarily feel like a creative process. A child's game of hunt =
the=20
      thimble doesn't feel creative. Turning things over at random and =
hoping to=20
      stumble on the sought object usually works when the space to be =
searched=20
      is small. As the search-space gets larger, more and more =
sophisticated=20
      searching procedures become necessary. Effective searching =
procedures=20
      become, when the search-space is </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">sufficiently </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">large, indistinguishable from =
true=20
      creativity. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.5pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The computer biomorph models =
make these=20
      points well, and they constitute an instructive bridge between =
human=20
      creative processes, such as planning a winning strategy at chess, =
and the=20
      evolutionary creativity of natural selection, the blind =
watchmaker. To see=20
      this, we must develop the idea of Biomorph Land as a mathematical =
'space',=20
      an endless but orderly vista of morphological variety, but one in =
which=20
      every creature is sitting in its correct place, waiting to be =
discovered.=20
      The 17 creatures of Figure 5 are arranged in no special order on =
the page.=20
      But in Biomorph Land itself each occupies its own unique position, =

      determined by its genetic formula, surrounded by its own =
<BR>particular=20
      neighbours. All the creatures in Biomorph Land have a definite =
spatial=20
      relationship one to another. What does that mean? What meaning can =
we=20
      attach to spatial position? </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The space we are talking about =
is genetic=20
      space. Each animal has its own position in genetic space. Near =
neighbours=20
      in genetic space are animals that differ from one another by only =
a single=20
      mutation. In Figure 3, the basic tree in the centre is surrounded =
by 8 of=20
      its 18 immediate neighbours in genetic space. The 18 neighbours of =
an=20
      animal are the 18 different kinds of children that it can give =
rise to,=20
      and the 18 different kinds of parent from which it could have =
come, given=20
      the rules of our computer model. At one remove, each animal has =
324 (18=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">x =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">18, ignoring back-mutations for =

      simplicity) neighbours, the set of its possible grandchildren,=20
      grandparents, aunts or nieces. At one remove again, each animal =
has 5,832=20
      (18 x 18 x 18) neighbours, the set of possible great =
grandchildren, great=20
      grandparents, first cousins, etc. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D629 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D383 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D629>
      <P class=3DStyle27 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.5pt 0pt 4.55pt"><I><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Accumulating small change=20
      </SPAN></I><B><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: 'Helvetica-Bold =
Oblique'">67=20
      </SPAN></I></B><B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.8pt 0pt 4.1pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">What is the point of thinking =
in terms of=20
      genetic space? Where does it get us? The answer is that it =
provides us=20
      with a way to understand evolution as a gradual, cumulative =
process. In=20
      any one generation, according to the rules of the computer model, =
it is=20
      possible to move only a single step through genetic space. In 29=20
      generations it isn't possible to move farther than 29 steps, in =
genetic=20
      space, away from the starting ancestor. Every evolutionary history =

      consists of a particular pathway, or trajectory, through genetic =
space.=20
      For instance, the evolutionary history recorded in Figure 4 is a=20
      particular winding trajectory through genetic space, connecting a =
dot to=20
      an insect, and passing through 28 intermediate stages. It is this =
that I=20
      mean when I talk metaphorically about 'wandering' through Biomorph =
Land.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.35pt 0pt 2.4pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">I wanted to try to represent =
this genetic=20
      space in the form of a picture. The trouble is, pictures are=20
      two-dimensional. The genetic space in which the biomorphs sit is =
not=20
      two-dimensional space. It isn't even three-dimensional space. It =
is=20
      nine-dimensional space! (The important thing to remember about =
mathematics=20
      is not to be frightened. It isn't as difficult as the mathematical =

      priesthood sometimes pretends. Whenever I feel intimidated, I =
always=20
      remember Silvanus Thompson's dictum in </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Calculus Made Easy: =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">'What one fool can do, another =
can'.) If=20
      only we could draw in nine dimensions we could make each dimension =

      correspond to one of the nine genes. The position of a particular =
animal,=20
      say the scorpion or the bat or the insect, is fixed in genetic =
space by=20
      the numerical value of its nine genes. Evolutionary change =
consists of a=20
      step by step walk through nine-dimensional space. The amount of =
genetic=20
      difference between one animal and another, and hence the time =
taken to=20
      evolve, and the difficulty of evolving from one to the other, is =
measured=20
      as the </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">distance=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">in =
ninedimensional space=20
      from one to the other. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.3pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Alas, we can't draw in nine =
dimensions. I=20
      sought a way of fudging it, of drawing a two-dimensional picture =
that=20
      conveyed something of what it feels like to move from point to =
point in=20
      the nine-dimensional genetic space of Biomorph Land. There are =
various=20
      possible ways in which this could be done, and I chose one that I =
call the=20
      triangle trick. Look at Figure 6. At the three corners of the =
triangle are=20
      three arbitrarily chosen biomorphs. The one at the top is the =
basic tree,=20
      the one on the left is one of 'my' insects, and the one on the =
right has=20
      no name but I thought it looked pretty. Like all biomorphs, each =
of these=20
      three has its own genetic formula, which determines its unique =
position in=20
      nine-dimensional genetic space. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The =
triangle lies=20
      on a flat two-dimensional 'plane' that cuts through the =
nine-dimensional=20
      hypervolume (what one </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold">fool=20
      can </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">do, =
another .=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
