<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D19 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D376 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D19>
      <P class=3DStyle6><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Helvetica-Bold">68=20
      </SPAN></B><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind =
Watchmaker=20
      </SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle6><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D246 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D361 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D246>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic"><IMG =
height=3D246=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image033.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D361></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D344 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D377 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D344>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.2pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">can). The plane is like a flat =
piece of=20
      glass stuck through a jelly. On the glass is drawn the triangle, =
and also=20
      some of the biomorphs whose genetic formulae entitle them to sit =
on that=20
      particular flat plane. What is it that entitles them? This is =
where the=20
      three biomorphs at the corners of the triangle come in. They are =
called=20
      the anchor biomorphs. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.4pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Remember that the whole idea of =

      'distance' in genetic 'space' is that genetically similar =
biomorphs are=20
      near neighbours, genetically different biomorphs are distant =
neighbours.=20
      On this particular plane, the distances are all calculated with =
reference=20
      to the three anchor biomorphs. For any given point on the sheet of =
glass,=20
      whether inside the triangle or outside it, the appropriate genetic =
formula=20
      for that point is calculated as a 'weighted average' of the =
genetic=20
      formulae of the three anchor biomorphs. You will already have =
guessed how=20
      the weighting is done. It is done by the distances on the page, =
more=20
      precisely the </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">nearnesses, </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">from the point in question to =
the three=20
      anchor biomorphs. So, the nearer you are to the insect on the =
plane, the=20
      more insect-like are the local biomorphs. As you move along the =
glass=20
      towards the tree, the 'insects' gradually become less insect-like =
and more=20
      tree-like. If you walk into the centre of the triangle the animals =
that=20
      you find there, for instance the spider with a Jewish =
seven-branched=20
      candelabra on its head, will be various 'genetic compromises' =
between the=20
      three anchor biomorphs. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.5pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">But this account gives =
altogether too=20
      much </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">prominence =
to the=20
      three </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">anchor =
biomorphs.=20
      Admittedly the computer did </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">use them to calculate =
</SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.5pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D11 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D33 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D11>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold"><IMG height=3D11=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image034.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D33></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D227 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D227>
      <P class=3DStyle29 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.1pt 0pt 1.7pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Accumulating small change=20
      </SPAN></I><B><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: 'Helvetica-Bold =
Oblique'">69=20
      </SPAN><BR><BR></I></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05pt 0pt 1.45pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the appropriate genetic formula =
for every=20
      point on the picture. But actually any three anchor points on the =
plane=20
      would have done the trick just as well, and would have given =
identical=20
      results. For this reason, in Figure 7 I haven't actually drawn the =

      triangle. Figure 7 is exactly the same kind of picture as Figure =
6. It=20
      just shows a different plane. The same insect is one of the three =
anchor=20
      points, this time the right-hand one. The other anchor points, in =
this=20
      case, are the spitfire and the bee-flower, both as seen in Figure =
5. On=20
      this plane, too, you will notice that neighbouring biomorphs =
resemble each=20
      other more than distant biomorphs. The spitfire, for instance, is =
part of=20
      a squadron of similar aircraft, flying in formation. Because the =
insect is=20
      on both sheets of glass, you can think of the two sheets as =
passing, at an=20
      angle, through each other. Relative to Figure 6, the plane of =
Figure 7 is=20
      said to be 'rotated about' the insect. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05pt 0pt 1.45pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D243 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D370 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D243>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG =
height=3D243=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image035.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D371></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D144 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D377 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D144>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.1pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The elimination of the triangle =
is an=20
      improvement to </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold">our=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">method, =
because it was a=20
      distraction. It gave undue prominence to three particular points =
in the=20
      plane. We still have one further improvement to make. In Figures 6 =
and 7,=20
      spatial distance represents genetic distance, but the =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">scaling </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">is all distorted. One inch =
upwards is not=20
      necessarily equivalent to one inch across. To remedy this, we must =
choose=20
      our three anchor biomorphs carefully, so that their genetic =
distances, one=20
      from the other, are all the same. Figure 8 does just this. Again =
the=20
      triangle is not actually drawn. The three anchors are the scorpion =
from=20
      Figure 5, the insect again (we have yet another 'rotation about' =
the=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.1pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D214 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D377 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D214>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.5pt 0pt 0.7pt">70 =
<I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.5pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">insect), and the rather =
nondescript=20
      biomorph at the top. These three biomorphs are all 30 mutations =
distant=20
      from each other. This means that it is equally easy to evolve from =
any one=20
      to any other one. In all three cases, a minimum of 30 genetic =
steps must=20
      be taken. The little blips along the lower margin of Figure 8 =
represent=20
      units of distance measured in genes. You can think of it as a =
genetic=20
      ruler. The ruler doesn't only work in the horizontal direction. =
You can=20
      tilt it in any direction, and measure the genetic distance, and =
hence the=20
      minimum evolution time, between any point on the plane and any =
other=20
      (annoy - ingly, that is not quite true on the page, because the =
computer's=20
      printer distorts proportions, but this effect is too trivial to =
make a=20
      fuss about, although it does mean that you will get slightly the =
wrong=20
      answer if you simply count blips on the scale). </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.5pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D277 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D373 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D277>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG =
height=3D277=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image036.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D373></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D116 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D377 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D116>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">These two-dimensional planes =
cutting=20
      through nine-dimensional genetic space give some feeling for what =
it means=20
      to walk through Biomorph Land. To improve that feeling, you have =
to=20
      remember that evolution is not restricted to one flat plane. On a =
true=20
      evolutionary walk you could 'drop through', at any time, to =
another plane,=20
      for instance from the plane of Figure 6 to the plane of Figure 7 =
(in the=20
      vicinity of the insect, where the two planes come close to each =
other).=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 10.3pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">I said that the 'genetic ruler' =
of Figure=20
      8 enables us to calculate the </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 10.3pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D380 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.05in"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Accumulating small change=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">71 =
<BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.25pt 0pt 3.35pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">minimum time it would take to =
evolve from=20
      one point to another. So it does, given the restrictions of the =
original=20
      model, but the emphasis is on the word </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">minimum. </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Since the insect and the =
scorpion are 30=20
      genetic units distant from one another, it takes only 30 =
generations to=20
      evolve from one to the other </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">if you never take a wrong =
turning,=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">if, that is, =
you know=20
      exactly what genetic formula you are heading towards, and how to =
steer=20
      towards it. In real-life evolution there is nothing that =
corresponds to=20
      steering towards some distant genetic target. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.45pt 0pt 2.15pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Let's now use the biomorphs to =
return to=20
      the point made by the monkeys typing Hamlet, the importance of =
gradual,=20
      step-by-step change in evolution, as opposed to pure chance. Begin =
by=20
      relabelling the graticules along the bottom of Figure 8, but in =
different=20
      units. Instead of measuring distance as 'number of genes that have =
to=20
      change in evolution', we are going to measure distance as 'odds of =

      happening to jump the distance, by sheer luck, in a single hop'. =
To think=20
      about this, we now have to relax one of the restrictions that I =
built into=20
      the computer game: we shall end by seeing why I built that =
restriction in=20
      in the first place. The restriction was that children were only =
'allowed'=20
      to be one mutation distant from their parents. In other words, =
only one=20
      gene was allowed to mutate at a time, and that gene was allowed to =
change=20
      its 'value' only by +1 or -1. By relaxing the restriction, we are =
now=20
      allowing any number of genes to mutate simultaneously, and they =
can add=20
      any number, positive or negative, to their current value. =
Actually, that=20
      is too great a relaxation, since it allows genetic values to range =
from=20
      minus infinity to plus infinity. The point is adequately made if =
we=20
      restrict gene values to single figures, that is if we allow them =
to range=20
      from -9 to +9. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.8pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">So, within these wide limits, =
we are=20
      theoretically allowing mutation, at a stroke, in a single =
generation, to=20
      change any combination of the nine genes. Moreover, the value of =
each gene=20
      can change any amount, so long as it doesn't stray into double =
figures.=20
      What does this mean? It means that, theoretically, evolution can =
jump, in=20
      a single generation, from any point in Biomorph Land to any other. =
Not=20
      just any point on one plane, but any point in the entire =
ninedimensional=20
      hypervolume. If, for instance, you should want to jump in one fell =
swoop=20
      from the insect to the fox in Figure 5, here is the recipe. Add =
the=20
      following numbers to the values of Genes 1 to 9, respectively:=20
      -2,2,2,-2,2,0,-4,-1,1. But since we are talking about random =
jumps,=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">all =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">points in Biomorph Land are =
equally=20
      likely as destinations for one of these jumps. So, the odds =
against=20
      jumping to any </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">particular </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">destination, say the fox, by =
sheer luck,=20
      are easy to calculate. They are simply the total number of =
biomorphs in=20
      the space. As you can see, we </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.8pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.45pt 0pt 1.45pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">72 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.95pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">are embarking on another of =
those=20
      astronomical calculations. There are nine genes, and each of them =
can take=20
      any of 19 values. So the total number of biomorphs that we =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">could </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">jump to in a single step is 19 =
times=20
      itself 9 times over: 19 to the power 9. This works out as about =
half a=20
      trillion biomorphs. Paltry compared with Asimov's 'haemoglobin =
number',=20
      but still what I would call a large number. If you started from =
the=20
      insect, and jumped like a demented flea half a trillion times, you =
could=20
      expect to arrive at the fox once. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.4pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">What is all this telling us =
about real=20
      evolution? Once again, it is ramming home the importance of=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">gradual,=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">step-by-step =
change.=20
      There have been evolutionists who have denied that gradualism of =
this kind=20
      is necessary in evolution. Our biomorph calculation shows us=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">exactly =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">one reason why gradual, =
step-by-step=20
      change is important. When I say that you can expect evolution to =
jump from=20
      the insect to one of its immediate neighbours, but </SPAN><I><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">not to </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">jump from the insect directly =
to the fox=20
      or the scorpion, what I exactly mean is the following. If =
genuinely random=20
      jumps really occurred, then a jump from insect to scorpion would =
be=20
      perfectly possible. Indeed it would be just </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">as </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">probable as a jump from insect =
to one of=20
      its immediate neighbours. But it would also be just as probable as =
a jump=20
      to any other biomorph in the land. And there's the rub. For the =
number of=20
      biomorphs in the land is half a trillion, and if no one of them is =
any=20
      more probable as a destination than any other, the odds of jumping =
to any=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">particular=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">one are small =
enough to=20
      ignore. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
1.05pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Notice that it doesn't help us =
to assume=20
      that there is a powerful nonrandom 'selection pressure'. It =
wouldn't=20
      matter if you'd been <BR>promised a king's ransom if you achieved =
a lucky=20
      jump to the scorpion. The odds against your doing so are still =
half a=20
      trillion to one. But if, instead of jumping you </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">walked, </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">one step at a time, and were =
given one=20
      small coin as a reward every time you happened to take a step in =
the right=20
      direction, you would reach the scorpion in a very short time. Not=20
      necessarily in the fastest possible time of 30 generations, but =
very fast,=20
      nevertheless. Jumping could </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">theoretically </SPAN></I><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">get you the prize faster - in a =
single=20
      hop. But because of the astronomical odds against success, a =
series of=20
      small steps, each one building on the accumulated success of =
previous=20
      steps, is the only feasible way. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.8pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The tone of my previous =
paragraphs is=20
      open to a misunderstanding which I must dispel. It sounds, once =
again, as=20
      though evolution deals in distant targets, homing in on things =
like=20
      scorpions. As we have seen, it never does. But if we think of our =
target=20
      as </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">anything =
that would=20
      improve survival chances, </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the argument still works. If an =
animal is=20
      a parent, it must be good enough to survive at least to adulthood. =
It is=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.8pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D9 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D66 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D9>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D9=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image037.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D66></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D382 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 4.55pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Accumulating small change=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">73 =
<BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.75pt 0pt 4.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">possible that a mutant child of =
that=20
      parent might be even better at surviving. But if a child mutates =
in a big=20
      way, so that it has moved a long distance away from its parent in =
genetic=20
      space, what are the odds of its being better than its parent? The =
answer=20
      is that the odds against are very large indeed. And the reason is =
the one=20
      we have just seen with our biomorph model. If the mutational jump =
we are=20
      considering is a very large one, the number of </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">possible </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">destinations of that jump is=20
      astronomically large. And because, as we saw in Chapter 1, the =
number of=20
      different ways of being dead is so much greater than the number of =

      different ways of being alive, the chances are very high that a =
big random=20
      jump in genetic space will end in death. Even a small random jump =
in=20
      genetic space is pretty likely to end in death. But the smaller =
the jump=20
      the less likely death is, and the more likely is it that the jump =
will=20
      result in improvement. We shall return to this theme in a later =
chapter.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.5pt 0pt 2.15pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">That is as far as I want to go =
in drawing=20
      morals from Biomorph Land. I hope that you didn't find it too =
abstract.=20
      There is another mathematical space filled, not with nine-gened =
biomorphs=20
      but with flesh and blood animals made of billions of cells, each=20
      containing tens of thousands of genes. This is not biomorph space =
but real=20
      genetic space. The actual animals that have ever lived on Earth =
are a tiny=20
      subset of the theoretical animals that </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">could </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">exist. These real animals are =
the=20
      products of a very small number of evolutionary trajectories =
through=20
      genetic space. The vast majority of theoretical trajectories =
through=20
      animal space give rise to impossible monsters. Real animals are =
dotted=20
      around here and there among the hypothetical monsters, each =
perched in its=20
      own unique place in genetic hyperspace. Each real animal is =
surrounded by=20
      a little cluster of neighbours, most of whom have never existed, =
but a few=20
      of whom are its ancestors, its descendants and its cousins. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.4pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.55pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Sitting somewhere in this huge=20
      mathematical space are humans and hyenas, amoebas and aardvarks, =
flatworms=20
      and squids, dodos and dinosaurs. In theory, if we were skilled =
enough at=20
      genetic engineering, we could move from any point in animal space =
to any=20
      other point. From any starting point we could move through the =
maze in=20
      such a way as to recreate the dodo, the tyrannosaur and =
trilobites. If=20
      only we knew which genes to tinker with, which bits of chromosome =
to=20
      duplicate, invert or delete. I doubt if we shall ever know enough =
to do=20
      it, but these dear dead creatures are lurking there forever in =
their=20
      private corners of that huge genetic hypervolume, waiting to be=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">found =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">if we but had the knowledge to =
navigate=20
      the right course through the maze. We might even be able to=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">evolve =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">an exact reconstruction of a =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.4pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.55pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D128 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D376 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D128>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.2pt 0pt 0.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">74 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">dodo by selectively breeding =
pigeons,=20
      though we'd have to live a million years in order to complete the=20
      experiment. But when we are prevented from making a journey in =
reality,=20
      the imagination is not a bad substitute. For those, like me, who =
are not=20
      mathematicians, the computer can be a powerful friend to the =
imagination.=20
      Like mathematics, it doesn't only stretch the imagination. It also =

      disciplines and controls it. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
