<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D558 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D377 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D558>
      <P class=3DStyle16 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 104.15pt 0pt =
109.2pt">CHAPTER 4 <SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <H2 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 17.5pt 0pt 22.55pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 16.5pt">MAKING TRACKS THROUGH ANIMAL SPACE =
</SPAN><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR><BR><BR></SPAN></H2>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.1pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">As we saw in Chapter 2, many =
people find=20
      it hard to believe that something like the eye, Paley's favourite =
example,=20
      so complex and well designed, with so many interlocking working =
parts,=20
      could have arisen from small beginnings by a gradual series of=20
      step-by-step changes. Let's return to the problem in the light of =
such new=20
      intuitions as the biomorphs may have given us. Answer the =
following two=20
      questions: <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.55pt 0pt 1.2pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">1. Could the human eye have =
arisen=20
      directly from no eye at all, in a single step? <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.3pt 0pt 0.5pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">2. Could the human eye have =
arisen=20
      directly from something slightly different from itself, something =
that we=20
      may call X? <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.5pt 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The answer to Question 1 is =
clearly a=20
      decisive no. The odds against a 'yes' answer for questions like =
Question 1=20
      are many billions of times greater than the number of atoms in the =

      universe. It would need a gigantic and vanishingly improbable leap =
across=20
      genetic hyperspace. The answer to Question 2 is equally clearly=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">yes, =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">provided only that the =
difference between=20
      the modern eye and its immediate predecessor X is sufficiently =
small.=20
      Provided, in other words, that they are sufficiently close to one =
another=20
      in the space of all possible structures. If the answer to Question =
2 for=20
      any particular degree of difference is no, all we have to do is =
repeat the=20
      question for a smaller degree of difference. Carry on doing this =
until we=20
      find a degree of difference sufficiently small to give us a 'yes' =
answer=20
      to Question 2. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.7pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">X is </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">defined </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">as something very like a human =
eye,=20
      sufficiently similar that the human eye could plausibly have =
arisen by a=20
      single alteration in X. If you have a mental picture of X and you =
find it=20
      <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle23 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.45pt 0pt 259.9pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica">77 </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle23 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.45pt 0pt 259.9pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Helvetica"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 8pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Helvetica"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.95pt 0pt 0.25pt">78 =
<I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"LINE-HEIGHT: 10.85pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
3.45pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">implausible that the human eye =
could have=20
      arisen directly from it, this simply means that you have chosen =
the wrong=20
      X. Make your mental picture of X progressively more like a human =
eye,=20
      until you find an X that you </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">do </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">find plausible as an immediate=20
      predecessor to the human eye. There has to be one for you, even if =
your=20
      idea of what is plausible may be more, or less, cautious than =
mine!=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.9pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
3.55pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Now, having found an X such =
that the=20
      answer to Question 2 is yes, we apply the same question to X =
itself. By=20
      the same reasoning we must conclude that X could plausibly have =
arisen,=20
      directly by a single change, from something slightly different =
again,=20
      which we may call X'. Obviously we can then trace X' back to =
something=20
      else slightly different from it, X", and so on. By interposing a =
large=20
      enough series of Xs, we can derive the human eye from something =
not=20
      slightly different from itself but </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">very </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">different from itself. We can =
'walk' a=20
      large distance across 'animal space', and our move will be =
plausible=20
      provided we take small-enough steps. We are now in a position to =
answer a=20
      third question. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.55pt 0pt 0.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">3. Is there a continuous series =
of Xs=20
      connecting the modem human eye to a state with no eye at all? =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.4pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.8pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">It seems to me clear that the =
answer has=20
      to be yes, provided only that we allow ourselves a </SPAN><I><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">sufficiently large =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">series of Xs. You might feel =
that 1,000=20
      Xs is ample, but if you need more steps to make the total =
transition=20
      plausible in your mind, simply allow yourself to assume 10,000 Xs. =
And if=20
      10,000 is not enough for you, allow yourself 100,000, and so on. =
Obviously=20
      the available time imposes an upper ceiling on this game, for =
there can be=20
      only one X per generation. In practice the question therefore =
resolves=20
      itself into: Has there been enough time for enough successive =
generations?=20
      We can't give a precise answer to the number of generations that =
would be=20
      necessary. What we do know is that geological time is awfully =
long. Just=20
      to give you an idea of the order of magnitude we are talking =
about, the=20
      number of generations that separate us from our earliest ancestors =
is=20
      certainly measured in the thousands of millions. Given, say, a =
hundred=20
      million Xs, we should be able to construct a plausible series of =
tiny=20
      gradations linking a human eye to just about anything! </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.6pt 0pt 3.1pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">So far, by a process of =
more-or-less=20
      abstract reasoning, we have concluded that there is a series of =
imaginable=20
      Xs, each sufficiently similar to its neighbours that it could =
plausibly=20
      turn into one of its neighbours, the whole series linking the =
human eye=20
      back to no eye at alL But we still haven't demonstrated that it is =

      plausible that this series of Xs actually existed. We have two =
more=20
      questions to answer. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.6pt 0pt 3.1pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D386 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle27 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 6.7pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Making tracks through animal =
space=20
      </SPAN></I><B><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: 'Helvetica-Bold =
Oblique'">79=20
      </SPAN></I></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.15pt 0pt 6pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.55pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">4. Considering each member of =
the series=20
      of hypothetical Xs connecting the human eye to no eye at all, is =
it=20
      plausible that every one of them was made available by random =
mutation of=20
      its predecessor? <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.85pt 0pt 5.3pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">This is really a question about =

      embryology, not genetics; and it is an entirely separate question =
from the=20
      one that worried the Bishop of Birmingham and others. Mutation has =
to work=20
      by modifying the existing processes of embryonic development. It =
is=20
      arguable that certain kinds of embryonic process are highly =
amenable to=20
      variation in certain directions, recalcitrant to variation in =
others. I=20
      shall return to this matter in Chapter 11, so here I'll just =
stress again=20
      the difference between small change and large. The smaller the =
change you=20
      postulate, the smaller the difference between X" and X', the more=20
      embryologically plausible is the mutation concerned. In the =
previous=20
      chapter we saw, on purely statistical grounds, that any =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">particular </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">large mutation is inherently =
less=20
      probable than any particular small mutation. Whatever problems may =
be=20
      raised by Question 4, then, we can at least see that the smaller =
we make=20
      the difference between any given X' and X", the smaller will be =
the=20
      problems. My feeling is that, provided the difference between =
neighbouring=20
      intermediates in our series leading to the eye is </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">sufficiently small, =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the necessary mutations are =
almost bound=20
      to be forthcoming. We are, after all, always talking about minor=20
      quantitative changes in an existing embryonic process. Remember =
that,=20
      however complicated the embryological status quo may be in any =
given=20
      generation, each mutational </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">change </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">in the status quo can be very =
small and=20
      simple. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 114.1pt 0pt 11.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">We have one final question to =
answer:=20
      <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.7pt 0pt 1.7pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.35pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">5. Considering each member of =
the series=20
      of Xs connecting the human eye to no eye at all, is it plausible =
that=20
      every one of them worked sufficiently well that it assisted the =
survival=20
      and reproduction of the animals concerned? <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 5.15pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Rather oddly, some people have =
thought=20
      that the answer to this question is a self-evident 'no'. For =
instance, I=20
      quote from Francis Hitching's book of 1982 called </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Neck of the Giraffe or =
Where Darwin=20
      Went Wrong. </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">I =
could have=20
      quoted basically the same words from almost any Jehovah's Witness =
tract,=20
      but I choose this book because a reputable publisher (Pan Books =
Ltd) saw=20
      fit to publish it, despite a very large number of errors which =
would=20
      quickly have been spotted if an unemployed biology graduate, or =
indeed=20
      undergraduate, had been asked to glance through the manuscript. =
(My=20
      favourites, if you'll indulge me just two in-jokes, are the =
conferring of=20
      a knighthood </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 5.15pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D11 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D48 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D11>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D11 =

      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image039.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D48></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D634 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D634>
      <P class=3DStyle18 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.2pt 0pt 0.25pt"><B><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica-Bold">80 </SPAN></B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker=20
      </SPAN><BR><BR></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.6pt">on=20
      Professor <I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">]ohn=20
      </SPAN></I>Maynard Smith, and the description of Professor Ernst =
Mayr,=20
      that eloquent and most unmathematical arch-critic of mathematical=20
      genetics, as 'the high priest' of mathematical genetics.) </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 13.05pt 0pt 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 9.85pt">For =
the eye to=20
      work the following minimum perfectly coordinated steps have to =
take place=20
      (there are many others happening simultaneously, but even a =
grossly=20
      simplified description is enough to point up the problems for =
Darwinian=20
      theory). The eye must be clean and moist, maintained in this state =
by the=20
      interaction of the tear gland and movable eyelids, whose eyelashes =
also=20
      act as a crude filter against the sun. The light then passes =
through a=20
      small transparent section of the protective outer coating (the =
<I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">cornea), </SPAN></I>and =
continues via a=20
      <I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">lens </SPAN></I>which =
focuses=20
      it on the back of the <I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">retina.=20
      </SPAN></I>Here 130 million light-sensitive rods and cones cause=20
      photochemical reactions which transform the light into electrical=20
      impulses. Some 1,000 million of these are transmitted every =
second, by=20
      means that are not properly understood, to a brain which then =
takes=20
      appropriate action. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 5.35pt 0pt 9.85pt; TEXT-INDENT: 7.45pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 9.95pt">Now=20
      it is quite evident that if the slightest thing goes wrong =
<I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">en route-it </SPAN></I>the =
cornea is=20
      fuzzy, or the pupil fails to dilate, or the lens becomes opaque, =
or the=20
      focussing goes wrong =97 then a recognizable image is not formed. =
The eye=20
      either functions as a whole, or not at all. So how did it come to =
evolve=20
      by slow, steady, infinitesimally small Darwinian improvements? Is =
it=20
      really plausible that thousands upon thousands of lucky chance =
mutations=20
      happened coincidentally so that the lens and the retina, which =
cannot work=20
      without each other, evolved in synchrony? What survival value can =
there be=20
      in an eye that doesn't sec? </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.5pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt">This=20
      remarkable argument is very frequently made, presumably because =
people=20
      <I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">want to =
</SPAN></I>believe its=20
      conclusion. Consider the statement that 'if the slightest thing =
goes wrong=20
      . . . if the focusing goes wrong . . . a recognizable image is not =

      formed'. The odds cannot be far from 50/50 that you are reading =
these=20
      words through glass lenses. Take them off and look around. Would =
you agree=20
      that 'a recognizable image is not formed'? If you are male, the =
odds are=20
      about 1 in 12 that you are colourblind. You may well be =
astigmatic. It is=20
      not unlikely that, <BR>without glasses, your vision is a misty =
blur. One=20
      of today's most distinguished (though not yet knighted) =
evolutionary=20
      theorists so seldom cleans his glasses that his vision is probably =
a misty=20
      blur anyway, but he seems to get along pretty well and, by his own =

      account, he used to play a mean game of monocular squash. If you =
have lost=20
      your glasses, it may be that you upset your friends by failing to=20
      recognize them in the street. But you yourself would be even more =
upset if=20
      somebody said to you: 'Since your vision is now not absolutely =
perfect,=20
      you might as well go around with your eyes tight shut until you =
find your=20
      glasses again.' Yet that is essentially what the author of the =
passage I=20
      have quoted is suggesting. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.5pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D9 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D66 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D9>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D9=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image040.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D66></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
