<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D383 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle5 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.4pt 0pt 4.55pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Making tracks through animal =
space=20
      </SPAN></I><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">81 =
</SPAN></B><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 4.1pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">He also states, as though it =
were=20
      obvious, that the lens and the retina cannot work without each =
other. On=20
      what authority? Someone close to me has had a cataract operation =
in both=20
      eyes. She has no lenses in her eyes at all. Without glasses she =
couldn't=20
      even begin to play lawn tennis or aim a rifle. But she assures me =
that you=20
      are far better off with a lensless eye than with no eye at all. =
You can=20
      tell if you are about to walk into a wall or another person. If =
you were a=20
      wild creature, you could certainly use your lensless eye to detect =
the=20
      looming shape of a predator, and the direction from which it was=20
      approaching. In a primitive world where some creatures had no eyes =
at all=20
      and others had lensless eyes, the ones with lensless eyes would =
have all=20
      sorts of advantages. And there is a <BR>continuous series of Xs, =
such that=20
      each tiny improvement in sharpness of image, from swimming blur to =
perfect=20
      human vision, plausibly increases the organism's chances of =
surviving.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.25pt 0pt 1.9pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The book goes on to quote =
'Stephen Jay=20
      Gould, the noted Harvard palaeontologist, as saying: </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 7.4pt 0pt 12.25pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">We avoid the excellent =
question, What=20
      good is 5 percent of an eye? by </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">arguing </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">that the possessor of such an =
incipient=20
      structure did not use it for sight. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.55pt 0pt 1.7pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">An ancient animal with 5 per =
cent of an=20
      eye might indeed have used it for something other than sight, but =
it seems=20
      to me at least as likely that it used it for 5 per cent vision. =
And=20
      actually I don't think it is an excellent question. Vision that is =
5 per=20
      cent as good as yours or mine is very much worth having in =
comparison with=20
      no vision at all. So is 1 per cent vision better than total =
blindness. And=20
      6 per cent is better than 5, 7 per cent better than 6, and so on =
up the=20
      gradual, continuous series. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.1pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">This kind of problem has =
worried some=20
      people interested in animals that gain protection from predators =
by=20
      'mimicry'. Stick insects look like sticks and so are saved from =
being=20
      eaten by birds. Leaf insects look like leaves. Many edible species =
of=20
      butterfly gain protection by resembling noxious or poisonous =
species.=20
      These resemblances are far more <BR>impressive than the =
resemblance of=20
      clouds to weasels. In many cases they are more impressive than the =

      resemblance of 'my' insects to real insects. Real insects, after =
all, have=20
      six legs, not eight! Real natural selection has had a least a =
million=20
      times as many generations as I had, in which </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">to </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">perfect the resemblance. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.95pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">We use the word 'mimicry' for =
these=20
      cases, not because we think that the animals consciously imitate =
other=20
      things, but because natural selection has favoured those =
individuals whose=20
      bodies were mistaken for other things. To put it another way, =
ancestors of=20
      stick insects that did not resemble sticks did not leave =
descendants. The=20
      German-American geneticist Richard Goldschmidt is the most =
distinguished=20
      of those who </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.95pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D634 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D634>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.4pt 0pt 0.7pt">82 =
<I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.55pt 0pt 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">have argued that the =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">early </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">evolution of such resemblances =
could not=20
      have been favoured by natural selection. As Gould, an admirer of=20
      Goldschmidt, said of dung-mimicking insects: 'can there be any =
edge in=20
      looking 5 per cent like a turd?' Largely through Gould's =
influence, it has=20
      recently become fashionable to say that Goldschmidt was =
<BR>underrated in=20
      his own lifetime, and that he really has much to teach us. Here is =
a=20
      sample of his reasoning. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 19.05pt 0pt 10.3pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 9.9pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Ford speaks . . . of any =
mutation which=20
      chances to give a 'remote resemblance' to a more protected =
species,=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">from =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">which some advantage, however =
slight,=20
      might accrue. We must ask how remote the resemblance can be to =
have=20
      selective value. Can we really assume that the birds and monkeys =
and also=20
      mantids are such wonderful observers (or that some very clever =
ones among=20
      them are) to notice a 'remote' resemblance and be repelled by it? =
I think=20
      that this is asking too much. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.65pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Such sarcasm ill becomes =
anybody on the=20
      shaky ground that Goldschmidt here treads. </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Wonderful </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">observers? Very </SPAN><I><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">clever </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">ones among them? Anybody would =
think the=20
      birds and monkeys </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">benefited </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">from being fooled by the remote =

      resemblance! Goldschmidt might rather have said: 'Can we really =
assume=20
      that the birds, etc. are such </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">poor </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">observers (or that some very =
stupid ones=20
      among them are)?' Nevertheless, there is a real dilemma here. The =
initial=20
      resemblance of the ancestral stick insect to a stick must have =
been very=20
      remote. A bird would need extremely </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">poor </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">vision to be fooled by it. Yet =
the=20
      resemblance of a modem stick insect to a stick is marvellously =
good, down=20
      to the last fine details of fake buds and leaf-scars. The birds =
whose=20
      selective predation put the finishing touches to their evolution =
must, at=20
      least collectively, have had excellently </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">good </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">vision. They must have been =
extremely=20
      hard to fool, otherwise the insects would not have evolved to =
become as=20
      perfect mimics as they are: they would have remained relatively =
imperfect=20
      mimics. How can we resolve this apparent contradiction? =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.1pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">One kind of answer suggests =
that bird=20
      vision has been improving over the same evolutionary timespan as =
insect=20
      camouflage. Perhaps, to be a little facetious, an ancestral insect =
that=20
      looked only 5 per cent like a turd would have fooled an ancestral =
bird=20
      with only 5 per cent vision. But that is not the kind of answer I =
want to=20
      give. I suspect, indeed, that the whole process of evolution, from =
remote=20
      resemblance to near perfect mimicry, has gone on, rather rapidly, =
many=20
      times over in different insect groups, during the whole long =
period that=20
      bird vision has been just about as good as it is today. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.95pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Another kind of answer that has =
been=20
      offered to the dilemma is the following. Perhaps each species of =
bird or=20
      monkey has poor vision and </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.95pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D382 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle23 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 4.1pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Making tracks through animal=20
      </SPAN></I><B><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: 'Times-Bold =
Italic'">space=20
      </SPAN></I></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica">83 =
</SPAN><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.2pt 0pt 0.05in; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">latches onto just one limited =
aspect of=20
      an insect. Maybe one predator species notices only the colour, =
another=20
      only the shape, another only the texture, and so on. Then an =
insect that=20
      resembles a stick in only one limited respect will fool one kind =
of=20
      predator, even though it is eaten by all other kinds of predators. =
As=20
      evolution progresses, more and more features of resemblance are =
added to=20
      the repertoire of the insects. The final multifaceted perfection =
of=20
      mimicry has been put together by the summed natural selection =
provided by=20
      many different species of predators. No one predator sees the =
whole=20
      perfection of mimicry, only we do that. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.3pt 0pt 2.15pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">This seems to imply that only =
we are=20
      'clever' enough to see the mimicry in all its glory. Not only =
because of=20
      this human snobbishness, I prefer yet another explanation. This is =
that,=20
      no matter how good any one predator's vision may be under some =
conditions,=20
      it can be exceedingly poor under other 'conditions. We can easily, =
in=20
      fact, appreciate from our own familiar experience the whole =
spectrum from=20
      exceedingly poor vision to excellent vision. If I am looking =
directly at a=20
      stick insect, 8 inches in front of my nose and in strong daylight, =
I shall=20
      not be fooled by it. I shall notice the long legs hugging the line =
of the=20
      trunk. I may spot the unnatural symmetry which a real stick would =
not=20
      have. But if I, with the very same eyes and brain, am walking =
through a=20
      forest at dusk, I may well fail to distinguish almost any =
dullcoloured=20
      insect from the twigs that abound everywhere. The image of the =
insect may=20
      pass over the edge of my retina rather than the more acute central =
region.=20
      The insect may be 50 yards away, and so make only a tiny image on =
my=20
      retina. The light may be so poor that I can hardly see anything at =
all=20
      anyway. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">In fact, it doesn't matter=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">how =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">remote, how poor is the =
resemblance of an=20
      insect to a stick, there must be </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">some </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">level of twilight, or some =
degree of=20
      distance away from the eye, or some degree of distraction of the=20
      predator's attention, such that even a very good eye will be =
fooled by the=20
      remote resemblance. If you don't find that plausible for some =
particular=20
      example that you have imagined, just turn down the imaginary light =
a bit,=20
      or move a bit further away from the imaginary object! The point is =
that=20
      many an insect was saved by an exceedingly slight resemblance to a =
twig or=20
      a leaf or a fall of dung, on occasions when it was far away from a =

      predator, or on occasions when the predator was looking at it at =
dusk, or=20
      looking at it through a fog, or looking at it while distracted by =
a=20
      receptive female. And many an insect was saved, perhaps from the =
very same=20
      predator, by an uncannily close resemblance to a twig, =
</SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">on </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">occasions when the predator =
happened to=20
      be seeing it at relatively </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">close </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">range and in a good light. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D11 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D39 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D11>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D11 =

      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image041.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D39></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.1pt 0pt 0.25pt"><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica-Bold">84 </SPAN></B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"LINE-HEIGHT: 10.8pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The important thing about light =

      intensity, distance of insect from predator, distance of image =
from centre=20
      of retina, and similar variables, is that they are all =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">continuous </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">variables. They vary by =
insensible=20
      degrees all the way from the extreme of invisibility to the =
extreme of=20
      visibility. Such continuous variables foster continuous and =
gradual=20
      evolution. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.9pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Richard Goldschmidt's problem - =
which was=20
      one of a set that made him resort, for most of his professional =
life, to=20
      the extreme belief that evolution takes great leaps rather than =
small=20
      steps - turns out to be no problem at all. And incidentally, we =
have also=20
      demonstrated to ourselves, yet again, that 5 per cent vision is =
better=20
      than no vision at all. The quality of my vision right at the edge =
of my=20
      retina is probably even poorer than 5 per cent of the quality at =
the=20
      centre of my retina, however you care to measure quality. Yet I =
can still=20
      detect the presence of a large lorry or bus out of the extreme =
corner of=20
      my eye. Since I ride a bicycle to work every day this fact has =
quite=20
      probably saved my life. I notice the difference on those occasions =
when it=20
      is raining and I wear a hat. The quality of our vision on a dark =
night=20
      must be far poorer than 5 per cent of what it is at midday. Yet =
many an=20
      ancestor was probably saved through seeing something that really =
mattered,=20
      a sabre-tooth 'tiger' perhaps, or a precipice, in the middle of =
the night.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.6pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Every one of us knows from =
personal=20
      experience, for example on dark nights, that there is an =
insensibly graded=20
      continuous series running all the way from total blindness up to =
perfect=20
      vision, and that every step along this series confers significant=20
      benefits. By looking at the world through progressively defocused =
and=20
      focused binoculars, we can quickly convince ourselves that there =
is a=20
      graded series of focusing quality, each step in the series being =
an=20
      improvement over the previous one. By progressively turning the=20
      colour-balance knob of a colour television set, we can convince =
ourselves=20
      that there is a graded series of progressive improvement from =
black and=20
      white to full colour vision. The iris diaphragm that opens and =
shuts the=20
      pupil prevents us from being dazzled in bright light, while =
allowing us to=20
      see in dim light. We all experience what it is like not to have an =
iris=20
      diaphragm, when we are momentarily dazzled by oncoming car =
headlights.=20
      Unpleasant, and even dangerous, as this dazzling can be, it still =
doesn't=20
      mean that the whole eye ceases to work! The claim that 'The eye =
either=20
      functions as a whole, or not at all' turns out to be, not merely =
false but=20
      self-evidently false to anybody who thinks for 2 seconds about his =
own=20
      familiar experience. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.2pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Let us </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">return to our Question 5. =
Considering=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">each member=20
      </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">of the =
</SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">series of </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">Xs connecting the human eye to =
no eye at=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">all, is it=20
      </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">plausible =
</SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.2pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D632 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D381 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D632>
      <P class=3DStyle15 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 2.9pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Making tracks through animal =
space=20
      </SPAN></I>85 <SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle15=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.4pt 0pt 2.4pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt">that =
every one of=20
      them worked sufficiently well that it assisted the survival and=20
      reproduction of the animals concerned? We have now seen the =
silliness of=20
      the anti-evolutionist's assumption that the answer is an obvious =
no. But=20
      is the answer yes? It is less obvious, but I think that it is. Not =
only is=20
      it clear that part of an eye is better than no eye at all. We also =
can=20
      find a plausible series of intermediates among modern animals. =
This=20
      doesn't mean, of course, that these modern <SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR></SPAN>intermediates really represent =
ancestral=20
      types. But it does show that intermediate designs are capable of =
working.=20
      </P>
      <P class=3DStyle15=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.6pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt">Some=20
      single-celled animals have a light-sensitive spot with a little =
pigment=20
      screen behind it. The screen shields it from light coming from one =

      direction, which gives it some 'idea' of where the light is coming =
from.=20
      Among many-celled animals, various types of worm and some =
shellfish have a=20
      similar arrangement, but the pigment-backed lightsensitive cells =
are set=20
      in a little cup. This gives slightly better direction- finding =
capability,=20
      since each cell is selectively shielded from light rays coming =
into the=20
      cup from its own side. In a continuous series from flat sheet of=20
      light-sensitive cells, through shallow cup to deep cup, each step =
in the=20
      series, however small (or large) the step, would be an optical=20
      improvement. Now, if you make a cup very deep and turn the sides =
over, you=20
      eventually make a lensless pinhole camera. There is a continuously =
graded=20
      series from shallow cup to pinhole camera (see, for illustration, =
the=20
      first seven generations of the evolutionary series in Figure 4). =
</P>
      <P class=3DStyle14=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.45pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 8.65pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.9pt">A=20
      pinhole camera forms a definite image, the smaller the pinhole the =
sharper=20
      (but dimmer) the image, the larger the pinhole the brighter (but =
fuzzier)=20
      the image. The swimming mollusc <I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Nautilus, </SPAN></I>a rather =
strange=20
      squid-like creature that lives in a shell like the extinct =
ammonites (see=20
      the 'shelled cephalopod' of Figure 5), has a pair of pinhole =
cameras for=20
      eyes. The eye is basically the same shape as ours, but there is no =
lens=20
      and the pupil is just a hole that lets the seawater into the =
hollow=20
      interior of the eye. Actually, <I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Nautilus </SPAN></I>is a bit =
of a puzzle=20
      in its own right. Why, in all the hundreds of millions of years =
since its=20
      ancestors first evolved a pinhole eye, did it never discover the =
principle=20
      of the lens? The advantage of a lens is that it allows the image =
to be=20
      both sharp <I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">and=20
      </SPAN></I>bright. What is worrying about <I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Nautilus </SPAN></I>is that =
the quality=20
      of its retina suggests that it would really benefit, greatly and=20
      immediately, from a lens. It is like a hi-fi system with an =
excellent=20
      amplifier'fed by a gramophone with a blunt needle. The system is =
<SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR></SPAN>crying out for a particular =
simple=20
      change. In genetic hyperspace, <I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Nautilus </SPAN></I>appears to =
be=20
      sitting right next door to an obvious and immediate improvement, =
yet it=20
      doesn't take the small step necessary. Why <B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">not? </SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle14=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.45pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 8.65pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.9pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D10 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D44 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D10>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold"><IMG=20
      height=3D10=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image042.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D44></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle18 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.25pt 0pt =
1.45pt"><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">86 </SPAN></B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker=20
      </SPAN><BR><BR></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle19 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.45pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.95pt">Michael=20
      Land of Sussex University, our foremost authority on invertebrate =
eyes, is=20
      worried, and so am I. Is it that the necessary mutations cannot =
arise,=20
      given the way <I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">Nautilus=20
      </SPAN></I>embryos develop? I don't want to believe it, but I =
don't have a=20
      better explanation. At least <I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Nautilus </SPAN></I>dramatizes =
the point=20
      that a lensless eye is better than no eye at all. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.5pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt">When=20
      you have a cup for an eye, almost any vaguely convex, vaguely =
transparent=20
      or even translucent material over its opening will constitute an=20
      improvement, because of its slight lens-like properties. It =
collects light=20
      over its area and concentrates it on a smaller area of retina. =
Once such a=20
      crude proto-lens is there, there is a continuously graded series =
of=20
      improvements, thickening it and making it more transparent and =
less=20
      distorting, the trend culminating in what we would all recognize =
as a true=20
      lens. <I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Nautilus's=20
      </SPAN></I>relatives, the squids and octopuses, have a true lens, =
very=20
      like ours although their ancestors certainly evolved the whole =
camera-eye=20
      principle completely independently of ours. Incidentally, Michael =
Land=20
      reckons that there are nine basic principles for image-forming =
that eyes=20
      use, and that most of them have evolved many times independently. =
For=20
      instance, the curved dish-reflector principle is radically =
different from=20
      our own camera-eye (we use it in radiotelescopes, and also in our =
largest=20
      optical telescopes because it is easier to make a large mirror =
than a=20
      large lens), and it has been independently 'invented' by various =
molluscs=20
      and crustaceans. Other crustaceans have a compound eye like =
insects=20
      (really a bank of lots of tiny eyes), while other molluscs, as we =
have=20
      seen, have a lensed camera-eye like ours, or a pinhole camera-eye. =
For=20
      each of these types of eye, stages corresponding to evolutionary=20
      intermediates exist as working eyes among other modern animals. =
</P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.95pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt">Anti-evolution=20
      propaganda is full of alleged examples of complex systems that =
'could not=20
      possibly' have passed through a gradual series of intermediates. =
This is=20
      often just another case of the rather pathetic 'Argument from =
Personal=20
      Incredulity' that we met in Chapter 2. Immediately after the =
section on=20
      the eye, for example, <I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">The Neck=20
      of the Giraffe </SPAN></I>goes on to discuss the bombardier =
beetle, which=20
      </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 14.75pt 0pt 9.6pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 9.85pt">squirts=20
      a lethal mixture of hydroquinone and hydrogen peroxide into the =
face of=20
      its enemy. These two chemicals, when mixed together, literally =
explode. So=20
      in order to store them inside its body, the Bombardier Beetle has =
evolved=20
      a chemical inhibitor to make them harmless. At the moment the =
beetle=20
      squirts the liquid out of its tail, an anti-inhibitor is added to =
make the=20
      mixture explosive once again. The chain of events that could have =
led to=20
      the evolution of such a complex, coordinated and subtle process is =
beyond=20
      biological explanation on a simple step-by-step basis. The =
slightest </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 14.75pt 0pt 9.6pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 9.85pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D9 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D66 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D9>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D9=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image043.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D66></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D630 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D384 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D630>
      <P class=3DStyle23 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 4.55pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica-Oblique">Making tracks through =
animal space=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica">87 </SPAN><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 15.9pt 0pt 13.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">alteration in the chemical =
balance would=20
      result immediately in a race of exploded beetles. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.4pt 0pt 3.35pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.55pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">A biochemist colleague has =
kindly=20
      provided me with a bottle of hydrogen peroxide, and enough =
hydroquinone=20
      for 50 bombardier beetles. I am now about to mix the two together. =

      According to the above, they will explode in my face. Here goes . =
. .=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.55pt 0pt 2.65pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Well, I'm still here. I poured =
the=20
      hydrogen peroxide into the hydroquinone, and absolutely nothing =
happened.=20
      It didn't even get warm. Of course I knew it wouldn't: I'm not =
that=20
      foolhardy! The Statement that 'these two chemicals, when mixed =
together,=20
      literally explode', is, quite simply, false, although it is =
regularly=20
      repeated throughout creationist literature. If you are curious =
about the=20
      bombardier beetle, by the way, what actually happens is as =
follows. It is=20
      true that it squirts a scaldingly hot mixture of hydrogen peroxide =
and=20
      hydroquinone at enemies. But hydrogen peroxide and hydroquinone =
don't=20
      react violently together unless a catalyst is </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">added. </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">This is what the bombardier =
beetle does.=20
      As for the evolutionary precursors of the system, both hydrogen =
peroxide=20
      and various kinds of quinones are used for other purposes in body=20
      chemistry. The bombardier beetle's ancestors simply pressed into =
different=20
      service chemicals that already happened to be around. That's often =
how=20
      evolution works. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.25pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">On the same page of the book as =
the=20
      bombardier beetle passage is the question: 'What use would be . . =
. half a=20
      lung? Natural selection would surely eliminate creatures with such =

      oddities, not preserve them.' In a healthy adult human, each of =
the two=20
      lungs is divided into about 300 million tiny chambers, at the tips =
of a=20
      branching system of tubes. The architecture of these tubes =
resembles the=20
      biomorph tree at the bottom of Figure 2 in the previous chapter. =
In that=20
      tree, the number of <BR>successive branchings, determined by 'Gene =
9', is=20
      eight, and the number of twig tips is 2 to the power 8, or 256. As =
you go=20
      down the page in Figure 2, the number of twig tips successively =
doubles.=20
      In order to provide 300 million twig tips, only 29 successive =
doublings=20
      would be required. Note that there is a continuous gradation from =
a single=20
      chamber to 300 million tiny chambers, each step in the gradation =
being=20
      provided by another two-way branching. This transition can be =
accomplished=20
      in 29 branchings, which we may naively think of as a stately walk =
of 29=20
      steps across genetic space. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
4.2pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">In the lungs, the result of all =
this=20
      branching is that the surface area inside each lung is rather more =
than 70=20
      square yards. Area is the important variable for a lung, for it is =
area=20
      that determines the rate at which oxygen can be taken in, and =
waste carbon=20
      dioxide pushed out. Now, the thing .ibout area is that it is a=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">continuous=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">variable. Area =
is=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
4.2pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D9 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D28 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D9>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D9=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image044.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D28></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D629 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D629>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.95pt 0pt 1.45pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">88 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.05pt 0pt 0.95pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">not one of those things that =
you either=20
      have or you don't. It is a thing that you can have a little bit =
more of,=20
      or a little bit less of. More than most things, lung area lends =
itself to=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">gradual,=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">step-by-step =
change, all=20
      the way from 0 square yards up to 70 square yards. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.7pt 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">There are plenty of surgical =
patients=20
      walking around with only one lung, and some of them are down to a =
third of=20
      normal lung area. They may be walking, but they aren't walking =
very far,=20
      nor very fast. That is the point. The effect of gradually reducing =
lung=20
      area is not an absolute, all-or-none effect on survival. It is a =
gradual,=20
      continuously varying effect </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">on </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">how far you can walk, and how =
fast. A=20
      gradual, continuously varying effect, indeed, on how long you can =
expect=20
      to live. Death doesn't suddenly arrive below a particular =
threshold lung=20
      area! It becomes <BR>gradually more probable as lung area =
decreases below=20
      an optimum (and as it increases above the same optimum, for =
different=20
      reasons connected with economicwaste). </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.2pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The first of our ancestors to =
develop=20
      lungs almost certainly lived in water. We can get an idea of how =
they=20
      might have breathed by looking at modem fish. Most modem fish =
breathe in=20
      water with gills, but many species living in foul, swampy water =
supplement=20
      this by gulping air at the surface. They use the internal chamber =
of the=20
      mouth as a kind of crude proto-lung, and this cavity is sometimes =
enlarged=20
      into a breathing pocket rich in blood vessels. As we've seen, =
there is no=20
      problem in imagining a continuous series of Xs connecting a single =
pocket=20
      to a branching set of 300 million pockets as in a modem human =
lung.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Interestingly, many modem fish =
have kept=20
      their pocket single, and use it for a completely different =
purpose.=20
      Although it probably began as a lung, over the course of evolution =
it has=20
      become the swimbladder, an ingenious device with which the fish =
maintains=20
      itself as a hydrostat in permanent equilibrium. An animal without =
an air=20
      bladder inside it is normally slightly heavier than water, so =
sinks to the=20
      bottom. This is why sharks have to swim continuously to stop =
themselves=20
      sinking. An animal with large air pockets inside it, like us with =
our=20
      great lungs, tends to rise to the surface. Somewhere in the middle =
of this=20
      continuum, an animal with an air bladder of exactly the right size =
neither=20
      sinks nor rises, but floats steadily in effortless equilibrium. =
This is=20
      the trick that modem fish, other than sharks, have perfected. =
Unlike=20
      sharks, they don't waste energy preventing themselves from =
sinking. Their=20
      fins and tail are freed for guidance and rapid propulsion. They no =
longer=20
      rely on outside air to fill the bladder, but have special glands =
for=20
      manufacturing gas. Using these glands and other means, they =
accurately=20
      regulate the volume of gas in the bladder, and hence keep =
themselves in=20
      precise hydrostatic equilibrium. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D625 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D380 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D625>
      <P class=3DStyle23 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 2.65pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica-Oblique">Making tracks through =
animal space=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica">89 </SPAN><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.4pt 0pt 2.15pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Several species of modem fish =
can leave=20
      the water. An extreme is the Indian climbing perch, which hardly =
ever goes=20
      into the water. It has independently evolved a quite different =
kind of=20
      lung from that of our ancestors - an air chamber surrounding the =
gills.=20
      Other fish live basically in water but make brief forays out of =
it. This=20
      is probably what our ancestors did. The thing about forays is that =
their=20
      duration can vary continuously, all the way down to zero. If you =
are a=20
      fish who basically lives and breathes in water, but who =
occasionally=20
      ventures on land, perhaps to cross from one mud puddle to another =
thereby=20
      surviving a drought, you might benefit not just from half a lung =
but from=20
      onehundredth of a lung. It doesn't matter </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">how </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">small your primordial lung is, =
there must=20
      be </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">some =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">time out of water that you can =
just=20
      endure with the lung, which is a little bit longer than you could =
have=20
      endured without the lung. Time is a continuous variable. There is =
no=20
      hard-and-fast divide between water-breathing and air-breathing =
animals.=20
      Different animals may spend 99 per cent of their time in water, 98 =
per=20
      cent, 97 per cent, and so on all the way to 0 per cent. At every =
step of=20
      the way, some fractional increase in lung area will be an =
advantage. There=20
      is continuity, gradualism, all the way. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.95pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">What use is half a wing? How =
did wings=20
      get their start? Many animals leap from bough to bough, and =
sometimes fall=20
      to the ground. Especially in a small animal, the whole body =
surface=20
      catches the air </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold">and=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">assists the =
leap, or=20
      breaks the fall, by acting as a crude aerofoil. Any tendency to =
increase=20
      the ratio of surface area to weight would help, for example flaps =
of skin=20
      growing out in the angles of joints. From here, there is a =
continuous=20
      series of gradations to gliding wings, and hence to flapping =
wings.=20
      Obviously there are distances that could not have been jumped by =
the=20
      earliest animals with proto-wings. Equally obviously, for =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">any </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">degree of smallness or =
crudeness of=20
      ancestral air-catching surfaces, there must be </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">some </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">distance, however short, which =
can=20
      </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">be =
</SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">jumped with the flap and which =
cannot be=20
      jumped without the flap. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.65pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Or, if prototype wingflaps =
worked to=20
      break the animal's fall, you cannot say 'Below a certain size the =
flaps=20
      would have been of no use at all'. Once again, it doesn't matter=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">how =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">small and un-winglike the first =
wingflaps=20
      were. There must be some height, call it </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">h, </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">such that an animal would just =
break its=20
      neck if it fell from that height, but would just survive if it =
fell from a=20
      slightly lower height. In this critical zone, any improvement in =
the body=20
      surface's ability to catch the air and break the fall, however =
slight that=20
      improvement, can make the difference between life and death. =
Natural=20
      selection will then favour slight, prototype wingflaps. When these =
small=20
      wingflaps have become the norm, the critical height A will become =
slightly=20
      greater. Now a </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.65pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.7pt 0pt 1.2pt"><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">90 </SPAN></B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 15.75pt 0pt 1.45pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">slight further increase in the =
wingflaps=20
      will make the difference between life and death. And so on, until =
we have=20
      proper wings. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.3pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">There are animals alive today =
that=20
      beautifully illustrate every stage in the continuum. There are =
frogs that=20
      glide with big webs between their toes, tree-snakes with flattened =
bodies=20
      that catch the air, lizards with flaps along their bodies; and =
several=20
      different kinds of mammals that glide with membranes stretched =
between=20
      their limbs, showing us the kind of way bats must have got their =
start.=20
      Contrary to the creationist literature, not only are animals with =
'half a=20
      wing' common, so are animals with a quarter of a wing, three =
quarters of a=20
      wing, and so on. The idea of a flying continuum becomes even more=20
      persuasive when we remember that very small animals tend to float =
gently=20
      in air, whatever their shape. The reason this is persuasive is =
that there=20
      is an infinitesimally graded continuum from small to large. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.75pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The idea of tiny changes =
cumulated over=20
      many steps is an immensely powerful idea, capable of explaining an =

      enormous range of things that would be otherwise inexplicable. How =
did=20
      snake venom get </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold">its=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">start? Many =
animals=20
      bite, and any animal's spit contains proteins which, if they get =
into a=20
      wound, may cause an allergic reaction. Even so-called non-venomous =
snakes=20
      can give bites that cause a painful reaction in some people. There =
is a=20
      continuous, graded series from ordinary spit to deadly venom. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.7pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">How did ears get their start? =
Any piece=20
      of skin can detect vibrations if they come in contact with =
vibrating=20
      objects. This is a natural outgrowth of the sense of touch. =
Natural=20
      selection could easily have enhanced this faculty by gradual =
degrees until=20
      it was sensitive enough to pick up very </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">slight </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">contact vibrations. At this =
point it=20
      would automatically have been sensitive enough to pick up =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">airborne </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">vibrations of sufficient =
loudness and/or=20
      sufficient nearness of origin. Natural selection would then favour =
the=20
      evolution of special organs =97 ears - for picking up airborne =
vibrations=20
      originating from steadily increasing distances. It is easy to see =
that=20
      there would have been a continuous trajectory of step-by-step =
improvement,=20
      all the way. How did echolocation get its start? Any animal that =
can hear=20
      at all may hear echoes. Blind humans frequently leam to make use =
of these=20
      echoes. A rudimentary version of such a skill in ancestral mammals =
would=20
      have provided ample raw material for natural selection to build =
upon,=20
      leading up by gradual degrees to the high perfection of bats. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.55pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
1.2pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Five per cent vision is better =
than no=20
      vision at all. Five per cent hearing is better than no hearing at =
all.=20
      Five per cent flight efficiency is better than no flight at all. =
It is=20
      thoroughly believable that every organ or apparatus that we =
actually see=20
      is the product of a smooth trajectory </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.55pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
1.2pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D9 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D27 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D9>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D9=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image045.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D27></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D381 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle5 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 3.1pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Making tracks through animal =
space=20
      </SPAN></I><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">91 =
</SPAN></B><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.4pt 0pt 2.9pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">through animal space, a =
trajectory in=20
      which every intermediate stage assisted survival and reproduction. =

      Wherever we have an X in a real live animal, where X is some organ =
too=20
      complex to have arisen by chance in a single step, then according =
to the=20
      theory of evolution by natural selection it must be the case that =
a=20
      fraction of an X is better than no X at all; and two fractions of =
an X=20
      must be better than one; and a whole X must be better than =
nine-tenths of=20
      an X. I have no trouble at all in accepting that these statements =
are true=20
      of eyes, ears including bat ears, wings, camouflaged and mimicking =

      insects, snake jaws, stings, cuckoo habits and all the other =
examples=20
      trotted out in antievolution propaganda. No doubt there are plenty =
of=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">conceivable=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Xs for which =
these=20
      statements would </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">not=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">be true, =
plenty of=20
      conceivable evolutionary pathways for which the intermediates =
would not be=20
      improvements on their predecessors. But those Xs are not found in =
the real=20
      world. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 102pt 0pt 11.3pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Darwin wrote (in =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Origin of Species]: =
</SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.65pt 0pt 11.05pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 9.8pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">If it could be demonstrated =
that any=20
      complex organ existed which could </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">not </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">possibly have been formed by =
numerous,=20
      successive, slight modifications, my theory would absolutely break =
down.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.25pt 0pt 0.7pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">One hundred and twenty five =
years on, we=20
      know a lot more about animals and plants than Darwin did, and =
still not a=20
      single case is known to me of a complex organ that could not have =
been=20
      formed by numerous successive slight modifications. I do not =
believe that=20
      such a case will ever be found. If it is - it'll have to be a=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">really =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">complex organ, and, as we'll =
see in later=20
      chapters, you have to be sophisticated about what you mean by =
'slight' - I=20
      shall cease to believe in Darwinism. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.55pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.55pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Sometimes the history of =
gradual,=20
      intermediate stages is clearly written into the shape of modem =
animals,=20
      even taking the form of outright imperfections in the final =
design.=20
      Stephen Gould, in his <BR>excellent essay on </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Panda's Thumb, =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">has made the point that =
evolution can be=20
      more strongly supported by evidence of telling imperfections than =
by=20
      evidence of perfection. I shall give just two examples. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.8pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Fish living on the sea bottom =
benefit by=20
      being flat and hugging the contours. There are two very different =
kinds of=20
      flat fish living on the sea bottom, and they have evolved their =
flatness=20
      in quite different ways. The skates and rays, relatives of sharks, =
have=20
      become flat in what might be called the obvious way. Their bodies =
have=20
      grown out sideways to form great 'wings'. They are like sharks =
that have=20
      passed under a steam roller, but they remain symmetrical and 'the =
right=20
      way up'. Plaice, sole, halibut and their relatives have become =
flat in a=20
      different way. They are bony fish (with swimbladders) related to=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.8pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D380 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN-RIGHT: 1.4pt"><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica-Bold">92 </SPAN></B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.05pt 0pt 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.8pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">herrings, trout, etc., and are =
nothing to=20
      do with sharks. Unlike sharks, bony fish as a rule have a marked =
tendency=20
      to be flattened in a vertical direction. A herring, for instance, =
is much=20
      'taller' than it is wide. It uses its whole, vertically flattened =
body as=20
      a swimming surface, which undulates through the water as it swims. =
It was=20
      natural, therefore, that when the ancestors of plaice and sole =
took to the=20
      sea bottom, they should have lain on one </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">side </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">rather than on the belly like =
the=20
      ancestors of skates and rays. But this raised the problem that one =
eye was=20
      always looking down into the sand and was effectively useless. In=20
      evolution this problem was solved by the lower eye 'moving' round =
to the=20
      upper side. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.05pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">We see this process of moving =
round=20
      re-enacted in the development of every young bony flatfish. A =
young=20
      flatfish starts life swimming near the surface, and it is =
symmetrical and=20
      vertically flattened just like a herring. But then the skull =
starts to=20
      grow in a strange, asymmetrical, twisted fashion, so that one eye, =
for=20
      instance the left, moves over the top of the head to finish up on =
the=20
      other side. The young fish settles </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">on </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the bottom, with both its eyes =
looking=20
      upwards, a strange Picasso-like vision. Incidentally, some species =
of=20
      flatfish settle on the right side, others on the left, and others =
on=20
      either side. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.05pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The whole skull of a bony =
flatfish=20
      retains the twisted and distorted evidence of its origins. Its =
very=20
      imperfection is powerful testimony of its ancient history, a =
history of=20
      step-by-step change rather than of deliberate design. No sensible =
designer=20
      would have conceived such a monstrosity if given a free hand to =
create a=20
      flatfish on a clean drawing board. I suspect that most sensible =
designers=20
      would think in terms of something more like a skate. But evolution =
never=20
      starts from a clean drawing board. It has to start from what is =
already=20
      there. In the case of the ancestors of skates this was =
free-swimming=20
      sharks. Sharks in general aren't flattened from side to side as=20
      free-swimming bony fish like herrings are. If anything, sharks are =
already=20
      slightly flattened from back to belly. This meant that when some =
ancient=20
      sharks first took to the sea bottom, there was an easy smooth =
progression=20
      to the skate shape, with each intermediate being a slight =
improvement,=20
      given bottom conditions, over its slightly less flattened =
predecessor.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.1pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">On the other hand, when the =
free-swimming=20
      ancestor of plaice </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold">and=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">halibut, =
being, like a=20
      herring, vertically flattened from side to side, took to the =
bottom, it=20
      was better off lying on its side than balancing precariously on =
its knife=20
      edge of a belly! Even though its evolutionary course was =
eventually=20
      destined to lead it into the complicated and probably costly =
distortions=20
      involved in having two eyes on one side, even though the skate way =
of=20
      being a flat fish might </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">ultimately </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">have </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.1pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D383 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle27 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 3.85pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Making tracks through animal =
space=20
      </SPAN></I><B><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: 'Helvetica-Bold =
Oblique'">93=20
      </SPAN></I></B><B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.15pt 0pt 3.35pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">been the best design for bony =
fish too,=20
      the would-be intermediates that set out along this evolutionary =
pathway=20
      apparently did less well in the short term than their rivals lying =
on=20
      their side. The rivals lying on their side were so much better, in =
the=20
      short term, at hugging the bottom. In genetic hyperspace, there is =
a=20
      smooth trajectory connecting free-swimming ancestral bony fish to =
flatfish=20
      lying on their side with twisted skulls. There is not a smooth =
trajectory=20
      connecting these bony fish ancestors to flatfish lying on their =
belly.=20
      This speculation cannot </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold">be=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the whole =
truth, because=20
      there are some bony fish that have evolved flatness in a =
symmetrical,=20
      skate-like way. Perhaps their free-swimming ancestors were already =

      slightly flattened for some other reason. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.65pt 0pt 1.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">My second example of an =
evolutionary=20
      progression that didn't happen because of disadvantageous =
intermediates,=20
      even though it might ultimately have turned out better if it had, =
concerns=20
      the retina of </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold">our=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">eyes (and all =
other=20
      vertebrates). Like any nerve, the optic nerve is a trunk cable, a =
bundle=20
      of separate 'insulated' wires, in this case about three million of =
them.=20
      Each of the three million wires leads from one cell in the retina =
to the=20
      brain. You can think of them as the wires leading from a bank of =
three=20
      million photocells (actually three million relay stations =
gathering=20
      information from an even larger number of photocells) to the =
computer that=20
      is to process the information in the brain. They are gathered =
together=20
      from all over the retina into a single bundle, which is the optic =
nerve=20
      for that eye. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.5pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Any engineer would naturally =
assume that=20
      the photocells would point towards the light, with their wires =
leading=20
      backwards towards the brain. He would laugh at any suggestion that =
the=20
      photocells might point away from the light, with their wires =
departing on=20
      the side </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">nearest=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the light. Yet =
this is=20
      exactly what happens in all vertebrate retinas. Each photocell is, =
in=20
      effect, wired in backwards, with its wire sticking out on the side =
nearest=20
      the light. The wire has to travel over the surface of the retina, =
to a=20
      point where it dives through a hole in the retina (the so-called =
'blind=20
      spot') to join the optic nerve. This means that the light, instead =
of=20
      being granted an unrestricted passage to the photocells, has to =
pass=20
      through a forest of connecting wires, presumably suffering at =
least some=20
      attenuation and distortion (actually probably not much but, still, =
it is=20
      the </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">principle=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">of the thing =
that would=20
      offend any tidy-minded engineer!). </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.15pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">I don't know the exact =
explanation for=20
      this strange state of affairs. The relevant period of evolution is =
so long=20
      ago. But I am ready to bet that it had something to do with the=20
      trajectory, the pathway through the real-life equivalent of =
Biomorph Land,=20
      that would have to be traversed in order to turn the retina the =
right way=20
      round, starting from </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.15pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle10 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.8pt 0pt 0.95pt"><B><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica-Bold">94 </SPAN></B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica-Oblique">The Blind Watchmaker=20
      </SPAN></I><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: =
9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.95pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">whatever ancestral organ =
preceded the=20
      eye. There probably is such a trajectory, but that hypothetical=20
      trajectory, when realized in actual bodies of intermediate =
animals, proved=20
      disadvantageous - temporarily disadvantageous only, but that is =
enough.=20
      Intermediates could see even less well than their imperfect =
ancestors, and=20
      it is no consolation that they are building better eyesight for =
their=20
      remote descendants! What matters is survival in the here and now.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.2pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">'Dollo's Law' states that =
evolution is=20
      irreversible. This is often confused with a lot of idealistic =
nonsense=20
      about the inevitability of progress, often coupled with ignorant =
nonsense=20
      about evolution 'violating the Second Law of Thermodynamics' =
(those that=20
      belong to the half of the educated population that, according to =
the=20
      novelist C. P. Snow, know what the Second Law is, will realize =
that it is=20
      no more violated by evolution than it is violated by the growth of =
a=20
      baby). There is no reason why general trends in evolution =
shouldn't be=20
      reversed. If there is a trend towards large antlers for a while in =

      evolution, there can easily be a subsequent trend towards smaller =
antlers=20
      again. Dollo's Law is really just a statement about the =
statistical=20
      improbability of following exactly the same evolutionary =
trajectory twice=20
      (or, indeed, any </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">particular </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">trajectory), in either =
direction. A=20
      single mutational step can easily be reversed. But for larger =
numbers of=20
      mutational steps, even in the case of the biomorphs with their =
nine little=20
      genes, the mathematical space of all possible trajectories is so =
vast that=20
      the chance of two trajectories ever arriving at the same point =
becomes=20
      vanishingly small. This is even more true of real animals with =
their=20
      vastly larger numbers of genes. There is nothing mysterious or =
mystical=20
      about Dollo's Law, nor is it something that we go out and 'test' =
in=20
      nature. It follows simply from the elementary laws of probability. =

      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.1pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">For just the same reason, it is =

      vanishingly improbable that exactly the same evolutionary pathway =
should=20
      ever be travelled twice. And </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">it </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">would seem similarly =
improbable, for the=20
      same statistical reasons, that two lines of evolution should =
converge on=20
      exactly the same endpoint from different starting points. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.25pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">It is all the more striking a =
testimony=20
      to the power of natural selection, therefore, that numerous =
examples can=20
      be found in real nature, in which independent lines of evolution =
appear to=20
      have converged, from very different starting points, on what looks =
very=20
      like the same endpoint. When we look in detail we find =97 it =
would be=20
      worrying </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">if=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">we didn't =97 =
that the=20
      convergence is not total. The different lines of evolution betray =
their=20
      independent origins in numerous points of detail. For instance, =
octopus=20
      eyes are very like ours, but the wires leading </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.25pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D390 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle11 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 8.9pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica-Oblique">Making tracks through=20
      </SPAN></I><B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: 'Helvetica-Bold Oblique'">animal=20
      </SPAN></I></B><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Helvetica-Oblique">space=20
      </SPAN></I><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica-Bold">95=20
      </SPAN></B><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: =
9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.15pt 0pt 7.9pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.3pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">from their photocells don't =
point=20
      forwards towards the light, as ours do. Octopus eyes are, in this =
respect,=20
      more 'sensibly' designed. They have arrived at a'similar endpoint, =
from a=20
      very different starting point. And the fact is betrayed in details =
such as=20
      this. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.15pt 0pt 6.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.5pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Such superficially convergent=20
      resemblances are often extremely striking, and I shall devote the =
rest of=20
      the chapter to some of them. They provide most impressive =
demonstrations=20
      of the power of natural selection to put together good designs. =
Yet the=20
      fact that the superficially similar designs also differ, testifies =
to=20
      their independent evolutionary origins and histories. The basic =
rationale=20
      is that, if a design is good enough to evolve once, the same =
design=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">principle is=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">good enough to =
evolve=20
      twice, from different starting points, in different parts of the =
animal=20
      kingdom. This is nowhere better illustrated than in the case we =
used for=20
      our basic illustration of good design itself - echolocation. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.9pt 0pt 4.1pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.55pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Most of what we know about =
echolocation=20
      comes from bats (and human instruments), but it also occurs in a =
number of=20
      other unrelated groups of animals. At least two separate groups of =
birds=20
      do it, and it has been carried to a very high level of =
sophistication by=20
      dolphins and whales. Moreover, it was almost certainly =
'discovered'=20
      independently by at least two different groups of bats. The birds =
that do=20
      it are the oilbirds of South America, and the cave swiftlets of =
the Far=20
      East, the ones whose nests are used for birds' nest soup. Both =
types of=20
      bird nest deep in caves where little or no light penetrates, and =
both=20
      navigate through the blackness using echoes from their own vocal =
clicks.=20
      In both cases the sounds are audible to humans, not ultrasonic =
like the=20
      more specialized bat clicks. Indeed, neither bird species seems to =
have=20
      developed echolocation to such a pitch of sophistication as bats =
have.=20
      Their clicks are not FM, nor do they appear suitable for =
Doppler-shift=20
      speed metering. Probably, like the fruit bat </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Rousettus, </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">they just time the silent =
interval=20
      between each click and its echo. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 6.4pt 0pt 1.45pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">In this case we can be =
absolutely certain=20
      that the two bird species have invented echolocation independently =
of=20
      bats, and independently of each other. The line of reasoning is of =
a kind=20
      that evolutionists frequently use. We look at all the thousands of =
species=20
      of birds, and observe that the vast majority of them don't use=20
      echolocation. Just two isolated little genera of birds do it, and =
those=20
      two have nothing else in common with each other except that both =
live in=20
      caves. Although we believe that all birds and bats must have a =
common=20
      ancestor if we trace their lineages back far enough, that common =
ancestor=20
      was also the common ancestor of all mammals (including ourselves) =
and all=20
      birds. The vast majority of mammals and the vast majority of birds =
don't=20
      use </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 6.4pt 0pt 1.45pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.35pt 0pt 1.45pt"><B><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">96 </SPAN></B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.45pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">echolocation, and it is highly =
probable=20
      that their common ancestor didn't either (nor did it fly - that is =
another=20
      technology that has been independently evolved several times). It =
follows=20
      that the echolocation technology has been independently developed =
in bats=20
      and birds, just as it was independently developed by British, =
American and=20
      German scientists. The same kind of reasoning, on a smaller scale, =
leads=20
      to </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">the =
</SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">conclusion that the common =
ancestor of=20
      the oil-bird and the cave swiftlet also did not use echolocation, =
and that=20
      these two genera have developed the same technology independently =
of each=20
      other. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.6pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Within the mammals too, bats =
are not the=20
      only group to have independently developed the echolocation =
technology.=20
      Several different kinds of mammals, for instance shrews, rats and =
seals,=20
      seem to use echoes to a small extent, as blind humans do, but the =
only=20
      animals to rival bats in sophistication are whales. Whales are =
divided=20
      into two main groups, toothed whales and baleen whales. Both, of =
course,=20
      are mammals descended from land-dwelling ancestors, and they may =
well have=20
      'invented' the whale way of life independently of one another, =
starting=20
      from different land-dwelling ancestors. The toothed whales include =
sperm=20
      whales, killer whales and the various species of dolphins, all of =
which=20
      hunt relatively large prey such as fish and squids, which they =
catch in=20
      their jaws. Several toothed whales, of which only dolphins have =
been=20
      thoroughly studied, have evolved sophisticated echo-sounding =
equipment in=20
      their heads. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.05pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Dolphins emit rapid trains of=20
      high-pitched clicks, some audible to us, some ultrasonic. It is =
probable=20
      that the 'melon', the bulging dome on the front of a dolphin's =
head,=20
      looking - pleasing coincidence - like the weirdly bulging radar =
dome of a=20
      Nimrod 'advance-warning' surveillance aircraft, has something to =
do with=20
      beaming the sonar signals forwards, but its exact workings are not =

      understood. As in the case of bats, there is a relatively slow =
'cruising=20
      rate' of clicking, rising to a high-speed (400 clicks per second) =
buzz=20
      when the animal is closing in on prey. Even the 'slow' cruising =
rate is=20
      pretty fast. The river dolphins that live in muddy water are =
probably the=20
      most skilled echolocators, but some open-sea dolphins have been =
shown in=20
      tests to be pretty good too. An Atlantic bottlenose dolphin can=20
      discriminate circles, squares and triangles (all of the same =
standardized=20
      area), using only its sonar. It can tell which of two targets is =
the=20
      nearer, when the difference is only 1 '/4 inches at an overall =
distance of=20
      about 7 yards. It can detect a steel sphere half the size of a =
golf ball,=20
      at a range of 70 yards. This performance is not quite as good as =
human=20
      vision in a good light, but probably better than human vision in=20
      moonlight. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.3pt 0pt 10.3pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The intriguing suggestion has =
been made=20
      that dolphins, if they </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.3pt 0pt 10.3pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D8 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D10 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D8>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D8=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image046.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D10></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D624 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D389 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D624>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 9.1pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Making tracks through animal =
space 97=20
      </SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 8.4pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">chose to use it, have a =
potentially=20
      effortless means of communicating 'mental pictures' to one =
another. All=20
      that they would have to do is use their highly versatile voices to =
mimic=20
      the pattern of sound that would be produced by echoes from a =
particular=20
      object. In this way they could convey to one another mental =
pictures of=20
      such objects. There is no evidence for this delightful suggestion. =

      Theoretically, bats could do the same thing, but dolphins seem =
more likely=20
      candidates because they are in general more social. They are also =
probably=20
      'cleverer', but this isn't necessarily a relevant consideration. =
The=20
      instruments that would be needed for communicating echo pictures =
are no=20
      more sophisticated than the instruments that both bats and =
dolphins=20
      already have for echolocating in the first place. And there would =
seem to=20
      be an easy, gradual continuum between using the voice to make =
echoes and=20
      using it to mimic echoes. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.8pt 0pt 4.8pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.55pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">At least two groups of bats =
then, two=20
      groups of birds, toothed whales, and probably several other kinds =
of=20
      mammals to a smaller extent, have all independently converged on =
the=20
      technology of sonar, at some time during the last hundred million =
years.=20
      We have no way of knowing whether any other animals now extinct -=20
      pterodactyls perhaps? - also evolved the technology independently. =

      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.7pt 0pt 0.05in; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">No insects and no fish have so =
far been=20
      found to use sonar, but two quite different groups of fish, one in =
South=20
      America and one in Africa, have developed a somewhat similar =
navigation=20
      system, which appears to be just about as sophisticated and which =
can be=20
      seen as a related, but different, solution to the same problem. =
These are=20
      so-called weakly electric fish. The word 'weakly' is to =
differentiate them=20
      from strongly electric fish, which use electric fields, not to =
navigate,=20
      but to stun their prey. The stunning technique, incidentally, has =
also=20
      been independently invented by several unrelated groups of fish, =
for=20
      example electric 'eels' (which are not true eels but whose shape =
is=20
      convergent on true eels) and electric rays. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 7.1pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.45pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The South American and the =
African weakly=20
      electric fish are quite unrelated to each other, but both live in =
the same=20
      kinds of waters in their respective continents, waters that are =
too muddy=20
      for vision to be effective. The physical principle that they =
exploit -=20
      electric fields in water - is even more alien to our consciousness =
than=20
      that of bats and dolphins. We at least have a subjective idea of =
what an=20
      echo is, but we have almost no subjective idea of what it might be =
like to=20
      perceive an electric field. We didn't even know of the existence =
of=20
      electricity until a couple of centuries ago. We cannot as =
subjective human=20
      beings empathize with electric fish, but we can, as physicists, =
understand=20
      them. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 7.1pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.45pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.35pt 0pt 0.5pt"><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">98 </SPAN></B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">It is easy to see on the dinner =
plate=20
      that the muscles down each side of any fish are arranged as a row =
of=20
      segments, a </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">battery=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">of muscle =
units. In most=20
      fish they contract successively to throw the body into sinuous =
waves,=20
      which propel it forwards. In electric fish, both strongly and =
weakly=20
      electric ones, they have become a battery in the electric sense. =
Each=20
      segment ('cell') of the battery generates a voltage. These =
voltages are=20
      connected up in series along the length of the fish so that, in a =
strongly=20
      electric fish such as an electric eel, the whole battery generates =
as much=20
      as 1 amp at 650 volts. An electric eel is powerful enough to knock =
a man=20
      out. Weakly electric fish don't need high voltages or currents for =
their=20
      purposes, which are purely <BR>informationgathering ones. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The principle of =
electrolocation, as it=20
      has been called, is fairly well understood at the level of physics =
though=20
      not, of course, at the level of what it feels like to be an =
electric fish.=20
      The following account applies equally to African and South =
American weakly=20
      electric fish: the convergence is that thorough. Current flows =
from the=20
      front half of the fish, out into the water in lines that curve =
back and=20
      return to the tail end of the fish. There are not really discrete =
'lines'=20
      but a continuous 'field', an invisible cocoon of electricity =
surrounding=20
      the fish's body. However, for human visualization it is easiest to =
think=20
      in terms of a family of curved lines leaving the fish through a =
series of=20
      portholes spaced along the front half of the body, all curving =
round in=20
      the water and diving into the fish again at the tip of its tail. =
The fish=20
      has what amounts to a tiny voltmeter monitoring the voltage at =
each=20
      'porthole'. If the fish is suspended in open water with no =
obstacles=20
      around, the lines are smooth curves. The tiny voltmeters at each =
porthole=20
      all register the voltage as 'normal' for their porthole. But if =
some=20
      obstacle appears in the vicinity, say a rock or an item of food, =
the lines=20
      of current that happen to hit the obstacle will be changed. This =
will=20
      change the voltage at any porthole whose current line is affected, =
and the=20
      appropriate voltmeter will register the fact. So in theory a =
computer, by=20
      comparing the pattern of voltages registered by the voltmeters at =
all the=20
      portholes, could calculate the pattern of obstacles around the =
fish. This=20
      is apparently what the fish brain does. Once again, this doesn't =
have to=20
      mean that the fish are clever mathematicians. They have an =
apparatus that=20
      solves the necessary equations, just as our brains unconsciously =
solve=20
      equations every time we catch a ball. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.25pt 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">It is very important that the =
fish's own=20
      body is kept absolutely rigid. The computer in the head couldn't =
cope with=20
      the extra distortions that would be introduced if the fish's body =
were=20
      bending and twisting like an ordinary fish. Electric fish have, at =
least=20
      twice independently, hit </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.25pt 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D382 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle27 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 4.3pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Making tracks through animal =
space=20
      </SPAN></I><B><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: 'Helvetica-Bold =
Oblique'">99=20
      </SPAN></I></B><B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.15pt 0pt 3.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt">upon =
this=20
      ingenious method of navigation, but they have had to pay a price: =
they=20
      have had to give up the normal, highly efficient, fish method of =
swimming,=20
      throwing the whole body into serpentine waves. They have solved =
the=20
      problem by keeping the body stiff as a poker, but they have a =
single long=20
      fin all the way along the length of the body. Then instead of the =
whole=20
      body being thrown into waves, just the long fin is. The fish's =
progress=20
      through the water is rather slow, but it does move, and apparently =
the=20
      sacrifice of fast movement is worth it: the gains in navigation =
seem to=20
      outweigh the losses in speed of swimming. Fascinatingly, the South =

      American electric fish have hit upon almost exactly the same =
solution as=20
      the African ones, but not quite. -The difference is revealing. =
Both groups=20
      have developed a single long fin that runs the whole length of the =
body,=20
      but in the African fish it runs along the back whereas in the =
South=20
      American fish it runs along the belly. This kind of difference in =
detail=20
      is very characteristic of convergent evolution, as we have seen. =
It is=20
      characteristic of convergent designs by human engineers too, of =
course.=20
      </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.1pt 0pt 1.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt">Although=20
      the majority of weakly electric fish, in both the African and the =
South=20
      American groups, give their electric discharges in discrete pulses =
and are=20
      called 'pulse' species, a minority of species in both groups do it =
a=20
      different way and are called 'wave' species. I shall not discuss =
the=20
      difference further. What is interesting for this chapter is that =
the=20
      pulse/wavg split has evolved twice, independently, in the =
unrelated New=20
      World and Old World groups. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle21=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.65pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt">One=20
      of the most bizarre examples of convergent evolution that I know =
concerns=20
      the so-called periodical cicadas. Before getting to the =
convergence, I=20
      must fill in some background information. Many insects have a =
rather rigid=20
      separation between a juvenile feeding stage, in which they spend =
most of=20
      their lives, and a relatively brief adult reproducing stage. =
Mayflies, for=20
      instance, spend most of their lives as underwater feeding larvae, =
then=20
      emerge into the air for a single day into which they cram the =
whole of=20
      their adult lives. We can think of the adult as analogous to the =
ephemeral=20
      winged seed of a plant like a sycamore, and the larva as analogous =
to the=20
      main plant, the difference being that sycamores make many seeds =
and shed=20
      them over many successive years, while a mayfly larva gives rise =
to only=20
      one adult right at the end of its own life. Anyway, periodical =
cicadas=20
      have carried the mayfly trend to an extreme. The adults live for a =
few=20
      weeks, but the 'juvenile' stage (technically 'nymphs' rather than =
larvae)=20
      lasts for 13 years (in some varieties) or 17 years (in other =
varieties).=20
      The adults emerge at almost exactly the same moment, having spent =
13 (or=20
      17) years cloistered underground. Cicada plagues, which occur in =
<B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">any </SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle21=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.65pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D11 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D57 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D11>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold"><IMG height=3D11=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image047.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D57></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D629 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D629>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.2pt 0pt 1.7pt"><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">100 </SPAN></B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The </SPAN></I><B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: 'Times-Bold Italic'">Blind =
</SPAN></I></B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Watchmaker </SPAN></I><I><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.1pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.8pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">given area exactly 13 (or 17) =
years=20
      apart, are spectacular eruptions that have led to their =
incorrectly being=20
      called 'locusts' in vernacular American speech. The varieties are =
known,=20
      respectively, as 13-year cicadas and 17-year cicadas. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Now here is the really =
remarkable fact.=20
      It turns out that there is not just one 13-year cicada species and =
one=20
      17-year species. Rather, there are three species, and each one of =
the=20
      three has both a 17-year and a 13-year variety or race. The =
division into=20
      a 13-year race and a 17-year race has been arrived at =
independently, no=20
      fewer than three times. It looks as though the intermediate =
periods of 14,=20
      15 and 16 years have been shunned convergently, no fewer than =
three times.=20
      Why? We don't know. The only suggestion anyone has come up with is =
that=20
      what is special about 13 and 17, as opposed to 14, 15 and 16, is =
that they=20
      are prime numbers. A prime number is a number that is not exactly=20
      divisible by any other number. The idea is that a race of animals =
that=20
      regularly erupts in plagues gains the benefit of alternately =
'swamping'=20
      and starving its enemies, predators or parasites. And if these =
plagues are=20
      carefully timed to occur a prime number of years apart, it makes =
it that=20
      much more difficult for the enemies to synchronize their own life =
cycles.=20
      If the cicadas erupted every 14 years, for instance, they could be =

      exploited by a parasite species with a 7-year life cycle. This is =
a=20
      bizarre idea, but no more bizarre than the phenomenon itself. We =
really=20
      don't know what is special about 13 and 17 years. What matters for =
our=20
      purposes here is that there must be </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">something </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">special about those numbers, =
because=20
      three different species of cicada have independently converged =
upon them.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.7pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Examples of convergence on a =
large scale=20
      occur when two or more continents are isolated from one another =
for a long=20
      time, and a parallel range of 'trades' is adopted by unrelated =
animals on=20
      each of the continents. By 'trades' I mean ways of making a =
living, such=20
      as burrowing for worms, digging for ants, chasing large =
herbivores, eating=20
      leaves up trees. A good example is the convergent evolution of a =
whole=20
      range of mammal trades in the separate continents of South =
America,=20
      Australia, and the Old World. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.7pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">These continents weren't always =
separate.=20
      Because our lives are measured in decades, and even our =
civilizations and=20
      dynasties are measured only in centuries, we are accustomed to =
thinking of=20
      the map of the world, the outlines of the continents, as fixed. =
The theory=20
      that continents drifted about was proposed long ago by the German=20
      geophysicist Alfred Wegener, but most people laughed at him until =
well=20
      after the Second World War. The admitted fact that South America =
and=20
      Africa look a bit like separated pieces of a jigsaw puzzle =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.7pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D630 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D383 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D630>
      <P class=3DStyle24 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 3.35pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Making tracks through animal =
space=20
      </SPAN></I>101 <SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.95pt 0pt 2.65pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">was assumed to be just an =
amusing=20
      coincidence. In one of the most rapid and complete revolutions =
science has=20
      known, the formerly controversial theory of 'continental drift' =
has now=20
      become universally accepted under the name of plate tectonics. The =

      evidence that the continents have drifted, that South America did =
indeed=20
      break away from Africa for instance, is now literally =
overwhelming, but=20
      this is not a book about geology and I shall not spell it out. For =
us the=20
      important point is that the timescale on which continents have =
drifted=20
      about is the same slow timescale on which animal lineages have =
evolved,=20
      and we cannot ignore continental drift if we are to understand the =

      patterns of animal evolution on those continents. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.85pt 0pt 1.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Up until about 100 million =
years ago,=20
      then. South America was joined to Africa in the east and to =
Antarctica in=20
      the south. Antarctica was joined to Australia, and India was =
joined to=20
      Africa via Madagascar. There was in fact one huge southern =
continent,=20
      which we now call Gondwanaland, consisting of what is now South =
America,=20
      Africa, Madagascar, India, Antarctica and Australia all rolled =
into one.=20
      There was also a single large northern continent called Laurasia=20
      consisting of what is now North America, Greenland, Europe and =
Asia (apart=20
      from India). North America was not connected to South America. =
About 100=20
      million years ago there was a big break-up of the land masses, and =
the=20
      continents have been slowly moving towards their present positions =

      ever^since (they will, of course, continue to move in the future). =
Africa=20
      joined up with Asia via Arabia and became part of the huge =
continent that=20
      we now speak of as the Old World. North America drifted away from =
Europe,=20
      Antartica drifted south to its present icy location. India =
detached itself=20
      from Africa and set off across what is now called the Indian =
Ocean,=20
      eventually to crunch into south Asia and raise the Himalayas. =
Australia=20
      drifted away from Antarctica into the open sea </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">to </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">become an island continent =
miles from=20
      anywhere else. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05in 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">It happens that the break-up of =
the great=20
      southern continent </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold">of=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Gondwanaland =
began=20
      during- the age of the dinosaurs. When South America and Australia =
broke=20
      away to begin their long periods of isolation from the rest of the =
world,=20
      they each carried their own cargo of dinosaurs, and also of the=20
      less-prominent animals that were to become the ancestors of modern =

      mammals. When, rather later, for reasons that are not understood =
and are=20
      the subject of much profitable speculation, the dinosaurs (with =
the=20
      exception of the group of dinosaurs that we now call birds) went =
extinct,=20
      they went extinct all over the world. This left a vacuum in the =
'trades'=20
      open to land-dwelling animals. The vacuum was filled, over a =
period of=20
      millions of years </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold">of=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">evolution, =
mostly by=20
      mammals. The interesting point for us here is </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05in 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D11 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D39 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D11>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D11 =

      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image048.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D39></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D11 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D50 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D11>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D11 =

      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image049.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D50></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D629 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D385 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D629>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.5pt 0pt 1.2pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">102 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.35pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 11.05pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">that there were three =
independent=20
      vacuums, and they were independently filled by mammals in =
Australia, South=20
      America and the Old World. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.3pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The primitive mammals that =
happened to be=20
      around in the three areas when the dinosaurs more or less =
simultaneously=20
      vacated the great life trades, were all rather small and =
insignificant,=20
      probably nocturnal, previously overshadowed and overpowered by the =
di-=BB=20
      nosaurs. They could have evolved in radically different directions =
in the=20
      three areas. To some extent this is what happened. There is =
nothing in the=20
      Old World that resembles the giant ground sloth of South America, =
alas now=20
      extinct. The great range of South American mammals included an =
extinct=20
      giant guinea-pig, the size of a modern rhinoceros but a rodent (I =
have to=20
      say 'modern' rhinoceros because the Old World fauna included a =
giant=20
      rhinoceros the size of a two-storey house). But although the =
separate=20
      continents each produced their unique mammals, the general pattern =
of=20
      evolution in all three areas was the same. In all three areas the =
mammals=20
      that happened to be around at the start fanned out in evolution, =
and=20
      produced a specialist for each trade which, in many cases, came to =
bear a=20
      remarkable resemblance to the corresponding specialist in the =
other two=20
      areas. Each trade, the burrowing trade, the large hunter trade, =
the=20
      plains-grazing trade, and so on, was the subject of independent =
convergent=20
      evolution in two or three separate continents. In addition to =
these three=20
      major sites of independent evolution, smaller islands such as =
Madagascar=20
      have interesting parallel stories of their own, which I shall not =
go into.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.55pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.85pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Setting aside the strange =
egg-laying=20
      mammals of Australia - the duck-billed platypus and the spiny =
anteaters -=20
      modern mammals all belong to one of two great groups. These two =
are the=20
      marsupials (whose young are born very small and are then kept in a =
pouch)=20
      and the placentals (all the rest of us). The marsupials came to =
dominate=20
      the Australian story and the placentals the Old World, while the =
two=20
      groups played important roles alongside each other in South =
America. The=20
      South American story is complicated by the fact that it was =
subject to=20
      sporadic waves of invasion by mammals from North America. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.55pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Having set the scene, we can =
now look at=20
      some of the trades and convergences themselves. An important trade =
is=20
      concerned with the exploitation of the great grasslands variously =
known as=20
      prairie, pampas, savannah, etc. Practitioners of this trade =
include horses=20
      (of which the main African species are called zebras and the =
desert models=20
      are called donkeys), and cattle, such as the North American bison, =
now=20
      hunted to near-extinction. Herbivores typically have very long =
guts=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.55pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D9 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D19 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D9>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D9=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image050.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D19></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D382 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05pt 0pt 0.05in"><I><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Making tracks through animal =
space=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">103 =
<BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 3.35pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">containing various kinds of =
fermenting=20
      bacteria, since grass is a poorquality food and needs a lot of =
digesting.=20
      Rather than break their eating up into discrete meals, they =
typically eat=20
      more or less continuously. Huge volumes of plant material flow =
through=20
      them like a river, all the day long. The animals are often very =
large, and=20
      they frequently go about in great herds. Each one of these big =
herbivores=20
      is a mountain of valuable food to any predator that can exploit =
it. As a=20
      consequence of this there is, as we shall see, a whole trade =
devoted to=20
      the difficult task of catching and killing them. These are the =
predators.=20
      Actually, when I say 'a' trade, I really mean a whole lot of =
'sub-trades':=20
      lions, leopards, cheetahs, wild dogs and hyenas all hunt in their =
own=20
      specialized ways. The same kind of subdivision is found in the =
herbivores,=20
      and in all the other 'trades'. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.55pt 0pt 2.15pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The herbivores have keen senses =
with=20
      which they are continuously alert for predators, and they are =
usually=20
      capable of running very fast to escape them. To this end they =
often have=20
      long, spindly legs, and they typically run on the tips of their =
toes,=20
      which have become specially elongated and strengthened in =
evolution. The=20
      nails at the ends of these specialized toes have become large and =
hard,=20
      and we call them hooves. Cattle have two enlarged toes at the =
extremities=20
      of each leg: the familiar 'cloven' hooves. Horses do much the same =
thing=20
      except that, probably for reasons of historical accident, they run =
on only=20
      one toe instead of two. It is derived from what was originally the =
middle=20
      one of the five toes. The other toes have almost completely =
disappeared=20
      over evolutionary time, although they occasionally reappear in =
freakish=20
      'throwbacks'. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.05pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Now South America, as we have =
seen, was=20
      isolated during the period in which horses and cattle were =
evolving in=20
      other parts of the world. But South America has its own great =
grasslands,=20
      and it evolved its own separate groups of large herbivores to =
exploit the=20
      resource. There were massive rhino-like Leviathans that had no =
connection=20
      with true rhinos. The skulls of some of the early South American=20
      herbivores suggest that they 'invented' the trunk independently of =
the=20
      true elephants. Some resembled camels, some looked like nothing on =
earth=20
      (today), or like weird chimeras of modern animals. The group =
called the=20
      litopterns are almost unbelievably similar to horses in their =
legs, yet=20
      they were utterly unrelated to horses. The superficial resemblance =
fooled=20
      a nineteenth-century Argentinian expert who thought, with =
pardonable=20
      national pride, that they were the ancestors of all horses in the =
rest of=20
      the world. In fact their resemblance to horses was =
<BR>superficial, and=20
      convergent. Grassland life is much the same the world over, and =
horses and=20
      litopterns independently evolved the same qualities to </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.05pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D629 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D377 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D629>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.5pt 0pt 1.2pt"><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">104 </SPAN></B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.35pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">cope with the problems of =
grassland life.=20
      In particular, the litoptems, like the horses, lost all their toes =
except=20
      the middle one on each leg, which became enlarged as the bottom =
joint of=20
      the leg and developed a hoof. The leg of a litoptem is all but=20
      indistinguishable from the leg of a horse, yet the two animals are =
only=20
      distantly related. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">In Australia the large grazers =
and=20
      browsers are very different - kangaroos. Kangaroos have the same =
need to=20
      move rapidly, but they have done it in a different way. Instead of =

      developing four-legged galloping to the high pitch of perfection =
that=20
      horses (and presumably litoptems) did, kangaroos have perfected a=20
      different gait: two-legged hopping with a large balancing tail. =
There is=20
      little point in arguing over which of these two gaits is 'better'. =
They=20
      are each highly effective if the body evolves in such a way as to =
exploit=20
      them to the full. Horses and litoptems happened to exploit =
four-legged=20
      galloping, and so ended up with almost identical legs. Kangaroos =
happened=20
      to exploit two-legged hopping, and so ended up with their own =
uniquely (at=20
      least since the dinosaurs) massive hind legs and tail. Kangaroos =
and=20
      horses arrived at different endpoints in 'animal space', probably =
because=20
      of some accidental difference in their starting points. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Turning now to the meat-eaters =
that the=20
      great grazers were running away from, we find some more =
fascinating=20
      convergences. In the Old World we are familiar with such large =
hunters as=20
      wolves, dogs, hyenas, and the big cats =97 lions, tigers, leopards =
and=20
      cheetahs. A big cat that has only recently gone extinct is the =
sabre-tooth=20
      ('tiger'), named after its colossal canine teeth which jutted down =
from=20
      the upper jaw in the front of what must have been a terrifying =
gape. Until=20
      recent times there were no true cats or dogs in Australia or the =
New World=20
      (pumas and jaguars are recently evolved from Old World cats). But =
in both=20
      those continents there were marsupial equivalents. In Australia =
the=20
      thylacine, or marsupial 'wolf (often called the Tasmanian wolf =
because it=20
      survived in Tasmania for a little longer than in mainland =
Australia), was=20
      tragically driven extinct within living memory, slaughtered in =
enormous=20
      numbers as a 'pest' and for 'sport' by humans (there is a slight =
hope that=20
      it may still survive in remote parts of Tasmania, areas which =
themselves=20
      are now threatened with destruction in the interests of providing=20
      'employment' for humans). It is not to be confused with the dingo, =
by the=20
      way, which is a true dog, introduced to Australia more recently by =

      (aboriginal) man. A cine film made in the 1930s of the last known=20
      thylacine, restlessly pacing its lonely zoo cage, shows an =
uncannily=20
      dog-like animal, its marsupial nature betrayed only by its =
slightly=20
      undog-like way of holding its pelvis and back legs, presumably =
something=20
      to do with accommodating its </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D629 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D384 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D629>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.3pt 0pt 5.05pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Making tracks through animal =
space=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">105 =
<BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 4.3pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">pouch. To any dog-lover, the=20
      contemplation of this alternative approach to the dog design, this =

      evolutionary traveller along a parallel road separated by 100 =
million=20
      years, this part-familiar yet part utterly alien other-worldly =
dog, is a=20
      moving experience. Maybe they were pests to humans, but humans =
were much=20
      bigger pests to them; now there are no thylacines left and a =
considerable=20
      surplus of humans. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.95pt 0pt 0.05in; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">In South America, too, there =
were no true=20
      dogs or cats during the long period of isolation that we are =
discussing=20
      but, as in Australia, there were marsupial equivalents. Probably =
the most=20
      spectactular was </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Thylacosmilus, =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">which looked exactly like the =
recently=20
      extinct sabre-tooth 'tiger' of the Old World, only more so if you =
see what=20
      I mean. Its daggered gape was even wider, and I imagine that it =
was even=20
      more terrifying. Its name records its superficial affinity with =
the=20
      sabre-tooth </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">[Smilodon}=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">and the =
Tasmanian wolf=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">(Thylacinus},=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">but in terms =
of ancestry=20
      it is very remote from both. It is slightly closer to the =
thylacine since=20
      both are marsupials, but the two have evolved their big carnivore =
design=20
      independently on different continents; independently of each other =
and of=20
      the placental carnivores, the true cats and dogs of the Old World. =

      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.8pt 0pt 12pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Australia, South America and =
the Old=20
      World offer numerous further examples of multiple convergent =
evolution.=20
      Australia has a marsupial 'mole', superficially almost =
indistinguishable=20
      from the familiar moles of other continents, but pouched, making =
its=20
      living in the same way as other moles and with the same enormously =

      <BR>strengthened forepaws for digging. There is a pouched mouse in =

      Australia, though in this case the resemblance is not so close and =
it does=20
      not make its living in quite the same way. Anteating (where 'ants' =
are=20
      deemed for convenience to include termites - another convergence =
as we=20
      shall see) is a 'trade' that is filled by a variety of convergent =
mammals.=20
      They may be subdivided into anteaters that burrow, anteaters that =
climb=20
      trees and anteaters that wander over the ground. In Australia, as =
we might=20
      expect, there is a marsupial anteater. Called </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Myrmecobius, </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">it has a long thin snout for =
poking into=20
      ants' nests, and a long sticky tongue with which it mops up its =
prey. It=20
      is a grounddwelling anteater. Australia also has a burrowing =
anteater, the=20
      spiny anteater. This is not a marsupial, but a member of the group =
of=20
      egglaying mammals, the monotremes, so remote from us that =
marsupials are=20
      our close cousins by comparison. The spiny anteater, too, has a =
long=20
      pointed snout, but its spines give it a superficial resemblance to =
a=20
      hedgehog rather than to another typical anteater. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.8pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">South America could easily have =
had a=20
      marsupial anteater, alongside its marsupial sabre-tooth 'tiger', =
but as it=20
      happens the anteater trade was early filled by placental mammals =
instead.=20
      The </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.8pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D380 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.2pt 0pt 2.15pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">106 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">largest of today's anteaters is =

      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Myrmecophaga=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">(which just =
means=20
      anteater in Greek), the large ground-wandering anteater of South =
America=20
      and probably the most extreme anteating specialist in the world. =
Like the=20
      Australian marsupial </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Myrmecobius, </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">it has a long and pointed =
snout,=20
      extremely long and pointed in this case, and an extremely long =
sticky=20
      tongue. South America also has a small treeclimbing anteater, =
which is a=20
      close cousin of </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Myrmecophaga </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">and looks like a miniature and =
less=20
      extreme version of it, and a third, intermediate form. Although =
placental=20
      mammals, these anteaters are very tar from any Old World =
placentals. They=20
      belong to a uniquely South American family, which also includes =
armadillos=20
      and sloths. This ancient placental family coexisted with the =
marsupials=20
      from the early days of the continent's isolation. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.25pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The Old World anteaters include =
various=20
      species of pangolin in Africa and Asia, ranging from tree-climbing =
forms=20
      to digging forms, all looking a bit like fircones with pointed =
snouts.=20
      Also in Africa is the weird ant-bear or aardvark, which is =
partially=20
      specialized for digging. A feature that characterizes all =
anteaters,=20
      whether marsupial, monotreme or placental, is an extremely low =
metabolic=20
      rate. The metabolic rate is the rate at which their chemical =
'fires' burn,=20
      most easily measured as the blood temperature. There is a tendency =
for=20
      metabolic rate to depend on body size in mammals generally. =
Smaller=20
      animals tend to have higher metabolic rates, just as the engines =
of small=20
      cars tend to turn over at a higher rate than those of larger cars. =
But=20
      some animals have high metabolic rates for their size, and =
anteaters, of=20
      whatever ancestry and affinities, tend to have very low metabolic =
rates=20
      for their size. It is not obvious why this is, but it is so =
strikingly=20
      convergent among animals that have nothing else in <BR>common but =
their=20
      anteating habit, that it almost certainly </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">is </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">somehow related to this habit.=20
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.9pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">As we have seen, the 'ants' =
that=20
      anteaters eat are often </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">not </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">true ants at all, but termites. =
Termites=20
      are often known as 'white ants', but they are related to =
cockroaches,=20
      rather than to true ants, which are related to bees and wasps. =
Termites=20
      resemble ants superficially because they have convergently adopted =
the=20
      same habits. The same range of habits, I should say, because there =
are=20
      many different branches of the ant/ termite trade, and both ants =
and=20
      termites have independently adopted most of them. As so often with =

      convergent evolution, the differences are revealing as well as the =

      similarities. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.25pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Both ants and termites live in =
large=20
      colonies consisting mostly of sterile, wingless workers, dedicated =
to the=20
      efficient production of winged reproductive castes which fly off =
to found=20
      new colonies. An </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.25pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D8 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D43 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D8>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D8=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image051.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D43></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D630 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D388 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D630>
      <P class=3DStyle5 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.25pt 0pt 7.7pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Making tracks through animal =
space=20
      </SPAN></I><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">107=20
      </SPAN></B><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 7.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">interesting difference is that =
in ants=20
      the workers are all sterile females, whereas in termites they are =
sterile=20
      males and sterile females. Both ant and termite colonies have one =
(or=20
      sometimes several) enlarged 'queens', sometimes (in both ants and=20
      termites) grotesquely enlarged. In both ants and termites the =
workers can=20
      include specialist castes such as soldiers. Sometimes these are =
such=20
      dedicated fighting machines, especially in their huge jaws (in the =
case of=20
      ants, but ' gunturrets' for chemical warfare in the case of =
termites),=20
      that they are -ncapable of feeding themselves and have to be fed =
by=20
      non-soldier workers. Particular species of ants parallel =
particular=20
      species </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">of=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">termites. For =
example,=20
      the habit of fungus-farming has arisen independently in ants (in =
the New=20
      World) and termites (in Africa). The ants (or termites) forage for =
plant=20
      material that they do not digest <BR>themselves but make into =
compost on=20
      which they grow fungi. It is the fungi that they themselves eat. =
The=20
      fungi, in both cases, grow nowhere else than in the nests of ants =
or=20
      termites, respectively. The fungus-farming habit has also been =
discovered=20
      independently and convergently (more than once) by several species =
of=20
      beetles. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.95pt 0pt 4.1pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">There are also interesting =
convergences=20
      within the ants. Although most </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">ant </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">colonies live a settled =
existence in a=20
      fixed nest, there seems </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold">to=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">be a =
successful living=20
      to be made by wandering in enormous pillaging armies. This is =
called the=20
      legionary habit. Obviously all ants walk about and forage, but =
most kinds=20
      return to a fixed nest with their booty, and the queen and the =
brood are=20
      left behind in the nest. The key to the wandering legionary habit, =
on the=20
      other hand, is that the armies take the brood and the queen with =
them. The=20
      eggs and larvae are carried in the jaws of workers. In Africa the=20
      legionary habit has been developed by the so-called driver ants. =
In=20
      Central and South America the parallel 'army ants' are very =
similar to=20
      driver ants in habit and appearance. They are not particularly =
closely=20
      related. They have certainly evolved the characteristics of the =
'army'=20
      trade independently and convergently. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 6.15pt 0pt 1.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Both driver ants and army ants =
have=20
      exceptionally large colonies, up to a million in army ants, up to =
about 20=20
      million in driver ants. Both have nomadic phases alternating with=20
      'statary' phases, relatively stable encampments or 'bivouacs'. =
Army ants=20
      and driver ants, or rather their colonies taken together as =
amoeba-like=20
      units, are both ruthless and terrible predators of their =
respective=20
      jungles. Both cut to pieces anything animal in their path, and =
both have=20
      acquired a mystique of terror in their own land. Villagers in =
parts of=20
      South America are reputed traditionally to vacate their villages, =
lock,=20
      stock and barrel when a large ant army is approaching, and to =
return when=20
      the legions have </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 6.15pt 0pt 1.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D630 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D630>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.95pt 0pt 0.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">108 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle6=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.3pt 0pt 0.7pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">marched through, having cleaned =
out every=20
      cockroach, spider and scorpion even from the thatched roofs. I =
remember as=20
      a child in Africa being more frightened of driver ants than of =
lions or=20
      crocodiles. It is worth getting this formidable reputation into=20
      perspective by quoting the words of Edward 0. Wilson, the world's =
foremost=20
      authority on ants as well as the author of </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Sociobiology: </SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.05pt 0pt 10.3pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 9.9pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">In answer to the single =
question I am=20
      asked most frequently about ants, I can give the following answer: =
No,=20
      driver ants are not really the terror of the jungle. Although the =
driver=20
      ant colony is an 'animal' weighing in excess of 20 kg and =
possessing on=20
      the order of 20 million mouths and stings and is surely the most=20
      formidable creation of the insect world, it still does not match =
up to the=20
      lurid stories told about it. After all, the swarm can only cover =
about a=20
      metre of ground every three minutes. Any competent bush mouse, not =
to=20
      mention man or elephant, can step aside and contemplate =
</SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">the </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">whole grass-roots frenzy at =
leisure, an=20
      object less of menace than of strangeness and wonder, the =
culmination of=20
      an evolutionary story as different from that of mammals as it is =
possible=20
      to conceive in this world. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.8pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">As an adult in Panama I have =
stepped=20
      aside and contemplated the New World equivalent of the driver ants =
that I=20
      had feared as a child in Africa, flowing by me like a crackling =
river, and=20
      I can testify to the strangeness and wonder. Hour after hour the =
legions=20
      marched past, walking as much over each others' bodies as over the =
ground,=20
      while I waited for the queen. Finally she came, and hers was an =
awesome=20
      presence. It was impossible to see her body. She appeared only as =
a moving=20
      wave of worker frenzy, a boiling peristaltic ball of ants with =
linked=20
      arms. She was somewhere in the middle of the seething ball of =
workers,=20
      while all around it the massed ranks of soldiers faced =
threateningly=20
      outwards with jaws agape, every one prepared to kill and to die in =
defence=20
      of the queen. Forgive my curiosity to see her: I prodded the ball =
of=20
      workers with a long stick, in a vain attempt to flush out the =
queen.=20
      Instantly 20 soldiers buried their massively muscled pincers in my =
stick,=20
      possibly never to let go, while dozens more swarmed up the stick =
causing=20
      me to let go with alacrity. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.4pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">I never did glimpse the queen, =
but=20
      somewhere inside that boiling ball she was, the central data bank, =
the=20
      repository of the master DNA of the whole colony. Those gaping =
soldiers=20
      were prepared to die for the queen, not because they loved their =
mother,=20
      not because they had been drilled in the ideals of patriotism, but =
simply=20
      because their brains and their jaws were built by genes stamped =
from the=20
      master die carried in the queen herself. They behaved like brave =
soldiers=20
      because they had inherited the genes of a long line of ancestral =
queens=20
      whose lives, and whose genes, had been saved by soldiers as brave =
as=20
      themselves. My </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.4pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D270 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D380 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D270>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.7pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Making tracks through animal =
space=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">109 =
<BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.3pt 0pt 1.45pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">soldiers had inherited the same =
genes=20
      from the present queen as those old soldiers had inherited from =
the=20
      ancestral queens. My soldiers were guarding the master copies of =
the very=20
      instructions that made them do the guarding. They were guarding =
the wisdom=20
      of their ancestors, </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold">the=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Ark of the =
Covenant.=20
      These strange statements will be made plain in the next chapter.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">I felt the strangeness then, =
and the=20
      wonder, not unmixed with revivals of half-forgotten fears, but=20
      transfigured and enhanced by a mature understanding, which I had =
lacked as=20
      a child in Africa, of what the whole performance was for. =
Enhanced, too,=20
      by the knowledge that this story of the legions had reached the =
same=20
      evolutionary culmination not once but twice. These were not the =
driver=20
      ants of my childhood nightmares, however similar they might be, =
but=20
      remote, New World cousins. They were doing the same thing as the =
driver=20
      ants, and for the same reasons. It was night now and I turned for =
home, an=20
      awestruck child again, but joyful in the new world of =
understanding that=20
      had supplanted the dark, African fears. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D535 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D372 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D535>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"><IMG=20
      height=3D535=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image052.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D372></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D561 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D380 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D561>
      <P class=3DStyle16 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 104pt 0pt 111.1pt">CHAPTER =
5 <SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <H2 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 51.75pt 0pt 58.8pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 16.5pt">THE POWER AND THE ARCHIVES =
</SPAN><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR><BR><BR></SPAN></H2>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">It is raining DNA outside. On =
the bank of=20
      the Oxford canal at the bottom of my garden is a large willow =
tree, and it=20
      is pumping downy seeds into the air. There is no consistent air =
movement,=20
      and the seeds are drifting outwards in all directions from the =
tree. Up=20
      and down the canal, as far as my binoculars can reach, the water =
is white=20
      with floating cottony flecks, and we can be sure that they have =
carpeted=20
      the ground to much the same radius in other directions too. The =
cotton=20
      wool is mostly made of cellulose, and it dwarfs the tiny capsule =
that=20
      contains the DNA, the genetic information. The DNA content must be =
a small=20
      proportion of the total, so why did I say that it was raining DNA =
rather=20
      than cellulose? The answer is that it is the DNA that matters. The =

      cellulose fluff, although more bulky, is just a parachute, to be=20
      discarded. The whole performance, cotton wool, catkins, tree and =
all, is=20
      in aid of one thing and one thing only, the spreading of DNA =
around the=20
      countryside. Not just any DNA, but DNA whose coded characters =
spell out=20
      specific instructions for building willow trees that will shed a =
new=20
      generation of downy seeds. Those fluffy specks are, literally, =
spreading=20
      instructions for making themselves. They are there because their =
ancestors=20
      succeeded in doing the same. It is raining instructions out there; =
it's=20
      raining programs; it's raining tree-growing, fluff-spreading, =
algorithms.=20
      That is not a metaphor, it is the plain truth. It couldn't be any =
plainer=20
      if it were raining floppy discs. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.15pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">It is plain and it is true, but =
it hasn't=20
      long been understood. A few years ago, if you had asked almost any =

      biologist what was special about living things as opposed to =
nonliving=20
      things, he would have told you about a special substance called=20
      protoplasm. Protoplasm wasn't like any other substance; it was =
vital,=20
      vibrant, throbbing, pulsating, <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.1pt 0pt 256.8pt"><B><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">111 </SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.1pt 0pt 256.8pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D16 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D18 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D16>
      <P class=3DStyle4><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">112 =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D602 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D602>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.55pt 0pt 0.5pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">'irritable' (a schoolmarmish =
way of=20
      saying responsive). If you took a living body and cut it up into =
ever=20
      smaller pieces, you would <BR>eventually come down to specks of =
pure=20
      protoplasm. At one time in the last century, a real-life =
counterpart of=20
      Arthur Conan Doyle's Professor Challenger thought that the =
'globigerina=20
      ooze' at the bottom of the sea was pure protoplasm. When I was a=20
      schoolboy, elderly textbook <BR>authors still wrote about =
protoplasm=20
      although, by then, they really should have known better. Nowadays =
you=20
      never hear or see the word. It is as dead as phlogiston and the =
universal=20
      aether. There is nothing special about the substances from which =
living=20
      things are made. Living things are collections of molecules, like=20
      everything else. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">What is special is that these =
molecules=20
      are put together in much more complicated patterns than the =
molecules of=20
      nonliving things, and this putting together is done by following =
programs,=20
      sets of instructions for how to develop, which the organisms carry =
around=20
      inside themselves. Maybe they do vibrate and throb and pulsate =
with=20
      'irritability', and glow with 'living' warmth, but these =
properties all=20
      emerge incidentally. What lies at the heart of every living thing =
is not a=20
      fire, not warm breath, not a 'spark of life'. It is information, =
words,=20
      instructions. If you want a metaphor, don't think of fires and =
sparks and=20
      breath. Think, instead, of a billion discrete, digital characters =
carved=20
      in tablets of crystal. If you want to understand life, don't think =
about=20
      vibrant, throbbing gels and oozes, think about information =
technology. It=20
      is this that I was hinting at in the previous chapter, when I =
referred to=20
      the queen ant as the central data bank. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.45pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The basic requirement for an =
advanced=20
      information technology is some kind of storage medium with a large =
number=20
      of memory locations. Each location must be capable of being in one =
of a=20
      discrete number of states. This is true, anyway, of the =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">digital </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">information technology that now =
dominates=20
      our world of artifice. There is an alternative kind of information =

      technology based upon </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">analogue </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">information. The information on =
an=20
      ordinary gramophone record is analogue. It is stored in a wavy =
groove. The=20
      information on a modem laser disc (often called 'compact disc', =
which is a=20
      pity, because the name is uninformative and also usually =
mispronounced=20
      with the stress on the first syllable) is digital, stored in a =
series of=20
      tiny pits, each of which is either definitely there or definitely =
not=20
      there: there are no half measures. That is the diagnostic feature =
of a=20
      digital system: its fundamental elements are either definitely in =
one=20
      state or definitely in another state, with no half measures and no =

      intermediates or <BR>compromises. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.15in"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The information technology of =
the genes=20
      is digital. This fact was </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.15in"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D16 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D132 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D16>
      <P class=3DStyle6><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The =
Blind=20
      Watchmaker </SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle6><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D382 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle19 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 3.35pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The power and the archives=20
      </SPAN></I>113 <BR><BR></P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.45pt 0pt 2.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt">discovered=20
      by Gregor Mendel in the last century, although he wouldn't have =
put it=20
      like that. Mendel showed that we don't blend our inheritance from =
our two=20
      parents. We receive our inheritance in discrete particles. As far =
as each=20
      particle is concerned, we either inherit it or we don't. Actually, =
as R.=20
      A. Fisher, one of the founding fathers of what is now called=20
      neo-Darwinism, has pointed out, this fact of paniculate =
inheritance has=20
      always been staring us in the face, every time we think about sex. =
We=20
      inherit attributes from a male and a female parent, but each of us =
is=20
      either male or female, not hermaphrodite. Each new baby born has =
an=20
      approximately equal <I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">probability=20
      </SPAN></I>of inheriting maleness or femaleness, but any one baby =
inherits=20
      only one of these, and doesn't combine the two. We now know that =
the same=20
      goes for all our particles of inheritance. They don't blend, but =
remain=20
      discrete and separate as they shuffle and reshuffle their way down =
the=20
      generations. Of course there is often a powerful appearance of =
blending in=20
      the effects that the genetic units have on bodies. If a tall =
person mates=20
      with a short person, or a black person with a white person, their=20
      offspring are often intermediate. But the appearance of blending =
applies=20
      only to effects on bodies, and is due to the summed small effects =
of large=20
      numbers of particles. The particles themselves remain separate and =

      discrete when it comes to being passed on to the next generation. =
</P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.75pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt">The=20
      distinction between blending inheritance and particulate =
inheritance has=20
      been of great importance in the history of evolutionary ideas. In =
Darwin's=20
      time everybody (except Mendel who, tucked away in his monastery, =
was=20
      unfortunately ignored until after his death) thought that =
inheritance was=20
      blending. A Scottish engineer called Fleeming Jenkin pointed out =
that the=20
      fact (as it was thought to be) of blending inheritance all but =
ruled out=20
      natural selection as a plausible theory of evolution. Ernst Mayr =
rather=20
      unkindly remarks that Jenkin's article 'is based on all the usual=20
      prejudices and misunderstandings of the physical scientists'.=20
      Nevertheless, Darwin was deeply worried by lenkin's argument. It =
was most=20
      colourfully embodied in a parable <B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">of a </SPAN></B>white man =
shipwrecked on=20
      an island inhabited by 'negroes': <BR><BR></P>
      <P class=3DStyle21=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 12.7pt 0pt 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 9.85pt">grant =
him every=20
      advantage which we can conceive a white to possess over the =
native;=20
      concede that in the struggle for existence his chance of a long =
life will=20
      be much superior to that of the native chiefs, yet from all these=20
      admissions, there does not follow the conclusion that, after a =
limited or=20
      unlimited number of generations, the inhabitants of the island =
will be=20
      white. Our shipwrecked hero would probably become king; he would =
kill a=20
      great many blacks in the struggle for existence; he would have a =
great=20
      many wives and children, while many of his subjects would live and =
die as=20
      bachelors . . . Our white's qualities would certainly tend very =
much=20
      <B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">to </SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle21=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 12.7pt 0pt 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 9.85pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D10 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D40 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D10>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold"><IMG height=3D10=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image053.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D40></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D621 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D621>
      <P class=3DStyle18 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.45pt">114 <B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: 'Times-Bold Italic'">The =
</SPAN></I></B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN><BR><BR></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 6.15pt 0pt 10.3pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
9.9pt">preserve him to=20
      a good old age, and yet he would not suffice in any number of =
generations=20
      to turn his subjects' descendants white . . . In the first =
generation=20
      there will be some dozens of intelligent young mulattoes, much =
superior in=20
      average intelligence to the negroes. We might expect the throne =
for some=20
      generations to be occupied by a more or less yellow king; but can =
any one=20
      believe that the whole island will gradually acquire a white, or =
even a=20
      yellow population, or that the islanders would acquire the energy, =

      courage, ingenuity, patience, self-control, endurance, in virtue =
of which=20
      qualities our hero killed so many of their ancestors, and begot so =
many=20
      children, these qualities, in fact, which the struggle for =
existence would=20
      select, if it could select anything? </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.4pt">Don't=20
      be distracted by the racist assumptions of white superiority. =
These were=20
      as unquestioned in the time of Jenkin and Darwin as our speciesist =

      assumptions of <I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">human =
rights,=20
      human </SPAN></I>dignity, and the sacredness of <I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">human </SPAN></I>life are =
unquestioned=20
      today. We can rephrase Jenkin's argument in a more neutral =
analogy. If you=20
      mix white paint and black paint together, what you get is grey =
paint. If=20
      you mix grey paint and grey paint together, you can't reconstruct =
either=20
      the original white or the original black. Mixing paints is not so =
far from=20
      the pre- Mendelian vision of heredity, and even today popular =
culture=20
      frequently expresses heredity in terms of a mixing of 'bloods'. =
Jenkin's=20
      argument is an argument about swamping. As the generations go by, =
under=20
      the assumption of blending inheritance, variation is bound to =
become=20
      swamped. Greater and greater uniformity will prevail. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.4pt 0pt =
0.25pt">Eventually there=20
      will be no variation left for natural selection to work upon. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.55pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt">Plausible=20
      as this argument must have sounded, it is not only an argument =
against=20
      natural selection. It is more an argument against inescapable =
facts about=20
      heredity itself! It manifestly isn't <I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">true </SPAN></I>that variation =

      disappears as the generations go by. People are not more similar =
to each=20
      other today than they were in their grandparents' time. Variation =
is=20
      maintained. There is a pool of variation for selection to work on. =
This=20
      was pointed out mathematically in 1908 by W. Weinberg, and =
independently=20
      by the eccentric mathematician G. H. Hardy, who incidentally, as =
the=20
      betting book of his (and my) college records, once took a bet from =
a=20
      colleague of 'One half penny to his fortune till death, that the =
sun will=20
      rise tomorrow'. But it took R. A. Fisher and his colleagues, the =
founders=20
      of modem population genetics, to develop the full answer to =
Fleeming=20
      Jenkin in terms of Mendel's theory of <I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">particle </SPAN></I>genetics. =
This was=20
      an irony at the time, because, as we shall see in Chapter 11, the =
leading=20
      followers of Mendel in the early twentieth century thought of =
themselves=20
      as anti-Darwinian. Fisher and his colleagues showed that Darwinian =

      selection made sense, and </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.55pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D11 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D32 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D11>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D11 =

      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image054.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D32></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
