<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D11 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D33 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D11>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D11 =

      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image055.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D33></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D382 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.05in"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The power and the archives=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">115 =
<BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.1pt 0pt 0.05in; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Jenkin's problem was elegantly =
solved, if=20
      what changed in evolution was the relative </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">frequency </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">of discrete hereditary =
particles, or=20
      genes, each of which was either there or not there in any =
particular=20
      individual body. Darwinism post-Fisher is called neo-Darwinism. =
Its=20
      digital nature is not an incidental fact that happens to be true =
of=20
      genetic information technology. Digitalness is probably a =
necessary=20
      <BR>precondition for Darwinism itself to work. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.05pt 0pt 2.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">In our electronic technology =
the=20
      discrete, digital locations have only two states, conventionally=20
      represented as 0 and 1 although you can think of them as high and =
low, on=20
      and off, up and down: all that matters is that they should be =
distinct=20
      from one another, and that the pattern of their states can be =
'read out'=20
      so that it can have some influence on something. Electronic =
technology=20
      uses various physical media for storing Is and Os, including =
magnetic=20
      discs, magnetic tape, punched cards and tape, and integrated =
'chips' with=20
      lots of little semiconductor units inside them. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.15pt 0pt 1.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The main storage medium inside =
willow=20
      seeds, ants and all other living cells is not electronic but =
chemical. It=20
      exploits the fact that certain kinds of molecule are capable of=20
      'polymerizing', that is joining up in long chains of indefinite =
length.=20
      There are lots of different kinds of polymer. For example, =
'polythene' is=20
      made of long chains of the small molecule called ethylene - =
polymerized=20
      ethylene. Starch and cellulose are polymerized sugars. Some =
polymers,=20
      instead of being uniform chains of one small molecule like =
ethylene, are=20
      chains of two or more different kinds of small molecule. As soon =
as such=20
      heterogeneity enters into a polymer chain, information technology =
becomes=20
      a theoretical possibility. If there are two kinds of small =
molecule in the=20
      chain, the two can be thought of as 1 and 0 respectively, and =
immediately=20
      any amount of information, of any kind, can be stored, provided =
only that=20
      the chain is long enough. The <BR>particular polymers used by =
living cells=20
      are called polynucleotides. There are two main families of =
polynucleotides=20
      in living cells, called DNA and RNA for short. Both are chains of =
small=20
      molecules called nucleotides. Both DNA and RNA are heterogeneous =
chains,=20
      with four different kinds of nucleotides. This, of course, is =
where the=20
      opportunity for information storage lies. Instead of just the two =
states 1=20
      and 0, the information technology of living cells uses four =
states, which=20
      we may conventionally represent as A, T, C and G. There is very =
little=20
      difference, in principle, between a two-state binary information=20
      technology like ours, and a four-state information technology like =
that=20
      </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">of =
</SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the living cell. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.2pt 0pt 9.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">As I mentioned at the end of =
Chapter 1,=20
      there is enough information </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.2pt 0pt 9.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.55pt 0pt 1.45pt"><B><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">116 </SPAN></B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.7pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">capacity in a single human cell =
to store=20
      the </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">Encyclopaedia=20
      Britannica, </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman">all 30=20
      volumes of it, three or four times over. I don't know the =
<BR>comparable=20
      figure for a willow seed or an ant, but it will be of the same =
order of=20
      staggeringness. There is enough storage capacity in the DNA of a =
single=20
      lily seed or a single salamander sperm to store the =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Encyclopaedia Britannica=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">60 times over. =
Some=20
      species of the unjustly called 'primitive' amoebas have as much=20
      information in their DNA as 1,000 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Encyclopaedia Britannicas.=20
      </SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.6pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Amazingly, only about 1 per =
cent of the=20
      genetic information in, for example, human cells, seems to be =
actually=20
      used: roughly the equivalent of one volume of the </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Encyclopaedia Britannica.=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Nobody knows =
why the=20
      other 99 per cent is there. In a previous book I suggested that it =
might=20
      be parasitic, freeloading on the efforts of the 1 per cent, a =
theory that=20
      has more recently been taken up by molecular biologists under the =
name of=20
      'selfish DNA'. A bacterium has a smaller information capacity than =
a human=20
      cell, by a factor of about 1,000, and it probably uses nearly all =
of it:=20
      there is little room for parasites. Its DNA could 'only' hold one =
copy of=20
      the New Testament! </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.6pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Modern genetic engineers =
already have the=20
      technology to write the New Testament or anything else into a =
bacterium's=20
      DNA. The 'meaning' of the symbols in any information technology is =

      arbitrary, and there is no reason why we should not assign =
combinations,=20
      say triplets, from DNA's 4-letter alphabet, to letters of our own=20
      26-letter alphabet (there would be room for all the upper and =
lower-case=20
      letters with 12 punctuation characters). Unfortunately, it would =
take=20
      about five man-centuries to write the New Testament into a =
bacterium, so I=20
      doubt if anybody will bother. If they did, the rate of =
reproduction of=20
      bacteria is such that 10 million copies of the New Testament could =
be=20
      </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">run =
</SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">off in a single day, a =
missionary's dream=20
      if only people could read </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">the </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">DNA alphabet but, alas, the =
characters=20
      are so small that all 10 million copies of the New Testament could =

      simultaneously dance </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold">upon=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the surface of =
a pin's=20
      head. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.75pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Electronic computer memory is=20
      conventionally classified into ROM and RAM. ROM stands for 'read =
only'=20
      memory. More strictly it is 'write once, read many times' memory. =
The=20
      pattern of Os and Is is 'burned' into it once and for all on =
manufacture.=20
      It then remains unchanged throughout the life of the memory, and =
the=20
      information </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">can=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">be read out =
any number=20
      of times. Other electronic memory, called RAM, can be 'written to' =
(one=20
      soon gets used to this inelegant computer jargon) as well as read. =
RAM can=20
      therefore do everything that ROM can do, and more. What the =
letters RAM=20
      actually stand for is misleading, so I won't mention it. The point =
about=20
      RAM is that you </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.75pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D10 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D55 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D10>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D10 =

      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image056.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D55></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D8 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D61 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D8>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D8=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image057.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D61></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D630 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D383 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D630>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.05in"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The power and the archives=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">117 =
<BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.35pt 0pt 3.35pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">can put any pattern of Is and =
Os into any=20
      part of it that you like, on as many occasions as you like. Most =
of a=20
      computer's memory is RAM. As I type these words they are going =
straight=20
      into RAM, and the wordprocessing program controlling things is =
also in=20
      RAM, although it could theoretically be burned into ROM and then =
never=20
      subsequently altered. ROM is used for a fixed repertoire of =
standard=20
      programs, which are needed again and again, and which you can't =
change=20
      even if you wanted to. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.6pt 0pt 2.65pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">DNA is ROM. It can be read =
millions of=20
      times over, but only written to once - when it is first assembled =
at the=20
      birth of the cell in which it resides. The DNA in the cells of any =

      individual is 'burned in', and is never altered during that =
individual's=20
      lifetime, except by very rare random deterioration. It can be =
copied,=20
      however. It is duplicated every time a cell divides. The pattern =
of A,T,C=20
      and G nucleotides is faithfully copied into the DNA of each of the =

      trillions of new cells that are made as a baby grows. When a new=20
      individual is conceived, a new and unique pattern of data is =
'burned into'=20
      his DNA ROM, and he is then stuck with that pattern for the rest =
of his=20
      life. It is copied into all his cells (except his reproductive =
cells, into=20
      which a random half of his DNA is copied, as we shall see). =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.5pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">All computer memory, whether =
'ROM' or=20
      'RAM', is </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">addressed.=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">This means =
that every=20
      location in the memory has a label, usually a number but this is =
an=20
      arbitrary convention. It is important to understand the =
distinction=20
      between the </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">address=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">and the =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">contents </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">of a memory location. Each =
location is=20
      known by its address. For instance the first two letters of this =
chapter,=20
      'It', are at this moment sitting in RAM locations 6446 and 6447 of =
my=20
      computer, which has 65,536 RAM locations altogether. At another =
time, the=20
      contents of those two locations will be different. The contents of =
a=20
      location is whatever was most recently written in that location. =
Each ROM=20
      location also has an address and a contents. The difference is =
that each=20
      location is stuck with its contents, once and for all. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.5pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The DNA is arranged along =
stringy=20
      chromosomes, like long computer tapes. All the DNA in each of our =
cells is=20
      addressed in the same sense as computer ROM, or indeed computer =
tape, is=20
      addressed. The exact numbers or names that we use to label a given =
address=20
      are arbitrary, just as they are for computer memory. What matters =
is that=20
      a particular location in my DNA corresponds precisely to one =
particular=20
      location in your DNA: they have the same address. The =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">contents </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">of my DNA location 321762 may =
or may not=20
      be the same as the contents of your location 321762. But my =
location=20
      321762 is in precisely the same position in my cells as your =
location=20
      321762 is in your cells. 'Position' </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.5pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D16 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D18 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D16>
      <P class=3DStyle4><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">118 =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D602 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D602>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.35pt 0pt 0.5pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">here means position along the =
length of a=20
      particular chromosome. The exact physical position of a chromosome =
in a=20
      cell doesn't matter. Indeed, it floats about in fluid so its =
physical=20
      position varies, but every location along the chromosome is =
precisely=20
      addressed in terms of linear order along the length of the =
chromosome,=20
      just as every location along a computer tape is precisely =
addressed, even=20
      if the tape is strewn around the floor rather than being neatly =
rolled up.=20
      All of us, all human beings, have the same set of DNA =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">addresses, </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">but not necessarily the same=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">contents=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">of those =
addresses. That=20
      is the main reason why we are all different from each other. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.7pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Other species don't have the =
same set of=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">addresses.=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Chimpanzees, =
for=20
      instance, have 48 chromosomes compared to our 46. Strictly =
speaking it is=20
      not possible to compare contents, address by address, because =
addresses=20
      don't correspond to each other across species barriers. Closely =
related=20
      species, however, like chimps and humans, have such large chunks =
of=20
      adjacent contents in common that we can easily identify them as =
basically=20
      the same, even though we can't use quite the same addressing =
system for=20
      the two species. The thing that defines a species is that all =
members have=20
      the same addressing system for their DNA. Give or take a few minor =

      exceptions, all members have the same number of chromosomes, and =
every=20
      location along the length of a chromosome has its exact opposite =
number in=20
      the same position along the length of the corresponding chromosome =
in all=20
      other members of the species. What can differ among the members of =
a=20
      species is the contents of those locations. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.05pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The differences in contents in =
different=20
      individuals come about in the following manner, and here I must =
stress=20
      that I am talking about sexually reproducing species such as our =
own. Our=20
      sperms or eggs each contain 23 chromosomes. Each addressed =
location in one=20
      of my sperms corresponds to a particular addressed location in =
every other=20
      one of my sperms, and in every one of your eggs (or sperms). All =
my other=20
      cells contain 46 - a double set. The same addresses are used twice =
over in=20
      each of these cells. Every cell contains two chromosome 9s, and =
two=20
      versions of location 7230 along chromosome 9. The contents of the =
two may=20
      or may not be the same, just as they may or may not be the same in =
other=20
      members of the species. When a sperm, with its 23 chromosomes, is =
made=20
      from a body cell with its 46 chromosomes, it only gets one of the =
two=20
      copies of each addressed location. Which one it gets can be =
treated as=20
      random. The same goes for eggs. The result is that every sperm =
produced=20
      and every egg produced is unique in terms of the </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">contents </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">of their locations, although =
their=20
      addressing system is identical in all members of one species (with =
minor=20
      exceptions that </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.05pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D16 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D132 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D16>
      <P class=3DStyle6><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The =
Blind=20
      Watchmaker </SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle6><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D383 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 4.3pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The power =
</SPAN></I><B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: 'Times-Bold Italic'">and the archives=20
      </SPAN></I></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">119=20
      <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.2pt 0pt 3.85pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.5pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">need not concern us). When a =
sperm=20
      fertilizes an egg, a full complement of 46 chromosomes is, of =
course, made=20
      up; and all 46 are then duplicated in all the cells of the =
developing=20
      embryo. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.85pt 0pt 0.05in; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">I said that ROM cannot be =
written to=20
      except when it is first manufactured, and that is true also of the =
DNA in=20
      cells, except for occasional random errors in copying. But there =
is a=20
      sense in which the collective data bank consisting of the ROMs of =
an=20
      entire species can be constructively written to. The nonrandom =
survival=20
      and reproductive success of individuals within the species =
effectively=20
      'writes' improved instructions for survival into the collective =
genetic=20
      memory of the species as the generations go by. Evolutionary =
change in a=20
      species largely consists of changes in how many copies there are =
of each=20
      of the various possible </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">contents </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">at each addressed DNA location, =
as the=20
      generations pass. Of course, at any particular time, every copy =
has to be=20
      inside an individual body. But what matters in evolution is =
changes in=20
      frequency of alternative possible contents at each address in=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">populations.=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The addressing =
system=20
      remains the same, but the statistical profile of location contents =
changes=20
      as the centuries go by. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.55pt 0pt 1.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Once in a blue moon the =
addressing system=20
      itself changes. Chimpanzees have 24 pairs of chromosomes and we =
have 23.=20
      We share a common ancestor with chimpanzees, so at some point in =
either=20
      our ancestry or chimps' there must have been a change in =
chromosome=20
      number. Either we lost a chromosome (two merged), or chimps gained =
one=20
      (one split). There must have been at least one individual who had =
a=20
      different number of chromosomes from his parents. There are other=20
      occasional changes in the entire genetic system. Whole lengths of =
code, as=20
      we shall see, may occasionally be copied to completely different=20
      chromosomes. We know this because we find, scattered around the=20
      chromosomes, long strings of DNA text that are identical. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05in 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">When the information in a =
computer memory=20
      has been read from a particular location, one of two things may =
happen to=20
      it. It can either simply be written somewhere else, or it can =
become=20
      involved in some 'action'. Being written somewhere else means =
being=20
      copied. We have already seen that DNA is readily copied from one =
cell to a=20
      new cell, and that chunks of DNA may be copied from one individual =
to=20
      another individual, namely its child. 'Action' is more =
complicated. In=20
      computers, one kind of action is the execution of program =
instructions. In=20
      my computer's ROM, location numbers 64489, 64490 and 64491, taken=20
      together, contain a particular pattern of contents - Is and Os =
which =97=20
      when interpreted as instructions, result in the computer's little=20
      loudspeaker uttering a blip sound. This bit pattern is=20
      101011010011000011000000. There is nothing inherently blippy or =
noisy=20
      about that bit pattern. Nothing about it tells you that it will=20
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05in 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D16 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D18 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D16>
      <P class=3DStyle4><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">120 =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D601 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D381 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D601>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.65pt 0pt 1.7pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">have that effect on the =
loudspeaker. It=20
      has that effect only because of the way the rest of the computer =
is wired=20
      up. In the same way, patterns in the DNA four-letter code have =
effects,=20
      for instance on eye colour or behaviour, but these effects are not =

      inherent in the DNA data patterns themselves. They have their =
effects only=20
      as a result of the way the rest of the embryo develops, which in =
turn is=20
      influenced by the effects of patterns in other parts of the DNA. =
This=20
      interaction between genes will be a main theme of Chapter 7. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.65pt 0pt 1.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Before they can be involved in =
any kind=20
      of action, the code symbols of DNA have to be translated into =
another=20
      medium. They are first transcribed into exactly corresponding RNA =
symbols.=20
      RNA also has a four-letter alphabet. From here, they are =
translated into a=20
      different kind of polymer called a polypeptide or protein. It =
might be=20
      called a polyamino acid, because the basic units are amino acids. =
There=20
      are 20 kinds of amino acids in living cells. All biological =
proteins are=20
      chains made of these 20 basic building-blocks. Although a protein =
is a=20
      chain of amino acids, most of them don't remain long and stringy. =
Each=20
      chain coils up into a complicated knot, the precise shape of which =
is=20
      determined by the order of amino acids. This knot shape therefore =
never=20
      varies for any given sequence of amino acids. The sequence of =
amino acids=20
      in turn is precisely determined by the code symbols in a length of =
DNA=20
      (via RNA as an intermediary). There is a sense, therefore, in =
which the=20
      three-dimensional coiled shape of a protein is determined by the=20
      one-dimensional sequence of code symbols in the DNA. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.8pt 0pt 2.15pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The translation procedure =
embodies the=20
      celebrated three-letter 'genetic code'. This is a dictionary, in =
which=20
      each of the 64 (4 x 4 x 4) possible </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">triplets </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">of DNA (or RNA) symbols is =
translated=20
      into one of the 20 amino acids or a 'stop reading' symbol. There =
are three=20
      of these 'stop reading' punctuation marks. Many of the amino acids =
are=20
      coded by more than one triplet (as you might have guessed from the =
fact=20
      that there are 64 triplets and only 20 amino acids). The whole=20
      translation, from strictly sequential DNA ROM to precisely =
invariant=20
      three-dimensional protein shape, is a remarkable feat of digital=20
      information technology. Subsequent steps by which genes influence =
bodies=20
      are a little less obviously computer-like. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.45pt 0pt 2.15pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Every living cell, even a =
single=20
      bacterial cell, can be thought of as a gigantic chemical factory. =
DNA=20
      patterns, or genes, exert their effects by influencing the course =
of=20
      events in the chemical factory, and they do this via their =
influence on=20
      the three-dimensional shape of protein molecules. The word =
gigantic may=20
      seem surprising for a cell, especially when you remember that 10 =
million=20
      bacterial cells could sit on the -surface of a pin's head. But you =
will=20
      also remember that each of these </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.45pt 0pt 2.15pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D16 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D132 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D16>
      <P class=3DStyle6><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The =
Blind=20
      Watchmaker </SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle6><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D383 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 4.55pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The power and the archives=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">121 =
<BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.45pt 0pt 4.3pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">cells is capable of holding the =
whole=20
      text of the New Testament and, moreover, it </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">is </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">gigantic when measured by the =
number of=20
      sophisticated machines that it contains. Each machine is a large =
protein=20
      molecule, put together under the influence of a particular stretch =
of DNA.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.85pt 0pt 3.85pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Protein molecules called =
enzymes are=20
      machines in the sense that each one causes a particular chemical =
reaction=20
      to take place. Each kind of <BR>protein machine churns out its own =

      particular chemical product. To do this it uses raw materials that =
are=20
      drifting around in the cell, being, very probably, the products of =
other=20
      protein machines. To get an idea of the size of these protein =
machines,=20
      each one is made of about 6,000 atoms, which is very large by =
molecular=20
      standards. There are about a million of these large pieces of =
apparatus in=20
      a cell, and there are more than 2,000 different kinds of them, =
each kind=20
      specialized to do a particular operation in the chemical factory - =
the=20
      cell. It is the <BR>characteristic chemical products of such =
enzymes that=20
      give a cell its individual shape and behaviour. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.15pt 0pt 2.4pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Since all body cells contain =
the same=20
      genes, it might seem surprising that all body cells aren't the =
same as=20
      each other. The reason is that a different subset of genes is=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">read =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">in different kinds of cells, =
the others=20
      being ignored. In liver cells, those parts of the DNA ROM =
specifically=20
      relevant to the building of kidney cells are not read, and vice =
versa. The=20
      shape and behaviour of a cell depend upon which genes inside that =
cell are=20
      being read and translated into their protein products. This in =
turn=20
      depends on the chemicals already in the cell, which depends partly =
on=20
      which genes have previously been read in the cell, and partly on=20
      neighbouring cells. When one cell divides into two, the two =
daughter cells=20
      aren't necessarily the same as each other. In the original =
fertilized egg,=20
      for instance, certain chemicals congregate at one end of the cell, =
others=20
      at the other end. When such a polarized cell divides, the two =
daughter=20
      cells receive different chemical allocations. This means that =
different=20
      genes will be read in the two daughter cells, and a kind of=20
      self-reinforcing divergence gets going. The final shape of the =
whole body,=20
      the size of its limbs, the wiring up of its brain, the timing of =
its=20
      behaviour patterns, are all the indirect consequences of =
interactions=20
      between different kinds of cells, whose differences in their turn =
arise=20
      through different genes being read. These diverging processes are =
best=20
      thought of as locally autonomous in the manner of the 'recursive'=20
      procedure of Chapter 3, rather than as coordinated in some grand =
central=20
      design. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.65pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">'Action', in the sense used in =
this=20
      chapter, is what a geneticist is talking about when he mentions =
the=20
      'phenotypic effect' of a gene. DNA has effects upon bodies, upon =
eye=20
      colour, hair crinkliness, </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.65pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D16 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D18 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D16>
      <P class=3DStyle4><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">122 =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D602 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D602>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"LINE-HEIGHT: 10.8pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
1.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">strength of aggressive =
behaviour and=20
      thousands of other attributes, </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">all </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">of which are called phenotypic =
effects.=20
      DNA exerts these effects initially locally, after being read by =
RNA and=20
      translated into protein chains, which then affect cell shape and=20
      behaviour. This is one of the two ways in which the information in =
the=20
      pattern of DNA can be read out. The other way is that it can be =
duplicated=20
      into a new DNA strand. This is the copying that we discussed =
earlier.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
2.45pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">There is a fundamental =
distinction=20
      between these two routes of transmission of the DNA information, =
vertical=20
      and horizontal transmission. The information is transmitted =
vertically to=20
      other DNA in cells (that make other cells) that make sperms or =
eggs. Hence=20
      it is transmitted vertically to the next generation and then, =
vertically=20
      again, to an indefinite number of future generations. I shall call =
this=20
      'archival DNA'. It is potentially immortal. The succession of =
cells along=20
      which archival DNA travels is called the germ line. The germ line =
is that=20
      set of cells, within a body, which is ancestral to sperms or eggs =
and=20
      hence ancestral to future generations. DNA is also transmitted=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">sideways=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">or =
horizontally: to DNA=20
      in non-germ-line cells such as liver cells or skin cells; within =
such=20
      cells to RNA, thence to protein and various effects on embryonic=20
      development and therefore on adult form and behaviour. You can =
think of=20
      horizontal transmission and vertical transmission as corresponding =
to the=20
      two sub-programs called DEVELOPMENT and REPRODUCTION in Chapter 3. =

      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Natural selection is all about =
the=20
      differential success of rival DNA in getting itself transmitted =
vertically=20
      in the species archives. 'Rival DNA' means alternative contents of =

      particular addresses in the chromosomes of the species. Some genes =
are=20
      more successful than rival genes at remaining in the archives. =
Although=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">vertical=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">transmission =
down the=20
      archives of the species is ultimately what 'success' means, the =
criterion=20
      for success is normally the </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">action </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">that the genes have on bodies, =
by means=20
      of their </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">sideways=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">transmission. =
This, too,=20
      is just like the biomorph computer model. For instance, suppose =
that in=20
      tigers there is a particular gene which, by means of its sideways=20
      influence in cells of the jaw, causes the teeth to be a little =
sharper=20
      than those that would be grown under the influence of a rival =
gene. A=20
      tiger with extra-sharp teeth can kill prey more efficiently than a =
normal=20
      tiger; hence it has more offspring; hence it passes on, =
vertically, more=20
      copies of the gene that makes sharp teeth. It passes on all its =
other=20
      genes at the same time, of course, but only the specific =
'sharp-teeth=20
      gene' will find itself, on </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">average, </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">in the bodies of sharp-toothed =
tigers.=20
      The gene itself benefits, in terms of its vertical transmission, =
from the=20
      average effects that it has on a whole series of bodies. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D16 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D131 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D16>
      <P class=3DStyle6><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The =
Blind=20
      Watchmaker </SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle6><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D385 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 6.5pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The power and the archives=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">123 =
<BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.75pt 0pt 5.75pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">DNA's performance as an =
archival medium=20
      is spectacular. In its capacity to preserve a message it far =
outdoes=20
      tablets of stone. Cows and pea plants (and, indeed, all the rest =
of us)=20
      have an almost identical gene called the histone H4 gene. The DNA =
text is=20
      306 characters long. We can't say that it occupies the same =
addresses in=20
      all species, because we can't meaningfully compare address labels =
across=20
      species. But what we can say is that there is a length of 306 =
characters=20
      in cows, which is virtually identical to a length of 306 =
characters in=20
      peas. Cows and peas differ from each other in only two characters =
out of=20
      these 306. We don't know exactly how long ago the common ancestor =
of cows=20
      and peas lived, but fossil evidence suggests that it was somewhere =
between=20
      1,000 and 2,000 million years ago. Call it 1.5 billion years ago. =
Over=20
      this unimaginably (for humans) long time, each of the two lineages =
that=20
      branched from that remote ancestor has preserved 305 out of the =
306=20
      characters (on average: it could be that one lineage has preserved =
all 306=20
      of them and the other has preserved 304). Letters carved on =
gravestones=20
      become unreadable in mere hundreds of years. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.9pt 0pt 2.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">In a way the conservation of =
the=20
      histone-H4 DNA document is even more impressive because, unlike =
tablets of=20
      stone, it is not the same physical structure that lasts and =
preserves the=20
      text. It is repeatedly being copied and recopied as the =
generations go by,=20
      like the Hebrew scriptures which were ritually copied by scribes =
every 80=20
      years to forestall their wearing-out. It is hard to estimate =
exactly how=20
      many times the histone H4 document has been recopied in the =
lineage=20
      leading to cows from the common ancestor with peas, but it is =
<BR>probably=20
      as many as 20 billion times. It is also hard to find a yardstick =
with=20
      which to compare the preservation of more than 99 per cent of =
information=20
      in 20 billion successive copyings. We can try using a version of =
the game=20
      of grandmothers' whispers. Imagine 20 billion typists sitting in a =
row.=20
      The line of typists would reach right round the Earth 500 times. =
The first=20
      typist writes a page of a document and hands it to his neighbour. =
He=20
      copies it and hands his copy to the next one. He copies it again =
and hands=20
      it on to the next, and so on. Eventually, the message reaches the =
end of=20
      the line, and we read it (or rather our 12,000th great =
grandchildren do,=20
      assuming that all the typists have a speed typical of a good =
secretary).=20
      How faithful a rendering of the original message would it be? =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 6.5pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">To answer this we have to make =
some=20
      assumption about the accuracy of the typists. Let's twist the =
question=20
      round the other way. How good would each typist have to be, in =
order to=20
      match the DNA's performance? The answer is almost too ludicrous to =

      express. For what it is worth, every typist would have to have an =
error=20
      rate of about one </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 6.5pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D377 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.6pt 0pt 1.2pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">124 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.15pt 0pt 0.5pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">in a trillion; that is, he =
would have to=20
      be accurate enough to make only a single error in typing the Bible =
250,000=20
      times at a stretch. A good secretary in real life has an error =
rate of=20
      about one per page. This is about half a billion times the error =
rate of=20
      the histone H4 gene. A line of real-life secretaries would degrade =
a text=20
      to 99 per cent of its original letters by the 20th member of the =
line of=20
      20 billion. By the 10,000th member of the line, less than 1 per =
cent of=20
      the original text would survive. This point of near total =
degradation=20
      would be reached before <BR>99.9995 per cent of the typists had =
even seen=20
      it. This whole comparison has been a bit of a cheat, but in an =
interesting=20
      and revealing respect. I gave the impression that what we are =
measuring is=20
      copying errors. But the histone H4 document hasn't just been =
copied, it=20
      has been subjected to natural selection. Histone is vitally =
important for=20
      survival. It is used in the structural engineering of chromosomes. =
Maybe=20
      lots more mistakes in </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">copying </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the histone H4 gene occurred, =
but the=20
      mutant organisms did not survive, or at least did not reproduce. =
To make=20
      the comparison fair, we should have to assume that built into each =

      typist's chair is a gun, wired up so that if he makes a mistake he =
is=20
      summarily shot, his place being taken by a reserve typist =
(squeamish=20
      readers may prefer to imagine a spring-loaded ejector seat gently=20
      catapulting miscreant typists out of the line, but the gun gives a =
more=20
      realistic picture of natural selection). </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.25pt 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">So, this method of measuring =
the=20
      conservatism of DNA, by looking </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">at </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the number of changes that have =
actually=20
      occurred during geological time, compounds genuine copying =
fidelity with=20
      the filtering effects of natural selection. We see only the =
descendants of=20
      successful DNA changes. The ones that led to death are obviously =
not with=20
      us. Can we measure the actual copying fidelity on the ground, =
before=20
      natural selection gets to work on each new generation of genes? =
Yes, this=20
      is the inverse of what is known as the mutation rate, and it can =
be=20
      measured. The probability of any particular letter being miscopied =
on any=20
      one copying occasion turns out to be a little more than one in a =
billion.=20
      The difference between this, the mutation rate, and the lower rate =
at=20
      which change has actually been incorporated in the histone gene =
during=20
      evolution, is a measure of the effectiveness of natural selection=20
      </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">in =
</SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">preserving this ancient =
document.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.4pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The histone gene's conservatism =
over the=20
      aeons is exceptional by genetic standards. Other genes change at a =
higher=20
      rate, presumably because natural selection is more tolerant of =
variations=20
      in them. For instance, genes coding the proteins known as =
fibrinopeptides=20
      change in evolution at a rate that closely approximates the basic =
mutation=20
      rate. This probably means that mistakes in the details of these =
proteins=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.4pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D629 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D384 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D629>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 4.8pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The power and the archives=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">125 =
<BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.4pt 0pt 4.55pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.55pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">(they are produced during the =
clotting of=20
      blood) don't matter much for the organism. Haemoglobin genes have =
a rate=20
      of changing that is intermediate betwen histones and =
fibrinopeptides.=20
      Presumably natural selection's tolerance of their errors is =
intermediate.=20
      Haemoglobin is doing an important job in the blood, and its =
details really=20
      matter, but several alternative variants of it seem capable of =
doing the=20
      job equally well. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.45pt 0pt 0.05in; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Here we have something that =
seems a=20
      little paradoxical, until we think about it further. The =
slowest-evolvjiig=20
      molecules, like histones, turn out to be the ones that have been =
most=20
      subject to natural selection. Fibrinopeptides are the =
fastest-evolving=20
      molecules because natural selection almost completely ignores =
them. They=20
      are free to evolve at the mutation rate. The reason this seems =
paradoxical=20
      is that we place so much emphasis on natural selection as the =
driving=20
      force of evolution. If there is no natural selection, therefore, =
we might=20
      expect that there would be no evolution. Conversely, strong =
'selection=20
      <BR>pressure', we could be forgiven for thinking, might be =
expected to=20
      lead to rapid evolution. Instead, what we find is that natural =
selection=20
      exerts a braking effect on evolution. The baseline rate of =
evolution, in=20
      the absence of natural selection, is the maximum possible rate. =
That is=20
      synonymous with the mutation rate. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.1pt 0pt 1.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">This isn't really paradoxical. =
When we=20
      think about it carefully, we see that it couldn't be otherwise. =
Evolution=20
      by natural selection could not be faster than the mutation rate, =
for=20
      mutation is, ultimately, the only way in which new variation =
enters the=20
      species. All that natural selection can do is accept certain new=20
      variations, and reject others. The mutation rate is bound to place =
an=20
      upper limit on the rate at which evolution can proceed. As a =
matter of=20
      fact, most of natural selection is concerned with preventing =
evolutionary=20
      change rather than with driving it. This doesn't mean, I hasten to =
insist,=20
      that natural selection is a purely destructive process. It can =
construct=20
      too, in ways that Chapter 7 will explain. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.15pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Even the mutation rate is =
pretty slow.=20
      This is another way of saying that, even without natural =
selection, the=20
      performance of the DNA code in accurately preserving its archive =
is very=20
      impressive. A conservative estimate is that, in the absence of =
natural=20
      selection, DNA replicates so accurately that it takes five million =

      replication generations to miscopy 1 per cent of the characters. =
Our=20
      hypothetical typists are still hopelessly outclassed by DNA, even =
if there=20
      is no natural selection. To match DNA with no natural selection, =
the=20
      typists would each have to be able to type the whole of the New =
Testament=20
      with only one error. That is, they would each have to be about 450 =
times=20
      more accurate </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.15pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D12 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D85 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D12>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D12 =

      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image058.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D85></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D380 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.2pt 0pt 2.9pt"><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">126 </SPAN></B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">than a typical real-life =
secretary. This=20
      is obviously much less than the comparable figure of half a =
billion, which=20
      is the factor by which the histone H4 gene </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">after natural selection =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">is more accurate than a typical =

      secretary; but it is still a very impressive figure. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">But I have been unfair to the =
typists. I=20
      assumed, in effect, that they are not capable of noticing their =
mistakes=20
      and correcting them. I have assumed a complete absence of =
proofreading. In=20
      reality, of course, they do proofread. My line of billions of =
typists=20
      wouldn't, therefore, cause the original message to degenerate in =
quite the=20
      simple way that I portrayed. The DNA-copying mechanism does the =
same kind=20
      of error-correction automatically. If it didn't, it wouldn't =
achieve=20
      anything like the stupendous accuracy that I have described. The=20
      DNAcopying procedure incorporates various 'proofreading' drills. =
This is=20
      all the more necessary because the letters of the DNA code are by =
no means=20
      static, like hieroglyphs carved in granite. On the contrary, the =
molecules=20
      involved are so small - remember all those New Testaments fitting =
on a=20
      pin's head - that they are under constant assault from the =
ordinary=20
      jostling of molecules that goes on due to heat. There is a =
constant flux,=20
      a turnover of letters in the message. About 5,000 DNA letters =
degenerate=20
      per day in every human cell, and are immediately replaced by =
repair=20
      mechanisms. If the repair mechanisms weren't there and ceaselessly =

      working, the message would steadily dissolve. Proofreading of =
newly copied=20
      text is just a special case of normal repair work. It is mainly=20
      proofreading that is responsible for DNA's remarkable accuracy and =

      fidelity of information storage. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.55pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">We have seen that DNA molecules =
are the=20
      centre of a spectacular information technology. They are capable =
of=20
      packing an immense amount of precise, digital information into a =
very=20
      small space; and they are capable of preserving this information - =
with=20
      astonishingly few errors, but still some errors - for a very long =
time,=20
      measured in millions of years. Where are' these facts leading us? =
They are=20
      leading us in the direction of a central truth about life on =
Earth, the=20
      truth that I alluded to in my opening paragraph about willow =
seeds. This=20
      is that living organisms exist for the benefit of DNA rather than =
the=20
      other way around. This won't be obvious yet, but I hope to =
persuade you of=20
      it. The messages that DNA molecules contain are all but eternal =
when seen=20
      against the time scale of individual lifetimes. The lifetimes of =
DNA=20
      messages (give or take a few mutations) are measured in units =
ranging from=20
      millions of years to hundreds of millions of years; or, in other =
words,=20
      ranging from 10,000 individual lifetimes to a trillion individual=20
      lifetimes. Each individual organism should be seen as a temporary=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.55pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D381 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 2.4pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The power and the archives=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">127 =
<BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.4pt 0pt 1.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">vehicle, in which DNA messages =
spend a=20
      tiny fraction of their geological lifetimes. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.85pt 0pt 1.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The world is full of things =
that exist .=20
      . . ! No disputing that, but is it going to get us anywhere? =
Things exist=20
      either because they have recently come into existence or because =
they have=20
      qualities that made them unlikely to be destroyed in the past. =
Rocks don't=20
      come into existence at a high rate, but once they exist they are =
hard and=20
      durable. If they were not they wouldn't be rocks, they would be =
sand.=20
      Indeed, some of them are, which is why we have beaches! It is the =
ones=20
      that happen to be durable that exist as rocks. Dewdrops, on the =
other=20
      hand, exist, not because they are durable, but because they have =
only just=20
      come into existence and have not yet had time to evaporate. We =
seem to=20
      have two kinds of 'existenceworthiness': the dewdrop kind, which =
can be=20
      summed up as 'likely to come into existence but not very durable'; =
and the=20
      rock kind, which can be summed up as 'not very likely to come into =

      existence but likely to last for a long time once there'. Rocks =
have=20
      durability and dewdrops have 'generatability'. (I've tried to =
think of a=20
      less ugly word but I can't.) </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.95pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">DNA gets the best of both =
worlds. DNA=20
      molecules themselves, as physical entities, are like dewdrops. =
Under the=20
      right conditions they come into existence at a great rate, but no =
one of=20
      them has existed for long, and all will be destroyed within a few =
months.=20
      They are not durable like rocks. But the </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">patterns </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">that they bear in their =
sequences are as=20
      durable as the hardest rocks. They have what it takes to exist for =

      millions of years, and that is why they are still here today. The=20
      essential difference from dewdrops is that new dewdrops are not =
begotten=20
      by old dewdrops. Dewdrops doubtless resemble other dewdrops, but =
they=20
      don't specifically resemble their own 'parent' dewdrops. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.45pt 0pt 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Unlike DNA molecules, they =
don't form=20
      lineages, and therefore can't pass </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">on </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">messages. Dewdrops come into =
existence by=20
      spontaneous generation, DNA messages by replication. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
2.5pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Truisms like 'the world is full =
of things=20
      that have what it takes to be in the world' are trivial, almost =
silly,=20
      until we come to apply them to a special kind of durability, =
durability in=20
      the form of lineages of multiple copies. DNA messages have a =
different=20
      kind of durability from that of rocks, and a different kind of=20
      generatability from that of dewdrops. For DNA molecules, 'what it =
takes to=20
      be in the world' comes to have a meaning that is anything but =
obvious and=20
      tautological. 'What it takes to be in the world' turns out to =
include the=20
      ability to build machines like you and me, the most complicated =
things in=20
      the known universe. Let us see how this can be so. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.7pt 0pt 9.85pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Fundamentally, the reason is =
that the=20
      properties of DNA that we </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.7pt 0pt 9.85pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D381 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle9 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.3pt 0pt 1.7pt">128 =
<I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.1pt 0pt 0.7pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">have identified turn out to be =
the basic=20
      ingredients necessary for any process of cumulative selection. In =
our=20
      computer models in Chapter 3, we deliberately built into the =
computer the=20
      basic ingredients of cumulative selection. If cumulative selection =
is=20
      really to happen in the world, some entities have got to arise =
whose=20
      properties constitute those basic ingredients. Let us look, now, =
at what=20
      those ingredients are. As we do so, we shall keep in mind the fact =
that=20
      these very same ingredients, at least in some rudimentary form, =
must have=20
      arisen spontaneously on the early Earth, otherwise cumulative =
selection,=20
      and therefore life, would never have got started in the first =
place. We=20
      are talking here not specifically about DNA, but about the basic=20
      ingredients needed for life to arise anywhere in the universe. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.55pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">When the prophet Ezekiel was in =
the=20
      valley of bones he prophesied to the bones and made them join up =
together.=20
      Then he prophesied to them and made flesh and sinews come around =
them. But=20
      still there was no breath in them. The vital ingredient, the =
ingredient of=20
      life, was missing. A dead planet has atoms, molecules and larger =
lumps of=20
      matter, jostling and nestling against each other at random, =
according to=20
      the laws of physics. Sometimes the laws of physics cause the atoms =
and=20
      molecules to join up together like Ezekiel's dry bones, sometimes =
they=20
      cause them to split apart. Quite large accretions of atoms can =
form, and=20
      they can crumble and break apart again. But still there is no =
breath in=20
      them. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.05pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Ezekiel called upon the four =
winds to put=20
      living breath into the dry bones. What is the vital ingredient =
that a dead=20
      planet like the early Earth must have, if it is to have a chance =
of=20
      eventually coming alive, as our planet did? It is not breath, not =
wind,=20
      not any kind of elixir or. potion. It is not a substance at all, =
it is a=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">property,=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the property =
of=20
      selfreplication. This is the basic ingredient of cumulative =
selection.=20
      There must somehow, as a consequence of the ordinary laws of =
physics, come=20
      into being </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">self-copying=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">entities or, =
as I shall=20
      call them, </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">replicators.=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">In modern life =
this role=20
      is filled, almost entirely, by DNA molecules, but anything of =
which copies=20
      are made would do. We may suspect that the first replicators on =
the=20
      primitive Earth were not DNA molecules. It is unlikely that a =
fully=20
      fledged DNA molecule would spring into existence without the aid =
of other=20
      molecules that normally exist only in living cells. The first =
replicators=20
      were probably cruder and simpler than DNA. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.9pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">There are two other necessary=20
      ingredients, which will normally arise automatically from the =
first=20
      ingredient, self-replication itself. There must be occasional =
errors in=20
      the self-copying; even the DNA system very occasionally makes =
mistakes,=20
      and it seems likely that the </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.9pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D383 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle5 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 3.85pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The power and the archives=20
      </SPAN></I><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">129=20
      </SPAN></B><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.6pt 0pt 3.35pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">first replicators on Earth were =
much more=20
      erratic. And at least some of the replicators should exert =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">power </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">over their own future. This =
last=20
      ingredient sounds more sinister than it actually is. All it means =
is that=20
      some properties of the replicators should have an influence over =
their=20
      probability of being replicated. At least in a rudimentary form, =
this is=20
      likely to be an inevitable consequence of the basic facts of=20
      selfreplication itself. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.25pt 0pt 2.65pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Each replicator, then, has =
copies of=20
      itself made. Each copy is the same as the original, and has the =
same=20
      properties as the original. Among these properties, of course, is =
the=20
      property of making (sometimes with errors) </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">more </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">copies of itself. So each =
replicator is=20
      potentially the 'ancestor' of an indefinitely long line of =
descendant=20
      replicators, stretching into the distant future, and branching to =
produce,=20
      potentially,. an exceedingly large number of descendant =
replicators. Each=20
      new copy must be made from raw materials, smaller building blocks =
knocking=20
      around. Presumably the replicators act as some kind of mould or =
template.=20
      Smaller components fall together into the mould in such a way that =
a=20
      duplicate of the mould is made. Then the duplicate breaks free and =
is able=20
      to act as a mould in its own right. Hence we have a potentially =
growing=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">population=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">of =
replicators. The=20
      population will not grow indefinitely, because eventually =
</SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">the </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">supply of raw materials, the =
smaller=20
      elements that fall into the moulds, will become limiting. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Now we introduce our second =
ingredient=20
      into the argument. Sometimes the copying will not be perfect. =
Mistakes=20
      will happen. The possibility of errors can never be totally =
eliminated=20
      from any copying process, although their probability can be =
reduced to low=20
      levels. This is what the manufacturers of hi-fi equipment are =
striving=20
      towards all the time, and the DNA-replication process, as we have =
seen, is=20
      spectactularly good at reducing errors. But modern DNA replication =
is a=20
      high-technology affair, with elaborate proofreading techniques =
that have=20
      been perfected over many generations of cumulative selection. As =
we have=20
      seen, the first replicators probably were relatively crude, =
lowfidelity=20
      contraptions in comparison. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.9pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Now go back to our population =
of=20
      replicators, and see what the effect of erratic copying will be.=20
      Obviously, instead of there being a uniform population of =
identical=20
      replicators, we shall have a mixed population. Probably many of =
the=20
      products of erratic copying will be found to have lost the =
property of=20
      self-replication that their 'parent' had. But a few will retain =
the=20
      property of self-replication, while being different from the =
parent in=20
      some other respect. So we shall have copies of errors being =
duplicated in=20
      the population. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.9pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D16 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D18 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D16>
      <P class=3DStyle4><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">130 =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D601 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D380 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D601>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.8pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
1.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">When you read the word 'error', =
banish=20
      from your mind all pejorative associations. It simply means an =
error from=20
      the point of view of high-fidelity copying. It is possible for an =
error to=20
      result in an improvement. I dare say many an exquisite new dish =
has been=20
      created because a cook made a mistake while trying to follow a =
recipe.=20
      Insofar as I can claim to have had any original scientific ideas, =
these=20
      have sometimes been misunderstandings, or misreadings, of other =
peoples'=20
      ideas. To return to our primeval replicators, while most =
miscopyings=20
      probably resulted in diminished copying effectiveness, or total =
loss of=20
      the self-copying property, a few might actually have turned out to =
be=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">better =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">at self-replication than the =
parent=20
      replicator that gave rise to them. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.4pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">What does 'better' mean? =
Ultimately it=20
      means more efficient </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold">at=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman">self-replication, but=20
      what might this mean in practice? This brings us to our third=20
      'ingredient'. I referred to this as 'power', and you'll see why in =
a=20
      moment. When we discussed replication as a moulding process, we =
saw that=20
      the last step in the process must be the new copy's breaking free =
of the=20
      old mould. The time that this occupies may be influenced by a =
property=20
      which I shall call the 'stickiness' of the old mould. Suppose that =
in our=20
      population of replicators, which vary because of old copying =
errors back=20
      in their 'ancestry', some varieties happen to be more sticky than =
others.=20
      A very sticky variety clings </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">to </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">each new copy for an average =
time of more=20
      than an hour before it finally breaks free and the process can =
begin=20
      again. A less-sticky variety lets go of each new copy within a =
split=20
      second of its formation. Which of these two varieties will come to =

      predominate in </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold">the=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">population of=20
      replicators? There is no doubt about the answer. If this =
</SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">is </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the only property by which the =
two=20
      varieties differ, the sticky one is bound to become far less =
numerous in=20
      the population. The non-sticky one is churning out copies of =
non-sticky=20
      ones at thousands of times </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">the </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">rate that the sticky one is =
making copies=20
      of sticky ones. Varieties of intermediate stickiness will have=20
      intermediate rates of selfpropagation. There will be an =
'evolutionary=20
      trend' towards reduced stickiness. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.4pt 0pt 1.45pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.95pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Something like this kind of =
elementary=20
      natural selection has been duplicated in the test-tube. There is a =
virus=20
      called Q-beta which lives as a parasite of the gut bacterium=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Escherichia =
coli.=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Q-beta has no =
DNA but it=20
      does contain, indeed it largely consists of, a single strand of =
the=20
      related molecule RNA. RNA is capable of being replicated =
</SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">in a </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">similar way to DNA. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 2.15pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">In the normal cell, protein =
molecules are=20
      assembled to the specification of RNA plans. These are working =
copies of=20
      plans, run off </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 2.15pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D16 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D132 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D16>
      <P class=3DStyle6><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The =
Blind=20
      Watchmaker </SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle6><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D384 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 4.55pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The power and the archives=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">131 =
<BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.4pt 0pt 4.3pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">from the DNA masters held in =
the cell's=20
      precious archives. But it is theoretically possible to build a =
special=20
      machine - a protein molecule like the rest of the cellular =
machines - that=20
      runs off RNA copies from other RNA copies. Such a machine is =
called an=20
      RNA-replicase molecule. The bacterial cell itself normally has no =
use for=20
      these machines, and doesn't build any. But since the replicase is =
just a=20
      protein molecule like any other, the versatile protein-building =
machines=20
      of the bacterial cell can easily turn to building them, just as =
the=20
      machine tools in a car factory can quickly be turned over in time =
of war=20
      to making munitions: all they need is to be fed the right =
blueprints. This=20
      is where the virus comes in. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.85pt 0pt 2.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The business part of the virus =
is an RNA=20
      plan. Superficially .it is indistinguishable from any of the other =
RNA=20
      working blueprints that are floating around, after being run off =
the=20
      bacterium's DNA master. But if you read the small print of the =
viral RNA=20
      you will find something devilish written there. The letters spell =
out a=20
      plan for making RNAreplicase: for making machines that make more =
copies of=20
      the very same RNA plans, that make more machines that make more =
copies of=20
      the plans, that make more . . . </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.85pt 0pt 2.15pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">So the factory is hijacked by =
these=20
      self-interested blueprints. In a sense it was crying out to be =
hijacked.=20
      If you fill your factory with machines so sophisticated that they =
can make=20
      anything that any blueprint tells them to make, it is hardly =
surprising if=20
      sooner or later a blueprint arises that tells these machines to =
make=20
      copies of itself. The factory fills up with more and more of these =
rogue=20
      machines, each churning out rogue blueprints for making more =
machines that=20
      will make more of themselves. Finally, the unfortunate bacterium =
bursts=20
      and releases millions of viruses that infect new bacteria. So much =
for the=20
      normal life cycle of the virus in nature. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.1pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">I have called RNA-replicase and =
RNA=20
      respectively a machine and a blueprint. So they are, in a sense =
(to be=20
      disputed on other grounds in a later chapter), but they are also=20
      molecules, and it is possible for human chemists to purify them, =
bottle=20
      them and store them on a shelf. This is what Sol Spiegelman and =
his=20
      colleagues did in America in the 1960s. Then they put the two =
molecules=20
      together in solution, and a fascinating thing happened. In the =
test-tube,=20
      the RNA molecules acted as templates for the synthesis of copies =
of=20
      themselves, aided by the presence of the RNA-replicase. The =
machine tools=20
      and the blueprints had been extracted and put into cold storage,=20
      separately from one another. Then, as soon as they were given =
access to=20
      each other, and also to the small molecules needed as raw =
materials, in=20
      water, both got back to their old tricks even though they were no =
longer=20
      in a living cell but in a test tube. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 5.25pt 0pt 9.85pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">It is but a short step from =
this to=20
      natural selection and evolution </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">in </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 5.25pt 0pt 9.85pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D16 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D18 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D16>
      <P class=3DStyle4><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">132 =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D601 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D601>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.1pt 0pt 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">laboratory. It is just a =
chemical version=20
      of the computer biomorphs. The experimental method is basically to =
lay out=20
      a long row of testtubes each containing a solution of =
RNA-replicase, and=20
      also of raw materials, small molecules that can be used for RNA =
synthesis.=20
      Each test-tube contains the machine tools and the raw material, =
but so far=20
      it is sitting idle, doing nothing because it lacks a blueprint to =
work=20
      from. Now a tiny amount of RNA itself is dropped into the first =
test-tube.=20
      The replicase apparatus immediately gets to work and manufactures =
lots of=20
      copies of the newly introduced RNA molecules, which spread through =
the=20
      test-tube. Now a drop of the solution in the first test-tube is =
removed=20
      and put into the second test-tube. The process repeats itself in =
the=20
      second test-tube and then a drop is removed and used to seed the =
third=20
      test-tube, and so on. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Occasionally, because of random =
copying=20
      errors, a slightly different, mutant RNA molecule spontaneously =
arises.=20
      If, for any reason, the new variety is competitively superior to =
the old=20
      one, superior in the sense that, perhaps because of its low =
'stickiness',=20
      it gets itself replicated faster or otherwise more effectively, =
the new=20
      variety will obviously spread through the test-tube in which it =
arose,=20
      outnumbering the parental type that gave rise to it. Then, when a =
drop of=20
      solution is removed from that test-tube to seed the next =
test-tube, it=20
      will be the new mutant variety that does the seeding. If we =
examine the=20
      RNAs in a long succession of test-tubes, we see what can only be =
called=20
      evolutionary change. Competitively superior varieties of RNA =
produced at=20
      the end of several test-tube 'generations' can be bottled and =
named for=20
      future use. One variety for example, called V2, replicates much =
more=20
      rapidly than normal Q-beta RNA, probably because it is smaller. =
Unlike=20
      Q-beta RNA, it doesn't have to 'bother' to contain the plans for =
making=20
      replicase. Replicase is provided free by the experimenters. V2 RNA =
was=20
      used as the starting point for an interesting experiment by Leslie =
Orgel=20
      and his colleagues in California, in which they imposed a =
'difficult'=20
      environment. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.45pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">They added to their test-tubes =
a poison=20
      called ethidium bromide which inhibits the synthesis of RNA: it =
gums up=20
      the works of the machine tools. Orgel and colleagues began with a =
weak=20
      solution of the poison. At first, the rate of synthesis was slowed =
down by=20
      the poison, but after evolving through about nine test-tube =
transfer=20
      'generations', a new strain of RNA that was resistant to the =
poison had=20
      been selected. Rate of RNA synthesis was now comparable to that of =
normal=20
      V2 RNA </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">in =
</SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the absence of poison. Now =
Orgel and his=20
      colleagues doubled the concentration of poison. Again the rate of =
RNA=20
      replication dropped, but after another 10 or so test-tube =
transfers a=20
      strain of RNA had </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.45pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D16 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D132 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D16>
      <P class=3DStyle6><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The =
Blind=20
      Watchmaker </SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle6><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D388 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle5 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 5.75pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica-Oblique">The power and the =
archives=20
      </SPAN></I><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">133=20
      </SPAN></B><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.35pt 0pt 5.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">evolved that was immune even to =
the=20
      higher concentration of poison. Then the concentration of the =
poison was=20
      doubled again. In this way, by successive doublings, they managed =
to=20
      evolve a strain of RNA that could self-replicate in very high=20
      concentrations of ethidium bromide, 10 times as concentrated as =
the poison=20
      that had inhibited the original ancestral V2 RNA. They called the =
new,=20
      resistant RNA V40. The evolution of V40 from V2 took about 100 =
test-tube=20
      transfer 'generations' (of course, many actual RNA-replication =
generations=20
      go on between each test-tube transfer). </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.25pt 0pt 3.85pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Orgel has also done experiments =
in which=20
      no enzyme was provided. He found that RNA molecules can replicate=20
      themselves spontaneously under these conditions, albeit very =
slowly. They=20
      seem to need some other catalyzing substance, such as zinc. This =
is=20
      important because, in the early days of life when. replicators =
first=20
      arose, we cannot suppose that there were enzymes around to help =
them to=20
      replicate. There probably was zinc, though. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.4pt 0pt 2.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The complementary experiment =
was carried=20
      out a decade ago in the laboratory of the influential German =
school=20
      working on the origin of life under Manfred Eigen. These workers =
provided=20
      replicase and RNA building blocks in the test-tube, but they did=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">not =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">seed the solution with RNA. =
Nevertheless,=20
      a particular large RNA molecule evolved </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">spontaneously in =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the test-tube, and the same =
molecule=20
      re-evolved itself again and again in subsequent independent =
experiments!=20
      Careful checking showed that there was no possibility of chance =
infection=20
      by RNA molecules. This is a remarkable result when you consider =
the=20
      statistical improbability of the same large molecule spontaneously =
arising=20
      twice. It is very much more improbable than the spontaneous typing =
of=20
      METHINKS IT IS LIKE A WEASEL. Like that phrase in our computer =
model, the=20
      particular favoured RNA molecule was built up by gradual, =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">cumulative </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">evolution. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 5pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.55pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The variety of RNA produced, =
repeatedly,=20
      in these experiments was of the same size and structure as the =
molecules=20
      that Spiegelman had produced. But whereas Spiegelman's had evolved =
by=20
      'degeneration' from naturally occurring, larger, Q-beta viral RNA, =
those=20
      of the Eigen group had built themselves up from almost nothing. =
This=20
      particular formula is well adapted to an environment consisting of =

      test-tubes provided with ready-made replicase. It therefore is =
converged=20
      upon by cumulative selection from two very different starting =
points. The=20
      larger, Q-beta RNA molecules are less well adapted to a test-tube=20
      environment but better adapted to the environment provided by=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">E.coli =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">cells. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 6.75pt 0pt 9.85pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Experiments such as these help =
us to=20
      appreciate the entirely </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 6.75pt 0pt 9.85pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D16 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D18 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D16>
      <P class=3DStyle4><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">134 =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D601 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D380 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D601>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.3pt 0pt 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.8pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">automatic and non-deliberate =
nature of=20
      natural selection. The replicase 'machines' don't 'know' why they =
make RNA=20
      molecules: it is just a byproduct of their shape that they do. And =
the RNA=20
      molecules themselves don't work out a strategy for getting =
themselves=20
      duplicated. Even if they could think, there is no obvious reason =
why any=20
      thinking entity should be motivated to make copies of itself. If I =
knew=20
      how to make copies of myself, I'm not sure that I would give the =
project=20
      high priority in competition with all the other things I want to =
do: why=20
      should I? But motivation is irrelevant for molecules. It is just =
that the=20
      structure of the viral RNA </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">happens to </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">be such that it makes cellular =
machinery=20
      churn out copies of itself. And if any entity, anywhere in the =
universe,=20
      happens to have the property of being good at making more copies =
of=20
      itself, then automatically more and more copies of that entity=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">will =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">obviously come into existence. =
Not only=20
      that but, since they automatically form lineages and are =
occasionally=20
      miscopied, later versions tend to be 'better' at making copies of=20
      themselves than earlier versions, because of the powerful =
processes of=20
      cumulative selection. It is all utterly simple and automatic. It =
is so=20
      predictable as to be almost inevitable. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">A 'successful' RNA molecule in =
a=20
      test-tube is successful because </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">of </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">some direct, intrinsic property =
of=20
      itself, something analogous to the 'stickiness' of my hypothetical =

      example. But properties like 'stickiness' are rather boring. They =
are=20
      elementary properties of the replicator itself, properties that =
have a=20
      direct effect on its probability of being replicated. What if the=20
      replicator has some effect upon <BR>something else, which affects=20
      something else, which affects something else, which . . . =
eventually,=20
      indirectly affects the replicator's chance of being replicated? =
You can=20
      see that, if long chains of causes like this existed, the =
fundamental=20
      truism would still hold. Replicators that happen to have what it =
takes to=20
      get replicated would come to predominate in the world, no =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">matter how long and indirect=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the chain of =
causal=20
      links by which they influence their probability of being =
replicated. And,=20
      by the same token, the world will come to be filled with the links =
in this=20
      causal chain. We shall see those links, and marvel at them. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.55pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">In modern organisms we see them =
all the=20
      time. They are eyes and skins and bones and toes and brains and =
instincts.=20
      These things are the tools of DNA replication. They are caused by =
DNA, in=20
      the sense that differences in eyes, skins, bones, instincts, etc. =
are=20
      caused by differences in DNA. They exert an influence over the =
replication=20
      of the DNA that caused them, in that they affect the survival and=20
      reproduction of their bodies - which contain that same DNA, and =
whose fate=20
      is therefore shared by the DNA. Therefore, the DNA itself exerts=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.55pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D16 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D133 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D16>
      <P class=3DStyle6><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The =
Blind=20
      Watchmaker </SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle6><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D11 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D44 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D11>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic"><IMG height=3D11 =

      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image059.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D44></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D385 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05pt 0pt 5.75pt"><I><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The power and the archives=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">135 =
<BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 5.3pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.5pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">an influence over its own =
replication,=20
      via the attributes of bodies. DNA can be said to exert power over =
its own=20
      future, and bodies and their organs and behaviour patterns are the =

      instruments of that power. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.55pt 0pt 4.8pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">When we talk about power, we =
are talking=20
      about consequences of replicators that affect their own future, =
however=20
      indirect those consequences might be. It doesn't matter how many =
links=20
      there are in the chain from cause to effect. If the cause is a=20
      self-replicating entity, the effect, be it ever so distant and =
indirect,=20
      can be subject to natural selection. I shall summarize the general =
idea by=20
      telling a particular story about beavers. In detail it is =
hypothetical,=20
      but it certainly cannot be far from the truth. Although nobody has =
done=20
      research upon the <BR>development of brain connections in the =
beaver, they=20
      have done this kind of research on-other animals, like worms. I am =

      borrowing the conclusions and applying them to beavers, because =
beavers=20
      are more interesting and congenial to many people than worms. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3pt 0pt 2.65pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">A mutant gene in a beaver is =
just a=20
      change in one letter of the billionletter text; a change in a =
particular=20
      gene G. As the young beaver grows, the change is copied, together =
with all=20
      the other letters in the text, into all the beaver's cells. In =
most of the=20
      cells the gene G is not read; other genes, relevant to the =
workings of the=20
      other cell types, are. G is read, however, in some cells in the =
developing=20
      brain. It is read and transcribed into RNA copies. The RNA working =
copies=20
      drift around the interior of the cells, and eventually some of =
them bump=20
      into protein-making machines called ribosomes. The protein-making =
machines=20
      read the RNA working plans, and turn out new protein molecules to =
their=20
      specification. These protein molecules curl up into a particular =
shape=20
      determined by their own amino-acid sequence, which in turn is =
governed by=20
      the DNA code sequence of the gene G. When G mutates, the change =
makes a=20
      crucial difference to the amino-acid sequence normally specified =
by the=20
      gene G, and hence to the coiled-up shape of the protein molecule.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.4pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">These slightly altered protein =
molecules=20
      are mass-produced by the protein-making machines inside the =
developing=20
      brain cells. They in turn act as enzymes, machines that =
manufacture other=20
      compounds in the cells, the gene products. The products of the =
gene G find=20
      their way into the membrane surrounding the cell, and are involved =
in the=20
      processes whereby the cell makes connections with other cells. =
Because of=20
      the slight alteration in the original DNA plans, the =
production-rate of=20
      certain </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">of=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">these membrane =
compounds=20
      is changed. This in turn changes the way </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">in </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">which certain developing brain =
cells=20
      connect up with one another. A subtle alteration in the wiring =
diagram of=20
      a particular part of the beaver's brain has occurred, the =
indirect, indeed=20
      far-removed, consequence </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">of a </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">change in the DNA text. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.4pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D381 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.2pt 0pt 3.1pt"><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">136 </SPAN></B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.25pt 0pt 2.4pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Now it happens that this =
particular part=20
      of the beaver's brain, because of its position in the total wiring =

      diagram, is involved in the beaver's dam-building behaviour. Of =
course,=20
      large parts of the brain are involved whenever the beaver builds a =
dam=20
      but, when the G mutation affects this particular part of the =
brain's=20
      wiring diagram, the change has a specific effect on the behaviour. =
It=20
      causes the beaver to hold its head higher in the water while =
swimming with=20
      a log in its jaws. Higher, that is, than a beaver without the =
mutation.=20
      This makes it a little less likely that mud, attached to the log, =
will=20
      wash off during the journey. This increases the stickiness of the =
log,=20
      which in turn means that, when the beaver thrusts it into the dam, =
the log=20
      is more likely to stay there. This will tend to apply to all the =
logs=20
      placed by any beaver bearing this particular mutation. The =
increased=20
      stickiness of the logs is a consequence, again a very indirect=20
      consequence, of an alteration in </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">the </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">DNA text. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.2pt 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The increased stickiness of the =
logs=20
      makes the dam a sounder structure, less likely to break up. This =
in turn=20
      increases the size of the lake created by the dam, which makes the =
lodge=20
      in the centre of the lake more secure against predators. This =
tends to=20
      increase the number of offspring successfully reared by the =
beaver. If we=20
      look at the whole population of beavers, those that possess the =
mutated=20
      gene will, on average, tend therefore to rear more offspring than =
those=20
      not possessing the mutated gene. Those offspring will tend to =
inherit=20
      archive copies of the self-same altered gene from their parents.=20
      Therefore, in the population, this form of the gene will become =
more=20
      numerous as the generations go by. Eventually it will become the =
norm, and=20
      will no longer deserve the title 'mutant'. Beaver dams in general =
will=20
      have improved another notch. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.9pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The fact that this particular =
story is=20
      hypothetical, and that the details may be wrong, is irrelevant. =
The beaver=20
      dam evolved by natural selection, and therefore what happened =
cannot be=20
      very different, except in practical details, from the story I have =
told.=20
      The general implications of this view of life are explained and =
elaborated=20
      in my book </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The =
Extended=20
      Phenotype, </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">and =
I shan't=20
      repeat the arguments here. You will notice that in this =
hypothetical story=20
      there were no fewer than 11 links in the causal chain linking =
altered gene=20
      to improved survival. In real life there might be even more. Every =
one of=20
      those links, whether it is an effect on the chemistry inside a =
cell, a=20
      later effect on how brain cells wire themselves together, an even =
later=20
      effect on behaviour, or a final effect on lake size, is correctly =
regarded=20
      as </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">caused=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">by a change in =
the DNA.=20
      It wouldn't matter if there were 111 links. Any effect that a =
change in a=20
      gene has on its own replication probability is fair game for =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.9pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D127 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D381 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D127>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 2.15pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The power and the archives=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">137 =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.85pt 0pt 1.45pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.4pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">natural selection. It is all =
perfectly=20
      simple, and delightfully automatic and unpremeditated. Something =
like it=20
      is well-nigh inevitable, once the fundamental ingredients of =
cumulative=20
      selection - replication, error and power - have come into =
existence in the=20
      first place. But how did this happen? How did they come into =
existence on=20
      Earth, before life was there? We shall see how this difficult =
question=20
      might be answered, in the next chapter. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.85pt 0pt 1.45pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.4pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D511 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D365 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D511>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"><IMG=20
      height=3D511=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image060.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D365></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D561 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D561>
      <P class=3DStyle33 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 106.6pt 0pt =
108.7pt"><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">CHAPTER 6 </SPAN></B><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></B></P>
      <H2 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 35.7pt 0pt 38.4pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 17pt">ORIGINS AND MIRACLES </SPAN><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR><BR><BR></SPAN></H2>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.45pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Chance, luck, coincidence, =
miracle. One=20
      of the main topics of this chapter is miracles and what we mean by =
them.=20
      My thesis will be that events that we commonly call miracles are =
not=20
      supernatural, but are part of a spectrum of more-or-less =
improbable=20
      natural events. A miracle, in other words, if it occurs at all, is =
a=20
      tremendous stroke of luck. Events don't fall neatly into natural =
events=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">versus =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">miracles. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.55pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">There are some would-be events =
that are=20
      too improbable to be contemplated, but we can't know this until we =
have=20
      done a calculation. And to do the calculation, we must know how =
much=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">time =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">was available, more generally =
how many=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">opportunities=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">were =
available, for the=20
      event to occur. Given infinite time, or infinite opportunities, =
anything=20
      is possible. The large numbers proverbially furnished by =
astronomy, and=20
      the large timespans characteristic of geology, combine to turn =
topsy-turvy=20
      our everyday estimates of what is expected and what is miraculous. =
I shall=20
      build up to this point using a specific example which is the other =
main=20
      theme of this chapter. This example is the problem of how life =
originated=20
      on Earth. To make the point clearly, I shall arbitrarily =
concentrate on=20
      one particular theory of the origin of life, although any one of =
the=20
      modern theories would have served the purpose. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.55pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">We can accept a certain amount =
of luck in=20
      our explanations, but not too much. The question is, =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">how </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">much? The immensity of =
geological time=20
      entitles us to postulate more improbable coincidences than a court =
of law=20
      would allow but, even so, there are limits. Cumulative selection =
is the=20
      key to all our modern explanations of life. It strings a series of =

      acceptably lucky events (random mutations) together in a nonrandom =

      sequence so that, at the end of the sequence, the finished=20
      <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.7pt 0pt =
256.55pt"><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">139 </SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.7pt 0pt 256.55pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D16 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D18 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D16>
      <P class=3DStyle4><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">140 =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D600 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D600>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.8pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">product carries the illusion of =
being=20
      very very lucky indeed, far too improbable to have come about by =
chance=20
      alone, even given a timespan millions of times longer than the age =
of the=20
      universe so far. Cumulative selection is the key but it had to get =

      started, and we cannot escape the need to postulate a =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">single-step </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">chance event in the origin of =
cumulative=20
      selection itself. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.8pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">And that vital first step was a =
difficult=20
      one because, at its heart, there lies what seems to be a paradox. =
The=20
      replication processes that we know seem to need complicated =
machinery to=20
      work. In the <BR>presence of a replicase 'machine tool', fragments =
of RNA=20
      will evolve, repeatedly and convergently, towards the same =
endpoint, an=20
      endpoint whose 'probability' seems vanishingly small until you =
reflect on=20
      the power of cumulative selection. But we have to assist this =
cumulative=20
      selection to get started. It won't go unless we provide a =
catalyst, such=20
      as the replicase 'machine tool' of the previous chapter. And that=20
      catalyst, it seems, is unlikely to come into existence =
spontaneously,=20
      except under the direction of other RNA molecules. DNA molecules =
replicate=20
      in the complicated machinery of the cell, and written words =
replicate in=20
      Xerox machines, but neither seem capable of spontaneous =
replication in the=20
      absence of their supporting machinery. A Xerox machine is capable =
of=20
      copying its own blueprints, but it is not capable of springing=20
      spontaneously into existence. Biomorphs readily replicate in the=20
      environment provided by a suitably written computer program, but =
they=20
      can't write their own program or build a computer to run it. The =
theory of=20
      the blind watchmaker is extremely powerful given that we are =
allowed to=20
      assume replication and hence cumulative selection. But if =
replication=20
      needs complex machinery, since the only way we know for complex =
machinery=20
      ultimately to come into existence is cumulative selection, we have =
a=20
      problem. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.45pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Certainly the modern cellular =
machinery,=20
      the apparatus of DNA replication and protein synthesis, has all =
the=20
      hallmarks of a highly evolved, specially fashioned machine. We =
have seen=20
      how staggeringly impressive it is as an accurate data storage =
device. At=20
      its own level of ultra-miniaturization, it is of the same order of =

      elaborateness and complexity of design as the human eye is at a =
grosser=20
      level. All who have given thought to the matter agree that an =
apparatus as=20
      complex as the human eye could not possibly come into existence =
through=20
      single-step selection. Unfortunately, the same seems to be true of =
at=20
      least parts of the apparatus of cellular machinery whereby DNA =
replicates=20
      itself, and this applies not just to the cells of advanced =
creatures like=20
      ourselves and amoebas, but also to relatively more primitive =
creatures=20
      like bacteria and blue-green algae. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.45pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D16 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D132 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D16>
      <P class=3DStyle6><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The =
Blind=20
      Watchmaker </SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle6><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D9 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D48 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D9>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic"><IMG height=3D9=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image061.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D48></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D383 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 4.3pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Origins and miracles =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">141 <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.4pt 0pt 3.85pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">So, cumulative selection can =
manufacture=20
      complexity while single-step selection cannot. But cumulative =
selection=20
      cannot work unless there is some minimal machinery of replication =
and=20
      replicator power, and the only machinery of replication that we =
know seems=20
      too complicated to have come into existence by means of anything =
less than=20
      many generations of cumulative selection! Some people see this as =
a=20
      fundamental flaw in the whole theory of the blind watchmaker. They =
see it=20
      as the ultimate proof that there must originally have been a =
designer, not=20
      a </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">blind =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">watchmaker but a far-sighted =
supernatural=20
      watchmaker. Maybe, it is argued, the Creator does not control the=20
      day-to-day succession of evolutionary events; maybe he did not =
frame the=20
      tiger and the lamb, maybe he did not make a tree, but he =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">did </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">set up the original machinery =
of=20
      replication and replicator power, the original machinery of DNA =
and=20
      protein that made cumulative selection, and hence all of =
evolution,=20
      possible. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.15pt 0pt 1.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">This is a transparently feeble =
argument,=20
      indeed it is obviously selfdefeating. Organized complexity is the =
thing=20
      that we are having difficulty in explaining. Once we are allowed =
simply to=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">postulate=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">organized =
complexity, if=20
      only the organized complexity of the DNA/ protein replicating =
engine, it=20
      is relatively easy to invoke it as a generator of yet more =
organized=20
      complexity. That, indeed, is what most of this book is about. But =
of=20
      course any God capable of intelligently designing something as =
complex as=20
      the DNA/protein replicating machine must have been at least as =
complex and=20
      organized as that machine itself. Far more so if we suppose him=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">additionally=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">capable of =
such advanced=20
      functions as listening to prayers and forgiving sins. To explain =
the=20
      origin of the DNA/protein machine by invoking a supernatural =
Designer is=20
      to explain precisely nothing, for it leaves unexplained the origin =
of the=20
      Designer. You have to say <BR>something like 'God was always =
there', and=20
      if you allow yourself that kind of lazy way out, you might as well =
just=20
      say 'DNA was always there', or 'Life was always there', and be =
done with=20
      it. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.05pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The more we can get away from =
miracles,=20
      major improbabilities, fantastic coincidences, large chance =
events, and=20
      the more thoroughly we can break large chance events up into a =
cumulative=20
      series of small chance events, the more satisfying to rational =
minds our=20
      explanations will be. But in this chapter we are asking =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">how </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">improbable, how </SPAN><I><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">miraculous, </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">a single event we are allowed =
to=20
      postulate. What is the largest single event of sheer naked =
coincidence,=20
      sheer unadulterated miraculous luck, that we are allowed to get =
away with=20
      in our theories, and still say that we have a satisfactory =
explanation of=20
      life? In order </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold">for=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">a monkey to =
write=20
      'Methinks it is like a weasel' by chance, it needs a </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.05pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D16 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D18 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D16>
      <P class=3DStyle4><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">142 =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D602 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D602>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.45pt 0pt 0.5pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">very large amount of luck, but =
it is=20
      still measurable. We calculated the odds against it as about 10 =
thousand=20
      million million million million million million (1040) to 1 =
against.=20
      Nobody can really comprehend or imagine such a large number, and =
we just=20
      think of this degree of improbability as synonymous with =
impossible. But=20
      although we can't comprehend these levels of improbability in our =
minds,=20
      we shouldn't just run away from them in terror. The number =
10</SPAN>40=20
      <SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">may be very large but we =
can still=20
      write it down, and we can still use it in calculations. There are, =
after=20
      all, even larger numbers: 10</SPAN>46, <SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">for instance, is not just =
larger; you=20
      must add 10</SPAN>4" <SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">to =
itself a=20
      million times in order to obtain 10</SPAN>46. <SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">What if we could somehow muster =
a gang of=20
      10</SPAN>46 <SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">monkeys each =
with its=20
      own typewriter? Why, lo and behold, one of them would solemnly =
type=20
      'Methinks it is like a weasel', and another would almost certainly =
type 'I=20
      think therefore I am'. The problem is, of course, that we couldn't =

      assemble that many monkeys. If all the matter in the universe were =
turned=20
      into monkey flesh, we still couldn't get enough monkeys. The =
miracle of a=20
      monkey typing 'Methinks it is like a weasel' is quantitatively too =
great,=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">measurably too =

      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">great, for us =
to admit=20
      it to our theories about what actually happens. But we couldn't =
know this=20
      until we sat down and did the calculation. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.65pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.85pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">So, there are some levels of =
sheer luck,=20
      not only too great for puny human imaginations, but too great to =
be=20
      allowed in our hard-headed calculations about the origin of life. =
But, to=20
      repeat the question, how great a level of luck, how much of a =
miracle,=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">are =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">we allowed to postulate? Don't =
let's run=20
      away from this question just because large numbers are involved. =
It is a=20
      perfectly valid question, and we can at least write down what we =
would=20
      need to know in order to calculate the answer. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.8pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.8pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Now here is a fascinating =
thought. The=20
      answer to our question - of how much luck we are allowed to =
postulate -=20
      depends upon whether our planet is the only one that has life, or =
whether=20
      life abounds all around the universe. The one thing we know for =
certain is=20
      that life has arisen once, here on this very planet. But we have =
no idea=20
      at all whether there is life anywhere else in the universe. It is =
entirely=20
      possible that there isn't. Some people have calculated that there =
must be=20
      life elsewhere, on the following grounds (I won't point out the =
fallacy=20
      until afterwards). There are probably at least 10</SPAN>20 <SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">(i.e. 100 billion billion) =
roughly=20
      suitable planets in the universe. We know that life has arisen =
here, so it=20
      can't be </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">all=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">that =
improbable.=20
      Therefore it is almost inescapable that at least some among all =
those=20
      billions of billions of other planets have </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">life. </SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle25 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 9.85pt">The flaw in the =
argument lies=20
      <B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">in </SPAN></B>the =
inference that,=20
      <I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">because life has=20
</SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle25 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 9.85pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D16 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D132 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D16>
      <P class=3DStyle6><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The =
Blind=20
      Watchmaker </SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle6><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D12 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D22 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D12>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic"><IMG height=3D12 =

      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image062.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D22></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D384 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 5.75pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Origins and miracles =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">143 <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.35pt 0pt 4.8pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">arisen here, it =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">can't be too terribly =
improbable. You=20
      will notice that this inference contains the built-in assumption =
that=20
      whatever went on on Earth is likely to have gone on elsewhere in =
the=20
      universe, and this begs the whole question. In other words, that =
kind of=20
      statistical argument, that there must be life elsewhere in the =
universe=20
      because there is life here, builds in, as an assumption, what it =
is=20
      setting out to prove. This doesn't mean that the conclusion that =
life=20
      exists all around the universe is necessarily wrong. My guess is =
that it=20
      is probably right. It simply means that that particular argument =
that led=20
      up to it is no argument at all. It is just an assumption. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.85pt 0pt 3.1pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Let us, for the sake of =
discussion,=20
      entertain the alternative assumption that life has arisen only =
once, ever,=20
      and that was here on Earth. It is tempting to object to this =
assumption on=20
      the following emotional grounds. Isn't there something terribly =
medieval=20
      about it? Doesn't it recall the time when the church taught that =
our Earth=20
      was the centre of the universe, and the stars just little =
pinpricks of=20
      light set in the sky for our delight (or, even more absurdly =
presumptuous,=20
      that the stars go out of their way to exert astrological =
influences on our=20
      little lives)? How very conceited to assume that, out of all the =
billions=20
      of billions of planets in the universe, our own little backwater =
of a=20
      world, in our own local backwater of a solar system, in our own =
local=20
      backwater of a galaxy, should have been singled out for life? Why, =
for=20
      goodness sake, should it have been </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">our </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">planet? </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.3pt 0pt 1.45pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">I am genuinely sorry, for I am =
heartily=20
      thankful that we have escaped from the small-mindedness of the =
medieval=20
      church and I despise modern astrologers, but I am afraid that the =
rhetoric=20
      about backwaters in the previous paragraph is just empty rhetoric. =
It is=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">entirely=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">possible that =
our=20
      backwater of a planet is literally the only one that has ever =
borne life.=20
      The point is that if there </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">were </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">only one planet that had ever =
borne life,=20
      then it would </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">have to=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">be our planet, =
for the=20
      very good reason that 'we' are here discussing the question! If =
the origin=20
      of life </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">is=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">such an =
improbable event=20
      that it happened on only one planet in the universe, then our =
planet has=20
      to be that planet. So, we can't use the fact that Earth has life =
to=20
      conclude that life must be probable enough to have arisen on =
another=20
      planet. Such an argument would be circular. We have to have some=20
      independent arguments about how easy or difficult it is for life =
to=20
      originate on a planet, before we can even begin to answer the =
question of=20
      how many other planets in the universe have life. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
4.9pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">But that isn't the question we =
set out=20
      with. Our question was, how much luck are we allowed to assume in =
a theory=20
      of the origin of life on Earth? I said that the answer depends =
upon=20
      whether life has arisen only </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
4.9pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.25pt 0pt 1.2pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">144 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.15pt 0pt 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">once, or many times. Begin by =
giving a=20
      name to the probability, however low it is, that life will =
originate on=20
      any randomly designated planet of some particular type. Call this =
number=20
      the spontaneous generation probability or SGP. It is the SGP that =
we shall=20
      arrive at if we sit down with our chemistry textbooks, or strike =
sparks=20
      through plausible mixtures of atmospheric gases in our laboratory, =
and=20
      calculate the odds of replicating molecules springing =
spontaneously into=20
      existence in a typical planetary atmosphere. Suppose that our best =
guess=20
      of the SGP is some very very small number, say one in a billion. =
This is=20
      obviously such a small probability that we haven't the faintest =
hope of=20
      duplicating such a fantastically lucky, miraculous event as the =
origin of=20
      life in our laboratory experiments. Yet if we assume, as we are =
perfectly=20
      entitled to do for the sake of argument, that life has originated =
only=20
      once in the universe, it follows that we are </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">allowed </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">to postulate a very large =
amount of luck=20
      in a theory, because there are so many planets in the universe =
where life=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">could =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">have originated. If, as one =
estimate has=20
      it, there are 100 billion billion planets, this is 100 billion =
times=20
      greater than even the very low SGP that we postulated. To conclude =
this=20
      argument, the maximum amount of luck that we are allowed to =
assume, before=20
      we reject a particular theory of the origin of life, has odds of =
one in=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">N, =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">where </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">N is </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the number of suitable planets =
in the=20
      universe. There is a lot hidden in that word 'suitable', but let =
us put an=20
      upper limit of 1 in 100 billion billion for the maximum amount of =
luck=20
      that this argument entitles us to assume. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Think about what this means. We =
go to a=20
      chemist and say: get out your textbooks and your calculating =
machine;=20
      sharpen your pencil and your wits; fill your head with formulae, =
and your=20
      flasks with methane and ammonia and hydrogen and carbon dioxide =
and all=20
      the other gases that a primeval nonliving planet can be expected =
to have;=20
      cook them all up together; pass strokes of lightning through your=20
      simulated atmospheres, and strokes of inspiration through your =
brain;=20
      bring all your clever chemist's methods to bear, and give us your =
best=20
      chemist's estimate of the probability that a typical planet will=20
      spontaneously generate a self-replicating molecule. Or, to put it =
another=20
      way, how long would we have to wait before random chemical events =
on the=20
      planet, random thermal jostling of atoms and molecules, resulted =
in a=20
      self-replicating molecule? </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Chemists don't know the answer =
to this=20
      question. Most modern chemists would probably say that we'd have =
to wait a=20
      long time by the standards of a human lifetime, but perhaps not =
all that=20
      long by the standards of cosmological time. The fossil history of =
earth=20
      suggests that we have about a billion years - one 'aeon', to use a =

      convenient </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D385 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 5.75pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Origins and miracles =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">145 <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.6pt 0pt 5.05pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">modern definition - to play =
with, for=20
      this is roughly the time that elapsed between the origin of the =
Earth=20
      about 4.5 billion years ago and the era of the first fossil =
organisms. But=20
      the point of our 'numbers of planets' argument is that, even if =
the=20
      chemist said that we'd have to wait for a 'miracle', have to wait =
a=20
      billion billion years - far longer than the universe has existed, =
we can=20
      still accept this verdict with equanimity. There are probably more =
than a=20
      billion billion available planets in the universe. If each of them =
lasts=20
      as long as Earth, that gives us about a billion billion billion=20
      planet-years to play with. That will do nicely! A miracle is =
translated=20
      into practical politics by a multiplication sum. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.95pt 0pt 3.35pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">There is a concealed assumption =
in this=20
      argument. Well, actually there are lots, but there's one in =
particular=20
      that I want to talk about. This is that, once .life (i.e. =
replicators and=20
      cumulative selection) originates at all, it always advances to the =
point=20
      where its creatures evolve enough intelligence to speculate about =
their=20
      origins. If this is not so, our estimate of the amount of luck =
that we are=20
      allowed to postulate must be reduced accordingly. To be more =
precise, the=20
      maximum odds against the origin of life on any one planet that our =

      theories are allowed to postulate, is the number of available =
planets in=20
      the universe divided by the odds that life, once started, will =
evolve=20
      sufficient intelligence to speculate about its own origins. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.65pt 0pt 1.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">It may seem a little strange =
that=20
      'sufficient intelligence to speculate about its own origins' is a =
relevant=20
      variable. To understand why it is, consider an alternative =
assumption.=20
      Suppose that the origin of life was quite a probable event, but =
the=20
      subsequent evolution of intelligence was exceedingly improbable, =
demanding=20
      a huge stroke of luck. Suppose the origin of intelligence is so =
improbable=20
      that it has happened on only one planet in the universe, even =
though life=20
      has started on many planets. Then, since we know we are =
intelligent enough=20
      to discuss the question, we know that Earth must be that one =
planet. Now=20
      suppose that the origin of life, </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">and </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the origin of intelligence =
given that=20
      life is there, are </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">both=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">highly =
improbable=20
      events. Then the probability of any one planet, such as Earth, =
enjoying=20
      both strokes of luck is the </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">product </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">of the two low probabilities, =
and this is=20
      a far smaller probability. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 5.1pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">It is as though, in our theory =
of how we=20
      came to exist, we are allowed to postulate a certain ration of =
luck. This=20
      ration has, as its upper limit, the number of eligible planets in =
the=20
      universe. Given our ration of luck, we can then 'spend' it as a =
limited=20
      commodity over the course of our explanation of our own existence. =
If we=20
      use up almost all our ration of luck in our theory of how life =
gets=20
      started on a planet in </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 5.1pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.2pt 0pt 1.9pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">146 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.95pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the first place, then we are =
allowed to=20
      postulate very little more luck in subsequent parts of our theory, =
in,=20
      say, the cumulative evolution of brains and intelligence. If we =
don't use=20
      up all our ration of luck in our theory of the origin of life, we =
have=20
      some left over to spend on our theories of subsequent evolution, =
after=20
      cumulative selection has got going. If we want to use up most of =
our=20
      ration of luck in our theory of the origin of intelligence, then =
we=20
      haven't much left over to spend on our theory of the origin of =
life: we=20
      must come up with a theory that makes the origin of life almost=20
      inevitable. Alternatively, if we don't need our whole luck ration =
for=20
      these two stages of our theory, we can, in effect, use the surplus =
to=20
      postulate life elsewhere in the universe. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.55pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">My personal feeling is that, =
once=20
      cumulative selection has got itself properly started, we need to =
postulate=20
      only a relatively small amount of luck in the subsequent evolution =
of life=20
      and intelligence. Cumulative selection, once it has begun, seems =
to me=20
      powerful enough to make the evolution of intelligence probable, if =
not=20
      inevitable. This means that we can, if we want to, spend virtually =
our=20
      entire ration of postulatable luck in one big throw, in our theory =
of the=20
      origin of life on a planet. Therefore we have at our disposal, if =
we want=20
      to use it, odds of 1 in 100 billion billion as an upper limit (or =
1 in=20
      however many available planets we think there are) to spend in our =
theory=20
      of the origin of life. This is the maximum amount of luck we are =
allowed=20
      to postulate in our theory. Suppose we want to suggest, for =
instance, that=20
      life began when both DNA and its protein-based replication =
machinery=20
      spontaneously chanced to come into existence. We can allow =
ourselves the=20
      luxury of such an extravagant theory, provided that the odds =
against this=20
      coincidence occurring on a planet do not exceed 100 billion =
billion to=20
      one. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.8pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">This allowance may seem large. =
It is=20
      probably ample to accommodate the spontaneous arising of DNA or =
RNA. But=20
      it is nowhere near enough to enable us to do without cumulative =
selection=20
      altogether. The odds against assembling a well-designed body that =
flies as=20
      well as a swift, or swims as well as a dolphin, or sees as well as =
a=20
      falcon, in a single blow of luck - single-step selection - are=20
      stupendously greater than the number of atoms in the universe, let =
alone=20
      the number of planets! No, it is certain that we are going to need =
a hefty=20
      measure of cumulative selection in our explanations of life. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.45pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">But although we are entitled, =
in our=20
      theory of the origin of life, to spend a maximum ration of luck =
amounting,=20
      perhaps, to odds of 100 billion billion to one against, my hunch =
is that=20
      we aren't going to need more than a small fraction of that ration. =
The=20
      origin of life on a planet can be a very improbable event indeed =
by our=20
      everyday standards, or </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.45pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D383 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 4.1pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Origins and miracles =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">147 <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.4pt 0pt 0.05in; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">indeed by the standards of the =
chemistry=20
      laboratory, and still be sufficiently probable to have occurred, =
not just=20
      once but many times, all over the universe. We can regard the =
statistical=20
      argument about numbers of planets as an argument of last resort. =
At the=20
      end of the chapter I shall make the paradoxical point that the =
theory we=20
      are looking for may actually </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">need to </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">seem improbable, even =
miraculous, to our=20
      subjective judgement (because of the way our subjective judgement =
has been=20
      made). Nevertheless, it is still sensible for us to begin by =
seeking that=20
      theory of the origin of life with the least degree of =
<BR>improbability.=20
      If the theory that DNA and its copying machinery arose =
spontaneously is so=20
      improbable that it obliges us to assume that life is very rare in =
the=20
      universe, and may even be unique to Earth, our'first resort is to =
try to=20
      find a more probable theory. So, can we come up with any =
speculations=20
      about relatively </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">probable </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">ways in which cumulative =
selection might=20
      have got its start? </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.3pt 0pt 1.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The word 'speculate' has =
pejorative=20
      overtones, but these are quite uncalled for here. We can hope for =
nothing=20
      more than speculation when the events we are talking about took =
place four=20
      billion years ago and took place, moreover, in a world that must =
have been=20
      radically different from that which we know today. For instance, =
there=20
      almost certainly was no free oxygen in the atmosphere. Though the=20
      chemistry of the world may have changed, the </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">laws </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">of chemistry have not changed =
(that's why=20
      they are called laws), and modern chemists know enough about those =
laws to=20
      make some well-informed speculations, speculations that have to =
pass=20
      rigorous tests of plausibility imposed by the laws. You can't just =

      speculate wildly and irresponsibly, allowing your imagination to =
run riot=20
      in the manner of such unsatisfying space fiction panaceas as=20
      'hyperdrives', 'time warps' and 'infinite <BR>improbability =
drives'. Of=20
      all possible speculations about the origin of life, most run foul =
of the=20
      laws of chemistry and can be ruled out, even if we make full use =
of our=20
      statistical fall-back argument about numbers of planets. Careful =
selective=20
      speculation is therefore a constructive exercise. But you do have =
to be a=20
      chemist to do it. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.05pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">I am a biologist not a chemist, =
and I=20
      must rely on chemists to get their sums right. Different chemists =
prefer=20
      different pet theories, and there is no shortage of theories. I =
could=20
      attempt to lay all these theories before you impartially. That =
would be=20
      the proper thing to do in a student textbook. This isn't a student =

      textbook. The basic idea of </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">is that we don't need to =
postulate a=20
      designer in order to understand life, or anything else in the =
universe. We=20
      are here concerned with the </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">kind </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">of solution that must be found, =
because=20
      of the kind of problem we are faced with. I think that this is =
best=20
      explained, </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.05pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D16 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D18 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D16>
      <P class=3DStyle4><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">148 =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D601 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D601>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.4pt 0pt 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 11pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">not by looking at lots of =
particular=20
      theories, but by looking at one as </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">an </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">example of how the basic =
problem - how=20
      cumulative selection got its Start - </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">might </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">be solved. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.85pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Now, which theory to choose as =
my=20
      representative sample? Most textbooks give greatest weight to the =
family=20
      of theories based on an organic 'primeval soup'. It seems probable =
that=20
      the atmosphere of Earth before the coming of life was like that of =
other=20
      planets which are still lifeless. There was no oxygen, plenty of =
hydrogen=20
      and water, carbon dioxide, very likely some ammonia, methane and =
other=20
      simple organic gases. Chemists know that oxygen-free climates like =
this=20
      tend to foster the spontaneous synthesis of organic compounds. =
They have=20
      set up in flasks miniature reconstructions of conditions on the =
early=20
      Earth. They have passed through the flasks electric sparks =
simulating=20
      lightning, and ultraviolet light, which would have been much =
stronger=20
      before the Earth had an ozone layer shielding it from the sun's =
rays. The=20
      results of these experiments have been exciting. Organic =
molecules, some=20
      of them of the same general types as are normally only found in =
living=20
      things, have spontaneously assembled themselves in these flasks. =
Neither=20
      DNA nor RNA has appeared, but the building blocks of these large=20
      molecules, called purines and pyrimidines, have. So have the =
building=20
      blocks of proteins, amino acids. The missing link for this class =
of=20
      theories is still the origin of replication. The building blocks =
haven't=20
      come together to form a self-replicating chain like RNA. Maybe one =
day=20
      they will. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.45pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">But, in any case, the organic=20
      primeval-soup theory is not the one I have chosen for my =
illustration of=20
      the kind of solution that we must look for. I did choose it in my =
first=20
      book, </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The =
Selfish Gene,=20
      so </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">I thought =
that here I=20
      would fly a kite for a somewhat less-fashionable theory (although =
it=20
      recently has started gaining ground), which seems to me to have at =
least a=20
      sporting chance of being right. Its audacity is appealing, and it =
does=20
      illustrate well the properties that any satisfying theory of the =
origin of=20
      life must have. This is the 'inorganic mineral' theory of the =
Glasgow=20
      chemist Graham Cairns-Smith, first proposed 20 years ago and since =

      developed and elaborated in three books, the latest of which,=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Seven Clues to =
the=20
      Origin of Life, </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman">treats=20
      the origin of life as a mystery needing a Sherlock Holmes =
solution.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.1pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Cairns-Smith's view of the =
DNA/protein=20
      machinery is that it probably came into existence relatively =
recently,=20
      perhaps as recently as three billion years ago. Before that there =
were=20
      many generations </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold">of=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">cumulative =
selection,=20
      based upon some quite different replicating entities. Once DNA was =
there,=20
      it proved to be so much more efficient as a replicator, and so =
much more=20
      powerful in its effects on its own </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.1pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D16 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D132 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D16>
      <P class=3DStyle6><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The =
Blind=20
      Watchmaker </SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle6><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D383 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 4.8pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Origins and miracles =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">149 <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 3.85pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">replication, that the original=20
      replication system that spawned it was cast off and forgotten. The =
modem=20
      DNA machinery, according to this view, is a late-comer, a recent =
usurper=20
      of the role of fundamental replicator, having taken over that role =
from an=20
      earlier and cruder replicator. There may even have been a whole =
series of=20
      such usurpations, but the original replication process must have =
been=20
      sufficiently simple to have come about through what I have dubbed=20
      'single-step selection'. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.1pt 0pt 2.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Chemists divide their subject =
into two=20
      main branches, organic and inorganic. Organic chemistry is the =
chemistry=20
      of one particular element, carbon. Inorganic chemistry is all the =
rest.=20
      Carbon is important and deserves to have its own private branch of =

      chemistry, partly because life chemistry is all carbon-chemistry, =
and=20
      partly because those same properties that make carbon-chemistry =
suitable=20
      for life also make it suitable for industrial processes, such as =
those of=20
      the plastics industry. The essential property of carbon atoms that =
makes=20
      them so suitable for life and for industrial synthetics, is that =
they join=20
      together to form a limitless repertoire of different kinds of very =
large=20
      molecules. Another element that has some of these same properties =
is=20
      silicon. Although the chemistry of modern Earth-bound life is all=20
      carbon-chemistry, this may not be true all over the universe, and =
it may=20
      not always have been true on this Earth. Cairns-Smith believes =
that the=20
      original life on this planet was based on self-replicating =
inorganic=20
      crystals such as silicates. If this is true, organic replicators, =
and=20
      eventually DNA, must later have taken over or usurped the role.=20
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.2pt 0pt 1.45pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">He gives some arguments for the =
general=20
      plausibility of this idea of 'takeover'. An arch of stones, for =
instance,=20
      is a stable structure capable of standing for many years even if =
there is=20
      no cement to bind it. Building a complex structure by evolution is =
like=20
      trying to build a mortarless arch if you are allowed to touch only =
one=20
      stone at a time. Think about the task naively, and it can't be =
done. The=20
      arch will stand once the last stone is in place, but the =
intermediate=20
      stages are unstable. It's quite easy to build the arch, however, =
if you=20
      are allowed to subtract stones as well as add them. Start by =
building a=20
      solid heap of stones, then build the arch resting on top of this =
solid=20
      foundation. Then, when the arch is all in position, including the =
vital=20
      keystone at the top, carefully remove the supporting stones and, =
with a=20
      modicum of luck, the arch will remain standing. Stonehenge is=20
      incomprehensible until we realize that the builders used some kind =
of=20
      scaffolding, or perhaps ramps of earth, </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">which are no longer there.=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">We can see =
only the=20
      endproduct, and have to infer the vanished scaffolding. Similarly, =
DNA and=20
      protein are two pillars of a stable and elegant arch, which =
persists=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.2pt 0pt 1.45pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D16 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D18 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D16>
      <P class=3DStyle4><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">150 =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D600 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D600>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.7pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">once all its parts =
simultaneously exist.=20
      It is hard to imagine it arising by any step-by-step process =
unless some=20
      earlier scaffolding has completely disappeared. That scaffolding =
must=20
      itself have been built by an earlier form of cumulative selection, =
at=20
      whose nature we can only guess. But it must have been based upon=20
      replicating entities with power over their own future. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.3pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Cairns-Smith's guess is that =
the original=20
      replicators were crystals of inorganic materials, such as those =
found in=20
      clays and muds. A crystal is just a large orderly array of atoms =
or=20
      molecules in the solid state. Because of properties that we can =
think of=20
      as their 'shape', atoms and small molecules tend naturally to pack =

      themselves together in a fixed and orderly manner. It is almost as =
though=20
      they 'want' to slot together in a particular way, but this =
illusion is=20
      just an inadvertent consequence of their properties. Their =
'preferred' way=20
      of slotting together shapes the whole crystal. It also means that, =
even in=20
      a large crystal such as a diamond, any part of the crystal is=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">exactly =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the same as any other part, =
except where=20
      there are flaws. If we could shrink ourselves to the atomic scale, =
we=20
      would see almost endless rows of atoms, stretching to the horizon =
in=20
      straight lines - galleries of geometric repetition. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.95pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Since it is replication we are =
interested=20
      in, the first thing we must know is, can crystals replicate their=20
      structure? Crystals are made of myriads of layers of atoms (or=20
      equivalent), and each layer builds upon the layer below. Atoms (or =
ions;=20
      the difference needn't concern us) float around free in solution, =
but if=20
      they happen to encounter a crystal they have a natural tendency to =
slot=20
      into position on the surface of the crystal. A solution of common =
salt=20
      contains sodium ions and chloride ions jostling about in a more or =
less=20
      chaotic fashion. A crystal of common salt is a packed, orderly =
array of=20
      sodium ions alternating with chloride ions at right angles to one =
another.=20
      When ions floating in the water happen to bump into the hard =
surface of=20
      the crystal, they tend to stick. And they stick in just the right =
places=20
      to cause a new layer to be added to the crystal just like the =
layer below.=20
      So once a crystal gets started it grows, each layer being the same =
as the=20
      layer below. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.6pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Sometimes crystals =
spontaneously start to=20
      form in solution. At other times they have to be 'seeded', either =
by=20
      particles of dust or by small crystals dropped in from elsewhere.=20
      Caims-Smith invites us to perform the following experiment. =
Dissolve a=20
      large quantity of photographer's 'hypo' fixer in very hot water. =
Then let=20
      the solution cool down, being careful not to let any dust drop in. =
The=20
      solution is now 'supersaturated', ready and waiting to make =
crystals, but=20
      with no </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.6pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D16 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D133 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D16>
      <P class=3DStyle6><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The =
Blind=20
      Watchmaker </SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle6><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D384 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle19 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 4.8pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Origins and miracles =
</SPAN></I>151=20
      <BR><BR></P>
      <P class=3DStyle18 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.1pt 0pt 4.3pt">seed =
crystals to=20
      start the process going. I quote from Cairns-Smith's <I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Seven Clues to the Origin of =
Life:=20
      </SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 8.65pt 0pt 13.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 9.85pt">Carefully=20
      take the lid off the beaker, drop one tiny piece of 'hypo' crystal =
onto=20
      the surface of the solution, and watch amazed at what happens. =
Your=20
      crystal grows visibly: it breaks up from time to time and the =
pieces also=20
      grow . . . Soon your beaker is crowded with crystals, some several =

      centimetres long. Then after a few minutes it all stops. The magic =

      solution has lost its power - although if you want another =
performance=20
      just re-heat and re-cool the beaker . . . to be supersaturated =
means to=20
      have more dissolved than there ought to be . . . the cold =
supersaturated=20
      solution almost literally did not know what to do. It had to be =
'told' by=20
      adding a piece of crystal that already had its units (billions and =

      billions of them) packed together in the way that is =
characteristic for=20
      'hypo' crystals. The solution had to be seeded. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.05pt 0pt 2.15pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt">Some=20
      chemical substances have the potential to crystallize in two =
alternative=20
      ways. Graphite and diamonds, for instance, are both crystals of =
pure=20
      carbon. Their atoms are identical. The two substances differ from =
each=20
      other only in the geometric pattern with which the carbon atoms =
are=20
      packed. In diamonds, the carbon atoms are packed in a tetrahedral =
pattern=20
      which is extremely stable. This is why diamonds are so hard. In =
graphite=20
      the carbon atoms are arranged in flat hexagons layered on top of =
each=20
      other. The bonding between layers is weak, and they therefore =
slide over=20
      each other, which is why graphite feels slippery and is used as a=20
      lubricant. Unfortunately you can't crystallize diamonds out of a =
solution=20
      by seeding them, as you can with hypo. If you could, you'd be =
rich; no on=20
      second thoughts you wouldn't, because any fool could do the same. =
</P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.75pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt">Now=20
      suppose we have a supersaturated solution of some substance, like =
hypo in=20
      that it was eager to crystallize out of solution, and like carbon =
in that=20
      it was capable of crystallizing in either of two ways. One way =
might be=20
      somewhat like graphite, with the atoms arranged in layers, leading =
to=20
      little flat crystals; while the other way gives chunky, =
diamond-shaped=20
      crystals. Now we simultaneously drop into our supersaturated =
solution a=20
      tiny flat crystal and a tiny chunky crystal. We can describe what =
would=20
      happen in an elaboration of Calms-Smith's description of his hypo=20
      experiment. You watch amazed at what happens. Your two crystals =
grow=20
      visibly: they break up from time to time and the pieces also grow. =
Flat=20
      crystals give rise to a population of flat crystals. Chunky =
crystals give=20
      rise to a population of chunky crystals. If there is any tendency =
for one=20
      type of crystal to grow and split more quickly than the other, we =
shall=20
      have a simple kind of natural selection. But the process still =
lacks a=20
      vital ingredient in order to give </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.75pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D16 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D18 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D16>
      <P class=3DStyle4><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">152 =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D600 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D380 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D600>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.6pt 0pt 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">rise to evolutionary change. =
That=20
      ingredient is hereditary variation, </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">or </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">something equivalent to =
it.Instead of=20
      just two types of crystal, there must be a whole range of minor =
variants=20
      that form lineages of like shape, and that sometimes 'mutate' to =
produce=20
      new shapes. Do </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold">real=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">crystals have =
something=20
      corresponding to hereditary mutation? </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.7pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Clays and muds and rocks are =
made of tiny=20
      crystals. They are abundant on Earth and probably always have =
been. When=20
      you look at the surface of some types of clay and other minerals =
with a=20
      scanning electron microscope you see an amazing and beautiful =
sight.=20
      Crystals grow like rows of flowers or cactuses, gardens of =
inorganic rose=20
      petals, tiny spirals like cross-sections of succulent plants, =
bristling=20
      organ pipes, complicated angular shapes folded as if in miniature=20
      crystalline origami, writhing growths like worm casts or squeezed=20
      toothpaste. The ordered patterns become even more striking at =
greater=20
      levels of magnification. At levels that betray the actual position =
of=20
      atoms, the surface of a crystal is seen to have all the regularity =
of a=20
      <BR>machinewoven piece of herringbone tweed. But - and here is the =
vital=20
      point - there are flaws. Right in the middle of an expanse of =
orderly=20
      herringbone there can be a patch, identical to the rest except =
that it is=20
      twisted round at a different angle so that the 'weave' goes off in =
another=20
      direction. Or the weave may lie in the same direction, but each =
row has=20
      'slipped' half a row to one side. Nearly all naturally occurring =
crystals=20
      have flaws. And once a flaw has appeared, it tends to be copied as =

      subsequent layers of crystal encrust themselves on top of it. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
1.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Flaws can occur anywhere over =
the surface=20
      of a crystal. If you like thinking about capacity for information =
storage=20
      (I do), you can imagine the enormous number of different patterns =
of flaws=20
      that could be created over the surface of a crystal. All those=20
      calculations about packing the New Testament into the DNA of a =
single=20
      bacterium could be done just as impressively for almost any =
crystal. What=20
      DNA has over normal crystals is a means by which its information =
can be=20
      read. Leaving aside the problem of read-out, you could easily =
devise an=20
      arbitrary code whereby flaws in the atomic structure of the =
crystal denote=20
      binary numbers. You could then pack several New Testaments into a =
mineral=20
      crystal the size of a pin's head. On a larger scale, this is =
essentially=20
      how music information is stored on the surface of a laser =
('compact')=20
      disc. The musical notes are converted, by computer, into binary =
numbers. A=20
      laser is used to etch a pattern of tiny flaws in the otherwise =
glassy=20
      smooth surface of the disc. Each little hole etched corresponds to =
a=20
      binary 1 (or a 0, the labels are arbitrary). When you play the =
disc,=20
      another laser beam 'reads' the pattern of flaws, and a =
special-purpose=20
      computer built into the player turns the binary </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
1.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D17 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D132 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D17>
      <P class=3DStyle9><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The =
Blind=20
      Watchmaker </SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle9><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D386 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 5.75pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Origins and miracles =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">153 <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.6pt 0pt 4.8pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">numbers back into sound =
vibrations, which=20
      are amplified so that you can hear them. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.85pt 0pt 4.3pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Although laser discs are used =
today=20
      mainly for music, you could pack the whole </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Encyclopaedia Britannica=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">onto one of =
them, and=20
      read it out using the same laser technique. Flaws in crystals at =
the=20
      atomic level are far smaller than the pits etched in a laser =
disc's=20
      surface, so crystals can potentially pack more information into a =
given=20
      area. Indeed DNA molecules, whose capacity for storing information =
has=20
      already impressed us, are something close to crystals themselves. =
Although=20
      clay crystals theoretically could store the same prodigious =
quantities of=20
      information as DNA or laser discs can, nobody is suggesting that =
they ever=20
      did. The role of clay and other mineral crystals in the theory is =
to act=20
      as the original 'low-tech' replicators, the ones that were =
eventually=20
      replaced by high-tech DNA. They form spontaneously in the waters =
of our=20
      planet without the elaborate 'machinery' that DNA needs; and they =
develop=20
      flaws spontaneously, some of which can be replicated in subsequent =
layers=20
      of crystal. If fragments of suitably flawed crystal later broke =
away, we=20
      could imagine them acting as 'seeds' for new crystals, each one=20
      'inheriting' its 'parent's' pattern of flaws. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.3pt 0pt 1.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">So, we have a speculative =
picture of=20
      mineral crystals on the primeval Earth showing some of the =
properties of=20
      replication, multiplication, heredity and mutation that would have =
been=20
      necessary in order for a form of cumulative selection to get =
started.=20
      There is still the missing ingredient of 'power': the nature of =
the=20
      replicators must somehow have influenced their own likelihood of =
being=20
      replicated. When we were talking about replicators in the =
abstract, we saw=20
      that 'power' might simply be direct properties of the replicator =
itself,=20
      intrinsic properties like 'stickiness'. At this elementary level, =
the name=20
      'power' seems scarcely justified. I use it only because of what it =
can=20
      become in later stages of evolution: the power of a snake's fang, =
for=20
      instance, to <BR>propagate (by its indirect consequences on snake=20
      survival) DNA coding for fangs. Whether the original low-tech =
replicators=20
      were mineral crystals or organic direct forerunners of DNA itself, =
we may=20
      guess that the 'power' they exercised was direct and elementary, =
like=20
      stickiness. Advanced levers of power, like a snake's fang or an =
orchid's=20
      flower, came far later. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 5.4pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">What might 'power' mean to a =
clay? What=20
      incidental properties of the clay could influence the likelihood =
that it,=20
      the same variety of clay, would be propagated around the =
countryside?=20
      Clays are made from chemical building blocks such as silicic acid =
and=20
      metal ions, which are in solution in rivers and streams having =
been=20
      dissolved - 'weathered' =97 </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 5.4pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D16 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D18 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D16>
      <P class=3DStyle4><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">154 =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D602 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D392 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D602>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 9.2pt 0pt 0.95pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">out of rocks further upstream. =
If=20
      conditions are right they crystallize out of solution again =
downstream,=20
      forming clays. (Actually the 'stream', in this case, is more =
likely to=20
      mean the seeping and trickling of the groundwater than a rushing =
open=20
      river. But, for simplicity, I shall continue to use the general =
word=20
      stream.) Whether or not a particular type of clay crystal is =
allowed to=20
      build up depends, among other things, upon the rate and pattern of =
flow of=20
      the stream. But deposits of clay can also </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">influence </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the flow of the stream. They do =
this=20
      inadvertently by changing the level, shape and texture of the =
ground=20
      through which the water is flowing. Consider a variant of clay =
that just=20
      happens to have the property of reshaping the structure of the =
soil so=20
      that the flow Speeds up. The consequence is that the clay =
concerned gets=20
      washed away again. This kind of clay, by definition, is not very=20
      'successful'. Another unsuccessful clay would be one that changed =
the flow=20
      in such <BR>a way that a rival variant of clay was favoured. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.8pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
9.5pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">We aren't, of course, =
suggesting that=20
      clays 'want' to go on existing. Always we are talking only about=20
      incidental consequences, events which follow from properties that =
the=20
      replicator just happens to have. Consider yet another variant of =
clay.=20
      This one happens to slow down the flow in such a way that future=20
      deposition of its </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">own=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">kind of clay =
is=20
      enhanced. Obviously this second variant will tend to become =
<BR>common,=20
      because it happens to manipulate streams to its own 'advantage'. =
This will=20
      be a 'successful' variant of clay. But so far we are dealing only =
with=20
      single-step selection. Could a form of cumulative selection get =
going?=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 9.6pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">To speculate a little further, =
suppose=20
      that a variant of a clay improves its own chances of being =
deposited, by=20
      damming up streams. This is an inadvertent consequence of the =
peculiar=20
      defect structure of the clay. In any stream in which this kind of =
clay=20
      exists, large, stagnant shallow pools form above dams, and the =
main flow=20
      of water is diverted into a new course. In these still pools, more =
of the=20
      same kind of clay is laid down. A succession of such shallow pools =

      proliferates along the length of any stream that happens to be =
'infected'=20
      by seeding crystals of this kind of clay. Now, because the main =
flow of=20
      the stream is diverted, during the dry season the shallow pools =
tend to=20
      dry up. The clay dries and cracks in the sun, and the top layers =
are blown=20
      off as dust. Each dust particle inherits the characteristic defect =

      structure of the parent clay that did the damming, the structure =
that gave=20
      it its damming properties. By analogy with the genetic information =
raining=20
      down on the canal from my willow tree, we could say that the dust =
carries=20
      'instructions' for how to dam streams and eventually make more =
dust. The=20
      dust spreads far and wide in the wind, and there is a good chance=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 9.6pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D16 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D133 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D16>
      <P class=3DStyle6><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The =
Blind=20
      Watchmaker </SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle6><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D385 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 5.75pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Origins and miracles =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">155 <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05pt 0pt 4.8pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.5pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">that some particles of it will =
happen to=20
      land in another stream, hitherto not 'infected' with the seeds of =
this=20
      kind of dam-making clay. Once infected by the right sort of dust, =
a new=20
      stream starts to grow crystals of dam-making clay, and the whole=20
      depositing, damming, drying, eroding cycle begins again. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.25pt 0pt 3.85pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">To call this a 'life' cycle =
would be to=20
      beg an important question, but it is a cycle of a sort, and it =
shares with=20
      true life cycles the ability to initiate cumulative selection. =
Because=20
      streams are infected by dust 'seeds' blown from other streams, we =
can=20
      arrange the streams in an order of 'ancestry' and 'descent'. The =
clay that=20
      is damming up pools in stream B arrived there in the form of dust =
crystals=20
      blown from stream <BR>A. Eventually, the pools of stream B will =
dry up and=20
      make dust, which will infect streams F and P. With respect to the =
source=20
      of their dammaking clay, we can arrange streams into 'family =
trees'. Every=20
      infected stream has a 'parent' stream, and it may have more than =
one=20
      'daughter' stream. Each stream is analogous to a body, whose =
'development'=20
      is influenced by dust seed 'genes', a body that eventually spawns =
new dust=20
      seeds. Each 'generation' in the cycle starts when seed crystals =
break away=20
      from the parent stream in the form of dust. The crystalline =
structure of=20
      each particle of dust is copied from the clay in the parent =
stream. It=20
      passes on that crystalline structure to the daughter stream, where =
it=20
      grows and multiplies and finally sends 'seeds' out again. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.65pt 0pt 1.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The ancestral crystal structure =
is=20
      preserved down the generations unless there is an occasional =
mistake in=20
      crystal growth, an occasional alteration in the pattern of laying =
down of=20
      atoms. Subsequent layers of the same crystal will copy the same =
flaw, and=20
      if the crystal breaks in two it will give rise to a sub-population =
of=20
      altered crystals. Now if the alteration makes the crystal either =
less or=20
      more efficient in the damming/drying/erosion cycle, this will =
affect how=20
      many copies it has in subsequent 'generations'. Altered crystals =
might,=20
      for instance, be more likely to split ('reproduce'). Clay formed =
from=20
      altered crystals might have greater damming power in any of a =
variety of=20
      detailed ways. It might crack more readily in a given amount of =
sun. It=20
      might crumble into dust more readily. The dust particles might be =
better=20
      at catching the wind, like fluff on a willow seed. Some crystal =
types=20
      might induce a shortening of the 'life cycle', consequently a =
speeding up=20
      of their 'evolution'. There are many opportunities for successive=20
      'generations' to become progressively 'better' at getting passed =
to=20
      subsequent generations. In other words, there are many =
opportunities for=20
      rudimentary cumulative selection to get going. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5 style=3D"MARGIN-RIGHT: 5.9pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">These little flights of fancy,=20
      embellishments of Cairns-Smith's </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">own, </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">concern only one of several =
kinds of=20
      mineral 'life cycle' that </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">could have </SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5 style=3D"MARGIN-RIGHT: 5.9pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D385 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3pt 0pt 2.65pt"><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">156 </SPAN></B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.8pt 0pt 1.7pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">started cumulative selection =
along its=20
      momentous road. There are others. Different varieties of crystals =
might=20
      earn their passage to new streams, not by crumbling into dust =
'seeds', but=20
      by dissecting their streams into lots of little streamlets that =
spread=20
      around, eventually joining and infecting new river systems. Some =
varieties=20
      might engineer waterfalls that wear down the rocks faster, and =
hence speed=20
      into solution the raw materials needed to make new clays further=20
      downstream. Some varieties of crystal might better themselves by =
making=20
      conditions hard for 'rival' varieties that compete for raw =
materials. Some=20
      varieties might become 'predatory', breaking up rival varieties =
and using=20
      their elements as raw materials. Keep holding in mind that there =
is no=20
      suggestion of 'deliberate' engineering, either here or in modern,=20
      DNA-based life. It is just that the world automatically tends to =
become=20
      full of those varieties of clay (or DNA) that </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">happen to </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">have properties that make them =
persist=20
      and spread themselves about. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.05pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Now to move on to the next =
stage of the=20
      argument. Some lineages of crystals might happen to catalyse the =
synthesis=20
      of new substances that assist in their passage down the =
'generations'.=20
      These secondary substances would not (not at first, anyway) have =
had their=20
      own lineages of ancestry and descent, but would have been =
manufactured=20
      anew by each generation of primary replicators. They could be seen =
as=20
      tools of the replicating crystal lineages, the beginnings of =
primitive=20
      'phenotypes'. Cairns-Smith believes that </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">organic </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">molecules were <BR>prominent =
among=20
      non-replicating 'tools' of his inorganic crystalline replicators. =
Organic=20
      molecules frequently are used in the commercial inorganic chemical =

      industry because of their effects on the flow of fluids, and on =
the=20
      break-up or growth of inorganic particles: just the sorts of =
effects, in=20
      short, that could have influenced the 'success' of lineages of =
replicating=20
      crystals. For instance, a clay mineral with the lovely name=20
      montmorillonite tends to break up in the presence of small amounts =
of an=20
      organic molecule with the less-lovely name carboxymethyl =
cellulose.=20
      Smaller quantities of carboxymethyl cellulose, on the other hand, =
have=20
      just the opposite effect, helping to stick montmorillonite =
particles=20
      together. Tannins, another kind of organic molecule, are used in =
the oil=20
      industry to make muds easier to drill. If oil-drillers can exploit =
organic=20
      molecules to manipulate the flow and drillability of mud, there is =
no=20
      reason why cumulative selection should not have led to the same =
kind of=20
      exploitation by selfreplicating minerals. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
4.8pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">At this point Cairns-Smith's =
theory gets=20
      a sort of free bonus of added plausibility. It so happens that =
other=20
      chemists, supporting more conventional organic 'primeval soup' =
theories,=20
      have long accepted that </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
4.8pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D6 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D21 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D6>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D6=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image063.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D21></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D383 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.05in"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Origins and miracles =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">157 <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.5pt 0pt 2.65pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">clay minerals would have been a =
help. To=20
      quote one of them (D. M. Anderson), 'It is widely accepted that =
some,=20
      perhaps many, of the abiotic chemical reactions and processes =
leading to=20
      the origin on Earth of replicating micro-organisms occurred very =
early in=20
      the history of Earth in close proximity to the surfaces of clay =
minerals=20
      and other inorganic substrates.' This writer goes on to list five=20
      'functions' of clay minerals in assisting the origin of organic =
life, for=20
      instance ' Concentration of chemical reactants by adsorption'. We =
needn't=20
      spell the five out here, or even understand them. From our point =
of view,=20
      what matters is that each of these five 'functions' of clay =
minerals can=20
      be twisted round the other way. It shows the close association =
that can=20
      exist between organic chemical synthesis and clay surfaces. It is=20
      <BR>therefore a bonus for the theory that clay replicators =
synthesized=20
      organic molecules and used them for their own purposes. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.85pt 0pt 1.45pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.55pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Cairns-Smith discusses, in more =
detail=20
      than I can accommodate here, early uses that his clay-crystal =
replicators=20
      might have had for proteins, sugars and, most important of all, =
nucleic=20
      acids like RNA. He suggests that RNA was first used for purely =
structural=20
      purposes, as oil drillers use tannins or we use soap and =
detergents.=20
      RNA-like molecules, because of their negatively charged backbones, =
would=20
      tend to coat the outsides of clay particles. This is getting us =
into=20
      realms of chemistry that are beyond our scope. For our purposes =
what=20
      matters is that RNA, or something like it, was around for a long =
time=20
      before it became self-replicating. When it finally did become=20
      self-replicating, this was a device evolved by the mineral crystal =
'genes'=20
      to improve the efficiency of manufacture of the RNA (or similar =
molecule).=20
      But, once a new self-replicating molecule had come into existence, =
a new=20
      kind of cumulative selection could get going. Originally a =
side-show, the=20
      new replicators turned out to be so much more efficient than the =
original=20
      crystals that they took over. They evolved further, and eventually =

      perfected the DNA code that we know today. The original mineral=20
      replicators were cast aside like worn-out scaffolding, and all =
modern life=20
      evolved from a relatively recent common ancestor, with a single, =
uniform=20
      genetic system and a largely uniform biochemistry. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.5pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">In </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Selfish Gene =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">I speculated that we may now be =
on the=20
      threshold of a new kind of genetic takeover. DNA replicators built =

      'survival machines' for themselves - the bodies of living =
organisms=20
      including ourselves. As part of their equipment, bodies evolved =
onboard=20
      computers - brains. Brains evolved the capacity to communicate =
with other=20
      brains by means of language and cultural traditions. But the new =
milieu of=20
      cultural tradition opens up new possibilities for selfreplicating=20
      entities. The new replicators are not DNA and they are not =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.5pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D380 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 3.85pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">158 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05pt 0pt 2.9pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">clay crystals. They are =
patterns of=20
      information that can thrive only in brains or the artificially=20
      manufactured products of brains =97 books, computers, and so on. =
But, given=20
      that brains, books and computers exist, these new replicators, =
which I=20
      called memes to distinguish them from genes, can propagate =
themselves from=20
      brain to brain, from brain to book, from book to brain, from brain =
to=20
      computer, from computer to computer. As they propagate they can =
change -=20
      mutate. And perhaps 'mutant' memes can exert the kinds of =
influence that I=20
      am here calling 'replicator power'. Remember that this means any =
kind of=20
      influence affecting their own likelihood of being propagated. =
Evolution=20
      under the influence of the new replicators - memic evolution - is =
in its=20
      infancy. It is manifested in the phenomena that we call cultural=20
      evolution. Cultural evolution is many orders of magnitude faster =
than=20
      <BR>DNAbased evolution, which sets one even more to thinking of =
the idea=20
      of <BR>'takeover'. And if a new kind of replicator takeover is =
beginning,=20
      it is conceivable that it will take off so far as to leave its =
parent DNA=20
      (and its grandparent clay if Cairns-Smith is right) far behind. If =
so, we=20
      may be sure that computers will be in the van. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.5pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Could it be that one far-off =
day=20
      intelligent computers will speculate about their own lost origins? =
Will=20
      one of them tumble to the heretical truth, that they have sprung =
from a=20
      remote, earlier form of life, rooted in organic, carbon chemistry, =
rather=20
      than the silicon-based electronic principles of their own bodies? =
Will a=20
      robotic Cairns-Smith write a book called </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Electronic Takeover! =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Will he rediscover some =
electronic=20
      equivalent of the metaphor of the arch, and realize that computers =
could=20
      not have sprung spontaneously into existence but must have =
originated from=20
      some earlier process of cumulative selection? Will he go into =
detail and=20
      reconstruct DNA as a plausible early replicator, victim of =
electronic=20
      usurpation? And will he be far-sighted enough to guess that even =
DNA may=20
      itself have been a usurper of yet more remote and primitive =
replicators,=20
      crystals of inorganic silicates? If he is of a poetic turn of =
mind, will=20
      he even see a kind of justice in the eventual return to =
silicon-based=20
      life, with DNA no more than an interlude, albeit one that lasted =
longer=20
      than three aeons? </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.4pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">That is science fiction, and it =
probably=20
      sounds far-fetched. That doesn't matter. Of more immediate moment =
is that=20
      Cairns-Smith's own theory, and indeed all other theories of the =
origin of=20
      life, may sound far-fetched to you and hard to believe. Do you =
find both=20
      Cairns-Smith's clay theory, and the more orthodox organic =
<BR>primevalsoup=20
      theory, wildly improbable? Does it sound to you as though it would =
need a=20
      miracle to make randomly jostling atoms join together into a=20
      self-replicating molecule? Well, at times it does to me too. But=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.4pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D9 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D51 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D9>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D9=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image064.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D52></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D380 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 3.35pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Origins and miracles =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">159 <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.1pt 0pt 2.4pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">let's look more deeply into =
this matter=20
      of miracles and improbability. By doing so, I shall demonstrate a =
point=20
      which is paradoxical but all the more interesting for that. This =
is that=20
      we should, as scientists, be even a little worried if the origin =
of life=20
      did </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">not =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">seem miraculous to our own =
human=20
      consciousness. An apparently (to ordinary human consciousness) =
miraculous=20
      theory is </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">exactly=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the kind of =
theory we=20
      should be looking for in this particular matter of the origin of =
life.=20
      This argument, which amounts to a discussion of what we mean by a =
miracle,=20
      will occupy the rest of this chapter. In a way it is an extension =
of the=20
      argument we made earlier about billions of planets. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.2pt 0pt 1.45pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.55pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">So, what do we mean by a =
miracle? A=20
      miracle is something that happens, but which is exceedingly =
surprising. If=20
      a marble statue of the Virgin Mary suddenly waved its hand at us =
we should=20
      treat it as a miracle, because all our experience and knowledge =
tells us=20
      that marble doesn't behave like that. I have just uttered the =
words 'May I=20
      be struck by lightning this minute'. If lightning did strike me in =
the=20
      same minute, it would be treated as a miracle. But actually =
neither of=20
      these two occurrences would be classified by science as utterly=20
      impossible. They would simply be judged very improbable, the =
waving statue=20
      much more improbable than the lightning. Lightning does strike =
people. Any=20
      one of us might be struck by lightning, but the probability is =
pretty low=20
      in any one minute (although the </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Guinness Book of Records=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">has a charming =
picture=20
      of a Virginian man, nicknamed the human lightning conductor, =
recovering in=20
      hospital from his seventh lightning strike, with an expression of=20
      apprehensive bewilderment on his face). The only thing miraculous =
about my=20
      hypothetical story is the </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">coincidence </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">between my being struck by =
lightning and=20
      my verbal invocation of the disaster. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.35pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.8pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Coincidence means multiplied=20
      improbability. The probability of my being struck by lightning in =
any one=20
      minute of my life is perhaps 1 in 10 million as a conservative =
estimate.=20
      The probability of my inviting a lightning strike in any =
particular minute=20
      is also very low. I have just done it for the only time in the =
23,400,000=20
      minutes of my life so far, and I doubt if I'll do it again, so =
call these=20
      odds one in 25 million. To calculate the joint probability of the=20
      coincidence occurring in any one minute we multiply the two =
separate=20
      probabilities. For my rough calculation this comes to about one in =
250=20
      trillion. If a coincidence of this magnitude happened to me, I =
should call=20
      it a miracle and would watch my language in future. But although =
the odds=20
      against the coincidence are extremely high, we can still calculate =
them.=20
      They </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">are =
</SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">not literally zero. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.45pt 0pt 9.1pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">In the case of the marble =
statue,=20
      molecules </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">in=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">solid marble=20
      </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">are =
</SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.45pt 0pt 9.1pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.45pt 0pt 2.4pt"><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">160 </SPAN></B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.45pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">continuously jostling against =
one another=20
      in random directions. The jostlings of the different molecules =
cancel one=20
      another out, so the whole hand of the statue stays still. But if, =
by sheer=20
      coincidence, all the molecules just happened to move in the same =
direction=20
      at the same moment, the hand would move. If they then all reversed =

      direction at the same moment the hand would move back. In this way =
it is=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">possible=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">for a marble =
statue to=20
      wave at us. It could happen. The odds against such a coincidence =
are=20
      unimaginably great but they are not incalculably great. A =
physicist=20
      colleague has kindly calculated them for me. The number is so =
large that=20
      the entire age of the universe so far is too short a time to write =
out all=20
      the noughts! It is theoretically possible for a cow to jump over =
the moon=20
      with something like the same improbability. The conclusion to this =
part of=20
      the argument is that we can </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">calculate </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">our way into regions of =
miraculous=20
      improbability far greater than we can </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">imagine </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">as plausible. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.05pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Let's look at this matter of =
what we=20
      think is plausible. What we can imagine as plausible is a narrow =
band in=20
      the middle of a much broader spectrum of what is actually =
possible.=20
      Sometimes it is narrower than what is actually there. There is a =
good=20
      analogy with light. Our eyes are built to cope with a narrow band =
of=20
      electromagnetic frequencies (the ones we call light), somewhere in =
the=20
      middle of the spectrum from long radio waves at one end to short =
X-rays at=20
      the other. We can't see the rays outside the narrow light band, =
but we can=20
      do calculations about them, and we can build instruments to detect =
them.=20
      In the same way, we know that the scales of size and time extend =
in both=20
      directions far outside the realm of what we can visualize. Our =
minds can't=20
      cope with the large distances that astronomy deals in or with the =
small=20
      distances that atomic physics deals in, but we can represent those =

      distances in mathematical symbols. Our minds can't imagine a time =
span as=20
      short as a picosecond, but we can do calculations about =
picoseconds, and=20
      we can build computers that can complete calculations within =
picoseconds.=20
      Our minds can't imagine a timespan as long as a million years, let =
alone=20
      the thousands of millions of years that geologists routinely =
compute.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
1.4pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Just as our eyes can see only =
that narrow=20
      band of electromagnetic frequencies that natural selection =
equipped our=20
      ancestors to see, so our brains are built to cope with narrow =
bands of=20
      sizes and times. Presumably there was no need for our ancestors to =
cope=20
      with sizes and times outside the narrow range of everyday =
practicality, so=20
      our brains never evolved the capacity to imagine them. It is =
probably=20
      significant that our own body size of a few feet is roughly in the =
middle=20
      of the range of sizes we can imagine. And our own lifetime of a =
few=20
      decades is roughly in the middle of the range of times we can =
imagine.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.8pt 0pt 9.85pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">We can say the same kind of =
thing about=20
      improbabilities and miracles. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.8pt 0pt 9.85pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D9 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D67 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D9>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D9=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image065.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D67></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D381 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle5 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 2.9pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Origins and miracles =
</SPAN></I><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">161 </SPAN></B><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.4pt 0pt 2.4pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Picture a graduated scale of=20
      improbabilities, analogous to the scale of sizes from atoms to =
galaxies,=20
      or to the scale of times from picoseconds to aeons. On the scale =
we mark=20
      off various landmark points. At the far left-hand end of the scale =
are=20
      events which are all but certain, such as the probability that the =
sun=20
      will rise tomorrow =97 the subject of G. H. Hardy's halfpenny bet. =
Near this=20
      left-hand end of the scale are things that are only slightly =
improbable,=20
      such as shaking a double six in a single throw of a pair of dice. =
The odds=20
      of this happening are 1 in 36.1 expect we've all done it quite =
often.=20
      Moving towards the right-hand end of the spectrum, another =
landmark point=20
      is the probability of a perfect deal in bridge, where each of the =
four=20
      players receives a <BR>complete suit of cards. The odds against =
this=20
      happening are 2,235,197,406,895,366,368,301,559,999 to 1. Let us =
call this=20
      one dealion, the unit of improbability. If something with an =
improbability=20
      of one dealion was predicted and then happened, we should diagnose =
a=20
      miracle unless, which is more probable, we suspected fraud. But it =

      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">could =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">happen with a fair deal, and it =
is far=20
      far far more probable than the marble statue's waving at us. =
Nevertheless,=20
      even this latter event, as we have seen, has its rightful place =
along the=20
      spectrum of events that could happen. It is measurable, albeit in =
units=20
      far larger than gigadealions. Between the double-six dice throw, =
and the=20
      perfect deal at bridge, is a range of more or less improbable =
events that=20
      do sometimes happen, including any one individual's being struck =
by=20
      lightning, winning a big prize on the football pools, scoring a =
hole-=20
      inone at golf, and so on. Somewhere in this range, too, are those=20
      coincidences that give us an eerie spine-tingling feeling, like =
dreaming=20
      of a particular person for the first time in decades, then waking =
up to=20
      find that they died in the night. These eerie coincidences are =
very=20
      impressive when they happen to us or to one of our friends, but =
their=20
      improbability is measured in only picodealions. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.35pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Having constructed our =
mathematical scale=20
      of improbabilities, with its benchmark or landmark points marked =
on it,=20
      let us now turn a spotlight on that subrange of the scale with =
which we,=20
      in our ordinary thought and conversation, can cope. The width of =
the=20
      spotlight's beam is analogous to the narrow range of =
electromagnetic=20
      frequencies that our eyes can see, or to the narrow range of sizes =
or=20
      times, close to our own size and longevity, that we can imagine. =
On the=20
      spectrum of improbabilities, the spotlight turns out to illuminate =
only=20
      the narrow range from the left-hand end (certainty) up to minor =
miracles,=20
      like a hole-in-one or a dream that comes true. There is a vast =
range of=20
      mathematically calculable improbabilities way outside the range of =
the=20
      spotlight. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.35pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D380 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.2pt 0pt 2.9pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">162 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Our brains have been built by =
natural=20
      selection to assess probability and risk, just as our eyes have =
been built=20
      to assess electromagnetic wavelength. We are equipped to make =
mental=20
      calculations of risk and odds, within the range of improbabilities =
that=20
      would be useful in human life. This means risks of the order of, =
say,=20
      being gored by a buffalo if we shoot an arrow at it, being struck =
by=20
      lightning if we shelter under a lone tree in a thunderstorm, or =
drowning=20
      if we try to swim across a river. These acceptable risks are =
commensurate=20
      with our lifetimes of a few decades. If we were biologically =
capable of=20
      living for a million years, and wanted to do so, we should assess =
risks=20
      quite differently. We should make a habit of not crossing roads, =
for=20
      instance, for if you crossed a road every day for half a million =
years you=20
      would undoubtedly be run over. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.45pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Evolution has equipped our =
brains with a=20
      subjective consciousness of risk and improbability suitable for =
creatures=20
      with a lifetime of less than one century. Our ancestors have =
always needed=20
      to take decisions involving risks and probabilities, and natural =
selection=20
      has therefore equipped our brains to assess probabilities against =
a=20
      background of the short lifetime that we can, in any case, expect. =
If on=20
      some planet there are beings with a lifetime of a million =
centuries, their=20
      spotlight of comprehensible risk will extend that much farther =
towards the=20
      right-hand end of the continuum. They will expect to be dealt a =
perfect=20
      bridge hand from time to time, and will scarcely trouble to write =
home=20
      about it when it happens. But even they will blench if a marble =
statue=20
      waves at them, for you would have to live dealions of years longer =
than=20
      even they do to see a miracle of this magnitude. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">What has all this to do with =
theories of=20
      the origin of life? Well, we began this argument by agreeing that=20
      Cairns-Smith's theory, and the primeval-soup theory, sound a bit=20
      far-fetched and improbable to us. We naturally feel inclined to =
reject=20
      these theories for that reason. But 'we', remember, are beings =
whose=20
      brains are equipped with a spotlight of comprehensible risk that =
is a=20
      pencil-thin beam illuminating the far left-hand end of the =
mathematical=20
      continuum of calculable risks. Our subjective judgement of what =
seems like=20
      a good bet is irrelevant to what is actually a good bet. The =
subjective=20
      judgement of an alien with a lifetime of a million centuries will =
be quite=20
      different. He will judge as quite plausible an event, such as the =
origin=20
      of the first replicating molecule as postulated by some chemist's =
theory,=20
      which we, kitted up by evolution to move in a world of a few =
decades'=20
      duration, would judge to be an astounding miracle. How can we =
decide whose=20
      point of view is the right one, ours or the long-lived alien's?=20
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.65pt 0pt 10.3pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">There is a simple answer to =
this=20
      question. The long-lived alien's </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.65pt 0pt 10.3pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D382 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 3.85pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Origins and miracles =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">163 <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.7pt 0pt 3.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">point of view is the right one =
for=20
      looking at the plausibility of a theory like Cairns-Smith's or the =

      primeval-soup theory. This is because those two theories postulate =
a=20
      particular event - the spontaneous arising of a self-replicating =
entity -=20
      as occurring only once in about a billion years, once per aeon. =
One and a=20
      half aeons is about the time that elapsed between the origin of =
the Earth=20
      and the first bacteria-like fossils. For our decade-conscious =
brains, an=20
      event that happens only once per aeon is so rare as to seem a =
major=20
      miracle. For the long-lived alien, it will seem less of a miracle =
than a=20
      golf hole-in-one seems to us - and most of us probably know =
somebody who=20
      knows somebody who has scored a hole-in-one. In judging theories =
of the=20
      origin of life, the long-lived alien's subjective timescale is the =

      relevant one, because it is approximately the timescale involved =
in the=20
      origin of life. Our own subjective judgement about the =
plausibility of a=20
      theory of the origin of life is likely to be wrong by a factor of =
a=20
      hundred million. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.6pt 0pt 1.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">In fact our subjective =
judgement is=20
      probably wrong by an even greater margin. Not only are our brains =
equipped=20
      by nature to assess risks of things in a short time; they are also =

      equipped to assess risks of things happening to us personally, or =
to a=20
      narrow circle of people that we know. This is because our brains =
didn't=20
      evolve under conditions dominated by mass media. Mass reporting =
means=20
      that, if an <BR>improbable thing happens to anybody, anywhere in =
the=20
      world, we shall read about it in our newspapers or in the =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Guinness Book of Records.=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">If an orator, =
anywhere=20
      in the world, publicly challenged the lightning to strike him if =
he lied,=20
      and it promptly did so, we should read about it and be duly =
impressed. But=20
      there are several billion people in the world to whom such a =
coincidence=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">could =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">happen, so the apparent =
coincidence is=20
      actually not as great as it seems. Our brains are probably =
equipped by=20
      nature to assess the risks of things happening to ourselves, or to =
a few=20
      hundred people in the small circle of villages within =
<BR>drumrange that=20
      our tribal ancestors could expect to hear news about. When we read =
in a=20
      newspaper about an amazing coincidence happening to somebody in =
Valparaiso=20
      or Virginia, we are more impressed by it than we should be. More =
impressed=20
      by a factor of perhaps a hundred million, if that is the ratio =
between the=20
      world population surveyed by our newspapers, and the tribal =
population=20
      about whom our evolved brains 'expect' to hear news. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.4pt 0pt 1.45pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">This 'population calculation' =
is also=20
      relevant to our judgement of the plausibility of theories of the =
origin of=20
      life. Not because of the population of people on Earth, but =
because of the=20
      population of planets in the universe, the population of planets =
where=20
      life </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">could=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">have =
originated. This is=20
      just the argument we met earlier in this chapter, so </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.4pt 0pt 1.45pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D11 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D50 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D11>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D11 =

      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image066.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D51></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 3.35pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">164 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">there is no need to dwell on it =
here. Go=20
      back to our mental picture of a graduated scale of improbable =
events with=20
      its benchmark coincidences of bridge hands and dice throws. On =
this=20
      graduated scale of dealions and microdealions, mark the following =
three=20
      new points. Probability of life arising on a planet (in, say, a =
billion=20
      years), if we assume that life arises at a rate of about once per =
solar=20
      system. Probability of life arising on a planet if life arises at =
a rate=20
      of about once per galaxy. Probability of life on a randomly =
selected=20
      planet if life arose only once in the universe. Label these three =
points=20
      respectively the Solar System Number, the Galaxy Number and the =
Universe=20
      Number. Remember that there are about 10,000 million galaxies. We =
don't=20
      know how many solar systems there are in each galaxy because we =
can only=20
      see stars, not planets, but we earlier used an estimate that there =
may be=20
      100 billion billion planets in the universe. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.1pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">When we assess the =
improbability of an=20
      event postulated by, for instance the Cairns-Smith theory, we =
should=20
      assess it, not against what we subjectively think of as probable =
or=20
      improbable, but against numbers like these three numbers, the =
Solar System=20
      Number, the Galaxy Number and the Universe Number. Which of these =
three=20
      numbers is the most appropriate depends upon which of the =
following three=20
      statements we think is nearest the truth: </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.55pt 0pt 1.45pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">1. Life has arisen in only one =
planet in=20
      the entire universe (and that planet, as we saw earlier, then has =
to be=20
      Earth). </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.45pt 0pt 0.5pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">2. Life has arisen on about one =
planet=20
      per galaxy (in our galaxy, Earth is the lucky planet). </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
1.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">3. The origin of life is a =
sufficiently=20
      probable event that it tends to arise about once per solar system =
(in our=20
      solar system Earth is the lucky planet). </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.9pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">These three statements =
represent three=20
      benchmark views about the uniqueness of life. The actual =
uniqueness of=20
      life probably lies somewhere between the extremes represented by =
Statement=20
      1 and Statement 3. Why do I say that? Why, in particular, should =
we rule=20
      out a fourth possibility, that the origin of life is a far =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">more </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">probable event than is =
suggested by=20
      Statement 3? It isn't a strong argument, but, for what it is =
worth, it=20
      goes like this. If the origin of life were a much more probable =
event than=20
      is suggested by the Solar System Number </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">we </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">should expect, by now, to have=20
      encountered extraterrestrial life, if </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">not </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">in (whatever passes for) the =
flesh, at=20
      least by radio. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5 style=3D"MARGIN-RIGHT: 2.15pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">It is often pointed out that =
chemists=20
      have failed in </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold">their=20
      attempts to </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman">duplicate=20
      the spontaneous origin of life in the laboratory. </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">This fact is </SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5 style=3D"MARGIN-RIGHT: 2.15pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D382 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 2.4pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Origins and miracles =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">165 <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.3pt 0pt 1.7pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">used as if it constituted =
evidence=20
      against the theories that those chemists are trying to test. But =
actually=20
      one can argue that we should be worried if it turned out to be =
very easy=20
      for chemists to obtain life spontaneously in the test-tube. This =
is=20
      because chemists' experiments last for years not thousands of =
millions of=20
      years, and because only a handful of chemists, not thousands of =
millions=20
      of chemists, are engaged in doing these experiments. If the =
spontaneous=20
      origin of life turned out to be a probable enough event to have =
occurred=20
      during the few man-decades in which chemists have done their =
experiments,=20
      then life should have arisen many times on Earth, and many times =
on=20
      planets within radio range of Earth. Of course all this begs =
important=20
      questions about whether chemists have succeeded in duplicating the =

      conditions of the early Earth but, even so, given that we can't =
answer=20
      these questions, the argument is worth pursuing. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">If the origin of life were a =
probable=20
      event by ordinary human standards, then a substantial number of =
planets=20
      within radio range should have developed a radio technology long =
enough=20
      ago (bearing in mind that radio waves travel at 186,000 miles per =
second)=20
      for us to have picked up at least one transmission during the =
decades that=20
      we have been equipped to do so. There are probably about 50 stars =
within=20
      radio range if we assume that they have had radio technology for =
only as=20
      long as we have. But 50 years is just a fleeting instant, and it =
would be=20
      a major coincidence if another civilization were so closely in =
step with=20
      us. If we embrace in our calculation those civilizations that had =
radio=20
      technology 1,000 years ago, there will be something like a million =
stars=20
      within radio range (together with however many planets circle =
round each=20
      one of them). If we include those whose radio technology goes back =
100,000=20
      years, the whole trillion-star galaxy would be within radio range. =
Of=20
      course, broadcast signals would become pretty attenuated over such =
huge=20
      distances. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">So we have arrived at the =
following=20
      paradox. If a theory of the origin of life is sufficiently =
'plausible' to=20
      satisfy our subjective judgement of plausibility, it is then too=20
      'plausible' to account for the paucity of life in the universe as =
we=20
      observe it. According to this argument, the theory we are looking =
for has=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">got to =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">be the kind of theory that =
seems=20
      implausible to our limited, Earth-bound, decade-bound =
imaginations. Seen=20
      in this light, both Cairns-Smith's theory and the primeval-soup =
theory=20
      seem if anything in danger of erring on the side of being too =
plausible!=20
      Having said all this I must confess that, because there is so much =

      uncertainty in the calculations, if a chemist </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">did </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">succeed in creating spontaneous =
life I=20
      would not actually be disconcerted! </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.35pt 0pt 10.1pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">We still don't know exactly how =
natural=20
      selection began on </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold">Earth.=20
      </SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.35pt 0pt 10.1pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D141 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D141>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.45pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">166 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05pt 0pt 0.5pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">This chapter has had the modest =
aim of=20
      explaining only the </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">kind=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">of way in =
which it must=20
      have happened. The present lack of a definitely accepted account =
of the=20
      origin of life should certainly not be taken as a stumbling block =
for the=20
      whole Darwinian world view, as it occasionally - probably with =
wishful=20
      thinking - is. The earlier chapters have disposed of other alleged =

      stumbling blocks, and the next chapter takes up yet another one, =
the idea=20
      that natural selection can only destroy, never construct. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05pt 0pt 0.5pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D511 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D366 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D511>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"><IMG=20
      height=3D511=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image067.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D366></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D561 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D561>
      <P class=3DStyle16 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 104.45pt 0pt =
110.15pt">CHAPTER 7 <SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <H2 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 16.85pt 0pt 23.5pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 16.5pt">CONSTRUCTIVE EVOLUTION </SPAN><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR><BR><BR></SPAN></H2>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">People sometimes think that =
natural=20
      selection is a purely negative force, capable of weeding out =
freaks and=20
      failures, but not capable of building up complexity, beauty and =
efficiency=20
      of design. Does it not merely subtract from what is already there, =
and=20
      shouldn't a truly creative process add something too? One can =
partially=20
      answer this by pointing to a statue. Nothing is added to the block =
of=20
      marble. The sculptor only subtracts, but a beautiful statue =
emerges=20
      nevertheless. But this metaphor can mislead, for some people leap =
straight=20
      to the wrong part of the metaphor - the fact that the sculptor is =
a=20
      conscious designer - and miss the important part: the fact that =
the=20
      sculptor works by subtraction rather than addition. Even this part =
of the=20
      metaphor should not be taken too far. Natural selection may only =
subtract,=20
      but mutation can add. There are ways in which mutation and natural =

      selection together can lead, over the long span of geological =
time, to a=20
      building up of complexity that has more in common with addition =
than with=20
      subtraction. There are two main ways in which this build-up can =
happen;=20
      The first of these goes under the name of 'coadapted genotypes'; =
the=20
      second under the name of 'arms races'. The two are superficially =
rather=20
      different from one another, but they are united under the headings =
of=20
      'coevolution' and 'genes as each others' environments'. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.55pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">First, the idea of 'coadapted =
genotypes'.=20
      A gene has the particular effect that it does </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">only </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">because there is an existing =
structure=20
      upon which to work. A gene can't affect the wiring up of a brain =
unless=20
      there is a brain being wired up in the first place. There won't be =
a brain=20
      being wired up in the first place, unless there is a complete =
developing=20
      embryo. And there won't be a complete developing embryo unless=20
      <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.2pt 0pt 257.3pt"><B><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">169 </SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.2pt 0pt 257.3pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D381 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 3.1pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">170 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05pt 0pt 2.15pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">there is a whole program of =
chemical and=20
      cellular events, under the influence of lots and lots of other =
genes, and=20
      lots and lots of other, non-genetic, causal influences. The =
particular=20
      effects that genes have are not intrinsic properties of those =
genes. They=20
      are properties of embryological processes, </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">existing </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">processes whose details may be=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">changed =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">by genes, acting in particular =
places and=20
      at particular times during embryonic development. We saw this =
message=20
      demonstrated, in elementary form, by the development of the =
computer=20
      biomorphs. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.55pt 0pt 1.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">In a sense, the whole process =
of=20
      embryonic development can be looked upon as a cooperative venture, =
jointly=20
      run by thousands of genes together. Embryos are put together by =
all the=20
      working genes in the developing organism, in collaboration with =
one=20
      another. Now comes the key to understanding how such =
collaborations come=20
      about. In natural selection, genes are always selected for their =
capacity=20
      to flourish in the environment in which they find themselves. We =
often=20
      think of this environment as the outside world, the world of =
predators and=20
      climate. But from each gene's point of view, perhaps the most =
important=20
      part of its environment </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">is all the other genes that it =

      encounters. </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman">And where=20
      does a gene 'encounter' other genes? Mostly in the cells of the =
successive=20
      individual bodies in which it finds itself. Each gene is selected =
for its=20
      capacity to cooperate successfully with the population of other =
genes that=20
      it is likely to meet in bodies. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.55pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The true population of genes, =
which=20
      constitutes the working environment of any given gene, is not just =
the=20
      temporary collection that happens to have come together in the =
cells of=20
      any particular individual body. At least in sexually reproducing =
species,=20
      it is the set of all genes in the population of interbreeding =
individuals=20
      - the gene 'pool'. At any given moment, any particular copy of a =
gene, in=20
      the sense of a <BR>particular collection of atoms, must be sitting =
in one=20
      cell of one individual. But the set of atoms that is any one copy =
of a=20
      gene is not of permanent interest. It has a life-expectancy =
measured only=20
      in months. As we have seen, the long-lived gene as an evolutionary =
unit is=20
      not any particular physical structure but the textual archival=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">information=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">that is copied =
on down=20
      the generations. This textual replicator has a distributed =
existence. It=20
      is widely distributed in space among different individuals, and =
widely=20
      distributed in time over many generations. When looked at in this=20
      distributed way, any one gene can be said to 'meet' another when =
they find=20
      themselves sharing a body. It can 'expect' to meet a variety of =
other=20
      genes in different bodies at different times in its distributed =
existence,=20
      and in its march through geological time. A successful gene will =
be one=20
      that does well in the environments provided by these other genes =
that it=20
      is likely to meet in lots of different </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.55pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D382 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle35 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 2.4pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Constructive evolution =
</SPAN></I>171=20
      <SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.7pt 0pt 1.7pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">bodies. 'Doing well' in such =
environments=20
      will turn </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">out=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">to be =
equivalent to=20
      'collaborating' with these other genes. It is most directly seen =
in the=20
      case of biochemical pathways. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.25pt 0pt 1.45pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Biochemical pathways are =
sequences of=20
      chemicals that </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold">constitute=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">successive =
stages in=20
      some useful process, like the release of energy or the synthesis =
of an=20
      important substance. Each step in the pathway needs an enzyme =97 =
one of=20
      those large molecules that is shaped to act like a machine in a =
chemical=20
      factory. Different enzymes are needed for different steps in the =
chemical=20
      pathway. Sometimes there are two, or more, alternative chemical =
pathways=20
      to the same useful end. Although both pathways culminate in the =
identical=20
      useful result, they have different intermediate stages leading up =
to that=20
      end, and they normally have different starting points. Either of =
the two=20
      alternative pathways will do the job, and it doesn't matter which =
one is=20
      used. The important thing for any particular animal is to avoid =
trying to=20
      do both at once, </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold">for=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">chemical =
confusion and=20
      inefficiency would result. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.15pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Now suppose that Pathway 1 =
needs the=20
      succession of enzymes Al, Bl and Cl, in order to synthesize a =
desired=20
      chemical D, while Pathway 2 needs enzymes A2, B2 and C2 in order =
to arrive=20
      at the same desirable end-product. Each enzyme is made by a =
particular=20
      gene. So, in order to evolve the assembly line for Pathway 1, a =
species=20
      needs the genes coding for Al, Bl and Cl all to coevolve together. =
In=20
      order to evolve the alternative assembly line for Pathway 2, a =
species=20
      would need the genes coding for A2, B2 and C2 to coevolve with one =

      another. The choice between these two coevolutions doesn't come =
about=20
      through advance planning. It comes about simply through each gene =
being=20
      selected by virtue of its compatibility with the other genes=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">that already =
happen to=20
      dominate the population. </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">If the population happens to be =
already=20
      rich in genes for Bl and Cl, this will set up a climate favouring =
the Al=20
      gene rather than the A2 gene. Conversely, if the population is =
already=20
      rich in genes for B2 and C2 this will set up a climate in which =
the A2=20
      gene is favoured by selection rather than the Al gene. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.7pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">It will not be as simple as =
that, but you=20
      will have got the idea: one </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">of </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the most important aspects of =
the=20
      'climate' in which a gene is favoured or disfavoured is the other =
genes=20
      that are already numerous in the population; the other genes, =
therefore,=20
      with which it is likely to have to share bodies. Since the same =
will=20
      obviously be true of these 'other' genes themselves, we have a =
picture of=20
      teams of genes all evolving towards cooperative solutions to =
problems. The=20
      genes themselves don't evolve, they merely survive or fail to =
survive in=20
      the gene pool. It is the 'team' that evolves. Other teams might =
have done=20
      the job just as </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.7pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D381 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle9 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.2pt 0pt 3.1pt">172 =
<I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 2.15pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">well, or even better. But once =
one team=20
      has started to dominate the gene pool of a species it thereby has =
an=20
      automatic advantage. It is difficult for a minority team to break =
in, even=20
      a minority team which would, in the end, have done the job more=20
      efficiently. The majority team has an automatic resistance to =
being=20
      displaced, simply by virtue of being in the majority. This doesn't =
mean=20
      that the majority team can never be displaced. If it couldn't, =
evolution=20
      would grind to a halt. But it does mean that there is a kind of =
built-in=20
      inertia. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.65pt 0pt 1.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Obviously this kind of argument =
is not=20
      limited to biochemistry. We could make the same kind of case for =
clusters=20
      of compatible genes building the different parts of eyes, ears, =
noses,=20
      walking limbs, all the cooperating parts of an animal's body. =
Genes for=20
      making teeth suitable for chewing meat tend to be favoured in a =
'climate'=20
      dominated by genes making guts suitable for digesting meat. =
Conversely,=20
      genes for making plant-grinding teeth tend to be favoured in a =
climate=20
      dominated by genes that make guts suitable for digesting plants. =
And vice=20
      versa in both cases. Teams of 'meat-eating genes' tend to evolve =
together,=20
      and teams of 'plant-eating genes' tend to evolve together. Indeed, =
there=20
      is a sense in which most of the working genes in a body can be =
said to=20
      cooperate with each other as a team, because over evolutionary =
time they=20
      (i.e. ancestral copies of themselves) have each been part of the=20
      environment in which natural selection has worked on the others. =
If we ask=20
      why the ancestors of lions took to meat-eating, while the =
ancestors of=20
      antelopes took to grass-eating, the answer could be that =
originally it was=20
      an accident. An accident, in the sense that it could have been the =

      ancestors of lions that took up grass-eating, and the ancestors of =

      antelopes that took up meat-eating. But once one lineage had=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">begun to=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">build up a =
team of genes=20
      for dealing with meat rather than grass, the process was =
self-reinforcing.=20
      And once the other lineage had begun to build up a team of genes =
for=20
      dealing with grass rather than meat, </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">that </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">process was self-reinforcing in =
the other=20
      direction. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.1pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">One of the main things that =
must have=20
      happened in the early evolution of living organisms was an =
increase in the=20
      numbers of genes participating in such cooperatives. Bacteria have =
far=20
      fewer genes than animals and plants. The increase may have come =
about=20
      through various kinds of gene duplication. Remember that a gene is =
just a=20
      length of coded symbols, like a file on a computer disc; and genes =
can be=20
      copied to different parts of the chromosomes, just as files can be =
copied=20
      to different parts of the disc. On my disc that holds this chapter =
there=20
      are officially just three files. By 'officially' I mean that the=20
      computer's operating system tells me that there are just three =
files. I=20
      can ask it to read one of these three files, and it presents me =
with a=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.1pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D381 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.9pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Constructive evolution =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">173 <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.5pt 0pt 1.45pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">one-dimensional array of =
alphabetical=20
      characters, including the characters that you are now reading. All =
very=20
      neat and orderly, it seems. But in fact, on the disc itself, the=20
      arrangement of the text is anything but neat and orderly. You can =
see this=20
      if you break away from the discipline of the computer's own =
official=20
      operating system, and write your own private programs to decipher =
what is=20
      actually written on every sector of the disc. It turns out that =
fragments=20
      of each of my three files are dotted around, interleaved with each =
other=20
      and with fragments of old, dead files that I erased long ago and =
had=20
      forgotten. Any given fragment may turn up, word for word the same, =
or with=20
      minor differences, in half a dozen different places all around the =
disc.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.85pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The reason for this is =
interesting, and=20
      worth a digression because </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">it </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">provides a good genetic =
analogy. When you=20
      tell a computer to delete a file, it appears to obey you. But it =
doesn't=20
      actually wipe out the text of that file. It simply wipes out all=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">pointers=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">to that file. =
It is as=20
      though a librarian, ordered to destroy </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Lady Chatterley's Lover,=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">simply tore up =
the card=20
      from the card index, leaving the book itself on the shelf. For the =

      computer, this is a perfectly economical way to do things, because =
the=20
      space formerly occupied by the 'deleted' file is automatically =
available=20
      for new files, as soon as the pointers to the old file have been =
removed.=20
      It would be a waste of time actually to go to the trouble of =
filling the=20
      space itself with blanks. The old file won't itself be finally =
lost until=20
      all its space happens to be used for storing new files. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.35pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">But this re-using of space =
occurs=20
      piecemeal. New files aren't exactly the same size as old ones. =
When the=20
      computer is trying to save a new file to a disc, it looks for the =
first=20
      available fragment of space, writes as much of the new file as =
will fit,=20
      then looks for another available fragment of space, writes a bit =
more, and=20
      so on until all the file is written </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">somewhere on </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the disc. The human has the =
illusion that=20
      the file is a single, orderly array, only because the computer is =
careful=20
      to keep records 'pointing' to the addresses of all the fragments =
dotted=20
      around. These 'pointers' are like the 'continued on page 94' =
pointers used=20
      by the </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">New =
York Times.=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The reason =
many copies=20
      of any one fragment of text are found on a disc is that if, like =
all my=20
      chapters, the text has been edited and re-edited many dozens of =
times,=20
      each edit will result in a new saving to the disc of (almost) the =
same=20
      text. The saving may ostensibly be a saving of the same file. But =
as we=20
      have seen, the text will in fact be repeatedly scattered around =
the=20
      available 'gaps' on the disc. Hence multiple copies of a given =
fragment of=20
      text can be found all around the surface of the disc, the more so =
if the=20
      disc is old and much used. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.65pt 0pt 10.1pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Now the DNA operating system of =
a species=20
      is very very old indeed, </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.65pt 0pt 10.1pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D382 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.25pt 0pt 3.85pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">174 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 2.65pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">and there is evidence that it, =
seen in=20
      the long term, does something a bit like the computer with its =
disc files.=20
      Part of the evidence comes from the fascinating phenomenon of =
'introns'=20
      and 'exons'. Within the last decade, it has been discovered that =
any=20
      'single' gene, in the sense of a single continuously read passage =
of DNA=20
      text, is not all stored in one place. If you actually read the =
code=20
      letters as they occur along the chromosome (i.e. if you do the =
equivalent=20
      of breaking out of the discipline of the 'operating system') you =
find=20
      fragments of 'sense', called exons, separated by portions of =
'nonsense'=20
      called introns. Any one 'gene' in the functional sense, is in fact =
split=20
      up into a sequence of fragments (exons) separated by meaningless =
introns.=20
      It is as if each exon ended with a pointer saying 'continued on =
page 94'.=20
      A complete gene is then made up of a whole series of exons, which =
are=20
      actually strung together only when they are eventually read by the =

      'official' operating system that translates them into proteins.=20
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.25pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Further evidence comes from the =
fact that=20
      the chromosomes are littered with old genetic text that is no =
longer used,=20
      but which still makes recognizable sense. To a computer =
programmer, the=20
      pattern of distribution of these 'genetic fossil' fragments is =
uncannily=20
      <BR>reminiscent of the pattern of text on the surface of an old =
disc that=20
      has been much used for editing text. In some animals, a high =
proportion of=20
      the total number of genes is in fact never read. These genes are =
either=20
      complete nonsense, or they are outdated 'fossil genes'. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.8pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Just occasionally, textual =
fossils come=20
      into their own again, as I experienced when writing this book. A =
computer=20
      error (or, to be fair, it may have been human error) caused me=20
      accidentally to 'erase' the disc containing Chapter 3. Of course =
the text=20
      itself hadn't literally all been erased. All that had been =
definitely=20
      erased were the </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">pointers=20
      to </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">where each =
'exon'=20
      began and ended. The 'official' operating system could read =
nothing, but=20
      'unofficially' I could play genetic engineer and examine all the =
text on=20
      the disc. What I saw was a bewildering jigsaw puzzle of textual =
fragments,=20
      some of them recent, others ancient 'fossils'. By piecing together =
the=20
      jigsaw fragments, I was able to recreate the chapter. But I mostly =
didn't=20
      know which fragments were recent and which were fossil. It didn't =
matter=20
      for, apart from minor details that necessitated some new editing, =
they=20
      were the same. At least some of the 'fossils', or outdated =
'introns', had=20
      come into their own again. They rescued me from my predicament, =
and saved=20
      me the trouble of rewriting the entire chapter. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
2.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">There is evidence that, in =
living species=20
      too, 'fossil genes' occasionally come into their own again, and =
are=20
      re-used after lying dormant for a million years or so. To go into =
detail=20
      would carry us too </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
2.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D380 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.45pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Constructive evolution =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">175 <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.2pt 0pt 0.7pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">far from the main pathway of =
this=20
      chapter, for you will remember that we are already out on a =
digression.=20
      The main point was that the total genetic capacity of a species =
may=20
      increase due to gene duplication. Reusing of old 'fossil' copies =
of=20
      existing genes is one way in which this can happen. There are =
other, more=20
      immediate, ways in which genes may be copied to widely distributed =
parts=20
      of the chromosomes, like files being duplicated to different parts =
of a=20
      disc, or different discs. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.2pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Humans have eight separate =
genes called=20
      globin genes (used for making haemoglobin, among other things), on =
various=20
      different chromosomes. It seems certain that all eight have been =
copied,=20
      ultimately from a single ancestral globin gene. About 1,100 =
million years=20
      ago, the ancestral globin gene duplicated, forming two genes. We =
can date=20
      this event because of independent evidence about how fast globins=20
      habitually evolve (see Chapters 5 and 11). Of the two genes =
produced by=20
      this original duplication, one became the ancestor of all the =
genes that=20
      make haemoglobin in vertebrates. The other became the ancestor of =
all the=20
      genes that make myoglobins, a related family of proteins that work =
in=20
      muscles. Various subsequent duplications have given rise to the =
so-called=20
      alpha, beta, gamma, delta, epsilon and zeta globins. The =
fascinating thing=20
      is that we can construct a complete family tree of all the globin =
genes,=20
      and even put dates on all the divergence points (delta and beta =
globin=20
      parted company, for example, about 40 million years ago, epsilon =
and gamma=20
      globins 100 million years ago). Yet the eight globins, descendants =
as they=20
      are of these remote branchings in distant ancestors, are still all =
present=20
      inside every one of us. They diverged to different parts of an =
ancestor's=20
      chromosomes, and we have each inherited them on our different =
chromosomes.=20
      Molecules are sharing the same body with their remote molecular =
cousins.=20
      It is certain that a great deal of such duplication has gone on, =
all over=20
      the chromosomes, and throughout geological time. This is an =
important=20
      respect in which real life is more complicated than the biomorphs =
of=20
      Chapter 3. They all had only nine genes. They evolved by changes =
in those=20
      nine genes, never by increasing the number of genes to ten. Even =
in real=20
      animals, such duplications are rare enough not to invalidate my =
general=20
      statement that all members of a species share the same DNA =
'addressing'=20
      system. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
2.1pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Duplication within the species =
isn't the=20
      only means by which the number of cooperating genes has increased =
in=20
      evolution. An even rarer, but still possibly very important =
occurrence, is=20
      the occasional incorporation of a gene from another species, even =
an=20
      extremely remote species. There are, for example, haemoglobins in =
the=20
      roots of plants of the pea family. They don't occur in any other =
plant=20
      families, and it </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
2.1pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D382 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.2pt 0pt 4.1pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">176 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 3.35pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">seems almost certain that they =
somehow=20
      got into the pea family by cross-infection from animals, viruses =
perhaps=20
      acting as intermediaries. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.25pt 0pt 2.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">An especially important event =
along these=20
      lines, according to the increasingly favoured theory of the =
American=20
      biologist Lynn Margulis, took place at the origin of the so-called =

      eukaryotic cell. Eukaryotic cells include all cells except those =
of=20
      bacteria. The living world is divided, fundamentally, into =
bacteria versus=20
      the rest. We are part of the rest, and are collectively called the =

      eukaryotes. We differ from bacteria mainly in that our cells have =
discrete=20
      little mini-cells inside them. These include the nucleus, which =
houses the=20
      chromosomes; the tiny bomb-shaped objects called mitochondria =
(which we=20
      briefly met in Figure 1), filled with intricately folded =
membranes; and,=20
      in the (eukaryotic) cells of plants, chloroplasts. Mitochondria =
and=20
      chloroplasts have their own DNA, which replicates and propagates =
itself=20
      entirely independently of the main DNA in the chromosomes of the =
nucleus.=20
      All the mitochondria in you are descended from the small =
population of=20
      mitochondria that travelled from your mother in her egg. Sperms =
are too=20
      small to contain mitochondria, so mitochondria travel exclusively =
down the=20
      female line, and male bodies are dead ends as far as mitochondrial =

      reproduction is concerned. Incidentally, this means that we can =
use=20
      mitochondria to trace our ancestry, strictly down the female line. =

      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.15pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Margulis's theory is that =
mitochondria=20
      and chloroplasts, and a few other structures inside cells, are =
each=20
      descended from bacteria. The eukaryotic cell was formed, perhaps 2 =
billion=20
      years ago, when several kinds of bacteria joined forces because of =
the=20
      benefits that each could obtain from the others. Over the aeons =
they have=20
      become so thoroughly integrated into the cooperative unit that =
became the=20
      eukaryotic cell, that it has become almost impossible to detect =
the fact,=20
      if indeed it is a fact, that they were once separate bacteria. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.65pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">It seems that, once the =
eukaryotic cell=20
      had been invented, a whole new range of designs became possible. =
Most=20
      interestingly from our point of view, cells could manufacture =
large bodies=20
      comprising many billions of cells. All cells reproduce by =
splitting into=20
      two, both halves getting a full set of genes. As we saw in the =
case of the=20
      bacteria on a pin's head, successive splittings into two can =
generate a=20
      very large number of cells in rather a short time. You start with =
one and=20
      it splits into two. Then each of the two splits, making four. Each =
of the=20
      four splits, making eight. The numbers go up by successive =
doublings, from=20
      8 to 16, 32, 64, 128, 256, 512, 1,024, 2,048, 4,096, 8,192. After =
only 20=20
      doublings, which doesn't take very long, we are up in the =
millions. After=20
      only 40 doublings the number of cells is more than a trillion. In=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.65pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D382 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 2.15pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Constructive evolution =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">177 <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.55pt 0pt 1.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the case of bacteria, the =
enormous=20
      numbers of cells produced by successive doublings go their =
separate ways.=20
      The same is true of many eukaryotic cells, for instance protozoa =
such as=20
      amoebas. A major step in evolution was taken when cells that had =
been=20
      produced by <BR>successive splittings stuck together instead of =
going off=20
      independently. Higher-order structure could now emerge, just as it =
did, on=20
      an incomparably smaller scale, in the two-way branching computer=20
      biomorphs. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Now, for the first time, large =
body size=20
      became a possibility. A human body is a truly colossal population =
of=20
      cells, all descended from one ancestor, the fertilized egg; and =
all=20
      therefore cousins, children, grandchildren, uncles, etc. of other =
cells in=20
      the body. The 10 trillion cells that make up each one of us are =
the=20
      product of a few dozens of generations of cell doublings. These =
cells are=20
      classified into about 210 (according to taste) different kinds, =
all built=20
      by the same set of genes but with different members of the set of =
genes=20
      turned on in different kinds of cells. This, as we have seen, is =
why liver=20
      cells are different from brain cells, and bone cells are different =
from=20
      muscle cells. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.3pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Genes working through the =
organs and=20
      behaviour patterns of many-celled bodies can achieve methods of =
ensuring=20
      their own propagation that are not available to single cells =
working on=20
      their own. Many-celled bodies make it possible for genes to =
manipulate the=20
      world, using tools built on a scale that is orders of magnitude =
larger=20
      than the scale of single cells. They achieve these large-scale =
indirect=20
      manipulations via their more direct effects on the miniature scale =
of=20
      cells. For instance, they change the shape of the cell membrane. =
The cells=20
      then interact with one another in huge populations to produce=20
      <BR>largescale group effects such as an arm or a leg or (more =
indirectly)=20
      a beaver's dam. Most of the properties of an organism that we are =
equipped=20
      to see with our naked eyes are so-called 'emergent properties'. =
Even the=20
      computer biomorphs, with their nine genes, had emergent =
properties. In=20
      real animals they are produced at the <BR>wholebody level by =
interactions=20
      between cells. An organism works as an entire unit, and its genes =
can be=20
      said to have effects on the whole organism, even though each copy =
of any=20
      one gene exerts its immediate effects only within its own cell.=20
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.7pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">We have seen that a very =
important part=20
      of a gene's environment is the other genes that it is likely to =
meet in=20
      successive bodies as the generations go by. These are the genes =
that are=20
      permuted and combined within the species. Indeed, a sexually =
reproducing=20
      species can be thought of as a device that permutes a discrete set =
of=20
      mutually accustomed genes in different combinations. Species, =
according to=20
      this view, are continually shuffling collections of genes that =
meet each=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.7pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D380 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 3.35pt"><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">178 </SPAN></B><B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: 'Times-Bold Italic'">The Blind =
</SPAN></I></B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Watchmaker </SPAN></I><I><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05pt 0pt 2.4pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">other within the species, but =
never meet=20
      genes of other species. But there is a sense in which the genes of =

      different species, even if they don't meet at close quarters =
inside cells,=20
      nevertheless constitute an important part of each others' =
environment. The=20
      relationship is often hostile rather than cooperative, but this =
can be=20
      treated as just a reversal of sign. This is where we come to the =
second=20
      major theme of this chapter, 'arms races'. There are arms races =
between=20
      predators and prey, parasites and hosts, even - though the point =
is a more=20
      subtle one and I shan't discuss it further - between males and =
females=20
      within one species. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.75pt 0pt 1.45pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Arms races are run in =
evolutionary time,=20
      rather than on the timescale of individual lifetimes. They consist =
of the=20
      improvement in one lineage's (say prey animals') equipment to =
survive, as=20
      a direct consequence of improvement in another (say predators') =
lineage's=20
      evolving equipment. There are arms races wherever individuals have =
enemies=20
      with their own capacity for evolutionary improvement. I regard =
arms races=20
      as of the utmost importance because it is largely arms races that =
have=20
      injected such 'progressiveness' as there is in evolution. For, =
contrary to=20
      earlier prejudices, there is nothing inherently progressive about=20
      evolution. We can see this if we consider what would have happened =
if the=20
      only problems animals had had to face had been those posed by the =
weather=20
      and other aspects of the nonliving environment. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.6pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">After many generations of =
cumulative=20
      selection </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">in=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">a particular =
place, the=20
      local animals and plants become well fitted to the <BR>conditions, =
for=20
      instance the weather conditions, in that place. If it is cold the =
animals=20
      come to have thick coats of hair, or feathers. If it is dry they =
evolve=20
      leathery or waxy waterproof skins to conserve what little water =
there is.=20
      The adaptations to local conditions affect every part of the body, =
its=20
      shape and colour, its internal organs, its behaviour, and the =
chemistry in=20
      its cells. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.9pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">If the conditions in which a =
lineage of=20
      animals lives remain constant; say it is dry and hot and has been =
so=20
      without a break for 100 generations, evolution in that lineage is =
likely=20
      to come to a halt, at least as far as adaptations to temperature =
and=20
      humidity are concerned. The animals will become as well fitted as =
they can=20
      be to the local conditions. This doesn't mean that they couldn't =
be=20
      completely redesigned to be even better. It does mean that they =
can't=20
      improve themselves by any </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">small </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">(and therefore likely) =
evolutionary step:=20
      none of their </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">immediate=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">neighbours in =
the local=20
      equivalent of 'biomorph space' would do any better. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.2pt 0pt 9.85pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Evolution will come =
</SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">to a </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">standstill until something in =
the=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.2pt 0pt 9.85pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D381 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle5 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.9pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Constructive evolution=20
      </SPAN></I><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">179=20
      </SPAN></B><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.5pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">conditions changes: the onset =
of an ice=20
      age, a change in the average rainfall of the area, a shift in the=20
      prevailing wind. Such changes do happen when we are dealing with a =

      timescale as long as the evolutionary one. As a consequence, =
evolution=20
      normally does not come to a halt, but constantly 'tracks' the =
changing=20
      environment. If there is a steady downward drift in the average=20
      temperature in the area, a drift that persists over centuries, =
successive=20
      generations of animals will be propelled by a steady selection =
'pressure'=20
      in the direction, say, of growing longer coats of hair. If, after =
a few=20
      thousand years of reduced temperature the trend reverses and =
average=20
      temperatures creep up again, the animals will come under the =
influence of=20
      a new selection pressure, and will be pushed towards growing =
shorter coats=20
      again. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">But so far we have considered =
only a=20
      limited part of the environment, namely the weather. The weather =
is very=20
      important to animals and plants. Its patterns change as the =
centuries go=20
      by, so this keeps evolution constantly in motion as it 'tracks' =
the=20
      changes. But weather patterns change in a haphazard, inconsistent =
way.=20
      There are other parts of an animal's environment that change in =
more=20
      consistently malevolent directions, and that also need to be =
'tracked'.=20
      These parts of the environment are living things themselves. For a =

      predator such as a hyena, a part of its environment that is at =
least as=20
      important as the weather is its prey, the changing populations of =
gnus,=20
      zebras and antelopes. For the antelopes and other grazers that =
wander the=20
      plains in search of grass, the weather may be important, but the =
lions,=20
      hyenas and other carnivores are important too. Cumulative =
selection will=20
      see to it that animals are well fitted to outrun their predators =
or outwit=20
      their prey, no less than it sees to it that they are well fitted =
to the=20
      prevailing weather conditions. And, just as long-term fluctuations =
in the=20
      weather are 'tracked' by evolution, so long-term changes in the =
habits or=20
      weaponry of predators will be tracked by evolutionary changes in =
their=20
      prey. And vice versa, of course. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
2.85pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">We can use the general term =
'enemies' of=20
      a species, to mean other living things that work to make life =
difficult.=20
      Lions are enemies of zebras. It may seem a little callous to =
reverse the=20
      statement to 'Zebras are enemies of lions'. The role of the zebra =
in the=20
      relationship seems too innocent and wronged to warrant the =
pejorative=20
      'enemy'. But individual zebras do everything in their power to =
resist=20
      being eaten by lions, and from the lions' point of view this is =
making=20
      life harder for them. If zebras and other grazers all succeeded in =
their=20
      aim, the lions would die of starvation. So by our definition =
zebras are=20
      enemies of lions. Parasites such as tapeworms are enemies of their =
hosts,=20
      and hosts are enemies of parasites since they tend to evolve =
measures to=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
2.85pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D380 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.3pt 0pt 2.9pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">180 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05pt 0pt 2.15pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">resist them. Herbivores are =
enemies of=20
      plants, and plants are enemies of herbivores, to the extent that =
they=20
      manufacture thorns, and poisonous or nasty-tasting chemicals. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Lineages of animals and plants =
will, in=20
      evolutionary time, 'track' changes in their enemies no less =
assiduously=20
      than they track changes in average weather conditions. =
Evolutionary=20
      improvements in cheetah weaponry and tactics are, from the =
gazelles' point=20
      of view, like a steady worsening of the climate, and they are =
tracked in=20
      the same kind of way. But there is one enormously important =
difference=20
      between the two. The weather changes over the centuries, but it =
does not=20
      change in a specifically malevolent way. It is not out to 'get' =
gazelles.=20
      The average cheetah will change over the centuries, just like the =
mean=20
      annual rainfall changes. But whereas mean annual rainfall will =
drift up=20
      and down, with no particular rhyme or reason, the average cheetah, =
as the=20
      centuries go by, will tend to become </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">better </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">equipped to catch gazelles than =
his=20
      ancestors were. This is because the succession of cheetahs, unlike =
the=20
      succession of annual weather conditions, is itself subject to =
cumulative=20
      selection. Cheetahs will tend to become fleeter of foot, keener of =
eye,=20
      sharper of tooth. However 'hostile' the weather and other =
inanimate=20
      conditions may seem to be, they have no necessary tendency to get =
steadily=20
      more hostile. Living enemies, seen over the evolutionary =
timescale, have=20
      exactly that tendency. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.8pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The tendency for carnivores to =
get=20
      progressively 'better' would soon run out of steam, as do human =
arms races=20
      (for reasons of economic cost which we shall come to), were it not =
for the=20
      parallel tendency in the prey. And vice versa. Gazelles, no less =
than=20
      cheetahs, are subject to cumulative selection, and they too will =
tend, as=20
      the generations go by, to improve their ability to run fast, to =
react=20
      swiftly, to become invisible by blending into the long grass. They =
too are=20
      capable of evolving in the direction of becoming better enemies, =
in this=20
      case enemies of cheetahs. From the cheetahs' point of view the =
mean annual=20
      temperature does not get systematically better or worse as the =
years go=20
      by, except in so far as any change for a well-adapted animal is a =
change=20
      for the worse. But the mean annual gazelle does tend to get =
systematically=20
      worse =97 more difficult to catch because better adapted to evade =
cheetahs.=20
      Again, the tendency towards progressive improvement in gazelles =
would slow=20
      to a halt, were it not for the parallel tendency to =
<BR>improvement shown=20
      by their predators. One side gets a little better because the =
other side=20
      has. And vice versa. The process goes into a vicious spiral,=20
      </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">on =
</SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">a timescale of hundreds of =
thousands of=20
      years. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5 style=3D"MARGIN-RIGHT: 2.2pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">In the world of nations on =
their shorter=20
      </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">timescale, when =
two=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">enemies each=20
      progressively improve their </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">weaponry in response to the=20
</SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5 style=3D"MARGIN-RIGHT: 2.2pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D380 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.7pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Constructive evolution =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">181 <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.8pt 0pt 0.95pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">other side's improvements, we =
speak of an=20
      'arms race'. The evolutionary analogy is close enough to justify =
borrowing=20
      the term, and I make no apology to my pompous colleagues who would =
purge=20
      our language of such illuminating images. I have introduced the =
idea here=20
      in terms of a simple example, gazelles and cheetahs. This was to =
get=20
      across the important difference between a living enemy, which =
itself is=20
      subject to evolutionary change, and an inanimate non-malevolent =
condition=20
      such as the weather, which is subject to change, but not =
systematic,=20
      evolutionary change. But the time has come to admit that in my =
efforts to=20
      explain this one valid point I may have misled the reader in other =
ways.=20
      It is obvious, when you come to think about it, that my picture of =
an=20
      everadvancing arms race was too simple in at least one respect. =
Take=20
      running speed. As it stands so far, the arms-race idea seems to =
suggest=20
      that cheetahs and gazelles should have gone on, generation after=20
      generation, getting ever faster until both travelled faster than =
sound.=20
      This has not happened and it never will. Before resuming the =
discussion of=20
      arms races, it is my duty to forestall misunderstandings. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.9pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The first qualification is =
this. I gave=20
      an impression of a steady upward climb in the prey-catching =
abilities of=20
      cheetahs, and the predator-avoiding abilities of gazelles. The =
reader=20
      might have come away with a Victorian idea of the inexorability of =

      progress, each generation better, finer and braver than its =
parents. The=20
      reality in nature is nothing like that. The timescale over which=20
      significant improvement might be detected is, in any case, likely =
to be=20
      far longer than could be detected by comparing one typical =
generation with=20
      its predecessor. The 'improvement', moreover, is far from =
continuous. It=20
      is a fitful affair, stagnating or even sometimes going =
'backwards', rather=20
      than moving solidly 'forwards' in the direction suggested by the =
arms-race=20
      idea. Changes in conditions, changes in the inanimate forces I =
have lumped=20
      under the general heading of 'the weather', are likely to swamp =
the slow=20
      and erratic trends of the arms race, as far as any observer on the =
ground=20
      could be aware. There may well be long stretches of time in which =
no=20
      'progress' in the arms race, and perhaps no evolutionary change at =
all,=20
      takes place. Arms races sometimes culminate in extinction, and =
then a new=20
      arms race may begin back at square one. Nevertheless, when all =
this is=20
      said, the arms-race idea remains by far the most satisfactory =
explanation=20
      for the existence of the advanced and complex machinery that =
animals and=20
      plants possess. Progressive 'improvement' of the kind suggested by =
the=20
      arms-race image does go on, even if it goes on spasmodically and=20
      interruptedly; even if its net rate of progress is too slow to be =
detected=20
      within the lifetime of a man, or even within the timespan of =
recorded=20
      history. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.9pt 0pt 10.3pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The second qualification is =
that the=20
      relationship that I </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold">am=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">calling =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.9pt 0pt 10.3pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D382 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.25pt 0pt 4.1pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">182 </SPAN><B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: 'Times-Bold Italic'">The =
</SPAN></I></B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 3.1pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">'enemy' is more complicated =
than the=20
      simple bilateral relationship suggested by the stories of cheetahs =
and=20
      gazelles. One complication is that a given species may have two =
(or more)=20
      enemies which are even more severe enemies of each other. This is =
the=20
      principle behind the commonly expressed half-truth that grass =
benefits by=20
      being grazed (or mown). Cattle eat grass, and might therefore be =
thought=20
      of as enemies of grass. But grasses also have other enemies in the =
plant=20
      world, competitive weeds, which, if allowed to grow unchecked, =
might turn=20
      out to be even more severe enemies of grasses than cattle. Grasses =
suffer=20
      somewhat from being eaten by cattle, but the competitive weeds =
suffer even=20
      more. Therefore the net effect of cattle on a meadow is that the =
grasses=20
      benefit. The cattle turn out to be, in this sense, friends of =
grasses=20
      rather than enemies. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.55pt 0pt 1.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Nevertheless, cattle are =
enemies of grass=20
      in that it is </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">still=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">true that an =
individual=20
      grass plant would be better off not being eaten by a cow than =
being eaten,=20
      and any mutant plant that possessed, say, a chemical weapon that =
protected=20
      it against cows, would set more seed ( containing genetic =
instructions for=20
      making the chemical weapon) than rival members of its own species =
that=20
      were more palatable to cows. Even if there is a special sense in =
which=20
      cows are 'friends' of grasses, natural selection does =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">not </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">favour individual grass plants =
that go=20
      out of their way to be eaten by cows! The general conclusion to =
this=20
      paragraph is as follows. It may be convenient to think of an arms =
race=20
      between two lineages such as cattle and grass, or gazelles and =
cheetahs,=20
      but we should never lose sight of the fact that both participants =
have=20
      other enemies against whom they are simultaneously running other =
arms=20
      races. I shall not pursue the point here, but it can be developed =
into one=20
      of the explanations for why particular arms races stabilize and do =
not go=20
      on for ever - do not lead to predators pursuing their prey at Mach =
2 and=20
      so on. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.9pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The third 'qualification' to =
the simple=20
      arms-race is not so much a qualification as an interesting point =
in its=20
      own right. In my hypothetical discussion of cheetahs and gazelles =
I said=20
      that cheetahs, unlike the weather, had a tendency as the =
generations go by=20
      to become 'better hunters', to become more severe enemies, better =
equipped=20
      to kill gazelles. But this does not imply that they become more=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">successful=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">at killing =
gazelles. The=20
      kernel of the arms-race idea is that both sides in the arms race =
are=20
      improving from their own point of view, while simultaneously =
making life=20
      more difficult for the other side in the arms race. There is no =
particular=20
      reason (or at least none in anything that we have discussed so =
far) to=20
      expect either side in the arms race to become steadily more =
successful or=20
      less successful than the other. In </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.9pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D381 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 3.1pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Constructive evolution =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">183 <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.3pt 0pt 2.15pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">fact the arms-race idea, in its =
purest=20
      form, suggests that there should be absolutely zero progress in =
the=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">success rate=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">on both sides =
of the=20
      arms race, while there is very definite progress in the =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">equipment </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">for success on both sides. =
Predators=20
      become better equipped for killing, but at the same time prey =
become=20
      better equipped to avoid being killed, so the net result is no =
change in=20
      the rate of successful killings. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.05pt 0pt 1.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The implication is that if, by =
the medium=20
      of a time machine, predators from one era could meet prey from =
another=20
      era, the later, more 'modern' animals, whether predators or prey, =
would=20
      run rings round the earlier ones. This is not an experiment that =
can ever=20
      be done, although some people assume that certain remote and =
isolated=20
      faunas, such as those of Australia and Madagascar, can be treated =
as if=20
      they were ancient, as if a trip to Australia were like a trip =
backwards in=20
      a time machine. Such people think that native Australian species =
are=20
      usually driven extinct by superior competitors or enemies =
introduced from=20
      the outside world, because the native species are 'older', 'out of =
date'=20
      models, in the same position </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">vis-a-vis </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">invading species as a Jutland =
battleship=20
      contending with a nuclear submarine. But the assumption that =
Australia has=20
      a 'living fossil' fauna is hard to justify. Perhaps a good case =
for it=20
      might be made, but it seldom is. I'm afraid it may be no more than =
the=20
      zoological equivalent of chauvinistic snobbery, analogous to the =
attitude=20
      that sees every Australian as an uncouth swagman with not much =
under his=20
      hat and corks dangling round the brim. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The principle of zero change in =
success=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">rate, =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">no matter how great the =
evolutionary=20
      progress in </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">equipment,=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">has been given =
the=20
      memorable name of the 'Red Queen effect' by the American biologist =
Leigh=20
      van Valen. In </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">Through=20
      the Looking Glass, </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman">you=20
      will remember, the Red Queen seized Alice by the hand and dragged =
her,=20
      faster and faster, on a frenzied run through the countryside, but =
no=20
      matter how fast they ran they always stayed in the same place. =
Alice was=20
      understandably puzzled, saying, 'Well in our country you'd =
generally get=20
      to somewhere else - if you ran very fast for a long time as we've =
been=20
      doing.' 'A slow sort of country!' said the Queen. 'Now, =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">here, </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">you see, it takes all the =
running you can=20
      do, to keep in the same place. If you want to get somewhere else, =
you must=20
      run at least twice as fast as that!' </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.7pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The Red Queen label is amusing, =
but it=20
      can be misleading if taken (as it sometimes is) to mean something=20
      mathematically precise, literally zero relative progress. Another=20
      misleading feature is that in the Alice story the Red Queen's =
statement is=20
      genuinely paradoxical, irreconcilable with common sense in the =
real=20
      physical world. But van Valen's evolutionary Red Queen effect is =
not=20
      paradoxical at all. It is </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.7pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D625 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D381 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D625>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.45pt 0pt 4.3pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">184 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 3.35pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">entirely in accordance with =
common sense,=20
      so long as common sense is intelligently applied. If not =
paradoxical,=20
      however, arms races can give rise to situations that strike the=20
      economically minded human as wasteful. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.65pt 0pt 2.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Why, for instance, are trees in =
forests=20
      so tall? The short answer is that all the other trees are tall, so =
no one=20
      tree can afford not to be. It would be overshadowed if it did. =
This is=20
      essentially the truth, but it offends the economically minded =
human. It=20
      seems so pointless, so wasteful. When all the trees are the full =
height of=20
      the canopy, all are approximately equally exposed to the sun, and =
none=20
      could afford to be any shorter. But if only they were =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">all </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">shorter; if only there could be =
some sort=20
      of trade-union agreement to lower the recognized height of the =
canopy in=20
      forests, </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">all=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the trees =
would benefit.=20
      They would be competing with each other in the canopy for exactly =
the same=20
      sunlight, but they would all have 'paid' much smaller growing =
costs to get=20
      into the canopy. The total economy of the forest would benefit, =
and so=20
      would every individual tree. Unfortunately, natural selection =
doesn't care=20
      about total economies, and it has no room for cartels and =
agreements.=20
      There has been an arms race in which forest trees became larger as =
the=20
      generations went by. At every stage of the arms race there was no=20
      intrinsic benefit in being tall for its own sake. At every stage =
of the=20
      arms race the only point in being tall was </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">to </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">be relatively taller than =
neighbouring=20
      trees. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.7pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">As the arms race wore on, the =
average=20
      height </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">of trees =
in=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the forest =
canopy went=20
      up. But the benefit that the trees obtained from being tall did =
not go up.=20
      It actually deteriorated because of the enhanced costs of growing. =

      Successive generations of trees got taller and taller, but at the =
end they=20
      might better, in one sense, have stayed where they started. Here, =
then, is=20
      the connection with Alice and the Red Queen, but you can see that =
in the=20
      case of the trees it is not really paradoxical. It is generally=20
      characteristic of arms races, including human ones, that although =
all=20
      would be better off if </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">none </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">of them escalated,, so long as =
one of=20
      them escalates none can afford </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">not </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">to. Once again, by the way, I =
should=20
      stress that I have told the story too simply. I do not mean to =
suggest=20
      that in every literal generation trees are taller than their =
counterparts=20
      in the previous generation, nor that the arms race is necessarily =
still=20
      going on. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
3.9pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Another point illustrated by =
the trees is=20
      that arms races do not necessarily have to be between members of =
different=20
      species. Individual trees are just as likely to be harmfully =
overshadowed=20
      by members of their own species as by members of other species. =
Probably=20
      more so in fact, for all organisms are more seriously threatened =
by=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
3.9pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D9 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D65 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D9>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D9=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image068.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D66></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D9 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D26 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D9>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D9=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image069.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D26></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 2.4pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Constructive evolution =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">185 <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.3pt 0pt 1.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">competition from their own =
species than=20
      from others. Members of one's own species are competitors for the =
same=20
      resources, to a much more detailed extent, than members of other =
species.=20
      There are also arms races within species between male roles and =
female=20
      roles, and between parent roles and offspring roles. I have =
discussed=20
      these in </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The =
Selfish=20
      Gene, </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">and will =
not=20
      pursue them further here. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.85pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The tree story allows me to =
introduce an=20
      important general distinction between two kinds of arms race, =
called=20
      symmetric and asymmetric arms races. A symmetric arms race is one =
between=20
      competitors trying to do roughly the same thing as each other. The =
arms=20
      race between forest trees struggling to reach the light is an =
example. The=20
      different species of trees are not all making their livings in =
exactly the=20
      same way, but as far as the particular race we are talking about =
is=20
      concerned - the race for the sunlight above the canopy - they are=20
      competitors for the same resource. They are taking part in an arms =
race in=20
      which success on one side is felt by the other side as failure. =
And it is=20
      a symmetric arms race because the nature of the success and =
failure on the=20
      two sides is the same: attainment of sunlight and being =
overshadowed,=20
      respectively. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The arms race between cheetahs =
and=20
      gazelles, however, is asymmetric. It is a true arms race in which =
success=20
      on either side is felt as failure by the other side, but the =
nature of the=20
      success and failure on the two sides is very different. The two =
sides are=20
      'trying' to do very different things. Cheetahs are trying to eat =
gazelles.=20
      Gazelles are not trying to eat cheetahs, they are trying to avoid =
being=20
      eaten by cheetahs. From an evolutionary point of view asymmetric =
arms=20
      races are more interesting, since they are more likely to generate =
highly=20
      complex weapons systems. We can see why this is by taking examples =
from=20
      human weapons technology. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
1pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">I could use the USA and the =
USSR as=20
      examples, but there is really no need to mention specific nations. =
Weapons=20
      manufactured by companies in any of the advanced industrial =
countries may=20
      end up being bought by any of a wide variety of nations. The =
existence of=20
      a <BR>successful offensive weapon, such as the Exocet type of =
surface=20
      skimming missile, tends to 'invite' the invention of an effective =
counter,=20
      for instance a radio jamming device to 'confuse' the control =
system of the=20
      missile. The counter is more likely than not to be manufactured by =
an=20
      enemy country, but it could be manufactured by the same country, =
even by=20
      the same company! No company, after all, is better equipped to =
design a=20
      jamming device for a particular missile than the company that made =
the=20
      missile in the first place. There is nothing inherently improbable =
about=20
      the same company producing both and selling them </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
1pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D381 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 4.55pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">186 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05pt 0pt 3.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: 'Times-Bold Italic'">to </SPAN></I></B><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">opposite sides </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">in a </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">war. I am cynical enough to =
suspect that=20
      it probably happens, and it vividly illustrates the point about=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">equipment=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">improving =
while its net=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">effectiveness=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">stands still =
(and its=20
      costs increase). </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.5pt 0pt 2.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">From my present point of view =
the=20
      question of whether the manufacturers on opposite sides of a human =
arms=20
      race are enemies of each other or identical with each other is =
irrelevant,=20
      and interestingly so. What matters is that, regardless of their=20
      manufacturers, the devices themselves are enemies of each other in =
the=20
      special sense I have defined in this chapter. The missile, and its =

      specific jamming device, are enemies of each other in that success =
in one=20
      is synonymous with failure in the other. Whether their designers =
are also=20
      enemies of each other is irrelevant, although it will probably be =
easier=20
      to assume that they are. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.25pt 0pt 2.15pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">So far I have discussed the =
example of=20
      the missile and its specific antidote without stressing the =
evolutionary,=20
      progressive aspect, which is, after all, the main reason for =
bringing it=20
      into this chapter. The point here is that not only does the =
present design=20
      of a missile invite, or call forth, a suitable antidote, say a =
radio=20
      jamming device. The antimissile device, in its turn, invites an=20
      improvement in the design of the missile, an improvement that =
specifically=20
      counters the antidote, an anti- antimissile device. It is almost =
as though=20
      each improvement in the missile stimulates the next improvement=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">in itself,=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">via its effect =
on the=20
      <BR>antidote. Improvement in equipment feeds on itself. This is a =
recipe=20
      for explosive, runaway evolution. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.3pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">At the end of some years of =
this=20
      ding-dong invention and counterinvention, the current version of =
both the=20
      missile and its antidote will have attained a very high degree of=20
      sophistication. Yet at the same time =97 here is the Red Queen =
effect again=20
      - there is no general reason for expecting either side in the arms =
race to=20
      be any more successful at doing its job than it was at the =
beginning of=20
      the arms race. Indeed if both the missile and its antidote have =
been=20
      improving at the same rate, we can expect that the latest, most =
advanced=20
      and sophisticated versions, and the earliest, most primitive and =
simplest=20
      versions will be exactly as successful as each other, against =
their=20
      contemporary counter-devices. There has been progress in design, =
but no=20
      progress in accomplishment, specifically because there has been =
equal=20
      progress in design on both sides of the arms race. Indeed, it is =
precisely=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">because =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">there has been approximately =
equal=20
      progress on both sides that there has been so much progress in the =
level=20
      of sophistication of design. If one side, say the antimissile =
jamming=20
      device, pulled too far ahead in the design race, the other side, =
the=20
      missile in this case, would simply </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.3pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D386 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle30 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 2.15pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica-Oblique">Constructive evolution=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica">187 =
</SPAN><BR><BR></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.5pt 0pt 1.7pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">cease to be used and =
manufactured: it=20
      would go 'extinct'. Far from being paradoxical like Alice's =
original=20
      example, the Red Queen effect in its arms-race context turns out =
to be=20
      fundamental to the very idea of progressive advancement. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.2pt 0pt 1.45pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">I said that asymmetric arms =
races were=20
      more likely to lead to interesting progressive improvements than =
symmetric=20
      ones, and we can now see why this is, using human weapons to =
illustrate=20
      the point. If one nation has a 2-megaton bomb, the enemy nation =
will=20
      develop a 5-megaton bomb. This provokes the first nation into =
developing a=20
      10- megaton bomb, which in turn provokes the second into making a =
20-=20
      megaton bomb, and so on. This is a true progressive arms race: =
each=20
      advance on one side provokes the counter-advance on the other, and =
the=20
      result is a steady increase in some attribute as time goes by - in =
this=20
      case, explosive power of bombs. But there is no detailed, one- =
toone=20
      correspondence between the designs in such a symmetric arms race, =
no=20
      'meshing' or 'interlocking' of design details as there is in an =
asymmetric=20
      arms race such as that between missile and missile- jamming =
device. The=20
      missile-jamming device is designed specificially to overcome =
particular=20
      detailed features of the missile; the designer of the antidote =
takes into=20
      account minute details of the design of the missile. Then in =
designing a=20
      counter to the antidote, the designer of the next generation of =
missiles=20
      makes use of his knowledge of the detailed design of the antidote =
to the=20
      previous generation. This is not true of the bombs of =
ever-increasing=20
      megatonnage. To be sure, designers on one side may pirate good =
ideas, may=20
      imitate design features, from the other side. But if so, this is=20
      incidental. It is not a </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">necessary </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">part of the design of a Russian =
bomb that=20
      it should have detailed, oneto- one correspondences with specific =
details=20
      of an American bomb. In the case of an asymmetric arms race, =
between a=20
      lineage of weapons and the specific antidotes to those weapons, it =
is the=20
      one-to-one correspondences that, over the successive =
'generations', lead=20
      to ever greater sophistication and complexity. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 5.95pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">In the living world too, we =
shall expect=20
      to find complex and sophisticated design wherever we are dealing =
with the=20
      end-products of a long, asymmetric arms race in which advances on =
one side=20
      have always been matched, on a one-to-one, point-for-point basis, =
by=20
      equally successful </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">antidotes </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">(as opposed to competitors) on =
the other.=20
      This is conspicuously true of the arms races between predators and =
their=20
      prey, and, perhaps even more, of arms races between parasites and =
hosts.=20
      The electronic and acoustic weapons systems of bats, which we =
discussed in=20
      Chapter 2, have all the finely tuned sophistication that we expect =
from=20
      the end-products of a long arms race. Not surprisingly, we =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 5.95pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D381 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle18 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.25pt 0pt 3.1pt"><B><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">188 </SPAN></B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker=20
      </SPAN><BR><BR></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 2.15pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt">can=20
      trace this same arms race on the other side. The insects that bats =
prey=20
      upon have a comparable battery of sophisticated electronic and =
acoustic=20
      gear. Some moths even emit bat-like (ultra-) sounds that seem to =
put the=20
      bats off. Almost all animals are either in danger of being eaten =
by other=20
      animals or in danger of failing to eat other animals, and an =
enormous=20
      number of detailed facts about animals makes sense only when we =
remember=20
      that they are the end-products of long and bitter arms races. H. =
B. Cott,=20
      author of the classic book <I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Animal Coloration, =
</SPAN></I>put the=20
      point well in 1940, in what may be the first use in print of the =
arms-race=20
      analogy in biology: <BR><BR></P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 6.05pt 0pt 11.75pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
9.9pt">Before=20
      asserting that the deceptive appearance of a grasshopper or =
butterfly is=20
      unnecessarily detailed, we must first ascertain what are the =
powers of=20
      perception and discrimination of the insects' natural enemies. Not =
to do=20
      so is like asserting that the armour of a battle-cruiser is too =
heavy, or=20
      the range of her guns too great, without inquiring into the nature =
and=20
      effectiveness of the enemy's armament. The fact is that in the =
primeval=20
      struggle of the jungle, as in the refinements of civilized =
warfare, we see=20
      in progress a great evolutionary armament race =97 whose results, =
for=20
      defence, are manifested in such devices as speed, alertness, =
armour,=20
      spinescence, burrowing habits, nocturnal habits, poisonous =
secretions,=20
      nauseous taste, and (camouflage and other kinds of protective =
coloration],=20
      and for offence, in such <BR>counter-attributes as speed, =
surprise,=20
      ambush, allurement, visual acuity, claws, teeth, stings, poison =
fangs, and=20
      [lures]. Just as greater speed in the pursued has developed in =
relation to=20
      increased speed in the pursuer; or defensive armour in relation to =

      aggressive weapons; so the perfection of concealing devices has =
evolved in=20
      response to increased powers of perception. <BR><BR></P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.8pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt">Arms=20
      races in human technology are easier to study than their =
biological=20
      equivalents because they are so much faster. We can actually see =
them=20
      going on, from year to year. In the case of a biological arms =
race, on the=20
      other hand, we can usually see only the end-products. Very rarely =
a dead=20
      animal or plant fossilizes, and it is then sometimes possible to =
see=20
      progressive stages in an animal arms race a little more directly. =
One of=20
      the most interesting examples of this concerns the electronic arms =
race,=20
      as shown in the brain sizes of fossil animals. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.2pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt">Brains=20
      themselves do not fossilize but skulls do, and the cavity in which =
the=20
      brain was housed - the braincase - if interpreted with care, can =
give a=20
      good indication of brain size. I said 'if interpreted with care', =
and the=20
      qualification is an important one. Among the many problems is the=20
      following. Big animals tend to have big brains partly just because =
they=20
      are big, but this doesn't necessarily mean that they are, in any=20
      interesting sense, 'cleverer'. Elephants have bigger brains than =
humans=20
      </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.2pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D8 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D67 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D8>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D8=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image070.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D68></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D381 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.2pt 0pt 3.35pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Constructive evolution =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">189 <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 2.9pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">but, probably with some =
justice, we like=20
      to think that we are cleverer than elephants and that our brains =
are=20
      'really' bigger if you make allowance for the fact that we are =
much=20
      smaller animals. Certainly </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">our </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">brains occupy a much larger=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">proportion=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">of our body =
than=20
      elephants' brains do, as is evident from the bulging shape of our =
skulls.=20
      This is </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">not=20
      </SPAN></B><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">just=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">species =
vanity.=20
      Presumably a substantial fraction of any brain is needed to =
perform=20
      routine caretaking operations around the body, and a big body=20
      automatically needs a big brain for this. We must find some way of =
'taking=20
      out' of our calculations that fraction of brain that can be =
attributed=20
      simply to body size, so that we can compare what is left over=20
      </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">as =
</SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the true 'braininess' of =
animals. This is=20
      another way of saying </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold">that=20
      we </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">need some =
good way of=20
      defining exactly what we mean by </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">true </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">braininess. Different people =
are at=20
      liberty to come up with different methods of doing the =
calculations, but=20
      probably the most authoritative index is the 'encephalization =
quotient' or=20
      EQ used by Harry Jerison, a leading American authority on brain =
history.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.55pt 0pt 1.45pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The EQ is actually calculated =
in a=20
      somewhat complicated way, taking logarithms of brain weight and =
body=20
      weight, and standardizing against the average figures for a major =
group=20
      such as the mammals as a whole. Just as the 'intelligence =
quotient' or IQ=20
      used (or it may be misused) by human psychologists is standardized =
against=20
      the average for a whole population, the EQ is standardized =
against, say,=20
      the whole of the mammals. Just as an IQ of 100 means, by =
definition, an IQ=20
      identical to the average for a whole population, so an EQ of 1 =
means, by=20
      definition, an EQ identical to the average for, say, mammals of =
that size.=20
      The details of the mathematical technique don't matter. In words, =
the EQ=20
      of a given species such as a rhino or a cat, is a measure of how =
much=20
      bigger (or smaller) the animal's brain is than we should =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">expect </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">it to be, given the animal's =
body size.=20
      How that expectation is calculated is certainly open to debate and =

      criticism. The fact that humans have an EQ of 7 and hippos an EQ =
of 0.3=20
      may not literally mean that humans are 23 times as clever as =
hippos! But=20
      the EQ as measured is probably telling us </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">something </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">about how much 'computing =
power' an=20
      animal has in its head, over and above the irreducible minimum of=20
      computing power needed for the routine running of its large or =
small body.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.4pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Measured EQs among modern =
mammals are=20
      very varied. Rats have an EQ of about 0.8, slightly below the =
average for=20
      all mammals. Squirrels are somewhat higher, about 1.5. Perhaps the =

      threedimensional world of trees demands extra computing power for=20
      controlling precision leaps, and even more for thinking about =
efficient=20
      paths through a maze of branches that may or may not connect =
farther on.=20
      Monkeys are well above average, and apes (especially ourselves)=20
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.4pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.2pt 0pt 1.45pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">190 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">even higher. Within the monkeys =
it turns=20
      out that some types have higher EQs than others and that, =
interestingly,=20
      there is some connection with how they make their living: =
insect-eating=20
      and fruit-eating monkeys have bigger brains, for their size, than=20
      leaf-eating monkeys. It makes some sense to argue that an animal =
needs=20
      less computing power to find leaves, which are abundant all =
around, than=20
      to find fruit, which may have to be searched for, or to catch =
insects,=20
      which take active steps to get away. Unfortunately, it is now =
looking as=20
      though the true story is more complicated, and that other =
variables, such=20
      as metabolic rate, may be more important. In the mammals as a =
whole,=20
      carnivores typically have a slightly higher EQ than the herbivores =
upon=20
      which they prey. The reader will probably have some ideas about =
why this=20
      might be, but it is hard to test such ideas. Anyway, whatever the =
reason,=20
      it seems to be a fact. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.45pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">So much for modern animals. =
What Jerison=20
      has done is to reconstruct the probable EQs of extinct animals =
that now=20
      exist only as fossils. He has to estimate brain size by making =
plaster=20
      casts of the insides of braincases. Quite a lot of guesswork and=20
      estimation has to go into this, but the margins of error are not =
so great=20
      as to nullify the whole enterprise. The methods of taking plaster =
casts=20
      can, after all, be checked for their accuracy, using modern =
animals. We=20
      make-believe that the dried skull is all that we have from a modem =
animal,=20
      use a plaster cast to estimate how big its brain was from the =
skull alone,=20
      and then check with the real brain to see how accurate our =
estimate was.=20
      These checks on modem skulls encourage confidence in Jerison's =
estimates=20
      of long-dead brains. His conclusion is, firstly, that there is a =
tendency=20
      for brains to become bigger as the millions of years go by. At any =
given=20
      time, the current herbivores tended to have smaller brains than =
the=20
      contemporary carnivores that preyed on them. But later herbivores =
tended=20
      to have larger brains than earlier herbivores, and later =
carnivores larger=20
      brains than earlier carnivores. We seem to be seeing, in the =
fossils, an=20
      arms race, or rather a series of restarting arms races, between =
carnivores=20
      and herbivores. This is a particularly pleasing parallel with =
human=20
      armament races, since the brain is the on-board computer used by =
both=20
      carnivores and herbivores, and electronics is probably the most =
rapidly=20
      advancing element in human weapons technology today. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.35pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">How do arms races end? =
Sometimes they may=20
      end with one side going extinct, in which case the other side =
presumably=20
      stops evolving in that particular progressive direction, and =
indeed it=20
      will probably even 'regress' for economic reasons soon to be =
discussed. In=20
      other cases, economic pressures may impose a stable halt to an =
arms race,=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.35pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D10 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D34 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D10>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D10 =

      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
