g"=20
      width=3D42></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D383 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle15 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 4.3pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Constructive evolution =
</SPAN></I>191=20
      <SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle15=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.8pt 0pt 3.35pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt">stable=20
      even though one side in the race is, in a sense, permanently =
ahead. Take=20
      running speed, for instance. There must be an ultimate limit to =
the speed=20
      at which a cheetah or a gazelle can run, a limit imposed by the =
laws of=20
      physics. But neither cheetahs nor gazelles have reached that =
limit. Both=20
      have pushed up against a lower limit which is, I believe, economic =
in=20
      character. High-speed technology is not cheap. It demands long leg =
bones,=20
      powerful muscles, capacious lungs. These things can be had by any =
animal=20
      that really needs to run fast, but they must be <I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">bought. </SPAN></I>They are =
bought at a=20
      steeply increasing price. The price is measured as what economists =
call=20
      'opportunity cost'. The opportunity cost of something is measured =
as the=20
      sum of all the other things that you have to forgo in order to =
have that=20
      something. The cost of sending a child to a private, fee-paying =
school is=20
      all the things that you can't afford to buy as a result: the new =
car that=20
      you can't afford, the holidays in the sun that you can't afford =
(if you're=20
      so rich that you can afford all these things easily, the =
opportunity cost,=20
      to you, of sending your child to a private school may be next to =
nothing).=20
      The price, to a cheetah, of growing larger leg muscles is all the =
other=20
      things that the cheetah <I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">could=20
      have done </SPAN></I>with the materials and energy used to make =
the leg=20
      muscles, for instance make more milk for cubs. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle15=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.35pt 0pt 1.45pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt">There=20
      is no suggestion, of course, that cheetahs do cost-accounting sums =
in=20
      their heads! It is all done automatically by ordinary natural =
selection. A=20
      rival cheetah that doesn't have such big leg muscles may not run =
quite so=20
      fast, but it has resources to spare for making an extra lot of =
milk and=20
      therefore perhaps rearing another cub. More cubs will be reared by =

      cheetahs whose genes equip them with the optimum compromise =
between=20
      running speed, milk production and all the other calls on their =
budget. It=20
      isn't obvious what the optimum trade-off is between, say, milk =
production=20
      and running speed. It will certainly be different for different =
species,=20
      and it may fluctuate within each species. All that is certain is =
that=20
      trade-offs of this kind will be inevitable. When both cheetahs and =

      gazelles reach the maximum running speed that they can 'afford', =
in their=20
      own internal economies, the arms race between them will come to an =
end.=20
      </P>
      <P class=3DStyle15=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.95pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt">Their=20
      respective economic stopping points may not leave them exactly =
equally=20
      matched. Prey animals may end up spending relatively more of their =
budget=20
      on defensive weaponry than predators do on offensive weaponry. One =
reason=20
      for this is summarized in the Aesopian moral: The rabbit runs =
faster than=20
      the fox, because the rabbit is running for his life, while the fox =
is only=20
      running for his dinner. In economic terms, this means that =
individual=20
      foxes that shift resources into other projects can do better than=20
      individual foxes that spend </P>
      <P class=3DStyle15=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.95pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D380 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.45pt 0pt 1.9pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">192 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.45pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">virtually all their resources =
on hunting=20
      technology. In the rabbit population, on the other hand, the =
balance of=20
      economic advantage is shifted towards those individual rabbits =
that are=20
      big spenders </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">on=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">equipment for =
running=20
      fast. The upshot of these economically balanced budgets =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">within </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">species is that arms races=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">between =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">species tend to come to a =
mutually stable=20
      end, with one side ahead. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.7pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">We are unlikely to witness arms =
races in=20
      dynamic progress, because they are unlikely to be running at any=20
      particular 'moment' of geological time, such as our time. But the =
animals=20
      that are to be seen in our time can be interpreted as the =
end-products of=20
      an arms race that was run in the past. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.15pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">To summarize the message of =
this chapter,=20
      genes are selected, not for their intrinsic qualities, but by =
virtue of=20
      their interactions with their environments. An especially =
important=20
      component of a gene's environment is other genes. The general =
reason why=20
      this is such </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">an=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">important =
component is=20
      that other genes also change, as generations go by in evolution. =
This has=20
      two main kinds of consequences. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.95pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">First, it has meant that those =
genes are=20
      favoured that have the property of 'cooperating' with those other =
genes=20
      that they are likely to meet in circumstances that favour =
cooperation.=20
      This is especially, though not exclusively, true of genes within =
the same=20
      species, because genes within one species frequently share cells =
with one=20
      another. It has led to the evolution of large gangs of cooperating =
genes,=20
      and ultimately to the evolution of bodies themselves, as the =
products of=20
      their cooperative enterprise. An individual body is a large =
vehicle or=20
      'survival machine' built by a gene cooperative, for the =
preservation of=20
      copies of each member of that cooperative. They cooperate because =
they all=20
      stand to gain from the same outcome - the survival and =
reproduction of the=20
      communal body - and because they constitute an important part of =
the=20
      environment in which natural selection works on each other. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.45pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Second, circumstances don't =
always favour=20
      cooperation. In their march down geological time, genes also =
encounter one=20
      another </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">in=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">circumstances =
that=20
      favour antagonism. This is especially, though not exclusively, =
true of=20
      genes in different species. The point about different species is =
that=20
      their genes don't mix =97 because members of different species =
can't mate=20
      with one another. When selected genes in one species provide the=20
      environment in which genes in another species </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">are </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">selected, the result is often =
an=20
      evolutionary arms race. Each new genetic improvement selected on =
one side=20
      of the arms race - say predators - changes the environment for =
selection=20
      of genes on the other side of the arms race - prey. It is arms =
races of=20
      this kind that have </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.45pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D485 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D381 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D485>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 2.9pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Constructive evolution =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">193 <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.25pt 0pt 2.15pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.55pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">been mainly responsible for the =

      apparently </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">progressive=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">quality of =
evolution,=20
      for the evolution of ever-improved running speed, flying skill, =
acuity of=20
      eyesight, keenness of hearing, and so on. These arms races don't =
go on=20
      forever, but stabilize when, for instance, further improvements =
become too=20
      economically costly to the individual animals concerned. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.75pt 0pt 1.45pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">This has been a difficult =
chapter, but it=20
      had to go into the book. Without it, we would have been left with =
the=20
      feeling that natural selection is only a destructive process, or =
at best a=20
      process of weeding-out. We have seen two ways in which natural =
selection=20
      can be a </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">constructive=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">force. One way =
concerns=20
      cooperative relationships between genes within species. Our =
fundamental=20
      assumption must be that genes are 'selfish' entities, working for =
their=20
      own propagation in the gene pool of the species. But because the=20
      environment of a gene consists, to such a salient degree, of=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">other =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">genes also being selected in =
the same=20
      gene pool, genes will be favoured if they are good at cooperating =
with=20
      other genes in the same gene pool. This is why large bodies of =
cells,=20
      working coherently towards the same cooperative ends, have =
evolved. This=20
      is why bodies exist, rather than separate replicators still =
battling it=20
      out in the primordial soup. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.8pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Bodies evolve integrated and =
coherent=20
      purposefulness because genes are selected in the environment =
provided by=20
      other genes </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">within the=20
      same species. </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman">But=20
      because genes are also selected in the environment provided by =
other genes=20
      in different species, arms races develop. And arms races =
constitute the=20
      other great force propelling evolution in directions that we =
recognize as=20
      'progressive', complex 'design'. Arms races have an inherently =
unstable=20
      'runaway' feel to them. They career off into the future in a way =
that is,=20
      in one sense, pointless and futile, in another sense progressive =
and=20
      endlessly fascinating to us, the observers. The next chapter takes =
up a=20
      particular, rather special case of explosive, runaway evolution, =
the case=20
      that Darwin called sexual selection. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.8pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D9 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D66 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D9>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D9=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
