<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D508 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D360 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D508>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"><IMG=20
      height=3D508=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image074.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D360></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D561 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D561>
      <P class=3DStyle16 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 103.65pt 0pt =
111.1pt">CHAPTER 8 <SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <H2 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 27.55pt 0pt 35.3pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 17pt">EXPLOSIONS AND SPIRALS </SPAN><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR><BR><BR></SPAN></H2>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The human mind is an inveterate =

      analogizer. We are compulsively drawn to see meaning in slight=20
      similarities between very different processes. I spent much of a =
day in=20
      Panama watching two teeming colonies of leaf-cutter ants fighting, =
and my=20
      mind irresistibly compared the limb-strewn battlefield to pictures =
I had=20
      seen of Passchendaele. I could almost hear the guns and smell the =
smoke.=20
      Shortly after my first book, </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Selfish Gene, =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">was published, I was =
independently=20
      approached by two clergymen, who both had arrived at the same =
analogy=20
      between ideas in the book and the doctrine of original sin. Darwin =
applied=20
      the idea of evolution in a discriminating way to living organisms =
changing=20
      in body form over countless generations. His successors have been =
tempted=20
      to see evolution in everything; in the changing form of the =
universe, in=20
      developmental 'stages' of human civilizations, in fashions in =
skirt=20
      lengths. Sometimes such analogies can be immensely fruitful, but =
it is=20
      easy to push analogies too far, and get overexcited by analogies =
that are=20
      so tenuous as to be unhelpful or even downright harmful. I have =
become=20
      accustomed to receiving my share of crank mail, and have learned =
that one=20
      of the hallmarks of futile crankiness is overenthusiastic =
analogizing.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle6=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">On the other hand, some of the =
greatest=20
      advances in science have come about because some clever person =
spotted an=20
      analogy between a subject that was already understood, and another =
still=20
      mysterious <BR>subject. The trick is to strike a balance between =
too much=20
      indiscriminate analogizing on the one hand, and a sterile =
blindness to=20
      fruitful analogies on the other. The successful scientist and the =
raving=20
      crank are separated by the quality of their inspirations. But I =
suspect=20
      that this amounts, in practice, to a difference, not so much in =
ability to=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">notice=20
      </SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.1pt 0pt 256.8pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">195 </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.1pt 0pt 256.8pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D380 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.1pt 0pt 3.35pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">196 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 2.4pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">analogies as in ability to=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">reject =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">foolish analogies and pursue =
helpful=20
      ones. Passing over the fact that we have here yet another analogy, =
which=20
      may be foolish or may be fruitful (and is certainly not original), =
between=20
      scientific progress and Darwinian evolutionary selection, let me =
now come=20
      to the point that is relevant to this chapter. This is that I am =
about to=20
      embark on two interwoven analogies which I find inspiring but =
which can be=20
      taken too far if we are not careful. The first is an analogy =
between=20
      various processes that are united by their <BR>resemblance to =
explosions.=20
      The second is an analogy between true Darwinian evolution and what =
has=20
      been called cultural evolution. I think that these analogies may =
be=20
      fruitful - obviously, or I would not devote a chapter to them. But =
the=20
      reader is warned. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.85pt 0pt 1.45pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The property of explosions that =
is=20
      relevant is the one known to engineers as 'positive feedback'. =
Positive=20
      feedback is best understood by comparison with its opposite, =
negative=20
      feedback. Negative feedback is the basis of most automatic control =
and=20
      regulation, and one of its neatest and best-known examples is the =
Watt=20
      steam governor. A useful engine should deliver rotational power at =
a=20
      constant rate, the right rate for the job in hand, milling, =
weaving,=20
      pumping or whatever it happens to be. Before Watt, the problem was =
that=20
      the rate of turning depended upon the steam pressure. Stoke the =
boiler and=20
      you speed up the engine, not a satisfactory state of affairs for a =
mill or=20
      loom that requires uniform drive for its machines. Watt's governor =
was an=20
      automatic valve regulating the flow of steam to the piston. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.05pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The clever trick was to link =
the valve to=20
      the rotary motion produced by the engine, in such a way that the =
faster=20
      the engine ran the more the valve shut down the steam. Conversely, =
when=20
      the engine was running slowly, the valve opened up. Therefore an =
engine=20
      going too slowly soon speeded up, and an engine going too fast =
soon slowed=20
      down. The precise means by which the governor measured the speed =
was=20
      simple but effective, and the principle is still used today. A =
pair of=20
      balls on hinged arms spin round, driven by the engine. When they =
are=20
      spinning fast, the balls rise up on their hinges, by centrifugal =
force.=20
      When they are spinning slowly, they hang down. The hinged arms are =

      directly linked to the steam throttle. With suitable fine-tuning, =
the Watt=20
      governor can keep a steam engine turning at an almost constant =
rate, in=20
      the face of considerable fluctuations in the firebox. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.5pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The underlying principle of the =
Watt=20
      governor is negative feedback. The output of the engine (rotary =
motion in=20
      this case) is fed back into the engine (via the steam valve). The =
feedback=20
      is </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">negative=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">because high =
output=20
      (fast rotation of the balls) has a negative effect upon the input =
(steam=20
      supply). Conversely, low output (slow rotation of the balls) =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.5pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D382 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 3.1pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Explosions and spirals =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">197 <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.95pt 0pt 2.4pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">boosts the input (of steam), =
again=20
      reversing the sign. But I introduced the idea of negative feedback =
only in=20
      order to contrast it with positive feedback. Let us take a =
Watt-governed=20
      steam engine, and make one crucial change in it. We reverse the =
sign of=20
      the relationship between the centrifugal ball apparatus and the =
steam=20
      valve. Now when the balls spin fast, the valve, instead of closing =
as Watt=20
      had it, </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">opens. =

      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Conversely, =
when the=20
      balls spin slowly, the valve, instead of increasing the flow of =
steam,=20
      reduces it. In a normal, Watt-governed engine, an engine that =
started to=20
      slow down would soon correct this tendency and speed up again to =
the=20
      desired speed. But our doctored engine does just the opposite. If =
it=20
      starts to slow down, this makes it slow down even more. =
</SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">It </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">soon throttles itself down to a =
halt. If,=20
      on the other hand, such a doctored engine happens to speed up a =
little,=20
      instead of the tendency being corrected as it would in a proper =
Watt=20
      engine, the tendency is increased. The slight speeding up is =
reinforced by=20
      the inverted governor, and the engine accelerates. The =
acceleration feeds=20
      back positively, and the engine accelerates even more. This =
continues=20
      until either the engine breaks up under the strain and the runaway =

      flywheel careers through the factory wall, or no more steam =
pressure is=20
      available and a maximum speed is imposed. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.65pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Where the original Watt =
governor makes=20
      use of negative feedback, </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">our </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">hypothetical doctored governor=20
      exemplifies the opposite process of positive feedback. =
Positive-feedback=20
      processes have an unstable, runaway quality. Slight initial =
perturbations=20
      are increased, and they run away in an ever-increasing spiral, =
which=20
      culminates either in disaster or in an eventual throttling down at =
some=20
      higher level due to other processes. Engineers have found it =
fruitful to=20
      unite a wide variety of processes under the single heading of =
negative=20
      feedback, and another wide variety under the heading of positive =
feedback.=20
      The analogies are fruitful not just in some vague qualitative =
sense, but=20
      because all the processes share the same underlying mathematics.=20
      Biologists studying such phenomena as temperature control in the =
body, and=20
      the satiation mechanisms that prevent overeating, have found it =
helpful to=20
      borrow the mathematics of negative feedback from engineers. =
Positive-=20
      feedback systems are used less than negative feedback, both by =
engineers=20
      and by living bodies, but nevertheless it is positive feedbacks =
that are=20
      the subject of this chapter. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.85pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The reason engineers and living =
bodies=20
      make more use of negative than positive-feedback systems is, of =
course,=20
      that controlled regulation near an optimum is useful. Unstable =
runaway=20
      processes, far from being useful, can be downright dangerous. In=20
      chemistry, the typical positivefeedback process is an explosion, =
and we=20
      commonly use the word </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.85pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D16 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D18 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D16>
      <P class=3DStyle5><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">198=20
      </SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D16 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D133 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D16>
      <P class=3DStyle6><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The =
Blind=20
      Watchmaker </SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle6><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D601 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D380 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D601>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.7pt 0pt 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">explosive as a description of =
any runaway=20
      process. For instance, we may refer to somebody as having an =
explosive=20
      temper. One of my schoolmasters was a cultured, courteous and =
usually=20
      gentle man, but he had occasional explosions of temper, as he =
himself was=20
      aware. When extremely provoked in class he would say nothing at =
first, but=20
      his face showed that something unusual was going on inside. Then,=20
      beginning in a quiet and reasonable tone he would say: 'Oh dear. I =
can't=20
      hold it. I'm going to lose my temper. Get down below your desks. =
I'm=20
      warning you. It's coming.' All the time his voice was rising, and =
at the=20
      crescendo he would seize everything within reach, books, =
<BR>woodenbacked=20
      blackboard erasers, paperweights, inkpots, and hurl them in quick=20
      succession, with the utmost force and ferocity but with wild aim, =
in the=20
      general direction of the boy who had provoked him. His temper then =

      gradually subsided, and next day he would offer the most gracious =
apology=20
      to the same boy. He was aware that he had gone out of control, he =
had=20
      witnessed himself becoming the victim of a positivefeedback loop.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.95pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">But positive feedbacks don't =
only lead to=20
      runaway increases; they can lead to runaway decreases. I recently =
attended=20
      a debate in Congregation, Oxford University's 'parliament', on =
whether to=20
      offer an honorary degree to somebody. Unusually, the decision was =
a=20
      <BR>controversial one. After the vote, during the 15 minutes that =
it took=20
      to count the ballot papers, there was a general hubbub of =
conversation=20
      from those waiting to hear the result. At one point the =
conversation=20
      strangely died away, and there was total silence. The reason was a =

      particular kind of positive feedback. It worked as follows. In any =
general=20
      buzz of conversation there are bound to be chance fluctuations in =
noise=20
      level, both up and down, which we normally don't notice. One of =
these=20
      chance fluctuations, in the direction of quietness, happened to be =

      slightly more marked than usual, with the result that some people =
noticed=20
      it. Since everybody was anxiously waiting for the result of the =
vote to be=20
      announced, those that heard the random decrease in noise level =
looked up=20
      and ceased their conversation. This caused the general noise level =
to go=20
      down a little more, with the result that more people noticed it =
and=20
      stopped their conversation. A positive feedback had been initiated =
and it=20
      continued rather rapidly until there was total silence in the =
hall. Then,=20
      when we realized that it was a false alarm, there was a laugh =
followed by=20
      a slow escalation in noise back up to its former level. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.25pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The most noticeable and =
spectacular=20
      positive feedbacks are those that result, not in a decrease, but =
in a=20
      runaway increase in something: a nuclear explosion, a schoolmaster =
losing=20
      his temper, a brawl in a pub, escalating invective at the United =
Nations=20
      (the reader may heed the </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.25pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D635 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D386 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D635>
      <P class=3DStyle5 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 6pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Explosions and spirals=20
      </SPAN></I><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">199=20
      </SPAN></B><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.55pt 0pt 4.8pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">warning with which I began this =
chapter).=20
      The importance of positive feedbacks in international affairs is=20
      implicitly recognized in the jargon word 'escalation': when we say =
that=20
      the Middle East is a 'powder keg', and when we identify =
'flashpoints'. One=20
      of the best-known expressions of the idea of positive feedback is =
in St=20
      Matthew's Gospel: 'Unto everyone that hath shall be given, and he =
shall=20
      have abundance: but from him that hath not shall be taken away =
even that=20
      which he hath.' This chapter is about positive feedbacks in =
evolution.=20
      There are some features of living organisms that look as though =
they are=20
      the endproducts of something like an explosive, =
positive-feedback-driven,=20
      runaway process of evolution. In a mild way the arms races of the =
previous=20
      chapter are examples of this, but the really spectacular examples =
are to=20
      be found in organs of sexual advertisement. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle6=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.7pt 0pt 3.1pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Try to persuade yourself, as =
they tried=20
      to persuade me when I was an undergraduate, that the peacock's fan =
is a=20
      mundanely functional organ like a tooth or a kidney, fashioned by =
natural=20
      selection to do no more than the utilitarian job of labelling the =
bird,=20
      unambiguously as a member of this species and not that. They never =

      persuaded me, and I doubt if you can be persuaded either. For me =
the=20
      peacock's fan has the unmistakable stamp of positive feedback. It =
is=20
      clearly the product of some kind of uncontrolled, unstable =
explosion that=20
      took place in evolutionary time. So thought Darwin in his theory =
of sexual=20
      selection and so, explicitly and in so many words, thought the =
greatest of=20
      his successors, R. A. Fisher. After a short piece of reasoning he=20
      concluded (in his book </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Genetical Theory of =
Natural=20
      Selection}: </SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 6.85pt 0pt 11.3pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 9.8pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">plumage development in the =
male, and=20
      sexual preference for such developments in the female, must thus =
advance=20
      together, and so long as </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">the </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">process is unchecked by severe=20
      counterselection, will advance with <BR>ever-increasing speed. In =
the=20
      total absence of such checks, it is easy to see that the speed of=20
      development will be proportional to the development already =
attained,=20
      which will therefore increase with time exponentially, =
</SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">or </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">in geometric progression. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.85pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">It is typical of Fisher that =
what he=20
      found 'easy to see' was not fully understood by others until half =
a=20
      century later. He did not bother to spell out his assertion that =
the=20
      evolution of sexually attractive plumage might advance with=20
      ever-increasing speed, exponentially, explosively. It took the =
rest of the=20
      biological world some 50 years to catch up and finally reconstruct =
in full=20
      the kind of mathematical argument that Fisher must have used, =
either on=20
      paper or in his head, to prove the point to himself. I am going to =
try to=20
      explain, purely in nonmathematical prose, these mathematical ideas =
which,=20
      in their modern form, have largely been worked out by the young =
American=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.85pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D382 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle13 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.1pt 0pt 2.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica">200 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica-Oblique">The Blind Watchmaker=20
      </SPAN><BR><BR></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 2.15pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">mathematical biologist Russell =
Lande.=20
      While I would not be so pessimistic as Fisher himself who, in the =
Preface=20
      to his 1930 book, said 'No efforts of mine could avail to make the =
book=20
      easy reading', nevertheless, in the words of a kind reviewer of my =
own=20
      first book, 'The reader is warned that he must put on his mental =
running=20
      shoes'. My own understanding of these difficult ideas has been a =
hard=20
      struggle. Here, despite his protests, I must acknowledge my =
colleague and=20
      <BR>former student Alan Grafen, whose own mental winged sandals =
are=20
      notoriously in a class of their own, but who has the even rarer =
ability to=20
      take them off and think of the right way to explain things to =
others.=20
      Without his teaching, I simply couldn't have written the middle =
part of=20
      this chapter, which is why I refuse to relegate my acknowledgment =
to the=20
      Preface. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.65pt 0pt 1.45pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Before we come to these =
difficult=20
      matters, I must back-track and say a little about the origin of =
the idea=20
      of sexual selection. It began, like so much else in this field, =
with=20
      Charles Darwin. Darwin, although he laid his main stress on =
survival and=20
      the struggle for existence, recognized that existence and survival =
were=20
      only means to an end. That end was reproduction. A pheasant may =
live to a=20
      ripe old age, but if it does not reproduce it will not pass its =
attributes=20
      on. Selection will favour <BR>qualities that make an animal =
successful at=20
      reproducing, and survival is only part of the battle to reproduce. =
In=20
      other parts of the battle, success goes to those that are most =
attractive=20
      to the opposite sex. Darwin saw that, if a male pheasant or =
peacock or=20
      bird of paradise buys sexual attractiveness, even at the cost of =
its own=20
      life, it may still pass on its sexually attractive qualities =
through=20
      highly successful procreation before its death. He realized that =
the fan=20
      of a peacock must be a handicap to its possessor as far as =
survival is=20
      concerned, and he suggested that this was more than outweighed by =
the=20
      increased sexual attractiveness that it gave the male. With his =
fondness=20
      for the analogy with <BR>domestication, Darwin compared the hen to =
a human=20
      breeder directing the course of evolution of domestic animals =
along the=20
      lines of aesthetic whims. We might compare her to the person =
selecting=20
      computer biomorphs in directions of aesthetic appeal. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.45pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Darwin simply accepted female =
whims as=20
      given. Their existence was an axiom of his theory of sexual =
selection, a=20
      prior assumption rather than something to be explained in its own =
right.=20
      Partly for this reason his theory of sexual selection fell into =
disrepute,=20
      until it was rescued by Fisher in 1930. Unfortunately, many =
biologists=20
      either ignored or misunderstood Fisher. The objection raised by =
Julian=20
      Huxley and others was that female whims were not legitimate =
foundations=20
      for a truly scientific theory. But Fisher rescued the theory of =
sexual=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.45pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D11 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D30 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D11>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D11 =

      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image075.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D30></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05pt 0pt 2.65pt"><I><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Explosions and spirals =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">201 <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 2.65pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">selection, by treating female =
preference=20
      as a legitimate object of natural selection in its own right, no =
less than=20
      male tails. Female preference is a manifestation of the female =
nervous=20
      system. The female nervous system develops under the influence of =
her=20
      genes, and its attributes are therefore likely to have been =
influenced by=20
      selection over past generations. Where others had thought of male=20
      ornaments evolving under the influence of static female =
preference, Fisher=20
      thought in terms of female preference evolving dynamically in step =
with=20
      male ornament. Perhaps you can already begin to see how this is =
going to=20
      link up with the idea of explosive positive feedback. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 1.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">When we are discussing =
difficult=20
      theoretical ideas, it is often a good idea to keep in mind a =
particular=20
      example from the real world. I shall use the tail of the African=20
      long-tailed widow bird as an example. Any sexually selected =
ornament would=20
      have done, and I had a whim to ring the changes and avoid the =
ubiquitous=20
      (in discussions of sexual selection) peacock. The male long-tailed =
Widow=20
      bird is a slender black bird with orange shoulder flashes, about =
the size=20
      of an English sparrow except that the main tail feathers, in the =
breeding=20
      season, can be 18 inches long. It is often to be seen performing =
its=20
      spectacular display flight over the grasslands of Africa, wheeling =
and=20
      looping the loop, like an aeroplane with a long advertising =
streamer. Not=20
      surprisingly it can be grounded in wet weather. Even a dry tail =
that long=20
      must be a burdensome load to carry around. We are interested in =
explaining=20
      the evolution of the long tail, which we conjecture has been an =
explosive=20
      evolutionary process. Our starting point, therefore, is an =
ancestral bird=20
      without a long tail. Think of the ancestral tail as about 3 inches =
long,=20
      about a sixth the length of the modern breeding male's tail. The=20
      evolutionary change that we are trying to explain is a sixfold =
increase in=20
      tail length. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.1pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">It is an obvious fact that, =
when we=20
      measure almost anything about animals, although most members of a =
species=20
      are fairly close to the average, some individuals are a little =
above=20
      average, while others are below average. We can be sure that there =
was a=20
      range of tail lengths in the ancestral widow bird, some being =
longer and=20
      some being shorter than the average of 3 inches. It is safe to =
assume that=20
      tail length would have been governed by a large number of genes, =
each one=20
      of small effect, their effects adding up, together with the =
effects of=20
      diet and other environmental variables, to make the actual tail =
length of=20
      an individual. Large numbers of genes whose effects add up are =
called=20
      polygenes. Most measures of ourselves, for instance our height and =
weight,=20
      are affected by large numbers of polygenes. The mathematical model =
of=20
      sexual selection that I am following most closely, that of Russell =
Lande,=20
      is a model of polygenes. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.85pt 0pt 10.1pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Now we must turn our attention =
to=20
      females, and how they choose </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.85pt 0pt 10.1pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D629 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D377 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D629>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.5pt 0pt 0.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">202 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.95pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">their mates. It may seem rather =
sexist to=20
      assume that it is the females that would choose their mates, =
rather than=20
      the other way round. Actually, there are good theoretical reasons =
for=20
      expecting it to be this way round (see </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Selfish Gene), =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">and as a matter of fact it =
normally is in=20
      practice. Certainly modern long-tailed widow bird males attract =
harems of=20
      half a dozen or so females. This means that there is a surplus of =
males in=20
      me population who do not reproduce. This, in turn, means that =
females have=20
      no difficulty in finding mates, and are in a position to be =
choosy. A male=20
      has a great deal to gain by being attractive to females. A female =
has=20
      little to gain by being attractive to males, since she is bound to =
be in=20
      demand anyway. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.45pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">So, having accepted the =
assumption that=20
      females do the choosing, we next take the crucial step that Fisher =
took in=20
      confounding Darwin's critics. Instead of simply agreeing that =
females have=20
      whims, we regard female preference as a genetically influenced =
variable=20
      just like any other. Female preference is a quantitative variable, =
and we=20
      can assume that it is under the control of polygenes in just the =
same kind=20
      of way as male tail length itself. These polygenes may act on any =
of a=20
      wide variety of parts of the female's brain, or even on her eyes; =
on=20
      anything that has the effect of altering the female's preference. =
Female=20
      <BR>preference doubtless takes account of many parts of a male, =
the colour=20
      of his shoulder patch, the shape of his beak, and so on; but we =
happen to=20
      be interested, here, in the evolution of male tail length, and =
hence we=20
      are interested in female preferences for male tails of different =
length.=20
      We can therefore measure female preference in exactly the same =
units as we=20
      measure male tail length - inches. Polygenes will see to it that =
there are=20
      some females with a liking for longer than average male tails, =
others with=20
      a liking for shorter than average male tails, and others with a =
liking for=20
      tails of about average length. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.75pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Now comes one of the key =
insights in the=20
      whole theory. Although genes for female preference only =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">express </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">themselves in female =
<BR>behaviour,=20
      nevertheless they are present in the bodies of males too. And by =
the same=20
      token, genes for male tail length are present in the bodies of =
females,=20
      whether or not they express themselves in females. The idea of =
genes=20
      failing to express themselves is not a difficult one. If a man has =
genes=20
      for a long penis, he is just as likely to pass those genes on to =
his=20
      daughter as to his son. His son may express those genes whereas =
his=20
      daughter, of course, will not, because she doesn't have a penis at =
all.=20
      But if the man eventually gets grandsons, the sons of his daughter =
may be=20
      just as likely to inherit his long penis as the sons of his son. =
Genes may=20
      be carried in a body but not expressed. In the same way. Fisher =
and Lande=20
      assume that genes for female preference are </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">carried </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">in male </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.75pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D6 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D16 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D6>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D6=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image076.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D16></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D382 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 4.1pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Explosions and spirals =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">203 <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.2pt 0pt 3.35pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.5pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">bodies, even though they are =
only=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">expressed=20
      </SPAN></I><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">in =
</SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">female bodies. And genes for =
male tails=20
      are carried in female bodies, even if they are not expressed in =
females.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.35pt 0pt 3.1pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Suppose we had a special =
microscope,=20
      which enabled us to look inside any bird's cells and inspect its =
genes.=20
      Take a male who happens to have a longer than average tail, and =
look=20
      inside his cells at his genes. Looking first at the genes for tail =
length=20
      itself, it comes as no surprise to discover that he has genes that =
make a=20
      long tail: this is obvious, since he </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">has </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">a long tail. But now look at =
his genes=20
      for tail </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">preference.=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Here we have =
no clue=20
      from the outside, since such genes only express themselves in =
females. We=20
      have to look with our microscope. What would we see? We'd see =
genes for=20
      making females prefer long tails. Conversely, if we looked inside =
a male=20
      who actually has a short tail, we should see genes for making =
females=20
      prefer short tails. This is really a key point in the argument. =
The=20
      rationale for it is as follows. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.3pt 0pt 1.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">If I am a male with a long =
tail, my=20
      father is more likely than not to have had a long tail too. This =
is just=20
      ordinary heredity. But also, since my father was chosen as a mate =
by my=20
      mother, my mother is more likely than not to have preferred =
long-tailed=20
      males. Therefore, if I have inherited genes for a long tail from =
my=20
      father, I am also likely to have inherited genes for preferring =
long tails=20
      from my mother. By the same reasoning, if you have inherited the =
genes for=20
      a short tail, the chances are that you have also inherited the =
genes for=20
      making females prefer a short tail. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.15pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">We can follow the same kind of =
reasoning=20
      for females. If I am a female who prefers long-tailed males, the =
chances=20
      are that my mother also preferred long-tailed males. Therefore the =
chances=20
      are that my father had a long tail, since he was chosen by my =
mother.=20
      Therefore if I have inherited genes for preferring long tails, the =
chances=20
      are that I have also inherited genes for having a long tail, =
whether or=20
      not those genes are actually expressed in my female body. And if I =
have=20
      inherited genes for preferring short tails, the chances are that I =
have=20
      also inherited genes for </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">having </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">a short tail. The general =
conclusion is=20
      this. Any individual, of either sex, is likely to contain =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">both </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">genes for making males =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">have </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">a certain quality, =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">and </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">genes for making females =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">prefer </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">that selfsame quality, whatever =
that=20
      quality might be. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.55pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
2.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">So, the genes for male =
qualities, and the=20
      genes for making females prefer those qualities, will not be =
randomly=20
      shuffled around the population, but will tend to be shuffled =
around=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">together.=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">This =
'togetherness',=20
      which goes under the daunting technical name of linkage =
disequilibrium,=20
      plays curious tricks with the equations of mathematical =
geneticists. It=20
      has strange and wonderful consequences, </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.55pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
2.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.25pt 0pt 0.5pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">204 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.3pt 0pt 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">not the least of which in =
practice, if=20
      Fisher and Lande are right, is the explosive evolution of =
peacocks' and=20
      widow birds' tails, and a host of other organs of attraction. =
These=20
      consequences can only be proved mathematically, but it is possible =
to say=20
      in words what they are, and we can try to gain some flavour of the =

      mathematical argument in nonmathematical language. We still need =
our=20
      mental running shoes, although actually climbing boots is a better =

      analogy. Each step in the argument is simple enough, but there is =
a long=20
      series of steps up the mountain of understanding, and if you miss =
any of=20
      the earlier steps you unfortunately can't take the later ones. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.55pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.25pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">So far we have recognized the =
possibility=20
      of a complete range of female preferences, from females with a =
taste for=20
      long-tailed males through to females with the opposite taste, for=20
      short-tailed males. But if we actually did a poll of the females =
in a=20
      particular population, we would probably find that a majority of =
females=20
      shared the same general tastes in males. We can express the=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">range =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">of female tastes in the =
population in the=20
      same units - inches - as we express the range of male tail =
lengths. And we=20
      can express the </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">average=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">female =
preference in the=20
      same units of inches. It could turn out that the average female =
preference=20
      was exactly the same as the average male tail length, 3 inches in =
both=20
      cases. In this case female choice will not be an evolutionary =
force=20
      tending to change male tail length. Or it could turn out that the =
average=20
      female preference was for a tail rather longer than the average =
tail that=20
      actually exists, say 4 inches rather than 3. Leaving open, for the =
moment,=20
      why there might be such a discrepancy, just accept that there is =
one and=20
      ask the next obvious question. Why, if most females prefer males =
with=20
      4-inch tails, do the majority of males actually have 3-inch tails? =
Why=20
      doesn't the average tail length in the population shift to 4 =
inches under=20
      the influence of female sexual selection? How can there be a =
discrepancy=20
      of 1 inch between the average preferred tail length and the actual =
average=20
      tail length? </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.5pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The answer is that female taste =
is not=20
      the only kind of selection that bears upon male tail length. Tails =
have an=20
      important job to perform in flight, and a tail that is too long or =
too=20
      short will decrease the efficiency of flight. Moreover, a long =
tail costs=20
      more energy to carry around, and more to make it in the first =
place. Males=20
      with 4-inch tails might well pull the female birds, but the price =
the=20
      males would pay is their less-efficient flight, greater energy =
costs and=20
      greater vulnerability to predators. We can express this by saying =
that=20
      there is a </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">utilitarian=20
      optimum </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">tail =
length,=20
      which is different from the sexually selected optimum: an ideal =
tail=20
      length from the point of view of ordinary useful criteria; a tail =
length=20
      that is ideal from all points of view apart from attracting =
females.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.15in"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Should we expect that the =
actual average=20
      tail length of males, 3 inches </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.15in"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D383 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle23 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.5pt 0pt 4.8pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Explosions and spirals =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica">205 </SPAN><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.25pt 0pt 4.3pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">in our hypothetical example, =
will be the=20
      same as the utilitarian optimum? No, we should expect the =
utilitarian=20
      optimum to be less, say 2 inches. The reason is that the actual =
average=20
      tail length of 3 inches is the result of a compromise between =
utilitarian=20
      selection tending to make tails shorter, and sexual selection =
tending to=20
      make them longer. We may surmise that, if there were no need to =
attract=20
      females, average tail length would shrink towards 2 inches. If =
there were=20
      no need to worry about flying efficiency and energy costs, average =
tail=20
      length would shoot out towards 4 inches. The actual average of 3 =
inches is=20
      a compromise. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.7pt 0pt 2.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">We left on one side the =
question of=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">why =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">females might agree in =
preferring a tail=20
      that departed from the utilitarian optimum. At first sight the =
very idea=20
      seems silly. Fashion-conscious females, with a taste for tails =
that are=20
      longer than they should be on good design criteria, are going to =
have=20
      poorly designed, inefficient, clumsily flying sons. Any mutant =
female who=20
      happened to have an unfashionable taste for shorter-tailed males, =
in=20
      particular a mutant female whose taste in tails happened to =
coincide with=20
      the utilitarian optimum, would produce efficient sons, well =
designed for=20
      flying, who would surely outcompete the sons of her more =
fashion-conscious=20
      rivals. Ah, but here is the rub. It is implicit in my metaphor of=20
      'fashion'. The mutant female's sons may be efficient flyers, but =
they are=20
      not seen as attractive by the majority of females in the =
population. They=20
      will attract only minority females, fashion-defying females, and =
minority=20
      females, by definition, are harder to find than majority females, =
for the=20
      simple reason that they are thinner on the ground. In a society =
where only=20
      one in six tnales mates at all and the fortunate males have large =
harems,=20
      pandering to the majority tastes of females will have enormous =
benefits,=20
      benefits that are well capable of outweighing the utilitarian =
costs in=20
      energy and' flight efficiency. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.15pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">But even so, the reader may =
complain, the=20
      whole argument is based upon an arbitrary assumption. Given that =
most=20
      females prefer nonutilitarian long tails, the reader will admit,=20
      everything else follows. But </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">why </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">did this majority female taste =
come about=20
      in the first place? Why didn't the majority of females prefer =
tails that=20
      are </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">smaller=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">than the =
utilitarian=20
      optimum, or exactly the same length as the utilitarian optimum? =
Why=20
      shouldn't fashion coincide with utility? The answer is that any of =
these=20
      things might have happened, and in many species it probably did. =
My=20
      hypothetical case of females preferring long tails was, indeed =
arbitrary.=20
      But </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">whatever=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the majority =
female=20
      taste had happened to be, and no matter how arbitrary, there would =
have=20
      been a tendency for that majority to be maintained by selection or =
even,=20
      under some </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.15pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D9 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D20 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D9>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D9=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image077.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D20></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.2pt 0pt 1.2pt"><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">206 </SPAN></B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">conditions, actually increased =
=97=20
      exaggerated. It is at this point in the argument that the lack of=20
      mathematical justification in my account becomes really =
noticeable. I=20
      could invite the reader simply to accept that the mathematical =
reasoning=20
      of Lande proves the point, and leave it at that. This might be the =
wisest=20
      course for me to pursue, but I shall have one try at explaining =
part of=20
      the idea in words. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.35pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The key to the argument lies in =
the point=20
      we established earlier about 'linkage disequilibrium', the =
'togetherness'=20
      of genes for tails of a given length - any length - and =
corresponding=20
      genes for preferring tails of that self-same length. We can think =
about=20
      the 'togetherness factor' as a measurable number. If the =
togetherness=20
      factor is very high, this means that knowledge about an =
individual's genes=20
      for tail length enables us to predict, with great accuracy, =
his/her genes=20
      for preference, and vice versa. Conversely, if the togetherness =
factor is=20
      low, this means that knowledge about an individual's genes in one =
of the=20
      two departments - preference or tail length - gives us only a =
slight hint=20
      about his/her genes in the other department. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.65pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The kind of thing that affects =
the=20
      magnitude of the togetherness factor is the strength of the =
females'=20
      preference - how tolerant they are of what they see as imperfect =
males;=20
      how much of the variation in male tail length is governed by genes =
as=20
      opposed to environmental factors; and so on. If, as a result of =
all these=20
      effects, the togetherness factor - the tightness of binding of =
genes for=20
      tail length and genes for tail-length preference - is very strong, =
we can=20
      deduce the following consequence. Every time a male is chosen =
because of=20
      his long tail, not only are genes for long tails being chosen. At =
the same=20
      time, because of the 'togetherness' coupling, genes for =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">preferring </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">long tails are also being =
chosen. What=20
      this means is that genes that make females choose male tails of a=20
      particular length are, in effect, </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">choosing copies of themselves. =

      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">This is the =
essential=20
      ingredient of a self-reinforcing process: it has its own =
self-sustaining=20
      momentum. Evolution having started in a particular direction, this =
can, in=20
      itself, tend to make it persist in the same direction. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.15pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Another way to see this is in =
terms of=20
      what has become known as the 'green-beard effect'. The green-beard =
effect=20
      is a kind of academic biological joke. It is purely hypothetical, =
but it=20
      is instructive nevertheless. It was originally proposed as a way =
of=20
      explaining the fundamental principle underlying W. D. Hamilton's =
important=20
      theory of kin selection, which I discussed at length in =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Selfish Gene. =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Hamilton, now my colleague at =
Oxford,=20
      showed that natural selection would favour genes for behaving=20
      altruistically towards close kin, simply because copies of those =
selfsame=20
      genes had a high probability </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">of </SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.15pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D9 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D71 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D9>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold"><IMG height=3D9=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image078.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D71></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D384 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 182pt 0pt 6.5pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Explosions and spirals=20
      </SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 5.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">being in the bodies of kin. The =

      'green-beard' hypothesis puts/trie same point more generally, if =
less=20
      practically. Kinship, the argument runs, is only one possible way =
in which=20
      genes can, in effect, locate copies of themselves in other bodies. =

      Theoretically, a gene could locate copies of itself by more direct =
means.=20
      Suppose a gene happened to arise that had the following two =
effects (genes=20
      with two or more effects are common): it makes its possessors have =
a=20
      conspicuous 'badge' such as a green beard, and it also affects =
their=20
      brains in such a way that they behave , altruistically towards=20
      green-bearded individuals. A pretty improbable coincidence, =
admittedly,=20
      but if it ever did arise the evolutionary consequence is clear. =
The=20
      green-beard altruism gene would tend to be favoured by natural =
selection,=20
      for exactly the same kinds of reason as genes for altruism towards =

      offspring or brothers. Every time a greenbearded individual helped =

      another, the gene for giving this discriminating altruism would be =

      favouring a copy of itself. The spread of the green-beard gene =
would be=20
      automatic and inevitable. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.7pt 0pt 4.1pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Nobody really believes, not =
even I, that=20
      the green-beard effect, in this ultra-simple form, will ever be =
found in=20
      nature. In nature, genes discriminate in favour of copies of =
themselves by=20
      means of less specific but more plausible labels than green =
beards.=20
      Kinship is just such a label. 'Brother' or, in practice, something =
like=20
      'he who has just hatched in the nest from which I have just =
fledged', is a=20
      statistical label. Any gene that makes individuals behave =
altruistically=20
      towards bearers of such a label has a good statistical chance of =
aiding=20
      copies of itself: for brothers have a good statistical chance of =
sharing=20
      genes. Hamilton's theory of kin selection can be seen as one way =
in which=20
      a green-beard type of effect can be made plausible. Remember, by =
the way,=20
      that there is no suggestion here that genes 'want' to help copies =
of=20
      themselves. It is just that any gene that happens to have the=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">effect =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">of helping copies of itself =
will tend,=20
      willy nilly, to become more numerous in the population. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.2pt 0pt 2.4pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Kinship, then, can be seen as a =
way in=20
      which something like the green-beard effect can be made plausible. =
The=20
      Fisher theory of sexual selection can be explained as yet another =
way in=20
      which the green-beard can be made plausible. When the females of a =

      population have strong preferences for male characteristics, it =
follows,=20
      by the reasoning we have been through, that each male body will =
tend to=20
      contain copies of genes that make females prefer his own =
characteristics.=20
      If a male has inherited a long tail from his father, the chances =
are that=20
      he has also inherited from his mother the genes that made her =
choose the=20
      long tail of his father. If he has a short tail, the chances are =
that he=20
      contains genes for making females prefer short tails. So, when a =
female=20
      exercises her choice of male, whichever way her preference lies, =
the=20
      chances are </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.2pt 0pt 2.4pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 3.1pt">208 <I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle24=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05pt 0pt 2.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt">that=20
      the genes that bias her choice <I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">are choosing copies of =
themselves=20
      </SPAN></I>in the males. They are choosing copies of themselves =
using male=20
      tail length as a label, in a more complicated version of the way =
the=20
      hypothetical green-beard gene uses the green beard as a label. =
</P>
      <P class=3DStyle24=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.55pt 0pt 2.65pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt">If=20
      half the females in the population preferred long-tailed males, =
and the=20
      other half short-tailed males, genes for female choice would still =
be=20
      choosing copies of themselves, but there would be no tendency for =
one or=20
      other tail type to be favoured in general. There might be a =
tendency for=20
      the population to split into two =97 a long-tailed, =
long-preferring faction,=20
      and a short-tailed, short-preferring faction. But any such two-way =
split=20
      in female 'opinion' is an unstable state of affairs. The moment a=20
      majority, <I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">however =
slight,=20
      </SPAN></I>started to accrue among females for one type of =
preference=20
      rather than the other, that majority would be reinforced in =
subsequent=20
      generations. This is because males preferred by females of the =
minority=20
      school of thought would have a harder time finding mates; and =
females of=20
      the minority school of thought would have sons who had a =
relatively hard=20
      time finding mates, so minority females would have fewer =
grandchildren.=20
      Whenever small minorities tend to become even smaller minorities, =
and=20
      small majorities tend to become bigger majorities, we have a =
recipe for=20
      positive feedback: 'Unto every one that hath shall be given, and =
he shall=20
      have abundance: but from him that hath not shall be taken away =
even that=20
      which he hath.' Whenever we have an unstable balance, arbitrary, =
random=20
      beginnings are self-reinforcing. Just so, when we cut through a =
tree=20
      trunk, we may be uncertain whether the tree will fall to the north =
or the=20
      south; but, after remaining poised for a time, once it starts to =
fall in=20
      one direction or the other, nothing can bring it back. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle24=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.15pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt">Lacing=20
      our climbing boots even more securely we prepare to hammer in =
another=20
      piton. Remember that selection by females is pulling male tails in =
one=20
      direction, while 'utilitarian' selection is pulling them in the =
other=20
      ('pulling' in the evolutionary sense, of course), the actual =
average tail=20
      length being a compromise between the two pulls. Let us now =
recognize a=20
      quantity called the 'choice discrepancy'. This is the difference =
between=20
      the actual average tail length of males in the population, and the =
'ideal'=20
      tail length that the average female in the population would really =
prefer.=20
      The units in which the choice discrepancy is measured are =
arbitrary, just=20
      as the Fahrenheit and Centigrade scales of temperature are =
arbitrary, fust=20
      as the Centigrade scale finds it convenient to fix its zero point =
at the=20
      freezing point of water, we shall find it convenient to fix our =
zero at=20
      the point where the pull of sexual selection exactly balances the =
opposite=20
      pull of utilitarian selection. In other words, a choice =
discrepancy of=20
      zero means that </P>
      <P class=3DStyle24=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.15pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D10 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D19 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D10>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt; COLOR: =
black"><IMG=20
      height=3D10=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image079.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D19></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D629 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D393 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D629>
      <P class=3DStyle11 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 5.55pt 0pt 7.7pt"><I><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Explosions and spirals=20
      </SPAN></I><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica-Bold">209=20
</SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.55pt 0pt 6.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">evolutionary change comes to a =
halt=20
      because the two opposite kinds </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">ot^ </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">selection exactly cancel each =
other out.=20
      / </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.25pt 0pt 6.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Obviously, the larger the =
choice=20
      discrepancy, the stronger ihe^ evolutionary 'pull' exerted by =
females=20
      against the counteracting pull/bf utilitarian natural selection. =
What we=20
      are interested in is not^the absolute value of the choice =
discrepancy at=20
      any particular time; but bow the choice discrepancy =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">changes </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">in successive generations.' As =
a=97- result=20
      of a given choice discrepancy, tails get longer, and at the same =
time=20
      (remember that genes for choosing long tails are being selected in =
concert=20
      with genes for having long tails) the females' ideal preferred =
tail gets=20
      longer too. After a generation of this dual selection, both =
average tail=20
      length and average preferred tail length have become longer, but =
which has=20
      increased the most? This is another way of asking what will happen =
to the=20
      choice discrepancy. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 9.05pt 0pt 3.85pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The choice discrepancy could =
have stayed=20
      the same (if average tail length and average preferred tail length =
both=20
      increased by the same amount). It could have become smaller (if =
average=20
      tail length increased more than preferred tail length did). Or, =
finally,=20
      it could have become larger (if average tail length increased =
somewhat,=20
      but average preferred tail length increased even more). You can =
begin to=20
      see that, if the choice discrepancy gets smaller as tails get =
larger, tail=20
      length will evolve towards a stable equilibrium length. But if the =
choice=20
      discrepancy gets </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">larger=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">as tails get =
larger,=20
      future generations should theoretically see tails shooting out at =
ever=20
      increasing speed. This is, without any doubt, what Fisher must =
have=20
      calculated before 1930, although his brief published words were =
not=20
      clearly understood by others at the time. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 11.35pt 0pt 2.15pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Let us first take the case =
where the=20
      choice discrepancy becomes ever smaller as the generations go by. =
It will=20
      eventually become so small that the pull of female, preference in =
one=20
      direction is exactly balanced by the pull of utilitarian selection =
in the=20
      other. Evolutionary change will then come to a halt, and the =
system is=20
      said to be in a state of equilibrium. The interesting thing Lande =
proved=20
      about this is that, at least under some conditions, there is not =
just one=20
      point of equilibrium, but many (theoretically an infinite number =
arranged=20
      in a straight line on a graph, but there's mathematics for you!). =
There is=20
      not just one &shy; balance point but many: for any strength of =
utilitarian=20
      selection pulling in one direction, the strength of female =
preference=20
      evolves in such a way as to reach a point where it balances it =
exactly.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 12.6pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">So, if conditions are such that =
the=20
      choice discrepancy tends </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">to </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">become smaller as the =
generations go by,=20
      the population will come </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">to rest </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">at the 'nearest' point of =
equilibrium.=20
      Here utilitarian selection </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 12.6pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
