<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D16 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D19 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D16>
      <P class=3DStyle4><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">210 =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D600 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D600>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.7pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">pulling in one direction will =
be exactly=20
      counteracted by female selection pulling in the other, and the =
tails of=20
      the males will stay the same length, regardless of how long that =
is. The=20
      reader may recognize that we have here a negative-feedback system, =
but it=20
      is a slightly weird kind of negative-feedback system. You can =
always tell=20
      a negativefeedback system by what happens if you 'perturb' it away =
from=20
      its ideal, 'set point'. If you perturb a room's temperature by =
opening the=20
      window, for instance, the thermostat responds by turning on the =
heater to=20
      compensate. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.2pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">How might the system of sexual =
selection=20
      be perturbed? Remember that we are talking about the evolutionary=20
      timescale here, so it is difficult for us to do experiments - the=20
      equivalent of opening the window - and live to see the results. =
But no=20
      doubt, in nature, the system is perturbed often, for instance by=20
      spontaneous, random fluctuations in numbers of males due to =
chance, lucky=20
      or unlucky, events. Whenever this happens, given the conditions we =
have so=20
      far discussed, a combination of utilitarian selection and sexual =
selection=20
      will return the population to the nearest one of the set of =
equilibrium=20
      points. This probably will not be the same equilibrium point as =
before,=20
      but will be another point a little bit higher, or lower, along the =
line of=20
      equilibrium points. So, as time goes by, the population can drift =
up or=20
      down the line of equilibrium points. Drifting up the line means =
that tails=20
      get longer - theoretically there is no limit to how long. Drifting =
down=20
      the line means that tails get shorter - theoretically all the way =
down to=20
      a length of zero. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The analogy of a thermostat is =
often used=20
      to explain the idea of a point of equilibrium. We can develop the =
analogy=20
      to explain the more difficult idea of a </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">line </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">of equilibria. Suppose that a =
room has=20
      both a heating device and a cooling device, each with its own =
thermostat.=20
      Both thermostats are set to keep the room at the same fixed=20
      <BR>temperature, 70 degrees F. If the temperature drops below 70, =
the=20
      heater turns itself on and the refrigerator turns itself off. If =
the=20
      temperature rises above 70, the refrigerator turns itself on and =
the=20
      heater turns itself off. The analogue of the widow bird's tail =
length is=20
      not the temperature (which remains approximately constant at =
70=B0) but the=20
      total rate of consumption of electricity. The point is that there =
are lots=20
      of different ways in which the desired temperature can be =
achieved. It can=20
      be achieved by both devices working very hard, the heater belting =
out hot=20
      air and the refrigerator working flat out to neutralize the heat. =
Or it=20
      can be achieved by the heater putting out a bit less heat, and the =
cooler=20
      working correspondingly less hard to neutralize it. Or it can be =
achieved=20
      by both devices working scarcely at all. Obviously, the latter is=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
