<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D383 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 4.55pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Explosions and spirals =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">211 <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.25pt 0pt 3.85pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the most desirable solution =
from the=20
      point of view of the electricity bill but, as far as the object of =

      maintaining the fixed temperature of 70 degrees is concerned, =
every one of=20
      a large series of working rates is equally satisfactory. We have a =

      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">line =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">of equilibrium points, rather =
than a=20
      single point. Depending upon details of how the system was set up, =
upon=20
      delays in the system and other things of the kind that preoccupy=20
      engineers, it is theoretically possible for the room's=20
      electricity-consumption rate to drift up and down the line of =
equilibrium=20
      points, while the temperature remains the same. If the room's =
temperature=20
      is perturbed a little below 70 degrees it will return, but it =
won't=20
      necessarily return to the same combination of work rates of the =
heater and=20
      the cooler. It may return </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">to a </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">different point along the line =
of=20
      equilibria. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.7pt 0pt 1.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">In real practical engineering =
terms, it=20
      would be pretty difficult to set up a room so that a true line of=20
      equilibria existed. The line is in practice likely to 'collapse to =
a=20
      point'. Russell Lande's argument too, about a line of equilibria =
in sexual=20
      selection, rests upon assumptions that may well not be true in =
nature. It=20
      assumes, for instance, that there will be a steady supply of new=20
      mutations. It assumes that the act of choosing, by a female, is =
entirely=20
      cost-free. If this assumption is violated, as it well may be, the =
'line'=20
      of equilibria collapses into a single point of equilibrium. But in =
any=20
      case, so far we have only discussed the case where the choice =
discrepancy=20
      becomes </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">smaller=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">as the =
successive=20
      generations of selection go by. Under other conditions the choice=20
      discrepancy may become larger. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.55pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">It is a while since we =
discussed the=20
      matter, so let us remind ourselves of what this means. We have a=20
      population whose males are undergoing evolution of some =
characteristic=20
      such as tail length in widow birds, under the influence of female=20
      preference tending to make the tails longer and utilitarian =
selection=20
      tending to make the tails shorter. The reason there is any =
momentum in the=20
      evolution towards longer tails is that, whenever a female chooses =
a male=20
      of the type she 'likes', she is, because of the nonrandom =
association of=20
      genes, choosing copies of the very genes that made her do the =
choosing.=20
      So, in the next generation, not only will the males tend to have =
longer=20
      tails, but the females will tend to have a stronger preference for =
long=20
      tails. It is not obvious which of these two incremental processes =
will=20
      have the highest rate, generation by generation. We have so far =
considered=20
      the case where tail length increases faster, per generation, than=20
      preference. Now we come to consider the other possible case, where =

      preference increases at an even higher rate, per generation, than =
tail=20
      length itself does. In other words, we are now going to discuss =
the case=20
      where the choice discrepancy gets bigger as the generations go by, =
not=20
      smaller as in the previous paragraphs. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.55pt 0pt 10.1pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Here the theoretical =
consequences are=20
      even more bizarre than before. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.55pt 0pt 10.1pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D11 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D35 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D11>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D11 =

      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image086.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D35></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D16 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D19 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D16>
      <P class=3DStyle4><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">212 =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D601 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D601>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
1.4pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Instead of negative feedback, =
we have=20
      positive feedback. As the generations go by, tails get longer, but =
the=20
      female desire for long tails increases at a higher rate. This =
means that,=20
      theoretically, tails will get even longer still, and at an=20
      ever-accelerating rate as the generations go by. Theoretically, =
tails will=20
      go on expanding even after they are 10 miles long. In practice, of =
course,=20
      the rules of the game will have been changed long before these =
absurd=20
      lengths are reached, just as our steam engine with its reversed =
Watt=20
      governor would not </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">really </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">have gone on accelerating to a =
million=20
      revolutions per second. But although we have to water down the =
conclusions=20
      of the mathematical model when we come to the extremes, the =
model's=20
      conclusions may well hold true over a range of practically =
plausible=20
      conditions. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.45pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Now, 50 years late, we can =
understand=20
      what Fisher meant, when he baldly asserted that 'it is easy to see =
that=20
      the speed of development will be proportional to the development =
already=20
      attained, which will <BR>therefore increase with time =
exponentially, or in=20
      geometric progression'. His rationale was clearly the same as =
Lande's,=20
      when he said: 'The two characteristics affected by such a process, =
namely=20
      plumage <BR>development in the male, and sexual preference for =
such=20
      developments in the female, must thus advance together, and so =
long as the=20
      process is unchecked by severe counterselection, will advance with =

      ever-increasing speed.' </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.05pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The fact that Fisher and Lande =
both=20
      arrived by mathematical reasoning at the same intriguing =
conclusion does=20
      not mean that their theory is a correct reflection of what goes on =
in=20
      nature. It could be, as the Cambridge University geneticist Peter=20
      O'Donald, one of the leading authorities on the theory of sexual=20
      selection, has said, that the runaway property of the Lande model =
is=20
      'built into' its starting assumptions, in such a way that it =
couldn't help=20
      emerging in a rather boring way at the other end of the =
mathematical=20
      reasoning. Some theorists, including Alan Grafen and W D. =
Hamilton, prefer=20
      alternative kinds of theory in which choice made by a female =
really does=20
      have a beneficial effect on her progeny, in a utilitarian, eugenic =
sense.=20
      The theory they are together working on is that female birds act =
as=20
      diagnostic doctors, picking out those males who are least =
susceptible to=20
      parasites. Bright plumage, according to this characteristically =
ingenious=20
      theory of Hamilton, is a male's way of conspicuously advertising =
his=20
      health. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.2pt 0pt 1.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The theoretical importance of =
parasites=20
      would take too long to explain fully. Briefly, the problem with =
all=20
      'eugenic' theories of female choice has always been as follows. If =
females=20
      really could successfully choose males with the best genes, their =
very=20
      success would reduce the </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.2pt 0pt 1.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D16 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D131 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D16>
      <P class=3DStyle6><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The =
Blind=20
      Watchmaker </SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle6><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D382 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05pt 0pt 5.3pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Explosions and spirals =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">213 <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 4.1pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">range of choice available in =
the future:=20
      eventually, if there were only good genes around, there would be =
no point=20
      in choosing. Parasites remove this theoretical objection. The =
reason is=20
      that, according to Hamilton, parasites and hosts are running a=20
      never-ceasing </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">cyclical=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">arms race =
against one=20
      another. This in turn means that the 'best' genes in any one =
generation of=20
      birds are not the same as the best genes in future generations. =
What it=20
      takes to beat the current generation of parasites is no good =
against the=20
      next generation of evolving parasites. Therefore there will always =
be some=20
      males that happen to be genetically better equipped than others to =
beat=20
      the current crop of parasites. Females, therefore, can always =
benefit=20
      their offspring by choosing the healthiest of the current =
generation of=20
      males. The only </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">general=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">criteria that =
successive=20
      generations of females can use are the indicators that any vet =
might use -=20
      bright eyes, glossy plumage, and so on. Only genuinely healthy =
males can=20
      display these symptoms of health, so selection favours those males =
that=20
      display them to the full, and even exaggerate them into long tails =
and=20
      spreading fans. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.9pt 0pt 1.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">But the parasite theory, though =
it may=20
      well be right, is off the point of my 'explosions' chapter. =
Returning to=20
      the Fisher/Lande runaway theory, what is needed now is evidence =
from real=20
      animals. How should we go about looking for such evidence? What =
methods=20
      might be used? A promising approach was made by Malte Andersson, =
from=20
      Sweden. As it happens, he worked on the very bird that I am using =
here to=20
      discuss the theoretical ideas, the long-tailed widow bird, and he =
studied=20
      it in its natural surroundings in Kenya. Andersson's experiments =
were made=20
      possible by a recent advance in technology: superglue. He reasoned =
as=20
      follows. If it is true that the actual tail length of males is a=20
      compromise between a utilitarian optimum on the one hand, and what =
females=20
      really want on the other, it should be possible to make a male=20
      superattractive by giving him an extra long tail. This is where =
the=20
      superglue came in. I'll describe Andersson's experiment briefly, =
as it is=20
      a neat example of experimental design. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.85pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Andersson caught 36 male widow =
birds, and=20
      divided them into nine groups of four. Each group of four was =
treated=20
      alike. One member of each group of four (scrupulously chosen at =
random to=20
      avoid any <BR>unconscious bias) had his tail feathers trimmed to =
14=20
      centimetres (about S'/z inches). The portion removed was stuck, =
with=20
      quick-setting superglue, to the end of the tail of the second =
member of=20
      the group of four. So, the first one had an artificially shortened =
tail,=20
      the second one an artificially lengthened tail. The third bird was =
left=20
      with his tail untouched, for comparison. The fourth bird was also =
left=20
      with his tail the same length, but it wasn't untouched. Instead, =
the ends=20
      of </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">the =
</SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">feathers were cut off =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.85pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D9 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D17 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D9>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D9=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image087.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D17></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D16 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D19 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D16>
      <P class=3DStyle4><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">214 =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D600 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D600>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.95pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">and then glued back on again. =
This might=20
      seem a pointless exercise, but it is a good example of how careful =
you=20
      have to be in designing experiments. It could have been that the =
fact of=20
      having his tail feathers manipulated, or the fact of being caught =
and=20
      handled by a human, affected a bird, rather than the actual change =
in=20
      length itself. Group 4 was a 'control' for such effects. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.95pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The idea was to compare the =
mating=20
      success of each bird with its differently treated colleagues in =
its own=20
      group of four. After being treated in one of the four ways, every =
male was=20
      allowed to take up its former residence on its own territory. Here =
it=20
      resumed its normal business of trying to attract females into its=20
      territory, there to mate, build a nest and lay eggs. The question =
was,=20
      which member of each group of four would have the most success in =
pulling=20
      in females? Andersson measured this, not by literally watching =
females,=20
      but by waiting and then counting the number of nests containing =
eggs in=20
      each male's territory. What he found was that males with =
artificially=20
      elongated tails attracted nearly four times as many females as =
males with=20
      artificially shortened tails. Those with tails of normal, natural =
length=20
      had intermediate success. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.85pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The results were analysed =
statistically,=20
      in case they had resulted from chance alone. The conclusion was =
that if=20
      attracting females were the only criterion, males would be better =
off with=20
      longer tails than they actually have. In other words, sexual =
selection is=20
      constantly pulling tails (in the evolutionary sense) in the =
direction of=20
      getting longer. The fact that real tails are shorter than females =
would=20
      prefer suggests that there must be some other selection pressure =
keeping=20
      them shorter. This is 'utilitarian' selection. Presumably males =
with=20
      especially long tails are more likely to die than males with =
average=20
      tails. Unfortunately, Andersson did not have time to follow the =
subsequent=20
      fates of his doctored males. If he had, the prediction would have =
been=20
      that the males with extra tail-feathers glued on should, on =
average, have=20
      died younger than normal males, probably because of greater =
vulnerability=20
      to predators. Males with artificially shortened tails, on the =
other hand,=20
      should probably be expected to live longer than normal males. This =
is=20
      because the normal length is supposed to be a <BR>compromise =
between the=20
      sexual selection optimum and the utilitarian optimum. Presumably =
the birds=20
      with artificially shortened tails are closer to the utilitarian =
optimum,=20
      and therefore should live longer. There's a lot of supposition in =
all=20
      this, however. If the main utilitarian disadvantage of a long tail =
turned=20
      out to be the economic cost of growing it in the first place, =
rather than=20
      increased dangers of dying after it has grown, males who are =
handed an=20
      extra-long tail on a plate, as a </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.85pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D16 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D132 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D16>
      <P class=3DStyle6><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The =
Blind=20
      Watchmaker </SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle6><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D386 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05pt 0pt 0.1in"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Explosions and spirals =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">215 <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.15pt 0pt 6.25pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">free gift from Andersson, would =
not be=20
      expected to die particularly young as a result. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 6pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">I have written as though female =

      preference will tend to drag tails </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">and </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">other ornaments in the =
direction of=20
      getting larger. In theory, as we saw earlier, there is no reason =
why=20
      female preference should not pull in exactly the opposite =
direction, for=20
      instance in the direction of ever shortening, rather than =
lengthening,=20
      tails. The common wren has a tail so short and stubby that one is =
tempted=20
      to wonder whether it is, perhaps, shorter than it 'ought' to be =
for=20
      strictly utilitarian purposes. Competition between male wrens is =
intense,=20
      as you might guess from the disproportionate loudness of their =
song. Such=20
      singing is bound to be costly, and a male wren has even been known =
to sing=20
      himself, literally, to death. Successful males have more than one =
female=20
      in their territory, like widow birds. In such a competitive =
climate, we=20
      might expect positive feedbacks to get going. Could the wren's =
short tail=20
      represent the end product of a runaway process of evolutionary =
shrinkage?=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.5pt 0pt 3.1pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Setting wrens on one side, =
peacock fans,=20
      and widow bird and bird of paradise tails, in their gaudy =
extravagance,=20
      are very plausibly seen as end-products of explosive, spiralling =
evolution=20
      by positive feedback. Fisher and his modern successors have shown =
us how=20
      this might have come about. Is this idea essentially tied to =
sexual=20
      selection, or can we find convincing analogies in other kinds of=20
      evolution? It is worth asking this question, if only because there =
are=20
      aspects of our own evolution that have more than a suggestion of =
the=20
      explosive about them, notably the extremely rapid swelling of our =
brains=20
      during the last few million years. It has been suggested that this =
is due=20
      to sexual selection itself, braininess being a sexually desirable=20
      character (or some manifestation of braininess, such as ability to =

      remember the steps of a long and complicated ritual dance). But it =
could=20
      also be that brain size has exploded under the influence of a =
different=20
      kind of selection, analogous but not identical to sexual =
selection. I=20
      think it is helpful to distinguish two levels of possible analogy =
to=20
      sexual selection, a weak analogy and a strong analogy. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 5.9pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The weak analogy simply says =
the=20
      following. Any evolutionary process in which the end-product of =
one step=20
      in evolution sets the stage for the next step in evolution is =
potentially=20
      progressive, sometimes explosively so. We have already met this =
idea in=20
      the previous chapter, in the form of 'arms races'. Each =
evolutionary=20
      improvement in predator design changes the pressures on prey, =
thereby=20
      making prey become better at avoiding the predators. This in turn =
puts=20
      pressure on the predators to improve, so we have an ever-rising =
spiral. As=20
      we saw, it is </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 5.9pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D16 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D19 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D16>
      <P class=3DStyle4><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">216 =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D601 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D601>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.5pt 0pt 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">likely chat neither predators =
nor prey=20
      will necessarily enjoy a higher success rate as a result, because =
their=20
      enemies are improving at the same time. But nevertheless, both =
prey and=20
      predators are becoming progressively better </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">equipped. </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">This, then, is the weak analogy =
with=20
      sexual selection. The strong analogy with sexual selection notes =
that the=20
      essence of the Fisher/Lande theory is the 'green beard'-like =
phenomenon=20
      whereby genes for female choice automatically tend to choose =
copies of=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">themselves,=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">a process with =
an=20
      automatic tendency to go explosive. It is not clear that there are =

      examples of this kind of phenomenon other than sexual selection =
itself.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.2pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">I suspect that a good place to =
look for=20
      analogies to explosive evolution of the sexual selection kind is =
in human=20
      cultural evolution. This is because, here again, choice by whim =
matters,=20
      and such choice may be subject to the 'fashion' or 'majority =
always wins'=20
      effect. Once again, the warning with which I began this chapter =
should be=20
      heeded. Cultural 'evolution' is not really evolution at all if we =
are=20
      being fussy and purist about our use of words, but there may be =
enough in=20
      common between them to justify some comparison of principles. In =
doing=20
      this we must not make light of the differences. Let us get these =
matters=20
      out of the way before returning to the particular issue of =
explosive=20
      spirals. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.65pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">It has frequently been pointed =
out -=20
      indeed any fool can see - that there is something =
quasi-evolutionary about=20
      many aspects of human history. If you sample a particular aspect =
of human=20
      life at regular intervals, say you sample the state of scientific=20
      knowledge, the kind of music being played, dress fashions, or =
vehicles of=20
      transport, at intervals of one century or perhaps one decade, you =
will=20
      find </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">trends.=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">If we have =
three=20
      samplings, at successive times A, B and C, then, to say that there =
is a=20
      trend is to say that the measurement taken at time B will be =
intermediate=20
      between the measurements taken at times A and C. Although there =
are=20
      exceptions, everyone will agree that trends of this kind =
characterize many=20
      aspects of civilized life. Admittedly the <BR>directions of trends =

      sometimes reverse (for example, skirt lengths), but this is true =
of=20
      genetic evolution too. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.15pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Many trends, particularly =
trends in=20
      useful technology as opposed to frivolous fashions, can, without =
much=20
      argument over value- judgements, be identified as </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">improvements. </SPAN></I><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">There can be no doubt, for =
instance, that=20
      vehicles for getting about the world have improved steadily and =
without=20
      reversal, over the past 200 years, passing from horse-drawn =
through=20
      steam-drawn vehicles, and culminating today in supersonic jet =
planes. I am=20
      using the word improvement in a neutral way. I don't mean to say =
that=20
      everybody would agree that the quality of life has improved as a =
result of=20
      these changes; personally I often doubt </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.15pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D17 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D131 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D17>
      <P class=3DStyle9><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The =
Blind=20
      Watchmaker </SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle9><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D9 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D66 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D9>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic"><IMG=20
      height=3D9=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image088.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D66></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D385 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 5.5pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Explosions and spirals =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">217 <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 4.55pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">it. Nor do I mean to deny the =
popular=20
      view that standards of workmanship have gone </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">down </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">as mass production has replaced =
skilled=20
      craftsmen. But looking at means of transport purely from the point =
of view=20
      of </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">transport,=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">which means =
getting from=20
      one part of the world to another, there can be no disputing the =
historical=20
      trend towards some kind of improvement, even if it is only an =
improvement=20
      in speed. Similarly, over a timescale of decades or even years, =
there is a=20
      progressive improvement in the quality of high-fidelity sound=20
      amplification equipment that is undeniable, even if you agree with =
me=20
      sometimes that the world would be a more agreeable place if the =
amplifier=20
      nad never been invented. It is not that tastes have changed; it is =
an=20
      objective, measurable fact that fidelity of reproduction is now =
better=20
      than it was in 1950, and in 1950 it was better than in 1920. The =
quality=20
      of picture reproduction is undeniably better in modern television =
sets=20
      than in earlier ones, although of course the same may not be true =
of the=20
      quality of the entertainment transmitted. The quality of machines =
for=20
      killing in war shows a dramatic trend towards <BR>improvement - =
they are=20
      capable of killing more people faster as the years go by. The =
sense in=20
      which this is not an improvement is too obvious </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">to </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">labour. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.2pt 0pt 1.45pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">There is no doubt about it, in =
the narrow=20
      technical sense things do get better as time goes by. But this is =
only=20
      obviously true of technically useful things such as aeroplanes and =

      computers. There are many other aspects of human life that show =
true=20
      trends without these trends being, in any obvious sense, =
improvements.=20
      Languages clearly evolve in that they show trends, they diverge, =
and as=20
      the centuries go by after their divergence they become more and =
more=20
      mutually unintelligible. The numerous islands of the Pacific =
provide a=20
      beautiful workshop for the study of language evolution. The =
languages of=20
      different islands clearly resemble each other, and their =
differences can=20
      be measured precisely by the numbers of words that differ between =
them, a=20
      measure that is closely analogous to the molecular taxonomic =
measures that=20
      we shall discuss in Chapter 10. Difference between languages, =
measured in=20
      numbers of divergent words, can be plotted on a graph against =
distance=20
      between islands, measured in miles, and it turns out that the =
points on=20
      the graph fall on a curve whose precise mathematical shape tells =
us=20
      something about rates of diffusion from island to island. Words =
travelled=20
      by canoe, island-hopping at intervals proportional to the degree =
of=20
      remoteness of the islands concerned. Within any one island words =
change at=20
      a steady rate, in very much the same way as genes occasionally =
mutate. Any=20
      island, if completely isolated, would exhibit some evolutionary =
change in=20
      its language as time went by, and hence </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.2pt 0pt 1.45pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D382 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.45pt 0pt 3.1pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">218 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 2.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">some divergence from the =
languages of=20
      other islands. Islands that are near each other obviously have a =
higher=20
      rate of word flow between them, via canoe, than islands that are =
far from=20
      each other. Their languages also have a more recent common =
ancestor than=20
      the languages of islands that are far apart. These phenomena, =
which=20
      explain the observed pattern of resemblances between near and =
distant=20
      islands, are closely analogous to the facts about finches on =
different=20
      islands of the Galapagos Archipelago which originally inspired =
Charles=20
      Darwin. Genes island-hop in the bodies of birds, just as words=20
      <BR>islandhop in canoes. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 1.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Languages, then, evolve. But =
although=20
      modern English has evolved from Chaucerian English, I don't think =
many=20
      people would wish to claim that modern English is an improvement =
on=20
      Chaucerian English. Ideas of improvement or quality do not =
normally enter=20
      our heads when we speak of language. Indeed, to the extent that =
they do,=20
      we often see change as deterioration, as degeneration. We tend to =
see=20
      earlier usages as correct, recent changes as corruptions. But we =
can still=20
      detect evolution-like trends that are progressive in a purely =
abstract,=20
      <BR>valuefree sense. And we can even find evidence of positive =
feedbacks,=20
      in the form of escalations (or, looking at it from the other =
direction,=20
      degenerations) in meaning. For instance, the word 'star' was used =
to mean=20
      a film actor of quite exceptional celebrity. Then it degenerated =
to mean=20
      any ordinary actor who was playing one of the principal roles in a =
film.=20
      Therefore, in order to recapture the original meaning of =
exceptional=20
      celebrity, the word had to escalate to 'superstar'. Later, studio=20
      publicity began to use 'superstar' for actors that many people had =
never=20
      heard of, so there was a further escalation to 'megastar'. Now =
there are=20
      quite a few advertised 'megastars' whom I, at least, have never =
heard of=20
      before, so perhaps we are due for yet another escalation. Shall we =
soon=20
      hear tell of 'hyperstars'? A similar positive feedback has driven =
down the=20
      currency of the word 'chef. It comes, of course, from the French=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">chef de =
cuisine,=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">meaning =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">chief </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">or head of the kitchen. This is =
the=20
      meaning given in the Oxford Dictionary. By definition, then, there =
can be=20
      only one chef per kitchen. But, perhaps to satisfy their dignity, =
ordinary=20
      (male) cooks, even junior hamburger-slingers, started referring to =

      themselves as 'chefs'. The result is that now the tautological =
phrase=20
      'head chef is frequently heard! </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
2.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">But if this is an analogy for =
sexual=20
      selection, it is so, at best, only in what I have called the =
'weak' sense.=20
      Let me jump now straight to the nearest approach I can think of to =
a=20
      'strong' analogy: to the world of 'pop' records. If you listen to=20
      discussion among aficionados of pop records, or switch on the =
mid-Atlantic=20
      mouthings of disc jockeys on </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
2.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D390 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 9.1pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Explosions and spirals =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">219 </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.55pt 0pt 8.15pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.55pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the radio, you will discover a =
very=20
      curious thing. Whereas other genres of art criticism betray some=20
      preoccupation with style or skill of performance, with mood, =
emotional=20
      impact, with the qualities and properties of the art-form, the =
'pop' music=20
      sub-culture is almost exclusively preoccupied with </SPAN><I><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">popularity itself. =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">It is quite clear that the =
important=20
      thing about a record is not what it sounds like, but =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">how many people are buying it. =

      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The whole =
sub-culture is=20
      obsessed with a rank ordering of records, called the Top 20 or Top =
40,=20
      which is based only upon sales figures. The thing that really =
matters=20
      about a record is where it lies in the Top 20. This, when you =
think about=20
      it, is a very singular fact, and a very interesting one if we are =
thinking=20
      about R. A. Fisher's theory of runaway evolution. It is probably =
also=20
      significant that a disc jockey seldom mentions the current =
position of a=20
      record in the charts, without at the same time telling us its =
position in=20
      the previous week. This allows the listener to assess, not just =
the=20
      present popularity of a record, but also its rate and direction of =

      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">change =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">in popularity. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.65pt 0pt 4.1pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">It appears to be a fact that =
many people=20
      will buy a record for no better reason than that large numbers of =
other=20
      people are buying the same record, or are likely to do so. =
Striking=20
      evidence comes from the fact that record companies have been known =
to send=20
      representatives into key shops to buy up large numbers of their =
own=20
      records, in order to push sales figures up into the region where =
they may=20
      'take off. (This is not so difficult to do as it sounds, because =
the Top=20
      20 figures are based upon sales returns from a small sample of =
record=20
      shops. If you know which these key shops are, you don't have to =
buy all=20
      that many records from them in order to make a significant impact =
on=20
      nationwide estimates of sales. There are also well-authenticated =
stories=20
      of shop assistants in these key shops being bribed.) </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.1in 0pt 1.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">To a lesser extent, the same =
phenomenon=20
      of popularity being popular for its own sake is well known in the =
worlds=20
      of book publishing, womens' fashions, and advertising generally. =
One of=20
      the best things an advertiser can say about a product is that it =
is the=20
      bestselling product of its kind. Best-seller lists of books are =
published=20
      weekly, and it is undoubtedly true that as soon as a book sells =
enough=20
      copies to appear in one of these lists, its sales increase even =
more,=20
      simply by virtue of that fact. Publishers speak of a book 'taking =
off, and=20
      those publishers with some knowledge of science even speak of a =
'critical=20
      mass for take-off. The analogy here is to an atomic bomb. =
Uranium-235 is=20
      stable as long as you don't have too much of it in one place. =
There is a=20
      critical mass which, once exceeded, permits a chain reaction or =
runaway=20
      process to get going, with devastating results. An </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.1in 0pt 1.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D11 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D34 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
