style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D484 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D386 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D484>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.65pt 0pt 1.9pt"><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">220 </SPAN></B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.25pt 0pt 1.7pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">atom bomb contains two lumps of =

      uranium-235, both smaller than the critical mass. When the bomb is =

      detonated the two lumps are thrust together, the critical mass is=20
      exceeded, and that is the end of a medium-sized^ city. When a =
book's sales=20
      'go critical', the numbers reach the point where word-of-mouth=20
      recommendations et cetera cause its sales suddenly to take-off in =
a=20
      runaway fashion. Rates of sales suddenly become dramatically =
larger than=20
      they were before critical mass was reached, and there may be a =
period of=20
      exponential growth before the inevitable levelling out and =
subsequent=20
      decline. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The underlying phenomena are =
not=20
      difficult to understand. Basically . we have here yet more =
examples of=20
      positive feedback. A book's, 01 even <BR>a pop record's, real =
qualities=20
      are not negligible in determining its sales but, nevertheless, =
wherever=20
      there are positive feedbacks lurking, there is bound to be a =
strong=20
      arbitrary element determining which book or record succeeds, and =
which=20
      fails. If critical mass and take-off are important elements in any =
success=20
      story, there is bound to be a lot of luck, and there is also =
plenty of=20
      scope for manipulation and exploitation by people that understand =
the=20
      system. It is, for instance, worth laying out a considerable sum =
of money=20
      to promote a book or record up to the point where it just 'goes =
critical',=20
      because you then don't need to spend so much money on promoting it =

      thereafter: the positive feedbacks take over and do the work of =
publicity=20
      for you. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 5.65pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The positive feedbacks here =
have=20
      something in common with those of sexual selection according to =
the=20
      Fisher/Lande theory, but there are differences too. Peahens that =
prefer=20
      long-tailed peacocks are favoured solely because </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">other </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">females have the same =
preference. The=20
      male's qualities themselves are arbitrary and irrelevant. In this =
respect,=20
      the record enthusiast who wants a particular record just because =
it is in=20
      the Top 20 is behaving just like a peahen. But the precise =
mechanisms by=20
      which the positive feedbacks work in the two cases are different. =
And=20
      this, I suppose, brings us back to where we began in this chapter, =
with a=20
      warning that analogies should be taken so far, and no farther. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 5.65pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
