<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D561 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D561>
      <P class=3DStyle16 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 104.55pt 0pt =
110.4pt">CHAPTER 9 <SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <H2 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 55.65pt 0pt 61.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 16.5pt">PUNCTURING PUNCTUATIONISM </SPAN><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR><BR><BR></SPAN></H2>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The children of Israel, =
according to the=20
      Exodus story, took 40 years to migrate across the Sinai desert to =
the=20
      promised land. That is a distance of some 200 miles. Their average =
speed=20
      was, therefore, approximately 24 yards per day, or 1 yard per =
hour; say 3=20
      yards per hour if we allow for night stops. However we do the =
calculation,=20
      we are dealing with an absurdly slow average speed, much slower =
than the=20
      proverbially slow snail's pace (an incredible 55 yards per hour is =
the=20
      speed of the world record snail according to the </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Guinness Book of Records].=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">But of course =
nobody=20
      really believes that the average speed was continuously and =
uniformly=20
      maintained. Obviously the Israelites travelled in fits and starts, =
perhaps=20
      camping for long periods in one spot before moving on. Probably =
many of=20
      them had no very clear idea that they were </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">travelling </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">in any particularly consistent =
direction,=20
      and they meandered round and round from oasis to oasis as nomadic =
desert=20
      herdsmen are wont to do. Nobody, I repeat, really believes that =
the=20
      average speed was continuously and uniformly maintained. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.35pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">But now suppose that two =
eloquent young=20
      historians burst upon the scene. Biblical history so far, they =
tell us,=20
      has been dominated by the 'gradualistic' school of thought. =
'Gradualist'=20
      historians, we are told, literally believe that the Israelites =
travelled=20
      24 yards per day, they folded their tents every morning, crawled =
24 yards=20
      in an east-northeasterly direction, and then pitched camp again. =
The only=20
      alternative to 'gradualism', we are told, is the dynamic new=20
      'punctuationist' school of history. According to the radical young =

      punctuationists, the Israelites spent most of their time in =
'stasis', not=20
      moving at all but camped, often for years at a time, in one place. =
Then=20
      they would move on, rather fast, to a </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">new </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">encampment, where they=20
<BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle23 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.5pt 0pt 3.55in"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica">223 </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle23 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.5pt 0pt 3.55in"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Helvetica"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 8pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Helvetica"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D381 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.25pt 0pt 2.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">224 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 2.15pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">again stayed for several years. =
Their=20
      progress towards the promised land, instead of being gradual and=20
      continuous, was jerky: long periods of stasis punctuated by brief =
periods=20
      of rapid movement. Moreover, their bursts of movement were not =
always in=20
      the direction of the promised land, but were in almost random =
directions.=20
      It is only when we look, with hindsight, at the large scale=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">maciomigiational=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">pattern, that =
we can see=20
      a trend in the direction of the promised land. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.7pt 0pt 1.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Such is the eloquence of the=20
      punctuationist biblical historians that they become a media =
sensation.=20
      Their portraits adorn the front covers </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">of </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">mass circulation news =
magazines. No=20
      television documentary about biblical history is complete without =
an=20
      interview with at least one leading punctuationist. People who =
know=20
      nothing else of biblical scholarship remember just the one fact: =
that in=20
      the dark days before the punctuationists burst upon the scene, =
everybody=20
      else got it wrong. Note that the publicity value of the =
punctuationists=20
      has nothing to do with the fact that they may be right. It has =
everything=20
      to do with the allegation that earlier authorities were =
'gradualist' and=20
      wrong. It is because the punctuationists sell themselves as=20
      revolutionaries that they are listened to, not because they are =
right.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.7pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">My story about the =
punctuationist=20
      biblical historians is, of course, not really true. It is a =
parable about=20
      an analogous alleged controversy among students of biological =
evolution.=20
      In some respects it is an unfair parable, but it is not totally =
unfair and=20
      it has enough truth in it to justify its telling at the beginning =
of this=20
      chapter. There is a highly advertised school of thought among =
evolutionary=20
      biologists whose proponents call themselves punctuationists, and =
they did=20
      invent the term 'gradualist' for their most influential =
predecessors. They=20
      have enjoyed enormous publicity, among a public that knows almost =
nothing=20
      else about evolution, and this is largely because their position =
has been=20
      represented, by secondary reporters more than by themselves, as =
radically=20
      different from the positions of previous evolutionists, especially =
Charles=20
      Darwin. So far, my biblical analogy is a fair one. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.15pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The respect in which the =
analogy is=20
      unfair is that in the story of the biblical historians 'the =
gradualists'=20
      were </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">obviously =

      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">non-existent =
straw men,=20
      fabricated by the punctuationists. In the case of the evolutionary =

      'gradualists', the fact that they are non-existent straw men is =
not quite=20
      so obvious. It needs to be demonstrated. It is possible to =
interpret the=20
      words of Darwin and many other evolutionists as gradualist in =
intent, but=20
      it then becomes important to realize that the word gradualist can =
be=20
      interpreted in different ways to mean different things. Indeed, I =
shall=20
      develop an interpretation of the word 'gradualist' according to =
which just=20
      about everybody is a gradualist. In the evolutionary case, unlike =
in=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.15pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D11 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D58 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D11>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D11 =

      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image093.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D58></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D9 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D52 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D9>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D9=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image094.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D52></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D380 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 2.9pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">puncturing punctuationism=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">225 =
<BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.2pt 0pt 2.4pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.55pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the parable of the Israelites, =
there is=20
      genuine controversy lurking, but that genuine controversy is about =
little=20
      details which are nowhere near important enough to justify all the =
media=20
      hype. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.45pt 0pt 1.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Among evolutionists, the=20
      'punctuationists' were originally drawn from the ranks of =
palaeontology.=20
      Palaeontology is the study of fossils. It is a very important =
branch of=20
      biology, because evolutionary ancestors all died long ago and =
fossils=20
      provide us with our only direct evidence of the animals and plants =
of the=20
      distant past. If we want to know what our evolutionary ancestors =
looked=20
      like, fossils are our main hope. As soon as people realized what =
fossils=20
      really were - previous schools of thought had held that they were=20
      creations of the devil, </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold">or=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">that they were =
the bones=20
      of poor sinners drowned in the flood - it became clear that any =
theory of=20
      evolution must have certain expectations about the fossil record. =
But=20
      there has been some discussion of exactly what those expectations =
are, and=20
      this is partly what the punctuationism argument is about. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.75pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">We are lucky to have fossils at =
all. It=20
      is a remarkably fortunate fact of geology that bones, shells and =
other=20
      hard parts of animals, before they decay, can occasionally leave =
an=20
      imprint which later acts as a mould, which shapes hardening rock =
into a=20
      permanent memory of the animal. We don't know what proportion of =
animals=20
      are fossilized after their death - I personally would consider it =
an=20
      honour to be fossilized =97 but it is certainly very small indeed. =

      Nevertheless, however small the proportion fossilized, there are =
certain=20
      things about the fossil record that any evolutionist should expect =
to be=20
      true. We should be very surprised, for example, to find fossil =
humans=20
      appearing in the record before mammals are supposed to have =
evolved! If a=20
      single, well-verified mammal skull were to turn up in 500. million =

      year-old rocks, our whole modern theory of evolution would be =
utterly=20
      destroyed. Incidentally, this is a sufficient answer to the =
canard, put=20
      about by creationists and their journalistic fellow travellers, =
that the=20
      whole theory of evolution is an 'unfalsifiable' tautology. =
Ironically, it=20
      is also the reason why creationists are so keen on the fake human=20
      footprints, which were carved during the depression to fool =
tourists, in=20
      the dinosaur beds of Texas. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.25pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.35pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Anyway, if we arrange our =
genuine fossils=20
      in order, from oldest to youngest, the theory of evolution expects =
to see=20
      some sort of orderly sequence rather than a higgledy-piggledy =
jumble. More=20
      to the point in this chapter, different versions of the theory of=20
      evolution, for instance 'gradualism' and 'punctuationism', might =
expect to=20
      see different kinds of pattern. Such expectations can be tested =
only if we=20
      have some means of </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">dating </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">fossils, or at least of knowing =
the order=20
      in which they were </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.25pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.35pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.4pt 0pt 1.45pt"><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">226 </SPAN></B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.45pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">laid down. The problems of =
dating=20
      fossils, and the solutions of these problems, require a brief =
digression,=20
      the first of several for which the reader's indulgence is asked. =
They are=20
      necessary for the explanation of the main theme of the chapter.=20
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.7pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">We have long known how to =
arrange fossils=20
      in the order in which they were laid down. The method is inherent =
in the=20
      very phrase 'laid down'. More recent fossils are obviously laid =
down on=20
      top of older fossils rather than underneath them, and they =
therefore lie=20
      above them in rock sediments. Occasionally volcanic upheavals can =
turn a=20
      chunk of rock right over and then, of course, the order in which =
we find=20
      fossils as we dig downwards will be exactly reversed; but this is =
rare=20
      enough to be obvious when it occurs. Even though we seldom find a =
complete=20
      historical record as we dig down through the rocks of any one =
area, a good=20
      record can be pieced together from overlapping portions in =
different areas=20
      (actually, although I use the image of 'digging down', =
palaeontologists=20
      seldom literally dig downwards through strata; they are more =
likely to=20
      find fossils exposed by erosion at various depths). Long before =
they knew=20
      how to date fossils in actual millions of years, palaeontologists =
had=20
      worked out a reliable scheme of geological eras, and they knew in =
great=20
      detail which era came before which. Certain kinds of shells are =
such=20
      reliable indicators of the ages of rocks that they are among the =
main=20
      indicators used by oil prospectors in the field. By themselves, =
however,=20
      they can tell us only about the relative ages of rock strata, =
never their=20
      absolute ages. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.65pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">More recently, advances in =
physics have=20
      given us methods to put absolute dates, in millions of years, on =
rocks and=20
      the fossils that they contain. These methods depend upon the fact =
that=20
      particular radioactive elements decay at precisely known rates. It =
is as=20
      though precision-made miniature stopwatches had been conveniently =
buried=20
      in the rocks. Each stopwatch was started at the moment that it was =
laid=20
      down. All that the palaeontologist has to do is dig it up and read =
off the=20
      time on the dial. Different kinds of radioactive decay-based =
geological=20
      stopwatches run at different rates. The radiocarbon stopwatch =
buzzes round=20
      at a great rate, so fast that, after some thousands of years, its =
spring=20
      is almost wound down and the watch is no longer reliable. It is =
useful for=20
      dating organic material on the archaeological/historical timescale =
where=20
      we are dealing in hundreds or a few thousands of years, but it is =
no good=20
      for the evolutionary timescale where we are dealing in millions of =
years.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
1.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">For the evolutionary timescale =
other=20
      kinds of watch, such as the potassium=97argon watch, are suitable. =
The=20
      potassium-argon watch is so slow that it would be unsuitable for =
the=20
      archaeological/historical </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
1.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D11 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D49 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D11>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D11 =

      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image095.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D49></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D381 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.05in"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Puncturing punctuationism=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">227 =
<BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.1pt 0pt 2.65pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">timescale. That would be like =
trying to=20
      use the hour hand on an ordinary watch to time an athlete =
sprinting a=20
      hundred yards. For timing the megamarathon that is evolution, on =
the other=20
      hand, <BR>something like the potassium-argon watch is just what is =
needed.=20
      Other radioactive 'stopwatches', each with its own characteristic =
rate of=20
      slowing down, are the rubidium-strontium, and the uranium=97 =
thorium-lead=20
      watches. So, this digression has told us that if a palaeontologist =
is=20
      presented with a fossil, he can usually know when the animal =
lived, on an=20
      absolute timescale of millions of years. We got into this =
discussion of=20
      dating and timing in the first place, you will remember, because =
we were=20
      interested in the expectations about the fossil record that =
various kinds=20
      of evolutionary theory - ' <BR>punctuationist', 'gradualist', etc. =
-=20
      should have. It is now time to discuss what those various =
expectations=20
      are. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Suppose, first, that nature had =
been=20
      extraordinarily kind to palaeontologists (or perhaps unkind, when =
you=20
      think of the extra work involved), and given them a fossil of =
every animal=20
      that ever lived. If we could indeed look at such a complete fossil =
record,=20
      carefully arranged in chronological order, what should we, as=20
      evolutionists, expect to see? Well, if we are 'gradualists', in =
the sense=20
      caricatured in the parable of the Israelites, we should expect =
something=20
      like the following. Chronological sequences of fossils will always =
exhibit=20
      smooth evolutionary trends with fixed rates of change. In other =
words, if=20
      we have three fossils, A, B and C, A being ancestral to B, which =
is=20
      ancestral to C, we should expect B to be proportionately =
intermediate in=20
      form between A and C. For instance, if A had a leg length of 20 =
inches and=20
      C had a leg length of 40 inches, B's legs should be intermediate, =
their=20
      exact length being proportional to the time that elapsed between =
A's=20
      existence and B's. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.3pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">If we carry the caricature of =
gradualism=20
      to its logical conclusion, just as we calculated the average speed =
of the=20
      Israelites as 24 yards per day, so we can calculate the average =
rate of=20
      lengthening of the legs in the evolutionary line of descent from A =
to C.=20
      If, say, A lived 20 million years earlier than C (to fit this =
vaguely into=20
      reality, the earliest known member of the horse family, =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Hyiacotherium, =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">lived about 50 million years =
ago, and was=20
      the size of a terrier), we have an evolutionary growth rate of 20=20
      leg-inches per 20 million years, or one-millionth of an inch per =
year. Now=20
      the caricature of a gradualist is supposed to believe that the =
legs=20
      steadily grew, over the generations, at this very slow rate: say=20
      four-millionths of an inch per generation, if we assume a =
horse-like=20
      generation-time of about 4 years. The gradualist is supposed to =
believe=20
      that, through all those millions of generations, individuals =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.3pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.5pt 0pt 1.2pt"><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">228 </SPAN></B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.95pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.8pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">with legs four-millionths of an =
inch=20
      longer than the average had an advantage over individuals with =
legs of=20
      average length. To believe this is like believing that the =
Israelites=20
      travelled 24 yards every day across the desert. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.5pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The same is true even of one of =
the=20
      fastest known evolutionary changes, the swelling of the human =
skull from=20
      an <BR></SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">Australopithecus</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">like ancestor, with a brain =
volume of=20
      about 500 cubic centimetres (cc), to the modern </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Homo sapiens's =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">average brain volume of about =
1,400 cc.=20
      This increase of about 900 cc, nearly a tripling in brain volume, =
has been=20
      accomplished in no more than three million years. By evolutionary=20
      standards this is a rapid rate of change: the brain seems to swell =
like a=20
      balloon and indeed, seen from some angles, the modem human skull =
does=20
      rather resemble a bulbous, spherical balloon in comparison to the =
flatter,=20
      sloping-browed skull of </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Australopithecus. =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">But if we count up the number =
of=20
      generations in three million years (say about four per century), =
the=20
      average rate of evolution is less than a hundredth of a cubic =
centimetre=20
      per generation. The caricature of a gradualist is supposed to =
believe that=20
      there was a slow and inexorable change, generation by generation, =
such=20
      that in all generations sons were slightly brainier than their =
fathers,=20
      brainier by 0.01 cc. Presumably the extra hundredth of a cubic =
centimetre=20
      is supposed to provide each succeeding generation with a =
significant=20
      survival advantage compared with the previous generation. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.3pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">But a hundredth of a cubic =
centimetre is=20
      a tiny quantity in comparison to the range of brain sizes that we =
find=20
      among modern humans. It is an often-quoted fact, for instance, =
that the=20
      writer Anatole France =97 no fool, and a Nobel prizewinner - had a =
brain=20
      size of less than 1,000 cc, while at the other end of the range, =
brains of=20
      2,000 cc are not unknown: Oliver Cromwell is frequently cited as =
an=20
      example, though I do not know with what authenticity. The average=20
      per-generation increment of 0.01 cc, then, which is supposed by =
the=20
      caricature of a gradualist to give a significant survival =
advantage, is a=20
      mere hundredthousandth part of the </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">difference </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">between the brains of Anatole =
France and=20
      Oliver Cromwell! It is fortunate that the caricature of a =
gradualist does=20
      not really exist. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
1.25pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Well, if this kind of =
gradualist is a=20
      non-existent caricature - a windmill for punctuationist lances =97 =
is there=20
      some other kind of gradualist who really exists and who holds =
tenable=20
      beliefs? I shall show that the answer is yes, and that the ranks =
of=20
      gradualists, in this second sense, include all sensible =
evolutionists,=20
      among them, when you look carefully at their beliefs, those that =
call=20
      themselves punctuationists. But we have to understand why the=20
      punctuationists </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">thought=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">that their =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
1.25pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D383 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle11 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.1pt 0pt 5.05pt"><I><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Puncturing punctuationism=20
      </SPAN></I><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica-Bold">229=20
      </SPAN></B><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: =
9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 4.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.35pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">views were revolutionary and =
exciting.=20
      The starting point for discussing these matters is the apparent =
existence=20
      of 'gaps' in the fossil record, and it is to these gaps that we =
now turn.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.4pt 0pt 0.05in; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">From Darwin onwards =
evolutionists have=20
      realized that, if we arrange all our available fossils in =
chronological=20
      order, they do not form a smooth sequence of scarcely perceptible =
change.=20
      We can, to be sure, discern long-term trends of change - legs get=20
      progressively longer, skulls get progressively more bulbous, and =
so on -=20
      but the trends as seen in the fossil record are usually jerky, not =
smooth.=20
      Darwin, and most others following him, have assumed that this is =
mainly=20
      because the fossil record is imperfect. Darwin's view was that a =
complete=20
      fossil record, if only we had one, </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">would </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">show gentle rather than jerky =
change. But=20
      since fossilization is such a chancy business, and finding such =
fossils as=20
      there, are is scarcely less chancy, it is as though we had a cine =
film=20
      with most of the frames missing. We can, to be sure, see movement =
of a=20
      kind when we project our film of fossils, but it is more jerky =
than=20
      Charlie Chaplin, for even the oldest and scratchiest Charlie =
Chaplin film=20
      hasn't completely lost nine-tenths of its frames. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.75pt 0pt 1.45pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The American palaeontologists =
Niles=20
      Eldredge and Stephen Jay Gould, when they first proposed their =
theory of=20
      punctuated equilibria </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold">in=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">1972, made =
what has=20
      since been represented as a very different suggestion. They =
suggested=20
      that, actually, the fossil record may not be as imperfect as we =
thought.=20
      Maybe the 'gaps' are a true reflection of what really happened, =
rather=20
      than being the annoying but inevitable consequences of an =
imperfect fossil=20
      record. Maybe, they suggested, evolution really did in some sense =
go in=20
      sudden bursts, punctuating long periods of 'stasis', when no =
evolutionary=20
      change took place in a given lineage. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.05pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.35pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Before we come to the sort of =
sudden=20
      bursts that they had in mind, there are some conceivable meanings =
of=20
      'sudden bursts' that they most definitely did not have in.mind. =
These must=20
      be cleared out of the way because they have been the subject of =
serious=20
      misunderstandings. Eldredge and Gould certainly would agree that =
some very=20
      important gaps really are due to imperfections in the fossil =
record. Very=20
      big gaps, too. For example the Cambrian strata of rocks, vintage =
about 600=20
      million years, are the oldest ones in which we find most of the =
major=20
      invertebrate groups. And we find many of them already in an =
advanced state=20
      of evolution, the very first time they appear. It is as though =
they were=20
      just planted there, without any evolutionary history. Needless to =
say,=20
      this appearance of sudden planting has delighted creationists.=20
      Evolutionists of all stripes believe, however, that this really =
does=20
      represent a very large gap in the fossil record, a gap that is =
simply due=20
      </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">to =
</SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.05pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.35pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D380 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.5pt 0pt 1.45pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">230 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.45pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the fact that, for some reason, =
very few=20
      fossils have lasted from periods before about 600 million years =
ago. One=20
      good reason might be that many of these animals had only soft =
parts to=20
      their bodies: no shells or bones to fossilize. If you are a =
creationist=20
      you may think that this is special pleading. My point here is =
that, when=20
      we are talking about gaps of this magnitude, there is no =
difference=20
      whatever in the <BR>interpretations of 'punctuationists' and=20
      'gradualists'. Both schools of thought despise so-called =
scientific=20
      creationists equally, and both agree that the </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">major </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">gaps are real, that they are =
true=20
      imperfections in the fossil record. Both schools of thought agree =
that the=20
      only alternative explanation of the sudden appearance of so many =
complex=20
      animal types in the Cambrian era is divine creation, and both =
would reject=20
      this alternative. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.1pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">There is another conceivable =
sense in=20
      which evolution might be said to go in sudden jerks, but which is =
also not=20
      the sense being proposed by Eldredge and Gould, at least in most =
of their=20
      writings. It is conceivable that some of the apparent 'gaps' in =
the fossil=20
      record really do reflect sudden change in a single generation. It =
is=20
      conceivable that there really never were any intermediates; =
conceivable=20
      that large evolutionary changes took place in a single generation. =
A son=20
      might be born so different from his father that he properly =
belongs in a=20
      different species from his father. He would be a mutant =
individual, and=20
      the mutation would be such a large one that we should refer to it =
as a=20
      macromutation. Theories of evolution that depend upon =
macromutation are=20
      called 'saltation' theories, from </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">saltus, </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the Latin for 'jump'. Since the =
theory of=20
      punctuated equilibria frequently is confused with true saltation, =
it is=20
      important here to discuss saltation, and show why it cannot be a=20
      significant factor in evolution. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
1.35pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Macromutations =97 mutations of =
large=20
      effect - undoubtedly occur. What is at issue is not whether they =
occur but=20
      whether they play a role in evolution; whether, .in other words, =
they are=20
      incorporated into the gene pool of a species, or whether, on the =
contrary,=20
      they are always eliminated by natural selection. A famous example =
of a=20
      macromutation is 'antennapaedia' in fruitflies. In a normal insect =
the=20
      antennae have something in common with the legs, and they develop =
in the=20
      embryo in a similar way. But the differences are striking as well, =
and the=20
      two sorts of limb are used for very different purposes: the legs =
for=20
      walking; the antennae for feeling, smelling and otherwise sensing =
things.=20
      Antennapaedic flies are freaks in which the antennae develop just =
like=20
      legs. Or, another way of putting it, they are flies that have no =
antennae=20
      but an extra pair of legs, growing out of the sockets where the =
antennae=20
      ought to be. This is a true mutation in that it results from an=20
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
1.35pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D381 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.5pt 0pt 3.35pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Puncturing punctuationism=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">231 =
<BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 2.65pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">error in the copying of DNA. =
And it=20
      breeds true if antennapaedic flies are cosseted in the laboratory =
so that=20
      they survive long enough to breed at all. They would not survive =
long in=20
      the wild, as their movements are clumsy and their vital senses are =

      impaired. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1pt 0pt 2.65pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">So, macromutations do happen. =
But do they=20
      play a role in evolution? People called saltationists believe that =

      macromutations are a means by which major jumps in evolution could =
take=20
      place in a single generation. Richard Goldschmidt, whom we met in =
Chapter=20
      4, was a true saltationist. If saltationism were true, apparent =
'gaps' in=20
      the fossil record needn't be gaps at all. For example, a =
saltationist=20
      might believe that the transition from sloping-browed =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Australopithecus to =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">domebrowed </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Homo sapiens </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">took place in a single =
macromutational=20
      step, in a single generation. The difference in form between the =
two=20
      species is probably less thap the difference between a normal and =
an=20
      antennapaedic fruitfly, and it is theoretically conceivable that =
the first=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Homo sapiens=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">was a freak =
child -=20
      probably an ostracized and persecuted one - of two normal =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Australopithecus =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">parents. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.4pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">There are very good reasons for =
rejecting=20
      all such saltationist theories of evolution. One rather boring =
reason is=20
      that if a new species really did arise in a single mutational =
step,=20
      members of the new species might have a hard time finding mates. =
But I=20
      find this reason less telling and interesting than two others =
which have=20
      already been foreshadowed in our discussion of why major jumps =
across=20
      Biomorph Land are to be ruled out. The first of these points was =
put by=20
      the great statistician and biologist R. A. Fisher, whom we met in =
other=20
      connections in previous chapters. Fisher was a stalwart opponent =
of all=20
      forms of saltationism, at a time when saltationism was much more=20
      fashionable than it is today, and he used the following analogy. =
Think, he=20
      said, of a microscope which is almost, but not quite perfectly, in =
focus=20
      and otherwise well adjusted for distinct vision. What are the odds =
that,=20
      if we make some random change to the state of the microscope=20
      (corresponding to a mutation), we shall improve the focus and =
general=20
      quality of the image? Fisher said: <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 9.3pt 0pt 9.6pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 9.9pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">It is sufficiently obvious that =
any large=20
      derangement will have a very small probability of improving the=20
      adjustment, while in the case of alterations much less than the =
smallest=20
      of those intentionally effected by the maker or the operator, the =
chance=20
      of improvement should be almost exactly one half. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
3.5pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">I have already remarked that =
what Fisher=20
      found 'easy to see' could place formidable demands on the mental =
powers of=20
      ordinary scientists, and the same is true of what Fisher thought =
was=20
      'sufficiently obvious'. Nevertheless, further cogitation almost =
always=20
      shows him </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">to=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">have =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
3.5pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.45pt 0pt 1.2pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">232 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">been right, and in this case we =
can prove=20
      it to our own satisfaction without too much difficulty. Remember =
that we=20
      are assuming the microscope to be almost in correct focus before =
we start.=20
      Suppose that the lens is slightly lower than it ought to be for =
perfect=20
      focus, say a tenth of an inch too close to the slide. Now if we =
move it a=20
      small amount, say a hundredth of an inch, in a random direction, =
what are=20
      the odds that the focus will improve? Well, if we happen to move =
it=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">down =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">a hundredth of an inch, the =
focus will=20
      get worse. If we happen to move it </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">up </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">a hundredth of an inch, the =
focus will=20
      get better. Since we are moving it in a random direction, the =
chance of=20
      each of these two eventualities is one half. The smaller the =
movement of=20
      adjustment, in relation to the initial error, the closer will the =
chance=20
      of improvement approach one half. That completes the justification =
of the=20
      second part of Fisher's statement. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.6pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">But now, suppose we move the =
microscope=20
      tube a large distance =97 equivalent to a macromutation - also in =
a random=20
      direction; suppose we move it a full inch. Now it doesn't matter =
which=20
      direction we move it in, up or down, we shall still make the focus =
worse=20
      than it was before. If we chance to move it down, it will now be =
one and=20
      one-tenth inches away from its ideal position (and will probably =
have=20
      crunched through the slide). If we chance to move it up, it will =
now be=20
      ninetenths of an inch away from its ideal position. Before the =
move, it=20
      was only one-tenth of an inch away from its ideal position so, =
either way,=20
      our 'macromutational' big move has been a bad thing. We have done =
the=20
      calculation for a very big move ('macromutation') and a very small =
move=20
      ('micromutation'). We can obviously do the same calculation for a =
range of=20
      intermediate sizes of move, but there is no point in doing so. I =
think it=20
      really will now be sufficiently obvious that the smaller we make =
the move,=20
      the closer we shall approach the extreme case </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">in </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">which the odds of an =
improvement are=20
      one-half, and the larger we make the move, the closer we shall =
approach=20
      the extreme case in which the odds of an improvement are zero. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.95pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The reader will have noticed =
that this=20
      argument depends upon the initial assumption that the microscope =
was=20
      already pretty close to being in focus before we even started =
making=20
      random adjustments. If the microscope starts 2 inches out of =
focus, then a=20
      random change of 1 inch has a 50 per cent chance of being an =
improvement,=20
      just as a random change of one-hundredth of an inch has. In this =
case the=20
      'macromutation' appears to have the advantage that it moves the =
microscope=20
      into focus more quickly. Fisher's argument will, of course, apply =
here to=20
      'megamutations' of, say, 6 inches movement in a random direction.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.95pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D381 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle37 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 3.35pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Puncturing punctuationism=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica">233 </SPAN><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.3pt 0pt 2.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Why, then, was Fisher allowed =
to make his=20
      initial assumption that the microscope was nearly in focus at the =
start?=20
      The assumption flows from the role of the microscope in the =
analogy. The=20
      microscope after its random adjustment stands for a mutant animal. =
The=20
      microscope before its random adjustment stands for the normal, =
unmutated=20
      parent of the supposed mutant animal. Since it is a parent, it =
must have=20
      survived long enough to reproduce, and therefore it cannot be all =
that far=20
      from being well-adjusted. By the same token, the microscope before =
the=20
      random jolt cannot be all that far from being in focus, or the =
animal that=20
      it stands for in the analogy couldn't have survived at all. It is =
only an=20
      analogy, and there is no point in arguing over whether 'all that =
far'=20
      means an inch or a tenth of an inch or a thousandth of an inch. =
The=20
      important point is that if we consider mutations of =
ever-increasing=20
      magnitude, there will come a point when, the larger the mutation =
is, the=20
      less likely it is to be beneficial; while if we consider mutations =
of=20
      ever-decreasing magnitude, there will come a point when the chance =
of a=20
      mutation's being beneficial is 50 per cent. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.05pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The argument over whether =
macromutations=20
      such as antennapaedia could ever be beneficial (or at least could =
avoid=20
      being harmful), and therefore whether they could give rise to =
evolutionary=20
      change, <BR>therefore turns on </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">how </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">'macro' the mutation is that we =
are=20
      considering. The more 'macro' it is, the more likely it is to be=20
      deleterious, and the less likely it is to be incorporated in the =
evolution=20
      of a species. As a matter of fact, virtually all the mutations =
studied in=20
      genetics laboratories - which are pretty macro because otherwise=20
      geneticists wouldn't notice them - are deleterious to the animals=20
      possessing them (ironically I've met people who think that this is =
an=20
      argument </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">against=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Darwinism!). =
Fisher's=20
      microscope argument, then, provides one reason for scepticism =
about=20
      'saltation' theories of evolution, at least in their extreme form. =

      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.5pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The other general reason for =
not=20
      believing in true saltation is also a statistical one, and its =
force also=20
      depends quantitatively on </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">how </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">macro is the macromutation we =
are=20
      postulating. In this case it is concerned with the complexity of=20
      evolutionary changes. Many, though not all, of the evolutionary =
changes we=20
      are interested in are advances in complexity of design. The =
extreme=20
      example of the eye, discussed in earlier chapters, makes the point =
clear.=20
      Animals with eyes like ours evolved from ancestors with no eyes at =
all. An=20
      extreme saltationist might postulate that the evolution took place =
in a=20
      single mutational step. A parent had no eye at all, just bare skin =
where=20
      the eye might be. He had a freak offspring with a fully developed =
eye,=20
      complete with variable focus lens, iris diaphragm for 'stopping =
down',=20
      retina with millions </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold">of=20
      </SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.5pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D15 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D18 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D15>
      <P class=3DStyle11><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Helvetica-Bold">234=20
      </SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle11><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Helvetica-Bold"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D16 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D132 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D16>
      <P class=3DStyle6><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The =
Blind=20
      Watchmaker </SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle6><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D600 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D600>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.3pt 0pt 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 11.15pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">three-colour photocells, all =
with nerves=20
      correctly connected up in the brain to provide him with correct,=20
      binocular, stereoscopic colour vision. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.5pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">In the biomorph model we =
assumed that=20
      this kind of multidimensional improvement could not occur. To =
recapitulate=20
      on why that was a reasonable assumption, to make an eye from =
nothing you=20
      need not just one improvement but a large number of improvements. =
Any one=20
      of these improvements is pretty improbable by itself, but not so=20
      improbable as to be impossible. The greater the number of =
simultaneous=20
      improvements we consider, the more improbable is their =
simultaneous=20
      occurrence. The coincidence of their simultaneous occurrence is =
equivalent=20
      to leaping a large distance across Biomorph Land, and happening to =
land on=20
      one particular, predesignated spot. If we choose to consider a=20
      sufficiently large number of improvements, their joint occurrence =
becomes=20
      so improbable as to be, to all intents and purposes, impossible. =
The=20
      argument has already been sufficiently made, but it may be helpful =
to draw=20
      a distinction between two kinds of hypothetical macromutation, =
both of=20
      which </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">appear=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">to be ruled =
out by the=20
      complexity argument but only one of which, in fact, =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">is </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">ruled out by the complexity =
argument. I=20
      label them, for reasons that will become clear, Boeing 747 =
macromutations=20
      and Stretched DC8 <BR>macromutations. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.55pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Boeing 747 macromutations are =
the ones=20
      that really are ruled out by the complexity argument just given. =
They get=20
      their name from the astronomer Sir Fred Hoyle's memorable =
misunderstanding=20
      of the theory of natural selection. He compared natural selection, =
in its=20
      alleged improbability, to a hurricane blowing through a junkyard =
and=20
      chancing to assemble a Boeing 747. As we saw in Chapter 1, this is =
an=20
      entirely false analogy to apply to natural selection, but it is a =
very=20
      good analogy for the idea of certain kinds of macromutation giving =
rise to=20
      evolutionary change. Indeed, Hoyle's fundamental error was that =
he, in=20
      effect, thought (without realizing it) that the theory of natural=20
      selection </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">did=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">depend upon=20
      macromutation. The idea of a single macromutation's giving rise to =
a fully=20
      functioning eye with the properties listed above, where there was =
only=20
      bare skin before, is, indeed, just about as improbable as a =
hurricane=20
      assembling a Boeing 747. This is why I refer to this kind of =
hypothetical=20
      macromutation as a Boeing 747 macromutation. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Stretched DC8 macromutations =
are=20
      mutations that, although they may be large in the magnitude of =
their=20
      effects, turn out not to be large in terms of their complexity. =
The=20
      Stretched DC8 is an airliner that was made by modifying an earlier =

      airliner, the DC8. It is like a DC8, but </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D383 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle23 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05pt 0pt =
5.05pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Puncturing punctuationism=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica">235 </SPAN><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 4.1pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">with an elongated fuselage. It =
was an=20
      improvement at least from one point of view, in that it could =
carry more=20
      passengers than the original DC8. The stretching is a large =
increase in=20
      length, and in that sense is analogous to a macromutation. More=20
      interestingly, the increase in length is, at first sight, a =
complex one.=20
      To elongate the fuselage of an airliner, it is not enough just to =
insert=20
      an extra length of cabin tube. You also have to elongate countless =
ducts,=20
      cables, air tubes and electric wires. You have to put in lots more =
seats,=20
      ashtrays, reading lights, 12- channel music selectors and =
fresh-air=20
      nozzles. At first sight there seems to be much more complexity in =
a=20
      Stretched DC8 than there is in an ordinary DC8, but is there =
really? The=20
      answer is no, at least to the extent that the 'new' things in the=20
      stretched plane are just 'more of the same'. The biomorphs of =
Chapter 3=20
      frequently show macromutations of the Stretched DC8 variety. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.1pt 0pt 2.4pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">What has this to do with =
mutations in=20
      real animals? The answer is that some real mutations cause large =
changes=20
      that are very like the change from DC8 to Stretched DC8, and some =
of=20
      these, although in a sense 'macro' mutations, have definitely been =

      incorporated in evolution. Snakes, for instance, all have many =
more=20
      vertebrae than their ancestors. We could be sure of this even if =
we didn't=20
      have any fossils, because snakes have many more vertebrae than =
their=20
      surviving relatives. Moreover, different species of snakes have =
different=20
      numbers of vertebrae, which means that vertebral number must have =
changed=20
      in evolution since their common ancestor, and quite often at that. =

      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.1pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Now, to change the number of =
vertebrae in=20
      an animal, you need to do more than just shove in an extra bone. =
Each=20
      vertebra has, associated with it, a set of nerves, a set of blood =
vessels,=20
      a set of muscles etc., just as each row of seats in an airliner =
has a set=20
      of cushions, a set of head rests, a set of headphone sockets, a =
set of=20
      reading-lights with their associated cables etc. The middle part =
of the=20
      body of a snake, like the middle part of the body of an airliner, =
is=20
      composed of a number of </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">segments, </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">many of which are exactly like =
each=20
      other, however <BR>complex they all individually may be. =
Therefore, in=20
      order to add new segments, all that has to be done is a simple =
process of=20
      duplication. Since there already exists genetic machinery for =
making one=20
      snake segment - genetic machinery of great complexity, which took =
many=20
      generations of step-by-step, gradual evolution to build up =97 new =
identical=20
      segments may easily be added by a single mutational step. If we =
think of=20
      genes as 'instructions to a developing embryo', a gene for =
inserting extra=20
      segments may read, simply, 'more of the same here'. I imagine that =
the=20
      instructions for building the first Stretched DC8 were somewhat=20
      </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">similar. =
</SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.1pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D377 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.5pt 0pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">236 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">We can be sure that, in the =
evolution of=20
      snakes, numbers of vertebrae changed in whole numbers rather than =
in=20
      fractions. We cannot imagine a snake with 26.3 vertebrae. It =
either had 26=20
      or 27, and it is obvious that there must have been cases when an =
offspring=20
      snake had at least one whole vertebra more than its parents did. =
This=20
      means that it had a whole extra set of nerves, blood vessels, =
muscle=20
      blocks, etc. In a sense, then, this snake was a macro-mutant, but =
only in=20
      the weak 'Stretched DC8' sense. It is easy to believe that =
individual=20
      snakes with half a dozen more vertebrae than their parents could =
have=20
      arisen in a single mutational step. The 'complexity argument' =
against=20
      saltatory evolution does not apply to Stretched DC8 macromutations =

      because, if we look in detail at the nature of the change =
involved, they=20
      are in a real sense not true macromutations at all. They are only=20
      macromutations if we look, naively, at the finished product, the =
adult. If=20
      we look at the </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">processes=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">of embryonic =
development=20
      they turn out to be micromutations, in the sense that only a small =
change=20
      in the embryonic </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">instructions </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">had a large apparent effect in =
the adult.=20
      The same goes for antennapaedia in fruitflies and the many other =
so-called=20
      'homeotic mutations'. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.5pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">This concludes my digression on =

      macromutation and saltatory evolution. It was necessary, because =
the=20
      theory of punctuated equilibria is frequently confused with =
saltatory=20
      evolution. But it was a digression, because the theory of =
punctuated=20
      equilibria is the main topic of this chapter, and that theory in =
truth has=20
      no connection with macromutation and true saltation. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.2pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The 'gaps' that Eldredge and =
Gould and=20
      the other 'punctuationists' are talking about, then, have nothing =
to do=20
      with true saltation, and they are much much smaller gaps than the =
ones=20
      that excite creationists. Moreover, Eldredge and Gould originally=20
      introduced their theory, not as radically and revolutionarily =
antipathetic=20
      to ordinary, 'conventional' Darwinism - which is how it later came =
to be=20
      sold =97 but as something that </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">followed </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">from long-accepted conventional =

      Darwinism, properly understood. To gain this proper understanding, =
I'm=20
      afraid we need another digression, this time into the question of =
how new=20
      species originate, the process known as 'speciation'. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.15pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Darwin's answer to the question =
of the=20
      origin of species was, in a general sense, that species were =
descended=20
      from other species. Moreover, the family tree of life is a =
branching one,=20
      which means that more than one modern species can be traced back =
to one=20
      ancestral one. For instance, lions and tigers are now members of =
different=20
      species, but they have both sprung from a single ancestral =
species,=20
      probably not very long ago. This ancestral species may have been =
the same=20
      as one of </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.15pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D383 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle37 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 4.55pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Puncturing punctuationism=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica">237 </SPAN><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.45pt 0pt 0.05in; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.55pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the two modem species; or it =
may have=20
      been a third modem species, or maybe it is now extinct. Similarly, =
humans=20
      and chimps now clearly belong to different species, but their =
ancestors of=20
      a few million years ago belonged to one single species. Speciation =
is the=20
      process by which a single species becomes two species, one of =
which may be=20
      the same as the original single one. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.4pt 0pt 2.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The reason speciation is =
thought to be a=20
      difficult problem is this. All the members of the single would-be=20
      ancestral species are capable of interbreeding with one another: =
indeed,=20
      to many people, this is what is </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">meant </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">by the phrase 'single species'. =

      Therefore, every time a new daughter species begins to be 'budded =
off, the=20
      budding off is in danger of being frustrated by interbreeding. We =
can=20
      imagine the would-be ancestors of the lions and the would-be =
ancestors of=20
      the tigers failing to split apart because they keep interbreeding =
with one=20
      another and therefore staying similar to one another. Don't, =
incidentally,=20
      read too much into my use of words like 'frustrated', as though =
the=20
      ancestral lions and tigers, in some sense, 'wanted' to separate =
from each=20
      other. It is simply that, as a matter of fact, species obviously=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">have =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">diverged from one another in =
evolution,=20
      and at first sight the fact of interbreeding makes it hard for us =
to see=20
      how this divergence came about. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.7pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">It seems almost certain that =
the=20
      principal correct answer to this problem is the obvious one. There =
will be=20
      no problem of interbreeding if the ancestral lions and the =
ancestral=20
      tigers happen to be in different parts of the world, where they =
can't=20
      interbreed with each other. Of course, they didn't go to different =

      continents in order to allow themselves to diverge from one =
another: they=20
      didn't think of themselves as ancestral lions or ancestral tigers! =
But,=20
      given that the single ancestral Species spread to different =
continents=20
      anyway, say Africa and Asia, the ones that happened to be in =
Africa could=20
      no longer interbreed with the ones that happened to be in Asia =
because=20
      they never met them. If there was any tendency for the animals on =
the two=20
      continents to evolve in different directions, either under the =
influence=20
      of natural selection or under the influence of chance, =
interbreeding no=20
      longer constituted a barrier to their diverging and eventually =
becoming=20
      two distinct species. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
3.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">I have spoken of different =
continents to=20
      make it clear, but the principle of geographical separation as a =
barrier=20
      </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">to =
</SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">interbreeding </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">can </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">apply to animals on different =
sides of a=20
      desert, a mountain range, a river, or even a motorway. It can also =
apply=20
      to animals separated by </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold">no=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">barrier other =
than sheer=20
      distance. Shrews in Spain cannot interbreed with shrews in =
Mongolia, and=20
      they can diverge, evolutionarily speaking, from shrews in =
Mongolia, even=20
      if there is </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">an=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">unbroken chain =

      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
3.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.25pt 0pt 2.45in"><I><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.7pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">of interbreeding shrews =
connecting Spain=20
      to Mongolia. Nevertheless the idea of geographical separation as =
the key=20
      to speciation is clearer if we think in terms of an actual =
physical=20
      barrier, such as the sea or a mountain range. Chains of islands, =
indeed,=20
      are probably fertile nurseries for new species. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.4pt 0pt 1.45pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Here, then, is our orthodox =
nee-Darwinian=20
      picture of how a typical species is 'bom', by divergence from an =
ancestral=20
      species. We start with the ancestral species, a large population =
of rather=20
      uniform, mutually interbreeding animals, spread over a large land =
mass.=20
      They could be any sort of animal, but let's carry on thinking of =
shrews.=20
      The landmass is cut in two by a mountain range. This is hostile =
country=20
      and the shrews are unlikely to cross it, but it is not quite =
impossible=20
      and very occasionally one or two do end up in the lowlands on the =
other=20
      side. Here they can flourish, and they give rise to an outlying =
population=20
      of the species, effectively cut off from the main population. Now =
the two=20
      populations breed and breed separately, mixing their genes on each =
side of=20
      the mountains but not across the mountains. As time goes by, any =
changes=20
      in the genetic composition of one population are spread by =
breeding=20
      throughout that population but not across to the other population. =
Some of=20
      these changes may be brought about by natural selection, which may =
be=20
      different on the two sides of the mountain range: we should hardly =
expect=20
      weather conditions, and predators and parasites, to be exactly the =
same on=20
      the two sides. Some of the changes may be due to chance alone. =
Whatever=20
      the genetic changes are due to, breeding tends to spread them=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">within =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">each of the two populations, =
but not=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">between =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the two populations. So the two =

      populations diverge genetically: they become progressively more =
unlike=20
      each other. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.2pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">They become so unlike each =
other that,=20
      after a while, naturalists would see them as belonging to =
different=20
      'races'. After a longer time, they will have diverged so far that =
we=20
      should classify them as different species. Now imagine that the =
climate=20
      warms up so that travel through the mountain passes becomes easier =
and=20
      some of the new species start trickling back to their ancestral =
homelands.=20
      When they meet the descendants of their long-lost cousins, it =
turns out=20
      that they have diverged so far in their genetic makeup that they =
can no=20
      longer successfully interbreed with them. If they do hybridize =
with them=20
      the resulting offspring are sickly, or sterile like mules. So =
natural=20
      selection penalizes any predilection, on the part of individuals =
on either=20
      side, towards hybridizing with the other species or even race. =
Natural=20
      selection thereby finishes off the process of 'reproductive =
isolation'=20
      that began with the chance intervention of a mountain range. =
'Speciation'=20
      is complete. We now have two species where previously </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.2pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D387 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 160.35pt 0pt =
7.45pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Puncturing punctuationism=20
      </SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.35pt 0pt 6.95pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">there was one, and the two =
species can=20
      coexist in the same area without interbreeding with one another.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 6.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Actually, the likelihood is =
that the two=20
      species would not coexist </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">for </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">very long. This is not because =
they would=20
      interbreed but because they would compete. It is a widely accepted =

      principle of ecology that two species with the same way of life =
will not=20
      coexist for long in one place, because they will compete and one =
or other=20
      will be driven extinct. Of course our two populations of shrews =
might no=20
      longer have the same way of life; for instance, the new species, =
during=20
      its period of evolution on the other side of the mountains, might =
have=20
      come to specialize on a different kind of insect prey. But if =
there is=20
      significant competition between the two species, most ecologists =
would=20
      expect one or other species'to go extinct in the area of overlap. =
If it=20
      happened to be the original, ancestral species that was driven =
extinct, we=20
      should say that it had been replaced by the new, immigrant =
species.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.95pt 0pt 5.3pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The theory of speciation =
resulting from=20
      initial geographical separation has long been a cornerstone of =
mainstream,=20
      orthodox nee-Darwinism, and it is still accepted on all sides as =
the main=20
      process by which new species come into existence (some people =
think there=20
      are others as well). Its incorporation into modern Darwinism was =
largely=20
      due to the influence of the distinguished zoologist Ernst Mayr. =
What the=20
      'punctuationists' did, when they first proposed their theory, was =
to ask=20
      themselves: Given that, like most neo-Darwinians, we <BR>. accept =
the=20
      orthodox theory that speciation starts with geographical =
isolation, what=20
      should we expect to see in the fossil record? </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.7pt 0pt 4.55pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Recall the hypothetical =
population of=20
      shrews, with a new species diverging on the far side of a mountain =
range,=20
      then eventually returning to the ancestral homelands and, quite =
possibly,=20
      driving the ancestral species extinct. Suppose that these shrews =
had left=20
      fossils; suppose even that the fossil record was </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">perfect, </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">with no gaps due to the =
unfortunate=20
      omission of key stages. What should we expect these fossils to =
show us? A=20
      smooth transition from ancestral species to daughter species? =
Certainly=20
      not, at least if we are digging in the main landmass where the =
original=20
      ancestral shrews lived, and to which the new species returned. =
Think of=20
      the history of what actually happened in the main landmass. There =
were the=20
      ancestral shrews, living and breeding happily away, with no =
particular=20
      reason to change. Admittedly their cousins the other side of the =
mountains=20
      were busy evolving, but their fossils are all on the-other side of =
the=20
      mountain so we don't find them in the main landmass where we are =
digging.=20
      Then, suddenly (suddenly by geological standards, that is), the =
new=20
      species returns, competes with the main species and, perhaps, =
replaces the=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.7pt 0pt 4.55pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D622 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D380 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D622>
      <P class=3DStyle18 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 2.15pt">240 <I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker=20
      </SPAN><BR><BR></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05pt 0pt 1.9pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.85pt">main =
species.=20
      Suddenly the fossils that we find as we move up through the strata =
of the=20
      main landmass change. Previously they were all of the ancestral =
species.=20
      Now, abruptly and without visible transitions, fossils .of the new =
species=20
      appear, and fossils of the old species disappear. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05pt 0pt 1.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt">The=20
      'gaps', far from being annoying imperfections or awkward =
embarrassments,=20
      turn out to be exactly what we should positively <I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">expect, </SPAN></I>if we take =
seriously=20
      our orthodox neo-Darwinian theory of speciation. The reason the=20
      'transition' from ancestral species to descendant species appears =
to be=20
      abrupt and jerky is simply that, when we look at a series of =
fossils from=20
      any one place, we are probably not looking at an <I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">evolutionary </SPAN></I>event =
at all: we=20
      are looking at a <I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">migrational=20
      </SPAN></I>event, the arrival of a new species from another =
geographical=20
      area. Certainly there were evolutionary events, and one species =
really did=20
      evolve, probably gradually, from another. But in order to see the=20
      evolutionary transition documented in the fossils we should have =
to dig=20
      elsewhere - in this case on the other side of the mountains. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.75pt">The=20
      point that Eldredge and Gould were making, then, could have been =
modestly=20
      presented as a helpful rescuing of Darwin and his successors from =
what had=20
      seemed to them an awkward difficulty. Indeed that is, at least in =
part,=20
      how it <I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">was =
</SPAN></I>presented=20
      =97 initially. Darwinians had always been bothered by the apparent =
gappiness=20
      of the fossil record, and had seemed forced to resort to special =
pleading=20
      about imperfect evidence. Darwin himself had written: </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 15.95pt 0pt 11.75pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10pt">The =
geological=20
      record is extremely imperfect and this fact will to a large extent =
explain=20
      why we do not find interminable varieties, connecting together all =
the=20
      extinct and existing forms of life by the finest graduated steps. =
He who=20
      rejects these views on the nature of the geological record, =
<B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">will </SPAN></B>rightly reject =
my whole=20
      theory. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.1pt 0pt 1.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt">Eldredge=20
      and Gould could have made this their main message: Don't worry =
Darwin,=20
      even if the fossil record <I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">were=20
      </SPAN></I>perfect you shouldn't expect to see a finely graduated=20
      progression if you only dig in one place, for the simple reason =
that most=20
      of the evolutionary change took place somewhere else! They could =
have gone=20
      further and said: </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 23.85pt 0pt 12pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 9.9pt">Darwin, =
when you=20
      said that the fossil record was imperfect, you were understating =
it. Not=20
      only is it imperfect, there are good reasons for expecting it to =
be=20
      <I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">particularly=20
      </SPAN></I>imperfect just when it gets interesting, just when =
evolutionary=20
      change is taking place, this is partly because evolution usually =
occurred=20
      in a different place from where we find most of our fossils; and =
it is=20
      partly because, even if we are fortunate enough to dig in one of =
the small=20
      outlying areas where most evolutionary change went on, that </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 23.85pt 0pt 12pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 9.9pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D630 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D382 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D630>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 3.35pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Puncturing punctuationism=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">241 =
<BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 9.25pt 0pt 12.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">evolutionary change (though =
still=20
      gradual) occupies such a short time that </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle38 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 53.2pt 0pt 12.5pt">we =
should need an=20
      extra <I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">rich =
</SPAN></I>fossil=20
      record in order to track it! </P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.75pt 0pt 2.4pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">But no, instead they chose, =
especially in=20
      their later writings in which they were eagerly followed by =
journalists,=20
      to sell their ideas as being radically </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">opposed to </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Darwin's and opposed to the =
neo-Darwinian=20
      synthesis. They did this by emphasizing the 'gradualism' of the =
Darwinian=20
      view of evolution as opposed to the sudden, jerky, sporadic=20
      'punctuationism' of their own. They even, especially Gould, saw =
analogies=20
      between themselves and the old schools of 'catastrophism' and=20
      'saltationism'. Saltationism we have already discussed. =
Catastrophism was=20
      an eighteenth- and nineteenth-century attempt to reconcile some =
form of=20
      creationism with the uncomfortable facts of the fossil record.=20
      Catastrophists believed that the apparent progression of the =
fossil record=20
      really reflected a series of discrete creations, each one =
terminated by a=20
      catastrophic mass extinction. The latest of these catastrophes was =
Noah's=20
      flood. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Comparisons between modern =
punctuationism=20
      on the one hand, and catastrophism or saltationism on the other, =
have a=20
      purely poetic force. They are, if I may coin a paradox, deeply=20
      superficial. They sound impressive in an artsy, literary way, but =
they do=20
      nothing to aid serious understanding, and they can give spurious =
aid and=20
      comfort to modem creationists in their disturbingly successful =
fight to=20
      subvert American education and textbook publishing. The fact is =
that, in=20
      the fullest and most serious sense, Eldredge and Gould are really =
just as=20
      gradualist as Darwin or any of his followers. It is just that they =
would=20
      compress all the gradual change into brief bursts, rather than =
having it=20
      go on all the time; and they emphasize that most of the gradual =
change=20
      goes on in geographical areas away from the areas where most =
fossils are=20
      dug up. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.9pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">So, it is not really the =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">gradualism </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">of Darwin that the =
punctuationists=20
      oppose: gradualism means that each generation is only slightly =
different=20
      from the previous generation; you would have to be a saltationist =
to=20
      oppose that, and Eldredge and Gould are not saltationists. Rather, =
it=20
      turns out to be Darwin's alleged belief in the constancy of rates =
of=20
      evolution that they and the other punctuationists object to. They =
object=20
      to it because they think that evolution (still undeniably =
gradualistic=20
      evolution) occurs rapidly during relatively brief bursts of =
activity=20
      (speciation events, which provide a kind of crisis atmosphere in =
which the=20
      alleged normal resistance to evolutionary change is broken); and =
that=20
      evolution occurs very slowly or not at all during long intervening =
periods=20
      of stasis. When we say 'relatively' brief we mean, of course, =
brief=20
      relative to the geological timescale in general. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.9pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D14 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D18 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D14>
      <P class=3DStyle37><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica">242 =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle37><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Helvetica"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D16 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D131 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D16>
      <P class=3DStyle6><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The =
Blind=20
      Watchmaker </SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle6><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D600 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D600>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.25pt 0pt 0.5pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Even the evolutionary jerks of =
the=20
      punctuationists, though they may be instantaneous by geological =
standards,=20
      still have a duration that is measured in tens or hundreds of =
thousands of=20
      years. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.3pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.35pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">A thought of the famous =
American=20
      evqlutionist G. Ledyard Stebbins is illuminating at this point. He =
isn't=20
      specifically concerned with jerky evolution, but is just seeking =
to=20
      dramatize the speed with which evolutionary change can happen, =
when seen=20
      against the timescale of available geological time. He imagines a =
species=20
      of animal, of about the size of a mouse. He then supposes that =
natural=20
      selection starts to favour an increase in body size, but only very =
very=20
      slightly. Perhaps larger males enjoy a slight advantage in the =
competition=20
      for females. At any time, males of average size are slightly less=20
      successful than males that are a tiny bit bigger than average. =
Stebbins=20
      put an exact figure on the mathematical advantage enjoyed by =
larger=20
      individuals in his hypothetical example. He set it at a value so =
very very=20
      tiny that it wouldn't be measurable by human observers. And the =
rate of=20
      evolutionary change that it brings about is consequently so slow =
that it=20
      wouldn't be noticed during an ordinary human lifetime. As far as =
the=20
      scientist studying evolution on the ground is concerned, then, =
these=20
      animals are not evolving at all. Nevertheless they are evolving, =
very=20
      slowly at a rate given by Stebbins's mathematical assumption, and, =
even at=20
      this slow rate, they would eventually reach the size of elephants. =
How=20
      long would this take? Obviously a long time by human standards, =
but human=20
      standards aren't relevant. We are talking about geological time. =
Stebbins=20
      calculates that at his assumed very slow rate of evolution, it =
would take=20
      about 12,000 generations for the animals to evolve from an average =
weight=20
      of 40 grams (mouse size) to an average weight of over 6,000,000 =
grams=20
      (elephant size). Assuming a <BR>generationtime of 5 years, which =
is longer=20
      than that of a mouse but shorter than that of an elephant, 12,000=20
      generations would occupy about 60,000 years. 60,000 years is too=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">short to=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">be measured by =
ordinary=20
      geological methods of dating the fossil record. As Stebbins says, =
'The=20
      origin of a new kind of animal in 100,000 years or less is =
regarded by=20
      <BR>paleontologists as "sudden" or "instantaneous".' </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.3pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The punctuationists aren't =
talking about=20
      jumps in evolution, they are talking about episodes of relatively =
rapid=20
      evolution. And even these episodes don't have to be rapid by human =

      standards, in order to appear instantaneous by geological =
standards.=20
      Whatever we may think of the theory of punctuated equilibria =
itself, it is=20
      all too easy to confuse gradualism (the belief, held by modern=20
      punctuationists as well as Darwin, that there are no sudden leaps =
between=20
      one generation and the next) with </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">'constant </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">evolutionary speedism' (opposed =
by=20
      punctuationists </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.3pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D380 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle24 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 3.85pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Puncturing punctuationism =
</SPAN></I>243=20
      <SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle24=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05pt 0pt 3.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt">and =
allegedly,=20
      though not actually, held by Darwin). They are not the same thing =
at all.=20
      The proper way to characterize the beliefs of punctuationists is:=20
      'gradualistic, but with long periods of "stasis" (evolutionary =
stagnation)=20
      punctuating brief episodes of rapid gradual change'. The emphasis =
is then=20
      thrown onto the long periods of stasis as being the previously =
overlooked=20
      phenomenon that really needs explaining. It is the emphasis on =
stasis that=20
      is the punctuationists' real contribution, not their claimed =
opposition to=20
      gradualism, for they are truly as gradualist as anybody else. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle24=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.55pt 0pt 1.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt">Even=20
      the emphasis on stasis can be found, in less-exaggerated form, in =
Mayr's=20
      theory of speciation. He believed that, of the two <SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR></SPAN>geographically separated =
races, the=20
      original large ancestral population is less likely to change than =
the new,=20
      'daughter' population (on the other side of the mountains in the =
case of=20
      our shrew example). This is not just because the daughter =
population is=20
      the one that has moved to new pastures, where conditions are =
likely to be=20
      different and natural <SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: =
9pt"><BR></SPAN>selection=20
      pressures changed. It is also because there are some theoretical =
reasons=20
      (which Mayr emphasized but whose importance can be disputed) for =
thinking=20
      that large breeding populations have an inherent tendency to =
<I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">resist </SPAN></I>evolutionary =
change. A=20
      suitable analogy is the <SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: =
9pt"><BR></SPAN>inertia of=20
      a large heavy object; it is hard to shift. Small, outlying =
populations, by=20
      virtue of being small, are inherently more likely, so the theory =
goes, to=20
      change, to evolve. Therefore, although I spoke of the two =
populations or=20
      races of shrews as diverging from each other, Mayr would prefer to =
see the=20
      original, ancestral population as relatively static, and the new=20
      population as diverging from it. The branch of the evolutionary =
tree does=20
      not fork into two equal twigs: rather, there is a main stem with a =
side=20
      twig sprouting from it. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle24=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.65pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt">The=20
      proponents of punctuated equilibrium took this suggestion <B><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">of </SPAN></B>Mayr, and =
exaggerated it=20
      into a strong belief that 'stasis', or lack <B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">of </SPAN></B>evolutionary =
change, is the=20
      norm for a species. They believe that there are genetic forces in =
large=20
      populations that actively <I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">resist </SPAN></I>evolutionary =
change.=20
      Evolutionary change, for them, is a rare event, coinciding with=20
      speciation. It coincides with speciation in the sense that, in =
their view,=20
      the conditions under which new species are formed =97 geographical =

      separation of small, isolated subpopulations - are the very =
conditions=20
      under which the forces that normally resist evolutionary change =
<B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">are </SPAN></B>relaxed or =
overthrown.=20
      Speciation is a time of upheaval, or revolution. And it is during =
these=20
      times of upheaval that evolutionary change is concentrated. For =
most of=20
      the history of a lineage it stagnates. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle24 style=3D"MARGIN-RIGHT: 3.9pt">It isn't true =
that Darwin=20
      believed that evolution proceeded at a constant rate. He certainly =
didn't=20
      believe it in the Ludicrously extreme </P>
      <P class=3DStyle24 style=3D"MARGIN-RIGHT: 3.9pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.45pt 0pt 0.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">244 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.7pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">sense that I satirized in my =
parable of=20
      the children of Israel, and I don't think he really believed it in =
any=20
      important sense. Quotation of the following well-known passage =
from the=20
      fourth edition (and later editions) of </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Origin of Species =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">annoys Gould because he thinks =
it is=20
      unrepresentative of Darwin's general thought: <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05in 0pt 10.3pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 9.9pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Many species once formed never =
undergo=20
      any further change . . .; and </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">the </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">periods, during which species =
have=20
      undergone modification, though </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">long </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">as measured by years, have =
probably been=20
      short in comparison with the periods during which they retain the =
same=20
      form. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 16.05pt 0pt 0.25pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Gould wants to shrug off this =
sentence=20
      and others like it, saying: <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 10.4pt 0pt 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 9.8pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">You cannot do history by =
selective=20
      quotation and search for qualifying footnotes. General tenor and=20
      historical impact are the proper criteria. Did his contemporaries =
or=20
      descendants ever read Darwin as a saltationist? </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.8pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Gould is right, of course, =
about general=20
      tenor and historical impact, but the final sentence of this =
quotation from=20
      him is a highly revealing </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">faux pas. Of course, =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">nobody has ever read Darwin as =
a=20
      saltationist and, of course, Darwin was consistently hostile to=20
      saltationism, but the whole point is that saltationism is not the =
issue=20
      when we are <BR>discussing punctuated equilibrium. As I have =
stressed, the=20
      theory of <BR>punctuated equilibrium, by Eldredge and Gould's own =
account,=20
      is not a saltationist theory. The jumps that it postulates are not =
real,=20
      single- <BR>generation jumps. They are spread out over large =
numbers of=20
      generations over periods of, by Gould's own estimation, perhaps =
tens of=20
      thousands of years. The theory of punctuated equilibrium is a =
gradualist=20
      theory, albeit it emphasizes long periods of stasis intervening =
between=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">relatively=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">short bursts =
of=20
      gradualistic evolution. Gould has misled himself by his own =
rhetorical=20
      emphasis on the purely poetic or literary resemblance between=20
      punctuationism, on the one hand, and true saltationism on the =
other.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
1pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">I think it would clarify =
matters if, at=20
      this point, I summarized a range of possible points of view about =
rates of=20
      evolution. Out on a limb we have true saltationism, which I have =
already=20
      discussed sufficiently. True saltationists don't exist among =
modern=20
      biologists. Everyone that is not a saltationist is a gradualist, =
and this=20
      includes Eldredge and Gould, however they may choose to describe=20
      themselves. Within gradualism, we may distinguish various beliefs =
about=20
      rates of (gradual) evolution. Some of these beliefs, as we have =
seen, bear=20
      a purely <BR>superficial ('literary' or 'poetic') resemblance to =
true,=20
      anti-gradualist <BR>saltationism, which is why they are sometimes =
confused=20
      with it. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1pt 0pt 10.1pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">At another extreme we have the =
sort of=20
      'constant speedism' that I </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1pt 0pt 10.1pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D383 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle23 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 5.3pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Puncturing punctuationism=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica">245 </SPAN><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.15pt 0pt 4.55pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">caricatured in the Exodus =
parable with=20
      which I began this chapter. An extreme constant speedist believes =
that=20
      evolution is plodding along steadily and inexorably all the time, =
whether=20
      or not there is any branching or speciation going on. He believes =
that=20
      quantity of evolutionary change is strictly proportional to time =
elapsed.=20
      Ironically, a form of constant speedism has recently become highly =

      favoured among modem molecular geneticists. A good case can be =
made for=20
      believing that evolutionary change at the level of protein =
molecules=20
      really does plod along at a constant rate exactly like the =
hypothetical=20
      children of Israel; and this </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">even if </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">externally visible =
characteristics like=20
      arms and legs are evolving in a highly punctuated manner. We have =
already=20
      met this topic in Chapter 5, and I shall mention it again in the =
next=20
      chapter. But as far as adaptive evolution of large-scale =
structures and=20
      behaviour patterns are concerned, just about all evolutionists =
would=20
      reject constant speedism, and Darwin certainly would have rejected =
it.=20
      Everyone that is not a constant speedist is a variable speedist.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.9pt 0pt 1.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Within variable speedism we may =

      distinguish two kinds of belief, labelled, 'discrete variable =
speedism'=20
      and 'continuously variable speedism'. An extreme 'discretist' not =
only=20
      believes that evolution varies in speed. He thinks that the speed =
flips=20
      abruptly from one discrete level to another, like a car's gearbox. =
He=20
      might believe, for instance, that evolution has only two speeds: =
very fast=20
      and stop (I cannot help being reminded here of the humiliation of =
my first=20
      school report, written by the Matron about my performance as a =
seven-=20
      <BR>yearold in folding clothes, taking cold baths, and other daily =

      routines of boarding-school life: 'Dawkins has only three speeds: =
slow,=20
      very slow, and stop'). 'Stopped' evolution is the 'stasis' that is =
thought=20
      by punctuationists to characterize large populations. Top-gear =
evolution=20
      is the evolution that goes on during speciation, in small isolated =

      populations round the edge of large, evolutionarily static =
populations.=20
      According to this view, evolution is always in one or other of the =
two=20
      gears, never in between. Eldredge and Gould tend in the direction =
of=20
      discretism, and in this respect they are genuinely radical. They =
may be=20
      called 'discrete variable speedists'. Incidentally, there is no=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">particular=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">reason why a =
discrete=20
      variable speedist should necessarily emphasize speciation as the =
time of=20
      high-gear evolution. In practice, however, most of them do. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
5.3pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">'Continuously variable =
speedists', on the=20
      other hand, believe that evolutionary rates fluctuate continuously =
from=20
      very fast to very slow and stop, with all intermediates. They see =
no=20
      particular reason to emphasize certain speeds more than others. In =

      particular, stasis, </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold">to=20
      </SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
5.3pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D380 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.75pt 0pt 0.95pt"><B><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">246 </SPAN></B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.3pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">them, is just an extreme case =
of=20
      ultra-slow evolution. To a punctuationist, there is something very =
special=20
      about stasis. Stasis, to him, is not just evolution that is so =
slow as to=20
      have a rate of zero: stasis is not just passive lack of evolution =
because=20
      there is no driving force in favour of change. Rather, stasis =
represents a=20
      positive </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">resistance to=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">evolutionary =
change. It=20
      is almost as though species are thought to take active steps not =
to=20
      evolve, </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">in =
spite of=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">driving forces =
in favour=20
      of evolution. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.55pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">More biologists agree that =
stasis is a=20
      real phenomenon than agree about its causes. Take, as an extreme =
example,=20
      the coelacanth </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Latimeria. </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The coelacanths were a large =
group of=20
      'fish' (actually, although they are called fish they are more =
closely=20
      related to us than they are to trout and herrings) that flourished =
more=20
      than 250 million years ago and apparently died out at about the =
same time=20
      as the dinosaurs. I say 'apparently' died out because in 1938, =
much to the=20
      zoological world's astonishment, a weird fish, a yard and a half =
long and=20
      with unusual leg-like fins, appeared in the catch of a deep-sea =
fishing=20
      boat off the South African coast. Though almost destroyed before =
its=20
      priceless worth was recognized, its decaying remains were =
fortunately=20
      brought to the attention of a qualified South African zoologist =
just in=20
      time. Scarcely able to believe his eyes, he identified it as a =
living=20
      coelacanth, and named it </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Latimeria. </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Since then, a few other =
specimens have=20
      been fished up in the same area, and the species has now been =
properly=20
      studied and described. It is a 'living fossil', in the sense that =
it has=20
      changed hardly at all since the time of its fossil ancestors, =
hundreds of=20
      millions of years ago. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.6pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">So, we have stasis. What are we =
to make=20
      of it? How do we explain it? Some of us would say that the lineage =
leading=20
      to </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Latimeria=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">stood still =
because=20
      natural selection did not move it. In a sense it had no 'need' to =
evolve=20
      because these animals had found a successful way of life deep in =
the sea=20
      where conditions did not change much. Perhaps they never =
participated in=20
      any arms races. Their cousins that emerged onto the land did =
evolve=20
      because natural selection, under a variety of hostile conditions =
including=20
      arms races, forced them to. Other biologists, including some of =
those that=20
      call themselves punctuationists, might say that the lineage =
leading to=20
      modern </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">Latimeria=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">actively =
resisted=20
      change, </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">in =
spite of=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">what natural =
selection=20
      pressures there might have been. Who is right? In the particular =
case of=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Latimeria=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">it is hard to =
know, but=20
      there is one way in which, in principle, we might go about finding =
out.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.5pt 0pt 0.25pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Let us, to be fair, stop =
thinking in=20
      terms of </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">Latimeria=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">in particular. =
It is a=20
      striking example but a very extreme one, and it is not one on =
which=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.5pt 0pt 0.25pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D380 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.05in"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">puncturing punctuatioaism=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">247 =
<BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.45pt 0pt 3.1pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the punctuationists =
particularly want to=20
      rely. Their belief is that less extreme, and shorter-term, =
examples of=20
      stasis are commonplace; are, indeed, the norm, because species =
have=20
      genetic mechanisms that actively resist change, even if there are =
forces=20
      of natural selection urging change. Now here is the very simple =
experiment=20
      which, in principle at least, we can do to test this hypothesis. =
We can=20
      take wild populations and impose our own forces of selection upon =
them.=20
      According to the hypothesis that species actively resist change, =
we should=20
      find that, if we try to breed for some quality, the species should =
dig in=20
      its heels, so to speak, and refuse to budge, at least for a while. =
If we=20
      take cattle and attempt to breed selectively for high milk yield, =
for=20
      instance, we should fail. The genetic mechanisms of the species =
should=20
      mobilize their anti-evolution forces and fight off the pressure to =
change.=20
      If we try to make chickens evolve higher egg-laying rates we =
should fail.=20
      If bullfighters, in pursuit of their contemptible 'sport', try to =
increase=20
      the courage of their bulls by selective breeding, they should =
fail. These=20
      failures should only be temporary, of course. Eventually, like a =
dam=20
      bursting under pressure, the alleged anti-evolution forces will be =

      overcome, and the lineage can then move rapidly to a new =
equilibrium. But=20
      we should experience at least some resistance when we first =
initiate a new=20
      program of selective breeding. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.9pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The fact is, of course, that we =
do not=20
      fail when we try to shape evolution by selectively breeding =
animals and=20
      plants in captivity, nor do we experience a period of initial =
difficulty.=20
      Animal and plant species are usually immediately amenable to =
selective=20
      breeding, and breeders detect no evidence of any intrinsic, =
anti-evolution=20
      forces. If anything, selective breeders experience difficulty=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">after =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">a number of generations of =
successful=20
      selective breeding. This is because after some generations of =
selective=20
      breeding the available genetic variation runs out, and we have to =
wait for=20
      new mutations. It is conceivable that coelacanths stopped evolving =
because=20
      they stopped mutating =97 perhaps because they were protected from =
cosmic=20
      rays at the bottom of the sea! =97 but nobody, as far as I know, =
has=20
      seriously suggested this, and in any case this is not what =
punctuationists=20
      mean when they talk of species having built-in resistance to =
evolutionary=20
      change. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
3.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">They mean something more like =
the point I=20
      was making in Chapter 7 about 'cooperating' genes: the idea that =
groups of=20
      genes are so well adapted to each other that they resist invasion =
by new=20
      mutant genes which are not members of the club. This is quite a=20
      sophisticated idea, and it can be made to sound plausible. Indeed, =
it was=20
      one of the theoretical props of Mayr's inertia idea, already =
referred to.=20
      Nevertheless, the fact that, whenever we try selective breeding, =
we=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
3.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D625 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D381 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D625>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.45pt 0pt 2.15pt"><B><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">248 </SPAN></B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">encounter no initial resistance =
to it,=20
      suggests to me that, if lineages go for many generations in the =
wild=20
      without changing, this is not because they resist change but =
because there=20
      is no natural selection pressure in favour of changing. They don't =
change=20
      because individuals that stay the same survive better than =
individuals=20
      that change. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.45pt 0pt 1.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Punctuationists, then, are =
really just as=20
      gradualist as Darwin or any other Darwinian; they just insert long =
periods=20
      of stasis between spurts of gradual evolution. As I said, the one =
respect=20
      in which punctuationists do differ from other schools of Darwinism =
is in=20
      their strong emphasis on stasis as something positive: as an =
active=20
      resistance to evolutionary change rather than as, simply, absence =
of=20
      evolutionary change. And this is the one respect in which they are =
quite=20
      probably wrong. It remains for me to clear up the mystery of why =
they=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">thought =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">they were so far from Darwin =
and=20
      neo-Darwinism. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.15pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The answer lies in a confusion =
of two=20
      meanings of the word 'gradual', coupled with the confusion, which =
I have=20
      been at pains </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">to =

      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">dispel here =
but which=20
      lies at the back of many peoples' minds, between punctuationism =
and=20
      saltationism. Darwin was a passionate anti-saltationist, and this =
led him=20
      to stress, over and over again, the extreme gradualness of the=20
      evolutionary changes that he was proposing. The reason is that =
saltation,=20
      to him, meant what I have called Boeing 747 macromutation. It =
meant the=20
      sudden calling into existence, like Pallas Athene from the head of =
Zeus,=20
      of brand-new complex organs at a single stroke of the genetic =
wand. It=20
      meant fully formed, complex working eyes springing up from bare =
skin, in a=20
      single generation. The reason it meant these things to Darwin is =
that that=20
      is exactly what it meant to some of his most influential =
opponents, and=20
      they really believed in it as a major factor in evolution. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.95pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The Duke of Argyll, for =
instance,=20
      accepted the evidence that evolution had happened, but he wanted =
to=20
      smuggle divine creation in by the back door. He wasn't alone. =
Instead of a=20
      single, once and for all creation in the Garden of Eden, many =
Victorians=20
      thought that the deity had intervened repeatedly, at crucial =
points in=20
      evolution. Complex organs like eyes, instead of evolving from =
simpler ones=20
      by slow degrees as Darwin had it, were thought to have sprung into =

      existence in a single instant. Such people rightly perceived that =
such=20
      instant 'evolution', if it occurred, would imply supernatural=20
      intervention: that is what they believed in. The reasons are the=20
      statistical ones I have discussed in connection with hurricanes =
and Boeing=20
      747s. 747 saltationism is, indeed, just a watered-down form of=20
      creationism. Putting it the other way around, divine creation is =
the=20
      ultimate in saltation. It is the ultimate leap from inanimate clay =
to=20
      fully formed </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.95pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle5 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 3.1pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">puncturing punctuationism=20
      </SPAN></I><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">249=20
      </SPAN></B><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.55pt 0pt 2.4pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">man. Darwin perceived this too. =
He wrote=20
      in a letter to Sir Charles Lyell, the leadinggeologist ofhis day:=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 9.55pt 0pt 11.5pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 9.8pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">If I were convinced that I =
required=20
      </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">such =
</SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">additions to the theory of =
natural=20
      selection, I would reject it as rubbish . . . I would give nothing =
for the=20
      theory of Natural-selection, if it requires miraculous additions =
at any=20
      one stage of descent. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.7pt 0pt 1.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">This is no petty matter. In =
Darwin's=20
      view, the whole </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">point=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">of the theory =
of=20
      evolution by natural selection was that it provided a =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">non - </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">miraculous account of the =
existence of=20
      complex adaptations. For what it is worth, it is also the whole =
point of=20
      this book. For Darwin, any evolution that had to be helped over =
the jumps=20
      by God was not evolution at all. It made a nonsense of the central =
point=20
      of evolution. In the light of this, it is easy to see why Darwin=20
      constantly reiterated the </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">gradualness </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">of evolution. It is easy to see =
why he=20
      wrote that sentence quoted in Chapter 4: <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 9.35pt 0pt 10.3pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 9.8pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">If it could be demonstrated =
that any=20
      complex organ existed, which could not possibly have been formed =
by=20
      numerous, successive, slight modifications, my theory would =
absolutely=20
      break down. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">There is another way of looking =
at the=20
      fundamental importance of gradualness for Darwin. His =
contemporaries, like=20
      many people still today, had a hard time believing that the human =
body and=20
      other such complex entities could conceivably have come into being =
through=20
      evolutionary means. If you think of the single-celled =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Amoeba </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">as our remote ancestor =97 as, =
until quite=20
      recently, it was fashionable to do - many people found it hard in =
their=20
      minds to bridge the gap between </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Amoeba </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">and man. They found it =
inconceivable that=20
      from such simple beginnings something so complex could emerge. =
Darwin=20
      appealed to the idea of a gradual series of small steps as a means =
of=20
      overcoming this kind of incredulity. You may find it hard to =
imagine an=20
      Amoeba turning into a man, the argument runs, but you do not find =
it hard=20
      to imagine an </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">Amoeba=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">turning into a =
slightly=20
      different kind of </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Amoeba. </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">From this it is not hard to =
imagine it=20
      turning into a slightly different kind of slightly different kind =
of . .=20
      ., and so on. As we saw in Chapter 3, this argument overcomes our=20
      incredulity only if we stress that there was an extremely large =
number of=20
      steps along the way, and only if each step is very tiny. Darwin =
was=20
      constantly battling against this source of incredulity, and he =
constantly=20
      made use of the same weapon: the emphasis on gradual, almost =
imperceptible=20
      change, spread out over countlessgenerations. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.3pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.35pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Incidentally, it is worth =
quoting=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">]. =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">B. S. Haldane's characteristic =
piece of=20
      lateral thinking in combating the same source of incredulity. =
Something=20
      like the transition from </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Amoeba to </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">man, he pointed out, goes on in =
every=20
      mother's womb in a mere nine months. Development is admittedly a =
very=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.3pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.35pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D10 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D77 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D10>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D10 =

      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image096.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D77></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.4pt 0pt 1.2pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">250 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.2pt 0pt 0.95pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">different process from =
evolution but,=20
      nevertheless, anyone sceptical of the very </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">possibility </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">of a transition from single =
cell to man=20
      has only to contemplate his own foetal beginnings to have his =
doubts=20
      allayed. I hope I shall not be thought a pedant if I stress, by =
the way,=20
      that the choice of </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Amoeba </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">for the title of honorary =
ancestor is=20
      simply following a whimsical tradition. A bacterium would be a =
better=20
      choice, but even bacteria, as we know them, are modern organisms.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.7pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">To resume the argument, Darwin =
laid great=20
      stress on the gradualness of evolution because of what he was =
arguing=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">against:=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the =
misconceptions about=20
      evolution that were prevalent in the nineteenth century. The=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">meaning =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">of 'gradual', in the context of =
those=20
      times, was 'opposite of saltation'. Eldredge and Gould, in the =
context of=20
      the late twentieth century, use 'gradual' in a very different =
sense. They=20
      in effect, though not explicitly, use it to mean 'at a constant =
speed',=20
      and they oppose to it their own notion of 'punctuation'. They =
criticize=20
      gradualism in this sense of 'constant speedism'. No doubt they are =
right=20
      to do so: in its extreme form it is as absurd as my Exodus =
parable.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">But to couple this justifiable =
criticism=20
      with a criticism of Darwin is simply to confuse two quite separate =

      meanings of the word 'gradual'. In the sense in which Eldredge and =
Gould=20
      are opposed to gradualism, there is no particular reason to doubt =
that=20
      Darwin would have agreed with them. In the sense of the word in =
which=20
      Darwin was a passionate gradualist, Eldredge and Gould are also=20
      gradualists. The theory of punctuated equilibrium is a minor gloss =
on=20
      Darwinism, one which Darwin himself might well have approved if =
the issue=20
      had been discussed in his time. As a minor gloss, it does not =
deserve a=20
      particularly large measure of publicity. The reason it has in fact =

      received such publicity, and why I have felt obliged to devote a =
whole=20
      chapter of this book to it, is simply that the theory has been =
sold -=20
      oversold by some journalists - as if it were radically opposed to =
the=20
      views of Darwin and his successors. Why has this happened? =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.95pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">There are people in the world =
who=20
      desperately want not to have to believe in Darwinism. They seem to =
fall=20
      into three main classes. First, there are those who, for religious =

      reasons, want evolution itself to be untrue. Second, there are =
those who=20
      have no reason to deny that evolution has happened but who, often =
for=20
      political or ideological reasons, find Darwin's theory of its=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">mechanism=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">distasteful. =
Of these,=20
      some find the idea of natural selection unacceptably harsh and =
ruthless;=20
      others confuse natural selection with randomness, and hence=20
      'meaninglessness', which offends their dignity; yet others confuse =

      Darwinism with Social Darwinism, which has racist and other =
disagreeable=20
      overtones. Third, there are people, including many working =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.95pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D381 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 4.3pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">puncturing punctuationism=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">251 =
<BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.35pt 0pt 0.05in; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.5pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">in what they call (often as a =
singular=20
      noun) 'the media', who just like seeing applecarts upset, perhaps =
because=20
      it makes good journalistic copy; and Darwinism has become =
sufficiently=20
      established and respectable to be a tempting applecart. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.95pt 0pt 3.1pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Whatever the motive, the =
consequence is=20
      that if a reputable scholar breathes so much as a hint of =
criticism of=20
      some detail of current Darwinian theory, the fact is eagerly =
seized on and=20
      blown up out of all proportion. So strong is this eagerness, it is =
as=20
      though there were a powerful amplifier, with a finely tuned =
microphone=20
      selectively listening out for anything that sounds the tiniest bit =
like=20
      opposition to Darwinism. This is most unfortunate, for serious =
argument=20
      and criticism is a vitally important part of any science, and it =
would be=20
      tragic if scholars felt the need to muzzle themselves because of =
the=20
      microphones. Needless to say the amplifier, though powerful, is =
not hi-fi:=20
      there is plenty of distortion! A scientist who cautiously whispers =
some=20
      slight misgiving about a current nuance of Darwinism is liable to =
hear his=20
      distorted and barely recognizable words booming and echoing out =
through=20
      the eagerly waiting loudspeakers. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.7pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Eldredge and Gould don't =
whisper, they=20
      shout, with eloquence and power! What they shout is often pretty =
subtle,=20
      but the message that gets across is that something is wrong with=20
      Darwinism. Hallelujah, 'the scientists' said it themselves! The =
editor of=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Biblical =
Creation=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">has written: =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 8.05pt 0pt 0.15in; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 9.85pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">it is undeniable that the =
credibility of=20
      our religious and scientific position has been greatly =
strengthened by the=20
      recent lapse in neo-Darwinian morale. And this is something we =
must=20
      exploit to the full. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.55pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Eldredge and Gould have both =
been doughty=20
      champions in the fight against redneck creationism. They have =
shouted=20
      their complaints at the misuse of their own words, only to find =
that, for=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">this =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">part of their message, the =
microphones=20
      suddenly went dead on them. I can symppathize, for I have had a =
similar=20
      experience with a different set of microphones, in this case =
politically=20
      rather than religiously tuned. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.75pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">What needs to be said now, loud =
and=20
      clear, is the truth: that the theory of punctuated equilibrium =
lies firmly=20
      within the neo-Darwinian synthesis. It always did. It will take =
time to=20
      undo the damage wrought by the overblown rhetoric, but it will be =
undone.=20
      The theory of punctuated equilibrium will come to be seen in =
proportion,=20
      as an interesting but minor wrinkle on the surface of =
neo-Darwinian=20
      theory. It certainly provides no basis for any 'lapse in =
neo-Darwinian=20
      morale', and no basis whatever for Gould to claim that the =
synthetic=20
      theory (another name for neo-Darwinism) 'is effectively dead'. It =
is as if=20
      the discovery that the Earth is </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">not </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">a perfect </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.75pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D256 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D377 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D256>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.15pt 0pt 0.95pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">252 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">sphere but a slightly flattened =
spheroid=20
      were given banner treatment under the headline: =
<BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 10.85pt 0pt 0.95pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">COPERNICUS WRONG. FLAT EARTH =
THEORY=20
      VINDICATED. <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.3pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">But, to be fair, Gould's remark =
was aimed=20
      not so much at the alleged 'gradualism' of the Darwinian synthesis =
as at=20
      another of its claims. This is the claim, which Eldredge and Gould =

      dispute, that all evolution, even on the grandest geological =
timescale, is=20
      an <BR>extrapolation of events that take place within populations =
or=20
      species. They believe that there is a higher form of selection =
which they=20
      call 'species selection'. I am deferring this topic to the next =
chapter.=20
      The next chapter is also the place to deal with another school of=20
      biologists who, on equally flimsy grounds, have in some cases been =
passed=20
      off as anti- Darwinian, the so-called 'transformed cladists'. =
These belong=20
      within the general field of taxonomy, the science of =
classification.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.3pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D508 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D362 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D508>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"><IMG=20
      height=3D508=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image097.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D362></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D560 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D375 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D560>
      <P class=3DStyle40 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.4in 0pt 106.1pt">CHAPTER =
10 <SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <H2 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 48.45pt 0pt 53.5pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 16.5pt">THE ONE TRUE TREE OF LIFE </SPAN><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR><BR><BR></SPAN></H2>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.45pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.35pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">This book is mainly about =
evolution as=20
      the solution of the complex 'design' problem; evolution as the =
true=20
      explanation for the phenomena that Paley thought proved the =
existence of a=20
      divine watchmaker. This is why I keep going on about eyes and=20
      echolocation. But there is another whole range of things that the =
theory=20
      of evolution explains. These are the phenomena of diversity: the =
pattern=20
      of different animal and plant types distributed around the world, =
and the=20
      distribution of characteristics among them. Although I am mainly =
concerned=20
      with eyes and other pieces of complex machinery, I mustn't neglect =
this=20
      other aspect of evolution's role in helping us to understand =
nature. So=20
      this chapter is about taxonomy. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.8pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Taxonomy is the science of=20
      classification. For some people it has an undeservedly dull =
reputation, a=20
      subconscious association with dusty museums and the smell of =
preserving=20
      fluid, almost as though it were being confused with taxidermy. In =
fact it=20
      is anything but dull. It is, for reasons that I do not fully =
understand,=20
      one of the most acrimoniously controversial fields in all of =
biology. It=20
      is of interest to philosophers and historians. It has an important =
role to=20
      play in any discussion of evolution. And from within the ranks of=20
      taxonomists have come some of the most outspoken of those modem =
biologists=20
      who pretend to be anti-Darwinian. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
1.55pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Although taxonomists mostly =
study animals=20
      or plants, all sorts of other things can be classified: rocks, =
warships,=20
      books in a library, stars, languages. Orderly classification is =
often=20
      represented as a measure of convenience, a practical necessity, =
and this=20
      is indeed a part of the truth. The books in a large library are =
nearly=20
      useless unless they are organized in some nonrandom way so that =
books on a=20
      particular <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle23 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.5pt 0pt 252.95pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica">255 </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle23 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.5pt 0pt 252.95pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Helvetica"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 8pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Helvetica"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.2pt 0pt 2.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">256 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 2.15pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">subject can be found when you =
want them.=20
      The science, or it may be an art, of librarianship is an exercise =
in=20
      applied taxonomy. For the same kind of reason, biologists find =
their life=20
      made easier if they can pigeonhole animals and plants in agreed =
categories=20
      with names. But to say that this is the only reason for animal and =
plant=20
      taxonomy would be to miss most of the point. For evolutionary =
biologists=20
      there is something very special about the classification of living =

      organisms, something that is not true of any other kind of =
taxonomy. It=20
      follows from the idea of evolution that there is one uniquely =
correct=20
      branching family tree of all living things, and we can base our =
taxonomy=20
      upon it. In addition to its uniqueness, this taxonomy has the =
singular=20
      property that I shall call </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">perfect nesting. =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">What this means, and why it is =
so=20
      important, is a major theme of this chapter. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.1pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Let us use the library as an =
example of=20
      nonbiological taxonomy. There is no single, unique, correct =
solution to=20
      the problem of how the books in a library or a bookshop should be=20
      classified. One librarian might divide his collection up into the=20
      following major categories: science, history, literature, other =
arts,=20
      foreign works, etc. Each of these major departments of the library =
would=20
      be subdivided. The science wing of the library might have =
subdivisions=20
      into biology, geology, chemistry, physics, and so on. The books in =
the=20
      biology section of the science wing might be subdivided into =
shelves=20
      devoted to physiology, anatomy, biochemistry, entomology, and so =
on.=20
      Finally, within each shelf, the books might be housed in =
alphabetical=20
      order. Other major wings of the library, the history wing, the =
literature=20
      wing, the foreignlanguage wing, and so on, would be subdivided in =
similar=20
      ways. The library is, therefore, hierarchically divided in a way =
that=20
      makes it possible for a reader to home in on the book that he =
wants.=20
      Hierarchical classification is convenient because it enables the =
borrower=20
      to find his way around the collection of books quickly. It is for =
the same=20
      kind of reason that the words in dictionaries are arranged in =
alphabetical=20
      order. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.2pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">But there is no unique =
hierarchy by which=20
      the books in a library must be arranged. A different librarian =
might=20
      choose to organize the same collection of books in a different, =
but still=20
      hierarchical, way. He might not, for instance, have a separate=20
      foreign-language wing, but might prefer to house books, regardless =
of=20
      language, in their appropriate subject areas: German biology books =
in the=20
      biology section, German history books in the history section, and =
so on. A=20
      third librarian might adopt the radical policy of housing all =
books, on=20
      whatever subject, in chronological order of publication, relying =
on card=20
      indexes (or computer equivalents) </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">to </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">find books on desired topics. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.2pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D8 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D21 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D8>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D8=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image098.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D21></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D380 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 257.3pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">257 </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.65pt 0pt 2.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">These three library plans are =
quite=20
      different from each other, but they would probably all work =
adequately and=20
      would be thought acceptable by many readers, though not, =
incidentally, by=20
      the choleric, elderly London clubman whom I once heard on the =
radio=20
      berating his club's committee for employing a librarian. The =
library had=20
      got along for a hundred years without organization, and he didn't =
see why=20
      it needed organizing now. The interviewer mildly asked him how he =
thought=20
      the books ought to be arranged. 'Tallest on the left, shortest on =
the=20
      right!', he roared without hesitation. Popular bookshops classify =
their=20
      books into major sections that reflect popular demand. Instead of =
science,=20
      history, literature, geography, and so on, their major departments =
are=20
      gardening, cookery, 'TV titles', the occult, and I once saw a =
shelf=20
      prominently labelled 'RELIGION AND UFOs'. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.75pt 0pt 1.45pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">So, there is no </SPAN><I><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">correct </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">solution to the problem of how =
to=20
      classify books. Librarians can have sensible disagreements with =
one=20
      another about classification policy, but the criteria by which =
arguments=20
      are won or lost will not include the 'truth' or 'correctness' of =
one=20
      classification system relative to another. Rather, the criteria =
that are=20
      bandied about in argument will be 'convenience for library users', =
'speed=20
      of finding books', and so on. In this sense the taxonomy of books =
in a=20
      library can be said to be arbitrary. This doesn't imply that it is =

      unimportant to devise a good classification system; far from it. =
What it=20
      does mean is that there is no single classification system which, =
in a=20
      world of perfect information, would be universally agreed as the =
only=20
      correct classification. The taxonomy of living creatures on the =
other=20
      hand, as we shall see, does have this strong property that the =
taxonomy of=20
      books lacks; at least it does if we take up an evolutionary =
standpoint.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.75pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">It is, of course, possible to =
devise any=20
      number of systems for classifying living creatures, but I shall =
show that=20
      all but one of these are just as arbitrary as any librarian's =
taxonomy. If=20
      it is simply convenience that is required, a museum keeper might =
classify=20
      his specimens according to size and keeping conditions: large =
stuffed=20
      specimens; small dried specimens pinned on cork boards in trays; =
pickled=20
      ones in bottles; microscopic ones on slides, and so on. Such =
groupings of=20
      convenience are common in zoos. In the London Zoo rhinos are =
housed in the=20
      'Elephant House' for no better reason than that they need the same =
kind of=20
      stoutly fortified cages as elephants. An applied biologist might =
classify=20
      animals into harmful (subdivided into medical pests, agricultural =
pests=20
      and directly dangerous biters or stingers), beneficial (subdivided =
in=20
      similar ways) and neutral. A nutritionist might classify animals =
according=20
      to the food value of their </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.75pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.2pt 0pt 1.9pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">258 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.45pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">meat to humans, again with =
elaborate=20
      subdivision of categories. My grandmother once embroidered a cloth =
book=20
      about animals for children, which classified them by their feet.=20
      Anthropologists have documented numerous elaborate systems of =
animal=20
      taxonomy used by tribes around the world. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.75pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">But of all the systems of =
classification=20
      that could be dreamed up, there is one unique system, unique in =
the sense=20
      that words like 'correct' and 'incorrect', 'true' and 'false' can =
be=20
      applied to it with perfect agreement given perfect information. =
That=20
      unique system is the system based on evolutionary relationships. =
To avoid=20
      confusion I shall give this system the name that biologists give =
to its=20
      strictest form: cladistic taxonomy. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">In cladistic taxonomy, the =
ultimate=20
      criterion for grouping organisms together is closeness of =
cousinship or,=20
      in other words, relative recency of common ancestry. Birds, for =
instance,=20
      are distinguished from nonbirds by the fact that they are all =
descended=20
      from a common ancestor, which is not an ancestor of any non-bird. =
Mammals=20
      are all descended from a common ancestor, which is not an ancestor =
of any=20
      non-mammal. Birds and mammals have a more remote common ancestor, =
which=20
      they share with lots of other animals like snakes and lizards and=20
      tuataras. The animals descended from this common ancestor are all =
called=20
      amniotes. So, birds and mammals are amniotes. 'Reptiles' is not a =
true=20
      taxonomic term, according to cladists, because it is defined by =
exception:=20
      all amniotes except birds and mammals. In other words, the most =
recent=20
      common ancestor of all 'reptiles' (snakes, turtles, etc.) is also=20
      ancestral to some non-'reptiles', namely birds and mammals. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
2.05pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Within mammals, rats and mice =
share a=20
      recent common ancestor with each other; leopards and lions share a =
recent=20
      common ancestor with each other; so do chimpanzees and humans with =
each=20
      other. Closely related animals are animals that share a recent =
common=20
      ancestor. More distantly related animals share an earlier common =
ancestor.=20
      Very distantly related animals, like people and slugs, share a =
very early=20
      common ancestor. Organisms can never be totally unrelated to one =
another,=20
      since it is all but certain that life as we know it originated =
only once=20
      on earth. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
1.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">True cladistic taxonomy is =
strictly=20
      hierarchical, an expression which I shall use to mean that it can =
be=20
      represented as a tree whose branches always diverge and never =
converge=20
      again. In my view (some schools of taxonomists, that we shall =
discuss=20
      later, would disagree), it is strictly hierarchical =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">not </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">because hierarchical =
classification is=20
      convenient, like a librarian's classification, nor because =
everything in=20
      the </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
1.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D380 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 3.1pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The one true tree of life=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">259 =
<BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.65pt 0pt 2.9pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">world falls naturally into a =
hierarchical=20
      pattern, but simply because the pattern of evolutionary descent is =

      hierarchical. Once the tree of life has branched beyond a certain =
minimum=20
      distance (basically the bounds of the species), the branches never =
ever=20
      come together again (there may be very rare exceptions, as in the =
origin=20
      of the eukaryotic cell mentioned in Chapter 7). Birds and mammals =
are=20
      descended from a common ancestor, but they are now separate =
branches of=20
      the evolutionary tree, and they will never come together again: =
there will=20
      never be a hybrid between a bird and a mammal. A group of =
organisms that=20
      has this property of all being descended from a common ancestor, =
which is=20
      not an ancestor of any non-member of the group, is called a=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">elude, =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">after the Greek for a tree =
branch.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.6pt 0pt 1.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.35pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Another way of representing =
this idea of=20
      strict hierarchy is in terms of 'perfect nesting'. We write the =
names of=20
      any set of animals on a large sheet of paper and draw rings round =
related=20
      sets. For example, rat and mouse would be united in a small ring=20
      indicating that they are close cousins, with a recent common =
ancestor.=20
      Guinea-pig and capybara would be united with each other in another =
small=20
      ring. The rat/mouse ring and the guinea-pig/capybara ring would, =
in turn,=20
      be united with each other (and beavers and porcupines and =
squirrels and=20
      lots of other animals) in a larger ring labelled with its own =
name,=20
      rodents. Inner rings are said to be 'nested' inside larger, outer =
rings.=20
      Somewhere else on the paper, lion and tiger would be united with =
one=20
      another in a small ring. This ring would be included with others =
in a ring=20
      labelled cats. Cats, dogs, weasels, bears, etc. would all be =
united, in a=20
      series of rings within rings, in a single large ring labelled =
carnivores.=20
      The rodent ring and the carnivore ring would then take part in a =
more=20
      global series of rings within rings in a very large ring labelled =
mammals.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.1pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The important thing about this =
system of=20
      rings within rings is that it is </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">perfectly nested. =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Never, not on a single solitary =
occasion,=20
      will the rings that we draw intersect each other. Take any two =
overlapping=20
      rings, and it will always be true to say that one lies wholly =
inside the=20
      other. The area enclosed by the inner one is always totally =
enclosed by=20
      the outer one: there are never any partial overlaps. This property =
of=20
      perfect taxonomic nesting is not exhibited by books, languages, =
soil=20
      types, or schools of thought in philosophy. If a librarian draws a =
ring=20
      round the biology books and another ring round the theology books, =
he will=20
      find that the two rings overlap. In the zone of overlap are books =
with=20
      titles like 'Biology and Christian Belief. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
2.8pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">On the face of it, we might =
expect the=20
      classification of languages to exhibit the property of perfect =
nesting.=20
      Languages, as we saw in Chapter 8, evolve in a rather animal-like =
way.=20
      Languages that have </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
2.8pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.2pt 0pt 2.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">260 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 2.4pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">recently diverged from a common =
ancestor,=20
      like Swedish, Norwegian and Danish, are much more similar to each =
other=20
      than they are to languages that diverged longer ago, like =
Icelandic. But=20
      languages don't only diverge, they also merge. Modern English is a =
hybrid=20
      between Germanic and Romance languages that had diverged much =
earlier, and=20
      English would therefore not fit neatly in any hierarchical nesting =

      diagram. The rings that enclosed English would be found to =
intersect, to=20
      overlap partially. Biological classificatory rings never intersect =
in this=20
      way, because biological evolution above the species level is =
always=20
      divergent. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.95pt 0pt 1.45pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Returning to the library =
example, no=20
      librarian can entirely avoid the problem of intermediates or =
overlaps. It=20
      is no use housing the biology and theology sections next door to =
each=20
      other and putting intermediate books in the corridor between them; =
for=20
      what then do we do with books that are intermediate between =
biology and=20
      chemistry, between physics and theology, history and theology, =
history and=20
      biology? I think I am right in saying that the problem of =
intermediates is=20
      inescapably, inherently a part of all taxonomic systems other than =
that=20
      which springs from evolutionary biology. Speaking personally, it =
is a=20
      problem that gives me almost physical discomfort when I am =
attempting the=20
      modest filing tasks that arise in my professional life: shelving =
my own=20
      books, and reprints of scientific papers that colleagues (with the =
kindest=20
      of intentions) send me; filing administrative papers; old letters, =
and so=20
      on. Whatever categories one adopts for a filing system, there are =
always=20
      awkward items that don't fit, and the uncomfortable indecision =
leads me, I=20
      am sorry to say, to leave odd papers out on the table, sometimes =
for years=20
      at a time until it is safe to throw them away. Often one has=20
      unsatisfactory recourse to a ' miscellaneous' category, a category =
which,=20
      once initiated, has a menacing tendency to grow. I sometimes =
wonder=20
      whether librarians, and keepers of all museums except biological =
museums,=20
      are particularly prone to ulcers. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.45pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">In the taxonomy of living =
creatures these=20
      filing problems do not arise. There are no 'miscellaneous' =
animals. As=20
      long as we stay above the level of the species, and as long as we =
study=20
      only modem animals (or animals in any given time slice: see below) =
there=20
      are no awkward intermediates. If an animal appears to be an =
awkward=20
      intermediate, say it seems to be exactly intermediate between a =
mammal and=20
      a bird, an evolutionist can be confident that it must definitely =
be one or=20
      the other. The appearance of intermediacy must be an illusion. The =
unlucky=20
      librarian can take no such reassurance. It is perfectly possible =
for a=20
      book to belong simultaneously in both the history and the biology=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.45pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D381 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 2.9pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The one true tree of life=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">261 =
<BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.7pt 0pt 2.4pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">departments. Cladistically =
inclined=20
      biologists never indulge in any librarians' arguments over whether =
it is=20
      'convenient' to classify whales as mammals or as fish, or as =
intermediate=20
      between mammals and fish. The only argument we have is a factual =
one. In=20
      this case, as it happens, the facts lead all modern biologists to =
the same=20
      conclusion. Whales are mammals and not fish, and they are not, =
even to a=20
      tiny degree, intermediate. They are no closer to fish than humans =
are, or=20
      duck-billed platypuses, or any other mammals. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.7pt 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Indeed, it is important to =
understand=20
      that all mammals =97 humans, whales, duck-billed platypuses, and =
the rest -=20
      are </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">exactly =
equally=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">close to fish, =
since all=20
      mammals are linked to fish via the same common ancestor. The myth =
that=20
      mammals, for instance, form a ladder or 'scale', with 'lower' ones =
being=20
      closer to fish than 'higher' ones, is a piece of snobbery that =
owes=20
      nothing to evolution. It is an ancient, preevolutionary notion, =
sometimes=20
      called the 'great chain of being', which should have been =
destroyed by=20
      evolution but which was, mysteriously, absorbed into the way many =
people=20
      thought about evolution. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.65pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">At this point I cannot resist =
drawing=20
      attention to the irony in the challenge that creationists are fond =
of=20
      hurling at evolutionists: ' Produce your intermediates. If =
evolution were=20
      true, there should be animals that are half way between a cat and =
a dog,=20
      or between a frog and an elephant. But has anyone ever seen a =
frelephant?'=20
      I have been sent creationist pamphlets that attempt to ridicule =
evolution=20
      with drawings of grotesque chimeras, horse hindquarters grafted to =
a dog's=20
      front end, for instance. The authors seem to imagine that =
evolutionists=20
      should expect such intermediate animals to exist. This not only =
misses the=20
      point, it is the precise antithesis of the point. One of the =
strongest=20
      expectations the theory of evolution gives us is that =
intermediates of=20
      this kind should not exist. This is the burden of my comparison =
between=20
      animals and library books. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.45pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The taxonomy of evolved living =
beings,=20
      then, has the unique property of providing perfect agreement in a =
world of=20
      perfect information. That is what I meant by saying that words =
like 'true'=20
      and 'false' could be applied to claims in cladistic taxonomy, =
though not=20
      to claims in any librarian's taxonomy. We must make two =
qualifications.=20
      First, in the real world we don't have perfect information. =
Biologists may=20
      disagree with one another over the facts of ancestry, and the =
disputes may=20
      be difficult to settle because of imperfect information - not =
enough=20
      fossils, say. I shall return to this. Second, a different kind of =
problem=20
      arises if we have too </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">many </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">fossils. The neat and clear-cut =

      discreteness of classification is liable to evaporate if we try to =
include=20
      all animals that have ever lived, rather than just modern animals. =
This is=20
      because, </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.45pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D381 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3pt 0pt 0.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">262 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.55pt 0pt 0.5pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">however distant from each other =
two=20
      modern animals may be - say they are a bird and a mammal =97 they =
did, once=20
      upon a time, have a common ancestor. If we are faced with trying =
to fit=20
      that ancestor into our modern classification, we may have =
problems.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.5pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The moment we start to consider =
extinct=20
      animals, it is no longer true that there are no intermediates. On =
the=20
      contrary, we now have to contend with potentially continuous =
series of=20
      intermediates. The distinction between modern birds, and modern =
non-birds=20
      like mammals, is a clear-cut one only because the intermediates =
converging=20
      backwards on the common ancestor are all dead. To make the point =
most=20
      forcibly, think again of a hypothetically 'kind' nature, providing =
us with=20
      a complete fossil record, with a fossil of every animal that ever =
lived.=20
      When I introduced this fantasy in the previous chapter, I. =
mentioned that=20
      from one point of view nature would actually be being unkind. I =
was=20
      thinking then of the toil of studying and describing all the =
fossils, but=20
      we now come to another aspect of that paradoxical unkindness. A =
complete=20
      fossil record would make it very difficult to classify animals =
into=20
      discrete nameable groups. If we had a complete fossil record, we =
should=20
      have to give up discrete names and resort to some mathematical or=20
      graphical notation of sliding scales. The human mind far prefers =
discrete=20
      names, so in one sense it is just as well that the fossil record =
is poor.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
3.5pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">If we consider all animals that =
have ever=20
      lived instead of just modem animals, such words as 'human' and =
'bird'=20
      become just as blurred and unclear at the edges as words like =
'tall' and=20
      'fat'. Zoologists can argue unresolvably over whether a particular =
fossil=20
      is, or is not, a bird. Indeed they often do argue this very =
question over=20
      the famous fossil </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Archaeopteryx. =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">It turns out that if =
'bird/non-bird' is a=20
      clearer distinction than 'tall/short', it is only because in the=20
      bird/non-bird case the awkward intermediates are all dead. If a =
curiously=20
      selective plague came along and killed all people of intermediate =
height,=20
      'tall' and 'short' would come to have just as precise a meaning as =
'bird'=20
      or 'mammal'. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.5pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">It isn't just zoological =
classification=20
      that is saved from awkward ambiguity only by the convenient fact =
that most=20
      intermediates are now extinct. The same is true of human ethics =
and law.=20
      Our legal and moral systems are deeply species-bound. The director =
of a=20
      zoo is legally entitled to 'put down' a chimpanzee that is surplus =
to=20
      requirements, while any suggestion that he might 'put down' a =
redundant=20
      keeper or ticket-seller would be greeted with howls of incredulous =

      outrage. The chimpanzee is the property of the zoo. Humans are =
nowadays=20
      not supposed to be anybody's property, yet the rationale for=20
      discriminating </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.5pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D10 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D65 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D10>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D10 =

      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image099.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D66></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D380 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05pt 0pt 0.05in"><I><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The one true tree of life=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">263 =
<BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 3.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">against chimpanzees in this way =
is seldom=20
      spelled out, and I doubt if there is a defensible rationale at =
all. Such=20
      is the breathtaking speciesism of our Christian-inspired =
attitudes, the=20
      abortion of a single human zygote (most of them are destined to be =

      spontaneously aborted anyway) can arouse more moral solicitude and =

      righteous indignation than the vivisection of any number of =
intelligent=20
      adult chimpanzees! I have heard decent, liberal scientists, who =
had no=20
      intention of actually cutting up live chimpanzees, nevertheless=20
      passionately defending their </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">right to do </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">so if they chose, without =
interference=20
      from the law. Such people are often the first to bristle at the =
smallest=20
      infringement of </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">human=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">rights. The =
only reason=20
      we can be comfortable with such a double standard is that the=20
      intermediates between humans and chimps are all dead. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.55pt 0pt 1.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The last common ancestor of =
humans and=20
      chimps lived perhaps as recently as five million years ago, =
definitely=20
      more recently than the common ancestor of chimps and orang-utans, =
and=20
      perhaps 30 million years more recently than the common ancestor of =
chimps=20
      and monkeys. Chimpanzees and we share more than 99 per cent of our =
genes.=20
      If, in various forgotten islands around the world, survivors of =
all=20
      intermediates back to the chimp/human common ancestor were =
discovered, who=20
      can doubt that our laws and our moral conventions would be =
profoundly=20
      affected, especially as there would presumably be some =
interbreeding along=20
      the spectrum? Either the whole spectrum would have to be granted =
full=20
      human rights (Votes for Chimps), or there would have to be an =
elaborate=20
      apartheid-like system of discriminatory laws, with courts deciding =
whether=20
      particular individuals were legally 'chimps' or legally 'humans'; =
and=20
      people would fret about their daughter's desire to marry one of =
'them'. I=20
      suppose the world is already too well explored for us to hope that =
this=20
      chastening fantasy will ever come true. But anybody who thinks =
that there=20
      is something obvious and self-evident about human 'rights' should =
reflect=20
      that it is just sheer luck that these embarrassing intermediates =
happen=20
      not to have survived. Alternatively, maybe if chimpanzees hadn't =
been=20
      discovered until today they would now be seen as the embarrassing=20
      intermediates. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.5pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Readers of the previous chapter =
may=20
      remark that the whole argument, that categories become blurred if =
we don't=20
      stick to contemporary animals, assumes that evolution goes at a =
constant=20
      speed, rather than being punctuated. The more our view of =
evolution=20
      approaches the extreme of smooth, continuous change, the more =
pessimistic=20
      shall we be about the very possibility of applying such words as =
bird or=20
      non-bird, human or non-human, to all animals that </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.5pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D11 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D38 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D11>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D11 =

      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image100.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D38></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
