<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D376 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.25pt 0pt 0.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">264 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">ever lived. An extreme =
saltationist could=20
      believe that there really was a first human, whose mutant brain =
was twice=20
      the size of his father's brain and that of his chimp-like brother. =

      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.25pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The advocates of punctuated =
equilibrium=20
      are for the most part not, as we have seen, true saltationists.=20
      Nevertheless, to them the problem of the ambiguity of names is =
bound to=20
      seem less severe than it will on a more continuous view. The =
naming=20
      problem would arise even for punctuationists if literally every =
animal=20
      that had ever lived was preserved as a fossil, because the =
punctuationists=20
      are really gradualists when we come right down to detail. But, =
since they=20
      assume that we are particularly unlikely to find fossils =
documenting short=20
      periods of rapid transition, while being particularly likely to =
find=20
      fossils documenting the long periods of stasis, the 'naming =
problem' will=20
      be less severe on a punctuationist view than on a =
nonpunctuationist view=20
      of evolution. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.25pt 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">It is for this reason that the=20
      punctuationists, especially Niles Eldredge, make a big point of =
treating=20
      'the species' as a real 'entity'. To a non-punctuationist, 'the =
species'=20
      is definable only because the <BR>awkward intermediates are dead. =
An=20
      extreme anti-punctuationist, taking a long view of the entirety of =

      evolutionary history, cannot see 'the species' as a discrete =
entity at=20
      all. He can see only a smeary continuum. On his view a species =
never has a=20
      clearly defined beginning, and it only sometimes has a clearly =
defined end=20
      (extinction); often a species does not end decisively but turns =
gradually=20
      into a new species. A punctuationist, on the other hand, sees a =
species as=20
      coming into existence at a particular time (strictly there is a =
transition=20
      period with a duration of tens of thousands of years, but this =
duration is=20
      short by geological standards). Moreover, he sees a species as =
having a=20
      definite, or at least rapidly accomplished, end, not a gradual =
fading into=20
      a new species. Since most of the life of a species, on the =
punctuationist=20
      view, is spent in unchanging stasis, and since a species has a =
discrete=20
      beginning and end, it follows that, to a punctuationist, a species =
can be=20
      said to have a definite, measurable 'life span'. The =
non-punctuationist=20
      would not see a species as having a 'life span' like an individual =

      organism. The extreme punctuationist sees 'the species' as a =
discrete=20
      entity that really deserves its own name. The extreme =
anti-punctuationist=20
      sees 'the species' as an arbitrary stretch of a continuously =
flowing=20
      river, with no particular reason to draw lines delimiting its =
beginning=20
      and end. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.5pt 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.35pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">In a punctuationist book on the =
history=20
      of a group of animals, say the history of the horses over the past =
30=20
      million years, the characters in the drama may all be species =
rather than=20
      individual organisms, because the punctuationist author thinks of =
species=20
      as real 'things', with their own discrete identity. Species will =
suddenly=20
      arrive on the </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.5pt 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.35pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D382 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle23 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 4.3pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The one true tree of life=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica">265 </SPAN><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.2pt 0pt 3.85pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">scene, and as suddenly they =
will=20
      disappear, replaced by successor species. It will be a history of=20
      successions, as one species gives way to another. But if an=20
      anti-punctuationist writes the same history, he will use species =
names=20
      only as a vague convenience. When he looks longitudinally through =
time, he=20
      ceases to see species as discrete entities. The real actors in his =
drama=20
      will be individual organisms in shifting populations. In his book =
it will=20
      be individual animals that give way to descendant individual =
animals, not=20
      species that give way to species. It is not surprising, then, that =

      punctuationists tend to believe in a kind of natural selection at =
the=20
      species level, which they regard as analogous to Darwinian =
selection at=20
      the ordinary individual level. Non-punctuationists, on the other =
hand, are=20
      likely to see natural selection as working at no higher level than =
the=20
      individual organism. The idea of 'species selection' has less =
appeal for=20
      them, because they do not think of species as entities with a =
discrete=20
      existence through geological time. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.85pt 0pt 1.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">This is a convenient moment to =
deal with=20
      the hypothesis of species selection, which is left over, in a =
sense, from=20
      the previous chapter. I shan't spend very much time on it, as I =
have=20
      spelled out in </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">The=20
      Extended Phenotype </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman">my=20
      doubts about its alleged importance in evolution. It is true that =
the vast=20
      majority of species that have ever lived have gone extinct. It is =
also=20
      true that new species come into existence at a rate that at least =
balances=20
      the extinction rate, so that there is a kind of 'species pool' =
whose=20
      composition is changing all the time. Nonrandom recruitment to the =
species=20
      pool and nonrandom removal of species from it could, it is true,=20
      theoretically constitute a kind of higher-level natural selection. =
It is=20
      possible that certain characteristics of species bias their =
probability of=20
      going extinct, or of budding off new species. The species that we =
see in=20
      the world will tend to have whatever it takes to come into the =
world in=20
      the first place - to 'be speciated' - and whatever it takes not to =
go=20
      extinct. You can call that a form of natural selection if you =
wish,=20
      although I suspect that it is closer to single-step selection than =
to=20
      cumulative selection. What I am sceptical about is the suggestion =
that=20
      this kind of selection has any great importance in explaining =
evolution.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
4.15pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">This may just reflect my biased =
view of=20
      what is important. As I said </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">at </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the beginning of this chapter, =
what I=20
      mainly want a theory </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold">of=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">evolution to =
do is=20
      explain complex, well-designed mechanisms like hearts, hands, eyes =
and=20
      echolocation. Nobody, not even the most ardent species =
selectionist,=20
      thinks that species selection can do this. Some people do think =
that=20
      species selection can explain certain <BR>longterm trends in the =
fossil=20
      record, </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">such as=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the rather =
commonly=20
      </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">observed =
</SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
4.15pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D377 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.2pt 0pt 1.2pt"><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">266 </SPAN></B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">trend towards larger body size =
as the=20
      ages go by. Modern horses, as we have seen, are bigger than their=20
      ancestors of 30 million years ago. Species selectionists object to =
the=20
      idea that this came about through consistent individual advantage: =
they=20
      don't see the fossil trend as indicating that large individual =
horses were=20
      consistently more <BR>successful than small individual horses =
within their=20
      species. What they think happened is this. There were lots of =
species, a=20
      species pool. In some of these species, average body size was =
large, in=20
      others it was small (perhaps because in some species large =
individuals did=20
      best, in other species small individuals did best). The species =
with large=20
      body size were less likely to go extinct (or more likely to bud =
off new=20
      species like themselves) than the species with small body size. =
Whatever=20
      went on within species, according to the species selectionist, the =
fossil=20
      trend towards larger body size was due to a succession of =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">species </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">with progressively larger =
average body=20
      size. It is even possible that in the majority of species =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">smaller </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">individuals were favoured, yet =
the fossil=20
      trend could still be towards larger body size. In other words the=20
      selection of </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">species=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">could favour =
that=20
      minority of species in which larger individuals were favoured. =
Exactly=20
      this point was made, admittedly in a spirit of devil's advocacy, =
by the=20
      great neo-Darwinian theorist George C. Williams, long before =
modern=20
      species selectionism came on the scene. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.65pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">It could be said that we have =
here, and=20
      maybe in all alleged examples of species selection, not so much an =

      evolutionary trend, more a suc</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">cessional </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">trend, like the trend towards =
larger and=20
      larger plants as a piece of waste ground becomes colonized =
successively by=20
      small weeds, larger herbs, shrubs and, finally, the mature =
'climax' forest=20
      trees. Anyway, whether you call it a successional trend or an =
evolutionary=20
      trend, the species selectionists may well be right to believe that =
it is=20
      this kind of trend that they, as palaeontologists, are often =
dealing with=20
      in successive strata of the fossil record. But, as I said, nobody =
wants to=20
      say that species selection is an important explanation for the =
evolution=20
      of complex adaptations. Here is why. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.75pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Complex adaptations are in most =
cases not=20
      properties of species, they are properties of individuals. Species =
don't=20
      have eyes and hearts; the individuals in them do. If a species =
goes=20
      extinct because of poor eyesight, this presumably means that every =

      individual in that species died because of poor eyesight. Quality =
of=20
      eyesight is a property of individual animals. What kinds of traits =
can=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">species =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">be said to have? The answer =
must be=20
      traits that affect the survival and reproduction of the species, =
in ways=20
      that cannot be reduced to the sum of their effects on individual =
survival=20
      and reproduction. In the hypothetical example </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.75pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D6 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D26 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D6>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D6=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image101.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D26></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D6 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D25 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D6>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D6=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image102.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D26></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 2.4pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The one true tree of life=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">267 =
<BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05pt 0pt 2.15pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">of the horses, I suggested that =
that=20
      minority of species in which larger individuals were favoured were =
less=20
      likely to go extinct than the majority of species in which smaller =

      individuals were favoured. But this is pretty unconvincing. It is =
hard to=20
      think of reasons why species survivability should be decoupled =
from the=20
      sum of the survivabilities of the individual members of the =
species.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.55pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">A better example of a species =
level trait=20
      is the following hypothetical one. Suppose that in some species =
all=20
      individuals make their living in the same way. All koalas, for =
instance,=20
      live in eucalyptus trees and eat only eucalyptus leaves. Species =
like this=20
      can be called uniform. Another species might contain a diversity =
of=20
      individuals that make their living in different ways. Each =
individual=20
      could be just as specialized as an individual koala, but the =
species as a=20
      whole contains a variety of dietary habits. Some members of the =
species=20
      eat nothing but eucalyptus leaves; others nothing but wheat; =
others=20
      nothing but yams; others nothing but lime peel, and so on. Call =
this=20
      second kind of species variegated species. Now I think it is easy =
to=20
      imagine <BR>circumstances in which uniform species would be more =
likely to=20
      go extinct than variegated species. Koalas rely totally on a =
supply of=20
      eucalyptus, and a eucalyptus plague analogous to Dutch elm disease =
would=20
      finish them. In the variegated species, on the other hand, =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">some </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">members of the species would =
survive any=20
      particular plague of food plants, and the species could go on. It =
is also=20
      easy to believe that variegated species are more likely to bud off =
new,=20
      daughter species than uniform species. Here, perhaps would be =
examples of=20
      true species-level selection. Unlike shortsightedness or =
long-leggedness,=20
      'uniformness' and 'variegatedness' are true species-level traits. =
The=20
      trouble is that examples of such species-level traits are few and =
far=20
      between. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">There is an interesting theory =
by the=20
      American evolutionist Egbert Leigh which can be interpreted as a =
possible=20
      candidate example of true species-level selection, although it was =

      suggested before the phrase 'species selection' came into vogue. =
Leigh was=20
      interested in that perennial problem, the evolution of =
'altruistic'=20
      behaviour in individuals. He correctly recognized that if =
individual=20
      interests conflict with those of the species, the individual =
interests -=20
      short-term <BR>interests - must prevail. Nothing, it seems, can =
prevent=20
      the march of selfish genes. But Leigh made the following =
interesting=20
      suggestion. There must be some groups or species in which, as it =
happens,=20
      what is best for the individual pretty much coincides with what is =
best=20
      for the species. And there must be other species in which the =
interests of=20
      the individual happen to depart especially strongly from the =
interests of=20
      the species. Other things being equal, the second type of species =
could=20
      well </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.9pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">268 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.1pt 0pt 1.45pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">be more likely to go extinct. A =
form of=20
      species selection, then, could favour, not individual =
self-sacrifice, but=20
      those species in which individuals are not </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">asked to </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">sacrifice their own welfare. We =
could=20
      then see apparently unselfish individual behaviour evolving, =
because=20
      species selection has favoured those species in which individual=20
      self-interest is best served by their own apparent altruism. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.5pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Perhaps the most dramatic =
example of a=20
      truly species-level trait concerns the mode of reproduction, =
sexual versus=20
      asexual. For reasons that I haven't the space to go into, the =
existence of=20
      sexual reproduction poses a big theoretical puzzle for Darwinians. =
Many=20
      years ago R. A. Fisher, usually hostile to any idea of selection =
at levels=20
      higher than the individual organism, was prepared to make an =
exception for=20
      the special case of sexuality itself. Sexually reproducing =
species, he=20
      argued, for reasons that, again, I shan't go into (they aren't as =
obvious=20
      as one might think), are capable of evolving faster than asexually =

      reproducing species. Evolving is something that species do, not =
something=20
      that individual organisms do: you can't talk of an organism as =
evolving.=20
      Fisher was suggesting, then, that species-level selection is =
partly=20
      responsible for the fact that sexual reproduction is so common =
among modem=20
      animals. But, if so, we are dealing with a case of single-step =
selection,=20
      not cumulative selection. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.25pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Asexual species when they occur =
tend,=20
      according to the argument, to go extinct because they don't evolve =
fast=20
      enough to keep up with the changing environment. Sexual species =
tend not=20
      to go extinct, because they can evolve fast enough to keep up. So =
what we=20
      see around us are mostly sexual species. But the 'evolution' whose =
rate=20
      varies between the two systems is, of course, ordinary Darwinian =
evolution=20
      by cumulative selection at the individual level. The species =
selection,=20
      such as it is, is simple single-step selection, chosing between =
only two=20
      traits, asexuality versus sexuality, slow evolution versus fast =
evolution.=20
      The machinery of sexuality, sex organs, sexual behaviour, the =
cellular=20
      machinery of sexual cell division, all these must have been put =
together=20
      by standard, low-level Darwinian cumulative selection, not by =
species=20
      selection. In any case, as it happens, the modem consensus is =
against the=20
      old theory that sexuality is maintained by some kind of group =
level or=20
      species level selection. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.6pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">To conclude the discussion of =
species=20
      selection, it could account for the pattern of species existing in =
the=20
      world at any particular time. It follows that it could also =
account for=20
      changing patterns of species as geological ages give way to later =
ages,=20
      that is, for changing patterns in the fossil record. But it is not =
a=20
      significant force in the evolution of the complex machinery of =
life. The=20
      most it can do is to choose between </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.6pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D381 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 2.65pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The one true tree of life=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">269 =
<BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.85pt 0pt 2.4pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.55pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">various alternative complex =
machineries,=20
      given that those complex machineries have already been put =
together by=20
      true Darwinian selection. As I have put it before, species =
selection may=20
      occur but it doesn't seem to </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">do </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">anything much! I now return to =
the=20
      subject of taxonomy and its methods. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.85pt 0pt 2.15pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">I said that cladistic taxonomy =
has the=20
      advantage over librarians' types of taxonomy that there is one =
unique,=20
      true hierarchical nesting pattern in nature, waiting to be =
discovered. All=20
      that we have to do is develop methods of discovering it. =
Unfortunately=20
      there are practical difficulties. The most interesting bugbear of =
the=20
      taxonomist is evolutionary convergence. This is such an important=20
      phenomenon that I have already devoted half a chapter to it. In =
Chapter 4=20
      we saw how, over and over again, animals have been found to =
resemble=20
      unrelated animals in other parts of the world, because they have =
similar=20
      ways of life. New World army ants resemble Old World driver ants. =
Uncanny=20
      resemblances have evolved between the quite unrelated electric =
fish of=20
      Africa and South America; and between true wolves and the =
marsupial 'wolf=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Thylacinus=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">of Tasmania. =
In all=20
      these cases I simply asserted without justification that these=20
      resemblances were convergent: that they had evolved independently =
in=20
      unrelated animals. But how do we know that they are unrelated? If=20
      taxonomists use resemblances to measure closeness of cousinship, =
why=20
      weren't taxonomists fooled by the uncannily close resemblances =
that seem=20
      to unite these pairs of animals? Or, to twist the question round =
into a=20
      more worrying form, when taxonomists tell us that two animals =
really=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">are =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">closely related - say rabbits =
and hares -=20
      how do we know that the taxonomists haven't been fooled by massive =

      convergence? </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.8pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">This question really is =
worrying, because=20
      the history of taxonomy is replete with cases where later =
taxonomists have=20
      declared their predecessors wrong for precisely this reason. In =
Chapter 4=20
      we saw that an Argentinian taxonomist had pronounced the =
litopterns=20
      ancestral to true horses, whereas they are now thought to be =
convergent on=20
      true horses. The African porcupine was long believed to be closely =
related=20
      to the American porcupines, but the two groups are now thought to =
have=20
      evolved their prickly coats independently. Presumably prickles =
were useful=20
      to both for similar reasons in the two continents. Who is to say =
that=20
      future generations of taxonomists won't change their minds yet =
again? What=20
      confidence can we vest in taxonomy, if convergent evolution is =
such a=20
      powerful faker of deceptive resemblances? The main reason why I =
personally=20
      feel optimistic is the arrival on the scene of powerful new =
techniques=20
      based on molecular biology. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.2pt 0pt 10.1pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">To recapitulate from earlier =
chapters,=20
      all animals and plants and </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.2pt 0pt 10.1pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.25pt 0pt 1.2pt"><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">270 </SPAN></B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.95pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">bacteria, however different =
they appear=20
      to be from one another, are astonishingly uniform when we get down =
to=20
      molecular basics. This is most dramatically seen in the genetic =
code=20
      itself. The genetic dictionary has 64 DNA words of three letters =
each.=20
      Every one of these words has a precise translation into protein =
language=20
      (either a <BR>particular amino acid or a punctuation mark). The =
language=20
      appears to be arbitrary in the same sense as a human language is =
arbitrary=20
      (there is nothing intrinsic in the sound of the word 'house', for=20
      instance, which suggests to the listener any attribute of a =
dwelling).=20
      Given this, it is a fact of great significance that every living =
thing, no=20
      matter how different from others in external appearance it may be, =

      'speaks' almost exactly the same language at the level of the =
genes. The=20
      genetic code is universal. I regard this as near-conclusive proof =
that all=20
      organisms are descended from a single common ancestor. The odds of =
the=20
      same dictionary of arbitrary 'meanings' arising twice are almost=20
      unimaginably small. As we saw in Chapter 6, there may once have =
been other=20
      organisms that used a different genetic language, but they are no =
longer=20
      with us. All surviving organisms are descended from a single =
ancestor from=20
      which they have inherited a nearly identical, though arbitrary, =
genetic=20
      dictionary, identical in almost every one of its 64 DNA words. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Just think of the impact of =
this fact on=20
      taxonomy. Before the age of molecular biology, zoologists could be =

      confident of the cousinship of only animals that shared a very =
large=20
      number of anatomical features. Molecular biology suddenly opened a =
new=20
      treasure chest of resemblances to add to the meagre list offered =
by=20
      anatomy and embryology. The 64 identities (resemblances is too =
weak a=20
      word) of the shared genetic dictionary is only the start. Taxonomy =
has=20
      been transformed. What were once vague guesses of cousinship have =
become=20
      statistical near-certainties. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.25pt 0pt 1.45pt; TEXT-INDENT: 8.4pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The almost complete =
word-for-word=20
      universality of the genetic dictionary is, for the taxonomist, too =
much of=20
      a good thing. Once it has told us that all living things are =
cousins, it=20
      cannot tell us which pairs are closer cousins than others. But =
other=20
      molecular information can, because here we find variable degrees =
of=20
      resemblance rather than total identity. The product of the genetic =

      translating machinery, remember, is <BR>protein molecules. Each =
protein=20
      molecule is a sentence, a chain of amino acid words from the =
dictionary.=20
      We can read these sentences, either in their translated protein =
form or in=20
      their original DNA form. Though all living things share the same=20
      dictionary, they don't all make the same sentences with their =
shared=20
      dictionary. This offers us the opportunity to work out varying =
degrees of=20
      cousinship. The protein sentences, </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.25pt 0pt 1.45pt; TEXT-INDENT: 8.4pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D381 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.05in"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The one true tree of life=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">271 =
<BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.15pt 0pt 3.1pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">though different in detail, are =
often=20
      similar in overall pattern. For any pair of organisms, we can =
always find=20
      sentences that are sufficiently similar to be obviously slightly =
'garbled'=20
      versions of the same ancestral sentence. We have already seen this =
in the=20
      example of the minor differences between the histone sequences of =
cows and=20
      peas. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.85pt 0pt 2.4pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Taxonomists can now compare =
molecular=20
      sentences exactly as they might compare skulls or leg bones. =
Closely=20
      similar protein or DNA sentences can be assumed to come from close =

      cousins; more different sentences from more distant cousins. These =

      sentences are all constructed from the universal dictionary of no =
more=20
      than 64 words. The beauty of modern molecular biology is that we =
can=20
      measure the difference between two animals exactly, as the precise =
number=20
      of words by which their versions of a particular sentence differ. =
In the=20
      terms of the genetic hyperspace of Chapter 3, we can measure =
exactly how=20
      many steps separate one animal from another, at least with respect =
to a=20
      particular protein molecule. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.05pt 0pt 1.45pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">An added advantage of using =
molecular=20
      sequences in taxonomy is that, according to one influential school =
of=20
      geneticists, the 'neutralists' (we shall meet them again in the =
next=20
      chapter), most of the evolutionary change that goes on at the =
molecular=20
      level is </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">neutral.=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">This means =
that it is=20
      not due to natural selection but is effectively random, and =
therefore=20
      that, except through occasional bad luck, the bugbear of =
convergence is=20
      not there to mislead the taxonomist. A related fact is that, as we =
have=20
      already seen, any one kind of molecule seems to evolve at a =
roughly=20
      constant rate in widely different animal groups. This means that =
the=20
      number of differences between <BR>comparable molecules in two =
animals, say=20
      between human cytochrome and warthog cytochrome, is a good measure =
of the=20
      time that has elapsed since their common ancestor lived. We have a =
pretty=20
      accurate 'molecular clock'. The molecular clock allows us to =
estimate, not=20
      just which pairs of animals have the most recent common ancestors, =
but=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">&amp;\so=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">approximately=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">when =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">those common ancestors lived. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.55pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.35pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The reader may be puzzled, at =
this point,=20
      by an apparent inconsistency. This whole book emphasizes the =
overriding=20
      importance of natural selection. How then can we now emphasize the =

      randomness of evolutionary change at the molecular level? To =
anticipate=20
      Chapter 11, there really is no quarrel with respect to the =
evolution of=20
      adaptations, which are the main subject of this book. Not even the =
most=20
      ardent neutralist thinks that complex working organs like eyes and =
hands=20
      have evolved by random drift. Every sane biologist agrees that =
these can=20
      only have evolved by natural selection. It is just that the =
neutralists=20
      think =97 rightly, in my opinion =97 that such adaptations are =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.55pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.35pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D9 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D19 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D9>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D9=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image103.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D19></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D11 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D73 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D11>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D11 =

      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image104.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D73></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 2.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">272 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05pt 0pt 2.15pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the tip of the iceberg: =
probably most=20
      evolutionary change, when seen at the molecular level, is =
non-functional.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05pt 0pt 2.15pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">So long as the molecular clock =
is a fact=20
      - and it does seem to be true that each kind of molecule changes =
at=20
      roughly its own characteristic rate per million years =97 we can =
use it to=20
      date branch points in the evolutionary tree. And if it is really =
true that=20
      most evolutionary change, at the molecular level, is neutral, this =
is a=20
      wonderful gift for the taxonomist. It means that the problem of=20
      convergence may be swept away by the weapon of statistics. Every =
animal=20
      has great volumes of genetic text written in its cells, text most =
of=20
      which, according to the neutralist theory, has nothing to do with =
fitting=20
      it to its peculiar way of life; text that is largely untouched by=20
      selection and largely not subject to convergent evolution except =
as a=20
      result of sheer chance. The chance that two large pieces of =
selectively=20
      neutral text could resemble each other by luck can be calculated, =
and it=20
      is very low indeed. Even better, the constant rate of molecular =
evolution=20
      actually lets us </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">date=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">branch points =
in=20
      evolutionary history. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.55pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">It is hard to exaggerate the =
extra power=20
      that the new molecular sequence-reading techniques have added to =
the=20
      taxonomist's armoury. Not all molecular sentences in all animals =
have yet,=20
      of course, been deciphered, but already one can walk into the =
library and=20
      look up the exact word-for-word, letter-for-letter, phraseology =
of, say,=20
      the ahaemoglobin sentences of a dog, a kangaroo, a spiny anteater, =
a=20
      chicken, a viper, a newt, a carp and a human. Not all animals have =

      haemoglobin, but there are other proteins, for instance histones, =
of which=20
      a version exists in every animal and plant, and again many of them =
can=20
      already be looked up in the library. These are not vague =
measurements of=20
      the kind which, like leg length or skull width, might vary with =
the age=20
      and health of the specimen, or even with the eyesight of the =
measurer.=20
      They are precisely worded alternative versions of the same =
sentence in the=20
      same language, which can be placed side by side and compared with =
each=20
      other as minutely and as exactly as a fastidious Greek scholar =
might=20
      compare two parchments of the same Gospel. DNA sequences are the =
gospel=20
      documents of all life, and we have learned to decipher them. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The basic taxonomists' =
assumption is that=20
      close cousins will have more similar versions of a particular =
molecular=20
      sentence than more distant cousins. This is called the 'parsimony=20
      principle'. Parsimony is another name for economic meanness. Given =
a set=20
      of animals whose sentences are known, say the eight animals listed =
in the=20
      previous paragraph, our task is to discover which of all the =
possible tree=20
      diagrams linking the eight animals is the most parsimonious. The =
most=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D355 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D355>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.9pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The one true tree of life=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">273 =
<BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.1pt 0pt 1.45pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">parsimonious tree is the tree =
which is=20
      'economically meanest' with its assumptions, in the sense that it =
assumes=20
      the minimum number of word changes in evolution, and the minimum =
amount of=20
      convergence. We are entitled to assume the minimum amount of =
convergence=20
      on grounds of sheer improbability. It is unlikely, especially if =
much of=20
      molecular evolution is neutral, that two unrelated animals would =
have hit=20
      upon exactly the same sequence, word for word, letter for letter.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.65pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">There are computational =
difficulties in=20
      trying to look at all possible trees. When there are only three =
animals to=20
      be classified, the number of possible trees is only three: A =
united with B=20
      excluding C; A with C excluding B; and B with C excluding A. You =
can do=20
      the same calculation for larger numbers of animals to be =
classified, and=20
      the number of possible trees rises steeply. When there are only =
four=20
      animals to be . considered, the total number of possible trees of=20
      cousinship is still manageable at only 15. It doesn't take the =
computer=20
      long to work out which of the 15 is the most parsimonious. But if =
there=20
      are 20 animals to be considered, I reckon the number of possible =
trees to=20
      be 8,200,794,532,637,891,559,375 (see Figure 9). It has been =
calculated=20
      that the fastest of today's computers would take 10,000 million =
years,=20
      approximately the age of the universe, to discover the most =
parsimonious=20
      tree for a mere 20 animals. And taxonomists often want to =
construct trees=20
      of more than 20 animals. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.05pt 0pt 9.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Although molecular taxonomists =
have been=20
      the first to make much </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.05pt 0pt 9.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D11 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D51 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D11>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D11 =

      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image105.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D51></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
