    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D11>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D11 =

      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image106.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D74></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D231 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D310 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D231>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG =
height=3D231=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image107.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D310></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D30 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D376 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D30>
      <P class=3DStyle4><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">Figure 9=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">This family =
tree is=20
      correct. There are 8200794532637891559374 other ways of =
classifying these=20
      20 organisms, and all of them are wrong. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D625 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D376 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D625>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.25pt 0pt 0.95pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">274 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05pt 0pt 0.7pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">of it, this problem of =
exploding large=20
      numbers has actually been lurking all along in non-molecular =
taxonomy.=20
      Nonmolecular taxonomists have simply evaded it by making intuitive =

      guesses. Of all the possible family trees that might be tried, =
huge=20
      numbers of trees can be eliminated immediately - for instance, all =
those=20
      millions of conceivable family trees that place humans closer to=20
      earthworms than to chimps. Taxonomists don't even bother to =
consider such=20
      obviously absurd trees of cousinship, but instead home in on the=20
      relatively few trees that do not too drastically violate their=20
      preconceptions. This is probably fair, although there is always =
the danger=20
      that the truly most parsimonious tree is one of those that have =
been=20
      thrown out without consideration. Computers, too, can be =
programmed to=20
      take short cuts, and the problem of the exploding large numbers =
can be=20
      mercifully cut down. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.75pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Molecular information is so =
rich that we=20
      can do our taxonomy separately, over and over again, for different =

      proteins. We can then use our conclusions, drawn from the study of =
one=20
      molecule, as a check on our conclusions based on the study of =
another=20
      molecule. If we are worried that the story told by one protein =
molecule is=20
      really confounded by convergence, we can immediately check it by =
looking=20
      at another protein molecule. Convergent evolution is really a =
special kind=20
      of coincidence. The thing about coincidences is that, even if they =
happen=20
      once, they are far less likely to happen twice. And even less =
likely to=20
      happen three times. By taking more and more separate protein =
molecules, we=20
      can all but eliminate coincidence. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.6pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">For instance, in one study by a =
group of=20
      New Zealand biologists, 11 animals were classified, not once but =
five=20
      times independently, using five different protein molecules. The =
11=20
      animals were sheep, rhesus monkey, horse, kangaroo, rat, rabbit, =
dog, pig,=20
      human, cow and chimpanzee. The idea was first to work out a tree =
of=20
      relationships among the 11 animals using one protein. Then see =
whether you=20
      get the </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">same=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">tree of =
relationships=20
      using a different protein. Then do the same for a third, fourth =
and fifth=20
      protein. Theoretically, if evolution were not true for example, it =
is=20
      possible for each of the five proteins to give a completely =
different tree=20
      of 'relationships'. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.75pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The five protein sequences were =
all=20
      available to be looked up in the library, for all 11 animals. For =
11=20
      animals, there are 654,729,075 <BR>possible trees of relationships =
to be=20
      considered, and the usual short-cut methods had to be employed. =
For each=20
      of the five protein molecules, the computer printed out the most=20
      parsimonious tree of relationship. This gives five independent =
best=20
      guesses as to the true tree of relationships among these 11 =
animals. The=20
      neatest </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">result=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">that we could=20
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.75pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.9pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The one true tree of life=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">275 =
<BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.7pt 0pt 1.7pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">hope for is that all five =
estimated trees=20
      turn out to be identical. The probability of getting this result =
by sheer=20
      luck is very small indeed: the number has 31 noughts after the =
decimal=20
      point. We should not be surprised if we fail to get agreement =
quite as=20
      perfect as this: a certain amount of convergent evolution and =
coincidence=20
      is only to be expected. But we should be worried if there is not a =

      substantial measure of agreement among the different trees. In =
fact the=20
      five trees turned out to be not quite identical, but they are very =

      similar. All the five molecules agree in placing human, chimp and =
monkey=20
      close to each other, but there are some disagreements over which =
animal is=20
      the next closest to this cluster: haemoglobin B says the dog is,=20
      fibrinopeptide B says the rat is; fibrinopeptide A says that a =
cluster=20
      consisting of rat and rabbit is; haemoglobin A says that a cluster =

      consisting of rat, rabbit and dog is. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.15pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">We have a definite common =
ancestor with=20
      the dog, and another definite common ancestor with the rat. These =
two=20
      ancestors really existed, at a particular moment in history. One =
of them=20
      has to be more recent than the other, so either haemoglobin B or=20
      fibrinopeptide B must be wrong in its estimate of evolutionary=20
      relationships. Such minor discrepancies needn't worry us, as I =
have said.=20
      We expect a certain amount of convergence and coincidence. If we =
are truly=20
      closer to the dog, then this means that we and the rat have =
converged on=20
      one another with respect to our fibrinopeptide B. If we are truly =
closer=20
      to the rat, this means that we and the dog have converged on each =
other=20
      with respect to our haemoglobin B. We can get an idea of which of =
these=20
      two is the more likely, by looking at yet other molecules. But I =
shan't=20
      pursue the matter: the point has been made. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.65pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">I said that taxonomy was one of =
the most=20
      rancorously ill-tempered of biological fields. Stephen Gould has =
well=20
      characterized it with the phrase 'names and nastiness'. =
Taxonomists seem=20
      to feel passionately about their schools of thought, in a way that =
we=20
      expect in political science or economics, but not usually in =
academic=20
      science. It is clear that members of a particular school of =
taxonomy think=20
      of themselves as a beleaguered band of brothers, like the early=20
      Christians. I first realized this when a taxonomist acquaintance =
told me,=20
      white-faced with dismay, the 'news' that So-and-so (the name =
doesn't=20
      matter) had </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">'gone over=20
      to </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the =
cladists'.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
2.95pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The following brief account of =
taxonomic=20
      schools of thought will probably annoy some members of those =
schools, but=20
      no more than they habitually infuriate each other so no undue harm =
will be=20
      done. In terms of their fundamental philosophy, taxonomists fall =
into two=20
      main camps. On the one hand there are those that make no bones =
about the=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
2.95pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D13 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D18 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D13>
      <P class=3DStyle41><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">276=20
      </SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle41><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D599 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D599>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.9pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">fact that their aim is openly =
to discover=20
      evolutionary relationships. To them (and to me) a good taxonomic =
tree=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">is =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">a family tree of evolutionary=20
      relationships. When you do taxonomy you are using all methods at =
your=20
      disposal to make the best guess you can about the closeness of =
cousinship=20
      of animals to one another. It is hard to find a name for these =
taxonomists=20
      because the obvious name, 'evolutionary taxonomists', has been =
usurped for=20
      one particular sub-school. They are sometimes called =
'phyleticists'. I=20
      have written this chapter, so far, from a phyleticist's point of =
view.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">But there are many taxonomists =
who=20
      proceed in a different way, and for quite sensible reasons. =
Although they=20
      are likely to agree that one ultimate aim of doing taxonomy is to =
make=20
      discoveries about evolutionary relationships, they insist on =
keeping the=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">practice=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">of taxonomy =
separate=20
      from the theory - presumably evolutionary theory - of what has led =
to the=20
      pattern of resemblances. These taxonomists study patterns of =
resemblances=20
      in their own right. They do not prejudge the issue of whether the =
pattern=20
      of resemblances is caused by evolutionary history and whether =
close=20
      resemblance is due to close cousinship. They prefer to construct =
their=20
      taxonomy using the pattern of resemblances alone. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.7pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">One advantage of doing this is =
that, if=20
      you have any doubts about the truth of evolution, you can use the =
pattern=20
      of resemblances to test it. If evolution is true, resemblances =
among=20
      animals should follow certain predictable patterns, notably the =
pattern of=20
      hierarchical nesting. If evolution is false, goodness knows=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">what =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">pattern we should expect, but =
there is no=20
      obvious reason to expect a nested hierarchical pattern. If you =
assume=20
      evolution throughout the </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">doing </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">of your taxonomy, this school =
insists,=20
      you can't then use the results of your taxonomic work to support =
the truth=20
      of evolution: the argument would be circular. This argument would =
have=20
      force if anybody was seriously in doubt about the truth of =
evolution. Once=20
      again, it is hard to find a suitable name for this second school =
of=20
      thought among taxonomists. I shall call them the 'pure-resemblance =

      measurers'. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
2.3pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The phyleticists, the =
taxonomists that=20
      openly try to discover evolutionary relationships, further split =
into two=20
      schools of thought. These are the cladists, who follow the =
principles laid=20
      down in Willi Hennig's famous book </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Phylogenetic Systematics;=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">and the =
'traditional'=20
      evolutionary taxonomists. Cladists are obsessed with branches. For =
them,=20
      the goal of taxonomy is to discover the order in which lineages =
split from=20
      each other in evolutionary time. They don't care how much, or how =
little,=20
      those lineages have changed since the branch-point. 'Traditional'=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">(don't =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">think of it as a pejorative =
name)=20
      evolutionary </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
2.3pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D248 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D248>
      <P class=3DStyle23 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 2.4pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The one true tree of life=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica">277 </SPAN><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.3pt 0pt 1.9pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.55pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">taxonomists differ from =
cladists mainly=20
      in that they don't consider </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">only </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the branching kind of =
evolution. They=20
      also take account of the </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">total </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">quantity of change that occurs =
during=20
      evolution, not just branching. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.85pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Cladists think in terms of =
branching=20
      trees, right from the outset of their work. They ideally begin by=20
      writingdown all possible branching trees forthe animals they are =
dealing=20
      with (two-way branching trees only, because there are limits to =
anyone's=20
      patience!). As we saw when discussing molecular taxonomy, this =
gets=20
      difficult if you are trying to classify lots of animals, because =
the=20
      number of possible trees becomes astronomically large. But as we =
also saw,=20
      there are fortunately short cuts and serviceable approximations =
which mean=20
      that this kind of taxonomy can, in practice, be done. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.8pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">If, for the sake of argument, =
we were=20
      trying to classify just the three animals squid, herring and =
human, the=20
      only three possible two-way branching trees are the following: =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 24pt 0pt 0.5pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">1. Squid and herring are close =
to each=20
      other, human is the 'outgroup'. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 24pt 0pt 0.5pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D153 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D246 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D153>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG =
height=3D153=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
