<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D42 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D376 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D42>
      <P class=3DStyle9 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.5pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica">278 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle24 style=3D"MARGIN-RIGHT: 1.55pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">3. </SPAN></I>Squid and human =
are close=20
      to each other, herring is the outgroup. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle24 style=3D"MARGIN-RIGHT: 1.55pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D155 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D277 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D155>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt; COLOR: =
black"><IMG=20
      height=3D155=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image110.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D277></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D401 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D381 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D401>
      <P class=3DStyle24=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.05in; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.65pt">Cladists=20
      would look at each of the three possible trees in turn, and choose =
the=20
      best tree. How is the best tree recognized? Basically, it is the =
tree that=20
      unites the animals that have the most features in common. We label =
as the=20
      'outgroup' the animal that has fewest features in common with the =
other=20
      two. Of the above list of trees, the second would be preferred, =
because=20
      human and herring share many more features in common with each =
other than=20
      squid and herring do or than squid and human do. Squid is the =
outgroup=20
      because it doesn't have many features in common with either human =
or=20
      herring. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle24=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.2pt 0pt 2.15pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt">Actually,=20
      it isn't quite as simple as just counting features in common, =
because some=20
      kinds of features are deliberately ignored. Cladists want to give =
special=20
      weight to features that are recently evolved. Ancient features =
that all=20
      mammals inherited from the first mammal, for instance, are useless =
for=20
      doing classifications within the mammals. The methods they use for =

      deciding which features are ancient are interesting, but they =
would take=20
      us outside the scope of this book. The main thing to remember at =
this=20
      stage is that, at least in principle, the cladist thinks about all =

      possible bifurcating trees that <I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">might </SPAN></I>unite the set =
of=20
      animals he is dealing with, and tries to choose the one correct =
tree. And=20
      the true cladist makes no bones about the fact that he thinks of =
the=20
      branching trees or 'cladograms' as family trees, trees of =
closeness of=20
      evolutionary cousinship. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle24=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.95pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt">If=20
      pushed to the extreme, the obsession with branchings alone could =
give=20
      strange results. It is theoretically possible for a species to be =
<I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">identical </SPAN></I>in every =
detail to=20
      its distant cousins, while being exceedingly different from its =
closer=20
      cousins. For instance, suppose that two very similar fish species, =
which=20
      we can call Jacob and Esau, lived 300 million years ago. Both =
these=20
      species founded dynasties of descendants, </P>
      <P class=3DStyle24=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.95pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D394 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle31 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 12.25pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica-Oblique">The one true tree of life =

      </SPAN></I><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica-Bold">279=20
</SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.15pt 0pt 11.3pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.35pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">which last to the present day. =
Esau's=20
      descendants stagnated. They went on living in the deep sea but =
they didn't=20
      evolve. The result is that a modem descendant of Esau is =
essentially the=20
      same as Esau, and is therefore also very like Jacob. Jacob's =
descendants=20
      evolved and proliferated. They eventually gave rise to all modem =
mammals.=20
      But one lineage of Jacob's descendants also stagnated in the deep =
sea, and=20
      also leaves modern descendants. These modern descendants are fish =
that are=20
      so similar to Esau's modern descendants that they are hard to tell =
apart.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.05pt 0pt 8.4pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Now, how shall we classify =
these animals?=20
      The traditional evolutionary taxonomist would recognize the great=20
      similarity between the primitive deep-sea descendants of Jacob and =
Esau,=20
      and would classify them together. The strict cladist could not do =
that.=20
      The deep-sea descendants of Jacob, for all that they look just =
like the=20
      deep-sea descendants of Esau, are, nevertheless, closer cousins of =

      mammals. Their common ancestor with mammals lived more recently, =
even if=20
      only slightly more recently, than their common ancestor with =
Esau's=20
      descendants. Therefore they must be classified together with =
mammals. This=20
      may seem strange, but personally I can treat it with equanimity. =
It is at=20
      least utterly logical and clear. There are indeed virtues in both =
cladism=20
      and traditional evolutionary taxonomy, and I don't much mind how =
people=20
      classify animals so long as they tell me clearly how they are =
doing it.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 8.05pt 0pt 4.1pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Turning now to the other major =
school of=20
      thought, the pure-resemblance measurers, they again can be split =
into two=20
      subschools. Both the sub-schools agree to banish evolution from =
their=20
      day-to-day thoughts while they do taxonomy. But they disagree over =
how to=20
      proceed in their day-to-day taxonomy. One sub-school among these=20
      taxonomists are sometimes called 'pheneticists' and sometimes =
called=20
      'numerical taxonomists'. I shall call them the 'average-distance=20
      measurers'. The other school of resemblance measurers call =
<BR>themselves=20
      'transformed cladists'. This is a poor name, since the one thing =
these=20
      people are not is cladists! When Julian Huxley invented the term =
clade he=20
      defined it, clearly and unambiguously, in terms of evolutionary =
branching=20
      and evolutionary ancestry. A clade is the set of all organisms =
descended=20
      from a particular ancestor. Since the main point of 'transformed =
cladists'=20
      is to avoid all notions of evolution and of ancestry, they cannot =
sensibly=20
      call themselves cladists. The reason they do so is one of history: =
they=20
      started out as true cladists, and kept some of the methods of =
cladists=20
      while abandoning their fundamental philosophy and rationale. I =
suppose I=20
      have no choice but to call them transformed cladists, although I =
do so=20
      with reluctance. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 8.05pt 0pt 4.1pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D625 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D625>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.75pt 0pt 0.5pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">280 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.55pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The average-distance measurers =
not only=20
      refuse to use evolution in their taxonomy (although they all =
believe in=20
      evolution). They are consistent in that they don't even assume =
that the=20
      pattern of resemblance will necessarily be a simply branching =
hierarchy.=20
      They try to employ methods that will uncover a hierarchical =
pattern if one=20
      is really there, but not if it isn't. They try to ask Nature to =
tell them=20
      whether she is really organized hierarchically. This is not an =
easy task,=20
      and it is probably fair to say that methods are not really =
available for=20
      achieving this aim. Nevertheless the aim seems to me to be all of =
a piece=20
      with the laudable one of avoiding preconceptions. Their methods =
are often=20
      rather sophisticated and mathematical, and they are just as =
suitable for=20
      classifying nonliving things, for instance rocks or archaeological =

      relics,' as for classifying living organisms. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.8pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">They usually begin by measuring =

      everything they can about their animals. You have to be a bit =
clever about=20
      how you interpret these measurements, but I shan't go into that. =
The end=20
      result is that the measurements are all combined together to =
produce an=20
      index of resemblance (or, its opposite, an index of difference) =
between=20
      each animal and each other animal. If you wish, you can actually =
visualize=20
      the animals as clouds of points in space. Rats, mice, hamsters, =
etc. would=20
      all be found in one part of the space. Far away in another part of =
the=20
      space would be another little cloud, consisting of lions, tigers,=20
      leopards, cheetahs, etc. The distance between any two points in =
the space=20
      is a measure of how closely the two animals resemble each other, =
when=20
      large numbers of their attributes are combined together. The =
distance=20
      between lion and tiger is small. So is the distance between rat =
and mouse.=20
      But the distance between rat and tiger, or mouse and lion, is =
large. The=20
      combining together of attributes is usually done with the aid of a =

      computer. The space that these animals are sitting in is =
superficially a=20
      bit like Biomorph Land, but the 'distances' reflect bodily =
resemblances=20
      rather than genetic resemblances. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.7pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Having calculated an index of =
average=20
      resemblance (or distance) between each animal and each other =
animal, the=20
      computer is next programmed to scan the set of =
distances/resemblances and=20
      to try to fit them into a hierarchical clustering pattern. =
Unfortunately=20
      there is a lot of-controversy about exactly which calculation =
method=20
      should be used to look for clusters. There is no one obviously =
correct=20
      method, and the methods don't all give the same answer. Worse, it =
is=20
      possible that some of these computer methods are over-'eager' to =
'see'=20
      hierarchically arranged clusters within clusters, even if they =
aren't=20
      really there. The school of distance measurers, or 'numerical=20
      taxonomists', has become a bit unfashionable lately. My view is =
that the=20
      unfashionableness is a </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.7pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D10 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D30 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D10>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D10 =

      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image111.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D30></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D626 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D384 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D626>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 6pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The one true tree of life=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">281 =
<BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.6pt 0pt 5.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.35pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">temporary phase, as fashions =
often are,=20
      and that this kind of 'numerical taxonomy' is by no means easily =
to be=20
      written off. I expect a <BR>comeback. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.55pt 0pt 4.8pt; TEXT-INDENT: 2.4pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">, The other school of =
pure-pattern=20
      measurers are the ones that call themselves transformed cladists, =
for=20
      reasons of history as we have seen. It is from within this group =
that the=20
      'nastiness' mainly emanates. I shall not follow the usual practice =
of=20
      tracing their historical origins from within the ranks of true =
cladists.=20
      In their underlying philosophy, so-called transformed cladists =
have more=20
      in common with the other school of pure-pattern measurers, the =
ones often=20
      called 'pheneticists' or 'numerical taxonomists', whom I have just =

      discussed under the title of average-distance measurers. What =
these share=20
      with each other is an antipathy to dragging evolution into the =
practice of=20
      taxonomy, although this does not </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">necessarily </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">betoken any hostility to the =
idea of=20
      evolution itself. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.65pt 0pt 3.1pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">What the transformed cladists =
share with=20
      true cladists is many of their methods in practice. Both think, =
right from=20
      the start, in terms of bifurcating trees. And both pick out =
certain kinds=20
      of characteristics as taxonomically important, other kinds of=20
      characteristics as taxonomically worthless. They differ with =
respect to=20
      the rationale that they give to this discrimination. Like =
average-distance=20
      measurers, transformed cladists are not out to discover family =
trees. They=20
      are looking for trees of pure resemblance. They agree with the=20
      averagedistance measurers to leave open the question of whether =
the=20
      pattern of resemblance reflects evolutionary history. But unlike =
the=20
      distance measurers, who, at least in theory, are prepared to let =
Nature=20
      tell them whether she is actually hierarchically organized, the=20
      transformed cladists </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">assume </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">that she is. It is an axiom, an =
article=20
      of faith with them, that things are to be classified into =
branching=20
      hierarchies (or, equivalently, into nested nests). Because the =
branching=20
      tree has nothing to do with evolution, it need not necessarily be =
applied=20
      to living things. The methods of transformed cladistics can, =
according to=20
      their advocates, be used for classifying not just animals and =
plants but=20
      stones, planets, library books and Bronze Age pots. In other words =
they=20
      would not subscribe to the point I made with my library =
comparison, that=20
      evolution is the only sound basis for a uniquely hierarchical=20
      classification. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 6pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.55pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The average-distance measurers, =
as we=20
      saw, measure how far each animal is from each other animal, where =
'far'=20
      means 'does not resemble' and 'near' means 'resembles'. Only then, =
after=20
      calculating a sort of summed average index of resemblance, do they =
start=20
      trying to <BR>interpret their results in terms of a branching,=20
      cluster-within-clustery </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 6pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.55pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D377 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.45pt 0pt 0.5pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">282 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.15pt 0pt 0.5pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">hierarchy or 'tree' diagram. =
The=20
      transformed cladists, however, like the true cladists that they =
once were,=20
      bring in clustery, branchy thinking right at the outset. Like true =

      cladists, they would begin, at least in principle, by writing down =
all=20
      possible bifurcating trees, and then choosing the best. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.35pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">But what are they actually =
talking about=20
      when they consider each possible 'tree', and what do they mean by =
the=20
      best? What hypothetical state of the world does each tree =
correspond to?=20
      To a true cladist, a follower of W. Hennig, the answer is very =
clear. Each=20
      of the 15 possible trees uniting four animals represents a =
possible family=20
      tree. Of all the 15 conceivable family trees uniting four animals, =
one and=20
      only one must be the correct one. The history of the animals' =
ancestors=20
      really did happen, in the world. There are 15 possible histories, =
if we=20
      make the assumption that all branchings are two-way branchings. =
Fourteen=20
      of those possible histories must be wrong. Only one can be right; =
can=20
      correspond to the way the history actually happened. Of all the =
135,135=20
      possible family trees culminating in 8 animals, 135,134 must be =
wrong.=20
      Only one represents historical truth. It may not be easy to be =
sure=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">which =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">one is the correct one, but the =
true=20
      cladist can at least be sure </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">that </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">not more than one is correct. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.5pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">But what do the 15 (or 135,135, =
or=20
      whatever it is) possible trees, and the one correct tree, =
correspond to in=20
      the nonevolutionary world of the transformed cladist? The answer, =
as my=20
      colleague and former student Mark Ridley has pointed out in his=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Evolution and=20
      Classification, </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman">is=20
      nothing very much. The transformed cladist refuses to allow the =
concept of=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">ancestry to=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">enter his=20
      considerations. 'Ancestor', to him, is a dirty word. But on the =
other hand=20
      he insists that classification must be a branching hierarchy. So, =
if the=20
      15 (or 135,135) possible hierarchical trees are not trees of =
ancestral=20
      history, what on earth are they? There is nothing for it but to =
appeal to=20
      ancient philosophy for some woolly, idealistic notion that the =
world just=20
      is organized hierarchically; some notion that <BR>everything in =
the world=20
      has its 'opposite', its mystical ying or yang. It never gets much =
more=20
      concrete than that. It certainly is not possible, in the =
nonevolutionary=20
      world of the transformed cladist, to make strong and clear =
statements such=20
      as 'only one out of the 945 possible trees uniting 6 animals can =
be right;=20
      all the rest must be wrong'. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.3pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Why is ancestor a dirty word to =
cladists?=20
      It is not (I hope) that they think that there never were any =
ancestors. It=20
      is rather that they have decided that ancestors have no place in =
taxonomy.=20
      This is a defensible position as far as the day-to-day =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">practice </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">of taxonomy is concerned. No =
cladist=20
      actually draws flesh and blood ancestors on family trees, though=20
      traditional evolutionary taxonomists sometimes do. Cladists, =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.3pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D382 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle23 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 5.3pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The one true tree of life=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica">283 </SPAN><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05pt 0pt 4.8pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.55pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">of all stripes, treat all =
relationships=20
      between real, observed animals as </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">cousinships, </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">as a matter of form. This is =
perfectly=20
      sensible. What is not sensible is to carry this over into a taboo =
against=20
      the very </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">concept=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">of ancestors, =
against=20
      the use of the language of ancestry in providing the fundamental=20
      justification for adopting the hierarchically branching tree as =
the basis=20
      for your taxonomy. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.05pt 0pt 4.1pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">I have left till last the =
oddest aspect=20
      of the transformed cladism school of taxonomy. Not content with a=20
      perfectly sensible belief that there is something to be said for =
leaving=20
      evolutionary and ancestral assumptions out of the </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">practice </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">of taxonomy, a belief that they =
share=20
      with pheneticist 'distance measurers', some transformed cladists =
have gone=20
      right over the top and concluded that there must be something =
wrong with=20
      evolution itself! The fact is almost too bizarre to credit, but =
some of=20
      the leading 'transformed cladists' profess an actual hostility to =
the idea=20
      of evolution itself, especially the Darwinian theory of evolution. =
Two of=20
      them, G. Nelson and N. Platnick from the American Museum of =
Natural=20
      History in New York, have gone so far as to write that 'Darwinism =
. . .=20
      is, in short, a theory that has been put to the test and found =
false'. I=20
      should love to know what this 'test' is and, even more, I should =
love to=20
      know by what alternative theory Nelson and Platnick would explain =
the=20
      phenomena that Darwinism explains, especially adaptive complexity. =

      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.75pt 0pt 1.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">It isn't that any transformed =
cladists=20
      are themselves fundamentalist creationists. My own interpretation =
is that=20
      they enjoy an exaggerated idea of the importance of taxonomy in =
biology.=20
      They have decided, perhaps rightly, that they can do taxonomy =
better if=20
      they forget about evolution, and especially if they never use the =
concept=20
      of the ancestor in thinking about taxonomy. In the same way, a =
student of,=20
      say, nerve cells, might decide that he is not aided by thinking =
about=20
      evolution. The nerve specialist agrees that his nerve cells are =
the=20
      products of evolution, but he does not need to use this fact in =
his=20
      research. He needs to know a lot about physics and chemistry, but =
he=20
      believes that Darwinism is irrelevant to his day-to-day research =
on nerve=20
      impulses. This is a defensible position. But you can't reasonably =
say=20
      that, because you don't need to use a particular theory in the day =
to day=20
      practice of your particular branch of science, therefore that =
theory is=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">false. =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">You will only say this if you =
have a=20
      remarkably grandiose estimation of the importance of your own =
branch of=20
      science. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 5.2pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Even then, it isn't logical. A =
physicist=20
      certainly doesn't need Darwinism in order to do physics. He might =
think=20
      that biology is a trivial subject compared with physics. It would =
follow=20
      from this that, in his opinion, Darwinism is of trivial importance =
to=20
      science. But he could </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 5.2pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D384 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D377 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D384>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.25pt 0pt 1.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">284 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.45pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.65pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">not </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">sensibly conclude from this =
that it is=20
      therefore </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">false\=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Yet this is =
essentially=20
      what some of the leaders of the school of transformed cladistics =
seem to=20
      have done. 'False', note well, is precisely the word Nelson and =
Platnick=20
      used. Needless to say, their words have been picked up by the =
sensitive=20
      microphones that I mentioned in the previous chapter, and the =
result has=20
      been considerable publicity. They have earned themselves a place =
of honour=20
      in fundamentalist, creationist literature. When a leading =
transformed=20
      cladist came to give a guest lecture in my university recently, he =
drew a=20
      bigger crowd than any other guest lecturer that year! It isn't =
hard to see=20
      why. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">There is no doubt at all that =
remarks=20
      like 'Darwinism . . . is a theory that has been put to the test =
and found=20
      false', coming from established biologists on the staff of a =
respected=20
      national museum, will be meat and drink to creationists and others =
who=20
      actively have an interest in perpetrating falsehoods. This is the =
only=20
      reason I have troubled my readers with the topic of transformed =
cladism at=20
      all. As Mark Ridley more mildly said, in a review of the book in =
which=20
      Nelson and Platnick made that remark about Darwinism being false, =
Who=20
      would have guessed that all that they really </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">meant </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">was that ancestral species are =
tricky to=20
      represent in cladistic classification? Of course it is difficult =
to pin=20
      down the precise identity of ancestors, and there is a good case =
for not=20
      even trying to do so. But to make statements that encourage others =
to=20
      conclude that there never were any ancestors is to debauch =
language and=20
      betray truth. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 43.6pt 0pt 9.85pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Now I'd better go out and dig =
the garden,=20
      or something. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 43.6pt 0pt 9.85pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D511 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D362 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D511>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"><IMG=20
      height=3D511=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image112.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D362></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D561 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D561>
      <P class=3DStyle16 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 102.05pt 0pt =
107.3pt">CHAPTER 11 <SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <H2 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 64.55pt 0pt 70.1pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 17pt">DOOMED RIVALS </SPAN><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR><BR><BR></SPAN></H2>
      <P class=3DStyle24=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.2pt 0pt 0.75pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt">No=20
      serious biologist doubts the fact that evolution has happened, nor =
that=20
      all living creatures are cousins of one another. Some biologists, =
however,=20
      have had doubts about Darwin's particular theory of <I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">how </SPAN></I>evolution =
happened.=20
      Sometimes this turns out to be just an argument about words. The =
theory of=20
      punctuated evolution, for instance, can be represented as =
anti-Darwinian.=20
      As I argued in Chapter 9, however, it is really a minor variety of =

      Darwinism, and does not belong in any chapter about rival =
theories. But=20
      there are other theories that are most definitely <I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">not </SPAN></I>versions of =
Darwinism,=20
      theories that go flatly against the very spirit of Darwinism. =
These rival=20
      theories are the subject of this chapter. They include various =
versions of=20
      what is called Lamarckism; also other points of view such as =
'neutralism',=20
      'mutationism' and creationism which have, from time to time, been =
advanced=20
      as alternatives to Darwinian selection. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle24=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.25pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt">The=20
      obvious way to decide between rival theories is to examine the =
evidence.=20
      Lamarckian types of theory, for instance, are traditionally =
rejected - and=20
      rightly so - because no good evidence for them has ever been found =
(not=20
      for want of energetic trying, in some cases by zealots prepared to =
fake=20
      evidence). In this chapter I shall take a different tack, largely =
because=20
      so many other books have examined the evidence and concluded in =
favour of=20
      Darwinism. Instead of examining the evidence for and against rival =

      theories, I shall adopt a more armchair approach. My argument will =
be that=20
      Darwinism is the only known theory that is in principle <I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">capable </SPAN></I>of =
explaining certain=20
      aspects of life. If I am right it means that, even if there were =
no actual=20
      evidence in favour of the Darwinian theory (there is, of course) =
we should=20
      still be justified in preferring it over all rival theories. <SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle23 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.75pt 0pt 254.9pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica">287 </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle23 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.75pt 0pt 254.9pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Helvetica"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 8pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Helvetica"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D15 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D19 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D15>
      <P class=3DStyle23><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica">288 =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle23><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Helvetica"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D16 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D131 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D16>
      <P class=3DStyle6><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The =
Blind=20
      Watchmaker </SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle6><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D600 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D380 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D600>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.25pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">One way in which to dramatize =
this point=20
      is to make a prediction. I predict that, if a form of life is ever =

      discovered in another part of the universe, however outlandish and =
weirdly=20
      alien that form of life may be in detail, it will be found to =
resemble=20
      life on Earth in one key respect: it will have evolved by some =
kind of=20
      Darwinian natural selection. Unfortunately, this is a prediction =
that we=20
      shall, in all probability, not be able to test in our lifetimes, =
but it=20
      remains a way of dramatizing an important truth about life on our =
own=20
      planet. The Darwinian theory is in principle capable of explaining =
life.=20
      No other theory that has ever been suggested is in principle =
capable of=20
      explaining life. I shall demonstrate this by discussing all known =
rival=20
      theories, not the evidence for or against them, but their =
adequacy, in=20
      principle, as explanations for life. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.25pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">First, I must specify what it =
means to=20
      'explain' life. There are, of course, many properties of living =
things=20
      that we could list, and some of them might be explicable by rival=20
      theories. Many facts about the distribution of protein molecules, =
as we=20
      have seen, may be due to neutral genetic mutations rather than =
Darwinian=20
      selection. There is one particular property of living things, =
however,=20
      that I want to single out as explicable </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">only </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">by Darwinian selection. This =
property is=20
      the one that has been the recurring topic of this book: adaptive=20
      complexity. Living organisms are well fitted to survive and =
reproduce in=20
      their environments, in ways too numerous and statistically =
improbable to=20
      have come about in a single chance blow. Following Paley, I have =
used the=20
      example of the eye. Two or three of an eye's well-'designed' =
features=20
      could, conceivably, have come about in a single lucky accident. It =
is the=20
      sheer number of interlocking parts, all well adapted to seeing and =
well=20
      adapted to each other, that demands a special kind of explanation =
beyond=20
      mere chance. The Darwinian explanation, of course, involves chance =
too, in=20
      the form of mutation. But the chance is filtered cumulatively by=20
      selection, step by step, over many generations. Other chapters =
have shown=20
      that this theory is capable of providing a satisfying explanation =
for=20
      adaptive complexity. In this chapter I shall argue that all other =
known=20
      theories are not capable of so doing. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.25pt 0pt 2.65pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">First, let us take Darwinism's =
most=20
      prominent historical rival, Lamarckism. When Lamarckism was first =
proposed=20
      in the early nineteenth century, it was not as a rival to =
Darwinism,=20
      because Darwinism had not yet been thought of. The Chevalier de =
Lamarck=20
      was ahead of his time. He was one of those eighteenth-century=20
      intellectuals who argued in favour of evolution. In this he was =
right, and=20
      he would deserve to be honoured for this alone, along with Charles =

      Darwin's </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.25pt 0pt 2.65pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D385 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle28 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 6.25pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Doomed rivals =
</SPAN></I><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica-Bold">289 </SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.6pt 0pt 5.05pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">grandfather Erasmus and others. =
Lamarck=20
      also offered the best theory of the mechanism of evolution that =
anyone=20
      could come up with at the time, but there is no reason to suppose =
that, if=20
      the Darwinian theory of mechanism had been around at the time, he =
would=20
      have rejected it. It was not around, and it is Lamarck's =
misfortune that,=20
      at least in the English-speaking world, his name has become a =
label for an=20
      error - his theory of the </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">mechanism </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">of evolution =97 rather than =
for his=20
      correct belief in the </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">fact </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">that evolution has occurred. =
This is not=20
      a history book, and I shall not attempt a scholarly dissection of =
exactly=20
      what Lamarck himself said. There was a dose of mysticism in =
Lamarck's=20
      actual words - for instance, he had a strong belief in progress up =
what=20
      many people, even today, think of as the ladder of life; and he =
spoke of=20
      animals striving as if they, in some sense, consciously =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">wanted to </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">evolve. I shall extract from =
Lamarckism=20
      those non-mystical elements which, at least at first sight, seem =
to have a=20
      sporting chance of offering a real alternative to Darwinism. These =

      elements, the only ones adopted by modern 'neo-Lamarckians', are =
basically=20
      two: the inheritance of acquired characteristics, and the =
principle of use=20
      and disuse. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.7pt 0pt 2.15pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The principle of use and disuse =
states=20
      that those parts of an organism's body that are used grow larger. =
Those=20
      parts that are not used tend to wither away. It is an observed =
fact that=20
      when you exercise particular muscles they grow; muscles that are =
never=20
      used shrink. By examining a man's body we can tell which muscles =
he uses=20
      and which he does not. We may even be able to guess his profession =
or his=20
      recreation. Enthusiasts of the 'body-building' cult make use of =
the=20
      principle of use and disuse to 'build' their bodies, almost like a =
piece=20
      of sculpture, into whatever unnatural shape is demanded by fashion =
in this=20
      peculiar minority culture. Muscles are not the only parts of the =
body that=20
      respond to use in this kind of way. Walk barefoot, and you acquire =
tougher=20
      skin on your soles. It is easy to tell a farmer from a bank clerk =
by=20
      looking at their hands alone. The farmer's hands are horny, =
toughened by=20
      long exposure to rough work. If the clerk's hands are horny at =
all, it=20
      amounts only to a little callus on the writing finger. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 5.7pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The principle of use and disuse =
enables=20
      animals to become better at the job of surviving in their world,=20
      progressively better during their own lifetime as a result of =
living in=20
      that world. Humans, through direct exposure to sunlight, or lack =
of it,=20
      develop a skin colour which equips them better to survive in the=20
      particular local conditions. Too much sunlight is dangerous. =
Enthusiastic=20
      sunbathers with very fair skins are susceptible to skin cancer. =
Too little=20
      sunlight, on the other hand, leads to vitamin-D deficiency and =
rickets,=20
      sometimes seen in hereditarily </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 5.7pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D15 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D20 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D15>
      <P class=3DStyle11><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Helvetica-Bold">290=20
      </SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle11><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Helvetica-Bold"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D17 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D132 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D17>
      <P class=3DStyle9><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The =
Blind=20
      Watchmaker </SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle9><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D602 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D602>
      <P class=3DStyle24=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.25pt 0pt 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt">black =
children=20
      living in Scandinavia. The brown pigment melanin, which is =
synthesized=20
      under the influence of sunlight, makes a screen to protect the =
underlying=20
      tissues from the harmful effects of further sunlight. If a =
suntanned=20
      person moves to a less sunny climate the melanin disappears, and =
the body=20
      is able to benefit from what little sun there is. This can be =
represented=20
      as an instance of the principle of use and disuse: skin goes brown =
when it=20
      is 'used', and fades to white when it is not 'used'. Some tropical =
races,=20
      of course, inherit a thick screen of melanin whether or not they =
are=20
      exposed to sunlight as individuals. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle24=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.1pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.8pt">Now=20
      turn to the other main Lamarckian principle, the idea that such =
acquired=20
      characteristics are then inherited by future generations. All =
evidence=20
      suggests that this idea is simply false, but through most of =
history it=20
      has been believed to be true. Lamarck did not invent it, but =
simply=20
      incorporated the folk wisdom of his time. In some circles it is =
still=20
      believed. My mother had a dog who occasionally affected a limp, =
holding up=20
      one hind leg and hobbling on the other three. A neighbour had an =
older dog=20
      who had unfortunately lost one hind leg in a car accident. She was =

      convinced that her dog must be the father of my mother's dog, the =
evidence=20
      being that he had obviously inherited his limp. Folk wisdom and =
fairy=20
      tales are filled with similar legends. Many people either believe, =
or=20
      would like to believe, in the inheritance of acquired =
characteristics.=20
      Until this century it was the dominant theory of heredity among =
serious=20
      biologists too. Darwin himself believed in it, but it was not a =
part of=20
      his theory of evolution so his name is not linked to it in our =
minds. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle24=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.75pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt">If=20
      you put the inheritance of acquired characteristics together with =
the=20
      principle of use and disuse, you have what looks like a good =
recipe for=20
      evolutionary improvement. It is this recipe that is commonly =
labelled the=20
      Lamarckian theory of evolution. If successive generations toughen =
their=20
      feet by walking barefoot over rough ground, each generation, so =
the theory=20
      goes, will have a slightly tougher skin than the generation =
before. Each=20
      generation gets an advantage over its predecessor. In the end, =
babies will=20
      be born with already toughened feet (which as a matter of fact =
they are,=20
      though for a different reason as we shall see). If successive =
generations=20
      bask in the tropical sun, they will go browner and browner as, =
according=20
      to the Lamarckian theory, each generation will inherit some of the =

      previous generation's tan. In time they will be born black (again =
as a=20
      matter of fact they are, but not for the Lamarckian reason). </P>
      <P class=3DStyle24=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.45pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.65pt">The=20
      legendary examples are the blacksmith's arms and the giraffe's =
neck. In=20
      villages where the blacksmith inherited his trade from his father, =

      grandfather and great grandfather before him, he was thought to =
</P>
      <P class=3DStyle24=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.45pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D383 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 5.3pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Doomed rivals </SPAN></I><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">291 <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.4pt 0pt 4.3pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">inherit the well-trained =
muscles of his=20
      ancestors too. Not just inherit them but add to them through his =
own=20
      exercise, and pass on the improvements to his son. Ancestral =
giraffes with=20
      short necks <BR>desperately needed to reach high leaves on trees. =
They=20
      strove mightily upwards, thereby stretching neck muscles and =
bones. Each=20
      generation ended up with a slightly longer neck than its =
predecessor, and=20
      it passed its head start on to the next generation. All =
evolutionary=20
      advancement, according to the pure Lamarckian theory, follows this =

      pattern. The animal strives for something that it needs. As a =
result the=20
      parts of the body used in the striving grow larger, or otherwise =
change in=20
      an appropriate direction. The change is inherited by the next =
generation=20
      and so the process goes on. This theory has the advantage that it =
is=20
      cumulative - an essential ingredient of any theory of evolution if =
it is=20
      to fulfil its role in our world view, as we have seen. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.55pt 0pt 2.15pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The Lamarckian theory seems to =
have great=20
      emotional appeal, for certain types of intellectual as well as for =
laymen.=20
      I was once approached by a colleague, a celebrated Marxist =
historian and a=20
      most cultivated and well-read man. He understood, he said, that =
the facts=20
      all seemed to be against the Lamarckian theory, but was there =
really no=20
      hope that it might be true? I told him that in my opinion there =
was none,=20
      and he accepted this with sincere regret, saying that for =
ideological=20
      reasons he had wanted Lamarckism to be true. It seemed to offer =
such=20
      positive hopes for the betterment of humanity. George Bernard Shaw =
devoted=20
      one of his enormous Prefaces (in </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Back to Methuselah) to =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">a passionate advocacy of the =
inheritance=20
      of acquired characteristics. His case was based not upon =
biological=20
      knowledge, of which he would cheerfully have admitted he had none. =
It was=20
      based upon an emotional loathing of the implications of Darwinism, =
that=20
      'chapter of accidents': <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 13.4pt 0pt 0.15in; LINE-HEIGHT: 9.75pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">it seems simple, because you do =
not at=20
      first realize all that it involves. But when its whole =
significance dawns=20
      on you, your heart sinks into a heap of sand within you. There is =
a=20
      hideous fatalism about it, a ghastly and damnable reduction of =
beauty and=20
      intelligence, of strength and purpose, of honor and aspiration.=20
      <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.45pt 0pt 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Arthur Koestler was another =
distinguished=20
      man of letters who could not abide what he saw as the implications =
of=20
      Darwinism. As Stephen Gould has sardonically but correctly put it, =

      throughout his last six books Koestler conducted 'a campaign =
against his=20
      own <BR>misunderstanding of Darwinism'. He sought refuge in an =
alternative=20
      which was never entirely clear to me but which can be interpreted =
as an=20
      obscure version of Lamarckism. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.45pt 0pt 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0.5pt"><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">292 </SPAN></B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.3pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Koestler and Shaw were =
individualists who=20
      thought for themselves. Their eccentric views on evolution have =
probably=20
      not been very influential although I do remember, to my shame, =
that my own=20
      appreciation of Darwinism as a teenager was held back for at least =
a year=20
      by Shaw's bewitching rhetoric in </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Back to Methuselah. =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The emotional appeal of =
Lamarckism, and=20
      the accompanying emotional hostility to Darwinism, has at times =
had a more=20
      sinister impact, via powerful ideologies used as a substitute for =
thought.=20
      T. D. Lysenko was a second-rate agricultural plant breeder of no=20
      distinction other than in the field of politics. His =
anti-Mendelian=20
      fanaticism, and his fervent, dogmatic belief in the inheritance of =

      acquired characteristics, would have been harmlessly ignored in =
most=20
      civilized countries. Unfortunately he happened to live in a =
country where=20
      ideology mattered more than scientific truth. In 1940 he was =
appointed=20
      director of the Institute of Genetics of the Soviet Union, and he =
became=20
      immensely influential. His ignorant views on genetics became the =
only ones=20
      allowed to be taught in Soviet schools for a generation. =
Incalculable=20
      damage was done to Soviet agriculture. Many distinguished Soviet=20
      geneticists were banished, exiled or imprisoned. For example, N. =
I.=20
      Vavilov, a geneticist of worldwide reputation, died of =
malnutrition in a=20
      windowless prison cell after a prolonged trial on ludicrously =
trumped up=20
      charges such as 'spying for the British'. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.8pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">It is not possible to prove =
that acquired=20
      characteristics are never inherited. For the same reason we can =
never=20
      prove that fairies do not exist. All we can say is that no =
sightings of=20
      fairies have ever been confirmed, and that such alleged =
photographs of=20
      them as have been produced are palpable fakes. The same is true of =
alleged=20
      human footprints in Texan dinosaur beds. Any categorical statement =
I make=20
      that fairies don't exist is vulnerable to the possibility that, =
one day, I=20
      may see a gossamer-winged little person at the bottom of my =
garden. The=20
      status of the theory of the inheritance of acquired =
characteristics is=20
      similar. Almost all attempts to demonstrate the effect have simply =
failed.=20
      Of those that have apparently succeeded, some have turned out to =
be fakes;=20
      for example, the notorious injection of Indian ink under the skin =
of the=20
      midwife toad, recounted by Arthur Koestler in his book of that =
name. The=20
      rest have failed to be replicated by other workers. Nevertheless, =
just as=20
      somebody may one day see a fairy at the bottom of the garden when =
sober=20
      and in possession of a camera, somebody may one day prove that =
acquired=20
      characteristics can be inherited. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.2pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">There is a little more that can =
be said,=20
      however. Some things </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold">that=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">have never =
been reliably=20
      seen are, nevertheless, believable insofar </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">as </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">they do not call in question =
everything=20
      else that we know. I have </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">seen </SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.2pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D8 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D66 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D8>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold"><IMG height=3D8=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image113.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D66></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D10 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D35 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D10>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold"><IMG height=3D10=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image114.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D35></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D382 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle5 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 3.85pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Doomed rivals =
</SPAN></I><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">293 </SPAN></B><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.15pt 0pt 3.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">no good evidence for the theory =
that=20
      plesiosaurs live today in Loch Ness, but my world view would not =
be=20
      shattered if one were found. I should just be surprised (and =
delighted),=20
      because no plesiosaur fossils are known for the last 60 million =
years and=20
      that seems a long time for a small relict population to survive. =
But no=20
      great scientific principles are at stake. It is simply a matter of =
fact.=20
      On the other hand, science has amassed a good understanding of how =
the=20
      universe ticks, an understanding that works well for an enormous =
range of=20
      phenomena, and certain allegations would be incompatible, or at =
least very=20
      hard to reconcile, with this understanding. For example, this is =
true of=20
      the allegation, sometimes made on spurious biblical grounds, that =
the=20
      universe was created only about 6,000 years ago. This theory is =
not just=20
      unauthenticated. It is incompatible, not only with orthodox =
biology and=20
      geology, but with the physical theory of radioactivity and with =
cosmology=20
      (heavenly bodies more than 6,000 light-years away shouldn't be =
visible if=20
      nothing older than 6,000 years exists; the Milky Way shouldn't be=20
      detectable, nor should any of the 100,000 million other galaxies =
whose=20
      existence modern cosmology acknowledges). </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.1pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">There have been times in the =
history of=20
      science when the whole of orthodox science has been rightly thrown =
over=20
      because of a single awkward fact. It would be arrogant to assert =
that such=20
      overthrows will never happen again. But we naturally, and rightly, =
demand=20
      a higher standard of authentication before accepting a fact that =
would=20
      turn a major and successful scientific edifice upside down, than =
before=20
      accepting a fact which, even if surprising, is readily =
accommodated by=20
      existing science. For a plesiosaur in Loch Ness, I would accept =
the=20
      evidence of my own eyes. If I saw a man levitating himself, before =

      rejecting the whole of physics I would suspect that I was the =
victim of a=20
      hallucination or a conjuring trick. There is a continuum, from =
theories=20
      that probably are not true but easily could be, to theories that =
could=20
      only be true at the cost of overthrowing large edifices of =
<BR>successful=20
      orthodox science. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.05pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Now, where does Lamarckism =
stand in this=20
      continuum? It is usually presented as well over on the 'not true =
but=20
      easily could be' end of the continuum. I want to make a case that, =
while=20
      not in the same class as levitation by the power of prayer, =
Lamarckism, or=20
      more specifically the inheritance of acquired characteristics, is =
closer=20
      to the 'levitation' end of the continuum than to the 'Loch Ness =
monster'=20
      end. The inheritance of acquired characteristics is not one of =
those=20
      things that easily could be true but probably isn't. I shall argue =
that it=20
      could only be true if one of our most cherished and successful =
principles=20
      of embryology is overthrown. Lamarckism therefore needs to be =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.05pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.05pt 0pt 0.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">294 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind WatchmakeT =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.7pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">subjected to more than the =
usual 'Loch=20
      Ness monster' level of scepticism. What, then, is this widely =
accepted and=20
      successful embryological principle that would have to be =
overthrown before=20
      Lamarckism could be accepted? That is going to take a little =
explaining.=20
      The explanation will seem like a digression, but its relevance =
will become=20
      clear <BR>eventually. And remember that this is all before we =
start the=20
      argument that Lamarckism, even if it </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">were </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">true, would still be incapable =
of=20
      explaining the evolution of adaptive complexity. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.15pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The field of discourse, then, =
is=20
      embryology. There has traditionally been a deep divide between two =

      different attitudes to the way single cells turn into adult =
creatures. The=20
      official names for them are preformationism and epigenesis, but in =
their=20
      modern forms I shall call them the blueprint theory and the recipe =
theory.=20
      The early preformationists believed that the adult body was=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">preformed=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">in the single =
cell from=20
      which it was to develop. One of them imagined that he could see in =
his=20
      microscope a little miniature human - a 'homunculus' - curled up =
inside a=20
      sperm (not egg!). Embryonic development, for him, was simply a =
process of=20
      growth. All the bits of the adult body were already there, =
preformed.=20
      Presumably each male homunculus had his own ultraminiature sperms =
in which=20
      his own children were coiled up, and each of them contained his =
coiled up=20
      grandchildren . . . Quite apart from this problem of infinite =
regress,=20
      naive preformationism neglects the fact, which was hardly less =
obvious in=20
      the seventeenth century than now, that children inherit attributes =
from=20
      the mother as well as the father. To be fair, there were other=20
      preformationists called ovists, rather more numerous than the =
'spermists',=20
      who believed that the adult was preformed in the egg rather than =
the=20
      sperm. But ovism suffers from the same two problems as spermism.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.7pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Modern preformationism does not =
suffer=20
      from either of these problems, but it is still wrong. Modern=20
      preformationism - the blueprint theory - holds that the DNA in a=20
      fertilized egg is equivalent to a blueprint of the adult body. A =
blueprint=20
      is a scaled-down miniature of the real thing. The real thing - =
house, car,=20
      or whatever it is - is a threedimensional object, while a =
blueprint is=20
      two-dimensional. You can represent a three-dimensional object such =
as a=20
      building by means of a set of two-dimensional slices: a ground =
plan of=20
      every floor, various elevation views, and so on. This reduction in =

      dimensions is a matter of convenience. Architects could provide =
builders=20
      with matchstick and balsa-wood scale models of buildings in three=20
      dimensions, but a set of two-dimensional models on flat paper - =
blueprints=20
      - is easier to carry around in a briefcase, easier to amend, and =
easier to=20
      work from. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.15pt 0pt 10.3pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">A further reduction to =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">one </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">dimension is necessary if =
blueprints=20
      </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">are =
</SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.15pt 0pt 10.3pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.45pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Doomed rivals </SPAN></I><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">295 <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.1pt 0pt 0.7pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">to be stored in a computer's =
pulse code=20
      and, for example, transmitted by telephone line to another part of =
the=20
      country. This is easily done by receding each two dimensional =
blueprint as=20
      a one-dimensional 'scan'. Television pictures are coded in this =
way for=20
      transmission over the airwaves. Again, the dimensional compression =
is an=20
      essentially trivial coding device. The important point is that =
there is=20
      still one-to-one correspondence between blueprint and building. =
Each bit=20
      of the blueprint corresponds to a matching bit of the building. =
There is a=20
      sense in which the blueprint is a miniaturized 'preformed' =
building,=20
      albeit the miniature may be receded into fewer dimensions than the =

      building has. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.55pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The reason for mentioning the =
reduction=20
      of blueprints to one dimension is, of course, that DNA is a=20
      one-dimensional code. fust as it is theoretically possible to =
transmit a=20
      scale model of a building via a onedimensional telephone line - a=20
      digitized set of blueprints - so it is theoretically possible to =
transmit=20
      a scaled-down body via the onedimensional digital DNA code. This =
doesn't=20
      happen but, if it did, it would be fair to say that modern =
molecular=20
      biology had vindicated the ancient theory of preformationism. Now =
to=20
      consider the other great theory of embryology, epigenesis, the =
recipe or=20
      'cookery book' theory. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.75pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">A recipe in a cookery book is =
not, in any=20
      sense, a blueprint for the cake that will finally emerge from the =
oven.=20
      This is not because the recipe is a one-dimensional string of =
words=20
      whereas the cake is a three-dimensional object. As we have seen, =
it is=20
      perfectly possible, by a scanning procedure, to render a scale =
model into=20
      a one-dimensional code. But a recipe is not a scale model, not a=20
      description of a finished cake, not in any sense a point-for-point =

      representation. It is a set of </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">instructions </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">which, if obeyed in the right =
order, will=20
      result in a cake. A true one-dimensionally coded blueprint of a =
cake would=20
      consist of a series of scans through the cake, as though a skewer =
were=20
      passed through it repeatedly in an orderly sequence across and =
down the=20
      cake. At millimetre intervals the immediate surroundings of the =
skewer's=20
      point would be recorded in code; for instance, the exact =
coordinates=20
      </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">of =
</SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">every currant and crumb would =
be=20
      retrievable from the serial data. There would be strict one-to-one =
mapping=20
      between each bit of the cake and a corresponding bit of the =
blueprint.=20
      Obviously this is nothing like a real recipe. There is no =
one-to-one=20
      mapping between 'bits' of cake and words or letters of the recipe. =
If the=20
      words of the recipe map onto anything, it is not single bits of =
the=20
      finished cake but single steps in the procedure for making a cake. =

      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.8pt 0pt 0.25pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Now, we don't yet understand =
everything,=20
      or even most things, about how animals develop from fertilized =
eggs.=20
      Nevertheless, the </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.8pt 0pt 0.25pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D10 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D18 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D10>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D10 =

      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image115.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D19></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D630 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D377 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D630>
      <P class=3DStyle9 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.7pt">296 <I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle15=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05pt 0pt 1.7pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.75pt">indications are=20
      very strong that the genes are much more like a recipe than like a =

      blueprint. Indeed, the recipe analogy is really rather a good one, =
while=20
      the blueprint analogy, although it is often unthinkingly used in=20
      elementary textbooks, especially recent ones, is wrong in almost =
every=20
      particular. Embryonic development is a process. It is an orderly =
sequence=20
      of events, like the procedure for making a cake, except that there =
are=20
      millions more steps in the process and different steps are going =
on=20
      simultaneously in many different parts of the 'dish'. Most of the =
steps=20
      involve cell multiplication, generating prodigious numbers of =
cells, some=20
      of which die, others of which join up with each other to form =
organs,=20
      tissues and other many-celled structures. As we saw in an earlier =
chapter,=20
      how a <I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">particular=20
      </SPAN></I>cell behaves depends not on the genes that it contains =
- for=20
      all the cells in a body contain the same set of genes - but on =
which=20
      subset of the genes is turned on in that cell. m any one place in =
the=20
      developing body, at any one time during development, only a =
minority of=20
      the genes will be switched on. In different parts of the embryo, =
and at=20
      different times during <SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR></SPAN>development, other sets of =
genes will be=20
      turned on. Precisely which genes are switched on in any one cell =
at any=20
      one time depends on chemical conditions in that cell. This, in =
turn,=20
      depends upon past conditions in that part of the embryo. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle15=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.95pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt">Moreover,=20
      the effect that a gene has when it <I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">is </SPAN></I>turned on =
depends upon=20
      what there is, in the local part of the embryo, to have an effect =
on. A=20
      gene turned on in cells at the base of the spinal cord in the =
third week=20
      of development will have a totally different effect from the same =
gene=20
      turned on in cells of the shoulder in the sixteenth week of =
development.=20
      So, the effect, if any, that a gene has is <I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">not </SPAN></I>a simple =
property of the=20
      gene itself, but is a property of the gene in interaction with the =
recent=20
      history of its local surroundings in the embryo. This makes =
nonsense of=20
      the idea that the genes are anything like a blueprint for a body. =
The same=20
      thing was true, you will remember, of the computer biomorphs. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle15=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.5pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt">There=20
      is no simple one-to-one mapping, then, between genes and bits of =
body, any=20
      more than there is mapping between words of recipe and crumbs of =
cake. The=20
      genes, taken together, can be seen as a set of instructions for =
carrying=20
      out a process, just as the words of a recipe, taken together, are =
a set of=20
      instructions for carrying out a process. The reader may be left =
asking=20
      how, in that case, it is possible for geneticists to make a =
living. How is=20
      it possible ever to speak of, let alone do research on, a gene =
'for' blue=20
      eyes, or a gene 'for' colour blindness? Doesn't the very fact that =

      geneticists can study such single-gene effects suggest that there =
really=20
      is some sort of one-gene/one-bit-of-body </P>
      <P class=3DStyle15=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.5pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D380 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 3.1pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Doomed rivals </SPAN></I><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">297 <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.6pt 0pt 2.15pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">mapping? Doesn't it disprove =
everything I=20
      have been saying about the set of genes being a recipe for =
developing a=20
      body? Well no, it certainly doesn't, and it is important to =
understand=20
      why. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.1pt 0pt 2.15pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Perhaps the best way to see =
this is to go=20
      back to the recipe analogy. It will be agreed that you can't =
divide a cake=20
      up into its component crumbs and say 'This crumb corresponds to =
the first=20
      word in the recipe, this crumb corresponds to the second word in =
the=20
      recipe', etc. In this sense it will be agreed that the whole =
recipe maps=20
      onto the whole cake. But now suppose we change one word in the =
recipe, for=20
      instance, suppose 'baking-powder' is deleted or is changed to =
'yeast'. We=20
      bake 100 cakes according to the new version of the recipe, and 100 =
cakes=20
      according to the old version of the recipe. There is a key =
difference=20
      between the two sets of 100 cakes, and this </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">difference is </SPAN></I><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">due to a oneword difference in =
the=20
      recipes. Although there is no one-to-one mapping from word to =
crumb of=20
      cake, there is one-to-one mapping from word </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">difference to </SPAN></I><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">whole-cake </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">difference. </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">'Baking-powder' does not =
correspond to=20
      any particular part of the cake: its influence affects the rising, =
and=20
      hence the final shape, of the whole cake. If ' bakingpowder' is =
deleted,=20
      or replaced by 'flour', the cake will not rise. If it is replaced =
by=20
      'yeast', the cake will rise but it will taste more like bread. =
There will=20
      be a reliable, identifiable difference between cakes baked =
according to=20
      the original version and the 'mutated' versions of the recipe, =
even though=20
      there is no particular 'bit' of any cake that corresponds to the =
words in=20
      question. This is a good analogy for what happens when a gene =
mutates.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.55pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">An even better analogy, because =
genes=20
      exert quantitative effects and mutations change the quantitative =
magnitude=20
      of those effects, would be a change from '350 degrees' to '450 =
degrees'.=20
      Cakes baked according to the 'mutated', higher-temperature version =
of the=20
      recipe will come out different, not just in one part but =
throughout their=20
      substance, from cakes baked according to the original =
lower-temperature=20
      version. But the analogy is still too simple. To simulate the =
'baking' of=20
      a baby, we should imagine not a single process in a single oven, =
but a=20
      tangle of conveyor belts, passing different parts of the dish =
through 10=20
      million different miniaturized ovens, in series and in parallel, =
each oven=20
      bringing out a different combination of flavours from 10,000 basic =

      ingredients. The point of the cooking analogy, that the genes are =
not a=20
      blueprint but a recipe for a process, comes over from the complex =
version=20
      of the analogy even more strongly than from the simple one. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
2.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">It is time to apply this lesson =
to the=20
      question of the inheritance of acquired characteristics. The thing =
about=20
      building something from a blueprint, as opposed to a recipe, is =
that the=20
      process is </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">reversible.=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">If =
</SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">you </SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle5=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
2.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D629 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D629>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.2pt 0pt 1.45pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">298 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.2pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">have a house, it is easy to =
reconstruct=20
      its blueprint. Just measure all the dimensions of the house and =
scale them=20
      down. Obviously, if the house were to 'acquire' any =
characteristics - say=20
      an interior wall were knocked down to give an open-plan ground =
floor - the=20
      'reverse blueprint' would faithfully record the alteration. Just =
so if the=20
      genes were a description of the adult body. If the genes were a =
blueprint,=20
      it would be easy to imagine any characteristic that a body =
acquired during=20
      its lifetime being faithfully transcribed back into the genetic =
code, and=20
      hence passed into the next generation. The blacksmith's son really =
could=20
      inherit the consequences of his father's exercise. It is because =
the genes=20
      are not a blueprint but a recipe that this is not possible. We can =
no more=20
      imagine acquired characteristics being inherited than we can =
imagine the=20
      following. A cake has one slice cut out of it. A description of =
the=20
      alteration is now fed back into the recipe, and the recipe changes =
in such=20
      a way that the next cake baked according the altered recipe comes =
out of=20
      the oven with one slice already neatly missing. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.8pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Lamarckians are traditionally =
fond of=20
      calluses, so let us use that example. Our hypothetical bank clerk =
had=20
      soft, pampered hands except for a hard callus on the middle finger =
of his=20
      right hand, his writing finger. If generations of his descendants =
all=20
      write a great deal, the Lamarckian expects that genes controlling =
the=20
      development of skin in that region will be altered in such a way =
that=20
      babies come to be bom with the appropriate finger already =
hardened. If the=20
      genes were a blueprint this would be easy. There would be a gene =
'for'=20
      each square millimetre (or appropriate small unit) of skin. The =
whole=20
      surface of the skin of an adult bank clerk would be 'scanned', the =

      hardness of each square millimetre carefully recorded and fed back =
into=20
      the genes 'for' that particular square millimetre, in particular =
the=20
      appropriate genes in his sperms. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.65pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">But the genes are not a =
blueprint. There=20
      is no sense in which there is a gene 'for' each square millimetre. =
There=20
      is no sense in which the adult body could be scanned and its =
description=20
      fed back into the genes. The 'coordinates' of a callus could not =
be=20
      'looked up' in the genetic record and the 'appropriate' genes =
altered.=20
      Embryonic development is a process, in which all working genes=20
      participate; a process which, if correctly followed in the forward =

      direction, will result in an adult body; but it is a process that =
is=20
      inherently, by its very nature, irreversible. The inheritance of =
acquired=20
      characteristics not only </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">doesn't </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">happen: it </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">couldn't </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">happen in any life-form whose =
embryonic=20
      development is epigenetic rather than preformationistic. Any =
biologist=20
      that advocates Lamarckism is, though he may be shocked to hear it, =

      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.65pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.6pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 2.65pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Doomed rivals 299 =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.3pt 0pt 1.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">implicitly advocating an =
atomistic,=20
      deterministic, reductionistic embryology. I didn't want to burden =
the=20
      general reader with that little string of pretentious jargon =
words: I just=20
      couldn't resist the irony, for the biologists who come closest to=20
      sympathizing with Lamarckism today also happen to be particularly =
fond of=20
      using those same cant words in criticizing others. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.6pt 0pt 1.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">This is not to say that, =
somewhere in the=20
      universe, there may not be some alien system of life in which =
embryology=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">is =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">preformationistic; a life-form =
that=20
      really does have 'blueprint genetics', and that really could, =
therefore,=20
      inherit acquired characteristics. All that I have shown so far is =
that=20
      Lamarckism is incompatible with embryology as we know it. My claim =
at the=20
      outset of this chapter was stronger: that, even if acquired=20
      characteristics </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">could=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">be inherited, =
the=20
      Lamarckian theory would still be incapable of explaining adaptive=20
      evolution. This claim is so strong that it is intended to apply to =
all=20
      life-forms, everywhere in the universe. It is based upon two lines =
of=20
      reasoning, one concerned with difficulties over the principle of =
use and=20
      disuse, the other with further problems with the inheritance of =
acquired=20
      characteristics. I shall take these in reverse order. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.6pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The problem with acquired =
characteristics=20
      is basically this. It is </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">all </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">very well inheriting acquired=20
      characteristics, but not all acquired characteristics are =
improvements.=20
      Indeed, the vast majority of them are injuries. Obviously =
evolution is not=20
      going to proceed in the general direction of adaptive improvement =
if=20
      acquired characteristics are inherited indiscriminately: broken =
legs and=20
      smallpox scars being passed down the generations just as much as =
hardened=20
      feet and suntanned skin. Most of the characteristics that any =
machine=20
      acquires as it gets older tend to be the accumulated ravages of =
time: it=20
      wears out. If they were gathered up by some kind of scanning =
process and=20
      fed into the blueprint for the next generation, successive =
generations=20
      would get more and more decrepit. Instead of starting afresh with =
a new=20
      blueprint, each new generation would begin life encumbered and =
scarred=20
      with the accumulated decay and injuries of previous generations.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">This problem is not necessarily =

      insuperable. It is undeniable that some acquired characteristics =
are=20
      improvements, and it is theoretically conceivable that the =
inheritance=20
      mechanism might somehow discriminate the improvements from the =
injuries.=20
      But in wondering how this discrimination might work, we are now =
led to ask=20
      why acquired characteristics sometimes </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">are </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">improvements. Why, for =
instance, do areas=20
      of skin that are used, like the soles of a barefoot runner, become =
thicker=20
      and tougher? On the face of it, it would seem more probable =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D377 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.35pt 0pt 0.5pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">300 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.95pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">that the skin would become =
thinner: on=20
      most machines, parts that </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">are </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">subject to wear and tear become =
thinner,=20
      for the obvious reason that wear removes particles rather than =
adding=20
      them. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.15pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The Darwinian, of course, has a =
ready=20
      answer. Skin that is subject to wear and tear gets thicker, =
because=20
      natural selection in the ancestral past has favoured those =
individuals=20
      whose skin happened to respond to wear and tear in this =
advantageous way.=20
      Similarly, natural selection favoured those members of ancestral=20
      generations who happened to respond to sunlight by going brown. =
The=20
      Darwinian maintains that the only reason even a minority of =
acquired=20
      characteristics are <BR>improvements is that there is an =
underpinning of=20
      past Darwinian selection. In other words, the Lamarckian theory =
can=20
      explain adaptive <BR>improvement in evolution only by, as it were, =
riding=20
      on the back of the Darwinian theory. Given that Darwinian =
selection is=20
      there in the background, to ensure that some acquired =
characteristics are=20
      advantageous, and to provide a mechanism for discriminating the=20
      advantageous from the disadvantageous acquisitions, the =
inheritance of=20
      acquired characteristics might, conceivably, lead to some =
evolutionary=20
      improvement. But the </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">improvement, </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">such as it is, is all due to =
the=20
      Darwinian underpinning. We are forced back to Darwinism to explain =
the=20
      adaptive aspect of evolution. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.95pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The same is true of a rather =
more=20
      important class of acquired improvements, those that we lump =
together=20
      under the heading of learning. During the course of its life, an =
animal=20
      becomes more skilled at the business of making its living. The =
animal=20
      leams what is good for it and what is not. Its brain stores a =
large=20
      library of memories about its world, and about which actions tend =
to lead=20
      to desirable consequences and which to undesirable consequences. =
Much of=20
      an animal's <BR>behaviour therefore comes under the heading of =
acquired=20
      characteristics, and much of this type of acquisition - 'learning' =
-=20
      really does deserve the title of improvement. If parents could =
somehow=20
      transcribe the wisdom of a lifetime's experience into their genes, =
so that=20
      their offspring were born with a library of vicarious experience =
built in=20
      and ready to be drawn upon, those offspring could begin life one =
jump=20
      ahead. Evolutionary progress might indeed speed up, as learned =
skills and=20
      wisdom would automatically be incorporated into the genes. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">But this all presupposes that =
the changes=20
      in behaviour that we call learning are, indeed, improvements. Why=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">should =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">they necessarily be =
improvements? Animals=20
      do, as a matter of fact, learn to do what is good for them, rather =
than=20
      what is bad for them, but why? Animals tend to avoid actions that =
have, in=20
      the past, led to pain. But pain is not a substance. Pain is just =
what the=20
      brain treats as pain. It is a fortunate </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.9pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.15pt 0pt 2.15pt"><I><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Doomed rivals </SPAN></I><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">301 <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.7pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">fact that those occurrences =
that are=20
      treated as painful, for instance violent puncturing of the body =
surface,=20
      also happen to be those occurrences that tend to endanger the =
animal's=20
      survival. But we could easily imagine a race of animals that=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">enjoyed =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">injury and other occurrences =
endangering=20
      their survival; a race of animals whose brain was so constructed =
that it=20
      took pleasure in injury and felt as painful those stimuli, such as =
the=20
      taste of nutritious food, which augur well for their survival. The =
reason=20
      we do not in fact see such masochistic animals in the world is the =

      Darwinian reason that masochistic ancestors, for obvious reasons, =
would=20
      not have survived to leave descendants that inherited their =
masochism. We=20
      could probably, by artificial selection in padded cages, in =
pampered=20
      conditions where survival is assured by teams of vets and minders, =
breed a=20
      race of hereditary masochists. But in nature such masochists would =
not=20
      survive, and this is the fundamental reason why the changes that =
we call=20
      learning tend to be improvements rather than the reverse. We have =
again=20
      arrived at the conclusion that there must be a Darwinian =
underpinning to=20
      ensure that acquired characteristics are advantageous. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.3pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">We now turn to the principle of =
use and=20
      disuse. This principle does seem to work rather well for some =
aspects of=20
      acquired improvements. It is a general rule that does not depend =
upon=20
      specific details. The rule says simply, 'Any bit of the body that =
is=20
      frequently used should grow larger; any bit that is not used =
should=20
      become'smaller or even wither away altogether'. Since we can =
expect that=20
      useful (and therefore presumably used) bits of body in general =
will=20
      benefit by being enlarged, while useless (and therefore presumably =
unused)=20
      bits might as well </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold">not=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">be there at =
all, the=20
      rule does seem to have some general merit. Nevertheless, there is =
a big=20
      problem about the principle of use and disuse. This is that, even =
if there=20
      were no other objection to it, it is much too crude a tool to =
fashion the=20
      exquisitely delicate adaptations that we actually see in animals =
and=20
      plants. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.25pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The eye has been a useful =
example before,=20
      so why not again? Think of all the intricately cooperating working =
parts:=20
      the lens with its clear transparency, its colour correction and =
its=20
      correction for spherical distortion; the muscles that can =
instantly focus=20
      the lens on any target from a few inches to infinity; the iris =
diaphragm=20
      or 'stopping down' mechanism, which fine-tunes the aperture of the =
eye=20
      continuously, like a camera with a built-in lightmeter and fast=20
      special-purpose computer; the retina with its 125 million =
colour-coding=20
      photocells; the fine network of blood vessels that fuels every =
part of the=20
      machine; the even finer network of nerves - the equivalent of =
connecting=20
      wires and electronic chips. Hold all this fine-chiselled =
complexity in=20
      your mind, </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.25pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.25pt 0pt 1.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">302 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.7pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.8pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">and ask yourself whether it =
could have=20
      been put together by the principle of use and disuse. The answer, =
it seems=20
      to me, is an obvious 'no'. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.75pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The lens is transparent and =
corrected=20
      against spherical and chromatic aberration. Could this have come =
about=20
      through sheer use? Can a lens be washed clear by the volume of =
photons=20
      that pour through it? Will it become a better lens because it is =
used,=20
      because light has passed through it? Of course not. Why on earth =
should=20
      it? Will the cells of the retina sort themselves into three=20
      colour-sensitive classes, simply because they are bombarded with =
light of=20
      different colours? Again, why on earth should they? Once the =
focusing=20
      muscles exist, it is true that exercising them will make them grow =
bigger=20
      and stronger; but this will not in itself make images come into =
sharper=20
      focus. The truth is that the principle of use and disuse is =
incapable of=20
      shaping any but the crudest and most unimpressive of adaptations.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Darwinian selection, on the =
other hand,=20
      has no difficulty in explaining every tiny detail. Good eyesight, =
accurate=20
      and true down to pernickity detail, can be a matter of life and =
death for=20
      an animal. A lens, properly focused and corrected against =
aberration, can=20
      make all the difference, for a fast-flying bird like a swift, =
between=20
      catching a fly and smashing into a cliff. A well-modulated iris =
diaphragm,=20
      stopping down rapidly when the sun comes out, can make all the =
difference=20
      between seeing a predator in time to escape and being dazzled for =
a fatal=20
      instant. Any improvement in the effectiveness of an eye, no matter =
how=20
      subtle and no matter how deeply buried in internal tissues, can =
contribute=20
      to the animal's survival and reproductive success, and hence to =
the=20
      propagation of the genes that made the improvement. Therefore =
Darwinian=20
      selection can explain the evolution of the improvement. The =
Darwinian=20
      theory explains the evolution of successful apparatus for =
survival, as a=20
      direct consequence of its very success. The coupling between the=20
      explanation, and that which is to be explained, is direct and =
detailed.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.55pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The Lamarckian theory, on the =
other hand,=20
      relies on a loose and crude coupling: the rule that anything that =
is used=20
      a great deal would be better if it were bigger. This amounts to =
relying on=20
      a correlation between the size of an .organ and its effectiveness. =
If=20
      there is such a correlation, it is surely an exceedingly weak one. =
The=20
      Darwinian theory in effect relies on a correlation between the=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">effectiveness=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">of an organ =
and its=20
      effectiveness: a necessarily perfect correlation! This weakness of =
the=20
      Lamarckian theory does not depend upon detailed facts about the =
particular=20
      forms of life that we see on this planet. It is a general weakness =
that=20
      applies to any kind of adaptive complexity, and I </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.55pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.8pt 0pt 2.65pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Doomed rivals </SPAN></I><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">303 <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 2.4pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">think it must apply to life =
anywhere in=20
      the universe, no matter how alien and strange the details of that =
life may=20
      be. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Our refutation of Lamarckism, =
then, is a=20
      bit devastating. First, its key assumption, that of the =
inheritance of=20
      acquired characteristics, seems to be false in all life-forms that =
we have=20
      studied. Second, it not only is false but it </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">has to </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">be false in any life-form that =
relies=20
      upon an epigenetic ('recipe') rather than a preformationistic=20
      ('blueprint') kind of embryology, and this includes all life-forms =
that we=20
      have studied. Third, even if the assumptions of the Lamarckian =
theory were=20
      true, the theory is in principle, for two quite separate reasons,=20
      incapable of explaining the evolution of serious adaptive =
complexity, not=20
      j,ust on this earth but anywhere in the universe. So, it isn't =
that=20
      Lamarckism is a rival to the Darwinian theory that happens to be =
wrong.=20
      Lamarckism isn't a rival to Darwinism at all. It isn't even a =
serious=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">candidate=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">as an =
explanation for=20
      the evolution of adaptive complexity. It is doomed from the start =
as a=20
      potential rival to Darwinism. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.25pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">There are a few other theories =
that have=20
      been, and even occasionally still are, advanced as alternatives to =

      Darwinian selection. Once again, I shall show that they are not =
really=20
      serious alternatives at all. I shall show (it is really obvious) =
that=20
      these 'alternatives' - 'neutralism', 'mutationism', and so on - =
may or may=20
      not be responsible for some proportion of observed evolutionary =
change,=20
      but they cannot be responsible for </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">adaptive </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">evolutionary change, that is =
for change=20
      in the direction of building up improved devices for survival like =
eyes,=20
      ears, elbow joints, and echo-ranging devices. Of course, large =
quantities=20
      of evolutionary change may be non-adaptive, in which case these=20
      alternative theories may well be important in parts of evolution, =
but only=20
      in the boring parts of evolution, not the parts concerned with =
what is=20
      special about life as opposed to non-life. This is especially =
clear in the=20
      case of the neutralist theory of evolution. This has a long =
history, but=20
      it is particularly easy to grasp in its modern, molecular guise in =
which=20
      it has been promoted largely by the great Japanese geneticist =
Motoo=20
      Kimura, whose English prose style, incidentally, would shame many =
a native=20
      speaker. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.2pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">We have already briefly met the =

      neutralist theory. The idea, you will remember, is that different =
versions=20
      of the same molecule, for instance versions of the haemoglobin =
molecule=20
      differing in their precise <BR>aminoacid sequences, are exactly as =
good as=20
      each other. This means that mutations from one alternative version =
of=20
      haemoglobin to another are </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">neutral </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">as far as natural selection is =
concerned.=20
      Neutralists believe that the vast majority of evolutionary =
changes, at the=20
      level of molecular genetics, are neutral - </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">random </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">with respect to natural =
selection. The=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.2pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.2pt 0pt 2.15pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">304 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 2.15pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">alternative school of =
geneticists, called=20
      selectionists, believe that natural selection is a potent force =
even at=20
      the level of detail </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold">at=20
      </SPAN></B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">every point =
along=20
      molecular chains. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.25pt 0pt 1.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">It is important to distinguish =
two=20
      distinct questions. First is the question that is relevant to this =

      chapter, whether neutralism is an alternative to natural selection =
as an=20
      explanation for adaptative evolution. Second, and quite distinct, =
is the=20
      question whether most of the evolutionary change that actually =
occurs is=20
      adaptive. Given that we are talking about an evolutionary change =
from one=20
      form of a molecule to another, how likely is it that the change =
came about=20
      through natural selection, and how likely is it that it is a =
neutral=20
      change which came about through random drift? Over this second =
question, a=20
      ding-dong battle has raged among molecular geneticists, first one =
side=20
      gaining the upper hand, then the other. But if we happen to be =
focusing=20
      our interest on adaptation - the first question - it is all a =
storm in a=20
      teacup. As far as we are then concerned, a neutral mutation might =
as well=20
      not exist because neither we, nor natural selection, can see it. A =
neutral=20
      mutation </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">isn't =

      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">a mutation at =
all, when=20
      we are thinking about legs and arms and wings and eyes and =
behaviour! To=20
      use the recipe analogy again, the dish will taste the same even if =
some=20
      words of the recipe have 'mutated' to a different print font. As =
far as=20
      those of us who are interested in the final dish are concerned, it =
is=20
      still the same recipe, whether printed like this or =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">like this </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">or </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">like this. </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Molecular geneticists are like =
pernickety=20
      printers. They care about the actual form of the words in which =
recipes=20
      are written down. Natural selection doesn't care, and nor should =
we when=20
      we are talking about the evolution of adaptation. When we are =
concerned=20
      with other aspects of evolution, for instance rates of evolution =
in=20
      different lineages, neutral mutations will be of surpassing =
interest.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.25pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Even the most ardent neutralist =
is quite=20
      happy to agree that natural selection is responsible for all =
adaptation.=20
      All he is saying is that most evolutionary change is not =
adaptation. He=20
      may well be right, although one school of geneticists would not =
agree.=20
      From the sidelines, my own hope is that the neutralists will win, =
because=20
      this will make it so much easier to work out evolutionary =
relationships=20
      and rates of evolution. Everybody on both sides agrees that =
neutral=20
      evolution cannot lead to adaptive improvement, for the simple =
reason that=20
      neutral evolution is, by definition, random; and adaptive =
improvement is,=20
      by definition, non-random. Once again, we have failed to find any=20
      alternative to Darwinian selection, as an explanation for the =
feature of=20
      life that distinguishes it from non-life, namely adaptive =
complexity.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.4pt 0pt 9.85pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">We now come </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">to </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">another historical rival to =
Darwinism =97=20
      the theory </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.4pt 0pt 9.85pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D10 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D51 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D10>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D10 =

      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image116.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D51></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.75pt 0pt 2.65pt"><I><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Doomed rivals </SPAN></I><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">305 <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">of 'mutationism'. It is hard =
for us to=20
      comprehend now but, in the early years of this century when the =
phenomenon=20
      of mutation was first named, it was regarded not as a necessary =
part of=20
      Darwinian theory but as an </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">alternative </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">theory of evolution! There was =
a school=20
      of geneticists called the mutationists, which included such famous =
names=20
      as Hugo de Vries and William Bateson among the early rediscoverers =
of=20
      Mendel's principles of heredity, Wilhelm Johannsen the inventor of =
the=20
      word gene, and Thomas Hunt Morgan the father of the chromosome =
theory of=20
      heredity. De Vries in particular was impressed by the magnitude of =
the=20
      change that mutation can wreak, and he thought that new species =
always=20
      originated from single major mutations. He and Johannsen believed =
that=20
      most variation </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">within=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">species was =
non-genetic.=20
      All the mutationists believed that selection had at best a minor=20
      weeding-out role to play in evolution. The really creative force =
was=20
      mutation itself. Mendelian genetics was thought of, not as the =
central=20
      plank of Darwinism that it is today, but as antithetical to =
Darwinism.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.45pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">It is extremely hard for the =
modern mind=20
      to respond to this idea with anything but mirth, but we must =
beware of=20
      repeating the patronizing tone of Bateson himself: 'We go to =
Darwin for=20
      his incomparable collection of facts (but. ..] for us he speaks no =
more=20
      with philosophical authority. We read his scheme of Evolution as =
we would=20
      those of Lucretius or Lamarck.' And again, 'the transformation of =
masses=20
      of populations by imperceptible steps guided by selection is, as =
most of=20
      us now see, so inapplicable to the fact that we can only marvel =
both at=20
      the want of penetration displayed by the advocates of such a =
proposition,=20
      and at the forensic skill by which it was made to appear =
acceptable even=20
      for a time.' It was above all R. A. Fisher who turned the tables =
and=20
      showed that, far from being antithetical to Darwinism, Mendelian=20
      paniculate heredity was actually essential to it. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.25pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Mutation is necessary for =
evolution, but=20
      how could anybody ever have thought it was sufficient? =
Evolutionary change=20
      is, to a far greater extent than chance alone would expect,=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">improvement.=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The problem =
with=20
      mutation as the sole evolutionary force is simply stated: how on =
earth is=20
      mutation supposed to </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">'know' </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">what will be good for the =
animal and what=20
      will not? Of all possible changes that might occur to an existing =
complex=20
      mechanism like an organ, the vast majority will make it worse. =
Only a tiny=20
      minority of changes will make it better. Anybody who wants to =
argue that=20
      mutation, without selection, is the driving force of evolution, =
must=20
      explain how it comes about that mutations tend to be for the =
better. By=20
      what mysterious, built-in wisdom does the body choose to mutate=20
      </SPAN><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">in =
</SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the direction of getting =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.25pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D11 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D52 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D11>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D11 =

      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image117.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D52></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D377 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle9 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.2pt 0pt 0.7pt">306 =
<I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle24 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.95pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt">better,=20
      rather than getting worse? You will observe that this is really =
the same=20
      question, in another guise, as we posed for Lamarckism. The =
mutationists,=20
      needless to say, never answered it. The odd thing is that the =
question=20
      hardly seems to have occurred to them. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle24=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt">Nowadays,=20
      and unfairly, this seems all the more absurd to us because we are =
brought=20
      up to believe that mutations are 'random'. If mutations are =
random, then,=20
      by definition, they cannot be biased towards improvement. But the=20
      mutationist school did not, of course, regard mutations as random. =
They=20
      thought that the body had a built-in tendency to change in certain =

      directions rather than others, though they left open the question =
of how=20
      the body 'knew' what changes would be good for it in the future. =
While we=20
      write this off as mystical nonsense, it is important for us to be =
clear=20
      exactly what we mean when we say that mutation is random. There is =

      randomness and randomness, and many people confuse different =
meanings of=20
      the word. There are, in truth, many respects in which mutation is =
not=20
      random. All I would insist on is that these respects do <I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">not </SPAN></I>include =
anything=20
      equivalent to anticipation of what would make life better for the =
animal.=20
      And something equivalent to anticipation would indeed be needed if =

      mutation, without selection, were to be used to explain evolution. =
It is=20
      instructive to look a little further at the senses in which =
mutation is,=20
      and is not, random. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle24=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.6pt">The=20
      first respect in which mutation is non-random is this. Mutations =
are=20
      caused by definite physical events; they don't just spontaneously =
happen.=20
      They are induced by so-called 'mutagens' (dangerous because they =
often=20
      start cancers): X-rays, cosmic rays, radioactive substances, =
various=20
      chemicals, and even other genes called 'mutator genes'. Second, =
not all=20
      genes in any species are equally likely to mutate. Every locus on =
the=20
      chromosomes has its own characteristic <I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">mutation rate. </SPAN></I>For =
instance,=20
      the rate at which mutation creates the gene for the disease =
Huntington's=20
      chorea (similar to St Vitus's Dance), which kills people in early =
middle=20
      age, is about 1 in 200,000. The corresponding rate for =
achondroplasia (the=20
      familiar dwarf syndrome, characteristic of basset hounds and =
dachsunds, in=20
      which the arms and legs are too short for the body) is about 10 =
times as=20
      high. These rates are measured under normal conditions. If =
mutagens like=20
      X-rays are present, all normal mutation rates are boosted. Some =
parts of=20
      the chromosome are so-called 'hot spots' with a high turnover of =
genes, a=20
      locally very high mutation rate. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle42=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.6pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt">Third,=20
      at each locus on the chromosomes, whether it is a hot spot =
<B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">or </SPAN></B>not, mutations in =
certain=20
      directions can be more likely than mutations in the reverse =
direction.=20
      This gives rise <B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">to =
</SPAN></B>the=20
      phenomenon known <B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">as=20
      </SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle42=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.6pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D380 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.65pt 0pt 2.9pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Doomed rivals </SPAN></I><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">307 <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 2.4pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">'mutation pressure' which can =
have=20
      evolutionary consequences. Even if, for instance, two forms of the =

      haemoglobin molecule. Form 1 and Form 2, are selectively neutral =
in the=20
      sense that both are equally good at carrying oxygen in the blood, =
it could=20
      still be that mutations from 1 to 2 are commoner than reverse =
mutations=20
      from 2 to 1. In this case, mutation pressure will tend to make =
Form 2=20
      commoner than Form 1. Mutation pressure is said to be zero at a =
given=20
      chromosomal locus, if the forward mutation rate at that locus is =
exactly=20
      balanced by the backward mutation rate. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.7pt 0pt 1.45pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">We can now see that the =
question of=20
      whether mutation is really random is not a trivial question. Its =
answer=20
      depends on what we understand random to mean. If you take 'random=20
      mutation' to mean that mutations are not influenced by external =
events,=20
      then X-rays disprove the contention that mutation is random. If =
you think=20
      'random mutation' implies that all genes are equally likely to =
mutate,=20
      then hot spots show that mutation is not random. If you think =
'random=20
      mutation' implies that at all chromosomal loci the mutation =
pressure is=20
      zero, then once again mutation is not random. It is only if you =
define=20
      'random' as meaning 'no general bias towards bodily improvement' =
that=20
      mutation is truly random. All three of the kinds of real =
nonrandomness we=20
      have considered are powerless to move evolution in the direction =
of=20
      adaptive improvement as opposed to any other (functionally) =
'random'=20
      direction. There is a fourth kind of non-randomness, of which this =
is also=20
      true but slightly less obviously so. It will be necessary to spend =
a=20
      little time on this because it is still muddling even some modern=20
      biologists. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.55pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">There are people for whom =
'random' would=20
      have the following meaning, in my opinion a rather bizarre =
meaning. I=20
      quote from two opponents (P. Saunders and M-W. Ho) of Darwinism, =
on their=20
      conception of what Darwinians believe about 'random mutation': =
'The=20
      neo-Darwinian concept of random variation carries with it the =
major=20
      fallacy that everything conceivable is possible'. </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">'All </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">changes are held to be possible =
and all=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">equally =
likely'=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">(my emphasis). =
Far from=20
      holding this belief, I don't see how you would begin to set about =
making=20
      such a belief even </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">meaningfuD. </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">What could it possibly mean to =
hold that=20
      'all' changes are equally likely? </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">All </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">changes? In order for two or =
more things=20
      to be 'equally likely', it is necessary that those things should =
be=20
      definable as discrete events. For instance, we can say 'Heads and =
Tails=20
      are equally likely', because Heads and Tails are two discrete =
events. But=20
      'all possible' changes to an animal's body are not discrete events =
of this=20
      type. Take the two possible events: 'Cow's tail lengthens by one =
inch';=20
      and 'Cow's tail lengthens by two inches'. Are these two separate=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.55pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.4pt 0pt 0.95pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">308 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.2pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">events, and therefore 'equally =
likely'?=20
      Or are they just quantitative variants of the same event? =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.75pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">It is clear that a kind of =
caricature of=20
      a Darwinian has been set up, whose notion of randomness is an =
absurd, if=20
      not actually meaningless, extreme. It took me a while to =
understand this=20
      caricature, for it was so foreign to the way of thinking of the =
Darwinians=20
      that I know. But I think I do now understand it, and I shall try =
to=20
      explain it, as I think it helps us to understand what lies behind =
quite a=20
      lot of alleged opposition to Darwinism. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.7pt 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Variation and selection work =
together to=20
      produce evolution. The Darwinian says that variation is random in =
the=20
      sense that it is not directed towards improvement, and that the =
tendency=20
      towards improvement in evolution comes from selection. We can =
imagine a=20
      kind of continuum of evolutionary doctrines, with Darwinism at one =
end and=20
      Mutationism at the other. The extreme mutationist believes that =
selection=20
      plays no role in evolution. The direction of evolution is =
determined by=20
      the direction of the mutations that are offered. For instance, =
suppose we=20
      take the enlargement of the human brain that has occurred during =
the last=20
      few million years of our evolution. The Darwinian says that the =
variation=20
      that was offered up by mutation for selection included some =
individuals=20
      with smaller brains and some individuals with larger brains; =
selection=20
      favoured the latter. The mutationist says that there was a bias in =
favour=20
      of larger brains in the variation that was offered up by mutation; =
there=20
      was no selection (or no need for selection) after variation was =
offered=20
      up; brains got bigger because mutational change was biased in the=20
      direction of bigger brains. To summarize the point: in evolution =
there was=20
      a bias in favour of larger brains; this bias could have come from=20
      selection alone (the Darwinian view) or from mutation alone (the=20
      mutationist view); we can imagine a continuum between these two =
points of=20
      view, almost a kind of trade-off between the two possible sources =
of=20
      evolutionary bias. A middle view would be that there was some bias =
in=20
      mutations towards enlargement of the brain, and that selection =
increased=20
      the bias in the population that survived. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.3pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The element of caricature comes =
in the=20
      portrayal of what the Darwinian means when he says that there is =
no bias=20
      in the mutational variation that is offered up for selection. To =
me, as a=20
      real-life Darwinian, it means only that mutation is not =
systematically=20
      biased in the direction of adaptive improvement. But to the=20
      larger-than-life caricature of a Darwinian, it means that all =
conceivable=20
      changes are 'equally likely'. Setting aside the logical =
impossibility of=20
      such a belief, already noted, the caricature of a Darwinian is =
thought to=20
      believe that </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.3pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D383 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle22 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.3pt 0pt 1.45pt"><I><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Doomed rivals </SPAN></I>309 =
<SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle22=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.45pt 0pt 1.2pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt">the =
body is=20
      infinitely malleable clay, ready to be shaped by all-powerful =
selection=20
      into any form that selection might favour. It is important to =
understand=20
      the difference between the real-life Darwinian and the caricature. =
We=20
      shall do so in terms of a particular example, the difference =
between the=20
      flight techniques of bats and of angels. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle22=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.8pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt">Angels=20
      are always portrayed as having wings sprouting from their backs, =
leaving=20
      their arms unencumbered by feathers. Bats, on the other hand, =
along with=20
      birds and pterodactyls, have no independent arms. Their ancestral =
arms=20
      have become incorporated into wings, and cannot' be used, or can =
only be=20
      used very clumsily, for other purposes such as picking up food. We =
shall=20
      now listen in on a conversation between a real-life Darwinian and =
an=20
      extreme caricature of a Darwinian. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle22=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 15.55pt 0pt 0.15in; LINE-HEIGHT: =
9.9pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Real-life. </SPAN></I>I wonder =
why bats=20
      didn't evolve wings like angels. You'd think that they could use a =
free=20
      pair of arms. Mice use their arms all the time for picking up food =
and=20
      nibbling it, and bats look terribly clumsy on the ground without =
arms. I=20
      suppose one answer might be that mutation never provided the =
necessary=20
      variation. There just never were any mutant ancestral bats that =
had wing=20
      buds sticking out of the middle <B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">of </SPAN></B>their backs. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle22=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 14pt 0pt 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
9.85pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Caricature. =
</SPAN></I>Nonsense.=20
      Selection is everything. If bats haven't got wings like angels, =
this can=20
      only mean that selection didn't favour wings like angels. There =
certainly=20
      were mutant bats with wing buds sticking out of the middle of =
their backs,=20
      but selection just didn't favour them. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle22=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 20.8pt 0pt 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
9.85pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Real-life. </SPAN></I>Well, I =
quite=20
      agree that selection might not have favoured them if they <I><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">had </SPAN></I>sprouted. For =
one thing=20
      they would have increased the weight of the whole animal, and =
surplus=20
      weight is a luxury no aircraft can afford. But surely you don't =
think=20
      that, <I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">whatever=20
      </SPAN></I>selection might in principle favour, mutation will =
always come=20
      up with the necessary variation? </P>
      <P class=3DStyle22 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 13.45pt 0pt =
10.1pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Caricature. =
</SPAN></I>Certainly I do.=20
      Selection is everything. Mutation is random. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle22=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 11.2pt 0pt 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
9.85pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Real-life. </SPAN></I>Well =
yes, mutation=20
      is random, but this only means that it can't see into the future =
and plan=20
      what would be good for the animal. It doesn't mean that absolutely =

      <I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">anything =
</SPAN></I>is=20
      possible. Why do you think that no animal breathes fire out of its =

      nostrils like a dragon, for instance? Wouldn't it be useful for =
catching=20
      and cooking prey? </P>
      <P class=3DStyle22=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 16pt 0pt 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 9.8pt"><I><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Caricature. </SPAN></I>That's =
easy.=20
      Selection is everything. Animals don't breathe fire, because it =
wouldn't=20
      pay them to do so. Fire-breathing mutants were eliminated by =
natural=20
      selection, perhaps because making fire was too costly in energy. =
</P>
      <P class=3DStyle22=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 16pt 0pt 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 9.8pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 8.5pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D377 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D377 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D377>
      <P class=3DStyle43><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">310=20
      </SPAN></B><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind =
Watchmaker=20
      </SPAN></I><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: =
9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle43 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 227.6pt 0pt =
0.15in"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Real-life. </SPAN></I><I><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle43 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 220pt 0pt =
10.55pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Caricature. =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle43 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 227.85pt 0pt =
10.55pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Real-life. </SPAN></I><I><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle43 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 220pt 0pt =
10.55pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Caricature. =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle43 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 227.85pt 0pt =
10.55pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Real-life. </SPAN></I><I><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle43 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 220.25pt 0pt =
10.3pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Caricature. =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle43 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 227.85pt 0pt =
10.55pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Real-life. </SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle43 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 220pt 0pt =
10.55pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Caricature. =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle43 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 227.85pt 0pt =
10.55pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Real-life. </SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle43 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 215.55pt 0pt =
10.3pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Mutationist. </SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle43 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 215.55pt 0pt 10.3pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D605 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D377 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D605>
      <P class=3DStyle22=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 6.1pt 0pt 57.35pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 9.95pt">I =
don't believe=20
      there ever were fire-breathing mutants. And <B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">if </SPAN></B>there had been, =
presumably=20
      they would have been in grave danger of burning themselves! </P>
      <P class=3DStyle22 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.35pt 0pt =
57.35pt">Nonsense. If that=20
      was the only problem, selection would have favoured the evolution =
of=20
      asbestos-lined nostrils. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle22=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 16.3pt 0pt 57.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 9.95pt">I =
don't believe=20
      any mutation ever produced asbestos-lined nostrils. I don't =
believe mutant=20
      animals could secrete asbestos, any more than mutant cows could =
jump over=20
      the moon. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle22=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 9.55pt 0pt 57.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.1pt">Any=20
      moon-jumping mutant cow would promptly be eliminated by natural =
selection.=20
      There's no oxygen up there you know. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle22 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 27.9pt 0pt 57.1pt">I'm =
surprised you=20
      don't postulate mutant cows with genetically determined =
space-suits and=20
      oxygen masks. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle22=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3.8pt 0pt 57.35pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 9.9pt">Good =
point!=20
      Well, I suppose the real explanation must be that it just wouldn't =
pay=20
      cows to jump over the moon. And we mustn't forget the energetic =
cost of=20
      reaching escape velocity. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle22 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 162.8pt 0pt 56.9pt">This =
is absurd.=20
      </P>
      <P class=3DStyle22 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 6.7pt 0pt 57.35pt">You are =
obviously=20
      not a true Darwinian. What are you, <B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">some </SPAN></B>kind of =
crypto-mutationist=20
      deviationist? </P>
      <P class=3DStyle22 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 31.05pt 0pt 57.1pt">If you =
think that,=20
      you should meet a real mutationist. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle22=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 4.4pt 0pt 57.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 9.9pt">Is this =
a=20
      Darwinian in-group argument, or can anyone join in? The trouble =
with both=20
      of you is that you give far too much prominence to selection. All =
that=20
      selection can do is weed out gross deformities and freaks. It =
can't=20
      produce really constructive evolution. Go back to the evolution of =
bat=20
      wings. What really happened is that in an ancient population of=20
      ground-dwelling animals, mutations started turning up with =
elongated=20
      fingers and webs of skin between. As the generations went by, =
these=20
      mutations became more and more frequent until, eventually, the =
whole=20
      population had wings. It had nothing to do with selection. There =
was just=20
      this built-in tendency in the ancestral bat constitution to evolve =
wings.=20
      </P>
      <P class=3DStyle22 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 19.85pt 0pt 57.35pt">Rank =
mysticism!=20
      Get back in the last century where you belong. <SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle22=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.1pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt">I=20
      hope I am not being presumptuous when I take it that the reader's=20
      sympathies are with neither the Mutationist nor with the =
caricature of a=20
      Darwinian. I assume that the reader agrees with the real-life =
Darwinian,=20
      as, <B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">of =
</SPAN></B>course, do I.=20
      The caricature does not really exist. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle22=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.1pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D41 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D53 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D41>
      <P class=3DStyle22=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 9.8pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.45pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Real-life &amp; Caricature=20
      </SPAN></I>(in unison). </P>
      <P class=3DStyle22=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 9.8pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.45pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D9 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D73 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D9>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 8.5pt; COLOR: =
black"><IMG=20
      height=3D9=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image118.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D73></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 8.5pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D380 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.55pt 0pt 3.35pt"><I><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Doomed rivals </SPAN></I><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">311 <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05pt 0pt 2.4pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Unfortunately some people =
</SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">think </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">he exists, and think that, =
since they=20
      disagree with him, they are disagreeing with Darwinism itself. =
There is a=20
      school of biologists who have taken to saying something like the=20
      following. The trouble with Darwinism is that it neglects the =
constraints=20
      imposed by embryology. Darwinians (this is where the caricature =
comes in)=20
      think that, if selection would favour some conceivable =
evolutionary=20
      change, then the necessary mutational variation will turn out to =
be=20
      available. Mutational change in any direction is equally likely: =
selection=20
      provides the only bias. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1pt 0pt 1.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">But any real-life Darwinian =
would=20
      acknowledge that, although any gene on any chromosome may mutate =
at any=20
      time, the consequences of mutation on </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">bodies </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">are severely limited by the =
processes of=20
      embryology. If I ever doubted this (I didn't), my doubts would =
have been=20
      dispelled by my biomorph computer simulations. You can't just =
postulate a=20
      mutation 'for' sprouting wings in the middle of the back. Wings, =
or=20
      anything else, can only evolve if the process of development =
allows them=20
      to. Nothing magically 'sprouts'. It has to be made by the =
processes of=20
      embryonic development. Only a minority of the things that =
conceivably=20
      could evolve are actually permitted by the status quo of existing=20
      developmental processes. Because of the way arms develop, it is =
possible=20
      for mutations to increase the length of fingers and cause webs of =
skin to=20
      grow between them. But there may not be anything in the embryology =
of=20
      backs that lends itself to 'sprouting' angel wings. Genes can =
mutate till=20
      they are blue in the face, but no mammal will ever sprout wings =
like an=20
      angel unless mammalian embryological processes are susceptible to =
this=20
      kind of change. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.2pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Now as long as we don't know =
all the ins=20
      and outs of how embryos develop, there is room for disagreement =
over how=20
      likely it is that particular imagined mutations have or have not =
ever=20
      existed. It might turn out, for instance, that there is nothing in =

      mammalian embryology to forbid angel wings, and that the =
caricature=20
      Darwinian was right, in this </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">particular </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">case, to suggest that angel =
wing-buds=20
      arose but were not favoured by selection. Or it might turn out =
that when=20
      we know more about embryology we shall see that angel wings were =
always a=20
      nonstarter, and that therefore selection never had a chance to =
favour=20
      them. There is a third possibility, which we should list for =
completeness,=20
      that embryology never allowed the possibility of angel wings and =
that=20
      selection would never have favoured them even if it had. But what =
we must=20
      insist on is that we can't afford to ignore the constraints on =
evolution=20
      that embryology imposes. All serious Darwinians would agree about =
this,=20
      yet some people portray Darwinians as denying it. It turns out =
that people=20
      who make a lot of noise about 'developmental </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.2pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D377 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.25pt 0pt 0.5pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">312 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 20.05pt 0pt 0.5pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">constraints' as an alleged =
anti-Darwinian=20
      force are confusing Darwinism with the caricature of Darwinism =
that I=20
      parodied above. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">This all began with a =
discussion over=20
      what is meant when we say that mutation is 'random'. I listed =
three=20
      respects in which mutation is not random: it is induced by X-rays, =
etc.;=20
      mutation rates are different for different genes; and forward =
mutation=20
      rates do not have to equal backward mutation rates. To this, we =
have now=20
      added a fourth respect in which mutation is not random. Mutation =
is=20
      non-random in the sense that it can only make alterations to=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">existing=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">processes of =
embryonic=20
      development. It cannot conjure, out of thin air, any conceivable =
change=20
      that selection might favour. The variation that is available for =
selection=20
      is constrained by the processes of embryology, as they actually =
exist.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.25pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">There is a fifth respect in =
which=20
      mutation </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">might =

      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">have been =
nonrandom. We=20
      can imagine (just) a form of mutation that was systematically =
biased in=20
      the direction of improving the animal's adaptedness to its life. =
But=20
      although we can imagine it, nobody has ever come close to =
suggesting any=20
      means by which this bias could come about. It is only in this =
fifth=20
      respect, the 'mutationist' respect, that the true, real-life =
Darwinian=20
      insists that mutation is random. Mutation is not systematically =
biased in=20
      the direction of adaptive improvement, and no mechanism is known =
(to put=20
      the point mildly) that could guide mutation in directions that are =

      non-random in this fifth sense. Mutation is random with respect to =

      adaptive advantage, although it is non-random in all sorts of =
other=20
      respects. It is selection, and only selection, that directs =
evolution in=20
      directions that are non-random with respect to advantage. =
Mutationism is=20
      not just wrong in fact. It never could have been right. It is not =
in=20
      principle capable of <BR>explaining the evolution of improvement.=20
      Mutationism belongs with Lamarckism, not as a disproved rival to =
Darwinism=20
      but as no rival at all. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.35pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The same is true of my next =
alleged rival=20
      to Darwinian selection, championed by the Cambridge geneticist =
Gabriel=20
      Dover under the odd name 'molecular drive' (since everything is =
made of=20
      molecules it is not obvious why Dover's hypothetical process =
should=20
      deserve the name </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">molecular </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">drive any more than any other=20
      evolutionary process; it reminds me of a man I knew who complained =
of a=20
      gastric stomach, and worked things out using his mental brain). =
Motoo=20
      Kimura and the other proponents of the neutralist theory of =
evolution do=20
      not, as we saw, make any false claims for their theory. They have =
no=20
      illusions about random drift being a rival to natural selection as =
an=20
      explanation for adaptive evolution. They recognize that only =
natural=20
      selection can </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.35pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.7pt 0pt 2.9pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Doomed rivals </SPAN></I><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">313 <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05pt 0pt 2.15pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN =

      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">drive evolution in adaptive =
directions.=20
      Their claim is simply that a lot of evolutionary change (as a =
molecular=20
      geneticist sees evolutionary change) is not adaptive. Dover makes =
no such=20
      modest claims for his theory. He thinks that he can explain=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">all =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">of evolution without natural =
selection,=20
      although he generously concedes that there may be </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">some </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">truth in natural selection as =
well!=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.55pt 0pt 1.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Throughout this book, our first =
recourse=20
      when considering such matters has been to the example of the eye, =
although=20
      it has, of course, been only a representative of the large set of =
organs=20
      that are too complex and well designed to have come about by =
chance. Only=20
      natural selection, I have repeatedly argued, even comes close to =
offering=20
      a plausible explanation for the human eye and comparable organs of =
extreme=20
      perfection and complexity. Fortunately, Dover has explicitly risen =
to the=20
      challenge, and has offered his own explanation of the evolution of =
the=20
      eye. Assume, he says, that 1,000 steps of evolution are needed to =
evolve=20
      the eye from nothing. This means that a sequence of 1,000 genetic =
changes=20
      were needed to transform a bare patch of skin into an eye. This =
seems to=20
      me to be an acceptable assumption for the sake of argument. In the =
terms=20
      of Biomorph Land, it means that the bare-skin animal is 1,000 =
genetic=20
      steps distant from the eyed animal. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Now, how do we account for the =
fact that=20
      just the right set of 1,000 steps were taken to result in the eye =
as we=20
      know it? Natural selection's explanation is well known. Reducing =
it to its=20
      simplest form, at each one of the 1,000 steps, mutation offered a =
number=20
      of alternatives, only one of which was favoured because it aided =
survival.=20
      The 1,000 steps of evolution represent 1,000 successive choice =
points, at=20
      each of which most of the alternatives led to death. The adaptive=20
      complexity of the modem eye is the end-product of 1,000 successful =

      unconscious 'choices'. The species has followed a particular path =
through=20
      the labyrinth of all possibilities. There were 1,000 branch-points =
along=20
      the path, and at each one the survivors were the ones that =
happened to=20
      take the turning that led to improved eyesight. The wayside is =
littered=20
      with the dead bodies of the failures who took the wrong turning at =
each=20
      one of the 1,000 successive choice points. The eye that we know is =
the=20
      end-product of a sequence of 1,000 successful selective 'choices'. =

      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">That was (one way of =
expressing) natural=20
      selection's explanation of the evolution of the eye in 1,000 =
steps. Now,=20
      what of Dover's explanation? Basically, he argues that it wouldn't =
have=20
      mattered which choice the lineage took at each step: it would=20
      retrospectively have found a use for the organ that resulted. Each =
step=20
      that the lineage took, according to him, was a random step. At =
Step 1, for=20
      example, a random mutation spread through the species. Since the =
newly=20
      evolved charac- </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 3pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D627 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D377 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D627>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.2pt 0pt 1.2pt"><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">314 </SPAN></B><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">teristic was functionally =
random, it=20
      didn't aid the animals' survival. So the species searched the =
world for a=20
      new place or new way of life in which they could use this new =
random=20
      feature that had been imposed upon their bodies. Having found a =
piece of=20
      environment that suited the random part of their bodies, they =
lived there=20
      for a while, until a new random mutation arose and spread through =
the=20
      species. Now the species had to scour the world for a new place or =
way of=20
      life where they could live with their new random bit. When they =
found it.=20
      Step 2 was completed. Now the Step 3 random mutation spread =
through the=20
      species, and so on for 1,000 steps, at the end of which the eye as =
we know=20
      it had been formed. Dover points out that the human eye happens to =
use=20
      what we call 'visible' light rather than infrared. But if random =
processes=20
      had happened to impose an infrared sensitive eye upon us, we =
would,=20
      doubtless, have made the most of it, and found a way of life that=20
      exploited infrared rays to the full. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">At first glance this idea has a =
certain=20
      seductive plausibility, but only at a very brief first glance. The =

      seductiveness comes from the neatly symmetrical way in which =
natural=20
      selection is turned on its head. Natural selection, in its most =
simple=20
      form, assumes that the environment is imposed upon the species, =
and those=20
      genetic variants best fitted to that environment survive. The =
environment=20
      is imposed, and the species evolves to fit it. Dover's theory =
turns this=20
      on its head. It is the nature of the species that is 'imposed', in =
this=20
      case by the vicissitudes of mutation, and other internal genetic =
forces in=20
      which he has a special interest. The species then locates that =
member of=20
      the set of all environments that best fits its imposed nature. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
1.25pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">But the seductiveness of the =
symmetry is=20
      superficial indeed. The wondrous cloud-cuckooism of Dover's idea =
is=20
      displayed in all its glory the moment we begin to think in terms =
of=20
      numbers. The essence of his scheme is that, at each of the 1,000 =
steps, it=20
      didn't matter which way the species turned. Each new innovation =
that the=20
      species came up with was functionally random, and the species then =
found=20
      an environment to suit it. The implication is that the species=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">would have =
found=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">a suitable =
environment,=20
      no matter which branch it had taken at every fork in the way. Now =
just=20
      think how many possible environments this lets us in for =
postulating.=20
      There were 1,000 branch points. If each branch point was a mere=20
      bifurcation (as opposed to a 3-way or 18-way branch, a =
conservative=20
      assumption), the total number of livable environments that must, =
in=20
      principle, exist, in order to allow Dover's scheme to work, is 2 =
to the=20
      power 1,000 (the first branch gives two pathways; then each of =
those=20
      branches into two, making four in all; then each of these =
branches, giving=20
      8, then 16, 32, 64,... all the way </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
1.25pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D380 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle5 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 2.65pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Doomed rivals =
</SPAN></I><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">315 </SPAN></B><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.45pt 0pt 1.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0.5pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">to 2</SPAN>1<SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">'000). This number may be =
written as a 1=20
      with 301 noughts after it. It is far far greater than the total =
number of=20
      atoms in the entire universe. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.85pt 0pt 1.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Dover's alleged rival to =
natural=20
      selection could never work, not just never in a million years but =
never in=20
      a million times longer than the universe has existed, never in a =
million=20
      universes each lasting a million times as long again. Notice that =
this=20
      conclusion is not materially affected if we change Dover's initial =

      assumption that 1,000 steps would be needed to make an eye. If we =
reduce=20
      it to only 100 steps, which is probably an underestimate, we still =

      conclude that the set of possible livable environments that must =
be=20
      waiting in the wings, as it were, to cope with whatever random =
steps the=20
      lineage might take, is more than a million million million million =

      million. This is a smaller number than the previous one, but it =
still=20
      means that the vast majority of Dover's 'environments' waiting in =
the=20
      wings would each have to be made of less than a single atom. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.1pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">It is worth explaining why the =
theory of=20
      natural selection is not susceptible to a symmetrical destruction =
by a=20
      version of the largenumbers argument'. In Chapter 3 we thought of =
all real=20
      and conceivable animals as sitting in a gigantic hyperspace. We =
are doing=20
      a similar thing here, but simplifying it by considering =
evolutionary=20
      branch points as 2-way, rather than 18-way branches. So the set of =
all=20
      possible animals that might have evolved in 1,000 evolutionary =
steps are=20
      perched on a gigantic tree, which branches and branches so that =
the total=20
      number of final twigs is 1 followed by 301 noughts. Any actual=20
      evolutionary history can be represented as a particular pathway =
through=20
      this hypothetical tree. Of all conceivable evolutionary pathways, =
only a=20
      minority actually ever happened. We can think of most of this =
'tree of all=20
      possible animals' as hidden in the darkness of non-existence. Here =
and=20
      there, a few trajectories through the darkened tree are =
illuminated. These=20
      are the evolutionary pathways that actually happened, and, =
numerous as=20
      these illuminated branches are, they are still an infinitesimal =
minority=20
      of the set of all branches. Natural selection is a process that is =
capable=20
      of picking its way through the tree of all conceivable animals, =
and=20
      finding just that minority of pathways that are viable. The theory =
of=20
      natural selection cannot be attacked by the kind of large-numbers =
argument=20
      with which I attacked Dover's theory, because it is of the essence =
of the=20
      theory of natural selection that it is continually cutting down =
most of=20
      the branches of the tree. That is precisely what natural selection =
does.=20
      It picks its way, step by step, through the tree of all =
conceivable=20
      animals, avoiding the almost infinitely large majority of sterile =
branches=20
      - animals with eyes </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 2.1pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D12 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D32 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D12>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D12 =

      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image119.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D32></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D628 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D628>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">316 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.05pt 0pt 1.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">in the soles </SPAN><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">of </SPAN></B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">their feet, etc. =97 which the =
Dover theory=20
      is obliged, by the nature of its peculiar inverted logic, to =
countenance.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.45pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">We have dealt with all the =
alleged=20
      alternatives to the theory of natural selection except the oldest =
one.=20
      This is the theory that life was created, or its evolution =
master-minded,=20
      by a conscious designer. It would obviously be unfairly easy to =
demolish=20
      some particular version of this theory such as the one (or it may =
be two)=20
      spelled out in Genesis. Nearly all peoples have developed their =
own=20
      creation myth, and the Genesis story is just the one that happened =
to have=20
      been adopted by one particular tribe of Middle Eastern herders. It =
has no=20
      more special Status than the belief of a particular West African =
tribe=20
      that the world was created from the excrement of ants. All these =
myths=20
      have in common that they depend upon the deliberate intentions of =
some=20
      kind of supernatural being. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.6pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">At first sight there is an =
important=20
      distinction to be made between what might be called 'instantaneous =

      creation' and 'guided evolution'. Modern theologians of any =
sophistication=20
      have given up believing in instantaneous creation. The evidence =
for some=20
      sort of evolution has become too overwhelming. But many =
theologians who=20
      call themselves evolutionists, for instance the Bishop of =
Birmingham=20
      quoted in Chapter 2, smuggle Cod in by the back door: they allow =
him some=20
      sort of supervisory role over the course that evolution has taken, =
either=20
      influencing key moments in evolutionary history (especially, of =
course,=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">human =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">evolutionary history), or even =
meddling=20
      more comprehensively in the day-to-day events that add up to =
evolutionary=20
      change. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.3pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">We cannot disprove beliefs like =
these,=20
      especially if it is assumed that God took care that his =
interventions=20
      always closely mimicked what would be expected from evolution by =
natural=20
      selection. All that we can say about such beliefs is, firstly, =
that they=20
      are superfluous and, secondly, that they </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">assume </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">the existence of the main thing =
we want=20
      to </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">explain,=20
      </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">namely =
organized=20
      complexity. The one thing that makes evolution such a neat theory =
is that=20
      it explains how organized complexity can arise out of primeval =
simplicity.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.1pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">If we want to postulate a deity =
capable=20
      of engineering all the organized complexity in the world, either=20
      instantaneously or by guiding evolution, that deity must already =
have been=20
      vastly complex in the first place. The creationist, whether a =
naive=20
      Bible-thumper or an educated bishop, simply </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">postulates </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">an already existing being of =
prodigious=20
      intelligence and complexity. If we are going to allow ourselves =
the luxury=20
      of postulating organized complexity without offering an =
explanation, we=20
      might as well make a job of it and simply postulate the existence =
of life=20
      as we know it! In short, divine creation, whether </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.1pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D629 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D629>
      <P class=3DStyle24 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.65pt 0pt =
2.15pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Doomed rivals </SPAN></I>317 =
<SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt"><BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle24=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.1pt 0pt 1.7pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt">instantaneous or=20
      in the form of guided evolution, joins the list of other theories =
we have=20
      considered in this chapter. All give some superficial appearance =
of being=20
      alternatives to Darwinism, whose merits might be tested by an =
appeal to=20
      evidence. All turn out, on closer inspection, not to be rivals of=20
      Darwinism at all. The theory of evolution by cumulative natural =
selection=20
      is the only theory we know of that is in principle <I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">capable </SPAN></I>of =
explaining the=20
      existence of organized complexity. Even if the evidence did not =
favour it,=20
      it would <I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">still =
</SPAN></I>be=20
      the best theory available! In fact the evidence does favour it. =
But that=20
      is another story. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle24=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.45pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.75pt">Let=20
      us hear the conclusion of the whole matter. The essence of life is =

      statistical improbability on a colossal scale. Whatever is the =
explanation=20
      for life, therefore, it cannot be chance. The true explanation for =
the=20
      existence of life must embody the very antithesis of chance. The=20
      antithesis of chance is nonrandom survival, properly understood. =
Nonrandom=20
      survival, improperly understood, is not the antithesis of chance, =
it is=20
      chance itself. There is a continuum connecting these two extremes, =
and it=20
      is the continuum from single-step selection to cumulative =
selection.=20
      Single-step selection is just another way of saying pure chance. =
This is=20
      what I mean by nonrandom survival improperly understood. <I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Cumulative selection, =
</SPAN></I>by slow=20
      and gradual degrees, is the explanation, the only workable =
explanation=20
      that has ever been proposed, for the existence of life's complex =
design.=20
      </P>
      <P class=3DStyle24=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.2pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.1pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt">The=20
      whole book has been dominated by the idea of chance, by the =
astronomically=20
      long odds against the spontaneous arising of order, complexity and =

      apparent design. We have sought a way of taming chance, of drawing =
its=20
      fangs. 'Untamed chance', pure, naked chance, means ordered design=20
      springing into existence from nothing, in a single leap. It would =
be=20
      untamed chance if once there was no eye, and then, suddenly, in =
the=20
      twinkling of a generation, an eye appeared, fully fashioned, =
perfect and=20
      whole. This is possible, but the odds against it will keep us busy =
writing=20
      noughts till the end of time. The same applies to the odds against =
the=20
      spontaneous existence of any fully fashioned, perfect and whole =
beings,=20
      including - I see no way of avoiding the conclusion =97 deities. =
</P>
      <P class=3DStyle24=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.15pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt">To=20
      'tame' chance means to break down the very improbable into less =
improbable=20
      small components arranged in series. No matter how improbable it =
is that=20
      an X could have arisen from a Y in a single step, it is always =
possible to=20
      conceive of a series of infinitesimally graded intermediates =
between them.=20
      However improbable a large-scale change may be, smaller changes =
are less=20
      improbable. And provided we postulate a sufficiently large series =
of=20
      sufficiently finely graded intermediates, we shall be able to =
derive=20
      anything from anything else, </P>
      <P class=3DStyle24=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.15pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 9.85pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9.5pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D213 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D213>
      <P class=3DStyle6 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.25pt 0pt 0.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">318 </SPAN><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker =
</SPAN></I><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR><BR></SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.95pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.65pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">without invoking astronomical=20
      improbabilities. We are allowed to do this only if there has been=20
      sufficient time to fit all the intermediates in. And also only if =
there is=20
      a mechanism for guiding each step in some particular direction, =
otherwise=20
      the sequence of steps will career off in an endless random walk.=20
      </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.5pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">It is the contention of the =
Darwinian=20
      world-view that both these provisos are met, and that slow, =
gradual,=20
      cumulative natural selection is the ultimate explanation for our=20
      existence. If there are versions of the evolution theory that deny =
slow=20
      gradualism, and deny the central role of natural selection, they =
may be=20
      true in particular cases. But they cannot be the whole truth, for =
they=20
      deny the very heart of the evolution theory, which gives it the =
power to=20
      dissolve astronomical improbabilities and explain prodigies of =
apparent=20
      miracle. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.5pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 10.3pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.7pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D509 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D362 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D509>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"><IMG=20
      height=3D509=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
