<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D553 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D376 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D553>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 96.25pt 0pt 97.45pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">APPENDIX (1991) =
<BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <H3 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 20.65pt 0pt 22.1pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
17.75pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 15.5pt">COMPUTER PROGRAMS AND THE EVOLUTION OF =

      EVOLVABILITY </SPAN><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: =
9pt"><BR><BR><BR></SPAN></H3>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.1pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 7.9pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">The biomorph computer program =
described=20
      in Chapter 3 is now available for Apple Macintosh, RM Nimbus and=20
      IBM-compatible computers (see advertisement on p. 341). All three =
programs=20
      have the basic nine 'genes' necessary to produce the biomorphs =
illustrated=20
      in Chapter 3 and trillions more like them - or not so like them. =
The=20
      Macintosh version of the program also possesses a range of =
additional=20
      genes, producing 'segmented' biomorphs (with segmentation =
'gradients') and=20
      biomorphic images reflected in various planes of symmetry. These=20
      enhancements of the biomorphic chromosome, together with a new =
colour=20
      version of the program now being developed for the Macintosh II =
and not=20
      yet released, led me to reflect on 'the evolution of =
evolvability'. This=20
      new reprinting of </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">The=20
      Blind Watchmaker </SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">provides an opportunity to =
share some of=20
      these thoughts. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.55pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 7.9pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Natural selection can act only =
on the=20
      range of variation thrown up by mutation. Mutation is described as =

      'random' but this means only that it is not systematically =
directed=20
      towards improvement. It is a highly nonrandom subset of all the =
variation=20
      that we can conceive of. Mutation has to act by altering the =
processes of=20
      existing embryology. You can't make an elephant by mutation if the =

      existing embryology is octopus embryology. That is obvious enough. =
What=20
      was less obvious to me until I started playing with the expanded =
Blind=20
      Watchmaker program is that not all embryologies are equally =
'fertile' when=20
      it comes to fostering future evolution. </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.1pt 0pt 0.7pt; TEXT-INDENT: 7.45pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Imagine that a wide-open space =
of=20
      evolutionary opportunity has suddenly opened up - say a deserted =
continent=20
      has suddenly become available through natural catastrophe. What =
kinds of=20
      animals will fill the evolutionary vacuum? They will surely have =
to be=20
      descendants of individuals good at surviving in the =
post-catastrophe=20
      conditions. But more <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle48 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 255.35pt"><B><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica-Bold">327 </SPAN></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle48 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 255.35pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Helvetica-Bold"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 7.5pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Helvetica-Bold"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D622 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D622>
      <P class=3DStyle18 style=3D"MARGIN-RIGHT: 1.65pt">328 <I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker=20
      </SPAN><BR><BR></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle18=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.25pt 0pt 0.5pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.7pt">interestingly,=20
      some kinds of embryology might be especially good not just at =
surviving=20
      but at <I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">evolving.=20
      </SPAN></I>Perhaps the reason the mammals took over after the =
extinction=20
      of the dinosaurs is not just that mammals were good at individual =
<I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">survival </SPAN></I>in the =
post-dionsaur=20
      world. It may be that the mammalian way of growing a new body is =
also=20
      'good' at throwing up a great variety of types - carnivores, =
herbivores,=20
      anteaters, tree-climbers, burrowers, swimmers and so on =97 and =
the mammals=20
      can therefore be said to be good at <I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">evolving. </SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.1pt 0pt 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 8.15pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt">What=20
      has this to do with computer biomorphs? Shortly after developing =
the Blind=20
      Watchmaker program, I experimented with other computer programs =
that were=20
      the same except that they employed a different basic embryology - =
a=20
      different fundamental body-drawing rule upon which mutation and =
selection=20
      could act. These other programs, although superficially similar to =
Blind=20
      Watchmaker, turned out to be sadly impoverished in the range of=20
      evolutionary possibility that they offered. Evolution continually =
became=20
      stuck up sterile blind alleys. Degeneration seemed to be the =
commonest=20
      outcome of even the most carefully guided evolution. In contrast, =
the=20
      branching-tree embryology at the heart of the Blind <BR>Watchmaker =
program=20
      seemed ever-pregnant with renewable evolutionary resources; there =
was no=20
      tendency towards automatic degeneration as evolution proceeded - =
the=20
      richness, versatility, even beauty, seemed to be indefinitely =
refreshed as=20
      the generations flashed by. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.2pt 0pt 0.95pt; TEXT-INDENT: 7.7pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt">Nevertheless,=20
      prolific and varied as the biomorphic fauna produced by the =
original Blind=20
      Watchmaker program was, I continually found myself coming up =
against=20
      apparent barriers to further evolution. If Blind Watchmaker's =
embryology=20
      was so evolutionarily superior to those alternative programs, =
might there=20
      not be modifications, extensions to the <BR>embryological drawing =
rule=20
      that could make Blind Watchmaker itself even more luxuriant with=20
      evolutionary diversity? Or =97 another way of putting the same =
question -=20
      could the basic chromosome of nine genes be expanded in fruitful=20
      directions? </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.5pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 7.9pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt">In=20
      designing the original Blind Watchmaker program, I deliberately =
tried to=20
      avoid deploying my biological knowledge. My purpose was to exhibit =
the=20
      power of non-random selection of random variation. I wanted the =
biology,=20
      the design, the beauty, to <I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">emerge </SPAN></I>as a result =
of=20
      selection. I didn't want to be able to accuse myself, later, of =
having=20
      built it in when I wrote the program in the first place. The=20
      branching-tree embryology of Blind Watchmaker was the very first=20
      embryology that I tried. That I had in fact been lucky was =
suggested by my=20
      subsequent disappointing experience with alternative embryologies. =
At all=20
      events, in thinking of ways to expand the basic 'chromosome', I =
did allow=20
      myself the luxury of using some of my biological knowledge and =
intuition.=20
      Among the most evolutionarily successful </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.5pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 7.9pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D382 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D378 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D382>
      <P class=3DStyle21 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1pt 0pt 2.15pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Computer programs and 'The =
evolution of=20
      evolvability' </SPAN></I><B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Bold">329=20
      </SPAN><BR><BR></B></P>
      <P class=3DStyle19 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 1.7pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.55pt">animal=20
      groups are those that have a <I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">segmented </SPAN></I>body =
plan. And=20
      among the most fundamental features of animal body plans are their =
plans=20
      of <BR><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">symmetry.=20
      </SPAN></I>Accordingly, the new genes that I added to the =
biomorphic=20
      <BR>chromosome controlled variations in segmentation and symmetry. =
</P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.55pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 7.9pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt">We,=20
      and all vertebrates, are segmented. This is clear in our ribs and =
our=20
      vertebral columns, whose repetitive nature is seen not just in the =
bones=20
      themselves but in the associated muscles, nerves and =
blood-vessels. Even=20
      our heads are fundamentally segmented, but in the adult head the=20
      <BR>segmental structure has become obscured to all but =
professionals=20
      schooled in embryonic anatomy. Fish are more obviously segmented =
than we=20
      are (think of the battery of muscles lying along the backbone of a =

      kippered herring). In crustaceans, insects, centipedes and =
millipedes the=20
      <BR>segmentation is even manifest on the outside. The difference, =
in this=20
      respect, between a centipede and a lobster is one of homogeneity. =
The=20
      centipede is like a long goods-train with all the trucks almost =
identical=20
      to one another. The lobster is like a train with a motley variety =
of=20
      carriages and trucks, all basically the same and with the same =
jointed=20
      appendages sticking out of each. But in some cases the trucks are =
welded=20
      together in groups and the appendages have become large legs or =
pincers.=20
      In the tail region the trucks are smaller and more uniform, and =
their=20
      clawed side-apparatuses have become small, feathery 'swimmerets'. =
</P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 7.9pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.55pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
1.55pt">To=20
      make biomorphs segmented I did the obvious thing: I invented a new =
gene=20
      controlling 'Number of Segments', and another new gene controlling =

      'Distance between Segments'. One complete old-style biomorph =
became a=20
      single segment of a new-style biomorph. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 7.9pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.55pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
1.55pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D113 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D309 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D113>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG =
height=3D113=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image131.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D309></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D86 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D376 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D86>
      <P class=3DStyle19 style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 7.7pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.5pt">Above are=20
      seven biomorphs differing only in their 'Number of Segments' gene =
or their=20
      'Distance between Segments' gene. The left-hand biomorph is the =
old,=20
      familiar branching tree, and the others are just serially arranged =

      repetitive trains of the same basic tree. The simple tree, like =
all the=20
      original Blind Watchmaker biomorphs, is the special case of a =
'one-segment=20
      animal'. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19 style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 7.7pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.5pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D14 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D19 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D14>
      <P class=3DStyle37><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica">330 =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle37><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Helvetica"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D16 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D120 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D16>
      <P class=3DStyle18><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic">The Blind=20
      Watchmaker </SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle18><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Italic"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D224 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D375 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D224>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 8.15pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.6pt">So=20
      far, I have talked only about uniform, centipede-like =
segmentation.=20
      Lobster segments differ from one another in complicated ways. A =
simpler=20
      way in which segments can vary is through 'gradients'. A =
woodlouse's=20
      segments are more like one another than a lobster's, but they are =
not as=20
      uniform as a typical millipede's (actually some apparent =
'woodlice' or=20
      'pillbugs' are technically millipedes). A woodlouse is narrow at =
the front=20
      and back, and broadens in the middle. As you work your way from =
the front=20
      to the back of the train, the segments have a size <I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">gradient </SPAN></I>which =
peaks in the=20
      middle. Other segmented animals, such as the extinct trilobites, =
are=20
      widest at the front and taper to the rear. They have a simpler =
size=20
      gradient which peaks at one end. It was this simpler kind of =
gradient that=20
      I sought to imitate in my segmented biomorphs. I did it by adding =
a=20
      constant number (which could be a negative number) to the =
expressed=20
      <I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">value </SPAN></I>of a =

      particular gene going from front to back. Of the following three=20
      biomorphs, the lefthand one has no gradients, the middle one has a =

      gradient on Gene 1, and the </P>
