<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D465 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D379 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D465>
      <P class=3DStyle19 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 2.65pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Computer programs and 'The =
evolution of=20
      evolvability' </SPAN></I>331 <BR><BR></P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 1.1pt 0pt 1.9pt; TEXT-INDENT: 7.9pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.5pt">I=20
      think you will agree that a more 'biologically interesting' range =
of=20
      evolutionary versatility has now become available. The 'invention' =
of=20
      segmentation, as a new breakthrough in embryology, has opened=20
      <BR>floodgates of evolutionary potential in the land of computer=20
      biomorphs. My conjecture is that something like that happened in =
the=20
      origin of the vertebrates, and in the origin of the first =
segmented=20
      ancestors of insects, lobsters and millipedes. The invention of=20
      segmentation was a watershed event in evolution. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 21.3pt 0pt 1.2pt; TEXT-INDENT: 8.15pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt">Symmetry=20
      was the other obvious innovation. The original Blind Watchmaker =
biomorphs=20
      were all constrained to be symmetrical about the midline. I =
introduced a=20
      new gene to make this optional. This new gene determined whether a =

      biomorph <BR>with its original nine gene values <BR>set to those =
of the=20
      basic tree looked <BR>like (a) or like (b). Other genes =
<BR>determined=20
      whether there was <BR>symmetric reflection in the updown =
<BR>plane, (c),=20
      or full four-way <BR>symmetry, (d). These new genes could <BR>vary =
in all=20
      combinations, as in (e| <BR>and |f). When segmented animals =
<BR>were=20
      asymmetrical in the midline <BR>plane, I introduced a botanically=20
      <BR>inspired constraint: alternate <BR>segments should be =
asymmetrical=20
      <B><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Bold">in =
</SPAN><BR></B>opposite=20
      directions, as in (g). </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 145.35pt 0pt 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.55pt">Armed with=20
      these further genes, I again set about a vigorous breeding =
program, to see=20
      whether the new embryology could foster a more exuberant evolution =
than=20
      the old. Here is a portfolio of segmented biomorphs with midline=20
      asymmetry: </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 145.35pt 0pt 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.55pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
