  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D30>
      <P class=3DStyle19>And here are some radially symmetrical =
biomorphs whose=20
      segmentation, if any, may be as cryptic as that of the adult human =
head:=20
      </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19><SPAN=20
style=3D"COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D186 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D322 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D186>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG =
height=3D186=20
      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image140.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D322></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D228 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D376 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D228>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 7.9pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.55pt">The=20
      gene for full radial symmetry tempts the selector to breed =
pleasing=20
      abstract designs rather than the biologically realistic ones that =
I had=20
      previously sought. The same is even more true of the colour =
version of the=20
      program that I am at present developing. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 8.15pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.45pt">One=20
      group of animals, the echinoderms (including starfish, sea =
urchins,=20
      brittle stars and sea lilies), are highly unusual in being =
five-sidedly=20
      symmetrical. I am confident that, no matter how hard I or anybody =
else=20
      tries, we shall never find five-sided symmetry emerging by random =
mutation=20
      from the existing embryology. This would require a new 'watershed' =

      innovation in biomorph embryology, and I have not attempted it. =
But freak=20
      starfish and sea-urchins with four or six arms rather than the =
usual five=20
      do sometimes turn up in nature. And in the course of exploring =
biomorph=20
      land I have encountered superficially starfish-like or urchin-like =
forms=20
      that have encouraged me to select for an increased resemblance. =
Here is a=20
      collection of echinoderm-like biomorphs, although none of them has =
the=20
      requisite five arms: </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 8.15pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.45pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D146 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D340 =
