vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D169>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.7pt 0pt 1.2pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">Computer programs and 'The =
evolution of=20
      evolvability' </SPAN></I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman">333=20
      <BR><BR></SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 8.15pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.55pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">As a final test of the =
versatility of my=20
      new biomorphic embryology, I set myself the task of breeding a =
biomorphic=20
      alphabet good enough to sign my own name. Every time I encountered =
a=20
      biomorph that resembled, however slightly, a letter of the =
alphabet, I=20
      bred and bred to enhance the resemblance. The verdict on this =
ambitious=20
      endeavour is mixed, to say the least. T and 'N' are well-nigh =
perfect. 'A'=20
      and 'H' are respectable if slightly ungainly. 'D' is poor, while =
to breed=20
      a proper 'K' is, I suspect, downright impossible -1 had to cheat =
by=20
      borrowing the upright stroke of the 'W. Yet another gene would =
have to be=20
      added, I suspect, before a plausible 'K' could be evolved. =
</SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4=20
      style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.5pt; TEXT-INDENT: 8.15pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.55pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D31 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D313 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D31>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D31 =

      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image142.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D313></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D44 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D376 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D44>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 8.15pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">After my somewhat illiterate =
attempt to=20
      sign my own name, I had more luck with evolving that of the =
inspired=20
      artefact with which all this work was done: </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 8.15pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D37 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D274 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D37>
      <P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"COLOR: black"><IMG height=3D37 =

      =
src=3D"file:///F:/&#1063;&#1058;&#1048;&#1042;&#1054;%20(&#1074;&#1090;&#=
1086;&#1088;&#1086;&#1089;&#1090;&#1077;&#1087;&#1077;&#1085;&#1085;&#108=
6;&#1077;)/mamb.ru%20(&#1052;&#1072;&#1083;&#1072;&#1103;%20&#1072;&#1082=
;&#1072;&#1076;&#1077;&#1084;&#1080;&#1103;%20&#1084;&#1086;&#1088;&#1089=
;&#1082;&#1086;&#1081;%20&#1073;&#1080;&#1086;&#1083;&#1086;&#1075;&#1080=
;&#1080;)/The%20Blind%20Watchmaker/The_Blind_Watchmaker_files/image143.jp=
g"=20
      width=3D275></SPAN></P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR =
clear=3Dall>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D298 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D377 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D298>
      <P class=3DStyle6=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.85pt 0pt 0.25pt; TEXT-INDENT: 7.9pt; =
LINE-HEIGHT: 10.6pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">It is my strong impression, =
borne out, I=20
      hope, by the illustrations here, that the introduction of a few =
radical=20
      changes in the fundamental <BR>embryology of the biomorphs has =
opened up=20
      new vistas of evolutionary possibility which simply were not =
available to=20
      the original program described in Chapter 3. And, as I said =
earlier, I=20
      believe that something similar happened at various junctures in =
the=20
      evolution of some prominent groups of animals and plants. The =
invention of=20
      segmentation by our own ancestors, and separately by the ancestors =
of=20
      insects and crustaceans, is probably only one of several examples =
of=20
      'watershed' events in our evolutionary history. These watershed =
events=20
      are, at least when seen with the wisdom of hindsight, different in =
kind=20
      from ordinary evolutionary changes. Our first segmented ancestors, =
and the=20
      first segmented ancestor of earthworms and insects, may not have =
been=20
      particularly good at surviving as individuals - though obviously =
they=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">did =
</SPAN></I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">survive as individuals, or we, =
their=20
      descendants, would not be here. My point now is that the invention =
of=20
      segmentation by these ancestors was more significant than just a =
new=20
      technique for <BR>surviving, like sharper teeth or keener eyes. =
When=20
      segmentation was added to the embryonic procedures of our =
ancestors,=20
      whether or not the individual animals concerned became better at=20
      surviving, the lineages to which they belonged suddenly became=20
      </SPAN><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">better at =
evolving.=20
      </SPAN></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 8.4pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman">Modem animals, we vertebrates =
and all our=20
      fellow-travellers on this </SPAN></P>
      <P class=3DStyle4 style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 8.4pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: =
Times-Roman"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; FONT-FAMILY: Times-Roman"><BR=20
style=3D"PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE: always" clear=3Dall></SPAN>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt; COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<DIV>
<TABLE height=3D296 cellSpacing=3D0 cellPadding=3D0 width=3D376 =
vspace=3D"0" hspace=3D"0">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD=20
    style=3D"PADDING-RIGHT: 0in; PADDING-LEFT: 0in; PADDING-BOTTOM: 0in; =
PADDING-TOP: 0in"=20
    vAlign=3Dtop align=3Dleft height=3D296>
      <P class=3DStyle18 style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.35pt 0pt =
181.9pt"><I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker=20
      </SPAN><BR><BR></I></P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"MARGIN: 0in 0.2pt 0pt 0.25pt; LINE-HEIGHT: =
10.6pt">planet, inherit=20
      the genes of an unbroken line of ancestors that were good at =
individual=20
      survival. That much I tried to make clear in <I><SPAN=20
      style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">The Blind Watchmaker. =
</SPAN></I>But we=20
      also inherit the embryological procedures of ancestral lineages =
that were=20
      good at <I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-FAMILY: Times-Italic">evolving.=20
      </SPAN></I>There has been a kind of higher-order selection among =
lineages,=20
      not for their ability to survive but for their longer-term ability =
to=20
      evolve. We bear the accumulated improvements of a number of =
watershed=20
      events, of which the invention of segmentation is just one =
example. It is=20
      not just bodies and behaviour that have evolved in improved =
directions. We=20
      could even say that evolution itself has evolved. There has been a =

      progressive evolution of evolvability. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 8.15pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.25pt">The=20
      Macintosh version of the Blind Watchmaker program has menu options =
to turn=20
      on or off each of the main categories of mutation. By turning off =
all the=20
      new types of mutation one reverts to the earlier version of the =
program=20
      (or the present IBM version). Breed for a while under these =
conditions,=20
      and youget somefeelfor theenormous range offaunas permitted by the =
earlier=20
      program, but also for its limitations. If you then switch on, say, =

      segmentation mutations, or symmetry mutations (or if you switch =
from IB M=20
      to a Macintosh! ), you can exult in something of the =
feelingofliberation=20
      that may have attended evolution's great watershed events. </P>
      <P class=3DStyle19=20
      style=3D"TEXT-INDENT: 8.15pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 10.65pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: =
0.25pt"><SPAN=20
      style=3D"COLOR: =
black"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></DIV><BR=20
clear=3Dall>
